<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA DOES MORE QB SHUFFLING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If it's Monday, Bruins coach Bob Toledo must have
a quarterback announcement. Cory Paus remains the starter, but he
probably won't start (or play) Saturday at Stanford because of
injuries, which means Drew Bennett, the former starter, will start.
</P>
<P>
   Got it?
</P>
<P>
   Paus did not practice Monday and is listed as doubtful because
of bruised ribs and a strained neck suffered in the second quarter
of the victory over Fresno State. If he can't play, then Bennett,
who directed the second-half comeback, will start against the
surging Cardinal.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Cory is healthy, he's the starting quarterback,'' Toledo
said. ``There's a reason we picked him before and a reason now...
</P>
<P>
   ``(But) I don't think at this point that he's going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Paus, a freshman, completed his first eight passes against
Fresno State and was 9 of 12 for 113 yards and a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   He was injured when he fell on the ball and two Bulldogs fell on
him. He bruised ribs on the upper left side of his chest, near the
collarbone.
</P>
<P>
   Third-string sophomore Scott McEwan, of Thousand Oaks, becomes
the backup if Paus can't play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brushing my teeth hurts _ anything with my arms, anything with
my upper torso,'' Paus said. ``I'm disappointed, obviously. It's
like, `Yeah, I played good, but I got hurt.' I could ice it all day
and it wouldn't help. I just have to let it heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love to play, but if I can't play up to the standards to
beat a team like Stanford, I won't even try. Drew did a fine job.
Obviously, he showed that in the second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Freed from the anxiety that accompanies starting, Bennett played
the best game of his career. He completed 13 of 24 passes for 176
yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   After losing the quarterback competition earlier in the week, he
proved to himself he could lead the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gave me confidence as a backup,'' he said. ``Coach Toledo
told me (last week) that no matter what happened, I'm still
valuable to the team, and I showed that when Cory got hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll probably have to show it again, and soon.
</P>
<P>
   Menace in the middle: Middle linebacker Robert Thomas returned
from a two-game suspension to show why he was a coveted national
recruit two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, a sophomore, had a game-high 14 tackles and was named
defensive player of the game. His punishing third-quarter hit
dislodged receiver Rodney Wright's helmet and ignited UCLA's
comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was all over the field,'' Toledo said. ``He made a few
mistakes from being a little inexperienced, but he's going to be a
great player.''
</P>
<P>
   Receiver Freddie Mitchell (nine catches, 149 yards) was named
offensive player of the game. Long-snapper Jeff Grau won the
special-teams honor.
</P>
<P>
   Injury update: Amid myriad bumps and bruises, the Bruins have
several significant injuries, excluding Paus:
</P>
<P>
   Receivers Danny Farmer (sprained ankle), Brian Poli-Dixon
(sprained wrist) and Mitchell (thigh bruise) are probable. Farmer
practiced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle Pete Holland (back) is questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Guard Mike Saffer (ankle) and cornerback Jason Bell (heel) are
out.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo dismissed the idea of redshirting Bell, who played as a
true freshman and is eligible for a medical exemption if he misses
the rest of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs to play,'' Toledo said. ``I'm going to sit and talk
to him. It hurts a little bit, but we want him to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Bell, UCLA's top four cornerbacks are freshmen.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: This week's captains are fullback Durell Price
and linebacker Tony White.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona State game starts at 12:30 p.m. and will be
televised on Channel 7. The Stanford game starts at 2 p.m. and will
not be televised live. However, Fox Sports West 2 will show a
tape-delayed broadcast beginning at 3:30 p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
