<SLUG> BC-HURRICANE-POLITICS-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS CAN SINK OR SWIM ON NATURE'S WHIM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By CARL HULSE   
 Washington Bureau   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Hurricane Floyd churned up the Eastern Seaboard,
Rep. Martin Frost turned his own wrath upon the Republican House
leadership, ripping into them for failing to adjourn Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are trapping members in the nation's capital who want to
be home with their constituents,'' roared Frost, D-Texas , on the
House floor. ``This is an extraordinary development.''
</P>
<P>
   Frost was speaking for many of his colleagues who were eager to
avoid becoming political casualties of the high-profile hurricane.
It is a hard-learned truth that public officials must be seen as
being fully engaged in preparing for a storm and efficiently
handling its aftermath or they risk being cast adrift by an angry
electorate.
</P>
<P>
   The nexus between politics and weather was never clearer than
the past week when Vice President Al Gore was interviewed on the
Weather Channel while Hurricane Floyd was leading the news on CNN's
show Inside Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Natural disasters are the ultimate test for political
leaders,'' said CNN's political analyst Bill Schneider. ``They have
to do the impossible _ reassure people that they are in control of
a situation that nobody can control.''
</P>
<P>
   After Frost's tirade, House leaders quickly canceled their
business last week, though the Senate stayed in town. And House
members weren't the only ones changing their plans. President
Clinton cut short his own trip to New Zealand to return home to
monitor the storm's progress and make sure emergency operations
were running smoothly.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Clinton flew to flood-ravaged Northeastern North
Carolina, where members of Congress from the state appeared with
the president as he urged battered residents to ``keep your spirits
up and know that we're going to be with you every step of the way.
Know that you have strong advocates in your local officials, your
wonderful governor and your very vigorous congressional
delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   History shows that storms can be politically deadly. In one
famous case, Chicago Mayor Michael Bilandic was ousted in 1979
after his administration failed to clear city streets for a week
following a blizzard. Detroit's mayor was subjected to a recall
after snow removal efforts fell short this year. Washington Mayor
Marion Barry, who had other problems, was often criticized for his
nonchalant approach to snow removal.
</P>
<P>
   The harshly critiqued federal relief effort following Hurricane
Hugo in 1989 as well as Hurricane Andrew in 1992 tarnished
political careers and led to a shakeup and restructuring at FEMA.
And Gore himself took some heat for not appearing sufficiently
comforting after tornados raked Alabama in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there is any sense that political figures are insensitive
to the trauma or disruption in life caused by a natural disaster,
are not right on top of it, it becomes almost disqualifying,'' said
Norm Ornstein, an analyst at the American Enterprise Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The past week's storm quickly sparked political sniping and
second-guessing. Charleston, S.C., Mayor Joseph P. Riley hit his
fellow Democrat, Gov. Jim Hodges, for waiting too long to make
Interstate 26 a one-way evacuation route inland. In Florida, Gov.
Jeb Bush was quizzed about traffic snarls caused by the massive
evacuation and by week's end he had launched a statewide review of
the matter. And there was commentary that the overall response to
the storm in some areas exceeded what was necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton predicted as much. ``There may be some people who
question ... whether we did the right thing to recommend all the
evacuations,'' he said. ``But now that we have this technology at
the National Weather Center, we have to act on it.''
</P>
<P>
   As the storm progressed, lawmakers remaining in Washington were
quick to make their attentiveness known. Sens. Connie Mack, R-Fla.,
and John Edwards, D-N.C., were on CNN exhibiting their firsthand
knowledge of the evolving emergency plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've gotten folks away from the greatest places of danger,''
announced Edwards one afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The House GOP campaign committee offered to make television
satellite time available to Florida members, giving them a chance
to reassure constituents and offer storm tips.
</P>
<P>
   And Florida Gov. Bush was not going to repeat a mistake made in
1992, when state officials were chastised for waiting too long
after Andrew hit to request full federal relief. The governor
wasted no time, seeking a disaster declaration for more than 50
counties even before the first hurricane winds reached the shores
of Florida, which was ultimately spared the brunt of the storm's
fury.
</P>
<P>
   Some Florida Republicans saw another political opening in the
hurricane, writing Clinton to urge him not to veto the $792 billion
GOP tax cut package in light of the storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hurricane Floyd is threatening our coast and you are
threatening to veto tax relief that would help its victims,' said
the letter signed by Sen. Mack and Reps. Dan Miller, Cliff Stearns,
Porter Goss and Charles Canady among others. ``In the aftermath of
a hurricane, our constituents need to know that we are doing
everything possible to help them recover and this one tangible way
to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
