<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-PAGEANT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: HERE SHE IS _ BUT WHERE IS SHE FROM 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. _ It didn't take long for Miss New York to
fall by the wayside at the Miss America Pageant the other night,
not that it came as a great shock. New York's standard-bearers have
not usually fared well at the pageant, and Brandi Burkhardt, 20,
was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   There was an interesting tidbit about her in the program. Alone
among the 51 contestants, she gave a hometown that was not in the
state she represented. Pasadena, Md., the program said. Graduate of
Chesapeake High School. Doesn't sound terribly New Yorky, does it?
</P>
<P>
   Then again, in the last few years Ms. Burkhardt seems to have
settled nicely into Manhattan life, studying at New York
University, working as an Off Broadway production assistant and
looking toward an acting career. So said the program.
</P>
<P>
   The point, if there is one, is that her New York sponsors were
clearly unfazed by the fact that she is new to their state _ what
some might go so far as to call a carpetbagger. Based on her
talents (and looks), she was deemed a fine representative, no
matter where born.
</P>
<P>
   You may already sense where this is headed. Might Ms.
Burkhardt's presence in Atlantic City be a sign that the
carpetbagger issue will prove a nonstarter in a certain Senate race
taking shape in New York?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps this is reaching, even overreaching, for a significance
that isn't there. Still, the question of what makes a New Yorker
came to mind over the weekend while spending time here with
Patricia Harris, originally of Detroit. For half a century, she
lived and flourished in Manhattan, and even though no longer there,
she remains as identifiably New York as the Statue of Liberty,
which comes from France.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Harris was in Atlantic City as grand marshal of the
boardwalk parade that preceded the pageant, a stream of contestants
and marching bands.
</P>
<P>
   She earned the honor because she was Miss America 1939. The name
then was Patricia Donnelly. Going into the contest, she was Miss
Michigan, all of 19 years old. For the talent section, she played a
bass fiddle while singing a number called ``Old Man Mose Is Dead.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I sang with bands back then,'' she recalled. ``I was a good
singer _ not great, but good.'' What clinched the title was her
gait, straight and firm even now in her 80th year. ``I always
walked well,'' she said, stepping in high heels around a sidewalk
grating on her way to the hall where the pageant was held.
</P>
<P>
   For the parade, Mrs. Harris wore a silk jacket she bought years
ago in Hong Kong. She rode tall, sitting on the back of a limo as
wide as the QE2 and waving to the crowds, filled with people not
embarrassed to stand and salute when a contingent of aging
ex-Marines strode by. Later, in restaurants and in her hotel, women
rushed up to ask for her autograph and to say that she looked like
a million, which in fact she did.
</P>
<P>
   You can, if you wish, dismiss the pageant as a silly exercise,
or as Babbitry in a bathing suit, or as an offense to women
everywhere. You may even be right. But 78 years after it got its
start, it still means a lot to many people. After a while, that
simple truth becomes hard to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fun,'' Mrs. Harris said. ``But kids do grow up admiring
Miss America, so the organizers try to keep her a person they can
look up to. I think they've done a pretty good job. These are about
as nice a group of women as you'll ever meet.''
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, after her year as Miss America, she moved to New York
City, where she met Robin Harris. He was a writer. They were
introduced at a night club and were married a few months later in
the Municipal Building.
</P>
<P>
   It was some time that they had. Theirs was the New York of white
gloves and snap-brim fedoras, of days at the track and nights on
the town. They got to meet everyone from J. Edgar Hoover to Meyer
Lansky. Of course, they had to make a living. They traveled the
world and wrote magazine articles on what they had seen. But the
road always led back to New York, until her husband died. Her home
is now outside Boston, near grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   All this is a buildup to the following question:
</P>
<P>
   What makes you a New Yorker _ merely taking up space in the city
for a stretch, or diving into it to make it your own? Patricia
Donnelly knew the answer. So, it seems, does Brandi Burkhardt, who
showed how quickly one can move from being an outsider to top of
the hill.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
