<SLUG> BC-BBN-MCGWIRE-SOSA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCGWIRE HITS NO. 59, SOSA JUST A SINGLE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL DEDMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Mark McGwire insists that there is no home run race.
``It doesn't matter who finishes first,'' he said. ``I was in a
race with Ken Griffey several times, and no one cared.''
</P>
<P>
   McGwire relaxed at his locker before Monday night's game, all
muscles and red hair, saying it was no big deal. Then he went out
into the cool night at Wrigley Field and hit his 59th home run,
breaking up a perfect game in the seventh inning against the
Chicago Cubs. Sammy Sosa remained at 61 home runs, hitting only a
single, as the St. Louis Cardinals won, 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   The race, McGwire said, was last year, the race for Roger Maris'
single-season record, and he broke it with 70. Winning this year's
home run crown is less important to him than hitting 50 home runs
for four years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that getting to 50 is a piece of cake,'' McGwire
said before the first of three games against the Cubs. ``You can't
fill up one hand naming the people who got to 50 consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   Two fingers should do it: Babe Ruth and Mark McGwire. Each has
done it four times. Several _ Sosa and Griffey, Jimmie Foxx and
Ralph Kiner, Mickey Mantle and Willie Mays _ have twice hit 50.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night didn't seem conducive to home runs. During the
national anthem the wind at Wrigley Field was blowing toward home
plate at 16 mph. The temperature was dipping below 60. The rookie
umpire Ian Lamplugh was calling everything within reach of home
plate a strike.
</P>
<P>
   And Jon Lieber was pitching a perfect game for the Cubs. The
former Pittsburgh right-hander (8-11) retired the first 20 batters,
striking out nine. McGwire struck out twice.
</P>
<P>
   No Cub has pitched a perfect game, a record that was preserved
with two outs in the seventh inning, as McGwire lined an 0-1 pitch
into the third row of the bleachers in straightaway center field. A
Cubs fan followed the tradition of disgust, throwing the No. 59
ball onto the field, but most of the crowd of 38,085 gave McGwire a
standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Lieber didn't last through the inning, giving up three homers in
a span of seven pitches _ to McGwire, Thomas Howard and J.D. Drew.
In all, the Cardinals scored seven runs in the inning. Mark
Thompson (1-2) won his first game for the Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was amazing,'' McGwire said of the turnaround. ``The way he
was pitching me, I didn't think I would make any contact.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa missed a home run by a few feet in the first inning,
hitting a ball into the wind to the right-field wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I hit mine a little high,'' said Sosa, who finished
the game 1 for 3 with a walk and a strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was 1 for 4, leaving the game in the eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Flashbulbs accompanied their every swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're swinging from their heels,'' said Jerome Holtzman, the
historian for Major League Baseball and the Hall of Fame and a
longtime sportswriter for Chicago newspapers. ``Of course, there's
nothing new about that. Ruth did it. Mantle did it.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, each team's manager swore that his pitchers
would pitch to the other guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to pitch them carefully, make them chase a pitch out
of the zone,'' said Tony La Russa, the Cardinals' manager.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire said he thought Sosa should get more recognition than he
has for hitting 61 home runs for such a bad team. The Cubs have won
60 games and lost 90. No player has ever hit more home runs than
his team has had victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your team's having a rough year,'' McGwire said, ``it's
not easy coming to the ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs have a winning percentage of .400.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year hurts me to my soul,'' the Cubs veteran Mark Grace
said. ``And I've played on some bad teams.''
</P>
</TEXT>
