<SLUG> BC-EDIT-FLOYD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C., N.J.)  
 EDITORIAL: FLOYD'S SELECTIVE DAMAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Sept. 21:
</P>
<P>
   At the end of last week, after Hurricane Floyd had come and
gone, most observers breathed a sigh of relief that the storm had
not been as dangerous and damaging as predicted. But the good
fortune that spared millions of residents along the Eastern
seaboard did not shine equally on everyone. Streams and rivers in
North Carolina and parts of Virginia and New Jersey began rising
ominously, then jumped their banks, leaving thousands of people
homeless, inundating entire towns, paralyzing commerce and causing
damage that could run into the billions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Regionally, northern New Jersey suffered the most when the
Raritan and other rivers and streams overflowed, ruining homes and
businesses and almost burying the town of Bound Brook. But North
Carolina was by far the hardest hit, and President Clinton, who
toured the state Monday, was visibly shocked by the damage. What
brought the state to a standstill was not the wind but the rain, 20
inches in all, which sent rivers like the Tar, the Neuse and the
Cape Fear to levels not seen in 70 years. One result was the
flooding of many thousands of acres of agricultural lowland.
Officials estimate that the toll on farmers alone could exceed $900
million.
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials at both the Environmental Protection Agency
and the Federal Emergency Management Agency are already searching
for lessons in the North Carolina disaster. The EPA is involved
because wastewater treatment plants have failed in lowland areas
and some factories may be leaking dangerous chemicals. There is
also the problem of agricultural runoff, which causes water
pollution even in normal times. North Carolina is the country's
largest producer of turkeys, its second-largest producer of hogs
and its third-largest producer of chickens. All these animals
generate vast amounts of waste. When the floodwaters recede, the
EPA will learn much about whether these wastes have been properly
stored and whether stronger state and federal regulation is
required.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the emergency management agency will try to
determine, as it always does, how much damage could have been
avoided if people had chosen not to build and live in the flood
plain. As it has since the Mississippi River floods of 1993, it
will also offer federal assistance to homeowners who wish to move
to higher ground and to communities that wish to protect themselves
against future floods. It is, of course, impossible to predict
floods of this magnitude. But each new disaster _ the Mississippi
flood, or the Grand Forks flood in North Dakota _ helps prepare for
the next one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
