<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GORBACHEV-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A SOVIET FIRST LADY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Sept. 21:
</P>
<P>
   When Mikhail Gorbachev's glasnost began to allow the Soviet
people to complain openly, his wife was one of the first targets of
bitter, public debate. Raisa Gorbachev, who died of leukemia Monday
in Germany, was too glamorous to be a Soviet leader's wife, her
people grumbled. She wore spiked heels and fox furs at a time when
most women her age were standing for hours in Soviet bread lines.
She was too arrogant, they groused, unwilling to keep her pedantry,
as professor of communist philosophy and sociology, safely confined
to academia. Once, after she prodded her husband to say hello to a
youngster who came to see the Soviet first couple, the citizenry
reeled. This bit of wifely intervention, so normal for any
political helpmate in America, brought a wave of visceral
disapproval, even in a country that repeatedly issued empty
proclamations about the equality of Soviet women.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, Mrs. Gorbachev simply declared herself the Soviet
Union's first first lady, a powerful act by a commanding woman.
Unlike most Kremlin wives, who favored mud-colored clothes and a
secure position out of sight, Mrs. Gorbachev's role was front and
center. She disrupted other upstaged wives like Nancy Reagan, who
labeled her ``arrogant'' for such stunts as appearing at a summit
that did not include spouses. Mikhail Gorbachev reported that she
also mystified his colleagues in the Kremlin, who kept asking,
``Who does she think she is, a member of the Politburo?''
</P>
<P>
   While her husband was the Soviet leader, Mrs. Gorbachev was his
closest ally. An expert on Marxist-Leninist philosophy, she helped
him oversee the end of the Soviet era. A sociologist, she toured
areas where her husband would attract too much official attention,
bringing back vital research on how people actually lived. On trips
abroad, Mrs. Gorbachev might veer into a shopping mall to get an
unvarnished view.
</P>
<P>
   Almost eight years after her husband's resignation and three
years after his pathetic efforts to be elected Russian president,
Mrs. Gorbachev, like her husband, is still more admired outside her
own country than within. Abroad, she is seen as a modern partner
who tried to help turn the old Soviet Union into a modern Russian
state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
