<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS TAKE TIMEOUT AT HALF TO CELEBRATE PAST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ One hundred eight former Cowboys, members of
teams spanning the franchise's 40 years in the NFL, took the field
once again Monday night at Texas Stadium in a star-studded
celebration of the organization's history.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the old Cowboys hobbled out, some trotted and others
walked out from under the giant inflatable Cowboys helmet leading
out of the tunnel. Then came Hall of Fame member Tony Dorsett.
Looking like he could still make a linebacker stand in quicksand,
Dorsett jogged onto the field, then unexpectedly struck the Heisman
pose. Dorsett won the Heisman Trophy in 1976 at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   Dorsett received one of the loudest welcomes from the sellout
crowd, along with fellow Hall of Fame members Roger Staubach, Bob
Lilly and Randy White, and Cowboy Ring of Honor members Drew
Pearson and Ed ``Too Tall'' Jones. Among others who lined up on the
field between arches made of white and blue balloons, were Lee Roy
Jordan, Chuck Howley and Mel Renfro.
</P>
<P>
   As he made his way off the field, Dorsett spiked the football in
the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Dorsett mocked scoring a touchdown, his successor,
Emmitt Smith, scored one on the first series of the third quarter.
In doing so, Smith passed Dorsett for fourth place among the NFL's
career rushing leaders.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
