<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
 
FALCONS NOTES: NO MIRACLES THIS TIME (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dan Reeves had said it would take a miracle for
Chris Chandler to start at quarterback for the Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night at Texas Stadium, there were no miracles in sight.
So the Falcons were forced to face the Cowboys with 25-year-old
Tony Graziani, whose resume includes a 24.4 career passer rating,
in place of the man who led Atlanta to the Super Bowl last season.
</P>
<P>
   Chandler, who suffered a strained right hamstring late in last
week's season-opening loss to Minnesota, limped noticeably as he
went through pregame warmups and was designated as Atlanta's
emergency third quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   That left the Falcons' offense in the hands of Graziani, a
third-year man from Oregon who made only his third NFL start.
Graziani was lifted in the third quarter after completing 7 of 16
passes for 90 yards with no touchdowns and one interception. He
also fumbled at the Atlanta 24 early in the third quarter, setting
up a Cowboys touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   For his career, Graziani is 30-of-72 for 330 yards with no
scores and five interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   CAPTAIN HOOKED: When Tony Graziani took the opening snap of the
third quarter, it marked the first time in his career he has
started the second half of a game. He was pulled at halftime of his
two previous starts. He was 8-for-18 for 102 yards with one
interception in the first half against St. Louis last season and
went 4-for-18 for 24 yards and two interceptions against Carolina
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   But while he made it into the third quarter Monday night,
Graziani watched the fourth from the sideline again. The longest
stint of his career ended when Danny Kanell replaced him with 1:05
remaining in the third quarter. Kanell didn't fare much better,
throwing two incompletions and taking a sack in his first series.
</P>
<P>
   MONDAY NIGHT BLUES: Some teams relish the prime-time stage that
comes with Monday night games, but the Falcons aren't among them.
Atlanta's most recent Monday night victory came in a wild 31-30
upset of Minnesota on Nov. 23, 1981.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have lost their past nine Monday games, a streak
that includes a 41-17 drubbing by the Cowboys in 1992. Atlanta's
overall Monday night record is an unenviable 5-16, including 1-8 on
the road.
</P>
<P>
   ANDERSEN'S STREAK ALIVE: Kicker Morten Andersen's scoring streak
appeared to be in jeopardy until the Falcons scored with 4 minutes
remaining Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   With his point-after touchdown, Andersen has scored in an
NFL-record 239 consecutive games, including 66 for the Falcons.
That's two games short of the franchise record of 68, held by Mick
Luckhurst (1981-85). Andersen has scored in every game he played
since Week 15 of the 1983 season, when he was kicking for New
Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   BRIEFLY: Falcons coach and former Cowboy Dan Reeves isn't too
fond of returning to Texas Stadium. He is 0-5 as a visiting coach
with Denver, the New York Giants and Atlanta. He had not previously
faced the Cowboys as Atlanta's coach ... In addition to Chris
Chandler and Jamal Anderson, several other Falcons spent time on
the bench with injuries Monday night. Defensive tackle Travis Hall
(hip) and wide receiver Chris Calloway (right knee) were both
knocked out of the game in the second quarter. Both returned in the
second half.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
