<SLUG> BC-HARRY-CLEBERG-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMLAND CEO IS STEPPING DOWN BUT NOT OUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK DAVIS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ To get the merger he wants, Harry Cleberg has
to give up the job he loves.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the most difficult decision of my career,'' Cleberg
said Monday in the Kansas City headquarters of Farmland Industries
Inc.
</P>
<P>
   The South Dakota native has led Farmland since April 1991. He
has been in its management ranks since 1977. His Farmland ties
stretch back 40 years to when he joined South Dakota Wheat Growers,
which is the largest equity owner of Farmland, a farmer-owned
cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   At 61, Cleberg is leaving his post as president and chief
executive officer early. Most chief executives his age would be
looking forward to at least four more years on the top corporate
rung.
</P>
<P>
   But Cleberg has agreed to step down as part of Farmland's merger
agreement with Cenex Harvest States Cooperatives. Noel Estenson,
Cleberg's counterpart at Minnesota-based Cenex, made the same
commitment.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Cleberg explained why. To win approval from both
cooperatives' member-owners, neither top manager could claim the
top job, even with the backing of the other.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed early on that that probably wouldn't work,'' Cleberg
said. ``If there was a perception that one or the other was the
victor in running the company, it could impair the (support) of the
ownership community.''
</P>
<P>
   In short, the merger might not win approval from members of the
co-op whose chief executive didn't get the job.
</P>
<P>
   Member-owners of both co-ops will vote on the merger in
November. A two-thirds approval from each is required.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said the unique structure of a cooperative made the
decision necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike publicly traded companies, cooperatives are owned by the
people and companies that do business with them. Furthermore, the
return on members' ownership is based on how much business they do
with the cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said the result was much more contact between owners of
a cooperative and its chief executive. He said a cooperative was
more like a partnership than a publicly traded company in which
owners come and go.
</P>
<P>
   So the top executives each agreed to clear the deck for new
leadership on March 1, when Farmland and Cenex are expected to
merge as United Country Brands. The new operation will have its
headquarters in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   On March 1, Bob Honse, Farmland's chief operating officer, will
become United Country's first chief executive officer. He is
scheduled to give way in four years to John Johnson, who will be
president of United Country Brands and is now the No. 2 executive
at Cenex Harvest States.
</P>
<P>
   Estenson and Cleberg will remain as advisers to United Country
Brands through the end of 2000. Cleberg said Monday that he might
continue with projects that carry on beyond 2000. Otherwise, he's
looking for a second career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clara and I are evaluating what my, and our, next career will
be,'' Cleberg said of his plans with his wife of 40 years. ``We
have never used the term `retirement.' I don't plan to ever
retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg said he would consider a second business career; his
contract prevents him from competing against Farmland until he
turns 65.
</P>
<P>
   He would consider a government post. He would consider a
nonprofit organization and has been involved with several area
groups for years.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the door is wide open _ but with one caveat. Cleberg
plans to stay in his adopted hometown of Kansas City, where the
Clebergs have lived since 1968.
</P>
<P>
   And whatever career Cleberg chooses, he said, it will allow more
time for his civic pursuits.
</P>
<P>
   That was welcome news to Guyla Stidmon, executive director of
the National Alliance for the Mentally Ill of Greater Kansas City.
Cleberg is the longtime chairman of the group's advisory board and
a past president.
</P>
<P>
   ``He probably is one of the most effective advocates I've ever
seen,'' Stidmon said. ``Wherever he is, he always remembers his
other causes.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg is a trustee, adviser, director or board member of 17
area businesses and civic groups.
</P>
<P>
   He is a member of the Civic Council of Greater Kansas City,
director and past chairman of the Greater Kansas City Chamber of
Commerce and the chairman of this year's Heart of America United
Way campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg serves on the board of governors at the National
Agricultural Center and Hall of Fame in Bonner Springs. He has been
on the board of governors of the American Royal Association since
the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   He is a director of three St. Luke's area hospitals, Commerce
Bank of Kansas City and Payless Cashways Inc. He is a trustee of
the Midwest Research Institute and the St. Paul School of Theology
in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Cleberg says he hasn't been as involved civically as he would
like. And his departure offers him the chance to rework his
schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect to remain active,'' he said. ``We're just deciding
where and which direction.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
