<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ENCEPHALITIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO ENCEPHALITIS CASES IN WESTCHESTER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two people in Westchester County have contracted the potentially
deadly mosquito-borne disease St. Louis encephalitis, county
officials announced Monday night, in the first cases in the current
outbreak reported outside of New York City. The officials said that
they would begin spraying pesticide on the southern third of the
county on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A third person is considered highly likely to have the disease,
said the County health commissioner, Dr. Harold N. Adel.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the confirmed patients _ a man from Yonkers in his
70's and a Mount Vernon resident in his 50's _ nor the likely case,
a 57-year-old woman from Port Chester, has died from the disease,
officials said. One of the victims is recovering in a hospital, one
is listed in stable condition and a third is recovering at home,
the officials added without giving further details.
</P>
<P>
   Officials are not sure whether the victims were exposed to the
virus in Westchester County, but they said two of the three had
recently visited neighborhoods in New York City where cases had
been reported. Since the disease was first reported in New York
City three weeks ago, Westchester officials have been sending
mosquito samples to the Federal Centers for Disease Control and
Prevention to be tested, and no encephalitis has been found in any
of the 350 mosquitoes tested so far, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But Adel said at a news conference that ``it would be imprudent
not to take action,'' adding that the county felt it had no choice
but to begin spraying. The county will use a pesticide called
Anvil, derived from an ingredient found in chrysanthemums, that is
considered less toxic than the malathion that is now being sprayed
in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although no pesticide can be considered completely harmless,
this is the safest type of pesticide available for the task,'' Adel
said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Westchester is scheduled to begin spraying the
entire county south of Interstate 287, home to most of its
population, as well as three communities north and east of the
interstate that border Connecticut: Port Chester, Harrison and Rye
Brook.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, where 12 cases of encephalitis have been
confirmed, three of them fatal, and 10 more cases are considered
probable, officials said the news from their northern neighbor
would not affect the city's policy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already doing what we felt we had to do to prevent
additional cases,'' said Sandra Mullin, a spokeswoman for the
city's Health Department.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the latest spraying campaign in the city,
helicopters, planes and trucks are scheduled to visit parts of
Queens, Brooklyn and Staten Island today, unless there is rain or
fog.
</P>
<P>
   Since Sept. 3, there have been 108 possible cases of St. Louis
encephalitis &UR; ,  &LR; which is spread by a species of mosquito called
Culex pipiens, reported in New York City. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Health officials say babies, the elderly and those with weak
immune systems are the most vulnerable. All three fatalities were
elderly people. The disease does not pose as great a risk to older
children and healthy adults.
</P>
<P>
   Encephalitis is hard to diagnose since its symptoms closely
resemble those of other illnesses, including the flu and a form of
meningitis that is common at this time of year. The disease is not
curable; only the symptoms can be treated.
</P>
<P>
   All of Manhattan was sprayed from 10 p.m. to 6 a.m. on Sunday.
On Wednesday, Riverside Park will be sprayed again. Several Queens,
Brooklyn and Bronx neighborhoods were sprayed Monday and several
other neighborhoods are scheduled to be sprayed on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
