<SLUG> BC-MANN-TROUBLES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANN THEATRES CONSIDERS PULLING CURTAIN ON SOME LOCATIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE McNARY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The parent of the struggling Mann Theatres chain,
which recently filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection, said
Monday that it might close underperforming locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to look at the overall business and the viability
of all the assets,'' said Michael Solomon, a turnaround specialist
named last week to the post of chief executive officer of WestStar
Cinemas Inc. ``One of the beauties of filing for Chapter 11 is we
now have the time to look at our options.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said no timetable has been set for possible closures or
filing a reorganization plan with the bankruptcy court. He plans to
seek renegotiation of lease agreements for Mann, which operates 54
theaters with 357 screens including the legendary Mann Chinese in
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Encino-based Mann has lagged rivals in building megaplex
theaters that cater to customers' preference for multiple screens,
tiered seating and staggered start times. Mann's only megaplex
among its 27 Southern California theaters is the 9-month-old Plant
16 in Panorama City and analysts have been warning that outmoded
multiplexes are creating cash-flow problems for operators.
</P>
<P>
   Mann's other local sites include the six-screen Agoura Mann, the
Village 8 in Westlake Village, the eight-screen Janss Marketplace
in Thousand Oaks, the four-screen Buenaventura in Ventura, the
five-screen Simi Valley Mann, the Marketplace 4 in Glendale, the
10-screen Exchange in Glendale, the nine-screen Valley West in
Tarzana, the eight-screen Granada Hills Mann and the seven-screen
Mann Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said the bankruptcy filing, which will have no immediate
impact on operations, was necessary in order for Mann to remain
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``As our industry continues to change, the expense of
retrofitting older, traditionally formatted theaters with
state-of-the-art technology has increased dramatically,'' Solomon
said. ``We believe it is in the best interests of all our
constituents to complete a strategic restructuring of the company,
thereby improving its financing structure and creating an
opportunity for capital infusion to make upgrades to our
theaters.''
</P>
<P>
   WestStar, an affiliate of Wall Street investment bank Warburg
Dillon Read, listed assets and debts at more than $100 million each
in the filing with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Wilmington, Del. It
has obtained up to $15 million of debtor-in-possession financing
from a group of creditors, led by Canadian Imperial Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``With our DIP financing in place, we are confident we will have
adequate financial resources to continue to operate uninterrupted
during the reorganization process,'' Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   Warburg Pincus, which bought the chain in 1997 for $165 million,
put Mann up for sale in January but was unable to find a buyer.
Solomon said his major task will not be to sell the company but to
improve its performance so that a sale will be more viable.
</P>
<P>
   Declining box office at older theaters has led to owners closing
the Americana 5 in Panorama City and the six-screen UA Warner
Center in Woodland Hills this summer. General Cinemas recently
announced it is seeking to sell its six Los Angeles-area theaters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
