<HEADER>
A9632 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FIELD-DREAMS-KAN &LR;      09-21 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIELD-DREAMS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHUBARB SPRINGS FROM `FIELD OF DREAMS' BASEBALL DIAMOND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DYERSVILLE, Iowa _ In the movie ``Field of Dreams,'' the ghost
of Shoeless Joe Jackson emerges from a stand of corn onto a
baseball outfield and asks: ``Is this heaven?''
</P>
<P>
   Although Kevin Costner's young farmer character responds ``No,
it's Iowa,'' the film implies that the hereafter has a rival in the
base paths and a backstop amid Midwestern farmland.
</P>
<P>
   Fans charmed by the movie's romance with baseball and farm life
have come here ever since, chasing fly balls and nostalgia on the
movie set playing field.
</P>
<P>
   But this piece of Iowa is heaven no more.
</P>
<P>
   The field's caretakers _ Becky and Don Lansing own most of the
infield and right field, Rita and Al Ameskamp hold deed to left and
center fields _ can't seem to get along.
</P>
<P>
   In a conflict perhaps as American as the game the field
celebrates, the Lansings and Ameskamps peddle souvenirs out of
competing shacks and regularly settle scores at meetings of the
county zoning panel.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' Don Lansing said. ``It takes away from the
field and the fun for the fans.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel real bad about it every day,'' echoed Rita Ameskamp.
``It's all about one word _ control.''
</P>
<P>
   The field remains a pleasant, if out-of-the-way, stop. On Labor
Day, families streamed to the field throughout the day to pose for
pictures where Costner, James Earl Jones, Burt Lancaster and Ray
Liotta brought to life the novel Shoeless Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heads up.'' A foul ball sails over the backstop. Another
whack, as ash slaps horsehide. In the informal batting practice
here, everybody swings not for the fences but for the corn. A
grade-schooler connects with a pitch. ``Atta boy!''
</P>
<P>
   An overhead power line marks each family's portion of the field,
but the grass is equally green on both sides, and the division
around third base is seamless.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Lansings say the Ameskamps sully the field with too much
commercialization. The Ameskamps say they're only doing what the
Lansings have done for a decade: making money off the movie.
</P>
<P>
   So now tourists coming down the gravel road tend to pause at the
entrances to two lanes, separated by a few yards, leading to the
field. The Lansings' sign beckons visitors to the ``Original Field
of Dreams Movie Site.'' The Ameskamps' hails travelers into the
``Left &AMP; Center Field of Dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It confused me for a second,'' said Myra Hayes of
Indianapolis. ``But then we figured out that they both go to the
same place.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood came to Dyersville in 1988, when producers went
looking for an idyllic Iowa farmstead. The white two-story home
with the wraparound porch where Don Lansing was born, and where his
family has lived for more than 90 years, fit their vision.
</P>
<P>
   For 15 weeks, he moved out and the filmmakers moved in. They
filmed Costner walking his cornfield and hearing a bodiless voice
promise ``If you build it, he will come.'' To the consternation of
his wife and the puzzled looks of his neighbors, Costner's
character carves a playing field out of the edge of his cornfield.
</P>
<P>
   His seemingly irrational decision to put a baseball diamond in
the middle of nowhere eventually brings the farmer peace with the
memory of his late father and saves the farm when people pay to
watch games there.
</P>
<P>
   After the filming, Lansing left his portion of the field intact.
``I thought it was neat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The film first screened in late April 1989. By early May of that
year, Lansing said, ``people just started showing up.''
</P>
<P>
   Tourists had to settle for most of the dreamy field. The
Ameskamps had plowed their land again and planted corn.
</P>
<P>
   Lansing began selling T-shirts, he said, to offset the cost of
keeping up the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 people came that first summer. By the spring of
1990, both families realized the attraction ``Field of Dreams'' had
made of their farmland. The Ameskamps restored their portion of the
ball field.
</P>
<P>
   Since they rebuilt it, the people have come. About 15,000 that
summer. Fantasy camps and exhibitions put on by Ghost Players teams
wearing old Chicago White Sox uniforms more than doubled those
numbers in subsequent years. This season, Dyersville is on track to
attract nearly 55,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so neat,'' said Mark Mason, who brought his two teen-age
sons with him from Effingham, Ill. ``It looks just like the movie,
and you don't have to pay anything to throw around a ball. My boys
will remember this their whole lives.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lansings met when Becky, a fan of the movie traveling from
her Boulder, Colo., home to see a cousin in Wisconsin, took a side
trip to the field in the summer of 1995.
</P>
<P>
   They married the next year, about the time the Ameskamps brought
in investors to manage their operation and the competition between
the two owners began to grow more tense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al has been fighting cancer for the last four years,'' said
Keith Rahe, who manages the Ameskamps' part of the field. ``I don't
think it's so bad that they should have this income for their
retirement years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lansings see nothing wrong with capitalizing on the luck
that made a movie set of three acres in eastern Iowa. But it's a
matter of scale, they say.
</P>
<P>
   When the Ameskamps sought a zoning change to put in batting
cages, the Lansings blocked them. When the Ameskamps wanted to
expand their gift shop, the Lansings got the county zoning board to
prevent the building of anything larger than their own. (Both sides
sell jerseys and caps and key chains. The Lansings have replaced
the white fence that circled their house in the movie with a vinyl
facsimile and sell pickets from the original for $25 apiece.)
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, the spat brought an end to organized games. Now
the Ghost Players, a traveling exhibition team that includes a few
extras from the film, perform their comedy routine using only left
and center fields.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' Rahe said, ``neighbors can't help fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   Things grew more bitter this summer, when the Ameskamps' Left &AMP;
Center outfit enlisted a seed company to sponsor the making of
``the most colossal corn maze on earth'' _ as their Web site calls
it _ beyond the outfield and charged $6 a head for tourists to poke
their way through.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was just the last straw for us,'' Becky Lansing said.
``It shows they have no respect for what's special out here.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early years, the Lansings and the Ameskamps talked about
managing the field jointly, maybe running a single gift shop. But
every meeting only left each side angrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've tried to get together and run it as one operation,''
Rita Ameskamp said. ``But the percentage they would give us was
nothing. They must feel that their side is more important to them
than ours is to us. We think ours is important because the ghost
players came out of our (corn) field....
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's ever going to get any better between us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0103EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9633 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-NUCLEAR-SECURITY     09-21 0429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NUCLEAR-SECURITY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: RUSHED JOB ON NUCLEAR SECURITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Tuesday, Sept. 21:
</P>
<P>
   Congress wants to reorganize the Department of Energy in order
to increase security at the nuclear weapons laboratories and
production plants that the department oversees. Such a step is
clearly needed to end the loose handling of classified material
that was discovered in the wake of allegations that the Chinese
government stole nuclear secrets from the labs. These concerns
remain despite the slight improvement in security procedures
claimed by the Energy Department Monday.
</P>
<P>
   This page initially favored removing the nuclear weapons
programs from the Energy Department entirely, given its long
history of mismanagement, and placing them instead in a fully
independent agency reporting directly to the White House. That was
one of the options recommended by the president's Foreign
Intelligence Advisory Board. But Congress has chosen to follow the
alternative route, also recommended by the board, of creating a
semi-independent agency within the Energy Department. In doing so,
it must be careful that its cure does not create other problems of
its own.
</P>
<P>
   A sound approach was taken by the Senate, which in July approved
formation of an agency to be run by an undersecretary of energy who
would have broad management powers, but would report to the energy
secretary. That left sufficient oversight in the secretary's office
to win the acquiescence of Energy Secretary Bill Richardson. But a
reorganization plan approved by the House last week, as part of the
defense authorization bill, would create an agency that could
largely escape departmental oversight even in critical areas like
environment, health and safety that are unrelated to security.
</P>
<P>
   The National Governors' Association, 46 state attorneys general
and the National Conference of state Legislatures have also
expressed fear that the new legislation would lessen their ability
to enforce state environmental regulations in the cleanup of
federal nuclear facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate should reject the proposed measure, which has not
been subject to any hearings or public scrutiny, and insist that
the legislation be clarified to ensure that states' regulatory
powers will not be weakened, and that the new agency will be
subject to meaningful oversight by the Energy Department in
environmental and safety matters. These concerns are too important
to let slip in a hastily drafted reorganization.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
