<SLUG> BC-ROCK-LIQUOR-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CD-ROM CARRIES LESSON IN LIQUOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The war against binge drinking on college campuses has featured
many weapons _ alcohol bans, lectures, newspaper advertisements,
alcohol awareness sessions.
</P>
<P>
   Now some colleges are using a new weapon appropriate for these
high-tech times. Alcohol 101 is an interactive CD-ROM that walks
students through a virtual party and virtual bar to teach them
about the dangers of drinking too much.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Karen McCarthy, a Democrat from Kansas City, said
during a demonstration Monday at Rockhurst University that Alcohol
101 could be an important tool in the battle to keep students
responsible about their intake of alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in college, I had no idea what the effects of
alcohol were on my body,'' she said. ``This will help students
understand the effects of alcohol and the choices we choose to make
when we use alcohol.''
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol 101 was developed by the University of Illinois and paid
for by the Century Council, a group of American liquor distillers.
It is aimed at fighting drunken driving and underage drinking.
</P>
<P>
   Rockhurst already has been using Alcohol 101 as part of an
educational program for underage students caught drinking, said Liz
Brent, vice president for student development.
</P>
<P>
   But some Rockhurst students who checked out the program Monday
said they thought the new weapon probably would have the same
effect on campus drinking that others have had _ not much.
</P>
<P>
   The program will get students' attention because it shows how
quickly alcohol streams through a drinker's blood, impairing the
person's judgment and balance, said Mary Klump, an 18-year-old
Rockhurst freshman.
</P>
<P>
   But students enjoying a party on a weekend probably won't make
their decisions based on a CD-ROM they used weeks or months before,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She and other students said their peers would react more
strongly to firsthand accounts of how alcohol destroyed a person's
life, not to computer simulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (CD) seems kind of funny, kind of goofy,'' said Casey
McGraw, a 21-year-old Rockhurst student from Independence who has
lived on campus for four years.
</P>
<P>
   He said it doesn't show the real-life effect drinking can have
on alcoholics and their families, as well as the victims of
drunken-driving accidents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
