<HEADER>
A9642 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI &LR;      09-21 1145
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UW MATCHUP ELECTRIFYING FOR COLORADO'S GREGORAK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOULDER, Colo. _ It's Washington week. Somebody get a fire truck
near Ty Gregorak in case he spontaneously combusts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe it's already here; I can't wait,'' Colorado's
star junior linebacker said Monday. ``Now I'm going to have to
watch (myself). It's going to be real emotional for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregorak probably won't need a plane to get to Seattle, not
after he traded his adrenal gland for a liquid hydrogen booster.
</P>
<P>
   For sure, he won't need a map.
</P>
<P>
   ``That stadium and team was my whole life,'' he said. ``Purple
and gold. The Washington program was it when I grew up. They'd won
a national championship, they were sending players to the NFL. That
was everything to me.''
</P>
<P>
   He might have grown up on the wrong side of the state _ he was a
three-sport star and honor student at Spokane's West Valley High _
but he was a Pup down to his last thought before sleep.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he is a Buffalo. Perhaps more than anything, that
symbolizes why Rick Neuheisel is at Washington and one of the
richest coaches in college football.
</P>
<P>
   His presence at Washington is also why Gregorak and his Buffs
teammates want to slap _ figuratively, it is presumed _ the smirk
off his face.
</P>
<P>
   The eagerness in this yuppie college town for Saturday's matchup
game is like a 5-year-old's for Christmas, times about seven.
Contempt for Neuheisel in general, and his unexpected departure in
particular, have fueled a public mad-on that the new coaching staff
is trying to keep from consuming Gregorak and his mates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, this team has grown beyond that,'' Buffs coach Gary
Barnett insisted Monday at his weekly media briefing. ``If this
game were played six months ago, it would be different. Now, both
teams think this is a must-win.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to remove the personalities and play between the
lines. The early losses by both teams take something out of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right.
</P>
<P>
   Just like nobody in this region is panicking because the NFL
champion Broncos have started 0-2. Given the hysteria surrounding
the Broncos and the sense of abandonment surrounding Neuheisel,
there's enough sports psychoses here in the Rockies to fill a year
of Jerry Springer shows.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to the widespread angst, Barnett has closed practice
to reporters this week and is attempting to cut down on interview
availability. CU athletic director Dick Tharp, who responded to
Barbara Hedges' hijacking of Neuheisel by hijacking Barnett from
Northwestern, is also a hard fellow to track down.
</P>
<P>
   One guy who can't shut up is Gregorak, a glib communications
major who spent most of an hour Monday filling reporters' notebooks
about his feelings for Neuheisel and Washington. Calm and
undemonstrative during his media chat, he nevertheless conveyed a
wistfulness about his decision to go elsewhere for college.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough to leave,'' he said. ``My family and friends have
a long way to travel to see me. But I love Colorado. This is where
I want to be after I'm done with football.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he avoided any directly critical remarks Monday, it was
plain that during recruiting in the fall of 1996, Gregorak and the
regime of former coach Jim Lambright failed to click. The all-state
pick was offered a UW scholarship, but with not nearly the
enthusiasm he received from Colorado, Ohio State and even
Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what was going through Washington's mind during
the recruiting process,'' he said. ``I don't want to say anything
negative about the staff, but I think if Don James had still been
there, there's a good chance I'd be a Husky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never got a real strong positive feeling from the staff. I
never felt real comfortable. It wasn't a place I saw myself
spending the next four or five years.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregorak admits Washington figured he was too slow _ ``which I
am,'' he said _ but was also utterly charmed by Neuheisel and his
staff at Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   ``The staff was a big part of it. They really know how to
recruit. I knew nothing about Colorado growing up. But they made me
feel special, especially (Bobby) Hauck.''
</P>
<P>
   Hauck, 34, was Colorado's recruiting coordinator and special
teams coach who is considered aces when it comes to the art of
adolescent persuasion. He also left Colorado to join Neuheisel at
Washington, their third school together.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a mom in the world who doesn't love him,''
Gregorak said. ``My mom still talks about him.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss of Gregorak was representative of the continuing drain
of home-grown talent away from Washington, which used to need only
wink at most top prep prospects in-state. Although no one around
the program will say much publicly, the biggest knock against
Lambright was that some of his own players weren't endorsing the
program to prospective recruits.
</P>
<P>
   That realization apparently drove Hedges to make her bold,
astonishing run at Neuheisel. Beyond money, the expense of that
maneuver could be tallied in the won-lost record Saturday as the
Buffaloes unleash the fury from the perceived piracy.
</P>
<P>
   But the Huskies' 0-2 start also helps make the case that the
program under Lambright was in full decay.
</P>
<P>
   Gregorak was at the heart of the Neuheisel betrayal last winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, everyone was shocked and disturbed by it,'' he said.
``I found out about it from friends and family back home that it
was happening. We'd just come off winning a bowl game over Oregon,
and that week we had had a bunch of top recruits on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   When Neuheisel returned from Seattle to meet briefly with his
old players, Gregorak uttered his now-notorious remark at the
meeting, the only Buff to speak: ``We'll see you on Sept. 25.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregorak says now the remark was misinterpreted, that he meant
it more as a farewell than a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respected the guy for flying back from Seattle and wanting
to meet us,'' he said. ``After his statement, he asked for
questions or comments. There was about a minute of silence. Then I
just said, `See you on Sept. 25th.' I didn't mean it the way it's
come out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope Rick and the staff have great careers. It takes
practice to be a good coach, and I don't mean this in a bad way,
but he'll probably be better there than he was here. He learned a
lot, and will take experiences from here and learn more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope he takes Washington back to where it was in the early
'90s.''
</P>
<P>
   Gregorak's education obviously has included classes in
diplomacy.
</P>
<P>
   But making nice with the press is one thing. Sweet oratory will
be utterly absent from the Colorado side Saturday when it comes to
Neuheisel and Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming Gregorak doesn't explode on first contact.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
