<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTEBOOK-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS NOTES: SMITH SILENCES OVER-THE-HILL TALK
</HEADLINE>
 1st WRITETHRU (adds notes) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. and JEFF CAPLAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A year ago, running back Emmitt Smith rebutted
charges that he was on the downside of his legendary career.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, he continued to distance himself from the
over-the-hill talk, rushing 29 times for 108 yards and two
touchdowns to help spark the Cowboys' 24-7 victory against the
Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Smith ran past former Cowboys running back Tony
Dorsett into fourth place on the NFL's all-time rushing list. Smith
has 12,783 yards in his 10-year career. Dorsett rushed for 12,739
yards in 12 years with the Cowboys and Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   Fittingly, Smith did it on the night the Cowboys set aside to
honor some of the greatest players in the franchise's 40-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   While former critics continue to be amazed by Smith's
resurgence, the former Florida Gators star said he's playing well
because his offensive line is playing well.
</P>
<P>
   And what gives Smith hope that he will do even better than last
season _ he rushed for 1,332 yards in 1998 after having subpar
seasons in 1996 and 1997 _ is the presence of center Mark
Stepnoski. Smith said an already-good offensive line turned into a
potentially great one with the free-agent addition of Stepnoski,
who played with the Oilers the past four years.
</P>
<P>
   The game plan Monday night was to let Stepnoski and the Cowboys'
offensive line to pave the way for Smith against the Falcons'
defense. The 29 carries were the most for Smith since 1995. The
plan worked, even though two regular starters, Erik Williams and
Everett McIver, were sidelined with injuries.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys are 84-14 when Smith has at least 20 attempts. They
are 55-9 when he tops the 100-yard mark.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE THE LOCKER ROOM: Sherman Williams certainly commands a
lot of respect from the coaching staff, which is interesting
considering that the Cowboys have tried their best to get rid of
him the past two years. They cut him before training camp last
season but brought him back before the season opened because of
injuries. They had no intention of him being with the team this
year, but injuries again necessitated a return. He was signed
Thursday and was the Cowboys' chief kickoff returner Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The competition between receivers Chris Brazzell and Jason
Tucker to not get cut when defensive tack Leon Lett comes back
continued last night. It likely will be based on who is the better
specials-teams player. Brazzell got his chance against the
Redskins, and Tucker got his chance last night.
</P>
<P>
   With receiver Raghib Ismail sidelined in the first quarter by a
strained left shoulder, Michael Irvin attracted some of his old
double-coverage treatment from the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way players are still en vogue with the Cowboys, even
without Deion Sanders. Rookie defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban,
drafted in the first round to shore up the Cowboys' pass rush,
showed his versatility last night as a short-yardage tight end.
Ekuban had the key block on Emmitt Smith's first-quarter touchdown
run. He also plays on defense as a nickel pass rusher.
</P>
<P>
   VICTORY ROCKET BOOSTED, AGAIN: Cowboys receiver Raghib
``Rocket'' Ismail didn't need a dramatic touchdown this time. And
he didn't play the whole game; however, he made his presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   Ismail keyed the Cowboys' first touchdown bailing the offense
out of a third-and-13 hole by turning a simple slant pass into a
38-yard catch and sprint.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys spread Atlanta out with a four-receiver set. Ismail,
who was lined up in the slot, took advantage of one-on-one coverage
against Falcons safety Eugene Robinson, whose 38-year-old legs
couldn't keep up.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons caught up with Ismail at the 9-yard line and knocked
him out the game for remainder of the first half with a sprained
left shoulder. Two plays later, running back Emmitt Smith scored on
a 1-yard run.
</P>
<P>
   ELLIS GOES ALL THE WAY: What a difference a year has made for
defensive end Greg Ellis.
</P>
<P>
   Previously known as the player the Cowboys drafted in the first
round of the 1998 NFL draft instead of Randy Moss, Ellis has become
a bit of a second-year phenomenon. In the season opener, he was the
lone bright spot on the Cowboys' defense with two sacks.
</P>
<P>
   In last night's 24-7 defeat of Atlanta, Ellis tipped a Danny
Kanell pass with about one minute to play in the game and hauled it
in for his first career interception, returning it 87 yards for a
touchdown. The play was the fifth-longest return for an
interception in Cowboys history.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER KEY PLAYS: The Texas Stadium turf did its part when
Atlanta running back Jamal Anderson went down in the first quarter
without being hit. He lost 2 yards on the play, and suffered a
sprained knee that knocked him out of the game. With quarterback
Chris Chandler already out, the Falcons' offense ran out of
options.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense did its part as well, highlighted by a
crucial third-and-one stop in the third quarter. Defensive tackle
Chad Hennings led the charge with his first sack of the season. He
also added the double-whammy by forcing Falcons quarterback Tony
Graziani to fumble. Alonzo Spellman recovered, and Smith followed
with his second touchdown of the game to up the score to 17-0.
</P>
<P>
   GAME BALLS: Defensive tackle Chad Hennings had two sacks,
doubling his total of last season. His first sack in the third
quarter caused a fumble that led the Cowboys' second touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive coordinator Dave Campo rallied his troops, who gave up
504 yards to Washington in the season opener. The Cowboys held
Atlanta to 14 yards total offense in the third quarter after giving
up more than 180 in the third quarter to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail had only one catch, but
it was a 38-yarder that set up the Cowboys' first touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Running back Emmitt Smith finished with 29 carries for 108 yards
and both Cowboys touchdowns and moved past Tony Dorsett into fourth
place on the NFL's all-time rushing list.
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker Dexter Coakley had an interception and a sack and was
the spark plug for the defense early in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Right tackle Tony Hutson stepped in for Erik Williams and didn't
allow a sack.
</P>
<P>
   TWO-WAY PLAYER: Rookie defensive end Ebenezer Ekuban debuted on
offense during the Cowboys' first-quarter touchdown drive. With the
Cowboys on the Falcons' 3-yard line, Ekuban lined up on first down
as a blocking tight end in motion. Emmitt Smith followed his lead
on a dive for 1 yard.
</P>
<P>
   On second down, Ekuban moved to the left side of the line in a
two tight-end set. This time, Ekuban stuffed right end Chuck Smith
allowing Emmitt Smith to walk around left end and into the end zone
for a 10-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   NO GO ON FG: The Cowboys passed up an opportunity to take
advantage of an obscure and rarely implemented rule.
</P>
<P>
   If a half or the game ends with a fair catch on a punt, the
receiving team can take a free kick, an unobstructed field goal
from the spot of the fair catch.
</P>
<P>
   Wane McGarity made a fair catch of a Dan Stryzinski punt on the
Atlanta 47 as time expired in the first half. Leading 10-0, the
Cowboys opted not to attempt what would have been a 64-yard field.
The NFL record is 63 yards set by Tom Dempsey and matched by the
Broncos' Jason Elam.
</P>
<P>
   SERVING UP FALCON: Troy Aikman entered the game 3-1 against the
Falcons as a starting quarterback. The following is a list of
Aikman's statistics in those four starts against Atlanta: Date
score statistics 9/17/89 at Atlanta L,27-21 13-23-2-241, 1 TD
12/21/92 at Atlanta W,41-17 18-21-0-239, 3 TDs 10/29/95 at Atlanta
W,28-13 19-25-1-198, 2 TDs 10/20/96 vs. Atlanta W,32-28
17-24-0-265, 2 TDs 9/20/99 vs. Atlanta W,24-7 10-22-2-109, 0 TDs
</P>
<P>
   SANDERS SITS: Deion Sanders' status for last night's game was
going to be a game-timedecision, however Sanders clearly made his
decision well before game time. Sanders was decked out in his usual
practice grays several hours before kickoff.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders continues to say he will not play until he is 100
percent. His projected return is Oct. 30, after this week's bye,
when the Cowboys play host to division rival Arizona, the team he
hurt his big toe against last season.
</P>
<P>
   INJURY LIST: Erik Williams, RT, quadricep during warmups,
strained right quadricep. Did not return. Tony Hutson started at
right tackle
</P>
<P>
   Raghib Ismail, WR, sprained left shoulder Everett McIver, RG,
straied right hamstring Emmitt Smith, RB, sprained ankle
</P>
<P>
   COWBOYS INACTIVE LIST: WR Chris Brazzell, TE Mike Lucky, CB
Kevin Smith, S Kenny Wheaton
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
