<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-GAMER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS DEFEAT DEFENDING NFC CHAMPS, 24-7
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The Dallas Cowboys joined the Detroit Lions as
the only 2-0 teams in the NFC by finishing fast on ``Monday Night
Football'' for a 24-7 victory against the Atlanta Falcons, the
defending conference champions, Monday night at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons, who have lost a record nine consecutive Monday
night games dating to 1982, were shut out by the Cowboys until four
minutes were left. Then, as the Falcons were driving for a
touchdown that would have cut the Cowboys' lead to 17-14, defensive
end Greg Ellis stepped in front of a Danny Kanell pass and returned
it 87 yards for a game-icing touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just in the right place at the right time,'' Ellis said.
The pass ``hit me in the face mask. I would've looked bad if I
hadn't caught it. ... then when I started running, I didn't think I
was going to make it'' all the way.
</P>
<P>
   With Emmitt Smith and Ellis providing the legs for this victory,
the Cowboys sit alone atop the NFC East. It's their first 2-0 start
since 1995, the last time Dallas went to the Super Bowl. The
Cowboys are 29-10-1 in home openers.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that the national anthem was sung by Waylon
Jennings, who needed the assistance of a walking cane to get in and
out of a golf cart, which carried the country &AMP; western singer on
and off the field.
</P>
<P>
   Because this game was not for the weak of heart.
</P>
<P>
   For Atlanta, quarterback Chris Chandler didn't start because of
a hamstring injury and running back Jamal Anderson was gone less
than six minutes into the game because of a sprained right knee
that he incurred on a noncontact play.
</P>
<P>
   For Dallas, offensive tackle Erik Williams strained his right
quadriceps muscle in pregame warmups and didn't play, and speedy
receiver Raghib ``Rocket'' Ismail sprained his left shoulder late
in the first quarter, while making his first catch of the game, and
he missed the remainder of the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith carried 29 times for 108 yards and became the NFL's
fourth all-time leading rusher, surpassing Tony Dorsett. By
halftime, Smith was running behind an offensive line that included
Tony Hutson at right tackle and Ben Fricke at right guard. Fricke
played more than half the game in place of Everett McIver (strained
hamstring).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was surprised the way Hutson and Fricke played,'' Cowboys
coach Chan Gailey said. ``(The Falcons) weren't just coming through
there all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Among all the injuries, none was bigger than Atlanta's loss of
Anderson, who ``was'' Atlanta's game plan with young Tony Graziani
starting at quarterback. Anderson, the defending NFC rushing
champion, will undergo a magnetic resonance imaging today.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, who was making only his third NFL start, hurt his team
by trying too hard early in the third quarter when he left the
pocket and fumbled deep in Falcons territory. Chad Hennings forced
it. Alonzo Spellman recovered it. Seven plays later, the Cowboys'
offense cashed in on it with a touchdown to take a 17-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   This game was more than just about the walking wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's feat came with Dorsett in attendance at Texas Stadium,
where he was joined by more than 100 other all-time Cowboys greats
in a halftime ceremony to commemorate the 40th anniversary of the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   It was fitting that Smith, who has 128 career rushing touchdowns
(compared with Dorsett's 72) eclipsed Dorsett's 12,739 career
rushing yards on his way into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's milestone breaker came on a 7-yard carry with 11:24
remaining in the third quarter, putting the Cowboys in front, 17-0.
Center Mark Stepnoski opened a hole about the size of Georgia,
through which Smith dashed and scored standing up.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, this was a game of attrition, with the Cowboys
holding onto a 10-0 halftime lead against a team without its two
best offensive players.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys linebacker Dexter Coakley returned a first-quarter
interception 43 yards to the Atlanta 10, but that resulted in only
three points.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Troy Aikman wasn't sharp early, and the Cowboys
stalled inside the 20, settling for a 23-yard Richie Cunningham
field goal to take a 3-0 lead with 9:53 remaining in the first
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson left with a knee sprain, the Cowboys rode a
would-be 46-yard punt return to the Atlanta 22, but it was
nullified by an illegal block called on Robert Thomas. But the
struggle continued for the Falcons, and the Cowboys responded by
mounting a seven-play, 60-yard touchdown drive at the end of the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Smith scored the first of his two touchdowns on a 2-yard left
sweep behind the block of rookie Ebenezer Ekuban, a converted
defensive end playing tight end in goal-line situations. Ekuban
sealed off Falcons defensive end Chuck Smith on the play.
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta, with Kanell replacing Graziani in Atlanta's dismal
third quarter (12 yards total offense), roared back with Tim Dwight
at the end of a 45-yard pass play for a touchdown with four minutes
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell later hit Kevin Mathis for 52 yards at the Dallas 8 on a
pass that caromed off two Cowboys defenders _ Duane Hawthorne and
George Teague _ but three plays later, Ellis intercepted a pass and
put the Dirty Birds on ice. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0136EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0031 </DOCNO>
