r s BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-T     09-21 0781
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
 
IN NFL GONE BAD, CHEAP WIN GOLDEN (For use by NYTimes News Service
clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cheap wins don't happen in today's NFL. Even
when the other club loses its all-world running back early in the
evening, and its Pro Bowl quarterback never took a snap due to
injury. A cheap win still doesn't compute, not by the league's
current standards.
</P>
<P>
   This brand of football has become all about a cut-rate,
bargain-basement, attention-Kmart-shoppers, made-in-Taiwan,
army-navy-store, dynasty-killing Sunday and Monday of mediocre
teams attempting to survive week to week.
</P>
<P>
   At halftime Monday night at Texas Stadium, the Dallas Cowboys
paraded more than 100 of their alums across the field in a tribute
to 40 years of what has consistently been an era of excellence.
</P>
<P>
   It's logical to assume these old-timers privately giggle when
they see what passes for the NFL of the late '90s. Salary cap, free
agency, expansion _ one and all have combined to transfer the
league into a shadow of its former self.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also the same as in any other season _ there's a
division to be won, a conference to be won, and, yes, a Super Bowl
berth to be earned.
</P>
<P>
   And frankly, it might as well be the Cowboys contending strongly
for all that, particularly in the NFC. Even if the league is in an
early-evaluation period, it's obvious the Cowboys are basically as
good as anyone else in the conference, and better than most. What
that says about the NFC is nobody is worth a flip. Not yet, anyway,
and probably never.
</P>
<P>
   But don't attempt to make a dummy drill out of Monday night's
24-7 win over the Atlanta Falcons, who nine months ago were the
NFC's Super Bowl rep.
</P>
<P>
   Taking advantage of what ails the opposition remains a survival
must, and for an ailing Atlanta that included quarterback Chris
Chandler, a no-go due to last week's hamstring ailment. From
Chandler to backup Tony Graziani is a Grand Canyon drop in class,
meaning the Falcons had only one chance to win Monday night _ and
then Jamal Anderson's evening also wrapped up quickly.
</P>
<P>
   There would be no jamming with Jamal after Anderson attempted a
cut on Jerry Jones' fake grass. His knee didn't hold up when his
shoe grabbed, and Jamal was finished for the night. That was on the
Falcons' second possession. You can slide by in today's NFL when
missing defensive stars (right, Nine-Toed?), but take away vital
offensive weapons and it's good-bye, bay-bee.
</P>
<P>
   Once Anderson was gone, the strategy became very simple for the
Cowboys: don't make any stupid mistakes and wait for Graziani's
lack of savvy to take over.
</P>
<P>
   It almost worked in both areas, too. Graziani helped the Cowboys
to 10 of their first 17 points. A Dexter Coakley interception set
up an early field goal, and when Chad Hennings, who had a very
active night, forced a third- quarter fumble by Graziani, it led to
a 17-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Some late mistakes by a young Cowboys secondary actually allowed
the Falcons to make it slightly interesting, but...
</P>
<P>
   A sure win became a sure win.
</P>
<P>
   On the down side, the Cowboys' offense struggled against a game
and solid Atlanta defense. Chan Gailey had billed the Falcons'
defense as the best his offense would face all season, and he'd
better be right. Troy Aikman, for one, hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   Aikman tried to take what was offered upstairs, which wasn't
that much. Plus, his arm wasn't exactly sharp. The Cowboys were
missing some offensive pieces of their own in the line. Tackle Erik
Williams damaged himself in pre-game warmups and didn't play and
guard Everett McIver went out in the first half and didn't return.
Aikman was under heavy pressure, and that may be why.
</P>
<P>
   Emmitt Smith gave the offense a boost with his work on the
ground, which was just enough Cowboys leverage to bend and finally
break the Atlanta defense.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly after last week in Washington, give the Cowboys'
defense it's share of credit. But it was also a defense blessed
with field position galore. The difference in the game? Start right
where the Falcons were forced to begin their offensive possessions.
</P>
<P>
   There was great Atlanta field position to begin with, but
starting at their 44 didn't benefit the Falcons when Coakley picked
off Graziani.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the Falcons got the ball back at the 20-, 25-, 13-,
10-, 7-, 8- and, moving to the start of the second half, the
15-yard line. And that's when Graziani fumbled, leading to a 17-0,
game-over, Cowboys lead.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing cheap about it. Win now, win often enough, and there's a
division, a conference, and, who knows, maybe a Super Bowl,
definitely up for grabs in an NFL gone bad. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
