<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS EDGE GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Growing up in Montreal, Eric Gagne didn't know
about the strange things that happen between the Los Angeles
Dodgers and San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it appeared Gagne might win his first major-league
game he couldn't have realized what goes on between these two
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's 6-5 victory in front of 33,280 at Dodger Stadium
was typical, won on a ninth-inning, bases-loaded single by Eric
Karros off Jerry Spradlin.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored three runs after Gagne was lifted for a pinch
hitter in the fifth. But the Giants scored three runs in the
seventh, two on a home run by J.T. Snow to tie the game at 5.
</P>
<P>
   With a good chance to start the final game between the clubs
Sept. 30 at Candlestick Park, Gagne got a glimpse of one of
baseball's most storied rivalries _ warts and all.
</P>
<P>
   As with the second inning, when Ellis Burks took off from first
and Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley made a perfect throw to second _
with nobody covering the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek and second baseman Eric Young had a
long and animated conversation about the blunder, which went down
as an error on Young because right-handed hitting Rich Aurilia was
at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The play didn't result in a run, but no doubt will go down as
the symbol for the Dodgers' season.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Giants, they are technically still in the National
League West race. Division-leading Arizona came in with an
eight-game lead over San Francisco and 13 games to play. The
Diamondbacks, who could clinch this weekend in San Francisco, lost
12-7 on Monday to Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers appeared to get Gagne his first victory by scoring
three runs in the fifth inning after he was lifted for pinch hitter
Craig Counsell.
</P>
<P>
   Counsell opened with a walk and one out later took third on a
double by Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield was intentionally walked and Karros followed with
a two-run double into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz was replaced by left-hander Rich Rodriguez, who escaped
big trouble when center fielder Marvin Bernard took away extra
bases from Devon White with a leaping catch at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield scored on the sacrifice fly to give the Dodgers a 5-2
lead, but it could have been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth was a nice gift for Gagne, who did not have good
control, walking five in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike his last start against the New York Mets, it didn't
hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants got their run in the first when Bernard opened the
game with a double, stole third and scored when Hundley's throw
sailed into left field.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers took a 2-1 lead on Grudzielanek's third-inning
homer, Bernard tied it in the fifth with an opposite field homer to
left.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne couldn't get him out, but he did far better against the
Giants top hitters, Barry Bonds and Jeff Kent, who went a combined
0 for 6.
</P>
<P>
   After Bernard's homer, Gagne walked Bill Mueller. With a pitch
count nearing 100, it was his last inning, but he went out with a
flourish.
</P>
<P>
   Gagne got Bonds on a pop to the catcher and struck out Kent.
J.T. Snow then popped to third to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Herges took over for Gagne to start the sixth, but didn't
get in trouble until the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   With one out, Bonds doubled to the gap in left-center and scored
on a single by Kent.
</P>
<P>
   Snow was next and quickly got ahead 3-1 in the count.
</P>
<P>
   Herges, who like Gagne was called up in September, threw a
fastball and Snow drove it into the empty right-field pavilion for
his 21st home run.
</P>
</TEXT>
