<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9654 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HN     09-21 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-PIRATES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
PITTSBURGH _ Astros reliever Brian Williams answers to the nickname
``Boogie,'' a tag he earned because of his skill under a disco ball
early in his career.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Apparently, he doesn't have a rain dance in his repertoire;
otherwise, you can bet he would have been giving his teammates a
crash course Monday night at Three Rivers Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After waiting out a rain delay that lasted 1 hour and 42
minutes, the Pirates waltzed to an 11-5 victory over the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   When play was halted in the third inning, the Astros trailed
7-4. League rules permit the umpires to call a rain-delayed game
after waiting at least 1 hour and 15 minutes, but considering the
circumstances _ the Astros are locked in a tight National League
Central Division race with the Reds _ every effort was made to
complete the game.
</P>
<P>
   Because an official game requires a minimum of five innings, the
Astros no doubt would have preferred to have the umpires call the
game _ as they almost certainly would have a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was never any doubt,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker
said. ``We were going to play this game even if we had to stay here
until 2 a.m., and that's the way it should have been. I have no
problem with that.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain also is on the radar for the next two days, and it will be
accompanied by cool temperatures. The Astros can only hope better
pitching is in their forecast.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Three _ Mike Hampton, Jose Lima and Shane Reynolds _
have spent all season lifting each other to new heights. But all
they have done is bring one another down during the most recent
trip through the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Monday was Reynolds' day to struggle, and he did, to the tune of
eight runs (five earned) in 2 innings. Reynolds surrendered the
mound to the bullpen after the rain delay and was left with plenty
of time to ponder his shortest outing since May 31, 1997, when he
was gone after 1 innings against the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   But Reynolds (16-12) shouldn't feel too bad. Lima lasted 3
innings in his last outing, and Hampton was knocked out after 3 the
next day. The trio, which has a combined record of 56-23, has
posted a cumulative ERA of 19.56 in this simultaneous funk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part is that we scored some runs and I didn't do my
job,'' Reynolds said. ``You don't want to get too down, but it's
time for us (the pitchers) to repay the offense. Hopefully the
starters will work out of this funk we're in and finish strong.''
</P>
<P>
   After winning a franchise-record 12 consecutive games, the
Astros have lost four of their last five and have been outscored
46-29 during that stretch. Their opponents have scored at least
eight runs in four of the games.
</P>
<P>
   And for the third time in four days, the Astros were victimized
by a big inning. The Pirates exploded for six runs in the third,
including Brant Brown's three-run homer, which could have brought
on the rain.
</P>
<P>
   The skies opened shortly thereafter, but the Astros appeared all
but washed away before the umpires cleared the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games we've lost on this trip are because teams are
scoring more runs against us in one inning than we're scoring in
the whole game,'' center fielder Carl Everett said. ``That's been
the key.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a smattering of the paid crowd of 10,256 stuck around for
the duration of the game, but it's safe to say everyone who
remained in the ballpark had a good chance to go home with at least
one foul ball. It was so quiet, players had no trouble hearing
individual fans, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   But don't even think about suggesting the dull atmosphere had a
bearing on the Astros' flat performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That didn't have anything to do with it,'' Astros shortstop
Bill Spiers said. ``If we can't get excited about what we have at
stake, then we don't need to be out there. When we won the 12 games
in a row, that was a good time to be winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a good time to be losing, but if we play like
we're capable of playing, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros opened the scoring against an old nemesis, Francisco
Cordova, who allowed an RBI single to Jeff Bagwell in the first.
The Pirates answered in the bottom of the inning with run-producing
singles by Brian Giles and Brown.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell struck again with a two-run single in the second, and
another run scored when Cordova walked Spiers with the bases
loaded. The Astros' three-run inning didn't look so good in the
third when the Pirates doubled that total to put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't get into a groove at all,'' said Reynolds, who
was working without his best pitch, the splitter. ``The weather
wasn't a factor; I just didn't have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Astro Pete Schourek (4-7), who relieved Cordova after the
rain passed, picked up the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0148EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
