<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-DEVILRAYS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT DEVIL RAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Most of his teammates call him ``Fin,'' but
his fellow starters might as well call him ``Gramps.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Finley, who pitched the Anaheim Angels to a 10-5 victory
over the Tampa Bay Devil Rays on Monday night before 16,165 fans
and former Angels manager Terry Collins at Edison Field, turns 37
in November and has become the elder statesman of a starting
rotation that is otherwise young and inexperienced. The average age
of the other four starters _ Ramon Ortiz, Jarrod Washburn, Brian
Cooper and Mike Fyhrie _ is 25.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Angels take a look at their young pitchers, it
would be wise for the young pitchers to take a look at Finley,
according to interim manager Joe Maddon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about the potential of (Finley) visiting and
talking with them,'' Maddon said. ``But if they just watched Chuck
work out, watched him during a game.... If you put a camera on his
face during a game, you don't know how the game is going. He always
has the same look on his face. He knows how to handle himself as a
major-league pitcher.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley went 51/3 innings, allowing three runs and seven hits to
earn his team-leading 11th win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Collins took up Angels general manager Bill Bavasi on his offer
to watch a game from Bavasi's private box, and spent some time in
the press box chatting with reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Collins' visit wasn't just a casual visit, though. Bavasi wants
Collins' input and evaluation of some of the younger players.
</P>
<P>
   ``They just want to know my thoughts about some guys,'' Collins
said. ''I appreciate they asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday's game included one of the most bizarre plays of the
season. You've heard of throwing at a hitter, but what about
throwing at the umpire?
</P>
<P>
   Devil Rays starter Wilson Alvarez (9-8) had just given up a
two-run homer to Garret Anderson in the third inning giving the
Angels a 7-1 lead. The count was 1-1 on the following hitter _ Matt
Walbeck _ when Alvarez's pitch sailed over the glove of catcher
Mike Difelice and grazed plate umpire John Shulock in the head.
</P>
<P>
   The pitch wasn't that high _ about chest-high to Walbeck _ so
Shulock apparently thought it was no accident. An incensed Shulock
charged the mound _ sort of _ and screamed at Alvarez. Devil Rays
manager Larry Rothschild came out and also got an earful from
Shulock.
</P>
<P>
   After Shulock calmed down a little, Rothschild took Alvarez out
of the game. But Difelice had nowhere to go, and stood at the plate
as Shulock screamed some more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
