<P>
   SCI-MARS-ORBITER (Undated) _ The Mars Climate Orbiter arrives at
Mars and undergoes the first of many braking maneuvers that will
leave it in orbit around the red planet to begin an extensive study
of Martian weather and geology. The orbiter will also serve as a
communications relay for the Mars Polar Lander, which will arrive
in December. By John Noble Wilford.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-SPINE (Undated) _ The human spinal cord _ the length of
nerve fibers, neural machinery and blood vessels that constitutes
the southern extension of the central nervous system _ is not as
much of a dullard as scientists have long believed. New studies
demonstrate that far from being a passive conduit, slavishly
ferrying information to and from the brain, or a repository of
unchanging reflexes, the spinal cord has its own contribution to
make. Spinal cord neurons, researchers are finding, are capable of
learning in simple ways, and show changes in response to
environmental cues that many investigators interpret as a form of
memory. By Erica Goode. (2100 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo and graphic are beign sent to NYT photo and
graphic clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HORGAN-MIND (Undated) _ Q and A with John Horgan, who
outraged countless scientists with his book ``The End of Science:
Facing the Limits of Knowledge in the Twilight of the Scientific
Age,'' and now promises to make new enemies with a new work, ``The
Undiscovered Mind _ How the Human Mind Defies Replication,
Medication and Explanation'' (Free Press, $25). By Claudia Dreifus.
(1300 words)
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-PRAIRIE (Undated) _ As habitats go, prairie remnants do a
poor job of sustaining the diversity of life that a large,
continuous stretch of prairie once could. Now, in the aptly named
town of Prairie City, Iowa, 20 miles east of Des Moines, vastness
is making a comeback. So are buffalo, elk, and a variety of plant
species. Prairie City is the location of the Neal Smith National
Wildlife Refuge, a project of the United States Fish and Wildlife
Service, and at about 5,000 acres, the scene of one of the most
ambitious and unlikely efforts to restore a prairie ever tried. By
Sam Hooper Samuels (1200 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WATCH (Undated) _ News and notes on science: Of courting
salamanders, the cooling effect of pollution and telescopes devoted
to looking for asteroids. By Henry Fountain. (700 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-HAND-TRANSPLANT (Undated) _ A year after he received a new
right hand and forearm in a transplant operation in France, Clint
Hallam of Australia has gained a sufficient grip to ride a
motorcycle and even write with a pen, his doctors say. By Lawrence
K. Altman Jr. (900 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ANGINA-SURGERY (Undated) _ It is, quite simply, a mystery:
Researchers treated 182 people with angina, the agonizing and
debilitating pain that is often a precursor to a heart attack, with
a laser that drills holes in the walls of their heart muscles. Half
of the patients got better, even though they had not responded to
standard treatments for angina. And a year after the laser surgery,
many who had been in pain even when resting could walk for blocks
without discomfort. The results, reported in The Lancet, the
British medical journal, were surprising _ all the more so because
the researchers admit they have no idea why the surgery seems to
have worked. By Anne Eisenberg.
</P>
<P>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BRODY-HEALTH (Undated) _ Personal Health column. The
American diet: how sweet it is. Way too sweet. The share of added
sugar in processed foods keeps going up, to the alarm of doctors
and consumer advocates, who say it is a leading cause of obesity
and may be leading to an increase in diabetes. By Jane E. Brody.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-BREAST-FEEDING (New York) _ An essay: Martha, my 3-year-old
daughter, is a drinker. She craves breast milk and she just won't
quit. On the other hand, her twin brother as well as her older
brother weaned themselves at 10 months. What I discovered from
interviews with specialists and a review of the medical research on
breast-feeding was that though Martha and I may be an oddity on the
Upper West Side of Manhattan, in the world at large we are the
norm. The global average is about three years. What's more, data
extrapolated from nonhuman primates suggest that humans might be
wise to nurse their young for several years, said Katherine A.
Dettwyler, an associate professor of anthropology and nutrition at
Texas A&AMP;M University. By Randi Hutter Epstein.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-VITAL-SIGNS (Undated) _ News and notes on health and
fitness:
</P>
<P>
   _ Osteoporosis, a loss in bone density that can lead to
brittleness and fractures even from everyday activities, is a major
cause of crippling disability in women past menopause. Now, a new
study of 3,676 elderly women in Britain and the United States has
shown that the higher their blood pressure, the more severe their
bone density loss.
</P>
<P>
   _ If you worry that you may get the wrong medicine when you go
into the hospital, you aren't alone.
</P>
<P>
   _ More detrimental effects of cocaine, both short and long-term.
</P>
<P>
   _ When children are in an intensive care unit, both they and
their parents seem to do better when the parents can stay with
them.
</P>
