<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINIMED-RISE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MINIMED INSULIN PUMP PROSPECTS BOOST STOCK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON Z. COHEN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ As one of its main products nears approval by the
federal government's Medicare reimbursement arm, MiniMed's stock
has been flirting with record high prices.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of the Los Angeles-based medical products company closed
Monday at $101, up $3.6875 for the day and just shy of last week's
52-week high of $102.875.
</P>
<P>
   The company is awaiting approval for its external insulin pump
by the Health Care Financing Administration, the agency that
decides whether Medicare will reimburse patients for treatments.
</P>
<P>
   The approval is ``highly probable,'' said Kurt Kruger, an
analyst with Banc of America Securities in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   If the federal government decides the product is worth
reimbursing its patients, the pressure will be on private insurers
and HMOs to follow suit, Kruger said.
</P>
<P>
   And all of these approvals probably would mean increased sales
and profits for MiniMed, he said. It's unknown, however, how much
sales would increase with HCFA and HMO adoptions; company officials
were unavailable for comment Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Patients wear MiniMed's insulin pump on a belt. It delivers a
constant dose of insulin through a tube in the abdomen, thus
eliminating the need for repeated injections during the day and
allowing patients to control their dosage of insulin.
</P>
<P>
   Kruger, who recommends the stock as a strong buy, said the stock
price isn't done climbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The potential and the prospects that this company possesses
are just now being realized and appreciated by Wall Street,''
Kruger said. ``They could have margins that are about twice the
level they are now.''
</P>
<P>
   MiniMed controls about 85 percent of the U.S. market and 35
percent of the European market for external insulin pumps and has
only one competitor, Disetronic Holding AG.
</P>
<P>
   ``MiniMed is the hands-down leader and essentially the only
company in the market,'' Kruger said. ``They owe that market share
and that lead position to their superior technology, and more
importantly to their extensive marketing and distribution efforts,
which have built this franchise for them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
