<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 02:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9680 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LAD     09-21 1612
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-CROUSE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAKER: GIANT AMONG MEN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You go to the doctor for a routine physical exam,
you can expect a shot in the arm. Dusty Baker got his last week
from a nurse who, recognizing the San Francisco Giants manager,
proceeded to thank him effusively.
</P>
<P>
   For what, giving good blood? Baker was bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   The nurse went on: ``Since you've been managing the Giants,
we've had hope.''
</P>
<P>
   At that moment he couldn't have felt dizzier if the nurse had
drawn two liters of blood. The patient making the nurse feel
better. That's pretty heady stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was cool,'' Baker says a few days later. ``Real cool.''
</P>
<P>
   Hope, unfortunately, sprang a leak in San Diego over the
weekend. The Giants lost twice to the Padres while the National
League West-leading Arizona Diamondbacks took two against Florida
to give themselves an eight-game cushion over San Francisco with
two weeks remaining in the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   No matter. Nobody in February expected the decidedly
middle-class Giants to be anywhere in the neighborhood of the
affluent Los Angeles Dodgers come September. They were separated by
$34million in player salaries at the season's start. And the gulf
between the free-spending Dodgers and the budget-conscious Giants
remains spacious; the Dodgers were 13 games behind the Giants at
the start of Monday's four-game series between the intrastate
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   When people say Baker used mirrors to keep Arizona in his club's
sight lines for so long, it's more than a figure of speech. The
Giants are a reflection of their manager. They play hard and lay
down their egos like so many sacrifice bunts.
</P>
<P>
   If you were a Dodgers fan in the club's L.A. heyday, it all
sounds achingly familiar. You remember Baker taking a hittable
fastball for ball four in the ninth inning of a game the Dodgers
were trailing by one, happy to end his 15-game hitting streak if it
helped the team win.
</P>
<P>
   You recall him hitting his 30th home run in his last at-bat of
the 1977 regular season to give the Dodgers the first team in the
majors with four players having at least 30 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   You can relate to why Darryl Hamilton would choose to wear
Baker's jersey (No. 12) when he was in Colorado, after leaving San
Francisco, and former teammate Gary Matthews would name one of his
sons (Dustin) after Baker.
</P>
<P>
   You don't laugh when one of his players, center fielder Marvin
Benard, says of Baker, ``If he would run for mayor of San
Francisco, it'd be close.''
</P>
<P>
   You cry when you think of what Baker could have done for the
Dodgers, if pride and prejudice hadn't stood in the way.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   For eight years beginning in 1976, Baker, an outfielder, was the
quintessential Dodger. He played hard, he played hurt and the only
thing he cared about was winning. It didn't bother him that the
spotlight fell on Ron Cey, Steve Garvey, Bill Russell and Davey
Lopes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty, as much as any player I've known, was always
team-oriented,'' says former general manager Fred Claire. ``You
would never hear Dusty talking about Dusty.''
</P>
<P>
   You still won't. When the conversation turns to himself, he
stammers and meanders, this man who is fluent in three languages _
Spanish, English and body language.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather give credit to the players,'' Baker says. ``They're
the ones getting the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   It'll be a windless day at Candlestick Point when you hear Baker
say, ``We did a great job'' after a win and ``They were dreadful''
after a loss.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be snowing in the Bay Area in July when you see Baker
managing from the top step of the dugout, courting the television
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   It'll be hill-less in San Francisco when Baker berates a player
in public.
</P>
<P>
   Is it any wonder Baker's players love him like a brother, like a
father? He slips between the fraternal and paternal roles as if
born to the task.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, he was.
</P>
<P>
   He led off the birth order in John and Christine Baker's
five-deep lineup. And just as the No. 1 hitter has different
strengths than the No.4 hitter, so it is with siblings.
</P>
<P>
   A sense of responsibility has always been Baker's natural
strength. He learned early how to handle his two brothers and two
sisters when his parents were both working. Little did he know then
he was, as he says now, ``a manager in training.''
</P>
<P>
   What, you thought he was an overnight success, this man who won
NL managerial honors in 1993, his first year at the helm in San
Francisco, and again in 1997?
</P>
<P>
   ``This isn't just an overnight process,'' Baker says, leveling
you with a stare that dares you to disagree. In that instant you
know how his siblings once must have felt and what it's like now to
be one of his players.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   ``Dusty very seldom tattled on his brothers and sisters,''
Christine Baker says by telephone from Rancho Cordova, a suburb of
Sacramento. ``I'm finding out now, all these years later, that it
was so-and-so who ate the cherries that went on the ham at
Thanksgiving.''
</P>
<P>
   On the rare occasions when there was hell to pay in the Baker
household, Dusty stoically accepted the bill. He'd settle with the
guilty party later, behind closed doors. It's the same way he
operates as a manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why embarrass a guy in front of the team or in the press?''
Baker says. ``No one wants to called out like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baker is speaking from experience. He says he'd never want any
of his players to face the same public censure he did on occasion
during his first few years in the big leagues, in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   That's why, when Baker recently got wind of a Giants pitcher
denigrating the defense of one of his outfielders, he called both
players into his office, shut the door and defused the tension
right then and there.
</P>
<P>
   Baker has been known to offer his players cold compresses even
before they admit to being hot under the collar. He is acutely
observant, which turns people into dime-store novels in his hands.
He can read them in a snap.
</P>
<P>
   Even when you think he's being inattentive, he's not. You notice
his digital wristwatch is flashing 5:24 when it's really 10:15 and
you jokingly ask him if he knows what time it is. Baker looks at
his watch, fiddles with a few of the knobs and admits he hasn't
figured out how to work the blasted thing. ``I just use it for
timing the opposing pitcher's delivery (for the purpose of stealing
bases),'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The opposing pitcher isn't the only one hard-pressed to get
anything past Baker. Benard remembers a trip to Dodger Stadium with
the Giants during his rookie season, in 1996. Benard was pressing
something awful in batting practice. He fouled one pitch off his
foot and popped up another. Before the Nicaraguan from Bell Gardens
got two steps out of the batting cage, Baker was there to rescue
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take any more cuts,'' Benard remembers. ``Instead, we
talked for 45 minutes, and it was like he was taking a big load off
my shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   The conversation could have been in Spanish. Pero naturalmente.
</P>
<P>
   Christine Baker insisted all her children study Spanish when
they were growing up, the better to facilitate communication and
camaraderie with everyone in their multi-ethnic neighborhood in
Riverside.
</P>
<P>
   After three years of high school Spanish and a few years of
winter ball in Mexico, Puerto Rico and the Dominican Republic,
Baker became fluent in the language. Conducting television and
radio interviews in Spanish now is second-nature to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes (the Spanish-speaking) players a lot more
comfortable, to be able to speak to him in their language,'' says
Benard. ``It makes you want to play hard for him.''
</P>
<P>
   As a manager Baker plays his gut, not the percentages. That's
what you always hear, anyway. Baker begs to differ.
</P>
<P>
   He does his homework. The hopelessly unsynchronized watch on his
wrist is grist for Baker's argument.
</P>
<P>
   Ask Baker if he manages by the book and he's liable to ask,
which one? He produces four of his favorites: ``Don't Sweat the
Small Stuff (And it's All Small Stuff),'' ``The Art of War,'' ``A
Book of Five Rings'' and ``The Gospel According to Casey.''
</P>
<P>
   From militarism to motivation, Baker would appear to have all
the bases covered.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
<P>
   Baker's world was mutual funds and money markets when Dodgers
executive Al Campanis made his televised comment in 1987 that
African-Americans lacked ``the necessities'' to be in baseball
management. Baker, a stockbroker one year removed from his
retirement from baseball, already was upset at the Dodgers for
having unceremoniously dealt him to the Giants in 1984. Campanis'
comments were so much salt on an open wound.
</P>
<P>
   The healing process has been slow. It doesn't matter that the
coaching door cracked open for minorities in the wake of that
``Nightline'' nightmare, allowing Baker and a few others to squeeze
through.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's still hurting over what happened,'' says Hamilton, the
former Giant who is now with the New York Mets. ``I don't know if
Dusty can swallow his pride.''
</P>
<P>
   It's true, Baker doesn't suffer hypocrites gladly. He'll never
forget how a certain Dodgers executive pitched Bobby Valentine to
the Giants before then-general manager Peter Magowan promoted Baker
from hitting coach to manager after the firing of Roger Craig.
</P>
<P>
   Six years later, Baker says the enmity he feels toward the
Dodgers ``is fading with time.''
</P>
<P>
   It's like his mother is fond of saying: You have to step over
rocks instead of dragging them behind you.
</P>
<P>
   John and Christine Baker's leadoff sibling wasn't always
nimble-footed. He has worked to make himself so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 02:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-COWBOYS-FALCONS-H     09-21 0618
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-FALCONS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JODY GOLDSTEIN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
IRVING _ When Atlanta quarterback Chris Chandler was unable to
start Monday night's game against Dallas, it looked like a game the
Falcons couldn't win.
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Atlanta running back Jamal Anderson went down with a knee
injury during the second series, it was assured.
</P>
<P>
   With the Falcons' two best players on the bench, it didn't take
much for the Cowboys to muster a 24-7 win before a Texas Stadium
crowd of 63,663.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons were forced to start Tony Graziani in place of Pro
Bowl quarterback Chandler, who had not recovered from a hamstring
injury suffered in Atlanta's opener against Minnesota. Graziani,
who had not lasted beyond halftime in his other two career starts,
bettered those appearances _ but not by much. He went 7-for-16 for
90 yards with one interception before being yanked in the third
quarter for Danny Kanell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was good to see a guy running around out there having to
fight for yardage or trying to try find a place to throw the
football,'' said Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, whose team will take a
2-0 record into its bye week.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for the Cowboys to get to Graziani. On the
third play of the game, Dexter Coakley picked off a pass, then ran
it back 43 yards to the Atlanta 10. The Cowboys couldn't punch it
in, but Richie Cunningham booted a 23-yard field goal, and Dallas
had an early 3-0 edge.
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't nearly as distressing to the Falcons as what
happened on their next possession. On only his third carry of the
game, Anderson, last year's leading NFC rusher, twisted his knee
making a cut on the artificial turf. He was diagnosed with a sprain
after a series of negative X-rays. He never returned.
</P>
<P>
   That left inexperienced Texas Tech product Byron Hanspard to
carry the load for an equally uninitiated quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Offensively, the Cowboys looked more like the team that
floundered for much of its opener against the Redskins than the
team that mounted an incredible fourth-quarter comeback and
overtime victory.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman started the game 1-for-5 and
finished with only 98 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's hero, Rocket Ismail, saw the end of the first
quarter in the locker room with a sprained left shoulder. Guard
Everett McIver joined him there before the end of the half with a
hamstring injury. Tackle Erik Williams never even stepped on the
field, injuring his quadriceps during pre-game warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   None of that mattered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost two guys on the right side of the ball, but we were
able to hold together,'' said Dallas running back Emmitt Smith, who
rushed for 108 yards and two TDs on 29 carries.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Falcons (0-2) were so inept, Dallas' job became
easy, although the Cowboys were far from artistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dropped too many passes, had too many negative-yard runs,
but I thought our guys played hard throughout the ballgame,''
Gailey said. ``And we took advantage of turnovers we got. That puts
you in position to win games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas defense, which surrendered 35 points in the opener
against Washington, shut out the Falcons until the 4:00 mark in the
final period when Kanell hit Tim Dwight with a 45-yarder to make it
17-7.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys defensive end Greg Ellis, who had two sacks in the
season opener, became a hero again when he thwarted any Falcons
hopes of a comeback by intercepting a Kanell pass and returning it
87 yards for Dallas' final touchdown with 46 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We set the tone early in the game that we were going to be a
force to be reckoned with,'' said Cowboys defensive tackle Chad
Hennings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
