<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 02:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9682 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS     09-21 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BLINEBURY-COL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
IRVING _ As part of their 40th-season celebration, the Cowboys
trotted some of the great names from their past out onto the field
at Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Too bad they couldn't find some extra pads and helmets for Tony
Dorsett, Bob Lilly, Roger Staubach, Harvey Martin and all the rest
for an intrasquad game. At least a bunch of middle-aged guys with
paunchy bellies might have upped the entertainment factor with
comic relief.
</P>
<P>
   What the Cowboys and Falcons brought to Monday night was a
compelling reason to flip the channel to Ally McBeal reruns and an
affair with less meat on its bones than Calista Flockhart.
</P>
<P>
   It will go down in the books as a 24-7 victory that jumps Dallas
to the top of the division standings, not to mention already
leaving the Cowboys as one of only two 2-0 teams in the entire NFC.
Which just goes to prove that they don't make the NFC like they
used to anymore, and the same can be said for Super Bowl teams.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are said to be driven this season to disprove the
notion held by most of the civilized world that last year's run to
the Super Bowl was one of those rare and inexplicable and
not-to-be-repeated occurrences. Like the Carter administration.
</P>
<P>
   But all they could offer up in this one was the atmosphere and
intensity of a preseason game. Not that the Cowboys don't
appreciate the opportunity for some extra work.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off the celebrated 41-35 comeback win at Washington in
the season opener, there was the nagging question of a Dallas
defense that allowed the Redskins to crank out 504 yards of
offense.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's true that Deion Sanders was still sidelined with his
sore toe, Kevin Smith with a bad back and Leon Lett because of his
latest substance-abuse suspension. But if the Cowboys are going to
eventually get consideration as a team that can be more than a
playoff poseur this time around, the onus is on them to prove they
can get the job done against good competition. Which Atlanta
clearly is not.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons began the game with their veteran starting
quarterback Chris Chandler on the sideline nursing a sore hamstring
and third-year man Tony Graziani leading the way. Not to say that
Graziani is green in the ways of the NFL, but he began the night
having never thrown a touchdown pass as a professional and did very
little to change that.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Graziani's best _ and maybe only _ opportunity to take
the Falcons to a score came on the very first play from scrimmage
on the night. That's when he handed the ball off to Jamal Anderson,
took a return pitch and then heaved a perfect rainbow down the
middle of the field on a flea-flicker to a streaking Chris
Calloway, who could have cruised all the way into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Problem was, Calloway did his cruising without the ball after it
hit him in the hands and bounced harmlessly to the turf.
</P>
<P>
   End of surprise. End of any fight the Falcons would put up.
Especially when Anderson, their workhorse running back, had to
leave the game with a sprained right knee on the second series of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Without Chandler and without Anderson, the Cowboys could
probably have played the rest of the night with their arms and legs
wrapped up in duct tape like Kevin Garnett in that Nike commercial
and the Falcons would have been like the short, fat kid, still
unable to score.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say there aren't still reasons for concern with
the Dallas defense. For until Sanders and/or Smith returns, there
will be too many times in the coming weeks when Charlie Williams is
left looking as confused on the corner as a lost tourist.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of game when you figured the Cowboys could again
put up some big offensive numbers and maybe would have, if they
hadn't lost interest.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the first quarter, Richie Cunningham had kicked a
23-yard field goal and Emmitt Smith had run two yards for a
touchdown and a 10-0 lead, and the gap between the Cowboys and
Falcons appeared to be at least three times as wide.
</P>
<P>
   Smith added another TD in the second half and finished with 29
carries for 108 yards and moved into fourth place on the NFL's
all-time rushing list, ahead of Dorsett.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Danny Kanell had replaced Graziani at quarterback
when there did not seem to be anything the Falcons could do. Except
there's always something to do against the patchwork Cowboys
secondary _ throw the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Kanell hit Tim Dwight with a 25-yard touchdown and then had the
Falcons back on the Dallas doorstep in the final minute until Greg
Ellis picked off a pass and went 87 yards the other way to score.
</P>
<P>
   A 2-0 start. Another win. Even if it felt like preseason. Until
all the main men are back on defense, the Cowboys can still use the
work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
