<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS END FORUM ERA WITH ROUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Through 17 years, Dave Taylor played in
1,111 games for the Los Angeles Kings, a team record. With Marcel
Dionne and Rogie Vachon, he is one of just three Kings to have his
jersey retired.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Taylor's feelings _ and those of the Kings' _
were far from bittersweet as they bid farewell to the Forum in an
8-1 exhibition victory over the Anaheim Mighty Ducks. Taylor, the
Kings' senior vice president and general manager, and his team were
looking to the future, not the past.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor cited reaching the Stanley Cup Finals in the 1992-93 as
his career highlight and what he will regard as his fondest memory
of the Forum. But he wasn't choked up about leaving, considering
the Kings are moving to the Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings dominated the Ducks as former Islanders starZiggy
Palffy scored his first goal as a King. On the power play, Luc
Robitaille passed across ice to Jozef Stumpel, who passed to Palffy
in front of the net. It was the Kings' first goal, the only one in
the first period. The Kings' Jaroslav Modry, Craig Johnson, Jason
Podollan, Len Barrie and Audette twice, scored in the second
period.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings' 7-0 lead in the third turned the game turn into a
cheap-shot and fighting fest, highlighted by a confrontation
between Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg and Kings coach Andy Murray
yelling at each other. Play was stopped for approximately 15
minutes as officials tried to get the game under control.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery Men win: As part of the Forum-farewell festivities there
was a charity exhibition before the Kings-Ducks game. Kings alumni
lost 4-2 to the Mystery Men. The Mystery Men were an array of
celebrities and players from the upcoming film Mystery, Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   One of the players was Scott Wolf, an actor on TV's ``Party of
Five.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not planning a career change,'' Wolf said, ``not unless
they need someone who constantly falls on the ice and is out of
breath all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
