<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS' POSSE FAILS TO ROUND UP ROYALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ It was spring training all over again Monday night at
Safeco Field. Rookie auditions on the mound. Balls soaring over the
fence. Runs aplenty. Everything but Arizona's blazing sun.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners settled for ``Blazing Saddles'' instead, relying on
a little levity to get through the dog days of a lost season.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted the Kansas City Royals were not amused. They
kept things serious, cranking out four home runs _ two by rookie
Mark Quinn _ to notch a 10-9 victory before a season-low Safeco
Field crowd of 33,254.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn provided solo blasts in the fourth and seventh innings,
giving him his second two-homer game in a week in the big leagues.
That was just enough to offset Ken Griffey Jr.'s 46th long ball, a
two-run shot in the eighth inning that tied the Mariners slugger
with Joe Carter for 32nd on the all-time homer list at 396.
</P>
<P>
   Trying, and failing, to even their record at 75-75, the Mariners
turned playful. In the second inning, with one runner on and one
out, nine players donned oversized, 10-gallon hats and hung on the
dugout rail as Jay Buhner did a makeshift gallop to the plate, bat
between legs, for his first at-bat. The moment apparently was
choreographed, with the theme song to the old television western,
``Bonanza,'' playing over the public address system while all this
took place.
</P>
<P>
   The hatwear was a combination Southwestern and Puyallup Fair
motif _ foam rubber in texture, coming in separate shades of
flourescent blue, green, red and yellow, each with a little star on
the front.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the ugliest things I'd ever seen,'' said Mariners
manager Lou Piniella, referring to the hats, not any on-field
performances.
</P>
<P>
   Buhner's ``posse'' included Griffey, Brian Hunter, Mike Blowers,
Paul Abbott, Tom Lampkin, John Halama, Gil Meche, Ozzie Timmons and
Shane Monahan.
</P>
<P>
   Griffey apparently was responsible for the fashion statement,
ordering the hats from a Northgate costume shop for no other reason
than to pull a prank on the Mariners' sometimes overbearing
clubhouse leader. The Bonanza theme song, which accompanied Buhner
to the plate, was the inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the big sheriff,'' Griffey said of Buhner. ``We said,
`OK, we'll fix him.' So I decided to get some hats.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Piniella, ``I told him to have his fun and get it over
with.''
</P>
<P>
   Buhner was so inspired, he took one for the team, hardly
flinching when a Blake Stein pitch glanced off his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   If only the Mariners could have shown as much togetherness when
it counted.
</P>
<P>
   They sent rookie Robert Ramsay to the mound for his first
big-league start. It didn't go well at all. The lefty lasted just
four innings, getting hit hard and often. His third batter, Carlos
Beltran, slugged a two-run homer. He gave up Quinn's long blast to
center in the fourth. Ramsay departed after throwing only 64
pitches, trailing 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   The first-year pitcher will receive two more starts, his next
coming Sunday at home against the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of the learning experience for a lot of pitchers
we've had this summer,'' said Piniella, who saw a few positive
signs in Ramsay's effort. ``He didn't back away. I like that.
That's what I want to see. He didn't walk anybody. If you get hit,
you try to make better pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way I try and do it, is to have them beat me with
what they've got,'' Ramsay said. ``I didn't walk anybody. I've just
got to make quality pitches when I need them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsay's teammates, sans cowboy hats, battled back with five
runs in the fifth to grab a short-lived 6-5 lead. Griffey had the
big hit in this uprising, a two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   However, Ramsay's replacement, fellow rookie Brett Hinchliffe,
had his own troubles, giving up four runs himself. Included in his
effort was a three-run sixth inning, one that hardly endeared him
to those trying to piece together a pitching staff for next season.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, Hinchliffe retired the first two batters, then
carelessly walked two. The next batter, Rey Sanchez doubled both
runners home, sending a ball deep into the gap in left-center and
pulling the Royals from a 6-5 deficit into a 7-6 lead. Sanchez had
a career-high four hits.
</P>
<P>
   Mariners rookie pitchers weren't the only ones who suffered on
this night. Veteran reliever Jose Paniagua, out 10 days with a
groin injury, served up consecutive launching-pad shots in the
eighth, Quinn and Joe Vitiello each crunching one hard off the
upper-deck facade in left to build a 10-7 advantage.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it was hats off to Kansas City.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
