<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9686 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-RE     09-21 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-GIANTS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARROS LIFTS DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Growing up in Montreal, Eric Gagne didn't know
about the strange things that happen between the Los Angeles
Dodgers and San Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Even when it appeared Gagne might win his first major-league
game he couldn't have realized what goes on between these two
teams.
</P>
<P>
   Monday night's 6-5 victory in front of 33,280 at Dodger Stadium
was typical, won on a ninth-inning, bases-loaded single by Eric
Karros off Jerry Spradlin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know very much, only what I saw of them on
video tape before the game,'' Gagne said after his third career
start. ``I guess that first win is the hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers scored three runs after Gagne was lifted for a
pinch-hitter in the fifth. But the Giants scored three runs in the
seventh, two on a home run by J.T. Snow, to tie the game at 5.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Borbon, the fourth Dodgers pitcher, had been struggling
for a month before he came for the ninth. All he did was set down
the Giants in order, including a called third strike on Barry
Bonds.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's my job _ Barry Bonds,'' said Borbon (4-2). ``We had a
chance to win it earlier, but it is never easy against the
Giants''.
</P>
<P>
   Karros had two hits and four RBI. Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek
had three hits, including a home run, and is batting .327.
</P>
<P>
   But as Borbon said, there was nothing easy about playing the
Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Such as the second inning, when Ellis Burks took off from first
and Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley made a perfect throw to second _
with nobody covering the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek and second baseman Eric Young had a long and
animated discussion about the blunder, which went down as an error
on Young because right-handed hitting Rich Aurilia was at the
plate.
</P>
<P>
   The play didn't result in a run, but no doubt will go down as
the symbol for the Dodgers' season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did it lead to a run?'' Young said. ``Then there is nothing to
talk about. We just had a miscommunication.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the Giants, they are technically still in the National
League West race. Division-leading Arizona has an eight-game lead
over San Francisco and 12 to play. The Diamondbacks, who could
clinch this weekend in San Francisco, lost 12-7 on Monday to
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers appeared to get Gagne his first victory by scoring
three runs in the fifth inning after he was lifted for a
pinch-hitter Craig Counsell.
</P>
<P>
   Counsell opened with a walk and one out later took third on a
double by Grudzielanek.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield was intentionally walked and Karros followed with
a two-run double into the left-field corner.
</P>
<P>
   Giants starter Russ Ortiz, in search of his 18th victory, was
replaced by left-hander Rich Rodriguez, who escaped big trouble
when center fielder Marvin Bernard took away extra bases from Devon
White with a leaping catch at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield scored on the sacrifice fly to give the Dodgers a 5-2
lead, but it could have been a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth appeared to be a nice gift for Gagne, who did not have
good control, walking five in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike his last start against the New York Mets, it didn't
hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   After the Dodgers took a 2-1 lead on Grudzielanek's third-inning
homer, Bernard tied it in the fifth with an opposite-field home run
to left.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the other guys, but their leadoff hitter had me all
day,'' Gagne said. ``Except for the walks I felt OK. I'm just glad
we won.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
