<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0053 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 03:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9692 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r w BC-BEATTY-PRESIDENCY-SFC     09-21 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEATTY-PRESIDENCY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BURTON, CRANSTON TAKE BEATTY SERIOUSLY  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A presidential race can get rougher than the final shootout in
``Bonnie and Clyde'' _ and actor Warren Beatty, who took most of
the bullets in that scene, knows it.
</P>
<P>
   But he may be willing to take another to get Democrats back on
the script of grassroots issues _ campaign finance, the environment
and the gap between rich and poor _ and he ``would do beautifully''
as a candidate, says former U.S. Senator Alan Cranston, a Beatty
adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty has been talking a presidential run with longtime friends
in political circles _ among them Cranston and Democratic state
Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, rumored to be at least some
of the inspiration for his colorful, straight-talking pol in the
title role of last year's movie ``Bulworth.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranston _ who made his own presidential run in 1984 _ met with
Beatty recently on the topic. And Burton, who suffered a mild heart
attack last week, said Monday that ``the only political thing I did
in the hospital'' was talk to Beatty about you-know-what.
</P>
<P>
   Both plan to attend Beatty's keynote address at a dinner Sept.
29 for the Southern California Chapter of Americans for Democratic
Action in Beverly Hills, where he is to receive the ADA's Eleanor
Roosevelt Award. The event has reporters from around the world
already clamoring to attend in hopes of catching a presidential bid
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little overwhelming,'' said one spokeswoman for the
ADA, who said demands have come from ``everyone from Stern Magazine
in Germany to ABC News to Agence France-Presse to the Toronto Globe
and Mail.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty himself has given little hint on the topic of his speech
or his plans _ other than authoring an opinion piece in the New
York Times that provided no direct clue to either.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not saying what he's going to talk about,'' said one
insider helping to coordinate the speech. ``Warren isn't putting
any spin on it. But there's no question he's considering (a
presidential bid).''
</P>
<P>
   But the celebrated director and star of such movies as
``Splendor in the Grass,'' ``Reds'' and ``Shampoo'' has long
cultivated political interests, and both Cranston and Burton say
Beatty may be underrated by so-called political insiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've talked to people who are fairly heavyweight finance
types, and they don't denigrate his candidacy or think it's a
joke,'' said Burton in an interview Monday. ``There is a serious
message to be made, and Warren has the stature and the celebrity to
immediately do so.''
</P>
<P>
   And, he said, Beatty has the capacity to run a different kind of
campaign if he so chooses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Assuming he got serious and did it, he could send out on the
Internet _ he's thinking of limiting contributions to $25 or $50 a
person _ and in my opinion, at least a million people would give,
even ones (already) giving 25 grand,'' Burton said. ``And they'd
give it to him to hear a second voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranston agrees that Beatty is ``touching on key and fundamental
issues.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Beatty ``admires Al Gore and Bill Bradley, but he wants
them to be more in keeping with traditional Democratic principles
like Franklin Roosevelt and John F. Kennedy. That's his purpose.
They haven't been as vigorous as he suggests they ought to be. ...
His goal is to get these issues addressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Beatty feels ``we have to get money out of campaigns,'' said
Cranston. ``He's concerned about those who cannot contribute the
big money that's practically mandatory under the system _ who are
left out of the decision-making.''
</P>
<P>
   Cranston was quick to point out that there are precedents for
actors holding high office. But he said that if Beatty is
``successful in moving Gore and/or Bradley ... I think he would not
run. If he fails, he is certainly considering it.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Cranston hinted the Beverly Hills speech may be too soon
for a formal launch. ``I don't think he's going to announce his
candidacy, and he's far from ready,'' Cranston said, adding that
Beatty has outlined issues that matter most to him _ and will be
the focus of his campaign, if there is one.
</P>
<P>
   Beatty is also deeply concerned about the environment, and
``he's thinking of impoverished people in our country. And people
who haven't gotten off to a good start in education and health care
and therefore have a tough time, all the time,'' said Cranston.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about his actor friend's prospects, Cranston predicted,
``He will attract media attention,'' and his wife, renowned actress
Annette Bening _ who played a presidential paramour in ``An
American President'' _ would be ``a big asset.''
</P>
<P>
   Both veteran pols say presidential politics can be brutal, but
they're not worried for Beatty.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are they going to say about him _ he went out with 8
million women?'' asked Burton. ``He's got a wonderful wife, and
he's absolutely proud of her. ... He's got great kids. All he needs
to do is get a dog and fireplace, and he's home free. ... There
ain't no secrets in Warren's life.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cranston: ``I told him he should be prepared for a lot of
slings and arrows.''
</P>
<P>
   But competitors say they're expecting a reprise of one of
Beatty's most notable _ and expensive _ flops.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not that worried,'' said one Gore adviser Monday. ``We
just saw `Ishtar' last weekend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 0350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 03:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9693 &Cx1f; ttd-z
