<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY BILLBOARD JUST BARGING IN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
SAN FRANCISCO _ If you think there's a lot of ugly stuff floating
in the bay now, just wait for the world's largest floating
billboard _ coming soon.
<P>
   The Bay Area is a breeding ground for wonderful and brilliant
ideas, and this isn't one of 'em.
</P>
<P>
   Any day now a massive billboard-on-a-barge, towed by a tug, will
begin cruising alongside Highway 101 south of Candlestick.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't miss this unique opportunity to have the most
talked-about message in the Bay Area,'' crows Adauction.com
(415-365-2261).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gee, honey, isn't the Bay beautiful this morning _ the &LR; 
 &UR; whitecaps, the seagulls, the way the sun glints off the &LR; 
 &UR; Preparation H billboard? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Next: Ads painted on octopi (``Acme Scuba Shop'').
</P>
<P>
   The company says of its bilgeboard, ``It's just another way that
Adauction is revolutionizing the media world.''
</P>
<P>
   Revolutions ain't what they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   SLITHERING PAST Le Central on Friday afternoon, Lotta Dotz
spotted da snake charmer, Willie Brown, rattling his dice cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Couldn't see if he rolled snake-eyes,'' Dotz sez. ``Good to
know he remains a regular at Le Central, that he still has a pit to
hiss in.''
</P>
<P>
   PREGNANT PAUSE: Seven extremely pregnant women and their
husbands stuffed themselves into an elevator at Sequoia Hospital in
Redwood City one recent evening.
</P>
<P>
   The group was touring the hospital in preparation for stork
time. The elevator protested the load by jamming between the third
and fourth floors.
</P>
<P>
   The seven couples, plus one man with a heart condition, were
trapped for an hour. Much anxiety, says Keith Majkut, but they all
kept their cool and their babies.
</P>
<P>
   The RCFD finally dropped a ladder and pulled everyone out
through the elevator roof.
</P>
<P>
   Those escape hatches are tiny. It was a tight squeeze _ kind of
a metaphor for upcoming events.
</P>
<P>
   REPORTS OF legendary barkeep Michael McCourt's minor heart
attack Saturday were greatly exaggerated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just heartburn,'' snorts McCourt.
</P>
<P>
   But for the hell of it, Michael underwent angioplasty and will
be back behind the mahogany at the Whitehall Tavern as early as
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Ix-nay on the pickled pig's feet, Michael.
</P>
<P>
   SACRED (and medium-sacred) cows are roasted weekly on the big
marquee outside Shanghai Kelly's neighborhood tavern, Polk and
Broadway. This week's message: ``Sign up here for the Committee of
S.F. Felons to Re-Elect Terence Hallinan.''
</P>
<P>
   NEW RULE IN THE NFL: Kickers must use a fresh, unused football
for each kick. Why? Because kickers cheat. They fill balls with
helium, overinflate 'em, microwave 'em (seriously), lots of tricks.
</P>
<P>
   Now each pristine, security-guarded kicking ball is branded with
a ``K'' inside a circle, and Matt Rudoff points out that's one of
the symbols used to denote kosher food.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosher pigskin?`' wonders Rudoff.
</P>
<P>
   He muses that the tenets of Judaism ain't what they used to be.
He himself went to a Giants game on Rosh Hashana Hoshanah &LR;   &LR; and saw
a guy wearing a cap with ``Giants'' written in Hebrew. ``Oy, the
chutzpah.''
</P>
<P>
   WHOLE LOTTA SHAKIN': Willie Brown saved Lotta's Fountain,
honoring a campaign promise to get it rebuilt and flowing.
</P>
<P>
   And now Brown has saved the annual ceremonial reunion of '06
Q &LR; quake survivors at Lotta's.
</P>
<P>
   At the recent re-dedication of the reborn fountain, raised from
rust and ruin on orders from Willie, the Arts Commission forgot to
invite the few remaining '06 survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Also snubbed: Taren Sapienza, for years the coordinator of the
annual Quake Day survivors' reunion. The commission also forgot a
promise to include a plaque saluting the survivors and to bury a
time capsule.
</P>
<P>
   The commission forgot that the fountain is 10 percent art and 90
percent memorial to the city's spirit. In the chaotic wake of the
Big Quake, the fountain was a bulletin board and gathering place
for dispersed and desperate friends and families.
</P>
<P>
   Da Mayor has personally apologized to the snubees and pleaded
with them to keep alive the annual ceremony at Lotta's. And it
shall be so.
</P>
<P>
   CELL PHOLLIES: Bill Higgs was in line at the Lafayette post
office behind a cell-yapper. Irritating, but get used to it, right?
</P>
<P>
   Bill elaborates: ``It's this guy's turn and he says into the
phone, `Hold on.' He reaches into his jacket pocket and answers a
second cell phone, which apparently just rang.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he walks up to the window with a phone at each ear. The
clerk gawks at the guy while he extricates himself from the two
calls, but not before holding up the line for several minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bitter Bill wonders, ``Do you suppose these guys will evolve
more ears to go with their multiple phones?''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but in the meantime, there are other places they can put
those extra phones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
