<SLUG> BC-EXCITE-WIRELESS-ACCESS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 EXCITE READY TO GO WIRELESS WITH AIRFLASH
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DEBORAH SOLOMON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO -- ExciteAtHome plans to announce a deal Tuesday with
AirFlash of Redwood City, Calif., that will let users access
Excite's Web content from wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   Excite said it will use AirFlash's wireless technology to offer
people on-the-go personalized content from Excite's portal.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies will develop applications to help people get
e-mail, news and stock quotes from their wireless phones, as well
as location-specific information _ such as the nearest ATM or
florist.
</P>
<P>
   The deal will allow ExciteAtHome to position itself for a
fast-growing market _ handheld devices that can access the
Internet. Cell-phone-makers and handheld-computer manufacturers are
beginning to roll out phones and PDAs that can access the Web
wirelessly.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome, Yahoo and other portals want to develop wireless
content so that they can translate their success on the desktop to
portable devices.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Flaum, ExciteAtHome's director of business development for
wireless, said the deal will allow Excite to offer mobile customers
content that they need in a user-friendly format.
</P>
<P>
   While the Web is great to surf on a PC, the handsets and PDAs
being released have small screens that make it tedious to browse
the Net. AirFlash is helping Excite develop personalized content
that mobile users need immediately _ such as traffic and weather _
and display it in a format that's easy to read.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of just translating an entire Web site to the handheld
device, Flaum said, AirFlash will help ExciteAtHome ``decide which
pieces really matter and then create content that users will
want.''
</P>
<P>
   The rewards could be great, as more wireless carriers start
rolling out Internet phones. This month, Sprint PCS is beginning to
offer wireless Web phones and the Strategis Group, a research firm
in Washington, D.C., projects that cell phone companies will spend
more than $2 billion on location technologies over the next five
years. Most of that money is being spent to meet federal
requirements, which mandate that wireless carriers be able to tell
the location of a 911 call by October 2001. But with more than 69
million people already carrying a mobile phone and several million
more with PDAs, the market has a lot of potential.
</P>
<P>
   ExciteAtHome will use AirFlash's mobile portal service, which
works with all types of cell phone technology.
</P>
<P>
   AirFlash allows someone who is using a wireless device to get
detailed information about their location. That information can
then be used to find the closest java joint, get updated traffic
reports or even find a movie theater nearby and order tickets
online.
</P>
<P>
   Other companies, such as SnapTrack of San Jose, Calif., are
developing technology to help wireless carriers pinpoint a caller's
location. And businesses such as Vicinity Corp. of Palo Alto,
Calif., and SignalSoft of Boulder, Colo., are creating databases of
shops, banks, hotels and other businesses that road warriors may
want to find.
</P>
<P>
   This is the first major wireless deal for ExciteAtHome, though
the company also offers limited Excite.com content on the Palm
handheld device.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
