<SLUG> BC-MONEYBAG-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 THE PLAN DOESN'T ADD UP
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
Q: I am 60 years old and retired, with a modest pension. My wife
and I need an additional $20,000 per year in pre-tax money to cover
our expenses. I have $100,000 in stocks in my Individual Retirement
Account, and we have $100,000 in stocks in a joint brokerage
account. So we would have to withdraw about 10 percent per year
from the assets in our portfolios, which is about the average rate
that stocks appreciate over the long run. Does our plan seem
feasible?
</P>
<P>
   &LR;   &LR;  A: To answer the question definitively, I would need to know
how well your stock portfolios will perform during your lifetimes,
and also what will happen to the cost of living. Alas, nobody can
say for sure.
</P>
<P>
   As you suggest, 10 percent per year could be a reasonable
expectation for long-term growth in the average stock portfolio.
But there will be years when you do worse than that _ yet you still
will be committed to selling $20,000 of your assets. Selling that
much stock when prices are depressed would weaken your long-term
performance.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, your plan doesn't seem to take inflation into
account. You say you need an extra $20,000 per year, but as prices
rise you will find that you need $21,000 per year, $22,000 and so
on to maintain the same standard of living.
</P>
<P>
   Because of inflation and the fact that stock performances vary
widely from year to year, your plan seems perilous. If I were in
your shoes, I wouldn't start out with a plan that required me to
sell more than 6 percent of my stocks per year. That probably would
give you the leeway you need to withstand stock-market dips and
inflationary surges. But it would require you to start with a much
larger portfolio: $333,333.33, to be more or less exact.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I know you don't like to give advice about particular stocks,
but in my case it's necessary. I bought shares of Iridium World
Communications at around $40 each, thinking that their satellite
technology was a no-brainer investment. But they got into trouble
and filed for reorganization, and the stock is down to around $3. I
have a paper loss of $3,000, and wonder whether I should sell and
take the tax loss, or hold on until the year is almost over to see
whether the stock bounces back.
</P>
<P>
   A: I don't have to render an opinion about Iridium to answer
your question.
</P>
<P>
   You can't sell your Iridium stock just now because trading has
been suspended since August 13, when the company announced plans to
file for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection. You may have to wait to
sell until the reorganization is complete.
</P>
<P>
   If your stock turns out to be worthless _ as often happens to
common stock in a reorganization _ you can declare the entire
purchase price, including commissions, as a capital loss.
</P>
<P>
   If my math is correct, you hold about 80 shares, worth in the
neighborhood of $250 before trading was halted. Any further
downside risk is negligible, so it won't do you much harm to hang
in there. Perhaps your stock will make a strong recovery _ although
if past Chapter 11 sagas are any guide, that appears to be a long
shot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I want to know about options trading. I'm told that it is
high-risk, but I assume that the potential rewards are large. What
exactly is options trading, and how does one find out more about
how to do it?
</P>
<P>
   A: When you buy an option on a particular stock, it gives you
the right to buy (in the case of a call option) or sell (if you buy
a put option) 100 shares of the stock at a fixed price before a
fixed expiration date. (You also can buy and sell options on
stock-market indexes.)
</P>
<P>
   Options are much cheaper than the stock itself, so if you guess
correctly about the direction the price is going to move, your
profits can be quite large relative to the size of your investment.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if you guess wrong, you can lose most or all
of the money you paid for the option. Many options expire
worthless.
</P>
<P>
   So, yes, the risk is high if you use options strictly for
speculation.
</P>
<P>
   However, options also can be used in various conservative
strategies to protect your assets. For example, you can buy put
options on a stock you own. If the stock price falls, the value of
the put option will rise, offsetting part of your loss.
</P>
<P>
   You can buy and sell options through most securities brokers.
You have to explain in advance that you plan to trade options,
because this usually requires a special kind of account. Also, the
broker is legally required to make certain that you understand the
risks and can afford the potential losses.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most useful book for a beginner is ``Options:
Essential Concepts and Trading Strategies,'' by the Options
Institute. The institute is an arm of the Chicago Board Options
Exchange, the biggest options exchange in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
