<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOTAL-INVEST-STRATEGIES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SWITCHING INVESTMENT STRATEGIES _ TOTAL-MARKET INDEX FUNDS HOT
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By ARTHUR M. LOUIS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
People who own shares in mutual funds that track the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index have enjoyed superior returns in recent years. But
now experts suggest that it might be time for these shareholders to
hedge their bets.
</P>
<P>
   The 500 large-capitalization companies that make up the S&AMP;P
index can't continue to outpace the rest of the market
indefinitely, the experts warn. At some point they will cool down,
and smaller-cap companies will outperform them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing goes on forever,'' says Sheldon Jacobs, publisher of
No-Load Fund Investor. ``Sooner or later, small caps are going to
do better than large caps. It has to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   If you accept that scenario, you might want to buy shares in one
of the so-called total-market mutual funds that track the Wilshire
5000 index. These funds are offered by the Fidelity, Schwab, T.
Rowe Price, Vanguard and Wilshire fund groups.
</P>
<P>
   The message appears to be getting through.
</P>
<P>
   In the 12 months ended in July, the assets of Vanguard's Total
Stock Market fund rose more than 80 percent to $13.1 billion. Only
about one-fifth of that was caused by an increase in the Wilshire
5000 index; the remainder was due to new share purchases by
investors.
</P>
<P>
   However, the enormous Vanguard Index 500 fund, which tracks the
S&AMP;P 500, was no slouch either. Its assets rose 40 percent in the
12-month period to $91 billion, with about half the gain
attributable to new investments.
</P>
<P>
   The Wilshire 5000 index includes almost every publicly held
company traded in the United States. Its name is misleading,
however, because it has grown to include more than 7,000 stocks.
</P>
<P>
   The S&AMP;P 500 stocks are part of the Wilshire 5000 index, of
course, and because that index is capitalization-weighted, they
dominate it, accounting for about 80 percent of the total market
value.
</P>
<P>
   So an investment in a Wilshire 5000 index fund is not a flight
from the S&AMP;P 500. It is, however, a significant step away.
</P>
<P>
   ``You will still have plenty of exposure to the big caps,''
notes Russ Kinnel, an equity fund analyst with Morningstar Inc.,
``but also to small and midcaps. So if the performance of big caps
is not great, you get the benefit of diversification.''
</P>
<P>
   Proceed with caution, however, because betting against the S&AMP;P
500 has been a losing proposition for years. The Wilshire 5000 has
lagged behind the S&AMP;P 500 every full year since 1993, and continues
to lag behind it this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody knows how long it's going to take for the broader
market to exert some strength again,'' says Craig Litman of the
Litman/Gregory investment-advisory firm in Larkspur, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, despite his prediction that a small-cap resurgence is
inevitable, warns that you shouldn't commit yourself heavily to
small caps until ``after the next bear market.''
</P>
<P>
   He explains: ``Small caps almost always decline more than large
caps in a bear market. That is a fairly consistent pattern. They
are less liquid than large caps, so their price declines are
exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   It's anyone's guess as to when the next bear market will occur.
And recognizing when it has reached bottom won't be easy _ unless
you happen to be clairvoyant.
</P>
<P>
   Vanguard, long the undisputed leader among index-fund sponsors,
has been heavily promoting its Total Stock Market Index Fund, which
mirrors the performance of the Wilshire 5000.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been stressing to investors that between an S&AMP;P 500 fund
and a fund that tracks the Wilshire 5000, the latter is the better
of the two,'' says Vanguard spokesman John Demming. ``It is more
broadly diversified, less concentrated, with less inherent risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Stevens, senior vice president of Wilshire Associates, notes
that his firm has been compiling the Wilshire 5000 index for 27
years, but didn't feel inspired to start a mutual fund based on it
until last year, when it detected a surge of interest among
investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were deluged with calls from people who want to position
themselves in case the relationship between large-cap performance
and small-cap performance reverts,'' he says. ``We've also seen
interest in our index among institutions who want to switch to the
Wilshire 5000 as a benchmark, and on the part of financial
planners.''
</P>
<P>
   Since it opened for business seven months ago, the Wilshire 5000
Index Portfolio Fund has attracted more than $100 million in
assets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the stars are lining up here for potentially a good
small-cap environment,'' Stevens says.
</P>
<P>
   Those who already hold shares in an S&AMP;P 500 fund don't have to
sell all their shares to diversify. They can simulate a Wilshire
5000 fund by shifting part of their money into a so-called
extended-market fund, which tracks all U.S. stocks except those in
the S&AMP;P 500.
</P>
<P>
   If you have $100,000 invested in an S&AMP;P 500 fund, for example,
you could sell $20,000 worth and invest the proceeds in one of the
extended-market funds. That would give you the same 80-20
big-cap/lesser-cap mix as a Wilshire 5000 fund.
</P>
<P>
   There appear to be only two extended-market funds: the Extended
Equity Market Index Fund from T. Rowe Price and the Extended Market
Index Fund from Vanguard.
</P>
<P>
   The Price fund opened for business early last year and has
assets of close to $40 million. The Vanguard fund was started in
1987 and has assets of more than $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Wilshire 5000 is confined to U.S. stocks, some
internationally minded investors may think that it isn't
diversified enough.
</P>
<P>
   Those who feel that way can put together an index-fund portfolio
that reflects the performance of all the world's markets.
</P>
<P>
   There is no single mutual fund that tracks all the markets, but
there are funds that track virtually all the non-U.S. markets. A
notable example is the Vanguard Total International Stock Index
Fund, which invests in 1,500 companies in 30 countries, covering
most of Europe, Asia, the Far East and Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Troyer, a principal with the Vanguard fund group, says U.S.
stocks currently represent about 48 percent of the total market
value of all stocks.
</P>
<P>
   So, if you own shares in a Wilshire 5000 fund and an
international index fund in the correct proportion _ 48 percent
versus 52 percent _ you can synthesize an all-world index fund.
</P>
<P>
   But Troyer says he doubts that many U.S. investors have the guts
to risk more than half their assets abroad. ``Ten to 20 percent is
probably diversification enough for most people,'' he remarks.
</P>
</TEXT>
