<HEADLINE>
ANDERSON INJURY MIGHT COST FALCONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A year ago, the Atlanta Falcons were headed for
the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two games into the 1999 season, their chances to
return might have gone down in a heap.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the first quarter of Monday night's game at Texas
Stadium, Atlanta's premier player, running back Jamal Anderson,
crumpled to the artificial turf clutching his right knee. Falcons
coach Dan Reeves said the injury has not been evaluated but
acknowledged that ``it could be an ACL.''
</P>
<P>
   That's football shorthand for an anterior cruciate ligament, the
most-feared injury for any player. But if it happens the man whose
1,846 rushing yards and 16 touchdowns led the Falcons to their
first Super Bowl appearance last season, the injury could mark the
beginning of a bleak season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know the extent of it yet, but it's devastating,''
fullback Bob Christian said. ``He's so important to this team.
Losing him, you're losing a guy who was our most valuable guy.
Maybe he'll be back this year, but we can't count on that.''
</P>
<P>
   The injury occurred on Anderson's third carry of Monday night's
24-7 loss to the Cowboys, a second-and-four from the Falcons' 24.
Anderson was cut off by the defense in the backfield and tried to
change direction, but, when he planted his right foot and cut, his
knee buckled and Anderson fell to the ground. He was not hit on the
play.
</P>
<P>
   The injury figures to have a huge impact on Atlanta's season,
which has begun with two difficult losses. In the opener against
Minnesota, quarterback Chris Chandler went down with a strained
right hamstring. He missed Monday night's game.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's injury, though, is a potential season-ender, and it
could be as difficult for the Falcons to overcome as the ruptured
Achilles' tendon that ended New York Jets quarterback Vinny
Testaverde's season.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on the Atlanta offense Monday night was obvious.
Without Anderson, the Falcons were held to 85 yards rushing _ 76 of
them by Anderson's replacement, former Texas Tech star Byron
Hanspard _ and 3.7 yards per carry. The Falcons never threatened
until the game's final four nminutes when they scored their only
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's part of the game, man,'' tight end O.J. Santiago said.
``Guys go down every week. Byron's a capable back. Losing two guys
is no excuse for the rest of us not to do our jobs.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
