<HEADER>
A9760 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     09-21 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH DOOMSDAY ON HAND, DEFENSE RISES TO OCCASION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Forty years of Dallas Cowboys' football came
parading onto the field at Texas Stadium on Monday night _ a
biblical number if there ever was one _ and a watered-down version
of the defending NFC champions had no chance against this
silver-starred legacy.
</P>
<P>
   There were too many ghosts in the place, too many reminders of
the glory years, for the toothless Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Embarrassed and maligned after surrendering 504 yards and 35
points to the Redskins last week, the Dallas defense hung a 24-7
shiner on the injury-depleted Falcons, sending the Cowboys into
their bye week with a pleasantly surprising 2-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   You beat the Redskins (who put up 50 on the Giants Sunday) in
Washington and last year's NFC Super Bowl finalist back-to-back,
you deserve a week off.
</P>
<P>
   Halftime ceremonies included a roll call of 108 former Cowboys'
players, including Bob Lilly, Jethro Pugh, Randy White and Harvey
Martin. No wonder the Cowboys played like the original Doomsday was
back in town.
</P>
<P>
   Most of it was.
</P>
<P>
   The inspired current Cowboys treated their distinguished guests
to a highlight film of sterling defensive plays, including a
stunning 87-yard interception return for a touchdown by second-year
defensive end Greg Ellis with less than a minute to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week we were proud of our offense for coming back and
winning the game,'' Ellis said, ``but we knew we didn't play well
defensively, and we wanted to come out tonight and make a
statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-seven-yard interception returns make statements that earn
exclamation marks.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so the Falcons started a lightweight named Tony Graziani at
quarterback. And yes, premier running back Jamal Anderson was
knocked out of the game in the first quarter with a sprained right
knee. Don't bore me with minutia.
</P>
<P>
   Only a face-saving 45-yard Danny Kanell-to-Tim Dwight touchdown
pass with four minutes left prevented the Cowboys from ringing up
their second Monday night shutout in two years. They buried the
Eagles, 34-0, on Monday night in Philadelphia last season.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys' owner Jerry Jones drooled happily in his luxury box
with Lilly sitting at his elbow like an oversized good-luck charm.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's better than watching Deion cavorting around on the
sideline in sweats. Prime Time, my foot.
</P>
<P>
   (And if there's anything that might get Deion back into uniform
quickly, it's watching his defensive mates get along just fine
without him.)
</P>
<P>
   Last week Washington's Brad Johnson riddled the Cowboys'
secondary for 369 yards. Dental records confirmed that it was
cornerbacks Kevin Mathis and Charlie Williams who were burned
beyond recognition.
</P>
<P>
   This week Mathis and Williams were part of a defensive effort
that held the Falcons to 14 total yards in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive pressure, you pleaded? Your prayers were answered. The
Cowboys chased, bedeviled, harassed and hounded Graziani, who
started for the injured Chris Chandler, and Kanell, his eventual
replacement, recording half a dozen sacks, including two by Chad
Hennings.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys' defense also had three interceptions and recovered
a Graziani fumble as he tried to scramble for a first down in the
third quarter, setting up Emmitt Smith's seven-yard touchdown run.
</P>
<P>
   Graziani, a left-hander who can throw from all angles (are you
listening, Doug Melvin?), was game but overmatched against the
Cowboys, especially once Anderson's right knee crumpled under him
on only his third carry of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense made some big plays in the ball game,'' Cowboys
coach Chan Gailey said. ``We took advantage of the turnovers we
got.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was impressed with (defensive coordinator Dave) Campo and
his staff's game plan,'' Gailey said. ``They did a real nice job of
preparing for this ball game and getting some pressure on the
quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that came up the middle from Hennings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into the game wanting to stop the run, wanting to stop
Jamal Anderson,'' Hennings said. ``We knew their main game plan was
to run the ball down our throats because Chris Chandler wasn't in
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to come from different angles, pressure from inside,
pressure from the outside. Disregard last week because I think this
is what our defensive front is capable of. This will be a big
morale booster for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Just when it began to get a little dicey, with the Falcons
threatening to score for the second time in the final minutes,
Darren Woodson blitzed from the corner and was in Kanell's face
when his pass was picked off by Ellis, the 286-pound defensive end,
at the 13.
</P>
<P>
   When Kanell went over backward, there was nothing but empty real
estate and a convoy of blockers between Ellis and the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked up and said, `Oh man.' It was a long run,'' Ellis
said. ``I thought I was going to run out of gas at the 10.''
</P>
<P>
   He didn't. Not with 108 glorious memories looking on and
providing an extra spiritual push. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
