<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 10:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9825 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX     09-21 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHUETT-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    I'm listening, honey, but i can't hear you
 &HT;    By Elizabeth Schuett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GIBSONBURG, Ohio _ Political candidates remind me of a song that
was popular in the early ?50s: ``First you say you do, and then you
don't. And then you say you will, and then you won?t. You're
undecided now, so what're you gonna do?''
</P>
<P>
   All politicians are guilty of an occasional flip-flop, but the
most recent (and glaring) example was New York Senate hopeful
Hillary Rodham Clinton's last minute roll over on the issue of
clemency for 16 Puerto Rican terrorists. One day she was for it,
and the next day she was against it. So what happened?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe politics happened. No big epiphany here. The lady might be
looking for votes.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, New York's get-tough mayor, Rudolph Giuliani,
swears he's bewildered by the first lady's positional agility. ``I
get confused,'' he says. ``Sometimes it's stand by him, sometimes
it's stand against him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudy _ I'm here to tell you _ it's just another name for
marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since the Clintons moved into the White House, Americans
have been relentlessly bombarded with more information on this
first couple than any of us ever wanted to know _ about anyone _
including the kid down the block with fake fangs and his face
painted green. Daily, we were inundated with updates on our
president's affinity for McDonald's (BIG Macs) and bimbos (any size
will do).
</P>
<P>
   In the name of news, we have been treated to candid shots of
Bill's burgeoning waistline, and meticulously kept up to date on
his golfing mulligans. We know who his friends are, and who they
aren't. Maybe even better than he does.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Hillary was occupied around the house with odd jobs
like culling chipped china, and drafting health care reforms. The
rest of the time she was busier than a finicky old cat in a sandbox
covering Bill's tracks, which didn't leave them much opportunity to
communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Or it could be they're just talked out. Haven't you ever sat in
a restaurant and picked out the married couples? It's easy. They're
the ones not talking to each other. Maybe that's what happened to
Hillary and Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Picture this: First couple sits down to dinner. Hillary speaks:
``Hi dear, how was your day?'' Bill answers without looking up from
his spy novel: ``Same old, same old. Janet Reno is investigating
herself, and I freed a bunch of terrorists.'' Hillary: ``That's
nice.'' Bill: ``Umm. What did you do today?''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary: ``Not much. Caught up on the ironing and came out
against clemency for the Puerto Rican prisoners.'' Bill (licking a
finger and turning the page): ``Good girl.''
</P>
<P>
   See, they're talking, but they're not hearing. That's exactly
what I think happened with the clemency thing. Bill probably forgot
to mention it, or if he did one morning over poached eggs on toast
points, Hillary was thinking about something else _ like curtains
for the new house or how to muzzle Giuliani, and just didn't hear
it.
</P>
<P>
   Face it folks, at its very best, marriage is a sanctified state
of ambivalence, the success of which is re-determined on a daily
basis by whether or not he washes his whiskers out of the sink
after shaving, and if she put the cap back on the toothpaste.
</P>
<P>
   Marital miscommunication is rampant. It even happened to my
parents who celebrated their golden anniversary _ and then some.
``Hold onto the trunk, Doris,'' my father instructed my mother as
he prepared to cut down a 10-foot, storm-damaged avocado tree in
the side yard. ``When I tell you, push against it.'' Daddy sawed
and the tree fell _ the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doris!'' he hollered when he could no longer see my mother.
``Where are you?'' A small voice answered, ``Under the tree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What in the hell are you doing under there?'' he fretted as he
scrambled to uncover her. ``?I told you to PUSH.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sorry,'' she said as she dusted herself off. ``Guess I wasn't
listening straight. I thought you said PULL.''
</P>
<P>
   So there you have it. A breakdown in communication. If it could
happen to my folks, it could happen to anyone. I'm not too worried
about the whole thing anyway _ the Clintons will be moving soon.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Schuett writes for Cox News Service. Mail: 320 West
Madison, Gibsonburg, OH 43431. E-mail: eschuett(AT)nwonline.net
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
