r k BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX     09-21 0693
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    To quell gun bloodshed, we need policy climate change
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ What it took one of history's largest hurricanes
to achieve in four states, one crazed man did with two guns in one
Fort Worth church: kill seven.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd savaged states up and down the east coast,
ultimately claiming 49 lives. But you had to combine the death
tolls of New York, Massachusetts, New Jersey and Maryland to match
what Larry Ashbrook did with his guns.
</P>
<P>
   And someone is saying that this is simply the price of human
nature.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Gov. Bush was saying in a Day 2 sound bite, which
quickly seemed divorced from the reality of events. ``A wave of
evil,'' is how he reacted.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, in the case of killer Larry Ashbrook, we are speaking
of mental illness _ delusional paranoia, most likely schizophrenia
_ which makes him maybe as evil as someone with tuberculosis or
polio: Someone ill. Someone with a chemical imbalance batting his
brain around. Someone ill and armed.
</P>
<P>
   One writes about guns in the wake of another such horror knowing
exactly what the response will be: ``More gun laws would not have
saved these lives.'' It will be pointed out that Ashbrook bought
his guns legally, that his mental illness was undiagnosed, and that
none of the minimalistic gun controls pending before House-Senate
conferees would have kept him from doing what he did.
</P>
<P>
   Though apparently correct, it's also a typical dodge. It's why
we continue in the clutches of the gun culture, even as most
Americans acknowledge a direct correlation between the
proliferation of guns, the ease of illegal purchase, and the
nation's staggering gun death toll.
</P>
<P>
   As a nation, the United States has done so little to put clamps
on the gun cult. Its leaders are so spooked by the gun cult that
what we have now is policy only scraping at a notion, rather than
scraping at solutions.
</P>
<P>
   The case of ``Crazy Larry'' is a tough one for gun cultists to
dismiss, for it has nothing to do with the Internet or video games
or Marilyn Manson. In all due respect, Mr. Governor, it doesn't
even have to do with evil. It has to do with mental illness and
guns.
</P>
<P>
   Lest it be said that the media only jump on these issues after
the fact to exploit a tragedy, direct your attention to the Sept.
20 Newsweek. It was headed for newsstands before Ashbrook's deeds.
</P>
<P>
   It refers to the fact that the federal system of background
checks is full of holes, inadequate to identify many people with
felony convictions, and, most pertinently this time, not linked to
state mental-health records, though that was the intent of the
instant-check system.
</P>
<P>
   The report underlines how little we've done in the 31 years
since Congress passed the Handgun Control Act, forbidding handgun
sales to juveniles, felons, illegal aliens and adjudicated mental
patients. We have done so little because forces of self-interest _
the gun lobby _ too often trump the public interest.
</P>
<P>
   Considering this history, National Rifle Association has taken a
peculiar tack recently. When horrific gun violence flares, as it
seems to every other week now, the NRA line is this: ``We need to
enforce the gun laws we have.'' This is interesting. Had the NRA
won every battle it waged, we wouldn't have the Handgun Control Act
of 1968 or the Brady Law, which is in place to enforce the 1968
act, to check the claims people make when they buy guns.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to me the NRA is saying it was wrong in opposing those
laws. And on that count it is right.
</P>
<P>
   Some historian needs to explain to the country what
``well-regulated militia'' meant when the founders led off the
Second Amendment. Did it mean an atmosphere in which semi-automatic
pistols would be a juvenile staple? Did it mean guns would be sold
at flea markets without any controls?
</P>
<P>
   Forecast: more destruction and death from coast to coast until
we get a handle on what the founders meant by ``regulated.''
</P>
<P>
   John Young writes for The Waco Tribune-Herald, Waco, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
