<HEADER>
A9831 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN22-CO     09-21 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONEYTALK-COLUMN22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Worry less about tax; focus on your net gain
 &HT;    By Hank Ezell
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   I get lots of mail from readers who want to know how to make
more money from their investments.
</P>
<P>
   I get even more mail from people who want to make more and avoid
paying taxes on their successes.
</P>
<P>
   People feel that they are the ones taking the risks, so they
shouldn't have to share the rewards with the Internal Revenue
Service. Many are agitated by the suspicion that somebody else is
getting better tax breaks than they are. Then there's just plain
greed.
</P>
<P>
   Those feelings are strong, and they are pervasive. Our elected
leaders are responding to them every time they noodle around with
the tax code and with tax-deferred savings plans.
</P>
<P>
   But too many people get carried away about tax avoidance.
``Minimizing taxes should not be the criterion,'' said Lori Heinel,
a strategist for SEI Investments in Oaks, Pa. ``What people should
work for is better after-tax return.''
</P>
<P>
   She believes that people who focus just on taxes are in danger
of investing too narrowly, passing up growth opportunities and
generally ending up with a risky, low-return portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   She has an interesting set of tips _ and warnings _ for
investors:
</P>
<P>
   _ Spread out your investments. Sticking to narrow, tax-friendly
things like growth stocks or municipal bonds will increase the
risks you face. ``Diversifying your assets is still a good thing,''
Heinel said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Beware of hotshot mutual funds. Spectacular returns are always
alluring. ``But you might be buying into a fund with a lot of
unrealized capital gains,'' Heinel said. ``You haven't gotten the
benefit of those gains, but when they distribute them, you're going
to pay the taxes. Look to Morningstar, the Chicago-based mutual
fund researcher, for estimates of that tax overhang.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't reject dividend-paying stocks. ``The argument a few
years ago was that if you buy stocks that don't pay dividends, you
won't have to pay taxes until you sell the stocks,'' Heinel said.
``Some people were just buying big technology companies or growth
stocks that didn't pay any dividends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is that you end up with stocks only in certain
industries. You don't buy any utility stocks or any banks. You
don't buy oil companies. You have to recognize that there are
periods when those cyclical companies come into favor, and you
won't own them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't limit yourself to index funds. Because an index mutual
fund holds onto the same basket of stocks year after year, it
doesn't have a lot of sales that generate tax liabilities. On the
other hand, Heinel pointed out, index funds are all but guaranteed
to be average performers. ``Most investors don't want indexlike
returns,'' she observed. ``They want higher performance.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want a core investment in an index fund, Heinel wouldn't
criticize you. ``But don't do it just for tax reasons,'' she
warned.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't buy and hold blindly. If you hold a stock forever, of
course, you won't incur taxes from selling your winners. But you
won't be able to move to new opportunities. ``If you bought the 20
largest stocks 10 years ago, you wouldn't have Microsoft, AOL,
Intel or Cisco,'' Heinel pointed out. ``You can buy and hold if you
like a stock, but you still need to re-evaluate on a regular basis
to see if you still like it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Think carefully about selling. It's a mistake to put off
selling an appreciated stock just because your tax bill will go up.
``Paying taxes because you have a gain is not a bad thing,'' she
observed. ``The extreme case would be if you had bought Yahoo last
year. You might have a 400 or 500 percent gain. If you have to pay
20 percent in taxes, you're still ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, it's a good idea to consider your next
investment as you prepare to sell. Heinel suggests comparing the
taxes you would owe with the returns you can reasonably expect from
the stock you want to buy next. The best new investment would be
one with a higher rate of return, which will eventually make up for
the taxes you owe.
</P>
<P>
   The big picture from Heinel: Don't get obsessed about taxes.
Concentrate on what you can keep after you pay Uncle Sam.
</P>
<P>
   Hank Ezell writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution, Atlanta,
Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
