<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-FEATURE-BUDGET-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service will file the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Mark Helm at
202-298-6320.    (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' categories)
</P>
<P>
   DISNEY-ONLINE (San Francisco) _ A sex scandal involving one of
Disney's hottest young Internet executives is also causing a
time-out for Mickey Mouse's burgeoning online empire. Executives at
Walt Disney Co. have pulled the plug on a cross- country media tour
that was to start this week promoting the company's burgeoning Web
presence, following the arrest of senior executive Patrick Naughton
on charges of soliciting a minor for sex on the Internet. By MATT
BEER.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-RESEARCH (San Francisco) _ As the digital culture zaps
its way into nearly every facet of our lives, the Web has evolved
into an awesome weapon for millions of investors and consumers.
Financial information is power, and you can quickly nab those
factoids online for free or for a reasonable cost _ compared with
the millions of dollars that companies pay brokerages, investment
firms and research consultants for their services. By EDWARD IWATA.
</P>
<P>
   PAPER-MILL (Albany, N.Y.) _ They handed out the U.S. Postal
Service's new 33-cent pink coral rose stamp last month at
International Paper Co.'s annual Hudson River Mill family picnic.
The stamp is more than just a way to mail a letter. It's a
harbinger of a new mindset for many troubled New York paper mills.
By JO-ANN JOHNSTON.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SF-MAYORAL (San Francisco) _ Mayoral candidate Clint Reilly said
he supports restrictions on chain stores in San Francisco, a stance
that could help him gain the favor of neighborhood activists. By
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-MEXICO-DEATHS (San Francisco) _ Local retirees like to call
their lakeside village of Ajijic, Mexico, an affordable vision of
paradise. The narrow cobblestone streets and tightly nestled homes
begin at the north side of Lake Chapala, the largest lake in
Mexico, and creep up into the nearby hills. The weather is dry and
warm much of the year, and housing is cheap. But the quiet sense of
bliss in Ajijic has been displaced by a rising fear, prompted by
the recent killing of two expatriate Americans. By RYAN KIM.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-PAST (Albany, N.Y.) _ Atonement of a deep and fragile kind
stirred in a rural Bavarian town this summer, where the fairy-tale
castle, red-tiled roofs and rolling farmland hide the sins of the
past. Fred Nauman of Ballston Lake, N.Y., and 40 members of his
extended family in early July traveled to Unsleben, Bavaria, in a
famously picturesque part of Germany, at the invitation of resident
Angela Bungert, who forced Unsleben to confront its Nazi past. By
MICHAEL LOPEZ.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Houston) _ A reader asks, ``What can I use on my
St.
</P>
<P>
   Augustine lawn for brown patch?'' Assorted Q&AMP;As. By KATHY HUBER.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   TV-REVIEW-ONCE (Undated) _ Of all the new shows, there is only
one guarantee: ``Once and Again'' will be knocked from its Tuesday
night perch come November. Yep, it's a goner. But it is also the
best show ABC is introducing, and one of the best dramas of the new
season, an insightful adult look at post-divorce dating and the
complications posed for and by the kids. By MARK MCGUIRE.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL (``t'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-ONLINE (Houston) _ After spending the past few years
getting its Internet legs, the industry is stepping up efforts to
get travelers to buy tickets from airline-owned Web sites. Airlines
are offering a variety of promotions, including discounts or extra
frequent flier miles, for booking on their Web sites. By LAURA
GOLDBERG.
</P>
<P>
   AIRLINES-ONLINE-TIPS (Houston) _ Advice for using the Internet
when buying tickets online. By LAURA GOLDBERG.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-WORLD-CRUISE (Undated) _ Many people have fantasized
about sailing around the world. Only a precious few could afford
it. Now, a new venture touts world cruises on a budget _ as low as
$69 a day _ with an emphasis on education. ``We think of it as a
floating university,'' says World Cruise Co. founder Sam Blyth. One
package even offers a full year at sea _ with a two-week ``vacation
from your vacation.'' By SYD KEARNEY.
</P>
<P>
   TRAVEL-COLUMN (Houston) _ Just back from an Alaska cruise
vacation, it seems an appropriate time to rekindle memories in
scrapbooks. And as the pages are turned, the ``Last Frontier''
image remains intact. Only one problem: These scrapbooks are from a
trip taken 14 years ago. This recent vacation found marked change _
3,700 cruise passengers invading a tiny town of 900 residents at
one point _ and evokes a question: At what price is mass tourism?
By HARRY SHATTUCK
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ One of the first things Steve
Mariucci did on Monday morning was pull right tackle Jeremy
Newberry into his office. The 49ers coach wasn't looking to extend
blame. He only wanted to see where Newberry's head was a day after
the New Orleans Saints rocked Steve Young's world. By JEFFRI
CHADIHA.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ I hereby announce my withdrawal
from the San Francisco mayor's race and the 2000 presidential
campaign. The public has spoken, saying it doesn't give a damn
about either. Actually, my wife has spoken. She said if I write
about either topic again she'll invoke the prenuptial clause about
boredom. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
