<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 11:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9874 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f BC-DISNEY-ONLINE-HNS &LR;      09-21 0632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DISNEY-ONLINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEX SCANDAL HALTS DISNEY MEDIA TOUR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MATT BEER  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A sex scandal involving one of the Walt Disney
Company's hottest young Internet executives is also causing a
time-out for Mickey Mouse's burgeoning online empire.
</P>
<P>
   Disney executives have pulled the plug on a cross-country media
tour that was to start this week promoting the company's
fast-growing Web presence, following the arrest of senior executive
Patrick Naughton on charges of soliciting a minor for sex on the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just too much in the news right now,'' said Disney
spokeswoman Julie Mathis. ``We don't think it's possible right now
to move ahead on this.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Thursday, Naughton, a 34-year-old computer whiz-kid and
executive vice president of the Infoseek Web portal site and
Disney's GO Network, was arrested at the Santa Monica (Calif.) Pier
on charges of attempting to solicit a minor for sex.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities allege that Naughton arranged to meet what he
thought was a 13-year-old girl after seven months of sending her
lewd e-mail messages though an online chat room. The girl turned
out to be an undercover male FBI agent.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton, a native of Rochester, N.Y., was reportedly released
Friday pending an Oct. 12 arraignment.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest came just as Disney was launching a nationwide press
tour this week, meeting with reporters to promote its growing GO
Network, a collection of popular Disney-owned Web sites, including
Family.com, ESPN.com, ABCnews.com, Infoseek and Disney Online.
</P>
<P>
   Disney Online was rated the most visited family-oriented Web
site this summer by the New York-based Internet market research
firm Media Metrix.
</P>
<P>
   Disney currently owns 43 percent of Infoseek. In July the
company said it would buy the remainder of Infoseek in a deal that
was supposed to close by year's end. The company plans to combine
Infoseek with its own Internet assets and create a stock to track
the new company's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek is a five-year-old, Sunnyvale, Calif.-based ``portal,''
which is a Web site that serves as jumping off point for users
entering the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Besides canceling the media tour, both Infoseek and Disney
scrambled to distance themselves from Naughton.
</P>
<P>
   Infoseek released a statement pointing out that Naughton came to
the company through Disney's acquisition of another Web developing
company, Starwave, where Naughton originally worked.
</P>
<P>
   Starwave was later traded to Infoseek as part of Disney's
initial investment in the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are shocked and disturbed by the arrest of Patrick
Naughton,'' said Infoseek in an unsigned statement released Monday.
``Mr. Naughton is no longer an employee of Infoseek.''
</P>
<P>
   Disney spokesperson Rebecca Anderson said Naughton had ``no
oversight responsibility for Disney-branded content'' on the Go
Network sites, which are developed in partnership with Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   But before Thursday's arrest, Naughton was an Internet executive
that Disney bragged about, hailing him as the ``best developer of
information-rich Web sites in the industry'' in a press release at
the time of its acquisition of Infoseek.
</P>
<P>
   As a 25-year-old programmer at Sun Microsystems, Naughton helped
create the concept that would later become the popular Java
programming language. He left the company for Starwave in 1995, fed
up with Sun's intent to use Java to attack rival Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Naughton, who lives in Seattle, was charged with interstate
travel with the intention of having sex with a minor, according to
a criminal complaint filed in U.S. District Court in Los Angeles.
He was released after agreeing to pay $100,000 if he fails to
appear in court for scheduled hearings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
