<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PAPER-MILL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPER MILLS ARE LEARNING TO FIND NICHE MARKETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JO-ANN JOHNSTON  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ They handed out the U.S. Postal Service's new
33-cent pink coral rose stamp last month at International Paper
Co.'s annual Hudson River Mill family picnic.
</P>
<P>
   The stamp is more than just a way to mail a letter. It's a
harbinger of a new mindset for many troubled New York paper mills.
No more complacency, no more heedless overproduction, no more
expecting the parent company to subsidize money-losing mills year
after year after year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each business is going to have to be able to stand on its
own,'' said mill manager Dave Liebetreu.
</P>
<P>
   As he and other executives made clear, the marching orders are:
Find niche markets you can profitably service with your existing
labor force and equipment. Put money into research that might
upgrade existing equipment. Use the latest financial management
tools and computer software to monitor profitability. Communicate
all this to employees, and get them behind the idea.
</P>
<P>
   The word seemed well understood by everybody at the mill picnic
in Corinth, Saratoga County, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're on the right road,'' said Angela Jenkins, who
has worked at the mill for 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't compete against big producers, leading us into a
different direction,'' added her husband Jim, a mill employee for
25 years.
</P>
<P>
   The stamps, for instance, aren't part of a lucrative deal. But
they are considered a prestigious commitment from the U.S. Postal
Service that appears to have helped the mill win other, more
lucrative contracts in specialty markets. Hudson River Mill is now
getting orders to produce shopping bag paper for upscale retailers
and department stores, and wrapping paper for cigarette
manufacturers.
</P>
<P>
   Such customers want to find paper mills that can produce short
runs of products with the correct textures, colors and durability.
For a mill, that means workers are going to have to switch the
product lines more often. But a mill handling such short runs
doesn't need the huge, high-speed paper machines now being
installed in places like Brazil and Indonesia for the
mass-manufacture of standard office and printing papers.
</P>
<P>
   New York's paper industry didn't exactly turn on a dime. For
years it resisted the niche markets and kept going for volume. Only
recently have managers begun looking for smaller markets. In fact,
the Corinth mill, then under different management, in past years
passed up the opportunity to pursue a stamp contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``We couldn't get out of our own way sometimes,'' said
Liebetreu, who came to the Corinth mill three years ago. The
results showed on the bottom line: The mill lost money through much
of the '90s, he said, adding that in 1998, the mill started turning
a profit.
</P>
<P>
   The mill may lose money again this year, a fact Liebetreu blames
on the Asian currency crisis. But the long-term looks good because
``we've finally gotten a competitive mindset,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Liebetreu's counterpart at International Paper's mill in
Ticonderoga, Calvin Staudt Jr., is preaching a similar message to
his employees. ``You have to remember, this is a business. We're
doing this to make money,'' Staudt said.
</P>
<P>
   While the gospel of profit might be ingrained at places like
General Electric, the paper industry is a different beast. Staudt
said when he arrived from an International Paper mill in Arkansas a
couple of years ago, he found the Ticonderoga motivations to be:
``Make as many tons of paper as you can.'' But the Ticonderoga mill
had lost money in nine of the 10 previous years.
</P>
<P>
   ``So making more is not necessarily more profitable,'' he
pointed out. Not enough attention was paid to costs. Sometimes new
investments had to be made, such as a better internal computer
network to speed along the flow of information critical to the
manufacturing process. Product adjustments can follow too, he said.
The mill is now stressing some opaque papers that are used for
products such as the brochures that might come in the mail with
consumers' credit card statements.
</P>
<P>
   That product line also makes sense because the hardwood trees in
the region produce fibers suitable for opaque printing papers, he
said. (Hardwood fibers in paper provide durability, and softwood
fibers deliver flexibility; papermakers blend the two in various
combinations to get the product they want.)
</P>
<P>
   Staudt said the mill has been profitable for the year to date.
He is practicing what International Paper internal consultant Brad
Johnson calls ``marginal economics,'' or using the most refined
business tools available to make sure each mill is profitable.
</P>
<P>
   That could mean cutting costs, switching products, or a
combination of both. The answers are likely to be individual to
each mill, he said. But the goal is the same. ``A facility these
days has to be profitable or have a plan that's going to bring them
to profitability soon,'' Johnson said. ``Otherwise, they're pulling
down the business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
