<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9926 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i BC-RUSSIA-BOMBING-$ADV26     09-21 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-BOMBING-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    LETTER FROM MOSCOW: AT LAST, AND SADLY, THE APATHY IS OVER
 &HT;    With Photo Mug of Holmes.
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (k) Commentary categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By Charles W. Holmes 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Beware of the watermelons. Keep your eyes on those
stray dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is above suspicion in Moscow these days. Rattled by a
string of devastating bombings this month that has left nearly 300
dead, Russians are on edge. They are wary of their own neighbors
and fearful that their apartment building could be the next target.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps not since the dismantling of the Soviet Union in 1991
have Russians felt so strongly, and vocally, about anything.
</P>
<P>
   Reports of rampant corruption bring a shrug and a yawn. Russians
have become all too accustomed to expect the worst of their
officials, from the ubiquitous streetcorner cop who demands bribes
from passing motorists to the bandit capitalists who have pumped
billions of dollars out of Russia and into Western banks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's economic crisis wiped out personal savings and jobs,
but elicited surprisingly little in the way of public outrage. Been
there, done that _ Russia and its struggling post-Soviet economy
have teetered on the brink of disaster several times in this
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Terrorism striking home is something new and ominous. Two
apartment-block blasts in Moscow, and two in southern Russia _ all
of which followed an Aug. 31 bombing in a shopping mall near the
Kremlin _ have given the entire nation nights of fitful sleep.
Russians share the same unanswered questions: Who is responsible
for the bombings, and who is to blame for not preventing them?
</P>
<P>
   The public dismay comes as Russia prepares for important
parliamentary elections in December and next summer's vote to
choose a new president.
</P>
<P>
   The men who want to replace President Boris Tylosin _
particularly his handpicked Prime Minister Vladimir Putin and his
chief rival Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov _ are scrambling to look
tough and blame the other for failing to protect Russians.
</P>
<P>
   It has been a losing game for both.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel they have no influence over what goes on in the
country,'' and they do not trust their leaders, said pollster Yuri
Levada. The result is cynicism and conspiracy theories, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fearful Muscovites are seeing the bogeyman everywhere. One rumor
swept the city that people should be on the lookout for
watermelons, allegedly used as a means of concealing and
transporting explosives. (Not true, said a police spokesman).
Another rumor reported in a local newspaper suggested that
stray-looking dogs could instead be highly trained canine couriers
used to carry bombs into buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Anything that goes bump in the night is suspect, as is anyone
with a dark complexion who may come from the mountainous Caucasus
region on Russia's southern border.
</P>
<P>
   Russian authorities widely blame Islamic guerrillas from the
breakaway republic of Chechnya for supporting the bombing campaign
in Russia. Chechen rebel leaders named by Moscow deny complicity in
the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow police and special Interior Ministry troops have swept
the streets looking for suspects, a mobilization of force dubbed
``Operation Whirlwind,'' in which dark-skinned people from Chechnya
and other states in the Caucasus region have been targeted. More
than 11,000 ``suspects'' were taken into custody last week(CQ),
though police conceded that only about 30 were under serious
questioning as possible terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   There has been little public debate about human rights and the
rule of law. Terrorism now tops the agenda and the public apathy
about affairs of state has ended. People are scared and they want
something done about the bombs _ now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why are there no resignations of people responsible for our
security? They should be ashamed to look into the eyes of the
people,'' said Slava, a shopkeeper in my neighborhood in southern
Moscow, just a short drive from the apartment buildings destroyed
by bombs on Sept. 9 and Sept. 13.
</P>
<P>
   Many others do not trust their government and believe the
Kremlin itself, or forces aligned with it, could be responsible for
the terror. For months Yeltsin's political rivals have warned that
the Kremlin is planning to declare a state of emergency as a way to
cancel the elections and extend Yeltsin's term in office.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lack of hard evidence of Chechen involvement _ or, at
least, evidence that has been made public _ and no plausible claims
of responsibility have been made for the bombings.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a proliferation of conspiracy theories and
supposed motives, often contradictory _ the Kremlin may have
ordered it, maybe the mob, maybe the state security services acting
on their own, Yeltsin wants to stay in power or Yeltsin will resign
early.
</P>
<P>
   Even the respected English-language daily, the Moscow Times, got
in on the act. In an editorial last week(CQ), it questioned why the
rubble from the two buildings destroyed in Moscow had been carted
away so soon. Why hadn't investigators taken their time sifting for
forensic evidence, the paper asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chechen theory has proved both viable and convenient for
federal authorities; investigators clearly think they've got a lock
on their suspects. Are they playing it safe (by trucking away the
ruins) and making sure no other options turn up?''
</P>
<P>
   Paranoia and politics reign in Moscow today in the fallout of
the bombs. It is not a healthy combination in a country that has
struggled toward democracy and is better known for is disreputable
government and corrupt system.
</P>
<P>
   If there is one hopeful sign, it is that Russians, at last, are
mad as hell. But will they do anything about it in the upcoming
elections?
</P>
<P>
   In Soviet times, the regime directed the terror campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, this highly charged political current has been reversed.
Terrorism, and the fear it has wrought in Moscow and across Russia,
could be the undoing of the powerful in post-Soviet Russia.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are rare moments in life when millions of people think
in the same way,'' said an editorial last week(CQ) in the daily
Nezavisimaya Gazeta. ``There is such a moment now when millions of
people who live in apartment blocks think the same thing when they
go to bed: whether they will be alive in the morning or not.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0085 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 12:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9927 &Cx1f; tad-z
s i BC-VENEZUELA-ECONOMY-$AD     09-21 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-ECONOMY-$ADV26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH ECONOMY IN TURMOIL, VENEZUELAN BUSINESS COMMUNITY
DESPERATELY SEEKING STRATEGY TO BOOST FOREIGN INVESTMENT
 &HT;    With Photos.
 &HT;    Moving in (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    For Use Sun., Sept. 26 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MIKE WILLIAMS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Soaring unemployment, political unrest,
restive labor unions, stifled consumer spending: the portrait of
Venezuela's economy isn't one to invite a stampede of foreign
investment.
</P>
<P>
   Yet American companies are already here in a big way, their
names gracing Caracas' soaring skyscrapers or plastered over
billboards lining the country's modern interstate-like highway
system: Ford, IBM, Coca-Cola and dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn here by the oil boom of the 1970s that vaulted Venezuela
to a broad-based prosperity that became the envy of Latin America,
the companies have weathered previous downturns, although none
perhaps as serious as the current situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is hurting,'' said Jorge Redmond, owner of a
chocolate-making firm and president of the Venezuelan-American
Chamber of Commerce. ``Our sales are down 15 percent, and that
applies to most consumer items. Even beer sales are down, and
that's unheard of. Unemployment is rising and people don't have
money, so they aren't spending.''
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty over the nation's political turmoil has sparked a
reported 40 percent drop in foreign investment this year, so far.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of that uncertainty is Venezuelan President Hugo
Chavez, an outspoken populist who swept to power in a campaign last
fall based on a promise to toss out the country's corrupt political
system, rewrite the constitution and redistribute the nation's oil
wealth.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez has worried business leaders by lashing out at the
``savage'' impact of market reforms in which state-run companies
have been turned over to the private sector. When the president of
Venezuela's state-owned oil company resigned, he quickly appointed
a close ally and vowed to wipe out the company's lavish habits of
paying executives huge salaries and squiring them around the world
in private jets.
</P>
<P>
   His actions have sent a wave of concern through financial
markets. Earlier this month, Moody's Investor Service placed
several affiliates of the Venezuelan oil company under review for a
possible downgrade, citing concerns that the Chavez administration
might try to exert undue control over the company.
</P>
<P>
   Most business leaders here are reluctant to comment publicly on
the situation. Those who will speak choose their words carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's safe to say most of the business community did
not accompany Mr. Chavez to the ballot box,'' Redmond said. ``But
far from being belligerent, we're in the mode of being helpful
where we can. We're trying very hard to get our ideas into the new
constitution.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials from Atlanta-base Coca-Cola Co., which became
Venezuela's dominant soft drink three years ago after luring away
rival PepsiCo Inc.'s longtime bottling partner, said they never
comment on politics in any of the countries where they do business.
They acknowledged, however, that the severe economic downturn and a
renewed effort by Pepsi have made for a challenging situation in
Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   One American company that has managed to skate above the turmoil
is BellSouth Corp., which moved into Venezuela's fledgling cellular
telephone market in the early 1990s. The Atlanta-based
telecommunications giant now owns 78 percent of TelCel, which
controls nearly two-thirds of the Venezuelan cellular market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been growing by 50 to 60 percent a year from the day we
started,'' said Mario Lizaso, BellSouth's point man at TelCel.
``Many industries here are hurting, but people are making a choice
about what they want to spend their money on, and fortunately for
us, they feel a hunger for telecommunications . . . we offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan companies, meanwhile, appear to be lobbying hard to
get Chavez to address the economic situation. They realize the
nation has taken something of a public-relations beating, with news
reports raising the specter of a dictatorship and a possible round
of nationalizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The business community around the world has gotten the view
that it is a very difficult situation here,'' said Vicente Britos,
president of Fedecamaras, the national association of Venezuelan
Chambers of Commerce. ``But they should realize that our political
confrontation and change have come about as a public debate. There
have been no actions or decisions taken against the business
community.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond, who has met with Chavez personally and finds him
cordial and attentive, agrees. But he worries that Chavez has spent
his first months in office focusing on politics and rewriting the
constitution, allowing the stumbling economy to worsen
dramatically.
</P>
<P>
   ``He hasn't stuck a finger in business's eye, but we're also
very much waiting for a signal that the economy will be what he
will attend to next,'' he said. ``It's very difficult to say where
he's going next.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond says the biggest worry of most business leaders is the
caliber of Chavez's economic team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He clearly doesn't have any economic training, and he's
surrounded with people who are from the leftist parties,'' he said.
``On the other hand, he clearly has a huge mandate from the people,
and we all agree there is a real need for change.''
</P>
<P>
   Redmond and other business leaders were expected to accompany
Chavez on a trip to New York and Washington last week(CQ),
hopefully using the visit to reassure financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all want this president to be a success,'' he said.
``People are giving him the benefit of the doubt. But as with
everything else, he is going to have to be the one giving the
message. We're still anxiously awaiting that message.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0086 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
