<HEADLINE>
RYDER CUP WILL BE A CORPORATE MECCA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GREGG KRUPA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ When the Ryder Cup was last played in the
United States in 1995, the golf world hailed the ascendancy of a
tournament that had once been considered something of a sleepy
contest between American and British golfers.
</P>
<P>
   The matches earned about $28 million for the PGA of America and
the Oak Hill Country Club in upstate New York, where it was played.
It was a commanding success for a tournament that in 1991 was
searching desperately for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   One reason for the turnaround was the golf: The British team had
expanded into a European team that had finally begun to beat the
Americans with some regularity. But another major reason was the
long and successful marriage between the sport and American
business. Already in professional golf's thrall, corporations saw
the international event as perfect way to entertain current and
prospective clients from around the country and the world.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the partnership between golf and corporate America has
evolved to the point where this Ryder Cup, which begins Tuesday
with practice rounds at The Country Club in, will be among the most
lucrative sports events ever staged.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the considerable growth in corporate spending on
luxury boxes in many new stadiums across the country, the Ryder Cup
is likely to draw a higher concentration of business executives
than other sports spectacles like the Super Bowl and college
basketball's Final Four. It has become the ultimate event for
business in the ultimate sport for business.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a corporation, you can be conspicuous by your absence,''
said David D'Alessandro, president of John Hancock Mutual Life
Insurance Co., who has cultivated a sports marketing strategy that
includes sponsoring the Olympics and the Boston Marathon. ``You
don't necessarily have to be at the Super Bowl or the World Series.
You don't have to be an Olympic sponsor. But you cannot afford to
have your competitors entertaining clients at the Ryder Cup, if
you're not.''
</P>
<P>
   Particularly if the event is in your hometown. ``Can you imagine
if someone like Prudential came in and brought in all of their
corporate clients, and Hancock wasn't there?'' D'Alessandro asked.
``It would reach beyond a breach of etiquette and run into the
category of business stupidity.''
</P>
<P>
   The boom has happened for several reasons. The tournament
features head-to-head matches, pitched international rivalry, and
the best players in the world in a sport that business underwrites
at increasingly higher levels, and which many executives play with
nearly religious fervor. And it is all driven by the PGA of America
and the PGA Tour, which have done a remarkable job of marketing and
catering to major companies. (The PGA of America represents club
professionals and runs the Ryder Cup and the PGA Championship, one
of golf's four major tournaments. The PGA Tour operates the weekly
tournament schedule for professional golf.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you look at the list of corporations that have
purchased tents at The Country Club to entertain their customers,
you are going to find them in a lot of other sports too,'' said
Larry Moulter, president of Woolf Associates. ``But golf offers
about the most premium approach to your dollar for the businesses
that get involved.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the leadership of its former commissioner, Deane Beman,
the PGA Tour set out 25 years ago on campaign to secure more
corporate dollars. Beman said that as a player on the tour in the
1960s, he grew tired of seeing businesses giving more and more
money to the National Football League and other professional sports
while the purses for golfers languished.
</P>
<P>
   He made golf more attractive to companies by selling title
sponsorships to major tournaments that offered sponsors
considerable freedom to market the events as they wished. He also
sweetened the deal by making many of the major names on the tour
available for ``pro-am'' tournaments with employees from the
companies during the week of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Total purses increased from about $8.4 million in 1973 to nearly
$100 million in 1994, when Beman stepped down. At the same time,
the PGA Tour's assets increased from $730,000 to $200 million. And
the organization started both the Senior PGA Tour, lengthening the
careers of some of the great names in the game, and the Nike Tour,
sort of a farm team for the big circuit.
</P>
<P>
   The PGA Tour's marketing partners, which serve as general
sponsors, read like a Who's Who of corporate America, including
Anheuser-Busch, Bank of America, John Deere, Delta Airlines,
Gillette, MasterCard, and Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   Both the PGA Tour and PGA of America have become expert at
providing businesses with opportunities to extend hospitality to
their customers by offering tickets for tournaments as part of
entertainment packages.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the PGA has been able to do a better job of appealing
to top-level executives,'' D'Alessandro said. ``And a lot of
tournaments are sponsored by top executives, whether or not they
have any return, because the PGA has done such a great job of
cultivating the top of the house.''
</P>
<P>
   Business people are hardly a difficult group for golf to woo.
Golf courses have long been extensions of the office. By various
estimates, about one-fourth of the 25 million to 30 million golfers
in the United States are top management executives.
</P>
<P>
   When Hyatt Hotels Corp. recently surveyed 400 executives who
play golf, 80 percent agreed it is a great way to make business
contacts, and one third said some of their biggest deals were made
on a golf course. Ninety of the executives surveyed were women.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, businesswomen may not realize what they are missing,
but it doesn't take long to realize, `I should be out there!' ''
said Nancy Oliver, founder and president of the Executive Women's
Golf Foundation. Starting with 28 women in 1991, the group now has
14,000 members and 90 chapters.
</P>
<P>
   Whether playing it or watching it, the leisurely pace of golf
allows for doing at least some business while the game proceeds.
And its stylish pedigree means some will always aspire to be in on
the action.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a much more casual pace, on a golf course or in a
corporate tent, than at a football game, or even a baseball game,''
Moulter said. ``Golf is both a leisurely pursuit and a sign of
success. The other sports just don't deliver the same cache. It's
not a snobbish thing so much as it is, `We've worked hard, we've
arrived, we're part of a class that no one else is a part of.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
