<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVALDO IS HEAR APPARENT AS WORLD'S BEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The soccer world has been expecting someone to emerge as the
heir to Pele and Diego Maradona. Historically, the soccer world has
had patience. Modern marketers do not.
</P>
<P>
   So the crown was thrust upon Brazilian striker Ronaldo before he
was prepared for it and before the public was prepared to accept
him. Though Ronaldo might well have been the world's best player
for a few weeks at a time in 1997 and '98, the overzealous campaign
to validate him always seemed manufactured. In soccer, as in most
entertainment and sports, those with the most enduring fame
generally earn it by popular acclaim.
</P>
<P>
   Ronaldo has shown signs of either burnout or simply being unable
to match the unrealistic hype. Inter has ordered Ronaldo to reduce
his extracurricular activity, postponing his visit to Kosovo and
announcing that the club will be involved in the visit.
</P>
<P>
   Inter has indulged Ronaldo and his sponsors to the limit and
probably should have taken action sooner. Inter's patrons, the
Moratti family, are prominent in anti-land mine campaigns and will
certainly organize a productive visit to Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But they also want Ronaldo to return to form. He was not even in
uniform for Inter's 5-1 victory over Parma Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Now, we have the answer to Ronaldo, the ``Anti-Phenomenon,'' as
described by La Gazzetta dello Sport: a Brazilian named Rivaldo
Victor Borba Ferreira.
</P>
<P>
   Said Pele, ``Rivaldo is indisputably the best player in the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johan Cruyff, ``He is one of the few modern players that
can still provide for me pleasure and excitement. He has South
American talent and European professionalism. But I must say that
above all it is the lack of great players in modern soccer that
accentuates the value of Rivaldo.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo succeeded Ronaldo at Barcelona and led Barca to
successive Spanish Liga titles. He has filled the No. 10 role with
Brazil and scored three goals and set up Ronaldo for one in a 4-2
victory over Argentina in Porto Alegre Sept. 7. The only other
Brazilian to score three times against Argentina was Pele in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   Rivaldo has grown strong despite a youth of malnutrition in the
favelas of Recife. At nearly 6 feet 3 inches, 165 pounds, Rivaldo
does not have the classic size of a playmaker. He is sort of a
combination of his predecessors, with Pele's athleticism and
imagination, plus Roberto Rivelinho's left-footed power.
</P>
<P>
   The Barcelona fans adore Rivaldo, and their opinion of him has
been boosted by his ability to stand up to Louis Van Gaal, the
hard-driving Dutch coach. Rivaldo often leaves his left wing
position to take charge of the team, but Van Gaal cannot easily
discipline him, even after a 2-1 loss to Alaves that dropped
Barcelona out of first place.
</P>
<P>
   The most refreshing aspect of Rivaldo's rise is that he is not
surrounded by agents and marketers. Rivaldo keeps a low profile
with his family, and he has remained faithful to his sponsor,
Mizuno, which has been judicious in promoting him.
</P>
<P>
   Manchester United and Italian clubs want to pry Rivaldo away
from Barcelona. Rivaldo's salary, about $3 million a year, would
have to be at least doubled. But Rivaldo is contracted to Barcelona
through 2003, and the buyout clause is $90 million.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reigning in Spain
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The surprise leader in Spain is Rayo Vallecano, located in
Madrid's Vallecas working-class section and traditionally the
city's No. 3 club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are living a dream,'' Rayo Vallecano's Maria Teresa Rivero
Ruiz, one of the few women presidents of professional clubs, told
the sports daily Marca. ``If I bring the team to the UEFA, they
will make a monument to me in Vallecas.''
</P>
<P>
   Rayo Vallecano, founded in 1924, has already become a tribute to
the Ruiz Mateos family, once considered the richest family in the
country, which named the stadium after themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The directors of the club have been efficient in their spending,
though. They assembled a team of cost-effective players, then added
US goalkeeper Kasey Keller from Leicester City in England. Keller
was attracted to the team because his wife had studied in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   Keller said he communicates with teammates in ``Spanglish.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And if we don't understand each other, Van den Bergh (a Dutch
teammate) acts as translator,'' Keller said. ``He speaks English
and Castellano perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Communication was good in Sunday's game, as Juan Antonio
``Bolo'' Perez scored in a 1-0 victory over Celta in Vigo, which
improved Rayo Vallecano's record to 4-0-0.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Misguided effort
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pele believes that Brazil is wasting money and time campaigning
for the 2006 World Cup, which will certainly go to England,
Germany, or South Africa. And, for once, former FIFA president Joao
Havelange agrees with Pele that this would be a lost cause. ``I
would rather lose a finger than a hand,'' Havelange said,
explaining that Brazil should bid for the 2010 finals. ``To win, it
is necessary to know how to lose. If Brazil does not organize the
2006 Cup, I can guarantee it for 2010.'' . . . Meanwhile, Pele is
being criticized in his role as a director of his former club,
Santos. As Botafogo edged Santos, 1-0, for its first victory of the
Brazilian Championship, fans chanted, ``Fora Samir, fora Pele,''
calling for the ouster of the team president and Pele. Supporters
also threw shoes onto the field at Vila Belmiro in Sao Paulo and
were involved in a dispute with vice president Jose Paulo
Fernandes. The other target of fans' displeasure was striker Dodo,
at $5.5 million the most expensive purchase in club history, who
was replaced in the second half by Colombian Victor Hugo
Aristizabal . . . Department of the League of Redundancy League:
The UEFA Champions League appears to have accomplished much of what
backers of a Super League wanted. The Champions Cup has been
compromised, at least in name, since even fourth-place teams can
qualify, and the sponsorship and television money has exceeded 800
million Swiss francs (about $600 million), according to the
Geneva-based UEFA. Two successive victories and first place in
Group D after the opening Champions League game was not enough for
Olympique Marseille coach Rolland Courbis. Marseille defeated Sturm
Graz, 2-0, in the Champions League and Troyes, 1-0, in the France
Le Championnat. But Robert Louis-Dreyfuss, a Harvard student in the
'60s and now chairman of Adidas-Salomon AG and president of
Marseille, has decided to recall Croat Tomislav Ivic to replace
Courbis for Wednesday's Champions League game at Croatia in Zagreb
. . . Porto, hoping to salvage Portuguese hopes, plays host to
Olympiakos in Group E. Last week, five Portuguese clubs were
outscored, 15-1, in European competition. A last-minute goal by
Brazilian defender Deco gave Porto a 1-0 win at Molde in Norway . .
. The Celtic-Rangers game in the Scottish League was postponed to
November so the teams could prepare for European matches. Rangers
could have an edge in Group F Tuesday against Bayern Munich, which
lost all three first-team goalkeepers to injuries and will have
20-year-old Stefan Wessels in goal. Wessels has been playing for
Bayern's B team in the regional amateur league . . . Chelsea, the
first-week sensation after playing Milan to a 0-0 draw in Group H,
was humbled by Watford, 1-0, in the Premier League. Coach Gianluca
Vialli rested several starters against Watford in preparation for
hs team's visit to Hertha Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Easy come, easy go
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Carolina Morace, the first woman to be named coach of an Italian
professional team, had Viterbese in first place after the first
week in Serie C1. But Morace was fired by president Luciano Gaucci
after a 5-2 loss to Crotone. Morace said she would return to law
school, and Viterbese has gone undefeated since . . . MLS is among
the youngest professional leagues, but soccer's roots in the US are
deep. In fact, the American Soccer League produced the all-time
world record-holder for goals scored in a season: Archibald
McPherson ``Archie'' Stark converted 67 goals in 44 games for
Bethlehem Steel in the 1924-25 season. According to the
International Federation of Soccer History and Statistics, No. 2 is
Ferenc Deak of Hungary, who had 66 goals in 34 games in the 1945-46
season, and then William ``Dixie'' Dean of England, with 60 in 39
games in 1927-28. Pele is seventh with 58 goals in 38 games in the
1958 Paulista season . . . Newcastle United does not seem to miss
Ruud Gullitt, who was replaced by former England manager Bobby
Robson. Newcastle earned its first victory of the Premier League
season as Alan Shearer scored five goals in an 8-0 win over
Sheffield Wednesday. Another former England manager, Glenn Hoddle,
is the top candidate to take over Sheffield Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
