<SLUG> BC-RAC-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORE THAN READY WAS LESS THAN SUCCESSFUL IN FUTURITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If there was one thing that seemed certain in what has been an
unsettled year in racing, it was that More Than Ready was the best
2-year-old colt in the country. Now, with More Than Ready having
gone down to defeat in the Futurity at Belmont Sunday, nothing can
be taken for granted.
</P>
<P>
   A son of Southern Halo, out of a Woodman mare, More Then Ready
had done everything right prior to the Futurity, winning five
races, four of them stakes, in fast times. However, as so often
happens, distance proved a problem for a promising young horse.
More Than Ready, who had never raced past 6 furlongs, tired coming
to the wire of the 1-mile Futurity and finished third, beaten two
necks. Ridden by John Velasquez, More than Ready was off at 2-5,
proving an old racing axiom that you never bet on a favorite to do
something he's never done before.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was his first start over 6 furlongs, and he hung on until
the end,'' said Todd Pletcher, who trains More Than Ready. ``This
horse is a fighter with a lot of heart. I'm a little disappointed
he didn't win. But that's the way the game goes. He was just beaten
by a nice horse (Bevo).''
</P>
<P>
   In a teleconference before the Futurity, Pletcher was fielding
questions about More Than Ready being Horse of the Year, let alone
2-year-old champion. You can forget that.
</P>
<P>
   An excuse can be made for More Than Ready. He had developed a
fever that caused him to miss the Hopeful at Saratoga Sept. 4, and
had not raced in 52 days. But he had bounced back quickly, working
out at the Saratoga training track Sept. 6, and then authoring a
best-of-the-day 6-furlong work at Belmont, going 1:13 Sept. 12.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains that he had the lead in the stretch and lost
it, shortening stride in the last 20 yards to be passed not only by
Bevo, who was 11-1 under Joe Bravo, but also by 30-1 bomb Greenwood
Lake and Jean-Luc Samyn. The time for the one-turn mile was 1:36,
and the loss may be an early indication that More Than Ready has
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just didn't respond like he did in the past,'' said
Velazquez. ``He just wasn't there in the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The division for 2-year-old males is now wide open. D. Wayne
Lukas trains a top one in High Yield, who took the Hopeful in More
Than Ready's absence, and Bob Baffert may have the next sensation
in Forest Camp, who captured the Del Mar Futurity in spectacular
fashion. Bevo, whose only loss in five starts came to More Than
Ready in the Flash Stakes at Belmont June 4, also joins the upper
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has improved leaps and bounds mentally,'' said Bill
Badgett, who trains Bevo, a son of Prospector's Gamble. ``We
thought this would be the time to go after More Than Ready. Todd's
horse was playing a little bit of catch-up, while my horse has
progressed after each race. We thought we had a legitimate chance.
The Champagne (at Belmont Oct. 9) is a possibility, but we might
just skip the Champagne, and go right to the Breeders' Cup (at
Gulfstream Nov. 6).''
</P>
<P>
   It is entirely possible that More Than Ready's off day was
caused by his layoff. Whether that's so or not, the coronation has
been canceled, and More Than Ready is now in a real horse race for
juvenile honors.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Keen eye for talent
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How good is Baffert? He claimed River Keen, then age 6, for
$100,000 at Hollywood Park Dec. 4. This year, River Keen won the
Bel Air Handicap at Hollywood, finished second in both the San
Diego Handicap and the $1 million Pacific Classic, both at Del Mar,
and won the $500,000 Woodward Stakes at Belmont Saturday. Since
joining Baffert's barn, the Irish-bred has earned more than
$700,000. Baffert took advantange when the prestigious Woodward
came up a little light, as the connections of heavy hitters such as
Behrens and Lemon Drop Kid chose to wait for the Gold Cup Oct. 10.
Win the Woodward with a claimer? Only Baffert . . . Trainer Nick
Zito hasn't been in the spotlight much this season, but he made a
solid mark when he saddled Doneraile Court to a victory in the
$150,000 Jerome Mile for 3-year-olds on the Woodward undercard. A
son of Seattle Slew, Doneraile Court cost $1 million as a yearling.
He'll probably never make that back _ he's up to $326,000 now _ but
he has a chance to do some good things now that his camp has
realized he doesn't want to go long. ``This horse is a miler, and
he definitely loves Belmont Park,'' said Zito. ``He beat a good
colt in Vicar. We're going to hang around New York, and the Cigar
Mile (at Aqueduct Nov. 7) is our main goal.'' . . . Pletcher had a
tough Sunday, as Circle of Life, his outstanding 2-year-old filly,
also finished third. Off at 9-5, she was beaten a total of 2
lengths by Finder's Fee and Darling My Darling in the $150,000
Matron, the companion race to the Futurity. The time for the mile
was 1:36 3/5. Finder's Fee, who was 5-1 under Mike Smith, is
another who likes Belmont. The daughter of Storm Cat had finished
out of the money in two stakes at Saratoga, but came off the pace
to take the Matron, the first race in which she had the
anti-bleeding medication Lasix. ``I think when we got her back to
Belmont, her attitude changed,'' said Shug McGaughey, who trains
Finder's Fee. ``At Saratoga, the long walk from the barn to the
paddock got to her. Plus, Mike told me she didn't like the track up
there. I always thought she had the ability.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Material from publicity departments at various racetracks was used
to prepare this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
