<HEADER>
A9960 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-STRATEGY-BO     09-21 1031
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-STRATEGY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR STRATEGY, THERE IS NO RIGHT ANSWER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Dave Stockton couldn't quite believe what he
was hearing. As a Ryder Cup rookie in 1971, he was trying hard to
calm his nerves and not be intimidated. Then his playing partner
spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just three holes into the match,'' said Stockton, ``(Jack)
Nicklaus begins whining about having to hit a 5-iron (approach). He
says: `I hit a wedge in here Monday.' '' Though Stockton, 29, was
only a few years younger than Nicklaus, he was obviously the
student driver in this tandem.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he couldn't help himself. ``I said, `You're the greatest
player in the world. What difference does it make if you're hitting
5-iron or wedge?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nicklaus just looked at Stockton and the discussion was over.
</P>
<P>
   Moral of the story: There is a difference between a 5-iron and a
wedge and if you don't know that, then you probably don't think it
matters who is paired with whom for these Ryder Cup matches.
</P>
<P>
   There indeed is a strategy, which is why American captain Ben
Crenshaw said he has been losing sleep for weeks. The challenge is
settling on a strategy that works.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foursomes (alternate shot)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   This is the toughest format to play and requires more thought on
a captain's part. Nicklaus preferred pairing long hitters with long
hitters, short hitters with short hitters, the thinking being that
each would have yardage into greens that they were used to hitting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would tend to agree with that sentiment,'' said Crenshaw,
who has a team with some marquee long hitters _ nothing more
attractive than Tiger Woods with David Duval.
</P>
<P>
   This philosophy has not been embraced by everyone, however. In
1997, for instance, American captain Tom Kite leaned toward
personalities and paired good friends Woods and Mark O'Meara. Their
discrepancy in length was a factor in a 5-and-3 foursomes loss to
Colin Montgomerie and Bernhard Langer.
</P>
<P>
   Others dismiss the notion of putting like hitters together,
claiming two other factors are more important.
</P>
<P>
   1) Keep the ball in play. This is what led captain Lanny Wadkins
to pass over Phil Mickelson in both phases of alternate shot in
1995, a decision he he was criticized for for when the talented
lefthander went 3-0 in his other matches. But Wadkins was concerned
about every player's fear in this style of play _ having to hit a
shot out of thick rough or from behind a tree.
</P>
<P>
   2) More than anything, said Tom Lehman, you need players who
understand each other. He was a Cup rookie in 1995 and found
himself in the lead group, paired with the heart of that year's
team, Corey Pavin. ``I remember, I hit a bad shot and kind of went,
aaaaahhhh, but Corey said, `Don't worry, I hit it in worse spots
than that all the time.' That made me feel at ease.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I didn't worry about where I hit it or didn't hit
it.''
</P>
<P>
   To Lee Westwood, the key is judging your own play. ``If you're
not playing well, (foursomes) gets a lot harder because you just
don't want to let your partner down and put him in trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is one golden rule, said Westwood. ``You never
apologize'' to your partner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Four-ball (best-ball)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Captains will tend to pay less attention to playing styles and
more to personalities in this format. Since players hit their own
ball all the way, the idea is to make birdies _ or at least have
lots of chances _ and in theory players who are friendly with one
another are looser, i.e. in better form.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a strategy that will come into play in four-ball at
The Country Club, it is a straight-forward one _ the par-4 fourth
(338 yards) and sixth (312 yards) holes are drivable by the longest
of hitters, so while Woods, Duval, Sergio Garcia, Jarmo Sandelin,
and others will perhaps give it a go, the first order of business
would be for their partner to get in play.
</P>
<P>
   Captains have a better feel for this format especially since
there are so many players who are easy fits because of their games
and personalities (Lehman, Hal Sutton, and Steve Pate come to
mind). For European coach Mark James, there is the fact that
countrymen sometimes pair well together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer to play with someone who speaks my language,'' said
Spaniard Jose Maria Olazabal, who was Seve Ballesteros's mate in a
Ryder Cup-record 15 matches. Now, look for him to guide Miguel
Angel Jimenez or perhaps teenage sensation Sergio Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Singles
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Much depends on how a team stands through two days. If it is
trailing (as the US was in 1997), look for a captain to load up the
front of his lineup with premier players to get back into the
match.
</P>
<P>
   It almost worked for Kite at Valderrama as Fred Couples (off
first), O'Meara (third) and Mickelson (fourth) did their part;
however, Davis Love III (second) was upset and Woods (fifth) was
shocked.
</P>
<P>
   A captain may try and protect a lead by putting better players
toward the back. Ballesteros did this in 1997, but his 9-10-11 guys
(Westwood, Olazabal, and Nick Faldo) were soundly beaten. What
saved him was the big lead going into the singles matches and
unexpected victories by Per-Ulrik Johansson (over Love) and
Costantino Rocca (over Woods).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Who plays
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the Americans have been so strong, captains have
usually been sensitive about playing everyone in three or four
matches, rarely all five. Not so the Europeans. As annual
underdogs, they don't have the luxury of balance and depth, so key
players are called upon to carry the load.
</P>
<P>
   Only Woods for the US played in five matches two years ago. The
Europeans turned to four players (Faldo, Montgomerie, Olazabal,
Westwood) to go all the way. Ian Woosnam played just twice, got
steamed, but nobody cared once the celebration started. Ballesteros
was not there to soothe egos.
</P>
<P>
   It is a sentiment that Crenshaw may adopt for this year's
matches. Having gone 2-4-1 in recent Ryder Cups, the situation is
desperate. ``If someone is hot,'' he said, ``I'll ride them.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if it means being ``Not So Gentle'' Ben.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
