<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SF-MAYORAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S.F. MAYORAL CANDIDATE WAGES WAR ON CHAIN STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Mayoral candidate Clint Reilly said he supports
stiff restrictions on chain stores in San Francisco, a stance that
could help him gain the favor of neighborhood activists.
</P>
<P>
   The political consultant-turned-candidate held a news conference
Monday across the street from a Starbucks coffee house to oppose
what he called the ``chain store invasion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``San Francisco is slowly losing the character of its
neighborhoods and its neighborhood shopping districts, and once it
is lost, it will never, ever be recovered,'' Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate's attack on chain stores hits an age-old San
Francisco campaign theme _ the neighborhoods vs. the downtown
business interests. By championing the cause of mom-and-pop stores,
Reilly is positioning himself as the protector of the
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly, one of 13 candidates challenging Mayor Willie Brown in
the Nov. 2 election here, said he would appoint planning
commissioners who oppose the spread of stores such as Blockbuster
and Starbucks. And he promised to tighten zoning controls, even
suggesting a ban on drive-through windows in certain neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Some skeptics suggested Reilly's anti-chain store stand may have
more to do with electioneering than conviction. ``He is running for
mayor and he needs to pick up whatever issues are important to him
in his campaign,'' Supervisor Leland Yee said.
</P>
<P>
   But Yee, who has been the board's most vocal opponent of chain
store development, praised Reilly for taking up the concerns of
neighborhood groups about chain stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had a mayor with the appropriate commitment, and if you
had a Planning Commission and a Board of Permit Appeals that was a
lot more sensitive to these issues, then neighborhood groups and
individuals would get a better shake in those decisions,'' Yee
said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood activists have fought the encroachment of chain
stores in several city neighborhoods, with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Rite-Aid, a Pennsylvania-based pharmacy chain, has lost two of
three requests to move into city neighborhoods in recent years. But
Starbucks, which had just seven stores here in 1993, now has 29
stores in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   At the news conference, Reilly charged that chain stores had
expanded dramatically under Brown's administration. He gave
reporters a list of lobbyists connected to Brown who he said had
taken money from chain stores, including the mayor's campaign
manager, Jack Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Reilly also held up a copy of a Starbucks brochure, distributed
at its San Francisco stores, featuring a picture of Brown holding a
Starbucks coffee mug.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many more neighborhoods will our mayor sell out to
Starbucks in order to get a free brochure for his re-election
campaign?'' Reilly asked.
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Johnston, the mayor's campaign spokesman, explained that
the mayor's appearance in the brochure is part of charitable
program. For every purchase of a Starbucks San Francisco mug, the
company donates 50 cents to the Mayor's Neighborhood Beautification
Fund.
</P>
<P>
   He said that ``the charitable donation campaign was in place
long before the election ever approached. And the neighborhood
beautification fund does nothing but good work in the
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly's plan to limit chain stores would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Define chain stores as ``formula businesses'' under the
planning code. According to Reilly, a formula business is one that
maintains standardized services, decor, uniforms, architecture and
signs.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require developers to notify nearby residents and businesses
by mail about any proposed new formula business. Current law
requires only businesses over a certain size or of a certain type,
such as a nightclub, to provide such notification.
</P>
<P>
   _ Require that any prominent signs for the business _ such as a
fast-food chain's logo _ be posted on the proposed site four weeks
before a public hearing on granting a permit.
</P>
<P>
   - Help neighborhoods strengthen zoning controls. Reilly said he
favors size limits, which can keep businesses of a certain size out
of neighborhoods, and density limits, which could, for example,
keep a new pharmacy from moving in on the same block as an existing
pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   Johnston argued that ``tons of public notice'' are already
required before a permit hearing. He said Reilly's blanket
opposition to chains could prevent residents from making up their
own minds about whether they want a given business in their
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mayor Brown's central position on the issue of chain stores is
that the neighborhood, on a neighborhood-by-neighborhood basis,
should determine what businesses are desirable in that community,''
Johnston said.
</P>
<P>
   Rich DeLeon, chairman of the political science department at San
Francisco State University, said Reilly hopes to cast himself as
the outsider more allied with the concerns of residents than
entrenched City Hall interests.
</P>
<P>
   ``This kind of appeal is especially attractive to those who are
longtime residents, who worked hard to create a home and establish
themselves in a neighborhood and who want to defend that quality of
life,'' DeLeon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
