<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 13:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9962 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-PARNEVIK-AR     09-21 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PARNEVIK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO JOKE: PARNEVIK CAN PLAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Hey, have you heard the one about the Swedish
golfer who flips up the bill of his cap as if he were at
kindergarten recess, carries a tee over his ear for decoration,
eats volcanic dust for its purgative value, wears skintight pants
straight from the '50s over his toothpick legs, ponders abstruse
mathematical problems in the midst of competitive rounds,
occasionally skulls spectators with errant shots _ and is on the
European Ryder Cup team?
</P>
<P>
   Of course you have, if you follow the sport. And you know it's
no joke, although Bo Parnevik, Sweden's foremost comedian and
impressionist, might try to turn it into one. Come to think of it,
Bo's son Jesper, who fits the above description, is often mistaken
for a punch line instead of what he is _ one of the world's finest
golfers, a winner on both the European and US PGA tours, twice the
British Open runner-up, and a member of the team that retained the
Ryder Cup against the United States at Valderrama, Spain, two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Jesper Parnevik will be at The Country Club in Brookline this
weekend as Europe tries to make it three in a row, and he is
enthralled by the prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot of fun,'' he says. ``It's different from any other
tournament on any tour. The atmosphere is so charged. You see guys
jumping up and high-fiving _ on the second hole. It's like playing
golf in the middle of the Super Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   And make no mistake about it, Parnevik loves playing golf. And
he's deadly serious about it, putting in 9 1/2-hour days in
preparation for tournaments. But his eccentricities seem to
outstrip his accomplishments in the public mind. And he did his
reputation no favors during the Loch Lomond Open in July when he
missed a short putt in the second round because he was pondering
this hypothetical question posed by his caddie: If you placed a
rope around the Earth's circumference and placed another rope above
it on 3-foot stakes, how much longer would the higher rope be? The
answer: 18.84 feet. Parnevik didn't get it, but he won the wager by
coming closest to the pinpoint.
</P>
<P>
   But there was another mathematical problem: Leading the
tournament at the time, Parnevik acknowledged being distracted by
the question, and he wound up finishing in a tie for fifth, four
strokes behind winner Colin Montgomerie.
</P>
<P>
   This is why some people associate him more with his father's
occupation _ freakish entertainment _ than with the solemnities
that big-time golf demands.
</P>
<P>
   Is this any way for a 34-year-old to act?
</P>
<P>
   Parnevik, who is in fact a sensitive, thoughtful man, considers
the dichotomy and says, ``The public may think (he's a sideshow
act), but I think it's more the media. They like to put you in a
compartment as soon as they see something different.''
</P>
<P>
   What's also different about Parnevik is his genuine compassion
in the often cold, impersonal golf world. In truth, his Loch Lomond
performance probably suffered less from his computations than it
did from his distress after he hit a fan in the head with a shot.
He was unaware of the damage at the time and was visibly upset when
he discovered the stricken man bleeding profusely. The first thing
Parnevik did after the round was to inquire about the man's
condition, and the next day, he presented him with a picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he was all right,'' says Parnevik. ``I don't know if
he wanted the picture. He probably didn't want to remember the
incident. In fact, he probably didn't remember the incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Rim shot.
</P>
<P>
   Well, some of the old man had to rub off on him. Parnevik
remembers that when he was a youngster, his father would try out
material on him and his three younger sisters. ``We were a tough
crowd,'' he says. ``You know how it is _ you never think your
father is that funny. So if he got us to laugh, he knew he had
something.''
</P>
<P>
   But there was a serious side to being the comedian's kid. His
father may not have been rich _ ``it's not like with David
Letterman and Jay Leno over in Sweden,'' says Parnevik _ but he
certainly was famous. And Jesper was caught in the spotlight's
reflection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been famous in Sweden since I was a kid as my dad's
son,'' he says. ``I used to do some (comic) things in school, but
you know how it is. If your dad is very successful, it's really
tough to be compared to him if you follow in his footsteps. I
probably subconsciously wanted to go a different route so I
wouldn't be known just as my dad's son.''
</P>
<P>
   That route was on the golf course, for which Parnevik indirectly
owes his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``He got the golf bug bad in the mid-'70s,'' recalls Parnevik.
``He dug up the backyard, put in holes and bunkers, tried
computers, bought all the golf books, went for every type of
gimmick. I had to try it out.''
</P>
<P>
   He made two marvelous discoveries. One: ``I found it a lot of
fun. I could spend hours putting and chipping.'' Two: He was good
at it.
</P>
<P>
   Sweden's premier junior player, Parnevik found a sponsor for the
European Tour after college and a stint on the national team when
he joined Team Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was me and a couple of other guys,'' he says. ``They gave
us some financial support so we could exist. Golf wasn't very big
in Sweden back then.''
</P>
<P>
   It is now. And the biggest thing in Swedish golf is Jesper
Parnevik.
</P>
<P>
   Seriously.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
