<HEADER>
A9963 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-TV-COLUMN-B     09-21 0979
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-TV-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS PROMISES TO BE MUST-SEE TV 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Blame all of the upcoming Ryder Cup hoopla
on Gordon Beck.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years ago, the young producer had the bright idea to spend
$200,000 to televise the little-known event on his lesser- known
cable network.
</P>
<P>
   Less than a million viewers watched the three days of coverage
from The Belfry in Sutton Coldfield, England, 1989. But USA Network
had it first and had it live.
</P>
<P>
   The match came down to the last day and the last hole of singles
competition, and when the 18th proved too much for Payne Stewart,
Mark Calcavecchia, and Fred Couples, the Americans settled for a
tie. The Europeans retained the Cup because they had won it
outright in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   The dramatic match and USA's coverage caught the attention of
NBC, which quickly put up $2 million to televise the 1991 Cup, live
from Kiawah Island, S.C. By 1995, the television rights went for
$4.5 million, and this year's Ryder Cup cost a little more than $13
million. Ratings have nearly doubled since 1989, a noteworthy
achievement considering the final day's broadcast competes with
Sunday afternoon NFL games.
</P>
<P>
   Beck had little idea that the Ryder Cup, first played in 1927 at
Worcester Country Club, would become a premier sporting event. He
had other problems to worry about in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, the PGA of America was nervous because the event
had never been televised live in America. They were not familiar
with USA Network. The cable station started broadcasting in the
early '80s and most of its programming was taped sporting events
and movies.
</P>
<P>
   More problems came from the BBC. The British television network
aired the Ryder Cup in Europe and tried to suffocate the upstart
American network. ``It wasn't that they were arrogant,'' Beck said.
``But they were a little too helpful, always telling us they would
give us a cameraman or otherwise help with our production. We had
our own production team and I got to tell you, some of their
cameramen you could tell had just been pulled from their studio and
had never covered flying golf balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Beck said he managed to get around the BBC and give his
broadcast an American flavor. ``It was a great dramatic event,''
Beck said. ``And it woke up a lot of people..
</P>
<P>
   This was pre-Tiger, when golf languished on network TV. ``It was
a like a backwater town,'' Beck said. ``And we've been able to ride
along.''
</P>
<P>
   The explosion has helped USA as well. The network airs many of
the early rounds of the top tennis and golf events during the
season. USA will broadcast the first day of the Ryder Cup from The
Country Club, from 7:30 a.m. to 6 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   NBC had the network rights but USA still had the cable rights.
NBC allowed USA to hire producer Tommy Roy to work on the cable
network's coverage of the 1991 Ryder Cup. In addition to four Emmys
for his coverage of the Atlanta Olympics, Roy won an Emmy in 1998
for his production of golf on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise. Roy grew up in a golf family. His father,
Billy Roy, was a PGA pro for 50 years before retiring this year.
His uncle, Jim Roy, is the pro at St. Boniface Country Club in
Winnipeg. Roy himself played for the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Roy has worked every Ryder Cup since 1991 for NBC and this year
presides over an amazing array of hardware, graphics, and on-air
talent to televise the event from The Country Club in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   The tower where host Dick Enberg and analyst Johnny Miller call
the match rests near the green of the 18th hole.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's deployment of 35 cameras includes 18 fixed cameras, one
behind each green, and five smaller cameras positioned near the
fourth, 14th, 15th, 16th, 17th, and 18th holes (the camera used on
the fourth is attached to a super slo mo unit and also will be used
on the 17th).
</P>
<P>
   NBC has two cameras attached to forklifts stationed near the
first and 12th fairways; three cameras attached to boom devices
enabling viewers to see a sweeping shot of the first tee, the 11th
fairway, and behind the 18th green; and another camera attached to
a huge crane positioned to the right of the eighth green enabling
NBC to provide coverage of the eighth, ninth, and 14th holes.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has stationed a smaller crane to the right of the 11th
fairway to give coverage of the 11th and 12th holes. Three flatbed
trucks called ``Rat Patrols'' will cover the entire course.
</P>
<P>
   The most unusual camera angle comes on the sixth tee, where NBC
has attached a small camera on an overhanging tree branch that will
give viewers a shot directly above the golfers as they take their
drives.
</P>
<P>
   The 35 cameras NBC is using for the Ryder Cup are more than the
30 the network used to televise Super Bowl XXXII.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has designed eight different types of graphics to provide
scoring updates of individual matches and team totals. NBC
spokesman Ed Markey said that the network will not have a permanent
on-screen scoreboard. ``Because this is match play as opposed to
stroke play, there's a lot of information that can clutter a screen
real fast,'' Markey said.
</P>
<P>
   At appropriate times, NBC will show eight different types of
displays, including the team totals and updates on current matches.
They will have a scoreboard for the foursomes competition, with a
photograph of the player and his country's flag, and one for
singles competition, giving viewers team totals as well as match
scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The viewer won't be wondering about information and scores,''
Markey promised.
</P>
<P>
   Beck didn't have the luxury of all that equipment and computer
wizardry. It still comes down to the performance on the field.
``There may be a hero or two,'' Beck said. ``And there might be a
goat or two.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 13:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9965 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-RYAN-COLUMN     09-21 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORPORATE FRAUDS? A WEALTH OF EVIDENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Oh, if Thorstein Veblen could be here at The
Country Club this week.
</P>
<P>
   The 19th-century economist, who gave birth to the phrase
``conspicuous consumption,'' would have been alternately appalled
and amused by what he would see. For rarely in the history of this
Republic have so many so overtly conspicuously consumed as they
will be doing, starting Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The 1999 Ryder Cup might well be the culmination of just about
everything that has gone wrong with sport in the last third of this
century. This is, after all, a golf tournament. In theory, at
least, the reason anyone should care about being at The Country
Club is the competition. In that sense, the overall opulence being
flouted here this week is irrelevant to the stated purpose of the
event. Except that it isn't.
</P>
<P>
   It all began with Judge Roy Hofheinz and his cute little luxury
suites at the Astrodome. Until that moment (1965), the most the
rich could say was that they had better seats. If it rained, and
they chose to stick around, they got wet. If some guy in the middle
of the row wanted to go out for a beer or to answer nature's call,
then Mr. Big Shot seated at the end of the aisle had to stand up,
smoosh himself back against his upturned seat and allow the other
fellow to pass by. He might even have his toes stepped on.
</P>
<P>
   Horrors!
</P>
<P>
   Thirty-four years later we live in a world of luxury suites and
club seats with waitress service. These entities are the engine
driving all arena and stadium construction in this country. Our
outdoor edifices are actually smaller in seating capacity than the
ones they replace, because basic attendance just doesn't matter
when stacked up against the money generated by the swells in their
luxury suites and club seats. The message to the average person
could not be clearer: You just don't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere is this more evident than at Jacobs Field in Cleveland.
What should be thousands of nice upper-deck seats available to vox
populi have been given over to obnoxious glassed-in luxury suites,
which, when lit, create the appearance of an ocean liner. At the
end of this horrifying display, adjacent to the left-field foul
pole, sits a three-tiered restaurant, where, you can be assured, no
one is concerned about what might be happening on the field.
</P>
<P>
   And just when you think that things cannot get any sicker or
more surreal, here come the New England Patriots. It's not enough
that the fat cats have their cozy suites and their overpriced meals
and their TV sets and their couches and their private bathrooms and
their own boring company. Oh, no. Now Robert Kraft has to give them
their own private road to the stadium. God forbid some of the elite
be forced to spend time in their cars listening to the pregame and
postgame shows like the rest of us. Their time is much too precious
for that. They might have mergers to consummate and people to throw
out of work. They can't waste time sitting in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   In none of their minds is simply attending a nice sporting event
good enough in itself. It must be a vehicle to entertain, and it
must provide an opportunity to show off. What good is wealth, after
all, if it cannot be conspicuously consumed?
</P>
<P>
   That said, we give you the obscenity of the Ryder Cup corporate
tents. The competition between the best American and best European
golfers is not enough. Far more important is the competition
between Corporation X and Corporation Y to see who can pamper
customers more. That's a worthy $250,000 investment.
</P>
<P>
   Even fellow rich people are awed by the scope of this particular
degree of conspicuous consumption. ``I don't ever think I've seen
such corporate hospitality,'' marvels Jaime Ortiz-Patino (``Jimmy''
to his friends), the billionaire Bolivian tin magnate who just
happens to own the course at Valderrama, where the Ryder Cup was
held two years ago. ``It breaks all the records.''
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is a parallel universe in which thousands of
people will sit all day in those corporate structures while the
golf takes place outside their front door. Some small percentage of
these fans will be real, live, golf fans who are genuinely thrilled
to be in attendance. The majority will come just to say they were
there. Meanwhile, of the 30,000 Ryder Cup tickets, only 10,000 were
made available to the general public.
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder that David Duval has labeled the Ryder Cup as
``just another corporate outing.'' As much as any of these players
profess to be single-minded about their golfing interests, how
could someone not be distracted by what is going on around them?
</P>
<P>
   ``There are definitely a lot of tents,'' acknowledges Jim Furyk.
``I don't think you can be oblivious to it. Half the course looks
white out there.''
</P>
<P>
   It is still supposed to be about the competition, and when you
turn to the sports page this week that will be the main focus. The
basic story line is that a powerful American squad _ ``the
strongest team ever to play in the Ryder Cup,'' according to
Sweden's Jesper Parnevik _ must forge enough of a team identity to
defeat a European team that has had more passion in the last two
competitions. As much as these millionaire private contractors are
businessmen to the core (and this goes for both sides), they are
athletes and competitors first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game of golf is getting bigger and bigger,'' agrees
Scotland's Andrew Coltart. ``The business aspect of it is
incredible. But at the end of the day it's still 18 holes of golf
and let's see who can play.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two parallel universes in play here; it's that simple.
Come to think of it, let the fat cats sit inside all day. In order
to see what's been going on, they might have to buy a morning
paper. We'll be happy to benefit from a little unconspicuous
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
