<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BECK-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BECK EASES BURDEN ON RED SOX BULLPEN 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ From the moment he stepped off a plane at Logan
Airport, hailed a cab, and showed up at Fenway Park just in time to
save a win in his first night in a Red Sox uniform _ before he even
knew his teammates' names _ Rod Beck has had a profound effect on
the Boston bullpen and the American League playoff chase.
</P>
<P>
   This, mind you, from a pitcher who had a bad back in spring
training, underwent surgery to remove bone chips that had been
floating around in his right elbow for a couple of years, and was
deemed a spare part by the Chicago Cubs when they unloaded his
salary for lefty bust Mark Guthrie and minor league third baseman
Cole Liniak last month.
</P>
<P>
   In seven appearances for the Sox, Beck has yet to give up a run
while allowing just four hits in nine innings. He has had three
save opportunities and come away with a save each time. Last
Wednesday in Cleveland, when the Sox played their longest game of
the season to beat the Indians in 13 innings, Beck pitched three
scoreless innings to give Boston a chance to win it after midnight.
</P>
<P>
   That outing became all the more impressive when Beck mentioned
he had pitched a three-inning stint just twice in the last seven
years.
</P>
<P>
   His presence has had a ripple effect on the bullpen. Derek Lowe
has four saves in five chances but also has pitched 15 2/3 innings
this month, nearly a starter's load on this team (Pat Rapp has 15
2/3 innings this month, Bret Saberhagen 11).
</P>
<P>
   In Sunday's 7-3 win over the Detroit Tigers, Lowe entered with
two outs in the sixth and ran the table, allowing just one hit over
the final 3 1/3 innings, striking out three while inducing seven
ground outs.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the bullpen has benefitted. Rich Garces, who has
pitched well all season, has two wins this month, lefthander Rheal
Cormier one. John Wasdin has allowed just two earned runs in 10 2/3
innings, with no home runs in seven appearances. Bryce Florie, who
threw four scoreless innings against his former Tiger teammates
last weekend, has two wins this month. The bullpen has a depth it
has lacked all season, and relievers are not being forced into
roles for which they're not suited.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it much easier for Jimy Williams to turn to his
relievers when his starters are spent. The staff hasn't pitched
better over any stretch this season. The record is 13-4, with a
league-best 3.16 ERA, in September, with the bullpen converting
seven saves in nine chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beck has made a tremendous difference,'' pitching coach Joe
Kerrigan said Sunday. ``Now we can bring Lowe into the seventh or
eighth inning. He can finish a game, but if he has trouble, now he
has a backup.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Beck pitches two days in a row, Lowe can close games out.
It gives us so much more flexibility, and you can see the impact
it's had on everyone: Cormier, Wasdin, Guapo (Garces).''
</P>
<P>
   Beck saved 51 games for the Cubs in their successful quest for a
wild card last season, but by the time of his trade, he had been
displaced as the team's closer by Terry Adams and Rick Aguilera.
Sox general manager Dan Duquette picked up the balance of a $5.5
million salary this season, and a guaranteed $3.5 million in 2000,
for a reliever who came to Boston with a 2-4 record and 7.88 ERA in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Beck's last save opportunity with the Cubs came back on May 12
against the Dodgers, and he blew that one, his fourth blown save in
11 chances. He didn't pitch at all from May 16 until July 23, as
surgery intervened, and when he returned, the Cubs used him more as
mopup man than closer.
</P>
<P>
   But Sox scouts advised Duquette that the reliever was throwing
better with each outing. And when Beck received the news in San
Diego that he'd been traded, he had little doubt that he was coming
to Boston to save games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the job is available right now, so I imagine so,'' he
said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Williams gave him the ball the first night, and there's little
doubt who would get last call against the Toronto Blue Jays Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel great now,'' said Beck, who warmed up Sunday but hasn't
pitched in a game since his three-inning stint last Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   And about that last time he was forced to go three innings . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``One of my most memorable games,'' he said. ``Against LA. They
booed me coming into the game. Three straight singles, the Dodgers
loaded the bases. Then I struck out Todd Zeile, and Eddie Murray
hit into a pitcher-to-home-to-first double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then they were cheering me. It was a big game for us. Helped
us clinch a playoff spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, he's doing the same for the Red Sox.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
