<SLUG> BC-TV-SPORTS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES WEAVE A TANTALIZING WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's bad enough that the Yankees are winning and the team's fans
are seem to be popping up everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   Now they'll have a cool three-dimensional Web site where fans
can create their own characters, walk around a cyber Yankee
Stadium, and chat with Yankee fans all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Worlds.com, a Boston-based Internet company, created the 3-D
site for the Yankees, which is scheduled to be up in time for the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   While most professional sports teams have conventional Web
sites, the Yankees are the first to have one in 3-D.
</P>
<P>
   Ultrastar, the New York-based company that owns the Yankees'
Internet rights, signed an agreement with Worlds.com Monday.
Worlds.com and Ultrastar will share advertising, sponsorships, and
VIP membership fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every baseball fan has a tactile and visual identity with
their favorite team,'' said Ultrastar president Rob Goodale. ``If
you are a Red Sox fan, you think of Fenway. If you are a Yankee
fan, you think of the House That Ruth Built. Baseball is a real,
physical thing and this 3-D site enables fans unable to attend
games to electronically be a part of the experience.''
</P>
<P>
   Worlds.com has been granted rights to re-create not only public
areas in Yankee Stadium such as the bleachers and front-row seats
but private areas as well, including the Yankees' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the next generation,'' said Worlds.com president Thom
Kidrin. ``The Yankees' Web site is now one of the most visited
sites in the country and this new site will take it to the next
level.''
</P>
<P>
   No one can predict how many visitors the 3-D site will attract.
But by all accounts, internet chat rooms are tremendously popular.
American On-Line is pulling about 150,000 new clients to its chat
rooms every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sports fans want to be intimate with their information and
their team,'' Kidrin said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Out of bounds on Ali
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NBC trained a camera on Muhammad Ali sitting in a luxury box
during the Michigan State-Notre Dame game Saturday. Ali suffers
from Parkinson's Disease and has a persistent tremor. It's one
thing for NBC to point him out, but do viewers have to watch Ali
seemingly for minutes, unable to control his movements? Put it this
way. NBC spent more time on Ali and a nothing report from Jim Gray
on the sidelines than it did on the latest allegation of corruption
(the part-time tutor writing a paper for a football player) at
Notre Dame, the network's television partner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly covers the sports media for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
