</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-LUBBOCK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS CITY READY FOR CHAOS, JUST IN Y2 CASE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNDA GOROV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUBBOCK, Texas _ The way Ralph Quest II sees it, being ready for
anything come Jan. 1 means stockpiling enough food to feed his
neighbors in Texas farm country and opening his two wells to slake
their thirst. Otherwise he might have to pull a rifle on them, and
the church elder wouldn't want to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``How long would it take for them to figure out you're eating
and they're not?'' said Quest, who heads up his church's new
disaster-relief committee. ``So I'll be storing up food for them,
too. Because what are you going to do? Shoot your neighbor?''
</P>
<P>
   Few in Lubbock, or elsewhere, anticipate Armageddon to result
from the computer glitch now known worldwide as the Y2K bug. Most
Americans _ who accept the word of companies and cities that their
computers will work properly come the new year _ anticipate only
minor problems or none at all, according to a summer Associated
Press poll.
</P>
<P>
   Still, no one seems certain of how ready America's small towns
and big cities are for whatever problems do occur. In the same
poll, almost one-third of the people said they plan to stock up on
food, water, and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of folks in Lubbock, Quest said he doesn't know if
the New Year will bring a blip, a bump, or disaster. But
self-reliance runs deep in cotton country. Even locals who scoff at
the idea that computer chips and software will go haywire the
second 1999 turns into 2000 tend to keep extras on hand in case
another tornado hits. Three decades ago, the big one laid waste to
25 square miles of homes and businesses, killing 26 residents and
injuring hundreds more.
</P>
<P>
   But natural disasters such as the 1970 tornado draw help from
neighboring communities. The man-made disaster that doomsayers
insist will shut down utilities, disable ATMs, and leave gas pumps
dry could mean every city for itself. On the rugged plains of West
Texas, they take the potential for even greater isolation
seriously.
</P>
<P>
   As Lubbock city manager Bob Cass put it, ``If there's a more
independent person than a West Texas farmer, I haven't heard of
them. It's in our nature to be ready for anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Y2K specialists said, should stand sun-baked, pancake-flat
Lubbock in good stead, whatever happens. For a city on the smallish
side, with almost 200,000 people spread over 104 square miles, it
recognized relatively early that it needed a contingency plan that
covered everything from the Lubbock-owned water and electric
companies to the traffic signals on street corners. Seven hundred
stoplights have been ordered in case they malfunction, though tests
show they should be working properly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nowhere is immune from this,'' said Cathy Moyer, managing
director of the Cassandra Project, a Colorado-based organization
that promotes individual and community preparedness. ``Some places
will have serious problems, some places insignificant ones. Every
town, every city, has a different issue. One running concern is
that a lot of places have overlooked the importance of effectively
communicating what they're doing, how they're doing, to their
citizenry.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Lubbock, proud to call itself Buddy Holly's
hometown, also pride themselves on the city's awareness campaign in
English and Spanish. One pamphlet offers Mayor Windy Sitton's
assurances that doom is not on the new calendar. Others note that
proper precautions can minimize disruptions, and provide tips on
alternative power sources and safekeeping of spare cash. Despite
its detailed Web site, the city owns up to not knowing what to
expect. But city officials do know how bad it can get.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, in what was billed as the first exercise of its kind
in the nation, officials staged mock Y2K chaos: a riot at a nearby
state psychiatric prison, a breakdown in the sewer system, 911
calls that couldn't go through, even icy streets from a cold front.
As the problems piled up, with one computer system after another
crashing, officials at the emergency-management headquarters
frantically sought to keep order and keep critical services
functioning during the five-hour test.
</P>
<P>
   The result, as Cass later testified before a US Senate
committee, was an understanding that cities without contingency
plans risk being blindsided if disaster does strike. For its part,
Lubbock discovered holes that it has been hustling to plug ever
since. If necessary, the city plans to use runners to relay
emergency calls to its fire and police departments, and to operate
a variety of city equipment by hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We assume there will be some failures out there; we expect
some business inefficiencies,'' said Cass, the city manager. ``But
it's the one emergency that has announced it's coming, or that it
could come, and we're going to be as ready as we can be. The
exercise gave us a qualified yes that we will be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Lubbock isn't telling its residents anything that many other
cities aren't telling theirs. From San Diego to Seattle, from
Boston to Baton Rouge, municipalities are offering assurances that
the stroke of midnight will not spell mayhem. Banks, power
companies, and water treatment plants say they have checked and
rechecked their systems, replacing faulty computer chips, updating
systems when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Vukamic, a senior principal at San Jose-based Solutions
Plus, said his company has identified problems in no more than 5
percent of the computer equipment and software it has examined for
companies and municipalities in the last year and a half. ``In
general, it's being addressed,'' he said, adding that he was more
concerned about smaller cities and companies that may lack the
resources or enthusiasm to update their systems.
</P>
<P>
   The same concern can be heard in Lubbock, where Jay Dycus, a
vice president at the Chamber of Commerce, said many small
businesses appear to be procrastinating Y2K fixes. No one in town
would even estimate how many have gotten their computers ready or
will in the coming months. And, as local officials conceded, the
ability of Lubbock and other cities across the country to function
depends on regional suppliers and local businesses making good on
their word that they will be able to deliver.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Peter de Jager, a Canadian Internet author who began urging
corporations and municipalities to check their systems years ago,
said he is now confident that no major power outages will occur. No
banks will fail. Any problems with water treatment will be solved
in a day or two. At the same time, he holds fast to his belief that
everyone should have two weeks of food and cash on hand, supplies
they might need in any emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world has woken up; we're now aware of what we need to
do,'' de Jager said. ``When everyone was asleep at the wheel and
saying this was generated by money-grubbing computer consultants, I
was terrified. . . . (But) it's a mix of yes, we're working on it,
and no, we're not. It's gotten to the point where it's real hard to
separate the wheat from the chaff.''
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is crowded with grass-roots groups trying to hold
their local governments and utilities accountable and pull their
neighbors together just in case. More than 500 people turned out
for a daylong seminar on Y2K preparation in Ketchikan, Ala.
Seminars in Prescott, Ariz., have drawn as many as 700 people.
Every city seems to have a citizen task force. Not everyone is
taking the millennium seriously, however.
</P>
<P>
   ``It varies from person to person,'' said Kenneth J. Smith, who
helps run a small preparedness group in an unincorporated area near
Spokane, Wash. ``It's a compound in the hills surrounded by
concertina wire, or you're thrown out of the house if you mention
it. We're just trying to pull together talent _ a retired nurse, an
electrician _ in case.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Per Kielland-Lund, who is helping run a group in Madison,
Wis., ``The least everyone should do is contact their neighbors and
see what resources they can share.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the city's encouragement, however, many people in
Lubbock said they had no plans to store up more than the usual.
</P>
<P>
   Kit Kraus, operations manager at the local Barnes &AMP; Noble
bookstore, joked that he had a sixpack of beer and a bottle of hot
sauce in his refigerator to tide him over. Paul Snyder, who owns an
industrial supply company, said he saw the potential for mayhem as
an excuse to buy extra guns. But Cathy Motty, whose family helped
organize a neighborhood meeting where city officials spoke about
Y2K, has purchased a $300 water filter and has been filling every
container she can with water now stored in her garage.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, Quest's Trinity Church decided not to rely on the
city alone to assist its 8,000 members. After tests showed that its
fire and alarm systems were fine, that its computer system needed
repair, and that its telephone system needed replacing, the
church's Y2K committee began stockpiling food a can at a time in
January. The 600 gallons of water it had in the storehouse was sent
to Oklahoma City after its recent tornado, so that stockpile is
being restarted from scratch. The church also drilled its own well,
and has been using it to keep the lawn green.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people can't afford to put back a week of groceries,
much less a month,'' Quest said. ``So we've got to help ourselves
and each other. Remember, if everyone is hit, no one is running to
help; no one is coming to your aid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1342EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
