<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9977 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-DIARY-OF-WAR-ART-NYTS     09-21 1401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DIARY-OF-WAR-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO DIARY  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
   (To purchase this special ``one-shot'' feature from DISCOVER
magazine, contact New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at (732) 390-4480; fax, 732-390-4697.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ---------------------FREE ART!----------------------
 &HT;    ONE B&AMP;W and THREE COLOR SLIDES are available FREE OF CHARGE to
purchasers of this article. The art can be sent ELECTRONICALLY by
e-mail. Please specify that you want the art when you order the
article.
 &HT;    ----------------------------------------------------
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``l'' lifestyle news and ``a'' general news files.)  
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ----- This article is also available in Spanish.-----
 &HT;    
 By PAM GRIM  
 c.1999 Discover magazine  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   Eleven weeks after NATO began raining bombs on Yugoslavia,
Slobodan Milosevic agreed to withdraw Serb forces from Kosovo. By
then, more than 850,000 Kosovars had fled the region. A few
refugees immigrated. The vast majority are housed with host
families or in refugee camps in Macedonia, Albania, and Montenegro.
</P>
<P>
   Pamela Grim, an American emergency physician, volunteered her
services at a Macedonian refugee camp during the thick of the war.
This is her journal.
 &UR; MAY 6, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Managers of Senokos Camp, a refugee shelter in northern
Macedonia, have been notified that 4,000 to 5,000 Kosovars are to
arrive. Doctors of the World, the organization that provides
medical care in the camp, has called for physician volunteers, so I
find myself in their headquarters in New York City, signing an
insurance policy for, among other things, kidnapping, ransom and
extortion.
 &UR; MAY 8, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   I arrive at the headquarters of Doctors of the World emergency
relief project in Skopje, the capital of Macedonia. Senokos Camp is
about an hour's drive away, near the Macedonian-Kosovar border.
</P>
<P>
   I am introduced around the office. Doctors of the World had been
in Pristina, Kosovo, for six years. The staff had been evacuated
two days before the bombing began in March. In the kitchen I meet
the cook, an elderly Kosovar who has been here a month. As she
serves me potatoes and Turkish coffee, she tries to explain
something. But she speaks no English. She seats herself abruptly,
takes off her glasses and starts to cry.
</P>
<P>
   Later that evening, we head off to Senokos Camp. The guard waves
us through the chicken- and barbed-wire fence that surrounds row
upon row of tents. The medical clinic is a small complex of three
tents joined by an awning.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees have not yet arrived. The borders are closed. We
are not needed tonight.
 &UR; MAY 9, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Several of the doctors working in the camp are Kosovars who fled
when the war began. The doctor in charge of the camp health
facilities, Visar Nushi, fled Pristina a few days after the bombing
started. He was separated from his fiancee and does not know if she
is alive or dead. He does not know if his parents are alive or
dead. His sister _ with his two nephews _ has also disappeared.
Still, Nushi puts in 14-hour days.
</P>
<P>
   Senokos Camp is a small shelter. It is equipped for 10,500
people. Some 2,500 have arrived. We await the rest. Everyone has
shelter, food, potable water and privies nearby.
</P>
<P>
   The problems in Senokos _ the crowding, the boredom, the anxiety
_ are severe but manageable. At Stenkovec II, just down the road,
there are sometimes as many as 30,000 exiles. The expanding
population has assumed a critical mass, a level of chaos that
breeds rioting.
</P>
<P>
   We are experiencing similar problems. Today a doctor treats a
refugee with two teeth knocked out by another refugee. There was no
disagreement; they didn't even know each other. The assailant had
just walked up to this man and kicked him twice in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Fuller, an American internist, sees s 32-year-old woman
brought in by her husband. She is accompanied by their 4-year-old
son. The mother says something in Albanian.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a headache,'' the translator explains.
</P>
<P>
   The woman covers her face with her hands. Her shoulders shake as
she weeps noiselessly.
</P>
<P>
   The translator frowns. ``She says she just found out her mother
and her father were massacred in Kosovo. They are dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The woman weeps. Her son stares up her, confused. He starts
sobbing in sympathy.
</P>
<P>
   That is one kind of case.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Fisher, one of the doctors working here, sees another. A
17-year-old kid who had stepped on a land mine in Kosovo had been
treated by an orthopedic surgeon in Pristina. The surgeon had fled
with him across the border and was now seated next to him on the
canvas cot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a medical emergency,'' the orthopedic surgeon told
Fisher. ``He must go to Germany for surgery immediately to save the
foot.''
</P>
<P>
   The surgeon leaned forward and whispered, ``He is KLA, Kosovo
Liberation Army. If they find him here, they will kill him. You
must get him out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan looked down at the foot. ``You've worked a miracle here,''
he told the orthopedist sadly. ``I just can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The orthopedist was himself very lucky to make it out. According
to the refugees and the people that I talked to in the camp, the
first thing that the Serbs did was kill all the doctors.
 &UR; MAY 14, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Doctors, nurses and other medical technicians make up half of
the organizations like Doctors of the World. The other half is
``Logistics.'' No doctor can work without nurses, translators or
the tools of modern medicine: IV fluids and catheters, sterilized
equipment, antibiotics, bandages, needles and syringes.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Fraser is a big Canadian who is the logistician in
Macedonia for Doctors of the World.
</P>
<P>
   At the general staff meeting, Fraser describes the campaign to
distribute buckets filled with local foods. About 900 have been
prepared, and recent donations have provided funding for 20,000
more. There is talk of making up boxes to feed a family of five for
a week _ to be used when the refugees go home.
</P>
<P>
   There is silence. No one really talks about what will be needed
when the war ends.
 &UR; MAY 19, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 9:00 p.m. we get word: A couple of busloads of refugees _ the
first to cross the border in weeks _ will arrive in a half hour.
</P>
<P>
   When the buses pull up, young men stand crowded in the aisles
while old women peer out through the windows into the night.
Macedonian soldiers are shouting, pointing at the gates. The
medical staff stands ready.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees have lined up on either side of the central
clearing, straining for a first glimpse of the arriving passengers.
Most are looking for relatives, friends, neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   The doors open slowly. Faces, harshly lit by the camp light,
descend. Everyone looks startled by the light, the noise, the idea
of safety. Children are sobbing. Old women weep. Young men look
bewildered, as if they are surprised they are still alive.
</P>
<P>
   No one looks critically ill, although everyone appears
shell-shocked. Some older people, hunched and frail, stumble feebly
in the direction of the camp. I stop an ancient woman who appears
to have a broken nose. It happened two days ago, she tells me. She
fell running from the Serbian police.
 &UR; MAY 20, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Fisher and I have a rare day off, so we drive to the border,
about 25 kilometers from Skopje. The dry countryside looks like the
foothills of the Sierras in California.
</P>
<P>
   An aide from the camp points to a patch of hillside that
overlooks the roofs of a small village beyond.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Serbs were there three weeks ago. Emptied the town right
out and set fire to everything that would burn.''
 &UR; MAY 27, 1999 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It is nearly a month since I arrived at Senokos. The number of
refugees has risen from 2,500 to 7,500.
</P>
<P>
   Today we learn that Milosevic has been indicted by the United
Nations War Crimes Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   I'm tending to an elderly women who hasn't slept for days. She
insists that otherwise she is fine _ as the tears stream down her
face. I prescribe Valium for what seems to be the hundredth time
tonight. In the waiting room are three more just like her.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   (Pam Grim, an emergency room physician in Cleveland, is a
frequent contributor to Discover magazine's Vital Signs column.)
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   -0-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
