<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 13:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9983 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e BC-MUSIC-POP-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-21 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-POP-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPING THE GHETTOS OF BLACK MUSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RENEE GRAHAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   What is black music?
</P>
<P>
   From Jimi Hendrix to Joan Armatrading, that question has long
badgered black artists whose creative inclinations and musical
directions challenge and stretch simplistic notions as to the kind
of music they are expected to create.
</P>
<P>
   This comes to mind as MeShell Ndegeocello's stellar CD
``Bitter'' is flailing for airplay. Released last month,
Ndegeocello's third album is already being hailed as one of the
year's best. A brooding 12-cut songscape about romance on the rocks
and love gone wrong, it's being compared favorably to such
I'm-so-lonesome-I-could-cry classics as Joni Mitchell's ``Blue''
and Frank Sinatra's ``In the Wee Small Hours of the Morning.''
Entertainment Weekly gave its ``stunning set of tough and tender
sob stories'' an A rating, while Robert Christgau in Rolling Stone
praised the songs as ``vivid sketches.''
</P>
<P>
   Ndegeocello puts aside her trademark bass-slapping funk for blue
jazzy overtones on this CD, her first since 1996's provocative
``Peace Beyond Passion.'' But you won't hear her songs wedged
between Ja Rule's ``Holla Holla'' and 702's ``Where My Girls At.''
For most radio programmers, Ndegeocello's music does not fit the
increasing slim definition of the urban contemporary format.
</P>
<P>
   And thus the question, what is black music? What makes Whitney
Houston more of an urban contemporary artist than Tracy Chapman, or
Maxwell more of a soul man than Lenny Kravitz?
</P>
<P>
   What's occurring, even within the black community, is a sad kind
of self-segregation against those whose music dares veer away from
such urban strongholds as R&AMP;B and rap. More often than not, artists
such as Ndegeocello find themselves unable to ``crossover'' in
their own communities.
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Ndegeocello, nor is this a nascent problem. It has
plagued such groups as Fishbone and the Family Stand, and was the
plight of the late, sorely underappreciated black hard rock band
Living Colour. Led by guitarist extraordinaire Vernon Reid, Living
Colour fused raw funk and metal, scoring such hits as ``Cult of
Personality,'' ``Open Letter to a Landlord,'' and ``Glamour Boys.''
The group also opened for the Rolling Stones on their 1989 Steel
Wheels tour. But Living Colour's support came mainly from rock
stations, not from those who found the music ``too white.''
</P>
<P>
   To counteract such myopic notions, Reid cofounded the Black Rock
Coalition in 1985. In its manifesto, the group denounces ``spurious
demographics'' and the ``demand that Black musicians tailor their
music to fit into the creative straitjackets the industry has
designed. We are individuals and will accept no less than full
respect for our right to be conceptually independent.''
</P>
<P>
   The mean-spirited ``too white'' label has also dogged Lenny
Kravitz. Though he has enjoyed multiplatinum success for the past
decade with such songs as ``It Ain't Over 'Til It's Over,'' ``Are
You Gonna Go My Way,'' ``Always on the Run,'' and more recently,
``Fly Away,'' the singer-songwriter has never enjoyed a fan base
within the African-American community.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with MTV several years ago, Kravitz said, ``I
grew up in a very strong Afro-American environment, so it's strange
to me that the majority of my own people don't consider me to be a
black artist.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, music industry success is about neither black nor
white _ it's about green, as in how many albums an artist sells.
But it's unfathomable that an artist like Ndegeocello is more
celebrated at Lilith Fair _ where she was a featured performer _
than in a community that would do well to embrace something other
than the uninspiring, cookie-cutter product passing itself off as
R&AMP;B these days.
</P>
<P>
   As white artists from David Bryne to Paul Simon to Chris Cornell
on his great new solo disc, ``Euphoria Morning,'' dabble in such
black music idioms as funk, soul, and gospel, so too should black
artists be supported in explorations outside of the limits of a
self-imposed music ghetto. As Black Rock Coalition cofounder Reid
has said, ``We (black people, specifically, and the public in
general) don't know the kind of future we're cheating ourselves out
of musically and intellectually.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
