<SLUG> BC-LEVINGSTON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE IS A MONEY SPENDER THING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN LEVINGSTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   My old pal, Joe King, is always good for a lesson or two on the
big questions in economics. Joe, you may remember, once
time-traveled to ProsperUtopia, a future world of free-market
tyranny where everyone is rich, the landscape is lovely but fake,
and the air is unbreathable. Now he has just returned from a place
of our own world, a tiny island in the Arafura Sea off New Guinea
that in recent years has emerged from its dark age into the bright
sunlight of the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   Joe turned up at my door all atwitter over a woman he had
romanced on that faraway island. ``The first time I saw her,'' he
said of Maoke, ``she had her head tilted back, polishing off a
bottle of Coke. Absolutely beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A lovely, long neck?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``No. It was the Coke. I knew instantly, here was a woman I
could love.''
</P>
<P>
   I was suddenly reminded of a remark by Roberto C. Goizueta, the
former Coca-Cola chairman: ``People around the world are today
connected to each other by brand name consumer products as much as
by anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe continued: ``Of course, Maoke and I are separated by
culture, upbringing, religion, language _ you name it. But I knew
right then that in the things that mattered we had the same
desires.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe explained that until economic globalization shone on Maoke's
island, the society had been nearly untouched by Western ways for
thousands of years, and had been under the authoritarian control of
a dynasty of noncapitalist tribal leaders who were called the
Baboman.
</P>
<P>
   ``She can barely speak English,'' Joe King went on, ``but she
knows all the right words: McDonald's, Levi's, Kodak, Marlboro,
Federal Express. And she's already heading up-market. You should
hear how perfect she pronounces: Armani, Cartier, Lancome, Remy
Martin, and Dunhill. We had so much to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So you got to know her pretty well?'' I inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like we knew each other all our lives. The minute I
heard her say Gucci, I knew exactly what she'd say next.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chanel,'' Joe said. ``She told me of her happiness, her
sadness, her dreams. She confided in me _ told me that for a long
time she didn't really like who she was. Then she switched from
Nike to Adidas, and she said, `I felt much better about myself.'
Wow. Don't I know the feeling! You can't get much closer to someone
than that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' I said, hesitating to raise delicate issues, ``she's
lived her whole life in the Arafura Sea, she bows to an absolute
leader named the Baboman, while you're American and all of that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm aware of that,'' said Joe King, a little peeved. ``One day
I asked her outright, `Tell me, Maoke, do you still believe in the
Baboman?' She laughed and said, `I believe in Aunt Jemima.' '' Joe
was beside himself: ``Do you know what that means? She's the Girl
Next Door.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to meet this woman,'' I offered.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I wanted to be sure,'' Joe went on, lowering his voice.
``So I pressed her on the island dogma. I asked, `Don't you still
thank the Baboman every day for all the good things in your life?'
She smiled, shook her head: `No, I say, Thank goodness for Chef
Boyardee.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``Sounds like destiny,'' I told my friend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exactly,'' Joe King said. ``She even has an Apple computer,
just like me, and loves the Apple slogan: Think Different. When I
heard that, I just had to hug her. `Me too!' I cried. `We're
exactly the same. We both think different.' ''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Levingston can be reached at
dollarsnonsense(at)hotmail.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
