A9988 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-TV-REVIEWS-LADN     09-21 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEWS-LADN </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID KRONKE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Deceptively simple and frankly brilliant, the
arrest-and-prosecution formula for Dick Wolf's evercreen
crime-drama procedural, ``Law &AMP; Order,'' marks its 10th season with
the birth of a sibling: ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit.''
``SVU'' basically offers more of the same, but if it can maintain
the quality of its predecessor, then it's certainly welcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Special Victims Unit'' is a euphemism for the new show's
original subtitle, ``Sex Crimes.'' The portentous narrator who
opens ``Law &AMP; Order'' reappears here, explaining, ``sexually based
offenses are considered especially heinous.'' This first episode is
a particularly grim and grisly affair, concerning the murder and
castration (or as a cop cynically quips, ``Whoever did this sliced
off his cigar and took it with 'em'') of a Serbian war criminal who
had raped 67 women in his homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators, after chasing down the usual dead-end suspects,
eventually conclude that the perpetrator or perpetrators were
themselves victims of the dead man's reign of terror. (All this at
9 p.m. _ why on earth didn't NBC honor Wolf's wishes to broadcast
this show at 10 p.m.?)
</P>
<P>
   The unrelenting bleakness of ``SVU's'' subject matter is
leavened, thankfully, by the charm and charisma of the show's
principles, Christopher Meloni (of HBO's similarly devastating
``Oz'') and Mariska Hargitay. Meloni defies the gravity with a
gracefully light but intelligent presence, while Hargitay projects
a strong, appealing no-nonsense tone. Richard Belzer reprises his
role as the mordant Detective Munch from the departed ``Homicide:
Life on the Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, it's established that Hargitay's character has a
powerfully personal motivation for serving in the Special Victims
Unit. Her mother urges her to switch assignments, and her superior
(Dann Florek, who starred in the first three seasons of ``Law &AMP;
Order'') questions her ability to function within it. At the end of
this episode, he barks at her, ``You've just used your
get-out-of-jail free card _ there's only one in the pack.'' How can
she possibly survive in this environment, when it's clear that
she'll have a personal stake in virtually every case she handles?
</P>
<P>
   ``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' wants it both ways _ it
makes light of certain sexual foibles while cloaking dark human
impulses in even darker dramatic raiment. It will require a
consistent, Herculean effort to maintain an appropriate tone for
its subject matter. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
`LADIES MAN'
</P>
<P>
   ``Ladies Man'' wins the award for the fall season's most retro
title _ it sounds like something out of the '60s or '70s. Alfred
Molina stars as Jimmy Stiles, a guy surrounded by a lot of (rather
moody) women _ his wife Donna (Sharon Lawrence), his mother Mitzi
(Betty White), two daughters, an ex-wife and a mother-in-law.
</P>
<P>
   In the pilot, Donna is pregnant and vacillating wildly on
whether or not she wants to have sex in her condition. Jimmy's
hoping the latest addition to his family will be a boy, which makes
those around him repeatedly suggest that he hates women; there's a
weak running joke about whether Jimmy ``likes little boys.'' The
series was created by Chris Thompson, who is doing far funnier work
on his other new sitcom, Fox's ``Action.''
</P>
<P>
   Molina's acting here is unduly, and uncharacteristically, forced
_ this fine character actor (``Boogie Nights,'' ``Maverick'') looks
like a stand-up comic giving his first sitcom performance. At one
point, debating his impending child's gender, Molina babbles, ``You
can call a `she' an `it' all you want, it still doesn't make a him
a `he,''' and the line gets applause. You can just imagine
t(0q\''f~
</P>
</TEXT>
