<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 13:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9990 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ARGENTINA-BOMB-BOS &LR;      09-21 1298
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARGENTINA-BOMB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BOMB'S WAKE, ALIENATION AND RESOLVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUENOS AIRES _ It has been five years now. But every Monday
morning of every week that passes, 270 Mondays in all so far, they
come to pay homage and plead for justice before the austere walls
of Argentina's Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   A young widow implores police and prosecutors to find and punish
the murderers of her husband, who perished along with 85 others in
the July 1994 bombing of the Jewish communal center. A community
leader sounds the sacred shofar, symbol of the Yom Kippur ceremony,
hoping the piercing pitch of the ram's horn will rouse those in the
courthouse much the way it tumbled the walls of Jericho more than
3,000 years before. Some 200 others stand in mute demand for
action.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no one has answered their call.
</P>
<P>
   The government vowed swift action in the wake of the bombing,
which was the second in two years against a Jewish target. But the
investigation has called into question the state's competence and
raised the possibility of its complicity; only low-level
functionaries face trial, and prosecutors concede they probably
never will determine who ordered and paid for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Within this country's Jewish community of 200,000 meanwhile, the
bombs continue to reverberate.
</P>
<P>
   For some, that means steering clear of connections to their
religion and culture for fear of further violence. But for many
more, including those who appear each Monday in front of the
Tribunales building, the attacks have spurred them to reach out to
fellow Jews for consolation and community.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people who put the bomb, what they want is for me to leave
the shul, to say, `Yes, Judaism here is finished,' '' said Debi
Pinson, a 17-year-old who sings in her synagogue's choir and helps
lead its services.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will not give them what they want.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To understand the impact of the bombings, it is critical to
understand the history of Argentina and its Jewish community _ the
biggest in Latin American and seventh largest in the world.
</P>
<P>
   That history begins with Russian Jews who fled the pogroms of
the late 1800s and settled in remote outposts in the Argentine
outback, spawning a culture of Jewish gauchos, or cowboys. Their
brethren followed from Morocco and the Ottoman Empire, and by 1920
there were 135,000 Jews who brought with them Yiddish theater and
Jewish newspapers, a commitment to Zionism and a loyalty to their
new homeland.
</P>
<P>
   But the heritage also has a dark side. President Juan Peron was
sympathetic to Germany in World War II and afterward gave refuge to
Nazi criminals such as Adolf Eichmann. The military junta that held
power in the 1970s and early '80s was especially ruthless in
torturing Jews. And while anti-Semitism seemed to be on the wane
more recently, it resurfaced in 1992, when a bomb at the Israeli
Embassy killed 29, and again on July 18, 1994, when an explosion
demolished the Argentine Israelite Mutual Aid Association
headquarters in the heart of Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish community at first took President Carlos Menem at his
word that he would find and punish the perpetrators of the two
bombings, but with each week that has passed without a resolution
that faith has been replaced by alienation and anger.
</P>
<P>
   It is partly that the investigations, especially on the communal
center bombing, have seemed half-hearted. For the first three years
only eight policemen were assigned, compared to the thousands in
the United States who investigated the 1995 bombing of the Alfred
P. Murrah Federal Building in Oklahoma City. Critical evidence
disappeared, key suspects were tape-recorded urging colleagues to
keep silent, and millions of dollars turned up in the bank account
of one key figure. Argentine law also hamstrung the investigators
by prohibiting them from questioning suspects and limiting their
use of informants.
</P>
<P>
   What they did turn up, however, raised more doubts than it
settled. Of 20 people facing charges, 15 are policeman, including
several believed to have purchased the van used in the bombing.
There also are suspicions that military officers, past and present,
were involved, along with anti-Semitic elements in Argentina's
large Arab community.
</P>
<P>
   Indictments of the 20 suspects were handed down last month, and
a trial is expected early next year. But many of the charges focus
on corruption rather than the bombing. And while the vice president
and other senior officials have suggested a link to Iranian-backed
terrorist groups, the case assembled so far focuses exclusively on
the local connection and prosecutors acknowledge they still are in
the dark about much of what transpired.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no answers,'' said Laura Ginsberg, whose husband died
in the bombing. ``At the present moment we believe there is not a
political decision to solve the bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jose Barbaccia, one of two prosecutors handling the case,
offered a similar verdict: ``In the government there is no need or
urge to solve the case.'' As for repeated suggestions of a Middle
East link, Barbaccia, who has been on the communal center bombing
case since the start, said, ``we have very weak evidence on that
link.''
</P>
<P>
   Yitzhak Aviran, Israel's ambassador to Argentina, insists that
by now, there should have been more answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want just a declaration, we want a few people put on
trial,'' said Aviran. ``Even though things now have quieted down,
we will continue insisting on and demanding justice and the
completion of the investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacobo Timerman, a journalist and author, said it is apparent
why international terrorists twice would choose Argentina for their
attacks on Jewish interests. ``Our large community of Jews is the
first part,'' said Timerman, whose highly publicized imprisonment
and torture during the military regime makes him Argentina's
best-known Jew.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have a large organization of police eager to accept the
job of carrying out attacks like those.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The back-to-back bombings have dramatically transformed the
Jewish community here, but not always in ways that could have been
anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   They exacerbated an economic crisis facing the communal
organizations, with the Aid Association now facing a debt of $25
million. They forced synagogues, schools, and other Jewish
institutions to install huge metal barriers and hire armed guards.
And they scared away some members of the community who worried
about the risks to themselves and their children.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, however, the bombs also rallied many to their
religion and culture and may help stem a decline that has seen
Argentina's Jewish population fall by more than 100,000 in recent
decades.
</P>
<P>
   That is partly because of rallies like the ones each Monday in
front of the high court.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, composed mainly of relatives of those killed in
the communal center bombing, holds a similar protest one Wednesday
each month in front of the bomb site, which now is home to a
rebuilt center.
</P>
<P>
   Even more, the bombing touched a nerve in thousands of
assimilated Jews, making them conclude that, whether or not they
viewed themselves as Jewish, the outside world did. It also pushed
many to learn more about their roots and seek a sense of community
with coreligionists, whether that be a Jewish sporting club or
school, a social welfare agency or a synagogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the . . . bombing, I said I really want to know what a
Jew is. I did my bat mitzvah then, and studied, and every Saturday
morning I come to the synagogue,'' said Lili Esses, a 42-year-old
artist and teacher. ``For me, Jewish life here can be divided into
after and before'' the bombing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
