<HEADLINE>
BASICS LIFT `ONCE AND AGAIN' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
ONCE AND AGAIN 
Starring: Sela Ward, Billy Campbell, Julia Whelan, Shane West,
Susanna Thompson, Jeffrey Nordling, Todd Field, Marin Hinkle 
On: ABC, 10 p.m., Tuesday  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Once and Again'' is certainly the classiest new show of the
fall TV season. And it's not just because the series bucks TV's
tidal wave of youth worship, as it tells the story of dating
parents in their 40s who actually have wrinkles curling around
their mouths. ``Once and Again'' is special because it returns to
the basics of what constitutes superior dramatic television:
three-dimensional characters to care about, smart scripts that
never short-shrift complexity, and deeply felt acting. The formula
is simple, engaging, and incredibly difficult for TV producers to
get right.
</P>
<P>
   The show is exactly the kind of drama you'd expect from Edward
Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz, the men behind ``thirtysomething''
and ``My So-Called Life.'' That means the characters are touchy,
and feely, and dive headlong into self-analysis while the New Age
guitarist plucks at heartstrings in the background. Warning: It's
not for those who think of this genre as a not-so-fine-whine. Zwick
and Herskovitz are able with the show's light moments _ the awkward
head angles of a kiss, for example _ but they are far more
interested in the rigors and raptures of good old-fashioned angst.
In ``thirysomething,'' it was yuppie angst, in ``My So-Called
Life'' it was teen angst, and in ``Once and Again'' it is
post-divorce family angst. Indeed, as it ranges between the turmoil
of the parents and their children, ``Once and Again'' is a hybrid
of the two earlier shows.
</P>
<P>
   The characters are entirely distinct, though, particularly Sela
Ward's Lily and Billy Campbell's Rick. The idea is that the newly
separated Lily and the divorced Rick are magically attracted to
each other, but their love affair will be inhibited by all kinds of
broken-family issues. Fear is a barrier, as Lily is still wary in
the aftermath of her womanizing husband. And needy children are
another barrier, as Lily's 14-year-old daughter, Grace, is openly
hostile to the possibility of her mother dating. ``Please don't
have sex with him tonight,'' Grace begs, trying to make Lily feel
guilty as she prepares for a date. Rick, meanwhile, is caught up in
his own guilt trip, afraid to give needed discipline to his
scholastically challenged son.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, best known for her Emmy-winning work on ``Sisters,'' is
especially appealing as Lily. She's flustered and frightened, but
she's also got a winning sense of self-knowledge. And as Rick,
Campbell is sincere and open and boyishly charming, with a leaning
toward stoicism. Together, they have a natural chemistry. Their
classic dating moments _ the first phone call, a rushed make-out
session in the car _ are awkwardly adolescent, exciting, and always
believable. You can't help but root for them. Next week's episode
makes an amusing parallel between their dating life and that of
Rick's 16-year-old son.
</P>
<P>
   As Grace, who is entering the world of men just as her mother
reenters it, Julia Whelan is also worth noting. She brings raw
feeling to Grace's nervousness and negative body image. She's more
sloppily expressive than Claire Danes in ``My So-Called Life,'' but
she's equally impressive. ``Once and Again'' explores her inner
conflict, but unlike most of the family dramas this season, it
keeps the focus on the parents' story.
</P>
<P>
   The show's only questionable move is the device of
black-and-white scenes in which Rick and Lily tell their secrets
directly to the camera as though they're in therapy. These moments
veer dangerously close to TV commercial testimonials, or the
confessional footage in MTV's ``The Real World,'' and they run the
risk of impeding the action. They are unnecessary explication,
especially given the strength of the performances.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``thirtysomething'' and ``My So-Called Life,'' ``Once and
Again'' is not a particularly original or groundbreaking hour of
TV. It works with familiar themes about divorce, and Zwick and
Herskovitz's style has been replicated all over the networks. But
it's absorbing, above average, and addictive. And if you watch it
once, you'll probably watch it again.
</P>
<P>
   Let's hope ABC finds a safe new home for it, after ``NYPD Blue''
returns to the 10 p.m. timeslot on Nov. 9.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
