u f BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      09-21 0754
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARSH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSING AND BRIDGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was something fitting about Microsoft chief Bill Gates
pledging $1 billion or more for scholarships for minority students
in science, engineering, math, and education the same week that
Judge W. Arthur Garrity Jr. died. Their lives intersected in Boston
in the autumn of 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Gates was a Harvard sophomore the year that Garrity ordered that
Boston's neighborhood schools be abolished to end their de facto
segregation. By all accounts, the bridge-playing college student
paid attention to the world around him. There can be little doubt
that the centi-billionaire's gift to education was related to
Garrity's decision.
</P>
<P>
   When reports of Garrity's death emerged, the question arose: Was
he a figure of national prominence? The answer, of course, is yes _
but not, perhaps, in the way that he had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   In the quarter-century before 1974, the nation had performed
small miracles of integration, especially in the armed forces, and
consciousness of pervasive and damaging inequality was beginning to
spill over into matters of gender. Martin Luther King Jr. had
become a martyr _ and a national hero. Progress was slow but real.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1970s, however, many citizens were weary of the the
relentless pressure to accelerate change. Daniel Patrick Moynihan,
who was among the first of the neoconservatives (and one of the few
who never deserted the Democratic Party for the GOP), called for a
policy of ``benign neglect.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Garrity's ruling, Boston's blue-collar neighborhoods
boiled over. The school population had been 51 percent white on the
eve of busing; it dropped to less than 20 percent. The total number
of public school students declined by a third as families moved to
the suburbs or sent their children to private ``academies.''
</P>
<P>
   For nearly nine years, Judge Garrity managed Boston's schools
himself, until their middle-class constituency was ground to
nubbins. His willingness to all but destroy a school system in
order to save it became a metaphor, in many minds, for heavy-handed
social engineering. Mistrust of governmental purposes spilled over
into inflation, taxation, corporate governance, and all the rest.
</P>
<P>
   To oversimplify, revulsion at the Vietnam War (at one end of the
spectrum) and the spectacle of Boston's failed busing (at the
other) led within a few years to the election of Ronald Reagan in
1980 and the subsequent Turn to the Right. Reagan's administration
in turn effected a cascade of policy changes. One consequence was
an asset boom that has made Gates the richest man on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Gates's politics have held sway for 20 years, as those of
Garrity waned. His stylized view is that government is all but
superfluous, that technologies, markets, and private philanthropies
will find a way, that ``the world refuses to be governed badly.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, workers on the front lines of poverty and
discrimination long ago concluded that throwing money at problems _
full scholarships all the way through graduate school of the sort
that Gates offered science students last week _ was by itself no
solution. Students who arrive for college unprepared for its rigors
have little chance of success. Hence the widespread interest in the
``bridge'' programs that, along with affirmative action, are the
preferred remedy in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, these enrichment programs for younger members of
disadvantaged communities have been under way for years. One of the
most powerful, Math-Science Squared, was developed as a summer
program in the mid-1970s at Phillips Exeter Academy. San Francisco
University High's Summerbridge program has spawned 35 similar
experiments since 1981 _ including the Citybridge program in Boston
and Cambridge, which last June celebrated its fifth anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   The principle of these programs is the same: Minority kids
invest six uninterrupted weeks or so in summer school, and often
Saturday mornings and Wednesday evenings, to work with minority
teachers and staffers to build their skills. The foundation-borne
cost is $5,000 or so per pupil.
</P>
<P>
   Seed money for these programs is not the problem now. Know-how
and cadre are. Progress is slow but real. And who is to say that
the pendulum won't swing back toward collective action? That it
isn't swinging now?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
