<SLUG> BC-RAIDED-WORKERS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID BOOM, UNIONS LURE WORKERS FROM OPEN SHOPS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE E. LEWIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Brian Richardson and Bill Corley may be among the most
hated _ and loved _ guys in construction.
</P>
<P>
   Less than 10 years ago, union organizers such as Corley and
Richardson had a hard time promising steady work to the jobless
journeymen who flocked to union halls during the recession.
Desperate for a job, some union workers settled for nonunion
positions with lower pay and fewer benefits
</P>
<P>
   The tables have turned.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with promises of higher pay, better benefits, and job
security, union organizers in the construction trades are raiding
small and midsized nonunion contractors of skilled carpenters,
glaziers, drywallers, and electricians, and are offering them to
contractors who have signed union agreements. As a result, shops
are losing employees in a tough labor market where replacements are
hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   The practice, called ``stripping,'' is being used by organizers
more and more these days to the chagrin of open-shop or nonunion
contractors with fast-track deadlines for residential, commercial,
or public projects.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tactic almost put us out of business,'' said Jim Marshall,
cofounder of Jupiter Electric in North Reading.
</P>
<P>
   In June, while working at a school in Fitchburg, 21 of
Marshall's 37 electricians, including a foreman, journeymen, and an
apprentice, walked off. The lure? Promises of more than $40 per
hour at union shop job sites in Boston instead of the $32 hourly
wage Marshall was paying electricians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had people who went out to lunch and never came back,''
Marshall said bitterly. ``I also lost written plans showing what
work had been done and changes that needed to be made. One of the
workers brought the plans back, but there were delays.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 3 percent unemployment, there was nobody out there.
Nobody,'' he added. ``I went to the electrical contractors
association and Associated Builders and Contractors and borrowed
eight to 10 people. We pulled through it, but it cost me more than
$200,000 in overtime, mistakes, and new hiring.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Beeman, executive director of Associated Builders and
Contractors in Burlington, which represents more than 400 nonunion
contractors, is disturbed by the trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stripping has been around for a while, but it has been turned
around, stepped up a notch or two, and turned into instant
stripping,'' Beaman said. ``The difference now is that people are
pretty much leaving immediately, without notice. The pitch from the
union is, `Come in now, and we'll waive the initiation fee.' We
don't think that's a good way to do business.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, whose union has stripped 100 top carpenters from
nonunion shops this year, concedes that a tight job market has made
stripping a more effective organizing tool. But he rebuts shop
owners' claims that the method is unethical.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know of contractors who can go three months without getting
a response to an ad, so for every person we take, they have little
hope of replacing that skilled person right away,'' said
Richardson. ``Does this mean we are taking advantage of the
economy? Certainly. But we're not trying to terrorize contractors.
We're doing it because, in this economy, everybody winds up making
good money except the nonunion carpenter who's making only $11 to
$15 per hour, with no benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   The carpenters union has been promising skilled workers as much
as $8,000 more per year in hourly wages, a pension annuity, health
benefits, and job security.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not out to get anybody,'' added Corley, an organizer
with the International Brotherhood of Electrical Workers Local 103,
which stripped Marshall of some of his most valuable workers.
``We're just offering union membership and job security, and people
are taking the offer.''
</P>
<P>
   Tell that to Bill Brodie, owner of Classic Glass in Woburn. The
International Brotherhood of Painters &AMP; Allied Trades, District 35,
in Jamaica Plain, stripped three of the company's five trained
glass workers this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first to go was very skilled and had been with us a number
of years,'' said Brodie. ``He gave me notice. Then, another fellow
who had been with us about six months left. He gave me only three
days notice. The third guy gave no notice at all. That hurt. We're
small. We offer some benefits, but we can't pay the salaries a
union shop can pay. But we also charge the customer less.''
</P>
<P>
   John Laughlin, a spokesman for the painters union, said the
organization has stripped 300 workers from glazing and glassworks
companies over the past 18 months and will probably target more as
demand for workers heats up with the construction next year of
several hotels and the renovation of schools in the Boston area.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, the union stripped a company of all of its
glaziers, forcing the firm to shut down its commercial operation
about 10 months ago. The company, Precision Glass of Charlestown,
confirmed that it has lost a significant chunk of its 25-member
staff over the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Department of Employment and Training
estimates that job vacancies in the construction trades will total
20,160 by 2006. Electricians will account for at least 3,500 of
those openings.
</P>
<P>
   One reason is a strong housing market. Last year, for example,
sales of existing and new houses surged. Close to 2 million new
housing units were produced, and more than $128 million was spent
on the renovation and restoration of existing housing stock,
spurring demand for electricians, painters, paperhangers,
carpenters, precision metal workers, and plumbers.
</P>
<P>
   Employment and Training predicts that demand for skilled workers
in the trades will continue for the next six or seven years,
forecasting 3,940 vacancies for carpenters, 2,600 for painters or
paperhangers, 4,470 for precision metal workers, and 2,570 for
skilled plumbers.
</P>
<P>
   That's good news for the IBEW's Corley. Over the past two years,
IBEW Local 103 has stripped 256 electricians and apprentices from
nonunion commercial and industrial work sites. The union has 179
signatories to its contract, and many are clamoring for
electricians.
</P>
<P>
   But while Local 103 could have filled requests for electricians
quickly in the past, there are no idle electricians at the
Dorchester union hall anymore. The union will need 300 to 400 more
electricians to fill jobs in the Boston area next spring, not
counting work already slated to begin later this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we've got overemployment,'' said Corley. ``We went
two weeks recently without being able to fill 470 jobs at union
shops.''
</P>
<P>
   Strapped for workers, 30 nonunion contractors joined the
electricians union over the past year. ``A lot of it had to do with
the fact that we've been stealing their people and they wanted them
back,'' said Corley. ``We had one guy actually come out and say,
`We want our men back.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the New England Council of Carpenters in
Boston raided a Rhode Island company doing business at Marina Bay
in Quincy of 19 of its 25 workers over a period of months.
</P>
<P>
   ``We met with the owner and told him there was real interest in
a union,'' said Richardson, ``but he was adamant. He wanted nothing
to do with us. Finally, as demand for skilled people increased, we
took about 19 of their 25 employees. We even petitioned for (a
union) election with the National Labor Relations Board, but we
couldn't wait for an election date to be set.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
