<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-TRIUMPH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CARNIVAL TRIUMPH: BIG IN SIZE _ AND FUN, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Carnival Triumph, one of the largest ships afloat, is part
of the Fun fleet of the ever-growing Carnival Cruise Line.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival is so sure you'll have fun that it has trademarked its
slogan, the Fun Ships.
</P>
<P>
   We sail out of New York City on a beautiful August day, admiring
the skyline, paying homage to the Statue of Liberty as we pass her,
then sailing under the Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, heading north to
Halifax, Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of this four-day itinerary is that you can enjoy
everything there is on a ship, visit a foreign land, and yet easily
work your trip into any schedule. For many, time to get away is
hard to find. Carnival has found its newly expanded short cruise
schedule very popular. And next year the line will also offer
three- to five-day sailings to Canada out of Boston aboard the
Triumph's sister ship, the Carnival Destiny.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Here we are on one of the newest ships in the world (its first
sailing was July 27 after leaving the Italian shipyard where it was
built), and are we having fun? Not so surprisingly, yes. It's hard
not to be happy, passing by that magnificent skyline, with lively
music on deck and a party atmosphere all around. All my cares and
concerns were left back on Pier 88.
</P>
<P>
   The Carnival Triumph is in a small group of super magaliners in
the 100,000-plus-ton class. Right now there are only three vessels
in the class, but both Carnival and Princess have more ships this
size on order. These will remain the largest cruise ships in the
world until November when Royal Caribbean introduces the Voyager of
the Seas at 142,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
   The thought of sailing on such a large vessel with all those
people (the Triumph carries 2,758 passengers, up to 3,473 if all
the upper berths in staterooms are utilized) is horrifying to many
a landlubber. But on the Triumph I encounter few crowds or lines _
mostly at the start of a meal service or along the promenade deck
just as a dinner or show ends.
</P>
<P>
   And, should I feel like escaping, I head back to my stateroom.
It is spacious, nothing plush but comfortably laid out with room
for all my belongings, a place to sit, television, a roomy bath,
and, one of the nicest features the new ships offer, a private
balcony where I can enjoy my room-service coffee, read, or just
relax. One morning I spent the longest time watching a small bird
flying nine decks below me along the water line _ where did that
bird come from? Where was it going? And how long can it keep up
with the ship?
</P>
<P>
   Like all Carnival ships, the Triumph comes with a theme. Aboard
this ship it is the world.
</P>
<P>
   And this is an international cruise. The diversity aboard this
ship is amazing. No Caribbean cruise I've been on has had such a
diversity of passengers aboard _ there is the blending of races,
cultures, and ages. There are partying singles, and groups of
families. Taking a short cruise out of New York is truly an
experience in itself.
</P>
<P>
   The world theme is found throughout the public areas of the
ship. There is Tokyo Underground, a labyrinth of high-tech video
grames. It's next door to the disco, and next to the casino is the
Olympic bar, where sports are projected on multiple TVs and the
walls bear witness to past Olympics. The piano bar's walls and
ceiling, meanwhile, are covered with oyster shells from New
Orleans. The library, a nice quiet spot, is named for Washington,
the lavish theater for Rome, and the dining rooms for London and
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain about a Carnival ship: You know you're not
at home. The creativity behind these themes is the result of one
designer, Joe Farcus, who's been doing Carnival ships since day one
_ and that's a lot of ships, with even more on the drawing boards.
It's difficult to catch all the many nuances of Farcus's work, but
Carnival is solving that by adding a short video, shown in
staterooms, featuring Farcus explaining his theme for the Triumph.
</P>
<P>
   Carnival promises fun at sea, offering activities that go from
early morning to early the next morning, long after most other
cruise lines have tucked their guests into bed.
</P>
<P>
   With each new ship, Carnival seems to be evolving and improving.
While the Triumph is similar to the Destiny, the line has managed
to carve out more deck space for the new ship and added staterooms
without affecting the overall spaciousness of the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Even the food service is enhanced. We are quite pleased with the
food and service in the dining room, but are also impressed with
the other dining options. Atop the ship is the South Beach Club, a
casual buffet-style dining area. Here one can enjoy not only
breakfast or lunch, but also have a casual alternative to evening
dining _ no dressing up needed here. (Some fellow passengers,
however, complained that the offerings were not so tempting.)
Adjacent to the South Beach are the Hong Kong Noodle Company and,
opposite it, the N.Y. Deli, serving Asian treats and great
sandwiches. The deli is open 11 a.m. to 11 p.m. Deckside, there are
hamburgers and hot dogs and 24-hours-a-day pizza service. For late
risers, there's even breakfast service on deck until noon. And, of
course, there's cabin service.
</P>
<P>
   While food is never a problem on a cruise ship, Carnival caters
to all tastes. Each meal calls for hard decisions because the
choices are all tempting _ one night included ziti with Italian
sausage, a catch of the day, sweet and sour shrimp, grilled
boneless chicken breasts, rack of New Zealand lamb Dijonnaise, or
grilled, aged New York sirloin steak. Vegetarian dishes are
available at dinner _ perhaps a Madras-style vegetable curry or
vegetable fajitas _ and deckside. If you're watching your diet, a
daily Nautica Selection is lower in fat, sodium, etc.
</P>
<P>
   There's plenty of room deckside for sunning, jogging, or
walking, and the pools are heavily used as are the hot tubs. There
seems to be a constant line to use the giant water slide. Deck and
pool games are also held throughout the cruise. As we near Nova
Scotia, the sunny day turns foggy, and all but the hardy head
inside, away from continuous blowing of the foghorn.
</P>
<P>
   But the fun doesn't end. There are games, bingo, casino
tournaments, horse racing, karaoke, a lavish spa, a huge fitness
center overlooking the ocean, game shows, ice carvings, and dance
classes. I am surprised by the number of people learning to fold
napkins or create animal shapes out of towels, just like the cabin
stewards leave in the rooms. There is also a large children's area
on the ship and supervised programs.
</P>
<P>
   Entertainment ranges from cabin movies to shows on deck, in the
lounges, a lively piano bar in the Big Easy Bar, lavish Las Vegas
style shows, and comedy (one late-night show was rated R). There
are duty-free shops, art auctions, and a tuxedo rental shop.
</P>
<P>
   While the ship does offer almost nonstop activities, there are
plenty of places to just relax, ranging from the World's Way
Promenade where a delightful Vienna Cafe offers pastries and
coffees to the California Wine Bar to lounges for listening to jazz
or for dancing. I enjoyed meeting friends for a before-dinner drink
in the Oxford Bar with its feel of an old English library, deep,
comfortable chairs, and live classical music.
</P>
<P>
   The Carnival Triumph may not be for everyone, especially for
those who don't like ships with a whole lot of passengers, but it
does offer a world of choices and a vacation that will be
remembered.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1400EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0128 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
