u t BC-TRAVEL-WONDER-BOS &LR;      09-21 1688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-WONDER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISNEY WONDER: SMOOTH SAILING FOR ALL AGES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Disney Wonder is the second of two ships from the Disney
Cruise Line. The first, the Disney Magic, arrived last year.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder and magic is what a Disney cruise is all about.
</P>
<P>
   From Cape Canaveral, we set sail on a four-day adventure that
would take us to Nassau and Disney's own private isle, Castaway
Cay. It's an easy sail, not that great a distance, so Captain Henry
Anderson could take it easy throughout this cruise, providing one
of the smoothest sailings in recent memory.
</P>
<P>
   Disney has learned a lot since taking to the seas last year.
Then the only way to book a Disney cruise was to take a seven-day
package that included a three- or four-day stay at Disney World
with a three- or four-day cruise, for what Disney called a seamless
vacation. The same credit-card-sized identification issued for your
hotel room at Disney World would also be your stateroom key aboard
ship. With the card you could charge purchases both on land and
sea, and also use it for identification for exiting and boarding
the ship. Now the option of just taking a three- or four-day cruise
is available.
</P>
<P>
   The company also has learned that the name ``Disney'' alone
doesn't guarantee a smooth sailing. Since the Magic's inaugural,
Disney has added a cruise director and a hotel manager, and these
staff additions are noticeable in the way the ship operates.
</P>
<P>
   The Wonder is almost a twin of the Magic; even the naming of all
the rooms is similar. The only differences I detected were the
renaming of one dining room and one lounge, along with an Art
Noveau look rather than the Art Deco of the Magic.
</P>
<P>
   Disney does work its magic into these ships, providing countless
hours of pleasure. But we wondered if the Wonder could keep two
mature people happy sans kids. Our four are all grown up and off on
adventures of their own. When they were younger we would always
take them on a cruise with us. The difference between cruising with
kids then and now is amazing. As children, ours would have loved
this ship. But would we find happiness without them, and maybe
surrounded by hordes of other children.
</P>
<P>
   We should never have been concerned. If you have children, bring
them; this is the ship for families (other cruise lines have very
good children's programs, but the Disney touch is a plus). If you
don't have kids to bring, come anyway. This ship caters to you. In
its short existence, the Disney Cruise Line is being credited with
introducing thousands of vacationers to the pleasures of cruising;
most passengers on this and other Disney cruises are first-timers.
</P>
<P>
   The Disney Wonder looks the way a cruise ship should. It has the
lines of a great ocean liner, not the boxy, top-heavy look of many
a modern cruise ship. It is spacious and well laid out. It has
areas just for kids, others just for adults. Further separating it
from other cruise ships is the fact that it doesn't have a casino.
(If you need gambling and want to feel the pull of slot machines,
take the four-day cruise, which includes a long stay into the wee
hours of the morning in Nassau. Disney has shore packages to
Atlantis, a resort that has to be seen to be believed, with a
mammoth casino.)
</P>
<P>
   For families, there are huge areas of the Wonder devoted to the
fine art of entertaining and caring for youngsters of all ages.
Disney has programs for the 3-to-8 set, another for those 9-12.
When children are checked into the program, parents are provided a
beeper for the length of the cruise in order to stay in touch with
the youngsters. This lets parents enjoy themselves, be in touch
with the children, and never be very far away should they be
needed. Even teenagers can find happiness. Teens on ships, as we
discovered long ago, don't like organized onboard programs; they're
too grown up for that. So Disney offers them their own lounge. No
adults _ and certainly no parents _ may enter.
</P>
<P>
   The Wonder is listed at 83,000 tons and carries 1,750 passengers
(2,400 maximum). Our stateroom was spacious, with a sitting area
featuring a couch that can be made into a bed. There was a TV with
a wide variety of programming, including classic and Disney films _
but no schedule to let you know what's on _ and a refrigerator. We
had a private deck (73 percent of the rooms on the ship are
outside, with 44 percent of those having a deck), which we enjoyed.
Our bathrooms got a mixed reaction. The staterooms come with two
bathrooms _ one with toilet and sink, the other with shower and
sink. While this can be handy for families, it creates two rather
tight rooms. The staterooms also offer a hair dryer, personal safe,
and 24-hour dining service.
</P>
<P>
   While the ship is designed for families, adults sans kids find
more than enough to do and enjoy. There are ``quiet'' areas on deck
and within the ship just for the big people. While there were lots
of children on board this cruise, the little people did not seem to
take over the ship. It was fun to see occasional groups of kids on
a scavenger hunt, or attending an autograph session with their
favorite Disney characters in the main atrium. We even stood in
line to have our picture taken with Minnie, my wife's favorite
mouse. Mary Beth is much happier now that Minnie has more of a role
in the Disney world (before she would complain when Mickey's
birthday was recognized, but not Minnie's, which is on the same
day; all she got to do was serve the cake for Mickey).
</P>
<P>
   For adults, the ship offers a nighttime entertainment district
with three clubs: The Cadillac Lounge, with deep comfortable chairs
for relaxing before or after a show, and the wonderful music of Joy
Wright; WaveBands, with music from country to rock; and Barrel of
Laughs, where talented improvisational comics provide lots of fun.
There's also the Promenade Lounge, a nice place to meet for a drink
or to enjoy a dance. For the sports fans, there's the ESPN Skybox,
hidden in one of the smokestacks, where you can keep up with the
latest action on the fields and courts. Studio Sea has a variety of
entertainment for the whole family. First-run films are shown in
the Buena Vista Theatre, where we caught ``The Sixth Sense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Walt Disney Theatre is a large and lavish showroom featuring
full-scale theatrical productions with good story lines, music,
theatrics, and performers. One show is built around ``Hercules,''
another the sailing of a ghost ship, and another the music of
Disney. All are a refreshing change from the traditional
song-and-dance numbers of other lines.
</P>
<P>
   The hardest thing about taking a cruise is deciding what to do
among the choices provided. And Disney doesn't make it easy,
providing a full plate of fun things. The ship is a very relaxed
one and casual. I wore a jacket only one night.
</P>
<P>
   Another area where Disney shines is in its food service _ a vast
improvement from my first experience on the Magic. The Wonder has
three dining rooms, and guests get to eat in each one during the
cruise. Even the waitstaff moves with you, which is nice. The
setting and the menu may be different, but the staff is the same,
anticipating your likes and dislikes. Our waitresses _ one French,
the other Swedish (more than 60 nationalities are on board) _ were
young, knowledgeable, and friendly. A fourth dining room, Palo, a
gourmet's delight, is available by reservation only, and only for
adults.
</P>
<P>
   The ship also has a Beach Blanket Buffet for breakfast and lunch
with seating indoors or out. On deck there are places for hot dogs,
hamburgers, pizza, and ice cream. You won't go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   The ship has a large deck area with three pools, one just for
adults, along with a sports area for basketball or volleyball. The
ship's workout area is small but well equipped. Its Vista Spa &AMP;
Salon, however, is large with a variety of ``treatments,'' from
facials and massages, to an interesting Surial Bath. We tried the
bath ($60 per couple), which offers three medicinal muds. You apply
the muds to one another, then relax in the steam room while the
minerals are absorbed, and finally shower. A mud and mineral bath
for two: Was it invigorating? Well, let's say it was interesting.
</P>
<P>
   Trying new experiences is what a cruise is all about. How often
do you indulge in a spa treatment? Or have a whole evening trying
out new clubs and hearing different sounds of music? Taking in a
movie or show? Or meeting new friends? Or trying new culinary
treats? And all this without a care or an extra charge.
</P>
<P>
   While the ship provides just about everything one could desire
in a cruise, Disney's private Bahamas isle, Castaway Cay, is a star
attraction on its own. It's the only private isle for a cruise line
where the ship docks. Thus there is no getting into small boats to
tender in _ just step off the gangway and you're there. The island
offers lots of water sports and activities from snorkeling to
kayaking. There are beaches for families, for teens, and just for
adults. You'll also find a supervised play area for the kids,
beachside massages, music, games, and a large barbecue (OK, but I
expected grilled, not steamed, hot dogs, and hamburgers just off
the grill _ not looking as though they had been sitting around for
a while).
</P>
<P>
   Most people book the cruise along with a stay at Disney World.
For those, Disney promises a ``seamless'' vacation between land and
sea. These vacations begin at Disney World, about an hour's drive
from Port Canaveral, at one's choice of accommodations _ from
modest to lavish. Upon checking in, guests receive a card that
serves as a room key for both the hotel and ship, as a credit card
for all purchases, and as identification for going on and off the
ship. After the three- or four-day stay at Disney World, guests are
bused to the ship.
</P>
<P>
   The four-day cruise portion includes a day in Nassau, as well as
a day at Castaway Cay and a day at sea.
</P>
<P>
   It's a great family cruise, and for those who haven't cruised,
the Disney Wonder is a great introduction to cruising.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
