<HEADLINE>
HALIFAX: A PORT WORTH VISITING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the constantly expanding cruise-line fleets, new ports are
being sought. Cities such as Galveston, New Orleans, Charleston,
Philadelphia, and Newport News are becoming home ports for some
lines for part or all the year. Boston is fast becoming not only a
favorite port of call for lines, but also the starting point for
many sailings.
</P>
<P>
   This weekend the newest star in Norwegian Cruise Lines' fleet,
the Norwegian Sky, begins its maiden voyages with cruises along the
New England and Canadian coasts. For the last few years the line's
Norwegian Majesty has been sailing a seasonal schedule of weekly
trips to Bermuda from Boston. Next May, Carnival Cruise Lines will
offer sailings out of Boston to Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Sailings to Canada from Boston and New York are becoming
increasingly popular. And Halifax, Nova Scotia, is one of the most
popular destinations.
</P>
<P>
   Halifax is a great city to visit any year, but this year is
special because the city marks its 250th anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   For cruise passengers on a short visit, the city is easy to get
around. Downtown is within walking distance of the cruise port.
There's a lively pub atmosphere, even a casino, history galore, and
some great values because the US dollar is still strong _ worth up
to $1.50 Canadian.
</P>
<P>
   A trip to nearby Peggy's Cove is popular. . After all, it's one
of the prettiest places along the coast _ a tiny village with a
picturesque lighthouse and rocky shore. A lobster boil or salmon
bake is available there.
</P>
<P>
   While trips to Peggy's Cove or the fishing village of Lunenburg
are nice, as is driving the Evangeline Trail, Halifax itself has
more than enough to see and do in a short stay.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the Titanic. The Maritime Museum of the Atlantic has a
wonderful exhibit on this famed ship; it was to Halifax that ships
brought both survivors and the dead. Items from the Titanic,
including a large piece of wood paneling, are on view. A replica of
the paneling was used in the final scenes of the film when Kate
clung to it, awaiting rescue. Also in Halifax are cemeteries where
the victims were buried.
</P>
<P>
   The museum also has a gripping exhibit on the Halifax explosion.
In 1917 a ship loaded with munitions exploded in the harbor, with a
force that was said to be the largest and most destructive until
the atomic age. The toll on Halifax was devastating: Thousands were
killed or injured, and homes and businesses were destroyed. Boston
played a major role in helping the city to recover, and to this day
the people of Nova Scotia send a Christmas tree as a thank you. The
tree can be found at Boston's Prudential Center each December.
</P>
<P>
   The ships dock at Pier 21, Canada's Ellis Island, an immigration
center where millions arrived from foreign lands for their new
homeland. Even if you don't have Canadian roots, this is a moving
place to visit.
</P>
<P>
   Halifax: a small city with a lot to offer on even the briefest
visit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ice skating
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You may be in the tropics, but on the Voyager of the Seas you
can not only go ice skating but catch a skating show. The newest
and largest cruise ship in the world, Voyager of the Seas will
begin sailing in November on seven-day Caribbean cruises. It will
be a ship filled with innovative cruise ideas, including a 900-seat
skating rink. The Royal Caribbean International ship's rink will be
featured on an NBC-TV skating special this November with stars
Katarina Witt, Todd Eldredge, and Brian Orser. Other Voyager
features include a climbing wall and a nine-hole putting green.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A `grand hotel'
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The MS Deutschland, one of the newest luxury vessels in the
world, recently called on Boston. The German-built and -owned
vessel of Peter Deilmann Ocean Cruises will soon begin a series of
Grand Hotel Voyages. From November through March, the 505-passenger
ship will visit Thailand, Malaysia, Java, Bali, Borneo, Singapore,
Vietnam, Hong Kong, the Philippines, India, and Egypt. The 13- and
18-night cruises will offer free air fare from 37 US gateways to
the ship. Fares begin at $4,370 a person. The Deutschland is
designed to recall the splendor of the Edwardian period and the
1920s in its interior design, decoration, and art works. The ship
is quite spacious and offers three restaurants and bars, a
ballroom, cafe, indoor and outdoor pools, sun decks, shops,
theater, fitness, beauty salon, sauna, and infirmary with a
dialysis center. Travel agents have details or call 800-348-8287.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
A Dream delayed
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Norwegian Dream, one of Norwegian Cruise Line's newest
ships, was damaged in a collision with a cargo ship in the English
Channel Aug. 24. While the damage ``looks worse than it is,''
according to Art Sbarsky, NCL vice president, the ship should be
back in service by Oct. 11. Vacationers booked on canceled cruises
are being offered a full refund and a 50 percent discount on a
future cruise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Tall Stacks
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steamboating, an era that introduced Americans to one of the
grandest ways to travel, will be celebrated Oct. 13-17 during Tall
Stacks '99 along the Ohio River. The cities of Cincinnati, Ohio,
and Covington and Newport, Ky., will join in welcoming 19
riverboats from 10 states and 14 cities for this once-in-four-years
event. For general information, call toll-free 877-421-TALL (8255).
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No children allowed
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Renaissance Cruises has adopted an adults-only (18 and up)
policy aboard its smoke-free ships. ``Renaissance Cruises has
always had limited facilities for children, and the policy is
consistent with all our existing programs,'' said Franck Del Rio, a
Renaissance vice president. The line is also unusual in that it
sells its cruises directly to travelers, rather than through travel
agents. The cruises also offer great value. For example, a Greek
island cruise (January through March) costs from $1,499 a person
for an inside cabin, and includes round-trip air fare from New
York, a five-day cruise, and a four-night hotel package; balcony
cabins begin at $1,799. There are also discounts for those booking
through AARP. For information, call 800-525-5350 or, on the Web,
visit www.RenaissanceCruises.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Savings and sailings
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Individual Investor, a magazine filled with investment advice,
will hold a seven-day Seminar at Sea departing Jan. 30 from Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., aboard the Grand Princess. Investment advisers
will discuss a range of topics from how to invest to analyzing
companies for investment potential. For information, call
877-562-2493.
</P>
<P>
   Crystal Cruises is offering savings of up to 50 percent on its
Christmas cruises. Since many passengers who normally book the
holiday cruise are booking millennium cruises, space is available
on the Crystal Harmony South America holiday cruise. The Crystal
Symphony is offering a savings of $1,000 a couple on its
Australia/New Zealand trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
