<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL TRIPS POSSIBLE FOR ALL JEWISH YOUTHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY MORRIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most ambitious programs of discovery has just been
launched by Birthright Israel, a worldwide initiative to provide a
first Israel experience for every Jewish young person age 15-26.
</P>
<P>
   Birthright Israel provides round-trip transportation to Israel
from designated cities and the first 10 days of programming. The
program, which begins in November, is open to all Jewish youth
18-26 (high school student trips will begin in 2001) in North
America.
</P>
<P>
   ``This program is the most far-reaching philanthropic effort
ever undertaken by the Jewish community,'' said Michael Papo,
executive vice president of Birthright Israel. ``The Birthright
Israel gift will make Israel accessible to every Jewish youth
regardless of his or her affiliation, nationality, or economic
status.'' Papo said statistics have shown that Jewish youth who
visit Israel at a young age are more likely to retain ties to the
Jewish community, and by introducing them to their heritage and the
culture of the modern state of Israel, they can discover their past
and begin building their Jewish future.
</P>
<P>
   Information is available by calling 888-99-ISRAEL or, on the
Web, visiting www.israelexperience.org.
</P>
<P>
   Birthright Israel was created by funding from philanthropists
Charles R. Bronfman and Michael H. Steinhardt and contributions
from the Jewish community, the state of Israel. Bronfman is
cochairman of the Seagram Co. and Steinhardt, a highly successful
Wall Street fund manger, retired in 1995 to devote his time to
Jewish causes.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
