<HEADLINE>
SAYING `I DO' AT SEA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD P. CARPENTER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some have been young, others haven't. Some have shown up in
beachwear, others in tuxedos. But all have this in common: They
were married at sea aboard the Grand Princess mega cruise ship.
Since such ceremonies _ the first of their kind in modern times _
were initiated aboard the ship in June 1998, some 117 couples have
said ``I do.''
</P>
<P>
   The line's program allows couples to be legally married by the
ship's captain in Hearts and Minds, the first and only wedding
chapel at sea. (When launched this November, Royal Caribbean's
Voyager of the Seas will have a wedding chapel, but like many other
vessels will allow marriages aboard only in port.)
</P>
<P>
   Here's the who, what, and ``wear'' of Grand Princess weddings:
</P>
<P>
   --The youngest couple were ages 19 (bride) and 22; the oldest
couple were 76 (bride) and 77.
</P>
<P>
   --Surprisingly, the majority of couples were from Canada. Within
the United States, most couples were from Florida and California.
Other brides and grooms have been from Japan, Australia, and New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   --About 60 percent of couples were marrying for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   --Beachwear was the most unusual attire. Most couples wore
traditional wedding attire (suits/tuxedos and gowns).
</P>
<P>
   --Mendelssohn's ``Wedding March'' from ``A Midsummer Night's
Dream'' was the most requested song. And ``Twelfth Night'' by
Olivia Newton-John was one of the more uncommon choices.
</P>
<P>
   --The largest wedding was held last March when 100 passengers,
including 13 attendants, celebrated the nuptials of a Michigan
couple. (The newlyweds were also the youngest wedded couple
referred to earlier.)
</P>
<P>
   --It's not for nothing that the Princess fleet is known
collectively as ``The Love Boat.'' One couple got engaged on Sun
Princess and married exactly one year later during Grand Princess's
Valentine's sailing.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nice things about marrying on this ship is that
romantic honeymoon destinations come with the trip. In summer, the
Grand Princess plies the western Mediterranean, and in the fall,
winter, and spring, the eastern Caribbean. Wedding packages begin
at $1,400 and include fees for the ceremony, registration, and an
official marriage certificate. All reception packages include
music, hors d'oeuvres, beverages, and a three-tiered cake. The
one-hour parties for up to 80 guests begin at $70 per person. For
more information about Princess's wedding program, call
800-421-1700. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of the Grand Princess: When the ship sailed into
Istanbul last month, it was carrying a contribution of $83,629 for
Turkey's earthquake victims. The cruise line donated $50,000, and
passengers and crew gave the rest. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Travel Trivia: What did the letters ``RMS'' stand for in the RMS
Titanic? (Answer at end of column.) &QL; 
 &QL; 
Quotable: ``Farewell to Nova Scotia, the seabound coast! Let your
mountains dark and dreary be. For when I am far away on the briny
ocean tossed, will you ever heave a sigh or a wish for me?'' _
``The Nova Scotia Song,'' sung best by Ian and Sylvia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
In a name: Princess Cruises calls its bartenders ``bartisans.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Today's loopy law: It is illegal to get a fish drunk in Ohio. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Wired: The new MS Norwegian Sky, which was to visit Boston's Black
Falcon Terminal this weekend, has an Internet Cafe that offers
access to AOL and other Internet sites for a mere 33 cents a
minute. Internet access is also available in all cabins for the
same rate, and 10 laptops are available to rent. &QL; 
 &QL; 
That's some aquarium: Royal Caribbean's Voyager of the Seas, which
will replace the Grand Princess as the world's largest cruise ship
in November, has a unique lounge called the Aquarium Bar. In it,
there are over 56 tons of salt water, hundreds of exotically
colored tropical fish, and aquariums valued at more than $1
million. All this and shimmering blue light to make you feel as if
you're under the sea. &QL; 
 &QL; 
And speaking of the Voyager: Among those on the ship's maiden
voyage will be ice-skating luminaries Katarina Witt, Robin Cousins,
Brian Orser, and Todd Eldredge. They will perform in a special on
the first permanent floating ice rink in the world. ```StarSkates
on Ice'' will be telecast Sunday, Nov. 28, from 4-6 p.m. on NBC. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Ducky doings: The new Disney Wonder has a sculpture of Donald Duck
on its aft. And as usual, the duck appears to be in trouble. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Did you guess it? Royal Mail Ship: Delivering mail was one of the
ill-fated ship's unfulfilled duties. (With thanks to frequent
contributor Dave Smith of El Al New England.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send comments and questions to Travel Tidbits, Boston Globe,
Boston, MA 02107. Send e-mail to carpen(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
