<SLUG> BC-LANGUAGE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOGGED PURSUIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAN FREEMAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Globe has announced the October launch of an early edition
of the Sunday paper, to be sold at retail outlets on Saturdays. In
the industry, this early edition is known as a bulldog _ to the
ongoing puzzlement of the very journalists who use the word.
Conjectures abound, but nobody can say for sure where the bulldog
got its name.
</P>
<P>
   What do we know? Well, bulldog edition is an American term,
probably coined around the turn of the century; its first citation
in the Oxford English Dictionary is dated 1926 _ it's a quote from
The Nation magazine _ but as insider jargon it might well have
escaped official notice for its first few decades of existence. A
bulldog isn't necessarily a Sunday paper, but any early,
hot-off-the-presses edition; in the '80s, the Centre Daily Times in
State College, Pa., published a weekday bulldog as a way to ease
its transition from afternoon to morning paper.
</P>
<P>
   But why bulldog? Here are some of the guesses, educated and
otherwise:
</P>
<P>
   --The dueling-papers theory. The term bulldog edition ``probably
originated in the 1890s, when the New York World and other morning
newspapers published early editions to catch the mail trains and
the newspapers fought like bulldogs to make their deadlines,'' says
Webster's New World Dictionary of Media and Communications, among
other sources.
</P>
<P>
   --The dueling-newsboys theory: A variation on the theme has it
that the kids who sold the papers were the ones duking it out. ``It
being the first edition, newsboys fought for first papers like
bulldogs,'' proposed Charley Stough of the Dayton Daily News in an
on-line etymological discussion. In the variant passed along by Jim
Howley, director of the Globe's fleet of delivery trucks, the
newsboys were fighting not for papers but for the prime
street-corner selling locations.
</P>
<P>
   --The Hearst theory. ``I had always heard that bulldog was
coined by W.R. Hearst who wanted his first editions to have grabber
headlines and `bite like a bulldog,' '' wrote Saul Daniels in the
abovementioned on-line discussion
(nyu.edu/projects/jhistory/jhist.95/).
</P>
<P>
   --The ugly-as-a-bulldog theory. Nobody I know remembers that
typographical errors were once called bulls, but it's part of
newspaper lore, and it inspires yet another explanation: That the
early edition, composed in haste, was full of bulls, or typos. Or
even, submits Stough, that the first edition was ``the ugliest in
terms of type alignment, inking, etc., hence . . . bulldog ugly.''
</P>
<P>
   --The Mack-truck theory. This one _ brought back by a colleague
after an official visit to some bulldog-savvy newspapers in other
cities _ holds that the bulldog edition got its name from the Mack
trucks that delivered papers from the plant to the waiting
newsboys. The Mack's bulldog logo and hood ornament seem just the
thing to capture the imagination of the young hawkers _ you can
almost hear them shouting to each other, ``Here comes the
bulldog!''
</P>
<P>
   There are drawbacks to this picturesque hypothesis, though. For
one thing, Mack trucks didn't get their ``bulldog'' nickname till
World War I, according to the official Mack history. The company's
version, available on its Web site (go to ``Corporate Information''
at www.macktrucks.com), says English soldiers gave the AC Mack
truck its bulldog moniker _ both for its snub-nosed profile and
because the bulldog was a beloved symbol of British tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   But if this is the source of the newspaper jargon, bulldog
editions couldn't have been part of the New York's 1890s newspaper
wars. The bulldog logo wasn't adopted till 1922, at first as a
nameplate on the door (it showed a bulldog chewing up a volume
labeled ``Hauling Costs''); not till 1932 did the patented bulldog
become a hood ornament.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Mack trucks were bought by some newspapers,
according to Sharon Shuman at the Mack museum. The Morning Call of
Allentown, Pa. (Mack's headquarters), bought one, and ``during
1923-24, several AB model trucks and at least one AC model truck
went to Boston to the Hotel &AMP; Railroad News Company,'' she reports.
</P>
<P>
   The search goes on. For instance, there may be clues in the 1936
film ``Bulldog Edition,'' directed by Charles Lamont (of ``Ma and
Pa Kettle Go to Town,'' ``Abbott and Costello go to Mars,'' etc.).
It's a rough tale, says the on-line video vendor, of ``Newspaper
wars! One paper engages gangsters to sabotage the success of the
other.'' (Do they slash the tires of the Mack delivery trucks?)
</P>
<P>
   All the current etymological proposals have advantages and
drawbacks _ and, probably, adherents who are absolutely sure
they're right. But with so many missing links in the chains of
evidence, nobody can say which is most likely. The truth is out
there, all right _ we just don't yet know where.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Write Jan Freeman at The Boston Globe, Box 2378, Boston, MA
02107-2378; freeman(at)globe.com. Please include a hometown.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
