<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-DEMOCRATS-RACE-BOS &LR;      09-21 1619
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-RACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY SLOW TO REACH OUT TO SOUTH'S BLACK ELECTORATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ANN SCALES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Bill Bradley's passion for improving race relations in
America, a signature issue in his presidential campaign, should
have a home in a thriving black middle-class city like this, flush
with memories of the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. and his
struggle for racial justice.
</P>
<P>
   But every time black voters here look around, Al Gore's in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore has been here many times,'' said Randy Willis, a
43-year-old chiropractor, as he waited for friends to finish
touring a museum that chronicles King's life. ``Bradley? I really
don't know much about him except that he was a ball player at one
time.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore has courted black voters with intensity, Bradley has
yet to take his message south, to the heartland of the black
electorate. Polls consistently show him getting clobbered among
black voters nationally, and, in a recent Zogby International poll,
Gore held a 71-to-10 percent advantage over Bradley among blacks.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say Bradley can't expect to compete with Gore
without going where more than 55 percent of the African-American
population lives and votes _ an increasingly active constituency
that may determine who wins the South and goes on to claim the
Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Bradley is a serious alternative to Gore, you have to ask
then, what is your southern strategy?'' said David Bositis, a
senior policy analyst at the Joint Center for Political and
Economic Studies, a black think-tank in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The answer from the Bradley campaign: Give us time.
</P>
<P>
   Anita Dunn, a spokewoman for the Bradley campaign, acknowledged
the obvious that Bradley had not focused on the south so much as
Iowa and New Hampshire, the first-caucus and first-primary states.
But she said that is the result of the bunched primary schedule
which places the early emphasis on California, Iowa and the
northeast. Bradley, she said, would begin campaigning in the South
``as we move forward in the primary calendar. It's going to be very
fast.''
</P>
<P>
   The first real test of Bradley and Gore's strength among blacks
will take place here in Georgia, which is scheduled to be the first
southern state to hold a primary, along with Maryland, six months
from now, in a precursor to the real southern showdown a week later
on Super Tuesday, March 14. In Georgia, African-American voters
make up at least 40 percent of the Democratic primary vote, but the
vote has risen as high as 50 percent in various elections.
</P>
<P>
   After black voters showed surprising strength last year, helping
the Democrats cut into the GOP's majority in the House of
Representatives in the November midterm elections, even some
Republican candidates _ most notably millionaire publisher Steve
Forbes, who has given African-Americans high-profile roles in his
campaign _ have sought to expand their outreach to this
constituency.
</P>
<P>
   And there is, in fact, a sliver of an opening for Republicans,
as polls find blacks have grown slightly less fervent in their
identification with the Democratic party over the course of the
decade. Some Democrats hope the Bradley and Gore jostling for the
black vote will energize this key constituency as President
Clinton, an immensely popular figure among blacks, exits the stage.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis B. Gans, director of the Committee for the Study of the
American Electorate, which tracks voter turnout, said that Bradley
and Gore stand apart from previous presidential candidates in the
intensity of their racial outreach.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been an avoidance of any effort to mobilize the poor
and minorities communities, and to the extent that may be changing
in this election is healthy,'' Gans said.
</P>
<P>
   But, across Atlanta, and especially here along Auburn Avenue,
where the King family church, the civil rights leader's childhood
home and his museum are located, Gore wins among black voters,
because the questions of who Bradley is, where he has been and what
he stands for have largely gone unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   Typical of those voters is Camille Jackson, a 27 year-old recent
law school graduate from Atlanta, who considers herself an
Independent, like some 23 percent of blacks surveyed in a recent
Joint Center poll. That independent spirit is largely a phenomenon
among younger blacks, age 35 and under, the poll found.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to vote today, I probably would vote for Gore, just
because of the time he has taken and the effort he has made to
include African Americans in different things,'' said Jackson as
she left the King museum.
</P>
<P>
   To the Rev. G.H. Williams, a volunteer guide to visitors at the
Ebenezer Baptist Church, the only thing that seems certain is that
``whoever follows Clinton is going to have to be a real Trojan.
</P>
<P>
   And though he has heard Gore speak at Ebenezer, the 74-year-old
Williams said he has yet to pick his candidate. ``He's a good
speaker,'' Williams said of Gore. ``But like I say, I've heard so
many good speakers. They are just like preachers, they don't
impress me too quick because I hear them preach one good sermon.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Williams, many black elected officials are keeping their
options open. Eighteen of the 38 members of the Congresssional
Black Caucus have withheld formal endorsements of either Democrat.
Most notable among those members still technically neutral are
civil rights stalwarts like Representatives John Lewis of Georgia,
Maxine Waters of California and John Conyers of Michigan, though a
Gore aide said last week an endorsement from Lewis might come soon.
The Rev. Jesse L. Jackson also has not officially taken sides, and
neither has his son, Jesse Jackson Jr., a congressman from
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson Jr. said he and other lawmakers were withholding
endorsements because it was too early in the selection process and
because they wanted to hear more from both Gore and Bradley about
their plans for bringing blacks and other minorities and poor
people into the economic mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still waiting for a real Democrat to emerge _ an FDR,
Truman, HHH, Kennedy, Johnson Democrat,'' the Congressman Jackson.
``Are either of them willing to put a progressive African-American
on their ticket as VP? That would be one thing that would energize
the country and inspire many of those who are not currently
participating,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Representative James E. Clyburn, a South Carolina Democrat
who is the black caucus chairman and has endorsed Gore, said: ``I
have talked to people in the caucus who are not yet ready to make
it formal. But I have not talked to anyody who tells me they do not
plan to be for Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   A poll released last month by the Joint Center showed that 69
percent of black adults polled held a favorable opinion of Gore, a
perception that has remained unchanged for the last several years.
(Clinton's numbers are about 20 points higher). Only 17 percent
held an unfavorable opinion of Gore, and 8 percent say they don't
know him well enough to have an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Bradley scored a 41 percent favorable rating, but
an almost equal number _ 42 Percent of the respondents -- said they
don't know Bradley, while 11 percent were unfavorable toward him.
Similarly, Republican front-runner, Texas Governor George W. Bush,
who has courted Hispanic voters more than blacks, had a 43 percent
favorable rating among blacks; 34 percent unfavorable and 14
percent who said they don't know him.
</P>
<P>
   Rev. Bobby Howard, who teaches English at Dekalb College in
Atlanta, explained those numbers this way: ``They don't know Gore
as a leader and they don't know Bradley as a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard, an independent who has voted for Bush's father; Clinton;
President Ronald Reagan and supported billionaire Ross Perot in
1992 ``until I realized we had a fool on our hands,'' said he would
vote for the Texas governor. Bush, he is convinced, ``is probably
going to wind up being the most liberal president that the
Republican Party has had since Lincoln.''
</P>
<P>
   Typically, however, Republican presidential candidates only
garner about 10 percent of the black vote nationally, said Bositis
of the Joint Center. The other 90 percent generally goes to the
Democrat, and that vote is no where as strong as it is in the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Blacks are often a majority of the Democratic vote in
Mississippi, Louisiana and South Carolina, about 20 percent in
North Carolina and Virginia; and between 10 and 20 percent in
Florida and Texas, Bositis said, though nationally, blacks make up
only 10 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to reach African-American voters, both Bradley and
Gore, whose civil rights records most regarded as equal and who
have assembled racially diverse staffs, have embraced affirmative
action and called for an end to racial profiling _ in which police
stop motorists based on their race.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Gore told applauding delegates to the NAACP
convention, ``If I am elected president, ending racial profiling
will be the first civil rights act of the next century.'' He added,
``Driving while intoxicated is a national crime. But driving while
black is a natural condition.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley, in a later speech to the Rainbow/PUSH annual convention
in Chicago, fired back, ``Why wait? Why doesn't he walk down the
hall, put the executive order in front of the president and ask him
to sign it?''
</P>
<P>
   The upshot, said Ronald Walters, a political scientist at the
University of Maryland at College Park, and an expert on black
politics, is that ``There is a big disconnect between the rhetoric
and public policy'' that both Bradley and Gore may need to
overcome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1411EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0032 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-RACING-ENVIRONMENT-BO     09-21 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACING-ENVIRONMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVVING UP A MEAN GREEN MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Race cars sure don't look like they're saving the
planet. Tearing around a track at 120 miles per hour, they spew
exhaust as they go, guzzling a gallon of gas every six to eight
miles. And, for all the smog they generate, the cars don't actually
go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   But there he is, John P. DeVillars, New England's top
environmental official, dressed in full racing gear and crash
helmet on a postcard promoting an auto race to raise money for the
environment.
</P>
<P>
   As some environmentalists look on with dismay, the regional
administrator of the Environmental Protection Agency is preparing
to go mano a mano with another environmentalist driver this weekend
in a benefit for land preservation in western Massachusetts. If the
unusual race goes well, organizers hope it will become an annual
event in which all kinds of environmental groups sponsor a race
car.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is part of an effort to democratize the environmental
movement,'' said DeVillars, an accomplished auto racer who finished
third in his first professional race last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought it would be kind of fun to have another wrinkle to
our fund-raising'' that attracts a different crowd than the usual
cocktail party at some posh location, he said.
</P>
<P>
   But many environmentalists view the automobile as one of the
world's leading environmental villains.And several of them openly
chided DeVillars, who is normally their ally, over the symbolism of
the auto race for the environment, organized by the Berkshire
Natural Resources Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't equate a 6-mile-per-gallon race car with an
environmental event,'' said Sheila Lynch of the Northeast Advanced
Vehicle Consortium, which promotes cars that run on batteries and
low-polluting fuels. ``It's a fine hobby, but it's not an
environmental program.''
</P>
<P>
   Added James McCaffrey of the Sierra Club, which supports more
fuel efficient vehicles, ``We'd rather see them racing trains (or)
solar-powered cars.''
</P>
<P>
   However, George Wislocki, director of the Pittsfield-based
Berkshire Natural Resources Council, was unapologetic about the
race. In Berkshire County, he explained, environmental groups are
often overshadowed by the major arts groups in fund-raising,
forcing environmental groups to be ``fairly cunning and fairly
artful.''
</P>
<P>
   Wislocki has parlayed the council into Berkshire County's
biggest private land owner, in part by building ties with groups
often overlooked by other environmentalists, especially hunters and
fishermen. Sportsmen for Land Preservation, a subsidiary of the
council, raises $50,000 a year through an outdoor-oriented auction
that includes hunting weapons and other sporting gear.
</P>
<P>
   Wislocki said this Saturday's auto race at Lime Rock Park in
Connecticut grew out of the sportsmen's group. Patrons will pay $50
apiece to see the race, part of a larger 25-car contest known as
the North Atlantic Road Racing Championships.
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars will drive a Ford prototype racing car with a 2-liter
engine on behalf of the Sportsmen for Land Preservation, while Jack
Baker, owner of a Connecticut bottled-water company, will represent
the Housatonic Valley Association over the 30-lap, 1.8-mile course.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name of the game in fund-raising is to make it fun,'' said
Wislocki. ``A race of this sort is so utterly unique. Let me put it
this way: It would be hard to get people to pay $50 a head to go to
an event where they are racing electric cars.''
</P>
<P>
   DeVillars, the star attraction, is no stranger to controversy
over his driving. A series of speeding tickets while he was
Governor Michael S. Dukakis's environmental affairs secretary in
1989 forced DeVillars to make a public apology and earned him the
nickname ``Speedy'' on Beacon Hill.
</P>
<P>
   But DeVillars has never been shy about his penchant for speed,
posing for the cover of the Boston Sunday Herald's magazine in the
cockpit of a souped-up Formula Ford just after the speeding ticket
controversy. Since then, he has raced all over the Northeast,
beating television stars Jason Priestley and Tim Allen last year
and finishing fourth in the North Atlantic Road Racing
Championships the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   As an EPA official who has cultivated a reputation for being
tough on pollution, DeVillars occasionally takes flak over his
choice of hobbies. But he believes people get too hung up on the
symbolism of auto racing, overlooking the fact that he walks to
work each day or that he spends his professional life trying to
clean up the environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's room enough in this world for auto racing in a clean
environment,'' said DeVillars.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, DeVillars believes that environmentalist disdain for
fast cars reflects the movement's difficulty in connecting with
people who never show up at Tanglewood or other elite places for
traditional fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Environmentalists should get more engaged in politics,'' said
DeVillars, noting that the Massachusetts Sportsmen's Council has
300,000 members who are often ``viewed warily and suspiciously'' by
environmentalists. Events such as the race for the environment can
help draw more sportsmen into the effort to protect open space, he
contends.
</P>
<P>
   Monday, few environmentalists wanted to be too hard on
DeVillars, who has taken a prominent role in fighting air pollution
and other auto-induced problems. But several scoffed at his
outreach ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are better ways to democratize the environmental
movement than to have car races,'' said Rob Sargent of the
Massachusetts Public Interest Research Group. ``You can have a bean
supper.''
</P>
<P>
   But one environmentalist, who asked not to be named, feared his
colleagues are caught up in political correctness. ``I'm not sure,
to be a good environmentalist, you have to be in favor of the
abolition of auto racing,'' the environmentalist said. ``If you
added up all the pollution of all the speedways in the US
throughout the year, I don't think it would make an appreciable
difference.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
