<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-US-SKINFLINTS-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAY UP OR SHUT UP, AMERICA  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This excellent 600-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 18 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The United States has a hard time with supranational
organizations. It never joined the League of Nations; it has often
sneered at the International Court of Justice; it views the World
Trade Organization as a veiled attack on American sovereignty.
</P>
<P>
   But all this pales beside its behavior as a member of the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   If it does not get its act together before the end of the year,
the United States will automatically lose its vote in the General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   America owes the U.N. more than $1 billion. Some of this debt
has accrued since the 1980s, when Congress decided to withhold
payment until the U.N. reformed its management and budget
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it is money owing from the 1990s, when Congress forbade
the payment of America's agreed share of U.N. peacekeeping
expenses.
</P>
<P>
   Those spats are now largely over. Peacekeeping ventures have
been greatly reduced, partly at America's insistence; if the
peacekeepers go in at all, it is only by invitation, currently
Indonesia's. And the U.N. has reformed itself internally, including
giving individual countries a power of veto over budgets they
dislike.
</P>
<P>
   But even after this, the United States has still not paid its
arrears. The Clinton administration, to its credit, has declared
that the money ought to be paid. Under the Balanced Budget Act of
1997, an allocation was set aside. But it has not been authorized
yet, because House, Senate and president cannot agree.
</P>
<P>
   The problem lies mostly in the House, where Chris Smith, a
Republican congressman from New Jersey, keeps trying to link the
payment of arrears to restrictions on American family-planning
programs abroad.
</P>
<P>
   He took this language out of the House bill in July, and the
bill passed; but when it goes to conference, he is expected to try
and get it back in again.
</P>
<P>
   The linking of these two unconnected issues has made America
look like a bigot and a fool on the world stage. But to the likes
of Smith, such epithets are badges of honor.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has done somewhat better with its authorization bill,
but not much. There, Jesse Helms and Joe Biden have pushed through
a bill that is festooned with brattish conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Before it gets its money, the U.N. must promise that American
sovereignty will always be maintained; it must promise not to set
up a standing army; it must give the United States a permanent seat
on the budget committee; it must charge no interest on late
payments.
</P>
<P>
   Such clauses have been added mostly to mollify that section of
American opinion _ not a large one, but loud _ that associates the
U.N. with the whirr of black helicopters and the threat of world
domination.
</P>
<P>
   If he wants to bang heads and insist on repayment _ as he must _
Clinton may have to accept all this. If he vetoes Helms/Biden, the
allocation will lapse, and America will quickly find it has lost
its General Assembly vote.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N., of course, can be a many-headed muddler, and some of
its agencies remain both inefficient and unaccountable. This gives
America reason to watch it like a hawk, but not to refuse to pay
its debts.
</P>
<P>
   This refusal is widely taken as a sign of something much deeper:
a reluctance to take up responsibilities and challenges in the
world as a whole. If America wants to reverse that impression
overnight, it knows what it must do. &QL; 
