<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0071 &Cx1f; tab-z
r k BC-IRAQ-`NICE-GUY'-IMAGE     09-21 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-`NICE-GUY'-IMAGE-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SADDAM HUSSEIN'S BUSY SNAKE CHARMERS  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This excellent 475-word ``separate buy'' article is from the
current (week beginning 18 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``i''
international news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k''
commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAIRO _ In the latest phase of its decade-long siege, Iraq is
fielding a novel weapon: charm.
</P>
<P>
   From the United Nations to the Arab League to the Vatican, Iraqi
officials are trying to project a kinder, gentler image. Their hope
is to exploit growing fatigue, and queasiness, with sanctions, and
to position Iraq for rehabilitation in a more forgiving world.
</P>
<P>
   Despite widespread sympathy for the Iraqi people, this
public-relations effort will take hard work. Not only does the
leadership style of Saddam Hussein remain a critical liability, but
his major foe, the United States, is mounting its own publicity
campaign to revive international revulsion at Hussein's regime.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the differences within the U.N. Security Council over
the embargo, which once were wide, seem to have narrowed lately.
</P>
<P>
   At meetings in London this week, the permanent members most
sympathetic to Iraq _ Russia, China and France _ moved a bit closer
to Britain and America. The three now appear to support continued
close monitoring of Iraq's trade, and of its weapons development,
even if most sanctions are lifted.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Baghdad's charm offensive has brought some results. It was
only last January that Iraq's foreign minister, Muhammad al-Sahhaf,
stormed out of an Arab League ministerial meeting after his
colleagues refused to condemn sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Now, for the first time since the invasion of Kuwait in 1990,
Iraq has assumed the rotating chairmanship of the 22-member
organization.
</P>
<P>
   When Arab ministers gathered in Cairo last week, al-Sahhaf
surprised observers by steering smoothly through the 46-point
agenda, which had been stripped in advance of controversial topics,
including the embargo.
</P>
<P>
   For the time being, no Arab country is likely to do what Iraq
wants, and openly flout sanctions. But many are moving in a
direction quite pleasing to Iraq. Several Arab states, notably
Egypt, have sent trade delegations in the hope of cashing in when
commerce opens up.
</P>
<P>
   These join a growing number of visitors to the Iraqi capital,
which recently played host to a Congress of Islamic Peoples
attended by delegates from 50 countries. A trade fair on oil
technology is to be held in Baghdad soon.
</P>
<P>
   The propaganda value of such openings, good as they are, are
minor compared with the possible visit from Pope John Paul II,
which the Vatican says may take place before Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   The mooted visit has attracted vigorous opposition from America,
Jewish groups and the exiled Iraqi opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Less controversial is Iraq's offer of aid to earthquake-stricken
Turkey. Since the Turkish government could hardly refuse a gift of
$10 million-worth of oil, the gesture has made it harder for Turkey
to condone the use of its bases for American and British air
strikes.
</P>
<P>
   In Baghdad, meanwhile, there are persistent rumors of an
imminent cabinet shuffle. Several old-guard figures, it is
whispered, may be replaced by technocrats with more appeal to
potential foreign investors. &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
