<HEADER>
A0075 &Cx1f; tab-z
r a BC-CYBER-CASBAH-ECONOMIS     09-21 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-CASBAH-ECONOMIST </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEXTTAG.COM: A NEW TALK-'EM-DOWN-IN-PRICE CYBERSTORE  
 
</HEADLINE>
   (This 475-word ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week
beginning 18 Sept. 1999) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. If
unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted into the ``f''
financial news, ``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 c.1999 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Economists seek to model reality _ or at least
most do. Many Internet entrepreneurs try to mimic the dismal
science by building ever more perfect marketplaces.
</P>
<P>
   First came online auctions. Then Priceline.com let consumers
name their prices for airline tickets or hotel rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Now a Silicon Valley start-up, NexTag.com, has come up with an
even better way of setting prices.
</P>
<P>
   At first sight, NexTag's website (http://www.nexttag.com), which
it launched in early August, looks like just another online auction
house for electronic equipment, albeit a big one featuring more
than 150,000 items.
</P>
<P>
   But the firm does not let buyers compete by bidding prices up.
It offers the opposite: multiple sellers bid prices down to win a
buyer's business.
</P>
<P>
   The company's site works best for people who know what they
want. They first search for a specific item. A click on its
hyperlink pulls up a list of online stores that currently carry the
product and its prices. A user can then either choose the best
offer or place a lower bid.
</P>
<P>
   Within a couple of minutes, sellers reply by accepting the bid
or by making a counter-offer. Recently, for example, eight online
resellers offered the base version of the Rio, a popular device for
playing online music files.
</P>
<P>
   The prices ranged from $145.98 to $193.25, including tax and
shipping. A bid of $140 prompted one seller to lower its asking
price from $152.91 to $145.84. Another offered $169.75 if the buyer
agreed to purchase a leather carrying case.
</P>
<P>
   NexTag, which will make its money from transaction fees and
advertising, supplements its service by providing the information
needed to make the right purchasing decision.
</P>
<P>
   The return policies of sellers _ if they pay the shipping fee,
for instance _ are only a click away. And customers can look at
charts of the pricing history of all products available through the
site. The chart for the Rio shows that it sold for about $190 in
January, but $140 in August.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to see why buyers would like such a service. But what
is in it for the sellers? So far, the firm has managed to sign up a
dozen online computer stores, among them such well-known names as
CDW computer centers, Egghead.com and PC Mall.
</P>
<P>
   The attraction is that they can discount products without having
to lower prices at their own outlets, explains Purnendu Ojha,
NexTag's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Equally enticing, apparently, is the fact that NexTag provides
sellers with free software to automate their responses to bids and
capture data about potential buyers. But if too many buyers cotton
on to the service, the sellers may change their tune. &QL; 
