   CLEMENCY-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A Senate counterterrorism
committee hears from Justice and FBI witnesses on Clinton's
clemency for FALN members; in the House, Rep. Burton's committee
will hear administration witnesses in the afternoon. By Katharine
Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   BANKRUPTCY-CONGRESS (Washington) _ The Senate may begin
considering bankruptcy legislation, and Democrats plan to attach
minimum wage bill to it. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   FILIBUSTER-CONGRESS (Washington) _ In the strange and often
convoluted politics of judicial nominations, filibusters are rarely
if ever used. But in an especially odd chapter, Senate Republicans
are expected to vote to block the Democrats from filibustering on
three judicial candidates, all Clinton nominees. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-BUS-SAFETY (Washington) _ The National Transportation
Safety Board issues a report on school bus safety, including a
recommendation on seatbelts. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-CAROLINA (Tarboro, N.C.) _ Following the storm
aftermath as North Carolina tries to dig out and more rain is
expected. There is particular concern about drinking water, which
is contaminated by pig waste in many areas. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   HURRICANE-NY (Undated) _ Flood cleanup in the New York
metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   STORM-FLORIDA (Clearwater, Fla.) _ Tropical Storm Harvey changed
course and bore down on southern Florida Tuesday with 50 mph winds
and heavy rain, forcing schools to close and prompting the
declaration of an emergency from the governor. Five to 10 inches of
rain were expected from the storm, which was forecast to come
ashore near Naples, 150 miles south of Clearwater, by Tuesday
night. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   ABERNATHY-TRIAL (Atlanta) _ A state judge orders an
investigation into possible jury tampering after the family of
Martin Luther King Jr. appeared at the trial of state Sen. Ralph
Abernathy III., who was charged with taking $13,000 through
falsified reimbursements. The case ended in a mistrial on Friday
when the jury was unable to reach a verdict. Abernathy, son of the
civil rights leader, says the charges are politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit surged to a
record $25.18 billion in July, as imports from western Europe,
China, Japan and Canada continued to grow. Economists had expected
the deficit to narrow from June's $24.6 billion gap, the previous
record. For the second month, imports topped $100 billion, at
$104.22 billion. Exports rose modestly, to $79.04 billion. The
dollar, which tumbled in Asian trading after the Bank of Japan
announced it was leaving monetary policy unchanged, extends its
slide. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-ECON (Tokyo) _ The Bank of Japan votes to leave monetary
policy unchanged, defying government officials and economists here
and abroad who have been demanding a further easing of the money
supply in response to the yen's recent heady rise. By Stephanie
Strom.
</P>
<P>
   BELL-ATLANTIC-VODAFONE (Undated) _ Bell Atlantic and Vodafone
announce their coast-to-coast U.S. cellular joint venture. Bell
Atlantic will own 55 percent of the new $70 billion company, and
Vodafone of Britain will own 45 percent. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ Closing arguments begin in
the U.S. antitrust suit against Microsoft. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily Marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN-EARNINGS (New York) _ Goldman, Sachs posts third-quarter
earnings that are sharply higher than expected. Goldman is the
first of the Wall Street firms to report.
</P>
<P>
   CREDIT-RATINGS (Washington) _ Freddie Mac study shows disparity
between black and white credit ratings; behind the statistics is a
realization that the only growth potential for lenders in the
saturated mortgage market lies among minority consumers. By Steven
A. Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   ORACLE-HP (San Francisco) _ Oracle says that Hewlett-Packard
will sell and distribute Oracle's software to manage customer
service. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS-TRAVEL (Undated) _ The business travel column. By Edwin
McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-OIL (Moscow) _ BP Amoco appears to be losing its
long-running battle to save its half-billion dollar investment in
the bankrupt oil company Sidanco, despite assurances by the
government only two weeks ago that it would try to protect the
Russian concern from liquidation. By Neela Banerjee.
</P>
<P>
   AIR-CANADA-ONEX (Toronto) _ Air Canada rejects Onex offer.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 2:15 p.m., stocks were down. The Dow
Jones industrial average was down 202 points, the S&AMP;P 500 down 24
points and the Nasdaq composite down 48 points. European markets
were also lower, with London down 1.66 percent and Frankfurt down
1.67 percent. The Nikkei closed up 2.03 percent, while the Hang
Seng fell 0.39 percent. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
