<P>
   Look to May and June of 1999 as a model for how the markets will
behave _ sinking on the worry and rallying on the news, even if the
news is a rate increase.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that almost certainly would deter the Federal Reserve
would be a resurgence of the financial crisis that rocked Asia in
1998. The region is clearly not out of the woods yet. The recovery
in Korea and Thailand appears to be real, but fragile.
</P>
<P>
   Japan cannot convincingly shake its recession. And now China
shows signs that it is considering a devaluation of its currency,
the yuan, an act that would send the area back into turmoil. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM _ 150 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 650) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese could be on the verge of a Japanese-style
deflationary spiral. Consumer prices have fallen in China for 21
consecutive months. At the same time, the Chinese savings rate has
climbed to 42 percent of household income _ people are putting
money away for an increasingly uncertain future.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, growth in the gross domestic product has slowed in
each year since 1996, and last year China's economy grew by a
lackluster 4 percent, according to non-governmental economists (the
Chinese government claims GDP grew by 7.8 percent).
</P>
<P>
   The glut of manufactured goods such as televisions is so great
that even price cuts of 25 percent can't clear the market. In some
industries, companies have closed factories for months to reduce a
mountain of inventory. That, of course, just increases fear (and
cuts incomes) and sends consumer spending lower. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF FIRST OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Devaluing the yuan so that Chinese exports are cheaper is a
tempting short-term solution. It would undoubtedly produce a spike
in exports _ until China's neighbors responded with their own
devaluations and set off a trade war that no side would win and
that would be blamed on the Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Devaluation would probably kill China's attempt to gain entry to
the World Trade Organization this year or next.
</P>
<P>
   That the Chinese are even willing to consider devaluation is a
sign of how dire the situation is. China's leaders know that a
deflationary spiral, once in place, can last for a decade or more _
all they have to do is look across the narrow sea for proof of
that.
</P>
<P>
   And domestic stability in China depends on strong economic
growth. China needs to add 7.5 million jobs a year just to hold
unemployment steady at the current 10 percent in cities and 30
percent in the countryside. The regime knows that the hope of a
better tomorrow is essential to contain potential unrest.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting what China will do is almost impossible _ the
country's course of action depends on massive political and
complicated internal struggles.
</P>
<P>
   It is that unpredictability that will send the bond market (and
with it parts of the equity market) into a speculative tizzy from
time to time over the remainder of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Neither a Federal Reserve interest-rate hike (or two) nor the
devaluation of the yuan would mean the end of the world, but worry
over those two issues certainly helps set the stage for those who
believe the YK2 problem will cause the demise of civilization as we
know it. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM _ 100 WORDS _ BEGINS HERE AT 1,075) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No one knows what the widespread use of two-digit year dates in
computer software will do to computer systems around the world in
January 2000. The absence of major problems so far _ computer
systems that make payments or order inventory, for example, have
been coping with the dating issue for months now _ makes it likely
that any blowups will be localized.
</P>
<P>
   But the truth is that no one knows. In that atmosphere of
uncertainty, investors tend to see a monster under every bed. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (END OF SECOND OPTIONAL TRIM) &LR;  &QC; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What's the likely effect of these worries on the stock market
during the next several months? In each case, at the moment, the
risk is all on the downside.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is already reflected in the prices of financial
assets; the bad news is just starting to get factored in. In
situations like that, investors tend to sell at the first sign of
real or imagined trouble.
</P>
<P>
   During May and June, that led to an over-sold market as
investors marked down everything. That was followed by a July
rally. And in early August, stocks and bonds took another tumble.
</P>
<P>
   Expect more of the same: lots of action without much direction. &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Jim Jubak is senior markets
editor at Microsoft's MoneyCentral _ www.Moneycentral.msn.com.) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
