<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 14:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0099 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f BC-`NEW-PARADIGM'-ECONOM     09-21 1224
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-`NEW-PARADIGM'-ECONOMY-WORTH-RESEND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMISTS WHISPER `NEW PARADIGM' _ BUT GREENSPAN TURNS A DEAF
EAR  
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (RESENDING from Aug. 29)   (This perceptive 1,000-word ``separate buy'' financial story is
from ``WORTH'' magazine. To publish this article, it must be
purchased from the New York Times Syndicate's sales representative
DEBRA WEYDERT at 732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her
e-mail address is Debra/Weydert/CORPHQ/NYTIMES. If unable to reach
Ms. Weydert, please call 800-444-0267, or fax us at
816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been filed into the ``a''
domestic/general news, ``f'' financial news and ``k'' commentary
news files.)  
  
 By JIM JUBAK  
 c.1999 Worth Magazine  
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has important converts among Wall Street's most visible
strategists. Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan has even
acknowledged that it could be valid. And it clearly does a better
job than the conventional wisdom of explaining how quarter after
quarter of economic growth at better than 4 percent can coexist
with low inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect what's known as the New Paradigm to stop the
Federal Reserve from raising interest rates. Even though the
numbers don't make an airtight case for a need to raise rates to
head off inflation, no one among the Federal Reserve's board of
governors wants to go down as a martyr to a new economic theory.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the problem facing the Federal Reserve _ and investors
trying to map a path through the current turmoil in the financial
markets. Conventional economic wisdom says the economy can grow
only just so fast before it starts to overheat. The exact speed
limit for the economy varies from expert to expert _ some say 2
percent, others 2.5 percent, and a few radicals crawl out on a limb
and mention 3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But that debate isn't important now, because the economy is
clearly growing at a speed that puts it off the dial. First-quarter
gross domestic product grew by 4.1 percent. And that's just the
latest in a string of quarters all well above the speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   By now, according to the conventional wisdom, the economy ought
to be showing serious signs of an uptick in inflation. Wages should
be climbing in a steepening spiral. Prices for everything from raw
materials to capital equipment to consumer goods should be marching
higher day by day.
</P>
<P>
   But through the first third of the year, there were no signs of
those inflationary pressures. Yes, labor markets were tight, but
hourly earnings climbed just 0.2 percent in April.
</P>
<P>
   Aluminum producers continued to plan for lower prices; computer
makers, still struggling with the bottom-line consequences of
$1,000 PCs, worried about prices falling below $800; and consumer
companies were, by and large, cutting prices.
</P>
<P>
   With traditional economics at a loss to explain the persistence
of above-the-speed-limit growth and low inflation, more and more
economists are willing to give the New Paradigm a hearing.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on in the U.S. economy right now makes sense, this
theory holds, once you consider some of the consequences of the
profound changes in the U.S. economy in the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   What, for example, is the effect on domestic inflation of the
transformation from a manufacturing economy into a service-based
one? The New Paradigm answer: First, since imports of manufactured
goods make up a bigger slice of domestic consumption, excess global
industrial capacity reduces the inflationary effect of any U.S.
bottlenecks.
</P>
<P>
   If a U.S. manufacturer can't keep up with demand, a foreign
supplier probably can, so there should be no price hikes because of
scarcity.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the increasing percentage of U.S. goods coming from
overseas plays into the recent improvement in the distribution
infrastructure in the U.S.
</P>
<P>
   Just-in-time inventory, computerized stocking and delivery
systems, the Internet, superstores, and more have all worked to
reduce the costs of getting stuff to U.S. consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Third, productivity in service industries in the U.S. may
finally be starting to pick up after years of investment
information systems.
</P>
<P>
   In area after area _ the increased flow of pricing information
to consumers because of computer systems and the Internet, the new
global wage competition even in service industries, the increased
efficiency of financial markets _ the New Paradigm argues that
things are different now.
</P>
<P>
   In his May testimony to Congress, Alan Greenspan even
acknowledged that the New Paradigm might be onto something. But, in
retrospect, that was the high-water mark for the theory, at least
in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   The economic numbers in May were just troubling enough to swing
the balance at the Fed back toward the conventional wisdom. For
example, the National Association of Purchasing Management's
Purchasing Managers' Index came in at 55.2 for May _ way above
April's 52.8.
</P>
<P>
   New-home sales soared 9.2 percent in April _ total numbers were
just shy of November's record _ and the average price climbed 3.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Those numbers aren't infallible harbingers of inflation. The
NAPM index has jumped like this before without producing inflation
at the wholesale or consumer level. (Anything above 50 indicates
prices are climbing.)
</P>
<P>
   The surge in housing sales and prices is at least partially a
reaction to rising interest rates _ consumers jump to buy when they
fear mortgage rates are headed up.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the bond market was spooked: The yield on the
30-year Treasury bond hit 5.96 percent on June 2, up from the low
of 4.72 percent in October 1998.
</P>
<P>
   And that has put the Fed in a tough political position. If the
central bankers decide not to act after the bond market has clearly
signaled it sees signs of inflation, they risk losing part of their
hard-won credibility as inflation fighters.
</P>
<P>
   Worries that the Fed has gone soft would, perversely, send the
bond market lower and set interest rates above the levels that Fed
would prefer.
</P>
<P>
   A 25-basis-point hike this summer would, on the other hand,
demonstrate the Fed's toughness and reassure the markets. And such
a hike might even actually fend off inflation _ just in case the
conventional wisdom about the economy is right.
</P>
<P>
   So let's calculate the odds. On the side of an interest rate
hike: a need to protect Federal Reserve credibility, a desire to
calm the U.S. bond market, some worrisome statistics indicating
that inflation may be kicking up, and the conventional economic
wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Against the rate hike: the potentially correct _ but ultimately
untested _ theories of the New Paradigm.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't sound like much of a contest, does it? &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; (EDITOR'S NOTE: Contributing editor Jim Jubak is senior markets
editor at Microsoft's MoneyCentral (www.MoneyCentral.msn.com).) &LR;  &QL; 
 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _______ &QC;
</P>
