<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIGHT BROWN PATCH WITH GOOD CULTURE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By KATHY HUBER 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Q: What can I use on my St. Augustine lawn for brown
patch?
</P>
<P>
   A: Brown patch, ``Rhizoctonia solani,'' is a fungal disease that
mars many a lawn when day temperatures cool to the 75- 85-degree
range and night temperatures drop below 68. Rainfall encourages the
process.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms on warm-season grasses such as Bermuda grass or St.
Augustine include circular to irregular patches of light brown,
thinned grass. You'll notice a grayish ``smoke ring'' of wilted
grass at the edges of the infected area. Leaf sheaths become
rotted, and the blade will separate from the runner with a gentle
pull.
</P>
<P>
   The patches may enlarge to several yards in diameter. And as the
disease spreads, new green leaves may emerge in the center of the
patches.
</P>
<P>
   The best treatment for brown patch is good culture to lessen the
severity of the disease:
</P>
<P>
   _ Water only as needed and early in the day to allow the grass
to dry quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Overwatering can promote the fungal disease.
</P>
<P>
   _ Apply a slow-release or organic fertilizer in spring when the
grass greens and begins to grow. Apply a slow-release or organic
fertilizer in the fall to encourage good root growth over the
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Overfertilizing also can promote the disease.
</P>
<P>
   _ Improve the turfgrass root system with good drainage and
aeration to reduce damage caused by brown patch.
</P>
<P>
   _ Use bio-stimulants to boost the population of beneficial
organisms in the soil.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mow at the proper height _ about 2 1/2 inches for St.
Augustine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mow frequently, removing no more than a third of the blade
height.
</P>
<P>
   _ Leave clippings on the lawn to break down and replenish
nutrients. However, remove if there are large accumulations
resulting from infrequent mowing.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avoid thatch buildup. Fungicides destroy beneficial soil
organisms that would otherwise help eliminate thatch.
</P>
<P>
   Some gardeners use the following baking soda treatment to
discourage brown patch:
</P>
<P>
   Mix 4 teaspoons baking soda per gallon of water. Add 1 teaspoon
liquid soap or vegetable oil to the mixture. Spray on the foliage
only _ avoid soil contact as much as possible. Baking soda is made
of sodium and bicarbonate, both necessary soil elements, but only
in small amounts.
</P>
<P>
   There are several fungicides that target brown patch; ask your
nurseryman for suggestions. And please avoid polluting runoff if
you do use a fungicide.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What hardy flowers can I plant for winter in shady and
filtered light areas? Pansies got leggy last year.
</P>
<P>
   Asian jasmine was planted in a 15-foot by 20-foot area early
this spring. It is spreading nicely but has not gotten to the thick
mat stage. When and what do I feed it?
</P>
<P>
   A: My favorite cool-season flower is ``Primula obconica,'' a
primrose available in subdued shades of blue, rose, lavender and
white. It actually is a short-lived perennial here. Those I planted
last fall bloomed until it got hot. The annual, jewel-toned
primroses, ``P. polyantha,'' are usually more readily available.
</P>
<P>
   You could use sweet alyssum with either of these or the
low-growing but brilliantly colored edging lobelia.
</P>
<P>
   I have enjoyed dianthus in partial shade. It likes an organic
soil and needs good drainage.
</P>
<P>
   Cyclamen could be added in late fall. Ask your nurseryman for
those appropriate for the garden. I like those in the `Laser'
series.
</P>
<P>
   Plant high. A sandy loam is ideal, and good drainage is a must.
While the plants like a soil on the moist side, avoid overwatering.
Remove spent blooms and foliage. Sweet alyssum and maidenhair ferns
are good garden companions.
</P>
<P>
   It takes awhile for the jasmine to thicken. It is most vigorous
spring into summer, so I would apply a water-soluble, balanced
formula just before growth really takes off and perhaps again in
May. However, if it is growing well, I would not overfertilize.
</P>
<P>
   Moisture during dry periods will help. You can use an organic
mulch to cover any bare spots and encourage good soil health.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Mail garden questions to Kathy Huber, garden editor, Houston
Chronicle, P.O. Box 4260, Houston, Texas 77210. The bulk of mail
prevents individual replies to each unpublished letter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
