<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-21 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST FRONTIER ISN'T THE SAME PLACE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By HARRY SHATTUCK 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Just back from a cruise vacation in Alaska, I'm
thumbing through scrapbooks and rekindling fond memories.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a photograph of an all-but-deserted main street _ the
only real street _ in Skagway, once the center of Klondike
gold-rush fever but with a permanent population now of only about
900.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the legendary Red Dog Saloon in the heart of Juneau, the
unlikeliest of state capitals with a glacier in its back yard and
no accessibility by road
</P>
<P>
   And if ever the cliche ``quaint'' is appropriate, it applies to
Ketchikan's Creek Street, seen as essentially a walking path beside
a creek in which thousands of salmon swim unbothered.
</P>
<P>
   America's ``Last Frontier,'' Alaska is dubbed. My scrapbooks
attest to that billing.
</P>
<P>
   Only one problem: The scrapbooks are 14 years old. I've dusted
off their covers to make certain that my mind isn't playing tricks.
</P>
<P>
   With only a sprinkling of cruise ships plying the waters of
southeast Alaska's Inside Passage in 1985, those of us arriving on
Cunard's Sagafjord were as much a novelty to the residents of
Skagway, Juneau and Ketchikan as they _ and their peaceful
communities _ were to us. Natives were thrilled at the chance to
show off their authentic treasures. They cared more about our
appreciative smiles than the greenbacks in our wallets.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned four years ago on a work assignment, I found
considerable change, inevitable given the fast-developing cruise
market. Even the Red Dog Saloon had moved closer to the dock so
that tourists could make it a convenient first _ and last _ stop in
Juneau.
</P>
<P>
   Still, that experience didn't prepare me for what I discovered
on this vacation.
</P>
<P>
   A combined 3,700 passengers from Celebrity's Galaxy and Mercury
cruise ships _ more than four times the town's population _
literally took over tiny Skagway, jamming its shops and sidewalks
and giving it more of a theme-park personality than that of a
frontier village.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some days are even busier,'' said one storekeeper.
</P>
<P>
   A midday departure on the scenic White Pass &AMP; Yukon rail route
was in such demand that 28 passenger cars were required,
necessitating two trains each propelled by three diesel engines.
</P>
<P>
   The first shops passengers now encounter _ if you don't count
the discount barns newly erected beside the dock _ are Starbucks
and Little Switzerland, an outlet specializing in jewelry, crystal
and fragrances, and familiar to anyone who has sailed in the
Caribbean.
</P>
<P>
   Many other establishments are managed by seasonal residents only
to capitalize on the tourist trade and primed to return to the
``Lower 48'' when the Alaska cruise calendar ends this week.
</P>
<P>
   Ketchikan, a town of 14,000 residents invaded by four ships with
a combined 8,000 passengers on the day of my visit, brought more
surprises. Creek Street remains an attractive lure. So does the
town's collection of beautiful totem poles. But they are now
surrounded by shops that include Diamonds International, Tanzanite
International, Colombian Emeralds International and Princess World
Jewelers. Indeed, 14 of 17 businesses listed in the Galaxy's
``Recommended Shopping'' guide specialize in some sort of glitter.
</P>
<P>
   Is this really the Last Frontier? Or was I strolling the streets
of towns on many Caribbean islands whose distinct individual
attributes too often become lost amid a frenzied competition to
capture the biggest share of a traveler's spending dollar _ even if
it means hanging out shingles that say as much about the native
culture as Kmart and Wal-Mart reveal about Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I'm jaded. I've long resented people who possess a
``Nothing's as good as it used to be'' attitude; but am I also
living too much in the past? Most passengers from the Galaxy
flocked into as many jewelry stores and T-shirt shops as time
permitted. I heard few complaints. More than 30 cruise ships now
traverse the Inside Passage each summer, and seldom does one depart
without a capacity load.
</P>
<P>
   These cruises have introduced Skagway, Ketchikan and Juneau to
millions of travelers who likely would never visit otherwise. John
Mazor, president of the Juneau Convention and Visitors Bureau,
recently told the New York Times that passenger arrivals this year
in his city of 30,000 residents will total about 590,000, quadruple
the number at the start of the decade. This accounts for most of
the estimated $75 million annually that Juneau businesses earn from
tourist expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   An Alaska cruise remains rewarding, too, especially if your ship
visits Glacier Bay National Park _ where a strict permit system
curbs mass visitation _ or Prince William Sound, spectacular
retreats far removed from the crowded ports.
</P>
<P>
   The ``real Alaska'' also remains on vivid display during scores
of optional shore excursions and pre- and post-cruise land tours.
Touch down on a remote glacier by helicopter. Visit a bald eagle
preserve. Spy for whales and bears. Fish for salmon (but not on
Creek Street, at least not yet).
</P>
<P>
   Here, too, however, are signs of the times. Dollar signs. Some
popular excursions now cost $200 or more per person. And these are
not included in the basic cruise fare.
</P>
<P>
   Also, while helicopter tours are embraced by tourists, their
impact on the environment is a continuing concern. According to The
New York Times, the U.S. Forest Service limited landings on the
Juneau Ice Field to 400 when it first issued a permit in 1984. Now,
four helicopter companies are allowed a total of 19,039 landings
per year, and have petitioned for twice that. The Forest Service is
studying the effects these tours have on wildlife and noise
pollution.
</P>
<P>
   As many Caribbean islands already have learned, the huge
economic benefits of mass cruise tourism must be weighed against
the toll taken on the local citizenry, culture and natural
environment.
</P>
<P>
   If travel along the Inside Passage continues to escalate, folks
in southeast Alaska may have to ask themselves some tough
questions. Otherwise, how sad if the frontier spirit is relegated
to photographs in a scrapbook.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
