<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-EDUCATION-CRUISES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDUCATIONAL CRUISES LET GUESTS WRAP MINDS AROUND THE WORLD _ AT
ECONOMY PRICES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SYD KEARNEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jules Verne's Phileas Fogg made literary history when he
traveled ``around the world in 80 days'' in 1873.
</P>
<P>
   A century later, we can make the journey in a much shorter time.
But why try? The essence of travel involves much more than getting
from Point A to Point B, or, in the case of world travel, from
Point A to Point Z.
</P>
<P>
   We are more of the mind of Lord Chesterfield, the English
statesman, who wrote, ``Those who travel heedlessly from place to
place, observing only their distance from each other, and attending
only to their accommodation at the inn at night, set out fools, and
will certainly return so.''
</P>
<P>
   Chesterfield's words, written in 1747, could serve as a motto
for World Cruise Co., a new enterprise specializing in
circumnavigations of the world. Its itineraries, which will begin
in November, focus on intriguing ports of call, cultural
interaction and educational enrichment.
</P>
<P>
   Company founder Sam Blyth likens his vessel to a floating
university. Crew members are explorers and teachers, and the staff
is complemented by a team of specialists who will share their
expertise on subjects ranging from botany to archaeology.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no division between staff and lecturers and guests,''
explains Blyth, a Canadian who also founded Marine Expeditions.
``Travelers get to know everyone on the ship.''
</P>
<P>
   And while several cruise lines boast around-the-world
itineraries, World Cruise Co. also distinguishes itself by its
pricing: Fares generally will be one-half to two-thirds those of
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started World Cruise Co. because we wanted to provide the
best educational cruise programs at an economical price,'' Blyth
says.
</P>
<P>
   This philosophy has served Blyth's Marine Expeditions well.
Since its founding in 1993, the company has become the leader in
travel to Antarctica, taking about 7,000 passengers a year to the
ends of the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   World Cruise Co.'s lone vessel isn't new: The 20,000-ton Ocean
Explorer I made its debut in 1944 as a World War II troop ship. In
the interim, it has been known by several names, most notably the
Emerald Seas during years of popular twice-weekly sailings from
Miami to the Bahamas. The ship served as a floating hotel during
the 1998 World Exposition in Lisbon, Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   It has been completely refurbished for these long-distance
voyages and boasts 385 staterooms (with an average size of 240
square feet, larger than on most ships), a dining room for
open-seating meals, a boutique, a hair salon, a fitness center,
four lounges, three bars, a heated outdoor pool, a 150-seat cinema
and a large library with computers for Internet access.
</P>
<P>
   One of the company's more ambitious programs is its ``Year at
Sea,'' which will comprise 361 days, seven continents, 55 countries
and 103 ports. Prices start at $35,947, or just under $100 a day,
including air fare from New York.
</P>
<P>
   This year-round adventure, which will include visits to
Antarctica and the Arctic, will set sail Nov. 20 from Athens,
Greece. Other trip highlights include Rio de Janeiro, Brazil; Bora
Bora; Australia's Great Barrier Reef; the Suez and Panama canals;
Ho Chi Min City, Vietnam; Reykjavik, Iceland; and Alaska's Inside
Passage.
</P>
<P>
   A unique feature of the ``Year at Sea'' is the scheduled
vacation from your vacation. Midway through the year, passengers
will be able to fly home (or as close as New York City) free from
Trinidad, then rejoin the ship two weeks later in Lima, Peru.
</P>
<P>
   The line also offers several cabins for cruisers' friends and
family members, who will get low rates for short-term stays aboard
ship.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers can choose from more than 450 shore excursions during
the year, many priced as low as $30.
</P>
<P>
   For adventurers who don't have a year to spare, the line's
inaugural season features three segments of the ``Year at Sea''
with diverse around-the-world itineraries.
</P>
<P>
   The first is ``Last Frontiers,'' a 127-day cruise that will call
on 22 countries and Antarctica. Departing with the year-round
cruisers Nov. 20 from Athens, passengers will celebrate New Year's
Day in Chile before heading to the game parks of Africa. Prices
start at $12,995.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost Worlds,'' a 116-day tour departing Athens on March 26,
will explore the mysteries of past civilizations, including those
of Peru, Vietnam, Egypt, Israel and Easter Island.
</P>
<P>
   Departing Athens on July 20, the 118-day ``Northern Exposures''
will take passengers to destinations such as Norway, Russia, India
and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
   Prices for these cruises start at $11,890.
</P>
<P>
   (By comparison, brochure prices for the Crystal Symphony's
104-day world cruise in early 2000 start at $39,660 and peak at
$180,840 for the exclusive Crystal Penthouse; prices for a 96-day
voyage to 38 ports beginning in January aboard Holland America's
new Rotterdam range from $27,135 to $138,225; and fares for a
104-day sailing to 37 ports starting that month aboard Cunard's QE2
start at $27,020.)
</P>
<P>
   Solo cruisers accustomed to paying high single supplements will
appreciate the 40 Ocean Explorer I cabins set aside just for them.
</P>
<P>
   One factor to keep in mind: Like the shore excursions, port
charges and gratuities are not included in the base fares and can
add significantly to the cost of the long cruises.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge University graduate Blyth is especially proud of his
new line's educational programs.
</P>
<P>
   Pointing to lectures on topics ranging from investing to wine
tasting, Blyth says, ``At any hour, there will be about five
activities from which to choose. We'll have 30 full-time faculty
aboard.''
</P>
<P>
   Blyth says he sails on his Marine Expedition ships ``a couple of
times each year'' but spends most of his time traveling around
North America and visiting with prospective and past cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Educating the traveler is a big factor in our success,'' Blyth
says. ``These people effectively are living with us for three or
four months, so it is important that they know what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   Talking with clients also gives Blyth ideas for future projects,
such as an upcoming Pole-to-Pole World Expedition. This 110-day
itinerary with Marine Expeditions will depart New York by air March
2. Participants will board the 128-passenger Marine Discovery in
Ushuaia, Argentina, often called the End of the World.
</P>
<P>
   After stops in Antarctica, the expedition will sail on to
Australia's Macquarie Islands, Papua New Guinea, the Seychilles,
Kenya and the Suez Canal. Other ports of call will put cruisers in
Greece, Portugal, Ireland and Iceland. The final port will be
Sondre Stromfjord in Greenland.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of this trip starts at $13,775, including air fare from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXXXXX &QL; 
 &QL; 
To request a free brochure or for more information about World
Cruise Company itineraries, visit a travel agent; call
888-558-0887; or access www.worldcruiseco.com on the Internet. For
information about Marine Expeditions, call 800-263-9147; or access
www.marineex.com. A travel agent also can advise about several
other world cruises planned during the next year.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
