<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0182 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-AIRLINES-ONLINE-2TAKE     09-21 1225
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-ONLINE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIRLINES' NET OFFERINGS HAVE OPENED UP SKIES TO EVERYDAY TRAVELER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ A recent air fare sale by major airlines came with an
Internet-inspired twist.
</P>
<P>
   The industry-wide sale in early August began the way such sales
always do. One carrier launches an across-the-board markdown, and
others, saying they must compete, follow. In this case, Northwest
Airlines announced 25 percent discounts and other carriers matched.
</P>
<P>
   However, Delta Air Lines jumped in with something new: Buy
tickets through its Web site and get an extra discount of up to 10
percent. As with the traditional discounts, other airlines followed
suit.
</P>
<P>
   After spending the past few years getting its Internet legs, the
industry is stepping up efforts to get travelers to buy tickets
from airline-owned Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines are offering a variety of promotions, including
discounts or extra frequent flier miles, for booking on their Web
sites. Last-minute deals are hawked through the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Many sites sell vacation packages or let travelers make hotel
and car reservations. A few airlines even let passengers buy
tickets on other airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Sites also are being tapped as customer service tools.
Itineraries, seating charts and frequent flier information may be
available, depending on the carrier.
</P>
<P>
   In the future, customers can expect faster and easier use of the
sites. Carriers are likely to expand offerings, allowing users to
buy event tickets or make restaurant reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've opened the door a little bit and realized, oh my God,
there's a huge world out there. There's so much to do,'' said
Michael Cavanaugh, who oversees distribution and planning for
United Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines embrace the Internet because sales through their sites
cost them less than those by travel agents, who still handle the
bulk of ticket transactions.
</P>
<P>
   The electronic highway also gives carriers new ways to sell
seats that otherwise might go empty.
</P>
<P>
   There has been some debate, though, about whether, in the early
stage, the Internet actually hurts carriers' revenues. It remains
an open question.
</P>
<P>
   However, airlines aren't the only ones online. With virtual
travel agents such as Travelocity (www.travelocity.com) or
Microsoft's Expedia (www.expedia.msn.com) apparently here to stay,
airlines are investing in or forming partnerships with them.
</P>
<P>
   Among the early players on the electronic commerce scene,
airlines began putting up Web sites in late 1994 and 1995. However,
for the most part, major carriers didn't let travelers buy tickets
online until 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jupiter Communications, a New York-based Internet research
company, &UR;  &LR; projects online consumers this year will spend more than
$3.2 billion on airline reservations, with the number hitting $9.8
billion by 2003.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. airlines now collect an average of 3 to 5 percent of total
revenues from online channels, with the lion's share coming from
their Web sites, according to a recent Salomon Smith Barney report.
</P>
<P>
   It's the same for bookings: Airlines are logging an average of 3
to 5 percent of bookings from the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers are rising fast. Revenues and bookings from airline
sites are shooting up 200 to 500 percent year-over-year, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's growing faster than we were able to predict,'' said John
Samuel, vice president of interactive marketing for American
Airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In its budget this year, American projected $320 million in
gross revenues would come through bookings on AA.com. It's on track
to hit $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   Eagan, Minn.-based Northwest Airlines put up its site at the end
of 1995, adding a booking component in early 1997. The carrier did
$80 million in sales through nwa.com last year, and expects to
reach nearly $200 million for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty big jump,'' said Al Lenza, Northwest's vice
president of distribution. ``We certainly didn't expect it to grow
this fast, to a $200 million channel in 2 1/2 years.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's sales through continental.com, the Web site of
Houston-based Continental Airlines, hit the $100 million mark Sept.
9, showing a 186 percent year-to-date increase over 1998's $35
million.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet appeals to airlines for a variety of reasons. It
allows them to lower costs, add sales and reach customers in new
ways.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; For purchases through the carriers' sites, airlines don't pay
travel agent commissions or fees charged by computer reservations
systems used by agents, who still handle as much as 75 to 80
percent of tickets.
</P>
<P>
   With sales made through virtual travel agents, carriers pay
cheaper commissions but still pay reservations system fees.
</P>
<P>
   Most carriers are saving $20 to $40 per ticket compared with
non-online sales, the Salomon Smith Barney report said. As time
goes on, the savings could jump another $15 or so per ticket, the
report concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Those buying online also are more likely to get electronic, or
paperless, tickets, which cost carriers less.
</P>
<P>
   Airlines also are tapping their Web sites to boost sales with
special Internet deals. Each carrier has its own program,but
generally customers register to be notified about the Internet
deals by e-mail, or the airline announces them on its own site.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers generally must take the trips within days, but a few
carriers have stretched the windows. Passengers are restricted on
when they can travel.
</P>
<P>
   Continental e-mails domestic specials on Wednesdays. Takers must
leave that Saturday and return Monday or Tuesday. A recent offer:
Houston-Indianapolis, $139 round trip.
</P>
<P>
   The e-mail specials spur people to fly who otherwise wouldn't
have, said Jim Young, Continental's director of distribution
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts, though, recently have questioned whether the
Internet has hurt revenues.
</P>
<P>
   The theory goes that since consumers have information available
directly to them, they can make better decisions about what they
will pay. There is no travel agent or airline reservations employee
to filter details.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has almost overnight downloaded near-perfect
information to the end users,'' said PaineWebber airline analyst
Sam Buttrick. ``Their decisions aren't going to be to spend more,
typically.''
</P>
<P>
   He believes the Internet is a modest negative to the industry's
bottom linehbut hopes that within five years cost savings will
outweigh harm and it will switch to a modest positive.
</P>
<P>
   The airlines counter that consumers already can find the best
fares through travel agents or the airlines.
</P>
<P>
   A good agent can save travelers a lot more money than a Web
site, maintains Colorado-based aviation consultant Michael Boyd.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the Internet is here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any airline has a choice except to
participate,'' said Alan Bender, a professor of aeronautical
science at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Florida.
``Consumers expect there to be a wealth of information on Web
sites.''
</P>
<P>
   And, if airlines don't offer their wares online, virtual travel
agents gladly would take the business.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're growing this channel aggressively because that's where
the customers are going,'' said William Reeves, general manager of
electronic commerce for Atlanta-based Delta. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1508EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0181 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0184 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-AIRLINES-ONLINE-2TAKE     09-21 1285
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-ONLINE-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>


</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
HOUSTON: Atlanta-based Delta..
<TEXT>
<P>
   Airlines keep trying new ways to get passengers to their sites.
Even if lookers don't book immediately, carriers hope they will get
used to the sites and do so eventually.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Delta tried a $2-per-round-trip surcharge for
tickets not booked through its Web site. Facing strong negative
reaction, the airline dropped it.
</P>
<P>
   Other carriers give extra frequent flier points for booking
through their Web sites and offer discounts aimed at specific
markets or regions. Tempe, Ariz.-based America West, for example,
recently offered a discount for booking trips at its site to and
from a half-dozen Texas cities. Continental matched the deal.
</P>
<P>
   While airlines continue to offer narrow promotions, travelers
can expect to see more system-wide markdowns like the one Delta
initiated.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers also are constantly tinkering with their sites. Some
have made two, three or four major revisions. They aim for sites
that are easier and quicker to navigate, allowing passengers to
book travel with as few clicks as possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The functionality and the technology is just now getting to
where it's customer-friendly,'' Reeves said. ``I would say we're
early in the cycle, and there's a lot coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers want more information without having to punch in
passwords, Continental's Young said. The airline responded by
moving the ability to check schedules up front, out from behind the
site's firewall.
</P>
<P>
   Continental, American and Dallas-based Southwest Airlines, like
others, also are moving their frequent flier programs online.
</P>
<P>
   As of this month, Southwest's Rapid Rewards members can enter a
password-protected area of the low-fare carrier's site to review
and update account information.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've certainly heard loud and clear our customers want more
access and better access to their frequent flier information,''
said Kevin Krone, director of marketing automation for Southwest.
``We think, we hope, when they're checking their account balance,
if they have a trip to purchase, they'll go ahead and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   When members of American's frequent flier program log on to
personalized home pages, mileage totals appear automatically.
Members soon will be able to book flights online earned with
frequent flier points.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Continental's OnePass also can check account totals,
and Young said the carrier is looking into offering the ability to
book travel awarded through the program.
</P>
<P>
   Among the latest buzzwords is personalization: Carriers want to
treat customers as individuals and market to them that way.
</P>
<P>
   At American, for example, frequent fliers can choose up to 10
cities or airports, and when they log on to their home pages, they
get messages about specials for those cities.
</P>
<P>
   Delta customers can get weekly e-mail specials for every market
or choose up to five departure cities.
</P>
<P>
   Carriers' targeted marketing efforts are just getting off the
ground, and airlines are likely to expand into tailoring e-mails by
using information gleaned from buying patterns of online customers.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the initial Internet focus has been on reducing
distribution costs, but American's Samuel predicts that, in three
to five years, marketing will be the dominant topic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in the early stages of a real change in how marketing is
done for the airlines,'' Samuel said. The Internet ``facilitates
less-homogeneous marketing, and that is a big deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Carriers also are expanding their sites' offerings to allow
travelers to obtain details on flight itineraries or meal
selections; make hotel and car reservations; or get airport maps.  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; At the site for Elk Grove, Ill.-based United, travelers
searching for flights can select airlines other than United and
book tickets on them.
</P>
<P>
   United, figuring people coming to its site would be predisposed
toward United, decided to offer as a service the ability to book on
other carriers if it couldn't meet someone's needs, Cavanaugh said.
He said United also thought it important to provide a comparison of
fares.
</P>
<P>
   Some 20 -30 percent of those booking through United's site
choose competitors, he said, a statistic United is satisfied with.
</P>
<P>
   Forrest Harding, a marketing professor at California State
University, Long Beach, envisions that airline sites eventually
could offer everything from tickets to Broadway shows or sporting
events, to restaurant reviews and reservations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's sell everything we can sell since we've already got the
customer in the store,'' said Harding, an airline consultant.
``What the airlines are going to become is travel merchandisers.''
</P>
<P>
   The airlines share the Internet with virtual travel agents.
Carriers view online agents as competition, models and partners. As
in the physical world, they realize some travelers aren't loyal to
brands and want easy comparison shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``Different customers have different needs and, therefore, they
go to the channel that best suits these needs,'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Turley of League City goes to Southwest's site for business
and personal trips.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because it's convenient, I go with Southwest on the
Internet,'' he said. ``I'm on the Net every day, so it's easier for
me to do than to pick up the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Booking through Southwest's site, he said, also gets him extra
frequent flier credits, ``a major bonus'' for someone who flies two
or three times a week.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie King, travel coordinator for Houston general
contractor US Builders, typically books four or five trips a week
via the Internet. Seventy-five percent are booked through
Continental's site because, she said, the employees like flying on
the airline.
</P>
<P>
   She prefers the Internet over a travel agent, which the office
previously used. It takes her less time and it is easier for her to
find the flights she wants, King said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to deal with anybody else,'' she said, adding
that she believes she's getting better deals.
</P>
<P>
   For Jason Presley of Houston, who typically buys tickets three
or four times a year, Travelocity makes more sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Travelocity gives me the option of seeing the best price,'' he
said. ``That way, I don't have to go to Southwest's site, to
Continental's site, to American's site.''
</P>
<P>
   In its May report, Jupiter Communications concluded that
airlines, for the most part, lag online travel agencies in
investing in ``functionality, services and marketing.''
</P>
<P>
   Airlines look to online agencies for ideas on how to improve
their Web sites, said Melissa Shore, a digital commerce analyst at
Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that airlines have a lot of potential to drive a
lot of traffic to their space. Brand is very important,'' she said.
``We are somewhat hesitant to say that they're performing as well
as they could have.''
</P>
<P>
   One way for carriers to see what would-be competitors are doing
is to join them.
</P>
<P>
   United and Internet retailer Buy.com recently announced they
will jointly create an online travel store to be called
BuyTravel.com.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Rosenbluth International, a business travel
management company, acquired Biztravel.com, a full-service business
travel agency. In the deal, Continental bought a minority stake.
</P>
<P>
   ``It gives us access to technology. It allows us to essentially
get in at the developer level,'' said Young of Continental. ``It's
a place we can go to understand where the technology is going.''
</P>
<P>
   Northwest's Lenza said carriers don't want to be left out.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to kind of cover your bases,'' he said. ``Nobody
knows who is going to be the winners and losers.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
