<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0187 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-CLINTON-UN-0922-COX     09-21 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-0922-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON DEFENDS ACTIONS IN KOSOVO, URGES MORE U.N. ACTION TO
AVERT MASS KILLINGS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton defended the U.S.-led NATO air
campaign to end repression in Kosovo Tuesday, responding to
criticism that the action lacked the backing of the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   In his annual address to the U.N. General Assembly in New York,
Clinton said the NATO air strikes were consistent with ``several''
U.N. Security Council resolutions condemning Serb atrocities in
Yugoslavia's Kosovo province.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to act would have undermined U.N. principles, said
Clinton. He then took a swipe at his U.N. critics, suggesting that
theory is no substitute for action.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the real world,'' Clinton said, ``principles often collide,
and tough choices must be made.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's remarks came a day after U.N. Secretary General
Kofi Annan raised concerns over the NATO action in his own opening
address to the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   NATO acted without a U.N. mandate in its 78-day air war against
Yugoslavia last spring. Of the five permanent U.N. Security Council
members, two _ Russia and China _ were opposed to NATO air strikes
against Serb-led Yugoslav troops and paramilitary gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Presuming that those countries would have used their votes to
block a U.N. mandate for the mission, NATO opted to act alone
rather than risk a rebuff at the Security Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``Is there not a danger of such interventions undermining the
imperfect, yet resilient, security system created after the Second
World War,'' Annan said on Monday, ``and of setting dangerous
precedents for future interventions without a clear criterion to
decide who might invoke these precedents and in what
circumstances?''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton responded that those risks were outweighed by the risks
of failing to act in Kosovo, where the majority ethnic Albanian
population was under attack by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we chosen to do nothing in the face of this brutality, I
do not believe we would have strengthened the United Nations,''
said Clinton, addressing the second day of the General Assembly _
and heads of state from most of the U.N.'s 188 member nations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead,'' said Clinton, ``we would have risked discrediting
everything it stands for.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also responded to Annan's long-standing criticism that
the international community _ and chiefly the United States _ did
little to stop the massacre of an estimated 800,000 civilians in
Rwanda in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Without singling out the United States, Annan referenced the
tragedy, saying ``the genocide in Rwanda will define for our
generation the consequences of inaction in the face of mass
murder.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also frequently cites Rwanda as a tragic example of
inaction. Tuesday, though, he said there were limits to what the
United States can do to counter violence in a world where more than
two dozen ethnic or regional conflicts continue to afflict
civilians and combatants alike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that some are troubled that the United States and
others cannot respond to every humanitarian catastrophe in the
world,'' Clinton said. ``We cannot do everything everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   And Clinton, who was criticized in some quarters for not acting
sooner than he did to end fighting in Bosnia, also cautioned
against lending false hope to embattled people.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is easy to say, 'Never again,' but much harder to make it
so,'' Clinton said, as the chief architects of his Balkans policy _
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, National Security Adviser
Samuel Berger, and U.N. Ambassador Richard Holbrooke _ looked on
from the cavernous General Assembly chamber at U.N. headquarters in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promising too much,'' Clinton said, ``can be as cruel as
caring too little.''
</P>
<P>
   With the U.N.'s latest peacekeeping operation _ the 50th such
mission in U.N. history _ entering its third day in East Timor,
Indonesia, the contentious themes of when and under what
circumstances the U.N. should support such missions dominated
Clinton's speech.
</P>
<P>
   He also called for increased efforts to address some of the
underlying factors in ethnic and regional conflict, challenging the
international community to ``wage an unrelenting battle,'' against
world poverty and its attendant ills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are still squandering the potential of far too many,'' said
Clinton, adding that ``1.3 billion people still live on less than a
dollar a day. More than half the population of many countries have
no access to safe water. A person in South Asia is 700 times less
likely to use the Internet as someone in the United States. And 40
million people a year still die of hunger, almost as many as the
total number killed in World War II.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton, ``We must refuse to accept a future in which one
part of humanity lives on the cutting edge of a new economy while
the other lives at the knife-edge of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's prescription, he said, would combine increased global
trade with aid increasingly targeting the world's poorest citizens
through micro-loans, education funding and assistance for mothers
and children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who has asked Congress for $100 million for AIDS
prevention, counseling and care in Africa next year, said he plans
to convene a White House conference grouping public health experts,
pharmaceutical executives, members of Congress and others to find
ways to step up the provision of vaccines to developing countries
still suffering from epidemics of malaria, tuberculosis, pneumonia
and other diseases all but banished from the industrialized world.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
