<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0183 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0190 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t BC-AIRLINES-ONLINE-TIPS-     09-21 0446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINES-ONLINE-TIPS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING THE MOST FROM THE INTERNET: BETTER SHOP AROUND 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LAURA GOLDBERG 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ If you're looking for the best air fare deals, you
might not find them on the Internet. Then again, you might.
</P>
<P>
   The key to getting the cheapest fares, experts say, is not to
lock yourself into one way of doing things, be it an airline's Web
site, a reservation call center, a flesh-and-blood travel agent or
an online agent.
</P>
<P>
   Getting good deals online can require time to comparison-shop
and research, say Laurie Berger, editor of Consumer Reports Travel
Letter, and Tom Parsons, editor of the travel Web site
Bestfares.com.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said travelers won't necessarily find cheaper fares
online unless they're booking last-minute deals offered by
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   In the September issue of the Travel Letter, she wrote a column
about Internet discounts headlined, ``What's the big deal?''
</P>
<P>
   Many online deals, she wrote, are markdowns off rates few ever
pay, and often don't stack up to the prices obtained by shopping
around.
</P>
<P>
   Pay attention to restrictions and consider if an online
transaction is worth the hassle, she wrote.
</P>
<P>
   To see if a Web-only fare is real, comparison-shop. She cited
Microsoft Expedia's Fare Compare, which she said charts the lowest
prices for any given itinerary.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers should go online, she said, because airlines are
experimenting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to get the best deal is to really shop around,''
she said. ``Ask airlines directly. Ask travel agents. Look online.
Check around.''
</P>
<P>
   Parsons agreed, saying the Internet isn't the 100 percent
answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't solely depend on the Internet and you can't solely
depend on a travel agent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Travelers should be aware that many booking search engines will
often search first or direct flights, which can be more expensive,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Before being lured by free bonus points for booking on an
airline Web site, consider whether it's worth it, he said.
Researching online takes time initially, until you get familiar
with sites and services and how they work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what I like; the Internet can inform you at your pace,
on your time,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   However, he cautioned, don't lock yourself into one site. Others
are constantly adding new benefits and features.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, Parsons points out his site posts continuous
lists of ``snooze, you lose deals'' that detail temporary fare
breaks offered by one or more airlines on specific routes.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, he said: ``If you see a stealin' deal, take it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1514EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0184 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 15:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0192 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-CLINTON-UN-0922-COX     09-21 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-UN-0922-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CLINTON DEFENDS ACTIONS IN KOSOVO, URGES MORE U.N. ACTION TO
AVERT MASS KILLINGS
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
