remarks that sought to rekindle the ``carpetbagger'' issue
shadowing the first lady's exploratory Senate bid. ``You don't go
on vacation during Thanksgiving. You go home. Are they going to
spend Thanksgiving in Washington or New York?''
</P>
<P>
   Luntz called the Clintons' choice ``the great indicator'' of
whether Mrs. Clinton will formally announce her candidacy to
succeed retiring Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's running, they will spend Thanksgiving in their new
home in New York,'' Luntz said. ``If she's not running, they'll
spend it here (in Washington).''
</P>
<P>
   The president and Mrs. Clinton signed a contract Sept. 2 to buy
the $1.7 million, five-bedroom house in Chappaqua, a Westchester
County suburb of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Luntz's remarks, Marsha Berry, the first lady's
press secretary, said the first family will again spend
Thanksgiving at Camp David, the presidential retreat in Maryland's
Catoctin Mountains about 60 miles northwest of the nation's
capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``They won't close on the house until Nov. 1,'' Berry said.
``There's a lot of work that needs to be done to get a house ready
for a president. They're looking forward to moving in as soon as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton will be overseas for almost two weeks before
Thanksgiving, leaving for Israel and Jordan several days after
closing on the couple's new home, and then joining the president
for a trip to Bulgaria, Greece, Turkey, and Italy. They will return
to Washington on Nov. 24, the day before Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   The Clintons traditionally have gathered with family members at
the Camp David retreat for the Thanksgiving weekend.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Luntz, who helped mastermind Giuliani's re-election drive in
1997, declined to say whether he was working with Giuliani's
exploratory Senate campaign in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The latest public opinion survey in New York, the Quinnipiac
College Poll completed Sept. 13, showed the Clintons' purchase of
the Chappaqua house has only slightly eased New Yorkers' concerns
about Mrs. Clinton's outsider status.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed 49 percent of the New Yorkers surveyed said it
bothered them that Mrs. Clinton was ``not currently a resident'' of
the Empire State. A similar Quinnipiac poll completed July 29 found
52 percent of those questioned said they were bothered.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and Giuliani remain in a statistical dead heat among
registered voters, according to the survey. Clinton led Giuliani,
45 percent to 44 percent in a survey of 911 registered voters that
had a margin of error of 3.3 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   (Stewart M. Powell can be reached at 202-298-6920 and via
E-mail: stewart(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
