<HEADLINE>
DISNEY'S `E TICKET' GOOD FOR LOTS OF WHEEEE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGERS CADENHEAD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What is the origin of the term ``E-ticket ride''?
</P>
<P>
   _ B.D., Arlington, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The term, used to describe something thrilling, originally
referred to a ticket used at Disney theme parks.
</P>
<P>
   Disneyland, Disney World and some of the company's other parks
sold ticket books with five sets of tickets, each marked with a
letter: A, B, C, D or E. The letter noted which rides the ticket
could be used for.
</P>
<P>
   E-ticket rides were the most popular attractions, including
Space Mountain, the Matterhorn, Pirates of the Caribbean, and the
Haunted Mansion. Today, Disney parks sometimes sell E-ride tickets
that allow several thousand guests to stay for three hours after
the normal closing time to ride popular attractions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Are the sports announcers Bob and Mike Golic related?
</P>
<P>
   _ J.K.K., Azle, Texas
</P>
<P>
   A: The Golics are brothers, and they both have worked as sports
broadcasters after playing for the NFL and Notre Dame.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Golic, 36, hosts the ``ESPN Morning Show'' for ESPN Radio
and has been an NFL reporter for ESPN since 1995. He played
defensive tackle for the Houston Oilers, Philadelphia Eagles and
Miami Dolphins during a nine-year NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Golic, 41, is a former Prime Sports Radio host, sports
broadcaster and actor who was a cast member of ``Saved by the Bell:
The College Years.'' The defensive lineman played 14 years for the
Oakland Raiders, Cleveland Browns and New England Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   There's also a third brother who played for the Fighting Irish:
Greg Golic.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who used the Meredith Wilson song, ``May the Good Lord Bless
and Keep You,'' as the closing song each week on a radio or TV
show?
</P>
<P>
   _ C.P., via the Internet
</P>
<P>
   A: That song closed each episode of ``The Big Show,'' a radio
variety show hosted by Tallulah Bankhead that aired from 1950 to
1952.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson handled the music for the NBC program, which often
starred Fred Allen, Eddie Cantor, Groucho Marx and Jimmy Durante.
</P>
<P>
   (Rogers Cadenhead writes a trivia column for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. He can be reached at the Star-Telegram, Box 1870,
Fort Worth, Texas 76101; or by E-mail at trivia(at)prefect.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
