<SLUG> BC-COOKING-RADISHES-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RECONSIDERING THE RADISH: NEW WAYS TO TAME ITS BITE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mich., Fla.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By JACK BISHOP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Radishes have been cultivated for so long that they actually
predate written history. By the time Confucius wrote about them in
the fifth century B.C., they were a staple crop in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Today, radishes turn up in Mexican, Indian, Chinese, Japanese,
Thai, North African, French, Italian and Russian cookbooks, but
they are barely on the culinary radar in this country.
</P>
<P>
   In France roasted radishes are a delicious addition to a
vegetable ragout with carrots and white beans. In Japan, radishes
are braised in dashi, sake and soy sauce as a bracing side dish for
fish or meat. In India, shredded radishes are seasoned with
chilies, ginger and toasted spices to make a filling for paratha.
</P>
<P>
   Even when used raw, radishes get better treatment elsewhere. In
Mexico, they are paired with avocado and lime juice in a simple
salad of contrasting flavors and textures. Greek restaurants offer
sliced radishes with fennel for scooping a feta cheese dip.
</P>
<P>
   Radishes are thought to have been cultivated in Europe since the
late Stone Age. The ancient Egyptians grew them for the oil that
could be pressed from the seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this history, Americans barely bother with radishes.
Although the consumption of fresh vegetables is on the rise over
all in the United States, sales of radishes have actually declined
slightly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much pressure to get exotic fruits and vegetables
on store shelves that the radish is being squeezed out a bit,''
said Ron Schut, the president of Miedema Produce in Hudsonville,
Mich., one of the country's largest radish wholesalers.
</P>
<P>
   This is surprising considering that radishes are available
year-round, with local supplies in summer and crops from Florida
and Arizona in colder months. And specialty radishes are turning up
more often. Farmers' markets this time of year sell every type,
from dainty French breakfast radishes, elongated versions that
shade from bright red at the stem end to white at the root, to the
sturdy daikon, which can grow to a foot or more and weigh more than
two pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the very mild Easter egg radishes, which come in
various shades of red, pink, purple and ivory. Icicle radishes are
white like the daikon but much smaller, usually about the size and
shape of your thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Any of these are good raw, with a little salt or butter, eaten
out of hand or on bread. But cooking literally transforms them,
eliminating any pepperiness. When braised for 10 minutes, even the
hottest radish loses its sting. What's left is pure radish flavor.
</P>
<P>
   As an added bonus, the alabaster flesh of the standard red
radish turns rosy pink. Pairing radishes with sauteed shallots and
a drop of honey actually makes them taste sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Like other root vegetables, radishes also take well to roasting.
Radishes emerge caramelized and tender from a hot oven. Tossing the
radishes with a little soy sauce as they finish cooking creates a
syrupy glaze and seasons them perfectly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Raw radishes are often as peppery as a chili, especially in
summer. The heat comes from mustard oils, or isothiocyanates, not
capsaicin, the fiery substance in chilies.
</P>
<P>
   Mustard oils, compounds that provide flavor and aroma, are found
in varying amounts in all cruciferous vegetables, a family that, in
addition to radishes, also includes kale, broccoli, cabbage and
turnips. Isothiocyanates are most prevalent in radishes,
horseradish, mustard greens and turnips.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Brecht, a professor of postharvest physiology at the
University of Florida in Gainesville, said the compounds are
volatile and their effect lasts only a few seconds. ``Cooking
drives off the isothiocyanates very quickly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even raw radishes can be tamed, though. Try mixing several cups
of sliced radishes with chopped oranges, a little extra virgin
olive oil and some paprika to make a juicy Moroccan salad, perfect
with grilled fish or chicken, or with sandwiches at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   If you have an hour or so, turn radishes into quick
Asian-flavored pickles: first salt them to draw out their bitter
juices, then marinate them in a rice vinegar and sugar mixture.
These sweet-and-sour radish pickles perfumed with a drop of sesame
oil are an unusual accompaniment for cocktails.
</P>
<P>
   For a five-minute appetizer, layer sliced radishes over pieces
of buttered bread and then sprinkle them lightly with coarse salt.
French cooks would use a baguette, but for an Eastern European
flavor, try buttered black bread.
</P>
<P>
   When shopping for radishes, try to buy them with healthy-looking
greens still attached, a good indicator that the radishes have been
freshly dug. The trimmed radishes sold in plastic bags are not
necessarily bad, but they may lose some flavor as they sit in the
produce aisle.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Radishes should be smooth, brightly colored and firm, never soft
or spongy. Really large red radishes can be woody in the center;
anything bigger than a golf ball is suspect.
</P>
<P>
   BRAISED RED RADISHES WITH SHALLOTS AND HONEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 bunches radishes, trimmed (about 1 pound when trimmed)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1 medium shallot, minced
</P>
<P>
   { cup chicken or vegetable stock
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon honey
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon minced fresh parsley leaves.
</P>
<P>
   1. Halve radishes lengthwise from stem to root end.
</P>
<P>
   2. Melt the butter in a large saute pan. Add the shallot, and
saute over medium heat until softened, about 2 minutes. Add
radishes, and stir; cook until well coated with butter, about 1
minute.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add stock and honey to pan, cover, and cook until radishes
are tender but not soft, about 10 minutes. Remove cover, season
with salt to taste, and simmer until any remaining juices in pan
reduce to a glaze, about 1 minute. Garnish with parsley, and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ROASTED RADISHES WITH SOY AND SESAME SEEDS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 bunches radishes, trimmed (about 1 pound when trimmed)
</P>
<P>
   1{ tablespoons roasted peanut oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   2 medium scallions, sliced thin
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon sesame seeds, toasted.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat the oven to 425 degrees. Halve radishes lengthwise
from stem to root end. Combine the radishes and oil on a large
rimmed baking sheet, and toss to coat. Roast, turning once or
twice, until the radishes are tender and beginning to brown, about
25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Drizzle soy sauce over radishes, and sprinkle with scallions.
Toss well, and continue roasting for 5 minutes. Turn radishes and
any juices on baking sheet into a serving bowl. Sprinkle with
sesame seeds, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   RADISH AND ORANGE SALAD WITH PAPRIKA &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 medium oranges
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon honey
</P>
<P>
   1 bunch radishes, trimmed (about 6 ounces when trimmed)
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon sweet paprika
</P>
<P>
   Salt.
</P>
<P>
   1. Trim thick slices from ends of oranges so they sit flat on
cutting board. With paring knife, slice downward around oranges to
remove peel and white pith. Chop peeled oranges, and transfer them
to a bowl with their juices. Drizzle with honey, and toss gently.
</P>
<P>
   2. Thinly slice trimmed radishes crosswise. Add to bowl with
oranges, and toss lightly. Drizzle with oil, and sprinkle with
paprika and salt to taste. Toss, and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 to 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SWEET-AND-SOUR RADISH PICKLES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 10 minutes, plus 1\ hours to marinate
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 bunches radishes, trimmed (about 1 pound when trimmed)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   { cup rice vinegar
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons Asian sesame oil.
</P>
<P>
   1. Slice the trimmed radishes into \-inch-thick rounds. Toss the
radishes with the salt in a medium bowl, and set aside, stirring
occasionally, for 45 minutes. Drain off the liquid; there should be
about \ cup of salty juices.
</P>
<P>
   2. Meanwhile, bring vinegar and sugar to a boil in a small
saucepan, stirring just until sugar dissolves. Remove pan from
heat, and cool mixture to room temperature. Whisk in oil.
</P>
<P>
   3. Pour vinegar mixture over drained radishes. Marinate,
stirring occasionally, for 30 minutes. Drain radishes, if desired
(they are less messy to eat this way). Serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 to 8 servings when used as an hors d'oeuvre. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
