<SLUG> BC-WINE-TASTINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STILL CLASSIC 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cakebread Cellars Cabernet Sauvignon, Napa Valley, Rutherford,
Calif. About $34.
</P>
<P>
   Every year, it seems, there are three or four new wineries in
the Napa Valley that, we are told, are redefining the meaning of
great cabernet. Good luck to them. It's nice to know there are
people out there who have been making cabernet for a long time and
somehow almost always get it right.
</P>
<P>
   Take this classic from Cakebread Cellars. There are grapes from
the Stag's Leap and Oakville appellations in this wine, along with
grapes from Cakebread's own vineyard in Rutherford. About 15
percent of it is merlot, there is a little cabernet franc and even
a touch of syrah.
</P>
<P>
   The final blend, after 15 months in French oak, produced a
smooth, elegant wine, an evocation of all that's good about the
Napa Valley.
</P>
</TEXT>
