<HEADER>
A0261 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e BC-ROCK-CORNELL-SPI &LR;      09-21 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-CORNELL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW SOLO ALBUM SHOWS ANOTHER SIDE OF CHRIS CORNELL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By GENE STOUT  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the lead singer of Soundgarden, Chris Cornell helped reinvent
hard rock.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing from heavy metal and punk, the Seattle band joined
Pearl Jam, Mudhoney, Nirvana and other local groups in creating a
sound that turned the city into an alternative-rock mecca in the
early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came from an era in music that had no rules,'' Cornell said
in a recent phone interview from Los Angeles. ``The idea was that
you can do whatever you want as long as you're inspired by it and
it's natural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landscape of music and what's possible is just enormous.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Seattle resident continues to explore that
landscape on his first solo album, ``Euphoria Morning,'' just out
from A&AMP;M Records. The first single, the seductive ``Can't Change
Me,'' was released a few weeks ago and is already a hit.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime fans of Soundgarden, which broke up in 1997 after
selling 10 million albums, will discover another side of the
group's imposing former frontman _ the tall prince of Seattle rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Euphoria Morning'' is more of a singer-songwriter's album than
anything Cornell ever recorded with guitar-heavy Soundgarden. The
vocals soar, and the lyrics are clear and powerful. Cornell
stretches his creative muscle too, combining elements of rock, soul
and R&AMP;B with experimental textures while remaining accessible to
Top 40 sensibilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty unusual record in a way,'' said the affable,
low-key musician. ``There was no focus in terms of musical identity
because it's not like I have the ability to step outside of myself
and think, `What kind of songs should this guy sing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell scrapped his original idea of reworking songs he had
written but never recorded during the Soundgarden era, choosing
instead to start anew.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something isn't happening and you're not happy with it, you
should just move on to something else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell wrote songs with a guitar, experimenting with sounds and
lyrics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't worry about looking into the future and imagining
what my record would sound like,'' he said. ``It was more a case of
doing one song at time and having fun and just playing around with
different influences and not worrying about when it would be done
or how it would turn out.''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of producers and longtime friends Alain Johannes
and Natasha Shneider of rock band Eleven, Cornell recorded a
remarkably strong debut solo album. Contributing were Jason Falkner
and former Soundgarden drummer Matt Cameron, now playing with Pearl
Jam.
</P>
<P>
   Working with Johannes and Shneider came naturally. Cornell has
been a fan of Johannes since the mid-'80s. Ten years later, Eleven
joined Soundgarden on tours of the United States and Europe.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the couple invited Cornell to hang out with them at
their home studio in Los Angeles. The visit resulted in a
collaboration that yielded ``Sweet Sunshower'' for the ``Great
Expectations'' soundtrack and a version of ``Ave Maria'' for an A&AMP;M
Records Christmas benefit album.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell's relationship with Johannes and Shneider was so
productive that he decided to work with the couple on his solo
album.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a last-minute idea that dawned on everybody,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's rock scene has produced dozens of successful bands,
but few high-profile solo artists. This could change with the
release of ``Euphoria Morning,'' an eclectic, 12-song collection
that explores a variety of styles, textures and emotions.
</P>
<P>
   The hard-rocking ``Mission'' recalls Soundgarden (Cornell used
an electric drink mixer on the guitar strings to produce a jarring
effect), while ``Disappearing One'' (which opens with a
retro-sounding bass clarinet) is bluesy, almost spiritual. The
sense of anguish and melancholy hangs from every word on ``When I'm
Down,'' which casts Cornell in the role of white-soul crooner.
</P>
<P>
   The sweet but sorrowful ``Wave Goodbye'' is a tribute to the
late singer-songwriter Jeff Buckley, son of '60s folk legend Tim
Buckley. ``I guess what bothered me the most about Jeff's death is
that people wouldn't get a chance to hear what he did, which was so
unique,'' Cornell said.
</P>
<P>
   The album's first single, ``Can't Change Me'' made its debut on
radio earlier this summer and is currently in the Top 20 of
Billboard's two rock charts.
</P>
<P>
   The song's signature line, ``She's going to change the world,
but she can't change me,'' has caused some local listeners to
wonder if the song is autobiographical (Cornell is married to
Soundgarden's manager, Susan Silver).
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of my songs are about characters in a sense,'' Cornell
said. ``So no one's going to know what's autobiographical and
what's fiction. I guess that's the beauty of words put together.
Everyone can have their own interpretation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cornell will begin his ``Euphoria Morning'' tour in Europe. The
U.S. portion will include a Seattle show in November or December.
</P>
<P>
   Backing Cornell will be Johannes on guitars, Shneider on
keyboards, Ric Markmann on bass and Greg Upchurch on drums.
Johannes and Shneider will add background vocals.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell said rumors of a Soundgarden reunion are false. But he
describes his former bandmates as family and regards ``Down on the
Upside'' as the group's best album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we got closer to the way I wanted us to sound on that
record than any other,'' he said. ``It just sounds more naturally
like how I imagined we sounded live.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
