<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-ITALY-COOKBOOK-REVIEW     09-21 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-COOKBOOK-REVIEW-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME SURPRISES FROM SOUTHERN ITALY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(pr) 
 By FLORENCE FABRICANT    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I spent a substantial portion of Labor Day weekend cooking from
``Regional Foods of Southern Italy'' by Marlena de Blasi (Viking,
$28.95) but could have devoted a week to it. Both the evocative
text and the recipes promise much and deliver more.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Blasi moves far beyond the red sauce and ricotta cliches
of the well-traversed terrain of southern Italy, especially in
dishes like braised forest mushrooms, and beyond dry directions,
with recipe instructions that read, ``Over a gentle flame, allow
the mushrooms to reabsorb their juices and to drink in the wine.''
</P>
<P>
   The result in this case is an intensely flavored stew from the
Basilicata region with succulent wild mushrooms made piquant with a
pinch of the typical hot red pepper of the south.
</P>
<P>
   This highly personal region-by-region survey of the southern
half of Italy's boot begins in Lazio, the province that encompasses
Rome, then travels south, alternating between the east and west
coasts, as far as ``the tiniest, last pieces of Italy that crumble
into the Mediterranean.''
</P>
<P>
   These are impoverished regions where no Medicis reigned and
where a sly ``cucina povera'' includes dishes like ``thin strings
of pasta with escaped clams,'' meaning no clams were available and
one had to make do with tomatoes, a bit of pancetta and a few
chilies. A salt cod salad with artichokes and olives is called a
``salad of fish in a place where there is no sea.''
</P>
<P>
   As Ms. de Blasi journeys, she tells of the food, the people who
lovingly craft it and the customs they observe to consume it. Olive
oil warmed with a freshly made paste of garlic and herbs is the
opening shot for many of the recipes, and a scattering of crunchy
bread crumbs sauteed in fragrant olive oil sometimes provides the
dashing finish.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. de Blasi, who lives in the Umbrian hill town of Orvieto,
also wrote ``Regional Food of Northern Italy,'' published in 1997
by Prima. Although the book was nominated for a James Beard award,
its recipes were less surprising and the writing less alluringly
ripe than in the new volume.
</P>
<P>
   A native New Yorker, Ms. de Blasi has lived with her Italian
husband, Fernando de Blasi, in Venice and Tuscany, and they now run
the Company of the Cauldron, a cooking and tourist service for
visitors to Italy who rent houses.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Regional Food of Southern Italy,'' the dishes all get an
anecdotal history taken from the home cooks, chefs and food vendors
Ms. de Blasi has met in her travels.
</P>
<P>
   Among the finest of her discoveries is veal braised with
sun-dried tomatoes, wine and olives. She labels it ``leg of veal in
the manner of the roving meat cooker,'' a dish that one could buy
by the slice from a carnacottaro, an itinerant vendor in Campania,
near Naples.
</P>
<P>
   A number of the dishes she includes are best when cooked over a
wood fire or simmered in a terra-cotta casserole, but those will be
the biggest challenges for home cooks.
</P>
<P>
   As for that braised mushroom dish, she included a variation in
her first book but said this one is a lunch stew served after a
mushroom hunt in the area of Vulture. Never mind the possible
poetic license she took in adapting it; the recipe is terrific.
</P>
<P>
   Among her other great dishes are pasta in a creamy ricotta and
sheep's-milk sauce, or in a well-spiced sauce of green tomatoes,
and mussels and clams steamed in an uncompromisingly garlicky and
peppery broth known as crazy water.
</P>
<P>
   Her description of a suavely spiced prune tart as ``the earth's
most delectable'' might be an overstatement. But not much of one.
</P>
<P>
   CLAMS AND MUSSELS IN CRAZY WATER
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Regional Foods of Southern Italy''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours, including soaking time
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds little neck clams (about 2{ dozen)
</P>
<P>
   Fine sea salt
</P>
<P>
   4 fat cloves garlic, peeled and crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fennel seeds, crushed
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup flat-leaf parsley, loosely packed
</P>
<P>
   1 one-third cups extra virgin olive oil, approximately
</P>
<P>
   1 small dried red chili pepper, crushed, or one-third to {
teaspoon dried chili flakes
</P>
<P>
   2 large ripe tomatoes, peeled, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 bottle dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds mussels, scrubbed, debearded and rinsed
</P>
<P>
   8 slices country bread, each { inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons red wine vinegar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Place clams in a bowl of salted water to cover, and set aside
for 1 hour. Rinse and scrub clams.
</P>
<P>
   2. Mince garlic, fennel seeds and parsley to a fine paste. In a
large casserole, warm one-third cup oil over medium heat. Lightly
saute the paste; add chili, tomatoes, about 1{ teaspoons sea salt
and wine; bring to a simmer, and cook about 5 minutes, until
tomatoes are soft.
</P>
<P>
   3. Add clams and mussels to simmering sauce, and cook,
uncovered, until they have opened.
</P>
<P>
   4. Warm remaining oil in a skillet. Lightly brown the bread
slices in it, drain on absorbent paper and place in a napkin-lined
basket.
</P>
<P>
   5. When clams and mussels have opened, remove from heat, stir in
the vinegar and serve with fried bread.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   VEAL BRAISED IN THE MANNER OF THE ROVING MEAT COOKER
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Regional Foods of Southern Italy''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 3 hours, plus one hour resting
</P>
<P>
   2 two-thirds cups white wine
</P>
<P>
   { cup white raisins
</P>
<P>
   \ cup extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 pounds boneless veal top round or leg, tied at 2-inch
intervals
</P>
<P>
   1{ teaspoons fine sea salt, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   2 ounces sun-dried tomatoes in oil, drained and slivered
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces green and black Sicilian, Greek or Spanish olives,
pitted and coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   1{ cups canned tomato puree
</P>
<P>
   { pound ziti or penne, cooked al dente and tossed with butter
and grated pecorino (optional).
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   1. Warm one-third cup wine in a small saucepan, add raisins and
set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Heat oil in a large casserole, preferably enameled cast iron
or terra cotta, and brown veal on all sides. Remove veal, and
sprinkle with salt. 3. Add sun-dried tomatoes, olives and raisins
with their wine to casserole, and stir for about a minute; then,
add tomato puree and remaining wine. Bring to a simmer, add veal
and its juices, reduce heat, cover casserole and cook over the
lowest possible heat for 1{ hours.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove cover, and baste meat. Simmer very gently another {
hour, or until the meat is fork-tender. Set veal aside in the
covered casserole 1 hour, then gently reheat.
</P>
<P>
   5. To serve, slice veal { inch thick and serve with sauce. If
desired, serve freshly cooked pasta dressed with butter, grated
pecorino and some of the sauce alongside.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SPICED PRUNE TART
</P>
<P>
   Adapted from ``Regional Foods of Southern Italy''
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1{ hours
</P>
<P>
   Sweet pastry for 10-inch tart pan
</P>
<P>
   14 ounces plump pitted prunes
</P>
<P>
   { cup dark rum
</P>
<P>
   1\ cups mascarpone
</P>
<P>
   1 large egg, lightly beaten
</P>
<P>
   \ cup heavy cream
</P>
<P>
   { teaspoon freshly grated nutmeg
</P>
<P>
   1 1-inch stick cinnamon, grated, or 1 teaspoon ground
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon ground cloves
</P>
<P>
   \ teaspoon freshly ground coarse black pepper
</P>
<P>
   one-third cup bitter orange marmalade
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon dark brown sugar.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Line a 10-inch tart pan with
pastry, line with foil and weight with dry beans or pie weights.
Bake 6 minutes. Remove foil, and bake until pastry is dry and
barely colored, about 10 minutes more.
</P>
<P>
   2. While pastry is baking, place prunes in a small saucepan with
rum, heat until almost boiling, remove from heat, cover and let
steep.
</P>
<P>
   3. Place mascarpone in a bowl, and stir until smooth. Stir in
remaining ingredients.
</P>
<P>
   4. Drain prunes, reserving rum. Arrange on pre-baked pastry.
Spoon mascarpone mixture over prunes, place in oven and bake 20
minutes. Reduce heat to 350 degrees, and bake another 20 minutes,
until surface is bronzed. Brush hot tart with a little reserved
rum, allow to cool to room temperature and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 8 servings.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
