<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-CHICKEN-ALTERNATIVES-     09-21 1125
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHICKEN-ALTERNATIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROM POUSSIN TO CAPON, A CHICKEN IN EVERY SIZE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JOHN WILLOUGHBY and CHRIS SCHLESINGER 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   You don't have to be a farmer to know that chickens come in
various sizes. Even cooks who know these birds as only
plastic-wrapped packages in the supermarket can distinguish a
three-pound broiler from an eight-pound roaster.
</P>
<P>
   But there is so much more to chicken than these oh-so-familiar
sizes and cuts. If ``poultry is for the cook what canvas is for a
painter,'' to quote the 19th-century French gastronome
Brillat-Savarin, why paint the same painting over and over again?
</P>
<P>
   More and more, chickens of various types and sizes are showing
up not only on restaurant menus but also in markets and home
kitchens. From the diminutive poussin to the opulent capon, these
birds have distinctive characteristics that make them not only very
tasty but also fun to cook.
</P>
<P>
   The basic difference among most of these types of chicken is
their age, reflected in both their tenderness and their flavor.
</P>
<P>
   The smallest commercially available chicken is the poussin,
usually less than 24 days old and weighing slightly less than a
pound. This tiny bird is not particularly flavorful, but many cooks
are wild about its soft, delicate texture. The legs are the best
part of the poussin, since the lack of muscle development makes
them much more tender than those of an adult bird.
</P>
<P>
   Poussins are sold at Greenmarkets, high-end food stores and some
supermarkets in New York, but in some parts of the country they can
be hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   A more readily available choice for a one-bird-a-person meal is
the Cornish game hen. This somewhat exotic-sounding fowl is
actually an American breed created by crossing a White Rock hen
with a Cornish game cock. Most game hens are about 1 month old and
weigh between 1 and 1{ pounds, although some are as much as 2
pounds. Because they are more mature and are specifically bred for
early slaughter, they have more flavor than poussins.
</P>
<P>
   Game hens and poussins are both great for cooking over live
fire. We like them either grill-roasted intact or butterflied and
grilled. No matter how you cook them, though, the best part is that
each guest gets his or her own whole bird, which somehow seems both
celebratory and a bit decadent.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet for roasting is a capon, which you will probably
have to order from your butcher. This bird was originally developed
by Romans in the second century who were looking to circumvent the
so-called famine laws that were put in place to save grain.
</P>
<P>
   One such law made it illegal for Romans to eat fattened hens.
Unwilling to give up their poultry feasts, some crafty Romans began
castrating young roosters and feeding them grain. This process
caused the roosters to put on so much extra fat that they grew to
almost twice their normal adult size _ and proved even tastier than
fattened hens.
</P>
<P>
   Capons are usually killed at 4 months, when they weigh 6 to 9
pounds. Because of their high fat content, they are particularly
juicy and flavorful and still quite tender. A roast stuffed capon
is a thing of beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Unless you live near a chicken farm, you probably won't be able
to find a stewing hen, but this bird is worth mentioning, if only
for historical perspective. This is a laying hen that is no longer
prolific and is therefore killed for food. Usually about 15 months
old and weighing 5 to 6 pounds, this hen is tough and stringy _
about as far from today's supermarket chicken as you can get _ but
has great flavor. In earlier days, it was the Sunday roast chicken
of farmers, but in chicken soup it is unsurpassed.
</P>
<P>
   GRILL-ROASTED WHOLE GAME HENS WITH ORANGE, OREGANO AND CUMIN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 1 hour 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2 oranges, unpeeled, cut in {-inch slices
</P>
<P>
   2 onions, peeled, halved and cut into thick slices
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and black pepper
</P>
<P>
   4 Cornish game hens, about 1\ to 1{ pounds each
</P>
<P>
   { cup chopped fresh oregano
</P>
<P>
   \ cup minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   { cup toasted cumin seeds (or \ cup ground cumin).
</P>
<P>
   1. Build a fire in half of a covered grill, using enough
charcoal to fill a shoe box. The fire is ready for cooking when the
flames have died down and you are left with flickering coals.
</P>
<P>
   2. In small bowl, combine oranges, onions, oil and salt and
pepper, and mix well. Stuff cavity of each bird with \ of this
mixture.
</P>
<P>
   3. In small bowl, combine oregano and garlic; mix well. With
fingers, loosen skin from breasts of birds, starting at tip of
breastbone and being careful not to tear skin. Gently rub oregano
and garlic mixture under skin, pushing it down as far as you can.
Sprinkle outside of hen with cumin seeds and salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   4. When fire is ready, place hens on the side of grill with no
fire; do not allow hens to come in contact with flames at any time.
Cover grill, and vent slightly. Cook for 45 minutes to 1 hour,
checking fire every 15 minutes or so, adding fuel, if necessary, to
keep fire going. Birds are done when thigh is pierced at thickest
part and juices run clear. Remove from grill, discard stuffing, and
serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   ROAST CAPON WITH CORN BREAD-CHORIZO STUFFING &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time: 2 hours
</P>
<P>
   1 capon, 7 to 9 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Salt and cracked black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   1 large onion, peeled and diced small
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1 jalapeno or other small fresh chili pepper, minced
</P>
<P>
   1 pound chorizo, sliced
</P>
<P>
   2 Granny Smith or other green apples, cored and diced small
</P>
<P>
   6 cups of 1-inch cubes of stale corn bread
</P>
<P>
   \ cup roughly chopped fresh cilantro (or parsley)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk.
</P>
<P>
   1. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Rinse bird with cold water, and
dry with paper towels. Sprinkle inside and outside with generous
amount of salt and pepper, and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   2. Make stuffing: In large saute pan over medium heat, heat oil
until hot but not smoking. Add onion; saute until transparent, for
7 to 9 minutes. Add garlic and jalapeno; saute for 1 minute. Add
sausage; saute for 5 minutes. Remove mixture with slotted spoon,
place in medium bowl, and stir in the apples, corn bread and
cilantro. Add milk, mix well, and season with salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   3. Fill cavity of bird } full with stuffing. (Cook any remaining
stuffing in separate, ovenproof, greased loaf pan.) Place bird in
roasting pan, and roast, turning pan front to back after about 30
minutes. Cook for about 1 more hour. Bird is done when thigh is
pierced at thickest part and juices run clear.
</P>
<P>
   4. Remove from oven, scoop stuffing into bowl, mixing with any
stuffing cooked separately. Let bird rest for about 15 minutes
before carving.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 6 servings.
</P>
</TEXT>
