<HEADER>
A0281 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-PORK-EATING-WELL-NYT &LR;      09-21 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PORK-EATING-WELL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORK WTH A PEDIGREE 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MARIAN BURROS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Last week, for only the second time in my life, I
tasted pork so delicious it needed no seasoning beyond salt and
pepper. Both times the meat was superior heirloom pork, suffused
with a bright, clean flavor, with none of the unpleasant aftertaste
pork often has.
</P>
<P>
   Not coincidentally, both pieces came from pigs raised in a
manner vastly different from that of ordinary supermarket pork.
</P>
<P>
   The first time I had heirloom pork was at Cabbage Hill Farm in
suburban Westchester County, which is dedicated to saving historic
breeds. The pork I had last week, at Gramercy Tavern, is available
by mail and will eventually be in some New York City grocery
stores. Sold under the brand Niman Ranch, which is known for its
fine beef, the pork had first been described to me several months
ago in terms of its environmental soundness rather than its taste.
</P>
<P>
   The pigs are raised on small family farms, not indoors at
factory farms that are similar to modern-day chicken houses, with
thousands of animals kept close together. The stench from these
large-scale hog farms is so great that neighbors' complaints have
made news across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Niman pigs are raised in pastures instead of
indoors, their waste products return to the soil naturally, instead
of creating environmental problems.
</P>
<P>
   These are all good reasons to choose this heirloom pork, but it
took a few tastes to make me a convert.
</P>
<P>
   Most pork today is leaner than in the past, but in the process
of breeding out the fat, the flavor went, too. The low fat content
also means that the pork becomes tough very quickly when it is
cooked. And the factory pork releases a lot of liquid in cooking
because the animals have been given hormones to increase their
weight through fluid retention.
</P>
<P>
   The Niman Ranch pork remains tender and releases little liquid.
The Midwestern hog farmers who raise pigs for Niman have agreed to
follow certain rules, and their pigs are fed no animal byproducts
or antibiotics. For this new ``old'' pork, they are guaranteed 37.5
cents a pound plus a 6-cent premium. Prices for conventionally
raised pork were as low as 11 cents a pound earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Other Midwestern farmers are going a step further and raising
certified organic pigs. The sample of the meat I tasted was not as
tender as the Niman Ranch pork. Sold under the Valley's Family
label, it will be available in mid-October in Manhattan at Fairway,
2127 Broadway (74th Street); Lifethyme, 408 Avenue of the Americas
(Eighth Street); Healthy Pleasures, 93 University Place (12th
Street), and West Side Health, 2568 Broadway (96th Street), and in
Brooklyn at Back to the Land, 142 Seventh Avenue (Carroll Street),
and Perelandra, 175 Remsen Street (Court Street). It is expected to
sell for about $5.75 a pound for tenderloin and boneless chops.
</P>
<P>
   Niman Ranch pork is also served at Savoy, Lutece and Beacon in
Manhattan. It will soon be available at retail nationwide. Until
then, D'Artagnan, (800) 327-8246, can supply it with three or four
days' notice. The tenderloin is $11 a pound; boneless loin chops,
$8 (shipping extra).
</P>
<P>
   Once again, small is beautiful.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
