A0288 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TE     09-21 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORATIO HORNBLOWER'S CREATOR IS MARKING 100TH BIRTHDAY, TOO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LARRY SWINDELL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the Hemingway centennial is solemnized by formal literary
occasions, fans of another esteemed ``man's author'' may not
realize that 1999 also marks the 100th birthday of their guy, who
at the very least is Ernest Hemingway's equal in the measure of
popularity.
</P>
<P>
   He's Cecil Lewis Troughton Smith. Well, he was that, until he
changed his name legally to Cecil Scott Forester. He's identified
literarily as C.S. Forester, but the name on his calling card is
forever Horatio Hornblower. As Arthur Conan Doyle is to Sherlock
Holmes, so is Forester to Hornblower.
</P>
<P>
   Doyle, we know, came to despise his most famous creation, sought
to abandon him, but yielded to that mighty warrior, Public Demand,
and kept the Holmes yarns coming. There's no clear evidence that
Forester regretted his horn-blown success, but one may wonder. In
his spirited autobiography, ``Long Before Forty,'' he asserts that
he might have realized keener fulfillment as a military and naval
historian. That was Forester's objective when he commenced a
writing career, after he forsook the study of medicine. He
despaired of most historical accounts, finding them deficient in
narrative vitality. He believed history should be read as one reads
a novel, and his venture into fiction was calculated to prepare him
as a ``serious'' historian.
</P>
<P>
   That wouldn't explain his first novel, the ironic ``Payment
Deferred'' (1926), which later was successfully dramatized. Charles
Laughton acted _ on both stage and screen _ the timid clerk who
gains wealth by murdering his landlord and is convicted instead of
murdering his wife, something that he did not do. ``The Gun''
(1933) was landlocked military history in a guise of fiction. It,
too, was filmed, much later, as ``The Pride and the Passion,'' and
not even Cary Grant could save it.
</P>
<P>
   The movies, though, were mostly kind to Forester. His World War
I adventure novel ``The African Queen'' (1935) emerged 16 years
later as one of our most cherished films. There was also a
Hornblower movie, with stolid, stalwart Gregory Peck as ``Captain
Horatio Hornblower.'' And that was the collective title for the
trilogy originally intended as the start and finish of the
Hornblower saga, consisting of ``Beat to Quarters'' (1937), ``Ships
of the Line'' (1938) and ``Flying Colors'' (1939). Forester's
wartime bestseller ``The Ship'' was maritime adventure minus his
resourceful hero; but postwar popularity of the Hornblower books
put pressure on Forester to deliver more of the same.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, the Hornblower series eventually stretched to
an even dozen novels, not including ``The Hornblower Companion,''
the author's 1964 account of the genesis and development of the
works that advance Horatio from midshipman to admiral. Ultimately,
he is ``Lord Hornblower.'' Forester in late career did manage some
sturdily historical nonfiction with ``The Story of the Naval War of
1812'' and ``The Last Nine Days of the Bismarck'' (the latter
filmed as ``Sink the Bismarck!'').
</P>
<P>
   Forester's death in 1967 effectively scuttled other similar
projects he had blueprinted. In the realm of adventure fiction,
C.S. Forester must rank near the very top. Seamanship is an
evolving technology, and Forester's mastery of the arts and
sciences of seafaring during the Napoleonic Wars is what earned for
him a devoted readership. Today's advocates of the Tom Clancy
high-tech thrillers respond to the same impulse. From what I'm told
(having not read any of the later Hornblower tales), Forester rose
above that well-known law of diminishing returns. Each title seems
to have been received respectfully, and sales never sagged. Even
today, they're healthy in the marketplace in various editions.
</P>
<P>
   (Larry Swindell is retired books editor for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
