<HEADER>
A0290 &Cx1f; taf-z
u d BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT &LR;      09-21 1029
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WINE-TALK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINERY OWNER REINVENTS HIMSELF AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By FRANK J. PRIAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RUTHERFORD, Calif. _ A Gustin Huneeus was between jobs, and
enjoying it thoroughly. He had just sold Franciscan Estates, his
Napa Valley winery, for $220 million to Canandaigua Brands, an
upstate New York wine and spirits conglomerate. And once again, he
was about to embark on a new career.
</P>
<P>
   Since Huneeus, 66, is known as one of the more perceptive _ and
successful _ people in the wine world, it seemed an appropriate
time to pose some questions about his future and that of the wine
business at the dawn of a new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   The sale of Franciscan by Huneeus and his partners also included
Mount Veeder, another Napa Valley winery; considerable vineyard
acreage in California, and two-thirds of a winery and vineyards in
Chile. But Huneeus (pronounced hoo-NAY-us) retained more than
enough to keep him busy: the Quintessa vineyard in the heart of the
Napa Valley, the 1,000-acre Veramonte estate in Chile, a vineyard
in the Alexander Valley in Sonoma County and another recently
acquired vineyard near the city of Napa called the Lewis Ranch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to reinvent my life,'' he said with no particular sense
of urgency. In fact, reinventing his life is something Agustin
Huneeus has always done well. He was born into an influential
family in Chile and raised there and in the United States. His
great-grandfather was a founder of the prominent Chilean winery
Concha y Toro. At 24, while running a modest fish exporting
business in Chile, Huneeus jumped at a chance to buy back Concha y
Toro, which the family had sold.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, after Salvador Allende was elected president of Chile,
the winery was nationalized. Tipped that he was to be arrested as a
subversive, Huneeus fled to Buenos Aires on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   There he ran Joseph I. Seagram &AMP; Sons' Argentine companies. But
Argentina was also in political turmoil. ``After a couple of years
of riding in three-car caravans with machine guns, I went to New
York,'' Huneeus said, ``to run all of Seagram's international
operations.'' Realizing that he was not cut out for corporate life,
he resigned in 1977 ``as soon as I got my green card,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing he did was to invest in a company growing grapes
for jug wine in California's Central Valley. Then, with a Chilean
friend, Sergio Traversio, he invested in the old Concannon Winery
in Livermore, Calif. When he sold that in 1983, he retired, so the
speak, at 50. But only for a couple of months. He was then asked to
help reorganize Souverain Cellars, a big Sonoma winery once owned
by the Pillsbury Company but then in the hands of some 40 feuding
grape growers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quality had nothing to do with the operation,'' Huneeus said.
``It was strictly a home for their grapes.'' Frustrated by so many
warring factions, Huneeus abandoned the project (Souverain later
went bankrupt and was sold to Beringer Estates). Two years later,
in 1985, the Eckes family, who had bought Franciscan Vineyards in
1979 for about $15 million, offered him a chance to buy in. ``If
you join us, we'll give you half,'' they told him. His response:
``Only if you let me run it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eckes family was the unfortunate winery's fifth owner in the
six years since its opening in 1973. In fact, the undercapitalized
first owners were gone before it even opened.
</P>
<P>
   In a relatively short time, Huneeus brought about a stunning
reversal of Franciscan's fortunes. He pared expenses, set cost
controls and established a highly successful second label,
Estancia, which allowed him to concentrate on the quality of the
Franciscan line. And early on, he invested in Chile, whose wine
business he knew well. Since 1995, Franciscan's sales have grown
more than 17 percent a year. Now, Franciscan will remain as a
separate entity within the Canandaigua group.
</P>
<P>
   Huneeus (friends call him Cucho) is understandably upbeat about
California wine's future. But he is wary about making predictions.
``Look at the success we are enjoying today,'' he said. ``Who could
have predicted this? No one.'' Still, he can see a few dark clouds.
``The trend is to bigness,'' he added. ``Little wineries can't find
anyone to distribute their wines, and the big wineries are becoming
anonymous corporate entities _ negociants rather than winemakers.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he said, some of the big wineries could suffer the
fate of wine companies of the past, like Paul Masson. ``Once they
were in every shop, every restaurant; then they collapsed,'' he
said. ``Robert Mondavi is the current Paul Masson. If they don't
take care, they'll grow bigger and bigger and then fall on their
face, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Huneeus takes a dim view of the current obsession with ratings.
``Everything is ratings, ratings, which is an artificial way to
enjoy wine,'' he said. ``People won't drink a wine unless it has a
high rating. It's nonsense. They give up the right to make their
own judgments.''
</P>
<P>
   His strongest criticism was aimed at the American practice of
identifying wines by the grape from which they are made. ``The
varietal market is not truthful,'' he said. ``It's a fantasy
market.'' Varietal designations came into vogue in the years after
World War II, when most California wines were identified by names
like ``burgundy,'' ``chablis'' or ``chianti.'' Then, beginning in
the 1950s, good wines started to be identified by the grapes from
which they were made, like chardonnay. But not all chardonnay or
cabernet is good wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think it's chic to order merlot,'' Huneeus said. ``Why,
50 percent of the merlot we're using around here now comes from the
Central Valley. It's not quality wine. It's not merlot I want, but
merlot from a certain place.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Great wines,'' Huneeus said, ``come from specific vineyards. I
hope that the future will be properties, not grapes. People drink a
wine from Chateau Latour because it comes from Chateau Latour; they
don't even ask what the grapes are.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
