<P>
   TAIWAN-QUAKE (Taipei, Taiwan) _ With the death toll from Tuesday
morning's earthquake rising by the hour, rescuers worked throughout
the day and night to free thousands of people trapped in the rubble
of high-rise apartment buildings and houses that crumbled under the
force of the mighty temblor. At last count, the Interior Ministry's
disaster management center reported that 1,712 people were killed
in the earthquake and at least 4,408 injured with some 2,820 people
still trapped in debris or missing by late evening. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CLINTON (United Nations) _ His authority undercut by the
failure of the United States to pay what it owes the United
Nations, President Clinton went before the General Assembly and
sketched out three goals for the coming century: eradicating
poverty, preventing mass slaughter and displacement, and stopping
the spread of nuclear, biological and chemical weapons. But in a
generally lackluster speech, Clinton offered no new proposals
beyond saying that he will convene a White House meeting of
pharmaceutical company executives, foundation representatives and
members of Congress to develop vaccines for combatting malaria,
tuberculosis, AIDS and other serious diseases and to send them to
developing countries. By Christopher S. Wren.
</P>
<P>
   With photo (NYT1)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dare, East Timor) _ As the international team of
peacekeepers fans out from East Timor's capital, there are
emotional scenes in the hills as pro-independence refugees meet
U.N. officials and peacekeepers who have arrived to help them
secure independence. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
