<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-DUCASSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROUBLE IN PARIS? DUCASSE SAYS NO 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Alain Ducasse, the only chef with two restaurants given
top ratings of three stars by the Michelin Guide, said Tuesday that
there was no truth to persistent rumors that his Paris restaurant
was losing money and that he might have to move it from the posh
Hotel Le Parc on the Avenue Raymond Poincare.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been making money, and we're taking reservations for
next year,'' Ducasse said in a telephone interview from New York
City.
</P>
<P>
   The possible move, or maybe even the demise, of the Restaurant
Alain Ducasse has been the talk of the food world both here and in
New York since an article last month in Le Figaro reported trouble
between Ducasse and the new owners of the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   The Demeure hotel chain, which owns Le Parc, was acquired from
Vivendi last spring by the Accor group of France and two American
pension funds, Colony and Blackstone.
</P>
<P>
   Marie-Claire Camus, a spokeswoman for Accor, said, ``There is no
disagreement of any kind between Accor and Ducasse.''
</P>
<P>
   Ducasse stated that the article in Le Figaro, which said that
Accor was unhappy with the financial situation of the two
restaurants Ducasse is involved with in the Hotel Le Parc, was a
scoop that wasn't one at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have no disagreement with Accor and no economic worries,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The other three-star restaurant of Ducasse is the Louis XV,
which is in the Hotel de Paris in Monte Carlo.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1703EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
