r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     09-21 0608
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT _ AND NOT SO GREAT _ EXPECTATIONS FOR FALL TV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We aren't strangers to walking the prediction plank. It's fun,
it makes for testy e-mails, it sparks interoffice and living-room
debate. But it's a lose-lose situation: People will always think
you're an idiot for wagering your credibility on the success of
this or that, like the Olsen twins' ``Two of a Kind.'' (``It's a
can't-miss!'' we beamed last season. Then it did. Miserably.)
</P>
<P>
   Ten shows return from last year's batch of 36. We fingered 12
shows ``worth watching.'' But ``worth watching'' doesn't always
jibe with what actually gets watched.
</P>
<P>
   Look at the inexplicably popular ``Jesse.''
</P>
<P>
   This season: 37 series are on tap. Dramas are up, comedies are
down, dramedys are in. We have more Love (as in Jennifer Hewitt),
more Heather (as in Locklear), more Mohr, (as in Jay), as in that
``Jerry Maguire'' sleazebo, now in ``Action.'' We have teen-age
alienation and teen-age aliens, a ``Ladies' Man,'' an ``Odd Man
Out,'' and ``Grown Ups'' toiling about in ``The West Wing'' for
``Love or Money.''
</P>
<P>
   There's ``Malcolm in the Middle'' and ``Jack and Jill,''
``Angel'' and ``Ally'' all searching for the ``Safe Harbor'' of
cushy ratings.
</P>
<P>
   There are more spinoffs this season, with David Boreanaz bolting
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer'' for ``Angel,'' Hewitt exiting ``Party
of Five'' for ``Time of Your Life,'' and Countess Vaughn
hip-hopping out of ``Moesha'' to ``The Parkers.''
</P>
<P>
   For better or worse, we'll get more from fewer minds. The short
list: Aaron Sorkin (''Sports Night,'' ``West Wing''); David E.
Kelley (''Ally McBeal,'' ``Ally,'' ``Chicago Hope,'' ``The
Practice,'' ``Snoops''); Dick Wolf (''Law &AMP; Order,'' ``Law &AMP; Order:
Special Victims Unit''); Kevin Williamson (''Dawson's Creek,''
``Wasteland''); and Chris Carter (''The X-Files,'' ``Harsh
Realm''); John Wells (''ER,'' ``Third Watch'').
</P>
<P>
   Are networks still programming by fear? Are we seeing shows
based more on economics than quality? Are we getting the same thing
we got last season and the season before that?
</P>
<P>
   Yes. Certainly. Of course.
</P>
<P>
   That said, let's stroll the plank, shall we?
</P>
<P>
   Great: ``Once and Again'' (ABC), ``The West Wing'' (NBC),
``Freaks and Geeks'' (NBC), ``Malcolm in the Middle'' (Fox).
</P>
<P>
   Good: ``Judging Amy'' (CBS), ``Roswell'' (WB), ``Action'' (Fox),
``Law &AMP; Order: Special Victims Unit'' (NBC).
</P>
<P>
   Promising: ``Grown Ups'' (UPN), ``Angel,'' (WB), ``Family Law''
(CBS), ``Get Real'' (Fox), ``Popular'' (WB), ``Now and Again''
(CBS).
</P>
<P>
   Stinkers: ``The Parkers'' (UPN), ``The Mike O'Malley Show''
(NBC), ``Shasta McNasty'' (UPN), ``Wasteland'' (ABC), ``Manchester
Prep'' (Fox), ``Odd Man Out'' (ABC).
</P>
<P>
   Who knows what'll stick, what won't. Figure in: days, times,
competition, whether a show's producer has ticked off a network
president. ``Once and Again'' and ``Judging Amy'' go head-to-head,
``Action'' is on Thursdays (where NBC still reigns, remember?),
``Freaks and Geeks'' is so dead-on it could turn off teens looking
for fantasy and adults unwilling to relive their own geekdom.
</P>
<P>
   Be selective. Be critical. Sample stuff you don't normally
watch. See what life is like outside the NBC Thursday universe,
away from WB's fountain of youth.
</P>
<P>
   You may just find something you love, something you desire,
something you rush home to catch each week.
</P>
<P>
   Until they cancel it.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is TV critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
