<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0353 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN     09-21 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTOR SAYS PRAYER GAINING WIDER ACCEPTANCE AS A HEALING POWER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dr. Larry Dossey began practicing as an internist in Dallas
several years ago, he was an agnostic who never considered praying
for his patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was skeptical of all this religious stuff,'' Dossey said.
</P>
<P>
   Not anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Dossey, a highly respected physician who was chief of staff of
Medical City Dallas in the 1980s, now is the nation's most
passionate advocate of combining faith and the practice of
medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The data was just too strong to ignore,'' Dossey said this
week. His own experiences with inexplicable ``miracle cures,'' and
studies showing that prayer and faith can be a factor in whether
someone gets well, finally convinced him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that grabbed me by the ears were the studies,'' said
Dossey, who received his doctorate from the University of Texas
Southwestern Medical School in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   Dossey's bestseller, ``Healing Words: The Power of Prayer and
the Practice of Medicine,'' and his ``Prayer Is Good Medicine''
told of his change of heart and cited convincing studies indicating
that prayer can help heal.
</P>
<P>
   Now he has a new book, ``Reinventing Medicine: Beyond Mind-Body
to a New Era of Healing,'' which updates the minirevolution going
on in which physicians and other healers are beginning to take
spirituality seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The movement has its critics _ those who say the studies are
flawed or not extensive enough. But they are not going to slow down
the trend, Dossey believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who have a cynical attitude toward this movement are
picking on the most superficial studies and avoiding the strong
ones,'' he said. ``They seem to be oblivious to the good this can
do. But they are doing nothing to slow down this rapidly evolving
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Reinventing Medicine'' goes a step further, declaring that
so-called isolated incidences of miracle happenings in medicine are
an example of a higher spiritual force at work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought another look at this was in order,'' Dossey said.
``When I wrote `Healing Words' in 1993, no medical schools had
courses in this. Now more than 60 medical schools have courses in
spirituality and healing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dossey's new book again cites studies from Duke University
Medical School and other respected institutions indicating that
prayer, even long-distance prayer, can have a salutory effect on
healing.
</P>
<P>
   But he goes even further in suggesting that the spiritual
dimension should be a major part of medical practice. He urges
doctors to consider use of dreams, intuition and even ``hunches''
given to them by patients in diagnosing and treating illnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do get more outrageous,'' Dossey said.
</P>
<P>
   He cites a study from the Southwest SIDS (Sudden Infant Death)
Center near Houston indicating that 21 percent of parents who lost
a child to sudden infant death syndrome had strong feelings that
their child would die.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I believe is that there is some faculty _ I call it the
`non-local' mind _ which sometimes causes us to see into the
future,'' he said. ``I know we have ridiculed it and scoffed at it
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Dossey said that in his own practice, he once had a woman who
dreamed she had three white spots on her left ovary.
</P>
<P>
   ``The radiologist laughed at her until his sonogram proved she
was right,'' Dossey said.
</P>
<P>
   Although he admits that not all of his conclusions are backed by
solid studies, Dossey declares in his new book that it is time for
physicians to use some of the same techniques physicians used in
earlier eras of medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even 100 years ago, most doctors were comfortable with using
prayer in medicine,'' he said. ``There wasn't a hell of a lot
doctors could do at that time, so they had better pray.''
</P>
<P>
   Dossey said that doctors should use spiritual forces as a matter
of practicality to help improve the chances of recovering from
heart disease or cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the biggest payoff that can come from these studies is the
realization that there is something about human beings that goes
beyond the brain and the physical,'' Dossey said. ``I don't know
any other way to slice and dice this.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he realizes he is mixing science and theology, Dossey
is convinced that the mysterious effects of spirituality on healing
can only lead to the conclusion that humans live beyond their
physical lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying I have a soul meter,'' he said. ``But I believe
there is something about us that is eternal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at 817-390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
