<HEADLINE>
HOW DOES RYDER RATE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ How quickly has this event grown? Consider
that the PGA of America will issue roughly 1,200 media credentials
for the matches at The Country Club, and USA and NBC will combine
to televise 27 hours of competition over the three days. To put
that growth in perspective, the 1983 Ryder Cup at Palm Beach
Gardens in Florida attracted a handful of media members (most of
them from the British press) and a local ABC affiliate shooting
highlight clips. Live coverage did not begin until 1989, and then
only on cable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(! used as column separator) &QL; 
Year ! Site ! Networks ! Hours !(1) Rating &QL; 
1989 ! Belfry (England) ! USA ! 9 ! 1.2 &QL; 
1991 ! Kiawah Island (S.C.) ! USA ! 15 1/2 ! 1.3 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! ! NBC ! 9 ! 2.5 &QL; 
1993 ! Belfry (England) ! USA ! 8 3/4 ! 1.1 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! ! NBC ! 8 1/2 ! 3.8 &QL; 
1995 ! Oak Hill (N.Y.) ! USA ! 10 1/2 ! 1.5 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! ! NBC ! 9 ! 4.1 &QL; 
1997 ! Valderrama (Spain) ! USA ! 10 ! 1.6 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ! ! NBC ! 10 1/2 ! 3.7 &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTABLE &QL; 
 &QL; 
While the national audience has been weak over the years, Boston
has _ by comparison _ embraced the Ryder Cup. In 1997, the 6.3
rating was tops in its time period for Boston and sixth overall.
Sunday's broadcast was 5.3, seventh overall. In '95, it drew a 7.2
on Saturday, twice the number of any college football game that
day, and 7.3 on Sunday, second only to the 4 p.m. NFL game
(Patriots were off that day). &QL; 
 &QL; 
USA paid $200,000 in rights fees for the first live coverage in
1989. That jumped to $2 million when NBC jumped into the picture in
'91. This year, the combined rights fee is $13 million. &QL; 
 &QL; 
(1. Average national rating) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
