<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0388 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-     09-21 0595
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXASATLARGE-CHAPMAN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SECRET'S IN THE MARINADE FOR TECH-STYLE CHICKEN-FRIED STEAK
</HEADLINE>
 (Resending to fix coding) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ART CHAPMAN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Even in peacetime, Mark Miller can't talk much about his job.
</P>
<P>
   He works in a laboratory at Texas Tech University in Lubbock and
what he does is secret.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is a professor of meat science and muscle biology and
right now he is applying his knowledge and expertise toward the
making of a really good, tasty, uniform chicken-fried steak.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder the need for stealth.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't as easy as it sounds.
</P>
<P>
   In the first place, we already have some pretty good
chicken-fried steak in Texas. And secondly, not everyone agrees on
how a good chicken-fried steak tastes. Some people like the
deep-fried kind, others prefer pan-fried. No one likes those frozen
little wafers sold in chain grocery stores, and let's not even talk
about cutlets.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been a pretty secret kind of development over the last
couple of years,'' Miller said of his research. ``We've been
working on it for two years and we think we can have the program up
and running by the turn of the century.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Miller and the people in the food lab at Texas Tech
have been working on more than just chicken-fried steak. The
project involves other cuts of steak like tenderloins, rib-eyes,
and strip loins. They even have some oven-ready roasts.
</P>
<P>
   But the chicken-fried steaks are where the real glamour lies.
They are literally the toughest cuts to master.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a proprietary, patented process,'' Miller said. ``We
marinate cuts of meat from the chuck and round _ normally tough and
dry and lower quality. We make it juicy, flavorful and tender.''
</P>
<P>
   The marinade is the secret part. Don't expect a quick wash in a
store-bought teriyaki sauce to work. It takes a good deal more.
</P>
<P>
   Miller and the folks at the food lab are working with Texas
T-Bone Express, a consortium of cattle raisers and feedlot
operators in Amarillo who will eventually market the product. Texas
T-Bone has put up the money for research and Tech put forth some of
its students as tasters.
</P>
<P>
   It was clearly an equitable trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a sensory panel here at the lab,'' Miller explained.
``We actually eat the meat and determine how much, or little, we
like it.''
</P>
<P>
   There have been some pretty bad efforts, he said. Some of the
early tests were tough in texture and bad in taste.
</P>
<P>
   But the final products are good, he insisted. ``We're ready. All
we need is a couple of million bucks to turn on the switch.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller and Texas T-Bone Express believe that the biggest problem
with beef these days is its varied quality. Beef producers claim
you can't tell one chicken from the other _ they all taste the same
_ but the same can't be said of beef.
</P>
<P>
   The marinade process will take care of that, they believe.
Whether you buy your steak at a restaurant, a wholesaler or
retailer, it will always taste juicy and tender. No matter the
cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't say what's in the marinade right now,'' Miller said.
``But it is something that offers quality consistency in beef
products.''
</P>
<P>
   That really leaves only one additional problem. Who's going to
make the gravy?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not our problem,'' Miller said. ``We'll leave that to
someone else.''
</P>
<P>
   (Art Chapman writes a weekly column on things Texan. You can
call him at (817) 390-7422, or e-mail: artc(at)star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1721EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
