<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0221 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0391 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE23-COX     09-21 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A rock-solid source of healing for spirit
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 23.
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MCCAYSVILLE, Ga. _ Call it the Rorschach rock: Look at it, and
you see so much more than a hunk of stone jutting from the earth,
halfway down the hill from the cabin toward Fightingtown Creek.
Like an ever-changing inkblot, this rock is a topographical wonder,
a garden feature, a place to sit and lie and be. And for me it is,
now more than ever, a dispenser of much-needed medicine.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, The Rock is one great piece of stone. Shaped like a
half-moon, with ruffled edges resembling flower petals on the
curved side, it measures some 20 feet across and 10 feet deep.
</P>
<P>
   Starting a year ago, it grew more and more impressive as Lyn, an
avid archaeologist by love, if not training, and I began shoveling,
hacking, snipping, pulling, scraping, chopping, sawing and sweeping
away layers of dirt, mosses, lichen, brush, weeds, saplings.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from under those stubborn layers were more than a dozen
mysterious markings _ gashes pointing toward the creek. The
indentations, up to about an inch deep and 6 inches long, intrigue
all who venture onto The Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Do these markings belong to Cherokees who held council meetings
on this great stone? Do they have meaning, mystical or ordinary? Or
do they simply result from chops with a tool of some sort? Seeking
answers, I arranged for The Rock to have a visitor: Tommy Charles,
archaeologist at the University of South Carolina in Columbia. He
spent some time one steamy day examining the big outcropping of
gray stone, during his summertime tour of North Georgia
petroglyphs.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy's visit was part of my threat to garden on the side of the
cabin that faces the creek _ a daunting task, considering the
land's stumps, roots, rocks and death-defying steepness. Still, it
must be done, as I need my stamp on the land. So, as I reached
near-saturation after planting furiously on the road side, I began
planning my plantings on the aerobic slope down to Fightingtown.
Uncovering The Rock necessarily had been the first step, as this
piece of stone is the focal point of all focal points, no matter
what flora I put in. On the creek side, all design flows from The
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   Just as we humans have an undeniable need to mark any piece of
land we light on, planting trees, shrubs, flowers, even in spaces
as abundant with natural beauty as the Blue Ridge, we also have an
insatiable desire to know intimate details of our spaces. Who lived
here? What signs of their existence did they leave? What does it
all mean to me? Thus, my invitation to Tommy Charles.
</P>
<P>
   With neighbor friends Ethelene Dyer Jones and her husband, the
Rev. Grover Jones, we climbed down the slope toward The Rock. The
closer we got, the more we saw, although we did not necessarily see
the same sights.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at one marking whose shape was particularly distinctive,
Ethelene, a gifted poet with the eye of a romantic, likened it to
``a bird in flight.'' The grooves remind me of birds, too. The
tracks of birds, large, winged creatures with feet of fire that lit
on this stone and burned in their footprints.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy conceded the grooves are unusual, and he understood our
temptation to romanticize them, to ascribe their existence to those
who belonged to the land before us.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, he was honor-bound to offer the most plausible
explanation, based on his examinations of many, many rocks and his
consultations with geologists over the years: ``Water is the
biggest culprit,'' he said. ``Ice is part of it, too, with the
freezes and thaws.'' During this process, he said, some material,
soft rock, maybe, or chunks of quartz, gets pushed out of the rock,
leaving the gashes.
</P>
<P>
   Tommy painted a picture of a world within The Rock filled with
creative chaos: ``The rock splits, and hot gases and water come
through it; residual quartz is left to bind it back together again.
All kinds of weird things go in rock. They appear cultural but are
really natural. Nature's still the champ'' in designing, whether on
a rock or in a garden.
</P>
<P>
   Though I had counted on learning that people made the scars, I
take natural comfort in knowing the gashes may be yet another
result of a beautiful power that always awes and inspires.
</P>
<P>
   And heals. In fact, whatever else The Rock is, it is a healing
place. For body and spirit.
</P>
<P>
   I will use it much in the coming months as I take strong,
wearying, doctor-prescribed medicines to recover from an illness.
During that time my column _ beginning with this one _ will appear
every other Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Lee May writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
