<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0392 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-TULIP-BULBS0923-COX     09-21 1276
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TULIP-BULBS0923-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tulipmania! Crazy or not, fall's the time to think spring
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Thursday, Sept. 23.
 &HT;    B y Danny c . Flanders
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stop what you're doing. Stick a note on the fridge. Tie a string
around your finger.
</P>
<P>
   Just don't forget to plant tulips this fall.
</P>
<P>
   If you do, come March, as you emerge from months of wintry
blahs, you'll miss out on that first burst of seasonal color _ the
simple reassurance that spring is just around the corner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every year, people forget to plant spring bulbs in the fall,
and we get this flurry of phone calls in January from people saying
they bought them but never got around to planting them and is it
too late,'' said Sally Ferguson, a spokeswoman for the Dutch bulb
industry. ``Then the next wild run of calls comes in April and May,
when they want to know where they can buy bulbs to plant for that
spring. People are so sad when they find out it's too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Fall begins today, and spring bulbs are popping up daily in
garden centers and mail-order catalogs and on Web sites. More than
half a million will be sold in the United States, and this fall
shoppers are expected to flock to tulips in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Fueling their interest are half a dozen new books and even a
Hollywood film about the simple bulb's rich history. Steven
Spielberg's DreamWorks studio has optioned the rights to Deborah
Moggach's romantic novel ``Tulip Fever,'' set in 17th-century
Amsterdam against the backdrop of Tulipmania _ the speculative
stock market scandal that arose in the Netherlands from
astronomical prices demanded for tulip bulbs.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1600s, the bulbs _ native to the eastern
Mediterranean, not the Netherlands _ were sold by weight, usually
while still in the ground. Traders earned as much as 60,000 florins
a month (about $44,000 by today's standards), and people rushing to
cash in traded family homes, small businesses and even dowries. By
1637, the bottom fell out, and thousands met financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fascinating,'' said Ferguson, who works at the
Netherlands Flower Bulb Information Center in New York. ``Beyond
the Dutch economy, the economy of Europe faltered as well, because
it really had big ripple effects.''
</P>
<P>
   So why the Tulipmania mania? Some economic experts believe angst
over Internet stocks _ many of which are considered grossly
overvalued _ may mirror the earlier episode, Ferguson said. Others
believe there's more to it than comparing financial frenzies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just such a simple, elegant flower, with tight buds, and
is good for cutting,'' said Chris Hansen of Wayside Gardens, a
mail-order nursery in Hodges, S.C. ``Plus, there's the fact that
they bloom when nothing else is out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Many adults were first exposed to tulips in kindergarten, when
the bud's pure classic shape made it a favorite for Crayola
drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Others are fascinated by the flower's ``movement'' in the garden
or vase. ``They almost dance,'' Ferguson said. ``After they're cut,
they can grow an inch taller because they follow the light and bend
with gravity. You never see them as stiff little soldiers.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the critical planting time. The autumn ritual of
buying and planting bulbs is a means for cleansing the gardening
slate of last summer's failures and looking ahead to spring 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some points to consider:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How to buy: About half of all bulbs are sold by mail-order
catalogs, published in summer; the rest are available at garden
centers in early fall. Catalogs offer more variety than retailers,
but bulbs can cost more because of shipping expenses. Regardless,
buy early while selection is greatest.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What to buy: Nearly all tulip bulbs sold by the Dutch are
propagated and grown in the Netherlands. Currently, more than 3,500
hybrids and species are available. Yet many gardeners opt for the
varieties grown nearly four centuries ago, such as Rembrandts
(circa 1610), the famous mottled tulips that launched the trading
frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   New tulips drawing wows include three late bloomers _ Dordogne,
with a raspberry-edged tangerine flower; Toyota, rosy red-edged in
white; and Avignon, dark rose edged in orange _ said Gerald Suhonen
of Van Bloem Gardens, a wholesale bulb and perennial distributor in
Alpharetta. ``Orange has become more and more popular, especially
when combined with blues and purples,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  When to plant: Late October to mid-November, while soil is
still warm enough to encourage root growth.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How to plant: Choose a sunny location and loosen the soil at
least 6 inches. Amend with compost and 10-10-10 fertilizer, mixing
thoroughly. (Feed tulips again in spring once leaves emerge.)
Slightly mound the soil to promote good drainage. Plant bulbs, tips
pointing up, about 6 inches deep, spaced about one bulb's width
apart. For best effect, plant in masses, not rows. Cover the bulbs,
water and top with about 2 inches of mulch.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  How to use: Because tulips need about three months of cool,
sunny weather after blooming to rebloom a second year, treat them
as annuals in this climate. Combine them with violas, muscari,
hostas or winter vegetables, said Mildred Pinnell, horticulturist
at the Atlanta Botanical Garden.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to use tulips so they come up through a ground cover
of parsley, evergreen thyme or oregano,'' said Dottie Myers, an
Atlanta landscape architect. ``Since you plant pansies earlier than
bulbs, you can go back and plant tulips between them.''
</P>
<P>
   Pansies? Make a note of it.
</P>
<P>
