<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOLF-WESTWING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `West Wing' chaos on the money, Blitzer says
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CNN's Wolf Blitzer was a White House correspondent for seven
years. Although he's now an anchor, he says that during his tenure,
``I spent more time in the West Wing of the White House than I did
at home.''
</P>
<P>
   So we gave Blitzer a tape of the pilot of NBC's ``The West
Wing'' for a reality check. How well does it capture both the feel
and the details of life in the White House? His reaction:
</P>
<P>
   ``This White House reminds me of the first year of the Clinton
administration. It was chaos, a real mess. You had all these close
aides from the campaign without a whole lot of experience in
government, and it was like a little kids' soccer game: Everybody
just goes after the ball. I think they were trying to re-create
that mess.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the details:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Everyone referring to the president as POTUS, an acronym for
President of the United States: ``That is widely used. The White
House has this paging system, and on that paging system it's always
POTUS: `POTUS will be in the Oval Office in 10 minutes.'''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The ubiquitous beepers: ``That's true. In this White House the
beeper is a very powerful communicator. But most (aides) have them
vibrating on their belts so you don't hear them going off. People
are always looking down at their belts and grabbing them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The physical layout: ``There were some serious flaws. When you
walk into the West Wing the lobby is really small. They made it
look huge, with huge marble floors. The Roosevelt Room has no glass
on the doors, and they made it look bigger than it really is. In
the press briefing room, the presidential seal behind the podium
was smaller than it really is.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The speech: ``They mention the president giving his Sunday
morning radio address. It isn't Sunday, it's a Saturday morning
radio address.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The press: ``I was sort of dreading that they'd have some
fictitious guy from a cable news organization with a beard and a
weird name.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Overall: ``Some of it was silly. Some of it was pretty
authentic. I thought as a TV show it was not `The Sopranos' or
`ER,' the ones I really like. It kept my interest. I think people
in Washington will like it, but people outside the Beltway might
not follow it too easily.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
