<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Wednesday, Sept. 22, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.)
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   An autumnal air mass will cover the Eastern states as a frontal
system shifts off the Atlantic seaboard. Farther west, unseasonable
warmth will spread from the Northwestern states to the northern and
central Plains. While most of the nation will be dry, moisture from
the remnants of Pacific Tropical Storm Hilary will bring numerous
showers to the Southwestern states.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and a few sprinkles will linger from the Appalachians to
the Middle Atlantic and Northeast coasts early Wednesday in the
wake of a cold front. Showers will linger through midday in
northern New England and near the North Carolina coast where
onshore winds will persist. Meanwhile, cool breezes from the north
and northwest will gradually deliver drier air to the region
resulting in some afternoon sunshine from the interior Northeast to
the Middle Atlantic states.
</P>
<P>
   After a chilly dawn, a mild day with abundant sunshine will
develop from the southern Plains to the interior Southeast. Patchy
clouds and a few showers will occur near the eastern and southern
shores of Florida as a cold front moves into the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In the Western states, high-level winds from the south will draw
tropical moisture north through the deserts of the Southwest into
central parts of California and Nevada. As a result, there will be
variable clouds and scattered showers. A few afternoon
thunderstorms will form, especially over the mountainous terrain.
Farther north, a sprawling zone of high pressure will sponsor
mainly sunny and very warm weather in most of the Northwestern
states.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Distant Danger
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday, Hurricane Gert passed 100 miles east of Bermuda
where winds gusted to 74 mph. But nearly 1000 miles away in Puerto
Rico, residents were being warned of danger from the storm as waves
up to 18 feet were crashing along the northern shores. The large
swells were spawned by the hurricane during the last several days
as it moved gradually north, churning the waters of the central
Atlantic. When the wind stirs the open sea, a wide spectrum of wave
sizes are generated. In time, smaller waves disperse, leaving
larger swells to carry on toward distant shores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1732EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0226 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0403 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-FLOOD-FARM22-COX     09-21 0964
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-FARM22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FLOODWATERS SPREADING POLLUTANTS, CONSERVATIONISTS WARN
 &HT;    By BOB DART and EUNICE MOSCOSO
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Contaminated floodwater from Hurricane Floyd is
spreading farm wastes and other pollutants into surrounding
waterways, conservationists warned Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recovering from a hurricane is tough enough without this major
water pollution crisis,'' said Carl Pope, executive director of the
Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   Millions of gallons of hog waste have washed out of giant
lagoons used to hold the excrement on North Carolina pig farms. On
Maryland's Eastern Shore, tons of chicken waste have floated into
the Chesapeake Bay. In addition, the floodwaters have been tainted
by carcasses of an estimated 2.4 million dead chickens, 500,000
dead turkeys and 100,000 dead hogs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wastewater treatment plants have failed. Septic tanks have
failed. Hog lagoons have been overrun. And swamps have emptied,''
said Dennis McBride, North Carolina's health director. ``That means
that all of the floodwater has the potential to have contamination
of some kind.''
</P>
<P>
   Floodwaters ``could harbor bacterial disease,'' McBride said in
a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Polluted floodwaters could also cause widespread environmental
damage as they mix into river systems.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the flooding, the Sierra Club urged the
Environmental Protection Agency to ban the lagoons used to store
animal waste and to prohibit ``factory farms'' from operating in
flood plains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The environmental disaster caused by the inundation of hog
lagoons and massive hog and chicken farms in North Carolina and
Maryland is a wake-up call for tough national rules on industrial
livestock operations,'' said Pope.
</P>
<P>
   However, Beth Anne Mumford, a spokesperson for the North
Carolina Pork Council, said it is too early to assess the
environmental damage. There has been no confirmation of the state's
estimate of 100,000 dead hogs, she said. ``Farmers are still out in
boats trying to save their animals.''
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina is the nation's largest producer of turkeys, its
second-largest producer of hogs and its third-largest producer of
chickens. Environmental activists have long urged stronger
regulation of large pork and poultry agribusinesses.
</P>
<P>
   These operations are more like ``a factory than a family farm,''
said Ed Hopkins, the Sierra Club's senior Washington
representative.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, in ``giant hog barns,'' the waste of
thousands of animals is flushed out into lagoons stretching across
several acres. The liquid portion of the waste is eventually
sprayed onto hay fields as fertilizer. The remaining sludge
decomposes _ ``giving off tremendous odors'' _ but eventually
builds up until a new lagoon must be dug.
</P>
<P>
   Floyd's floodwaters have overflowed some of these lagoons. The
result is not only possible contamination of drinking water from
wells but also large amounts of nitrogen and phosphorous being
flushed into rivers. These chemicals ``basically kill rivers,''
said Hopkins, by spurring algae growth. Oxygen is depleted, so fish
die.
</P>
<P>
   The effect is the same when waste from chickens and turkeys is
washed into the Chesapeake Bay, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   A flood of this magnitude is the worst possible scenario for hog
waste lagoons, said Marion Smith, executive director of the Neuse
River Foundation, a North Carolina environmental protection group.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many words for disaster do you know?'' asked Smith. She
described aerial photos showing pink ribbons of pig waste streaming
from some barely flooded lagoons. On completely submerged farms,
the waste water is completely mixed and indistinguishable from the
surrounding floodwaters, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Neuse riverkeeper Rick Dove said a disaster like this was
inevitable. ``It's never been a question of if. It's always been a
question of when,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Gaskins, a hog farmer in Black Jack, N.C., said Tar
River flooding has not been a problem for his operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had just got through pumping my lagoon down where it was
supposed to be'' before Floyd struck, he explained. When rains came
and the lagoon threatened to overflow, he called the state Division
of Water Quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave me permission to pump it back down,'' he said.
Normally farmers are not allowed to spray the liquid waste onto
already soaked fields.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in North Carolina, an immediate health concern is the
disposal of rotting livestock carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   State officials said two portable incinerators were already
burning dead hogs and that 10 more will be brought in from Florida.
Above-ground composting is being considered for poultry carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture commissioner Jim Graham notified the EPA that the
state plans to use several insecticides approved for other uses to
kill blowflies that feed on livestock carcasses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fly populations could become a huge public health menace,''
Graham told the Associated Press. The insecticides will be applied
to hog, turkey, chicken, cattle and horse carcasses before they are
buried or burned.
</P>
<P>
   The polluted floodwaters pose ``all kinds'' of health risks,
said Debbie Crain, a spokeswoman with the North Carolina Public
Health Service. For instance, drinking the contaminated water could
cause gastrointestinal diseases, she said, and getting it on the
skin could cause infections.
</P>
<P>
   However, floodwaters are not associated with hepatitis A or
typhoid fever, she said, and the agency is not recommending any
special immunizations _ except a tetanus shot for those who haven't
had one in the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   T. Scott Batchelor of the Greenville Daily Reflector contributed
to this story.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
