<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SKOL-VIOLENCE-COX     09-21 0628
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKOL-VIOLENCE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ministers bring message of change to Ohio with prayer breakfast
 &HT;    (EDS: ALSO MOVED IN (l) Lifestyle category as
PRAYER-CHANGES-COX.)
 &HT;    By Kathy Whyde Jesse
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ The Rev. Jimmy Adcox and the Rev. Laird Duran
aren't itinerant preachers by choice. ``We're just a couple of
local ministers who want to go back home,'' Adcox says.
</P>
<P>
   But ``home'' is Jonesboro, Ark., and because they were in the
wrong place at the right time, they now reluctantly find themselves
in demand.
</P>
<P>
   On March 24, 1998, two boys at Westside Middle School pulled the
fire alarm and waited in a nearby woods as students and teachers
filed outside. Then they shot at them, killing four students and
one teacher.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Adcox, Duran and other Jonesboro ministers were
called upon to plan a memorial service, and they began to learn
what it takes to heal a grieving community.
</P>
<P>
   It's a lesson they shared Tuesday at the fourth annual Dayton
Prayer Breakfast, held in the Dayton Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
   The event drew 1,750 people, down from last year, when 3,000
attended. Event organizers said the decrease might have been
because the event was moved this year from spring to fall.
</P>
<P>
   The theme for this year's breakfast was ``No Greater Time Than
Now: Prayer for the Youth of our City'' _ a fitting topic given
recent national tragedies such as the shootings at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., in April, said Dayton Mayor Mike
Turner, who hosts the event and chooses the guest speakers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Duran and Adcox were asked to come to Littleton to
assist clergy and counselors. This is only the third time they have
spoken publicly about their experiences, and they had mixed
feelings about speaking in Dayton, concerned that anyone might
think they are capitalizing on the tragedy. Another member of the
Jonesboro clergy scheduled to speak _ the Rev. Jack Harris _ pulled
out at the last minute. ``He feels an incredible closeness to the
kids at Westside, and he didn't want to be perceived as betraying
their trust and confidence in any way,'' Adcox explained.
</P>
<P>
   Duran described Jonesboro's Westside neighborhood as
country-turning-suburban, ``one of those places that is safe.''
When he heard about the shootings, he remembered thinking, ``This
isn't happening in my little town.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other clergy worked as a team, finding ways to help
friends and family members begin the hard work of healing, which
continues today. Some clergy still visit the school regularly.
There was never a trial _ the attackers were juveniles. So parents
were left to deal with their anger: ``Their child was dead, and
nothing happened.'' Helping them deal with anger became part of
Duran's ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them what to tell the people of Dayton,'' Duran said.
``One woman said, 'Tell them it's not the '50s anymore.' The world
has changed, and we need to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to find new ways to minister. I used to think that
Lutherans did their thing, Baptists did their thing, and so on. But
we have our faith in common. These are all our children. We are
church. And we are called to look after all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Adcox praised the concept of a prayer breakfast, ``but it's not
enough to come together and pray. Prayers have to have feet and
hands.'' He urged the audience to make a difference in the life a
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to be paralyzed by the spiritual devastation all
around us. Tell yourself, 'I can't do everything, but I can do
something. God, how can you use me?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Whyde Jesse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio. E-mail: kathywhydejesse(AT)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
