<P>
   TEXAS AT LARGE-CHAPMAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Even in peacetime, Mark Miller can't talk much about
his job. He works in a laboratory at Texas Tech University and what
he does is secret. Miller is a professor of meat science and muscle
biology and right now he is applying his knowledge and expertise
toward the making of a really good, tasty, uniform chicken-fried
steak. No wonder the need for stealth. By ART CHAPMAN. Story has
moved in ``a'' general news category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Great _ and not so great _ expectations for fall TV.
By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SWINDELL-BOOKSHELF &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ While the Hemingway centennial is solemnized by formal
literary occasions, fans of another esteemed ``man's author'' may
not realize that 1999 also marks the 100th birthday of their guy,
who at the very least is Ernest Hemingway's equal in the measure of
popularity. He's Cecil Lewis Troughton Smith. Well, he was that,
until he changed his name legally to Cecil Scott Forester. He's
identified literarily as C.S. Forester, but the name on his calling
card is forever Horatio Hornblower. As Arthur Conan Doyle is to
Sherlock Holmes, so is Forester to Hornblower. By LARRY SWINDELL.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
