<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0429 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-ECU-COX     09-21 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-ECU-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flood forces students from homes
 &HT;    By Amy L. Royster
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ An estimated 2,000 to 5,000 East Carolina
University students, faculty and staff have been displaced from
their homes by flooding related to Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   Dean of Students Ronald Speier said Tuesday that estimates are
rough and that they were made by tallying the number of flooded
apartments in the area. He said there also are no precise numbers
on how many faculty and staff were displaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know four of our campus police officers are homeless
because of flooding, and about half of the people in the mail room
were devastated, but came to work anyway to keep their minds off
their situations at home,'' Speier said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite rumors that classes were canceled for the entire
semester, administrators assure students that classes will resume
on Monday. Parent's Weekend festivities, planned for this weekend,
are also canceled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking all students not to come back to Greenville
until Sunday,'' Cliff Webster, president of the Student Government
Association, said. ``We also want any student who has not called
home to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   ECU Police Captain J.P. Smith reports no flood related injuries
to students. In addition to heightened patrols, the department is
providing special services such as driving some students to the
Raleigh-Durham airport and charging the electric wheel-chairs of
physically handicapped students.
</P>
<P>
   As of Tuesday, one student, 18-year-old Aaron Christopher
Childs, reported missing earlier this week, had still not been
located. Childs was last seen Thursday at 2 p.m. The Greenville
Police Department is investigating.
</P>
<P>
   A temporary shelter at Jones Residence Hall housed more than 100
students Tuesday morning. The shelter was established for students
who cannot return to their flooded Greenville apartments or
permanent homes. Calls by area residents, willing to volunteer
extra rooms to students in need of housing, inundated a telephone
matching service. By Tuesday afternoon, Speier said, only 13
students remained in need of more permanent housing.
</P>
<P>
   Speier said that while most of the students in the Jones shelter
have been placed with families, an influx of students returning for
classes next week will mean many more will need a place to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who want to go ahead and be put on a list to house
these students next week can call the ECU-HOME line
(252-328-4663),'' Speier said. ``Some people are offering their
homes for the entire semester. Some are providing a place to stay
for an evening and a warm meal. We will do our best to match
people's needs on both sides.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will provide a Flood Relief Center to provide counseling,
clothing and legal services,'' Speier said. ``The Student
Government Association also has an attorney on retainer, who we
will try to get down here to answer questions for students.''
</P>
<P>
   Other UNC-system schools are offering help to ECU in the form of
donated materials and financial assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have had some of the most wonderful expressions of support
from our sister institutions,'' said Chancellor Richard Eakin.
</P>
<P>
   Webster has fielded several calls from people affiliated with
ECU's sister institutions, which want to offer assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Chapel Hill and State are taking up monetary donations
on their campuses,'' Webster said. ``SGA will make sure that money
gets into students' hands.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our administration is working heavily to get us back in the
class and get us all on line again,'' Webster said. ``We're a
family at ECU, we've pulled together in the past and we will pull
together now.''
</P>
<P>
   Amy L. Royster writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
