<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 17:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0434 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TALENT-AGENT-ART-NYT &LR;      09-21 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TALENT-AGENT-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
END OF AN ODD COUPLE ROILS HOLLYWOOD'S TALENT AGENTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ Hollywood partnerships, like Hollywood marriages,
often don't survive the high-pressure strains they're subject to.
Michael Ovitz and Ron Meyer, once best friends who helped found the
Creative Artists Agency, barely speak.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Katzenberg, formerly of Disney, and Michael Eisner
loathe each other. Don Simpson and Jerry Bruckheimer's successful
producing partnership was virtually over even before Simpson died
after years of drug abuse. And Bob Daly and Terry Semel, a
successful and enduring partnership that ran Warner Brothers, left
the studio two months ago and may now go their separate ways.
</P>
<P>
   And then there were Jim Wiatt and Jeff Berg. For nearly a decade
the two men ran International Creative Management, a top talent
agency representing such high-priced stars as Julia Roberts, Mel
Gibson and Jodie Foster. Berg, cool, cerebral and a bit aloof, was
the agency's No. 1. By contrast Wiatt, the No. 2, was known as
``the good cop,'' approachable and friendly, a schmoozer, an agent
who enjoyed guiding the careers not only of actors but of studio
executives and producers. The two men, an odd couple, seemed
inseparable.
</P>
<P>
   Until last month.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 6, Wiatt announced that he was quitting International
Creative Management after a 22-year tenure, most recently as
co-chairman and co-chief executive. Three days later, the William
Morris Agency announced the appointment of Wiatt as president and
co-chief executive, succeeding Arnold Rifkin, who resigned.
</P>
<P>
   The title itself was a bit of a comedown for Wiatt, but the
money was not: he is earning at least twice what he was at ICM and
possibly more than $4 million, according to rival talent agents.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt's departure marked the biggest talent agency upheaval
since Ovitz left Creative Artists to take on the presidency of the
Walt Co. in 1994. Ovitz was dismissed from his job at Disney by
Michael D. Eisner, the chairman, and is now back representing
clients as a manager.
</P>
<P>
   The decision by Wiatt, 52, to move less than two miles west to
the William Morris office in Beverly Hills has not only set off
seismic tremors in the lucrative but volatile talent agency
business. It underlined the way money, ego and power _ the forces
that drive Hollywood _ undermine even the most stable partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt, sipping coffee in his elegant house in Pacific Palisades
recently, said that internal turmoil at the agency over the last
year had taken a personal toll. In June, ICM replaced its premier
film agent in New York, Sam Cohn, 70, with two younger literary
agents. ``There was a lot of anger involved and a lot of threats,''
Wiatt said, ``and it was distracting and I found myself very
unhappy in that process.'' (ICM executives said Wiatt was part of
the process.)
</P>
<P>
   More significant for Wiatt, the agency had promoted Ed Limato, a
prominent film agent who represents such stars as Gibson, Michelle
Pfeiffer and Denzel Washington, and Nancy Josephson, a television
agent, to serve as co-presidents and essentially run the agency's
day-to-day business.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt said the decision left him ambivalent. Not only was a
close friend, David Wirtschafter, passed over at the last minute to
give the job to Limato, but Wiatt said he found his job diminished.
(Wirtschafter quit earlier this month and has joined Wiatt at
William Morris).
</P>
<P>
   ``It was originally going to be Nancy and David, and it became
Nancy and Ed,'' said Wiatt. ``I didn't have so much a problem with
Nancy and Ed on a personal level, but how we worked together was
kind of ill defined. I felt my management responsibilities had been
diminished, and I was not thrilled with that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Wiatt said, Berg ``was becoming more
fascinated by the technology and Internet world and seemed to spend
a great deal of time doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Berg said in an interview that, although he is first and
foremost a talent agent, it was vital to expand the agency into the
world of telecommunications, the Internet and satellite business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any client, studio or agent who has worked with me knows I've
remained and continue to be a full-time agent in all aspects of the
entertainment business,'' said Berg, who personally represents such
formidable moneymakers as James L. Brooks, the film and television
writer and director.
</P>
<P>
   When Wiatt left the agency, Berg said he was ``saddened'' and
that his former partner had made ``invaluable contributions'' to
ICM.
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt is well liked in Hollywood and is often seen at premieres
and at a choice table at hangouts like the Palm and the Grill. ``He
has this ability to be very honest, very direct and very
enthusiastic,'' said Sherry Lansing, chairwoman and chief executive
of Paramount Pictures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tells it to you straight. In a town where people don't
often have good things to say about each other, I don't think
you'll find anyone who doesn't like and respect Jimmy Wiatt.''
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt brought over most of his clients to William Morris,
including Eddie Murphy, Sylvester Stallone, Neil Simon, Nora Ephron
and Penny Marshall. William Morris itself has in recent years
emerged as one of the most powerful music and television agencies,
but the movie side has not rivaled such agencies as Creative
Artists and International Creative Management (William Morris' top
moneymakers include Bruce Willis, John Travolta, Bill Cosby, Clint
Eastwood and Arnold Schwarzenegger).
</P>
<P>
   Wiatt grew up in Los Angeles, attended the University of
Southern California and worked as an administrative assistant to
Sen. John Tunney. After Tunney's loss in 1976, Wiatt worked for the
Frank Cooper television agency and then became an assistant at ICM
to Guy McElwaine, the head of the movie department. He started his
climb after that.
</P>
<P>
   He said the agency business had changed remarkably over the last
20 years. ``When I started out all I needed to do was sign some
clients and get them jobs,'' he said. ``Now a good agent needs to
know the cable business, the first-run business, the foreign
finance business, the technology business. Successful agents have
got to make sure that their education and experience allows them to
give clients the opportunities to find jobs that they ordinarily
wouldn't find.''
</P>
<P>
   The people who enter the talent agency business have also
changed. Once, talent agents were mostly men with reputations as
sharks in bad suits. Now far more women have entered the business.
And agents, male and female, are almost uniformly wearing Prada
(Armani seems out). Moreover, many agents today are business school
and law school graduates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to think that I hustle,'' said Wiatt. ``But I don't
consider myself a hustler.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
