<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Wednesday, Sept. 11 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan. (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-QUAKE (Taipei, Taiwan) _ With the death toll from the
massive earthquake rising by the hour, rescuers work to free
thousands of people trapped in the rubble of high-rise apartment
buildings and houses that crumbled under the force of the quake. By
Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A Senate counterterrorism
committee hears from Justice and FBI witnesses on Clinton's
clemency for FALN members. The director of the FBI, in strongly
objecting to clemency for 16 Puerto Rican nationalists, said their
release would re-invigorate terrorist organizations in Puerto Rico.
According to documents released by Congress on Tuesday, Louis
Freeh, the FBI director, had warned the Justice Department that
releasing any of the prisoners ``would likely return committed,
experienced, sophisticated and hardened terrorists to the
clandestine movement.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
</P>
<P>
   ASIANAMERICANS-POLITICS (Los Angeles) _ In the relatively brief
span of one presidential cycle the role of Asian Americans in
national politics appears to have changed in fundamental ways.
After years as one of the most financially generous but
underrepresented ethnic minorities in American politics, many Asian
Americans are nursing deep wounds from what they regard as a string
of insulting scandals. And this time, they say, things will be
different. There will be less interest in photo opportunities with
the candidates, they say, and in its place a focus on getting more
Asian Americans appointed to positions in Washington and to
judgeships around the country and to bolster government efforts to
fight hate crimes and discrimination. By James Sterngold. 2,000
words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ The U.S. trade deficit surged to a
record $25.18 billion in July, as imports from western Europe,
China, Japan and Canada continued to grow. Economists had expected
the deficit to narrow from June's $24.6 billion gap, the previous
record. For the second month, imports topped $100 billion, at
$104.22 billion. Exports rose modestly, to $79.04 billion. The
dollar, which tumbled in Asian trading after the Bank of Japan
announced it was leaving monetary policy unchanged, extends its
slide. By David E. Sanger.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIVORCE (New York) _ The head of the Manhattan Matrimonial
Court has accepted tens of thousands of dollars in bribes over the
last seven years to expedite or falsify hundreds of divorces in the
city, prosecutors announce. Court officials are now pouring over
thousands of Manhattan divorce cases to determine how many
fraudulent divorces were granted, and how many unwitting bigamists
there may be in the city. If the divorces are found to be improper,
they could be thrown out, officials said. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   Reefers:
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ISRAEL (Berlin) _ Israel's prime minister, Ehud Barak,
becomes the first foreign leader to visit the new German capital.
By Roger Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   BELL-ATLANTIC-VODAFONE (Undated) _ Bell Atlantic and Vodafone
announce their coast-to-coast U.S. cellular joint venture. Bell
Atlantic will own 55 percent of the new $70 billion company, and
Vodafone of Britain will own 45 percent. By Laura M. Holson.
</P>
<P>
   FDA-ANTIBIOTIC (Washington) _ With drug-resistant bacteria on
the rise, the Food and Drug Administration has approved Synercid, a
new antibiotic that can rescue patients when vancomycin fails.
Syncercid, manufactured by Rhone Poulenc Rorer, is not a cure-all
for antibiotic resistance; it is only effective against a handful
of disease-causing bugs, but the drug could be a lifesaver for
some. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   SCHIELE-PAINTING (New York) _ An appeals court rules that the
Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, had no right to try
to seize Egon Schiele paintings on loan from Vienna for an exhibit
here. By Judith H. Dobrzynski. (MOVED)
</P>
