<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0467 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-GRIFTON-COX     09-21 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-GRIFTON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Volunteers fight uphill battle to help neighbors left homeless
in Grifton
 &HT;    By Nichole Monroe
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRIFTON, N.C. _ When Leona Miller went home after hours of
serving hot meals to hungry residents, she shook from weariness.
</P>
<P>
   Then she cried.
</P>
<P>
   She did not cry because she was tired from working. Miller cried
because no matter how many meals she served, she could do nothing
to change the fact that many of her friends and neighbors are
homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so tired I had the shakes, but I thought, I've come home
to a dry house and a soft chair,'' said Miller, her voice giving
way while her eyes held fast to tears. Miller was one of several
volunteers who for three days served meals at an unofficial
distribution center at Grifton School. ``I thought about all the
people I know who have nowhere to go. A lot of them lived paycheck
to paycheck, and now they don't even have that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Grifton, where 2,300 people live, dozens of families have
lost their homes along Contentnea Creek since rains from hurricanes
Dennis and Floyd plunged the stream from its banks. The water has
been indiscriminate: It has taken the homes of those in public
housing and of city officials.
</P>
<P>
   Flooding has cut the town in two, making it impossible to travel
from one side to the other on one street. The police and fire
stations are inundated and water is chest-high in the local grocery
store. Many businesses are also submerged.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, the townspeople volunteered to accept and distribute
items for flood victims. Residents opened the school center
themselves when they realized how much help their neighbors needed.
They cook three meals a day.
</P>
<P>
   Five days into the town's worst flood ever, volunteers, police
and city officials fought fatigue, but kept relief efforts going.
</P>
<P>
   ``Emotionally and physically right now, I'm drained,'' said
Police Chief Linwood Outlaw. He had already worked more than 40
hours straight before the flooding began.
</P>
<P>
   Because the police station is underwater, officers have had to
work out of their cars to coordinate efforts to bring supplies into
town. Some computers and phones were salvaged before the water got
too high, Outlaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Some officers who lost their own homes to water have also slept
in their cars. Officers are now working in 12-hour shifts out of
the town hall, where waters had receded.
</P>
<P>
   The process of putting the town back together will be slow.
</P>
<P>
   Residents regained power and phone service, and the water is
safe to drink. But sewage began to bubble up from manholes in the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   Exasperated, town commissioner Johnny Craft and Sheriff's
department Sgt. K.L. Kilpatrick slumped against a wall in the
Grifton School cafeteria. The pair had patrolled the town on
Jetskis, rescuing animals and delivering food to people who are
unable to leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's affected every walk of life,'' Craft said. ``We haven't
had time to even stop and think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Kilpatrick agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really starts to get to you when you deliver ice and water
to someone and they say, 'Thank you, we haven't seen anyone in five
days,''' she said. ``That's when your emotions start running. But
you have to stop and put it out your mind so you can go on to help
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Supplies streamed into the cafeteria all day. Volunteers at the
center said they still need powdered and canned milk, disposable
plates and utensils, toiletries and detergent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to feed those that are hungry and don't have
anything at all,'' said Barbara Atwell, who helped coordinate
efforts in the cafeteria. ``It's all you can do to keep from crying
when you see the people come in. I just think there's a lot of good
cooperation here.''
</P>
<P>
   Nichole Monroe writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
