<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0468 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-HEROES-TEXAS-2TAKES-H     09-21 0925
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEROES-TEXAS-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIAL TO MLK JR. SERVES AS COUNTERPOINT TO UT STATUES OF
CONFEDERATE SOLDIERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Attn: Ga.) 
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Looking back now on the days they manned a table
at the West Mall, a humble donation jar in front of them, the
former activists at the University of Texas still get a chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   The band of three students was determined to raise money so UT
could erect a statue honoring civil rights leader Martin Luther
King Jr. It was the late 1980s and minority students complained
that they felt unwelcome at Texas' largest university, where
enrollment now reaches 49,000. They felt intimidated and offended
by the university's prominently placed memorials to Confederate
President Jefferson Davis and other Confederate heroes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had buttons, we had T-shirts and a petition, if I remember.
That was our feeble, poorly conceived effort to generate
momentum,'' said Dave Winter, now a high school journalism teacher
in Marietta, Ga. ``We had a benefit concert on Sixth Street called
`Statue Aid.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you think about it now, it's just the optimism of
youth,'' said Becky Helton, now 35, of Austin. ``We literally had a
little jar for donations out on our table. I don't know what we
were thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus were the humble beginnings of what became a 12-year odyssey
that will culminate at noon CST Friday with the historic unveiling
of an MLK statue costing nearly $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   UT officials believe the school will be the first predominantly
white campus in the nation to erect such a tribute to the man who
made the famous ``I Have a Dream'' speech. The only other
university they know of with an MLK statue is King's alma mater,
Morehouse College in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   UT, admittedly rocked by a history of racial strife and saddled
with a segregationist past, hopes the new memorial sends a message
of inclusion to counter the uncomfortable presence of the statues
of Confederate heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The giant Confederate statues of Davis, Robert E. Lee and Albert
Sidney Johnston were dedicated on the campus' prominent South Mall
in 1933 as part of a $250,000 gift from the late Major George W.
Littlefield.
</P>
<P>
   A Houston Chronicle editorial in 1920 said that nothing in
Littlefield's last will and testament expressed a nobler or
worthier or more beneficial purpose than the section describing the
UT memorials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The present generation and generations yet unborn will be
debtors to George W. Littlefield for his princely gift,'' the
editorial said.
</P>
<P>
   Littlefield fought for the Confederacy and grew up on a cotton
plantation in Gonzales County. His mother frequently offered her
home as refuge to Confederate soldiers. The family owned 200
slaves, according to a glowing biographical account, all of whom
were liberated at the war's end.
</P>
<P>
   ``In coming years those who read the truth _ of which the South
is not afraid _ they will realize that George W. Littlefield
`though dead, yet speaketh,''' the Chronicle's editorial said.
</P>
<P>
   What his ``princely gift'' says to those now-born children,
however, is not what Littlefield must have intended. In a fateful
1987 editorial, Daily Texan editor Sean Price decried the ``Great
White University'' and took special aim at the glorified campus
figures of the Confederacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If those statues aren't offensive to everyone, they ought to
be,'' Price wrote. ``For starters, all three men were bigots and
traitors whose cause was the preservation of an inhuman
institution. And the presence of the statues is constantly cited by
blacks as one of many sources of intimidation on campus.''
</P>
<P>
   While UT's student editor said he understood the temptation to
remove the statues, he cautioned against trying to erase history
just because it is unpleasant. Instead, he argued, it was better to
write the next chapter with a statue in tribute to King.
</P>
<P>
   Becky Helton grew animated as she read the editorial while
sitting on the West Mall, the university's free-speech mecca.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several of us were sitting on the West Mall, saying ,`Wow,
that's a really good idea.' Someone should do something about
that,'' recalled Helton, who works for the Texas Natural Resource
Conservation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we kind of looked at each other and went: `Well, someone
should. We're someone, so we should do something about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Helton found two other students and a faculty adviser to
formally start an official group under university rules. Before
long, her tiny band gained strength when Helton was joined by
Winter and Michael Mark, now an assistant district attorney in
Liberty, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Negative reactions to the Confederate statues continued to mount
until vandals in 1989 defaced Jefferson Davis' pedestal, scrawling
``Roots (of KKK) fight racism now!'' in red spray paint. Helton
remembers palpable resentment of the statues when strolling
students stopped by the MLK donation table to chat.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least once a day someone would say, `Hey! Why don't we melt
down the statue of Jefferson Davis?'' she said. ``And, we would try
to change the subject. It's easier to accomplish something if you
keep your focus.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Winter and Mark became friends and co-directors of
the Martin Luther King Jr. Sculpture Foundation. On Nov. 3, 1988,
Mark held his first meeting with Ronald M. Brown, vice president
for student affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a lukewarm reception at best,'' he said recently.
``Really, we got nowhere.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really struck by the fact that it was a student
movement. It was not just African-Americans,'' said Vick. ``It was
the feeling that the university needed to make a tangible
expression of welcome to all people of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   While talks were ongoing, the university grappled with two
separate racial incidents that occurred during the spring 1990
Roundup festivities, Vick said. An attentive Daily Texan
photographer snapped a front-page photograph of a beaten up old
jalopy painted with racial epithets and parked outside the Delta
Tau Delta fraternity House. The same weekend, the Phi Gamma Deltas
offended black basketball players by presenting winners at a
Roundup game with T-shirts depicting the fraternity's ``Fiji
Island'' mascot, a rather unsubtle cannibal caricature with
exaggerated black features.
</P>
<P>
   After that, Vick said, the university no longer celebrated
Roundup.
</P>
<P>
   Mark says now that he felt a debt of gratitude to King and the
civil rights movement, which made it possible for him to attend UT,
despite its turbulent racial past and ongoing racial struggles. He
and others point to the case of UT's first black law student, Heman
Sweatt.
</P>
<P>
   Sweatt, sponsored by the National Association for the
Advancement of Colored People, applied to the law school in 1946
but was rejected because he was black. He filed a lawsuit the next
month and in 1950 the U.S. Supreme Court ordered the university to
admit Sweatt. He was met, however, with hostility _ slashed tires
and a burning cross on the law school's yard, according to a 1990
edition of Utmost, a student magazine. He dropped out with ulcers,
unable to bear the stress.
</P>
<P>
   Mark said he's not convinced when those who would defend the
Confederate statues argue that the Civil War was actually a fight
for state's rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``People always say it's not about white superiority or racism,
but every time you see these Klan rallies or skinheads, they always
have the Confederate flag,'' he said. ``It's not a coincidence.''
</P>
<P>
   For Nina Taylor, 49, of Houston and her family, the dedication
of the MLK statue drives home three generations of black history at
UT.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor's father, Fidelus Breeding, was among UT's first black
graduates, earning a master's degree in education in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a lot of resistance. I remember him personally
telling me there were places on campus he wasn't allowed to walk on
when he was there,'' said Taylor, who last year earned a law degree
and passed the state bar exam.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she arrived, attending UT between 1968 and 1971,
``there were professors who obviously were very prejudiced about
having us in class,'' she said. Her husband, Elgin, was an
engineering student and said that one of his professors told him
the first day of class that he would not pass.
</P>
<P>
   Their daughter, Nichele, was a 1998 UT honors graduate and
served on the MLK Sculpture Committee. During her era, she said, UT
had two black student body presidents. But the campus was also
rocked by heated protests over the devastating drop in minority
enrollments on the heels of the Hopwood court decision. That ruling
of the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals barred racial preferences
in scholarships and admissions.
</P>
<P>
   While blacks still seemed largely socially separated from many
of their white colleagues, ``certainly it was better than the
stories I heard growing up from my parents,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In the earliest days of the MLK statue campaign, Mark said, the
first little band of earnest students couldn't get the ear of UT
Chancellor William Cunningham. But, by January 1990, Cunningham
endorsed the project and the following December the UT regents
joined the bandwagon. In the ensuing years, graduating students
passed the cause onto those who followed.
</P>
<P>
   The funding problem was finally resolved with a referendum, in
which students voted 1064 to 657 in favor of a $1 per semester
statue fee. The fee recently ended after raising $465,000, and
officials say any money left over will go toward a new MLK
scholarship. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; The statue of King, draped in doctoral robes and reaching out
with a welcoming outstretched arm, will be placed in the East Mall,
facing predominantly black East Austin.
</P>
<P>
   For Marlen Whitley, a law student and former student body
president who serves on the sculpture committee, the new statue
represents a departure from the Confederate and segregationist
past.
</P>
<P>
   ``As an African-American male, it's kind of disturbing to walk
across campus and see a statue of a man who fought in a sense
against my existence in terms of freedom,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Noteworthy, he said, are the continuing racial issues UT has
been forced to confront during the 12 years it took to erect the
statue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every decade here at the university, for students of color
particularly, has been marred by some type of turmoil or
struggle,'' Whitley said. ``In the '80s, it was the investments the
university had with South Africa. In the '90s, it's been with the
affirmative action programs and &UR;  &LR; (law Professor Leo Graglia) making
the remarks concerning the academic competitiveness of students of
color.''
</P>
<P>
   While few think a statue of Martin Luther King Jr. alone will
end the racial divisions altogether, most everyone considers it a
step in the right direction. The dedication ceremony itself will be
steeped in significance, Whitley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to move us closer, in a sense, to the dream Dr.
King talked about, all people coming together,'' he said. ``At
least for one hour, there will be people from all races, colors and
walks of life.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
