<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-GROW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GROW UP': SPOTLIGHTING A TV SITCOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Production notes are at and of review)  
 (af)  
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a sitcom so skillfully derivative that you'll swear
you're already tired of it, even though you've never seen it
before. Three hunky young guys with unusual first names share a
Brooklyn brownstone: Hunter (Stephen Dunham), the self-absorbed
lothario; Norris (David Alan Basche), the self-absorbed struggling
artist, and Ford (John Ducey), the self-absorbed gay guy.
</P>
<P>
   Having cloned these characters, the show's creators seem to have
been unable to find anything funny for them to do. Elated after a
one-night stand, Hunter tells Norris: ``I think she might be the
one. You didn't happen to get her name, did ya?'' Norris says,
``You just officially became a parody of yourself.'' (Sounds as if
someone's waving a white flag already.)
</P>
<P>
   If the show can't distinguish itself with humor, it tries
tacking on some serious stuff. Serious mistake. Ford has just
acknowledged his homosexuality, and his wife, Suzanne (Rena Sofer),
sure is miffed. She drinks too much wine and tells him, ``You
promised to love, honor and not go Nancy on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Hunter discovers that a college romance produced a
daughter, Chloe (Niesha Trout), who shows up at the boys' doorstep
toting a backpack and not a little anger of her own.
</P>
<P>
   The freshest notion here is a dog named Mom who's jealous of
Hunter's girlfriends. You know that because her barks are
translated by subtitles. That makes one more character who can't
locate a clever line. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES
</P>
<P>
   Grow Up &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ABC, Wednesday at 9:30 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Channel 7 in New York) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0476 &Cx1f; ttg-z
a l BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV28-     09-21 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-$ADV28-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GUYS, LET'S TALK, WE CAN HELP HERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Tuesday, Sept. 28)  
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 Santa Rosa (Calif.) Press Democrat   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not good news that adolescent boys are preoccupied with
their chest, waist and bicep ratio and that their fathers are
getting eyelid tucks in order to remain marketable.
</P>
<P>
   Nor is there any triumph in reading that men are unsure about
whether they're supposed to be quiet or loud, sensitive or
thick-skinned. Or that they feel inadequate next to pictures of
male underwear models.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, there were times we've been jealous of how men can buy and
don a bathing suit without their ego getting in the way, but it
wasn't necessary that they become as obsessed as women are.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the status of men and boys in America has become a
worrisome issue we're finding from social psychologists and
magazine writers that the American male is confused and frustrated.
He's not sure what it means to be masculine anymore. He's concerned
about his body image. He feels as if he's being told how to look
and act by society and he resents it.
</P>
<P>
   It's like deja vu in a deeper voice and hairier body.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it's about time society starts paying attention to men
again. Some wonder when we ever stopped.
</P>
<P>
   Some want to say, ``Now you know what it feels like, Bud.''
</P>
<P>
   There may be some good aspects to this so-called masculinity
crisis. Men in turmoil is not necessarily a terrible thing. If men
are not sure if they're supposed to be warriors or nurturers,
that's OK. Some can be one, some the other. If some men are lashing
out because they've been hoodwinked by their own culture, as author
Susan Faludi says in her upcoming book ``Stiffed,'' this is still
no time to revolt and rip out the diaper changing tables from the
men's restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Now, maybe, women and men can combine their uncertainties and
start to work together. First we have to ignore the notion, which
some people are aching to stir up, that we're in a gender war and
that men are losing because women have won.
</P>
<P>
   As a card-carrying feminist I've done my share of grousing about
men having advantages women don't and chuckled at Ally McBeal's
little joke about there being only two good men per state, but I
think it would be a sad crime if men and boys decided their value
was limited to looking buff and making money.
</P>
<P>
   Men could take a cue from women's struggles to find a new
identity. We may not have cracked the glass ceiling but we did
climb out of a few boxes. One thing that helped was getting
together and talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Experts on the worried man say they fear they've lost control.
They feel like castoffs. The standards have changed and they're
lost and panicky. That's a lot to talk about, but are they talking?
The stereotype is that men get together only to walk around in
gangs or go pig hunting. When they tried sharing their feelings in
rituals in the woods people made fun of the drumming part. But
there is no reason for men to feel alone in their discontent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess some people would think it's time for white men to pay
the piper,'' said one young white male who feels that he's
pigeonholed, resented and unfairly labeled as someone who enjoys a
superior status that he personally doesn't claim.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone starts talking about affirmative action or glass
ceiling for women or diversity in the workplace it's assumed that
I've already taken a side because of my race and gender. I'm not
even allowed into the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   And while he has more choices than many, he also feels the
pressure to be rich and studly. ``The media says to be successful
as a man you have to drive a Mercedes, have stock options, look
like Pierce Brosnan and have a woman who is arm candy.'' This young
guy would rather mark his masculinity by the fact that he cries at
movies, is passionate about his girlfriend and can be as dazzled by
a hummingbird as a football game. But he says a certain tough guy
stance is necessary and were he to admit the same around the
campfire, the others would call him a word that also means a small
cat.
</P>
<P>
   While the mixing of gender roles may be dismaying to some, it
has allowed men to exhibit new styles of male strengths in the form
of attentive fathering, men working as nurses and caregivers and
men showing their softer, creative sides.
</P>
<P>
   So far, this looks more like a turning point for men than a
revolution. As far as we know a matriarchy has not been declared.
Individual males may feel they've lost control but men still have
the power.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the goal was never to trade places or get anybody back.
There's enough fairness and good will to go around.
</P>
<P>
   (The Press Democrat in Santa Rosa, Calif., is part of the New
York Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0253 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0481 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-TV-WESTWING22-COX     09-21 0584
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WESTWING22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A vote for presidential politics
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The timing seems a little wrong for a drama set in the White
House, filled with journalists pestering presidential aides, and
staffers trying to cover their, uh, careers, and gasbags yammering
away on talk shows, and more chaos than a kindergarten fire drill.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't we just watch that show for 13 months on CNN?
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the White House of NBC's new drama ``The West
Wing'' is a thong-free zone, and nearly everyone keeps his or her
pants on. (The only pants-doffing is done by Rob Lowe, which is an
inside joke of a different kind.)
</P>
<P>
   It's also a White House of endless intensity, a non-stop Maalox
moment, sort of like ``ER'' but everybody wears suits instead of
scrubs and nobody says ``stat.'' Policy, schmolicy. Let's rock.
</P>
<P>
   And ``West Wing'' wastes no time plunging viewers into a frantic
set-up, with everyone barking in Beltway shorthand. The prez
(Martin Sheen, who makes a grand entance late in the show) has hurt
his ankle in a bicycle accident, and from the reaction of his staff
you'd think Chinese ICBMs were raining down. We quickly meet
pretty-boy deputy communications director Sam Seaborn (Lowe),
growly chief of staff Leo McGarry (John Spencer), his beleaguered
deputy Josh Lyman (Bradley Whiford), press secretary C.J. Gregg
(Allison Janney) and opposition political consultant Madeline
Hampton (Moira Kelly). Whew. Don't worry, it's a jumble at first
but starts to sort out by the end of the hour.
</P>
<P>
   Besides concerns about the First Ankle, ``West Wing'' deals with
Sam's one-night stand, whom he thought was just a sweet young thing
but turns out to be a hooker (working for free, natch, since he's
Rob Lowe); the business where they mix up their beepers is way too
obvious. And Josh has just insulted the Christian right on a
``Crossfire''-style show.
</P>
<P>
   That brings in, finally, President Josiah Bartlett, who bursts
into a showdown between testy evangelicals and the White House
staff and reels off a humdinger of a speech about anti-abortion
fanatics harrassing his 12-year-old granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Sorkin, who wrote the pilot, has every right to tee off on
evangelicals, but it's the cheapest of shots to have a Jerry
Falwell lookalike not know one of the 10 Commandments. Sorkin
swears ``West Wing'' won't be a liberal's game of Whack-a-Mole
every week, but the big finale of ``West Wing'' is a little too
self-congratulatory and full of its own smug virtue.
</P>
<P>
   The bigger question is whether the series can maintain the pace
of the pilot. Sorkin and director Tommy Schlamme owe their first
allegiance to ABC's ``Sports Night'' and executive producer John
Wells is still doing ``ER'' and another new show, ``Third Watch.''
Complicated series like ``West Wing'' work best when there's one,
undistracted overseer at the helm, unless they're David E. Kelley
shows, in which case anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Wing'' is a quick, brisk little drama that viewers will
find engaging, but it doesn't yet have the emotional heft of ``ER''
or the giddy wordiness of ``Sports Night'' (which returns Oct. 5 on
ABC and is the show you should be checking out). It's more than a
little slick. Hmm. Where have we heard that before?
</P>
<P>
   TV REVIEW
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   9 tonight on NBC
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Phil Kloer writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
