<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0254 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0483 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-CMA-PREVIEW22-COX     09-21 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMA-PREVIEW22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sneak peek backstage at CMA awards
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   They're spraying hair and shining boots in Nashville as the city
gets ready for its biggest shindig of the year, tonight's 33rd
annual Country Music Association awards. But like any true Southern
get-together, the live ceremony at the Grand Ole Opry is rife with
behind-the-scenes facts and feuds that probably won't show through
the camera lens. When you plop down on the sofa tonight to check
out the action, watch for these plot lines:
</P>
<P>
   1. NO-SHOW JONES: Pistol packing singer George Jones is ticked
off. Although he's nominated for single of the year for
``Choices,'' and had the comeback of the year after a near-fatal
car accident, the Possum says he's not performing on the show as of
press time. He's angry that producers asked him to sing an
abbreviated version of the tune to save TV time for other acts.
</P>
<P>
   The practice isn't all that unusual. In the 1970s, outlaw Waylon
Jennings boycotted the CMA ceremony when he was asked to trim his
performance of ``Only Daddy That'll Walk the Line.'' Last year,
Steve Wariner whacked the second verse of the single of the year,
``Holes in the Floor of Heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   As country music has grown in popularity, making the CMA awards
show one of the highest-rated network programs of the year,
performance time has become as precious as initial shares in
Microsoft stock. Vince Gill, who is hosting the awards, says the
CMA is getting a bum rap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people should try to put themselves in the shoes of
the folks at the CMA who have to put the show together,'' he says.
``These people are under incredible pressure from everybody, all
the labels in town who want their acts on the show. It's a hard,
hard job, and I'm not just saying that because I'm hosting.''
</P>
<P>
   No word as to whether Jones will be in a seat.
</P>
<P>
   2. RIMES NOR REASON: Don't look for teen queen LeAnn Rimes at
the podium either. CMA voters snubbed her; she hasn't a single
nomination. Mike Curb, president and founder of Rimes' record
label, is so angry that he resigned from the CMA's performers
selection committee in protest. Rimes recently halted plans to buy
a house in Music City, saying that the atmosphere there was ``too
political.'' Judging from the CMA's reluctant recognition of the
young star, who many in the close-knit community consider an
outsider, she may be right.
</P>
<P>
   3. COLLECTING FOR CONWAY: The late Conway Twitty is being
inducted into the CMA Hall of Fame, but who will show up to accept
the trophy? Six years after the sultry singer's death, his heirs
are still bitterly fighting over his $12-14 million estate, which
includes royalties to hits such as ``It's Only Make Believe,'' a
massive Nashville mansion and a $2.5 million life insurance policy.
In one corner is Dee Henry Jenkins, Twitty's second wife and his
widow, who was named as heir in a will Twitty drew up in 1987. One
small problem: he never signed it. In the other corner you have
Twitty's two daughters, who don't agree that Dee is entitled to the
fortune she has claimed. In June, a Nashville judged handed Dee
one-third of the estate, but the daughters may still appeal the
decision. A political solution: Have Twitty's longtime singing
partner, Loretta Lynn, accept the award.
</P>
<P>
   4. POOR PORTER: Dolly Parton also is going into the Hall of
Fame. However, one person who might not be too happy about that
honor is Parton's former singing partner, Porter Wagoner. The
Wagonmaster ``discovered'' the Smoky Mountain songbird, put her on
his syndicated TV show, and recorded a string of top duets with her
until she struck out on her own in 1974. Although Parton's talent
has clearly eclipsed Wagoner's, there is still friction between the
two that might be exacerbated by Dolly getting to the Hall of Fame
before Porter. Let's see if she mentions him in her acceptance
speech.
</P>
<P>
   5. ODD COUPLES: The most bizarre performance of the evening
might be the pairing of crusty roadhouse troubador Merle Haggard
with sweet pop songbird Jewel. The duo is scheduled to perform
Haggard's classic hit ``That's the Way Love Goes.'' And in what is
perhaps the most contrived marketing scheme of the year, RCA
country group Alabama will team with RCA pop group 'N Sync to
perform ``God Must Have Spent a Little More Time on You,'' a song
which is not nominated in any category.
</P>
<P>
   6. CHICKS COULD FLY: Although Tim McGraw goes into the awards
with the most nominations (seven), it is possible that the night
could belong to hot country trio, the Dixie Chicks. This has been
their year, as their first album on the Monument label, ``Wide Open
Spaces,'' sold 7 million copies and produced five hit singles. The
group's new album, ``Fly,'' hit the No. 1 spot on country charts
the week it was released in late August. The Chicks are scheduled
to open the CMA show with their latest chart-topper, ``Ready to
Run,'' a moment that could rival Garth Brooks' show-stopping
performance of ``Friends in Low Places'' in 1991. It would not be
surprising to see the Chicks overtake Brooks in the coveted
entertainer of the year category, particularly since Brooks'
somewhat weird metamorphosis into fictional pop star Chris Gaines.
But traditionally polite CMA voters may want to give a nod to the
staying power of McGraw, and save the Chicks for later.
</P>
<P>
   7. MARK'S MOMENT: On a happy note, Atlanta's Mark Wills, who was
once the house singer at the Buckboard, Smyrna's (Ga.) country
watering hole, has finally made it. He's nominated for two CMA
awards _ single of the year and music video of the year for the hit
``Don't Laugh at Me.'' Writers Allen Shamblin and Steve Seskin are
nominated for song of the year. Wills is scheduled to perform the
song on the show.
</P>
<P>
   8. RHUBARB REPORTS: As he has done for 21 years, Rhubarb Jones
is covering the behind-the-scenes action at CMA week live from 6 to
10 a.m. on Atlanta country station Y-106.7. He'll also host an
audio simulcast of the show.
</P>
<P>
   CMA NOMINEES
</P>
