u a BC-FLOODS-SHELTERS-COX     09-21 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-SHELTERS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Two shelters moved after losing water
 &HT;    By Jenna Hunt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ Two shelters housing some 3,000 flood victims
in Pitt County were relocated on Tuesday afternoon because they
were without water.
</P>
<P>
   Four area shelters lost running water before noon. Many parts of
Greenville lost water service because flooding has limited the
capacity to treat and distribute water.
</P>
<P>
   About 500 people from shelters at Wintergreen and E.B. Aycock
schools were transported to Ayden Middle School and Ayden
Elementary School, said Red Cross officials. Water is still
available in Ayden, Eastern Pines and areas in Winterville.
</P>
<P>
   This is the second move for many Wintergreen shelter residents.
They were evacuated from D.H. Conley High School on Wednesday due
to flooding there.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters at North Pitt High School and Welcome Middle School are
both without running water. Red Cross officials are trying to find
additional shelters in the area with running water and back-up
generators.
</P>
<P>
   The county has turned over shelter operations to national
officials with the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross emergency response vehicles are heading to eastern
North Carolina and Pitt County, said Jay Penuel, Red Cross
Wintergreen Shelter director.
</P>
<P>
   Each shelter has two military police officers, two county police
officers, nurses, and some shelters have volunteer mental health
workers and doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Christena Woods offered to house Linda Green and her infant son,
who were staying at Wintergreen shelter. Woods, an Eastern Pines
resident, had running water for bathing and bottled water
</P>
<P>
   Greene, 17, and her 6-month-old son, Nehemiah, went to Woods'
home Tuesday. The Greenes' mobile home at Pinecrest Mobile Home
Park is now flooded. Greene came to the shelter with her mother and
siblings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We barely made it because the water was almost covering our
car,'' her mother said. ``It was terrible to see people in boats,
walking in the water and hollering for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Pregnant mothers and infants drinking formula can't drink boiled
water or water treated with bleach _ they must drink bottled water
only, said Dr. John Morrow, director of Pitt County Health
Department. Boiling the water concentrates chemicals that can be
harmful to babies, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Greene will stay with Woods until the city turns the water back
on, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Katina Warren, a former Wintergreen Shelter resident, is eight
months pregnant. She said she doesn't like the shelter food and has
trouble eating.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't eaten anything here period,'' Warren said. She
brought several cans of chicken noodle soup from her home before
she evacuated on Saturday. ``I'm hungry.''
</P>
<P>
   Warren, 26, said they have apples, oranges, pastries, cereal and
milk available, but she can't eat. She said the milk tastes spoiled
to her sensitive palate.
</P>
<P>
   Warren and her husband, Lintay, lost their mobile home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like we're in jail _ lights out at 11 p.m. and door
closed,'' Warren said as she took a drag from her husband's
cigarette.
</P>
<P>
   Jenna Hunt writes for The Daily Reflector, Greenville, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
