<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-MEXICO-DEATHS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICAN `PARADISE' FOR EXPATRIATE AMERICANS NOW A PLACE OF FEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RYAN KIM  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The local retirees like to call their lakeside
village of Ajijic, Mexico, an affordable vision of paradise.
</P>
<P>
   The narrow cobblestone streets and tightly nestled homes begin
at the north side of Lake Chapala, the largest lake in Mexico, and
creep up into the nearby hills. The weather is dry and warm much of
the year, and housing is cheap.
</P>
<P>
   But the quiet sense of bliss in Ajijic has been displaced by a
rising fear, prompted by the recent killing of two expatriate
Americans. The death of the elderly couple has shocked residents,
who said they barely encountered crime in this normally placid
municipality.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone is shocked and concerned that something like this
could happen,'' said former Oakland, Calif., resident Vierl Bunnell
said. ``It was very brutal.'' Bunnell is president of the Lake
Chapala Society, a social organization that serves the area's large
retirement community.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy performed on the bodies of Oakland native and former
Los Altos resident Robert Ramsdell Koll, 91, and his 90-year-old
companion Melba Boudreau Wasey, formerly of Garden Grove, Calif.,
indicated Koll's throat had been cut while Wasey had been
strangled. Their bodies were found in their living room Sept. 13 by
their maid.
</P>
<P>
   While police are investigating the possibility that the killings
were part of a robbery, the initial evidence leaves the door open
to other motives.
</P>
<P>
   Two rooms in the small home were thoroughly ransacked, but the
killer or killers did not take the couple's cars, paintings or
sculptures. Koll was found with his wallet, while Wasey had on a
diamond ring and earrings.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators are also looking into whether Koll or Wasey had
any problems with other residents in the area. No arrests have been
made, and people are wondering how the killings could have taken
place without anyone hearing or seeing something.
</P>
<P>
   The killings were not the first signs of trouble in paradise. A
48- year-old New Jersey woman and a 72-year-old Ontario woman were
killed in unrelated cases in February 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Peggy Koll, Koll's wife, from whom he was separated and who
lives on the other side of Ajijic, said she'd seen an increase in
crime in the area as it had become more populated. She said a
friend had been robbed at gunpoint three times in the past few
years. The deaths of her husband and Wasey have left her
grief-stricken.
</P>
<P>
   Koll said the character of Ajijic had changed as thousands of
seniors poured into the area. Other local residents, however, said
the town was still safe by U.S. standards, despite the killings of
Koll and Wasey.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame, but it's not something you live in fear of,''
said Georgette Richmond, 52, a former Berkeley, Calif., resident
and Ajijic real estate agent. ``It's just sad to live so long and
then meet such a violent end.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Americans retiring in Mexico has increased
noticeably over the years. The Ajijic area is home to about 10,000
foreign retirees, mostly Americans and Canadians. The bulk of the
expatriates come for the mild weather and low cost of living.
</P>
<P>
   The town offers the charm of a small village, many of the
amenities of the United States, and a nearby bustling metropolis in
Guadalajara. Spanish tile and palm trees dominate the landscape.
</P>
<P>
   Though a number of Ajijic retirees are well-to-do, Bunnell said,
many come from middle-class backgrounds. To live in Mexico,
retirees must have an income of at least $1,000 per month and are
not allowed to work while there.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Embassy spokesman Stephen Morisseau said officials were
watching the Ajijic investigation closely. But he said no warnings
had gone out to U.S. citizens, and he does not think U.S. retirees
in the Lake Chapala area face an unreasonable risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a mistake to infer that much from a few
incidents,'' he said. ``But of course people do need to be
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Koll, a former Oakland food supply salesman, came to Ajijic in
1968 with his wife, Peggy. The two separated in 1974 but remained
friends, Peggy Koll said. A few years before the Kolls separated,
Wasey moved to Ajijic. She and Robert Koll started dating in the
late '70s.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a lot of good years,'' Peggy Koll said. ``They got
along really well.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
