<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-Y2K-EDUCATION22-COX     09-21 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-EDUCATION22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SCHOOLS VULNERABLE TO Y2K BUG, SURVEYS SHOW
 &HT;    By RAVEN HILL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many U.S. elementary and secondary schools could
experience disruptions from the Y2K computer bug, federal
investigators reported Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The surveys also found that many colleges and universities have
not eliminated the programming flaw that leaves computer unable to
recognize dates starting with Jan. 1, 2000, leaving student
financial aid programs vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   A report from the Congressional Accounting Office, released at a
Senate hearing, examined ``mission critical'' functions in 25 large
school districts. Most districts reported that computers
controlling administrative systems, student records, facilities,
student transportation and food service would not be Y2K-ready
until nearly the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Only seven of the 25 districts said they were already in full
compliance, and two more estimated they would be in compliance by
the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Late completion dates leave very little time for testing to
make sure everything works,'' said Sen. Bob Bennett, R-Utah,
chairman of the Senate Special Committee on the Year 2000
Technology Problem.
</P>
<P>
   A similar survey conducted by the U.S. Department of Education
found only 30 percent of districts ready for the date change,
Deputy Education Secretary Marshall Smith told the committee.
Larger school districts were less likely to be compliant, he said.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers indicate that millions of students could be
affected by Y2K-related disruptions, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., co-chairman of the panel, noted
that elementary and secondary schools are often used as emergency
shelters in many communities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our schools have always served as integral parts of our
communities and we must be sure that they can continue this service
without interruption,'' Dodd said.
</P>
<P>
   Dodd said that time is quickly running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``With only 101 days remaining before the millennium,
remediation is now almost as futile as late night cramming for a
major exam,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the Education Department survey, colleges and universities
fared no better than elementary and secondary schools, Smith told
the panel. Of more than 6,000 responding, only 30 percent had
achieved full compliance.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the Education Department has provided technical
assistance to institutions that might face ``special challenges,''
including historically black colleges, tribally controlled colleges
and Hispanic-serving institutions.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to financial aid programs, smaller institutions are
most vulnerable to Y2K disruptions because they may lack resources
to upgrade their systems, said George Chin, representing the
National Association of Financial Aid Administrators.
</P>
<P>
   Though students' financial aid packages for this school year are
not likely to be affected, new or transfer students who plan to
enroll in the spring may have problems, Chin said. He encouraged
students to file their documents early and make sure their
financial aid records are current.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
