<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPOT-BUDGET-BOS </SLUG>
  
 For Release WEDNESDAY AMs, September 22, 1999  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Boston Globe plans to move the following stories for use by
NYTimes News Service clients.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; For questions about stories, contact  &UR; Frank Perrotta  &LR; at the
Boston Globe,  &UR; 617-929-2597. &LR;  For individual purchase of graphics
or photos please call 212 556-4204 or -1927.
</P>
<P>
   All stories will bear the BOS designator.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL (i) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-VIOLENCE (Dili, Indonesia) _ Deadly violence is reported
in rural East Timor, even as the main group of Australian
peacekeepers arrives. By Indira A.R. Lakshmanan. 1300 words.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-KOSOVO (New York) _ President Clinton, speaking at the
UN General Assembly, defends military intervention for peace in
Kosovo and elsewhere. By John Donnelly. 1200 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON (w) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SENATE-BANKRUPTCY (Washington) _ Heavily lobbied bill will make
it easier for banks and other credit card companies to go after
people who are not meeting their obligations, at a time when US
population owes more than ever before. By Ann E. Kornblut. 900
words. (w and f coding)
</P>
<P>
   KERRY-EDUCATION (Washington) _ Senator John F. Kerry, in what he
is billing as a major policy speech, plans to attack both George W.
Bush and the Democratic Party for education ideas that are
old-fashioned and narrow. By Ann E. Kornblut. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL (a) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AMNESTY-CLINTON (New York) _ _ President Clinton further
explains his decision to offer amnesty to jailed Puerto Rican
nationalists. Law enforcement officials warn those pardoned are
dangerous. By Susan Milligan. 1000 words.
</P>
<P>
   BOOMING-POPULATION (Undated) _ In the fastest population growth
in history, the world will have 6 billion people on Oct. 12,
marking a milestone that could determine the future of the planet,
UN says. By Dolores Kong. 900 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRADLEY (Manchester, N.H.) _ As the upstart campaign of
Bill Bradley continues to gain ground, advisers to Vice President
Al Gore are hoping that discrepancies between Bradley's campaign
rhetoric and his voting record will halt his momentum in the
first-primary state. By Jill Zukcman. 600 words.
</P>
<P>
   TRUMP-REFORM (Washington) _ Donald J. Trump is serious about
running for president under the Reform Party banner. He says there
is a public outpouring of support. By Michael Kranish. 750 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL (f) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BELL-VODAFONE (Undated) _ Bell Atlantic and Vodafone AirTouch to
combine their US operations to create the country's largest mobile
phone company, with more than 20 million customers and a network
twice the size of AT&AMP;T's. By Peter Howe. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   CAHNERS-RESIGN (Newton, Mass.) _ Cahners Business Information
chief executive Bruce Barnet resigned abruptly last week, raising
concerns about the future of the trade publishing company's
operations. By Ross Kerber. 800 words.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (s) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   BBA-JAYS-REDSOX (Boston) _ By Gordon Edes.
</P>
<P>
   w/
</P>
<P>
   BBA-COMMENT (Boston) _ By Larry Whiteside.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Boston Globe &LR;  &QC;
