<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0500 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-RDP-2TAKES(TRIM     09-21 1305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-RDP-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEACEKEEPERS RESTORE CALM TO DILI, BUT FEAR REMAINS
</HEADLINE>
  (With TIMOR-INDONESIA) 
 (nk) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DARE, East Timor _ Panic seized the refugees in this mountain
hideout Tuesday morning. Soldiers were coming. Screaming and
scrambling, the refugees tumbled down the hillside seeking safety.
</P>
<P>
   Moments later the panic turned to shouts of jubilation. The
soldiers were Australian peacekeepers, not the Indonesian soldiers
or the militias that people feared.
</P>
<P>
   Winding up the steep hills overlooking Dili, the seaside
capital, the peacekeepers were escorting U.N. officials for their
first look at the situation in the countryside after three weeks of
violence and terror.
</P>
<P>
   When the officials arrived here, the 2,000 people who gathered
to greet them began to leap and cheer, celebrating at last the
victory of their vote on Aug. 30 for independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Viva Xanana!'' they shouted, chanting the revolutionary name
of Jose Alexandre Gusmao, their long-exiled leader, as small
children raced wildly among them. ``Viva East Timor!''
</P>
<P>
   Two huge gray transport ships, visible in the harbor far below
them, were unloading the latest in a continuing stream of foreign
forces, most from Australia. Military officials said the troops in
East Timor had climbed above 2,000 Tuesday and would reach 3,000 by
late Wednesday, building toward a final target of 8,000.
</P>
<P>
   The commander of the Australian forces, Brig. Gen. Mark Evans,
said his soldiers are consolidating their hold on Dili and will
move in to secure Baucau town in the coming days.
</P>
<P>
   Under tight military control, the situation in Dili is already
beginning to shift. The militias that have laid waste to much of
the city with the backing of the Indonesian military are either
disappearing or blending into the population.
</P>
<P>
   In their place, tough young men from the hills around Dare, a
stronghold of pro-independence rebels six miles south of Dili,
began gathering near the port Tuesday morning. They eyed the
Indonesian soldiers, who have begun a final pullout, with most
expected to be gone by the end of the week.
</P>
<P>
   One of these young men, moving with an air of authority, wore a
conspicuously bright yellow beret and a freshly laundered white
T-shirt with the slogan: ``Falintil'' _ the acronym of the
separatist guerrilla force.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, it seems, the city will, on the surface at least, belong
not to the militias but to the forces who have fought for
independence since Indonesia invaded this former Portuguese colony
in 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging from his van in Dare Tuesday morning, the head of the
U.N. mission here, Ian Martin, embraced leaders of the
pro-independence movement, who control the hilltop area and who are
now among the potential leaders of an independent East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Martin had not seen them since the post-referendum violence
forced the United Nations to evacuate its mission a week ago. This
time, he told them, ``the United Nations is here to stay until an
independent East Timor no longer wants us to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the U.N. office, looted but not destroyed after the
evacuation, is being secured by British, Danish and Swedish troops
in preparation for reopening. At the moment, he said, the United
Nations has 17 staff members in Dili along with 10 aid workers and
six members of the International Committee for the Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their moment of thrill and hope Tuesday, the 37,000
people taking shelter in the hills of Dare _ among the estimated
200,000 refugees throughout East Timor _ still face danger and
severe hardship.
</P>
<P>
   Though the peacekeepers have moved to seal off and secure Dili
in their second day on the ground, armed men who oppose
independence still roam the hills around Dare, and elsewhere
throughout the territory.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, as many as 200,000 other people have fled or been
forced into camps in neighboring West Timor, long a province of
Indonesia. These East Timorese are under the control of militias
that so far have prevented most aid workers from entering West
Timor.
</P>
<P>
   An Indonesian representative of the U.N. High Commissioner for
Refugees also visited Dare Tuesday and said many families had been
separated as the militias forced people, under threat of death, to
move with them to West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Casimiro Reis, 45, spoke with quiet dignity of his family's
separation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am refugee,'' he said in carefully enunciated English. ``My
wife told me to go to mountain. If I stay in Dili, my safety is not
guaranteed. The main reason is, I am a man and they will kill me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a wife and five children. I don't know what has
happened to them. I hope that if they are alive in Kupang or
Atambua [in West Timor). I hope they will be able to come back
soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The refugees in Dare included several dozen East Timorese
policemen who had defected, some with their uniforms and side arms,
to remain here with their countrymen. There are also numerous
reports of police officers and soldiers who have broken ranks and
joined the militias in their fight to keep East Timor part of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   One of the officers here, Agostinho Gomes, said he had joined
the Indonesian police force in 1994 specifically to learn about
police work so he could apply his knowledge in a future independent
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Ross Mountain, who coordinates humanitarian aid for the United
Nations and who visited Dare Tuesday, was asked if the estimates
for the numbers of displaced people mean that half of East Timor's
800,000 people need assistance. He replied: ``Frankly, those in
need are well in excess of that. It's almost easier to talk about
who does not need assistance.''
</P>
<P>
   A major difficulty, he said, is distributing the supplies that
are expected to pour into the country. Most trucks were destroyed
or sent into West Timor in the mass evacuation. And even with
transportation, he said, ``this is quite a difficult country to
move around in.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Scott-Bowden, the East Timor representative of the World
Food Program, which is coordinating the food aid, said air drops
that began and then paused just before the beginning of the
peacekeeping operation would resume, mostly bringing specially
packed emergency rations from the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Not all the refugees are in the hills. In vacant lots and along
the long waterfront of Dili, thousands of families fleeing the
violence in their own city have created whole settlements of
displaced people. Many, young and old, lounge like retired elders
in displaced armchairs.
</P>
<P>
   Even with Australian soldiers stationed around the city, these
hungry people are terrified, jumping at rumors of attacks and
afraid even to cross the city to see whether their homes have been
burned or are still standing.
</P>
<P>
   But with the arrival of the peacekeepers to support the vote of
independence, the remaining threats from militia members are likely
to stem from the cornered fury of a retreating force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The militia in itself is not a threat for East Timor,'' said
Salar Kosi, a leader in the independence movement who greeted the
U.N. team here in Dare. ``But if they continue to be supported by
elements of the military that have run out of control, it may be
dangerous in the next coming weeks, the next coming months, the
next coming years.''
</P>
<P>
   A top lieutenant here for Gusmao, Leandro Isaac, said he is
still far from ready to declare victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This might be one more step,'' he said of the arrival of the
foreign forces. ``But I still don't trust the Indonesian military.
As long as there is one Indonesian soldier, one Indonesian
policeman in East Timor, our struggle continues.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether, after the horrors of the past three weeks, the
leaders of the independence movement could still hold to their
policy of reconciliation with their enemies in East Timor, he said:
``We maintain our policy of reconciliation, but it must be
reconciliation based on justice. We cannot have peace without
justice; peace without justice would be a bad peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosi said that in a new East Timor, some leaders of the militias
may be pardoned and some may be punished.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Dare, it is clear that the destruction and personal
traumas caused by the militias in the past three weeks will not be
forgotten quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Reynaldo Peveida, 28, said that with his home in ruins, he is
ready to live ``in a church or a school or a convent or under a
tree.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he voiced a rare complaint _ a criticism that is heard more
often abroad than in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Why did the United Nations dismiss or fail to consider the
danger of assigning Indonesian security forces to keep the peace
during the referendum _ in effect, to police themselves? And he
addressed his comment to the U.N. secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a very bad decision,'' Peveida said. ``You see what
happened. I have that question for Mr. Kofi Annan.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1833EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0506 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-CORPS-COX     09-21 0769
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-CORPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Businessess getting Y2K ready; some will continue testsBy
Charles Haddad
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The software has been upgraded, the networks tested
and retested. Still, BellSouth is not resting on its laurels as the
Millennium approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us are done with this until way past the turn of the
year,'' says Rick Harder vice president with overall
responsibilities for the corporate Year 2000 project. ``We prefer
to say we are ready for Y2K _ not that we are finished with testing
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth is not alone. Every big company in metro Atlanta,
while prepared on paper, is anxiously awaiting the arrival of the
New Year. They realize that no test, no matter how tough, can't
fully predict what will happen in real life.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a moment to be sitting back on your laurels,''
says James M. McCullough, a Y2K consultant and board member of the
Atlanta/Southeast Region Y2K Solution Center.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough calculates that even the best, most well-financed
plan can't anticipate 30 percent to 40 percent of the potential
risk posed by a failure of computers to understand any date after
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   That failure could ripple far and wide through a metro area in
which nearly every business, large and small, now uses computers.
</P>
<P>
   What the experts fear is not an earthquake-like catastrophe but
a continual series of disruptions that could slow the economy,
ending the 9-year-old expansion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst case scenarios won't occur,'' says Bud Hamilton, a
professor at Georgia State University. ``But problems related to
Y2K will persist for the first of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dolinsky, the computer consultant who heads up the Solution
Center, worries that Hamilton is right. ``Y2K is greatly
misunderstood,'' he says. ``It's not an event and it's not a bug.
There'd be no problem at all if everyone just converted their
computers to read the year 2000.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in metro Atlanta, especially the billion-dollar
corporations, have done just that.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Gas, for example, will have spent an estimated $6.2
million this year alone readying its computers to handle 2000.
Among other things, the company has replaced nine software
applications.
</P>
<P>
   BellSouth has tested its own lines, systems used for 911 and
connections with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We at BellSouth are doing everything we can to make sure our
telephone network and computer systems will be ready for the Year
2000,'' said Harder.
</P>
<P>
   Such work has not come cheap. Bank of America, formerly
NationsBank, has spent more than $500 million in the past five
years to ready its vast computer network for the next century.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have contingency plans for any emergency,'' says company
spokesman Mark Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Billion-dollar behemoths such as Bank of America can spend
hundreds of millions of dollars upgrading their own systems, but
that effort could be for naught it key suppliers aren't also
upgrading.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Solution Center has identified suppliers as the weak
link in the Y2K preparation effort. The problem is that suppliers
tend to be small to mid-sized companies. Many of them are either
reluctant to do or can't afford expensive computer upgrades.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the little guys who make me nervous,'' says McCullough.
``The big companies have the money and resources to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Many big companies share McCullough's concern. ``We have some of
our people working with our outside vendors,'' says Bank of
America's Williams. ``They are trying to help our key suppliers be
ready for Y2K.''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough also worries that many big companies have focused on
critical systems and neglected or cut back on upgrading
nonessential services.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, if something fails because of Y2K, it won't be
the power grid or the telephone system. What you'll see instead a
series of smaller but still disconcerting problems such as an
inability to book a flight or renew your driver's license.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vacations will get canceled, flight reservations booked on the
wrong days, stuff like that,'' says McCullough. He likens the
potential impact of these problems as being ``nibbled to death by
ducks.''
</P>
<P>
   Companies such as Bank of America say they're prepared but
company spokesman Williams agrees that there is an element of the
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're as prepared for Y2K as we can be, but you never know
what will happen,'' says Williams. ``There could be an earthquake
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Haddad writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
