<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0266 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-Y2K-QA-COX     09-21 1371
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-QA-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q and A on Y2K
 &HT;    By Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Even the experts are uncertain about the effect of the
Y2K bug after Jan. 1, leaving many people with questions about how
and if to prepare for disruptions. Here are some answers.
</P>
<P>
   Lights, heat, water, other services
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will electric or natural gas service be interrupted?
</P>
<P>
   A: The state's report on Y2K preparedness says major national
disruptions in power are unlikely, but there could be limited,
local disruptions. Georgia Power is 100 percent in compliance,
according to its report to the state, but there could be temporary
interruptions in service because of the interdependence of power
systems. Atlanta Gas Light reported to the state it will be ready
by this month, but it is dependent on gas distribution, and the
Public Service Commission has reported concern about the readiness
of gas marketers.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will water service be interrupted?
</P>
<P>
   A: That could be a concern. When local jurisdictions were
required in July to report to the state on Y2K readiness, Atlanta's
two water plants were rated ``not yet ready/making progress.'' The
plants supply water to most of the city and parts of Fulton County
and sell water wholesale to other metro-area water systems. Also
ranked ``not yet ready/making progress'' were water systems in
Coweta, DeKalb, Douglas, Fayette and Gwinnett counties and the
cities of Lawrenceville, Fayetteville and Roswell. Rated ``ready''
were water systems in Fulton and Clayton counties, Cobb-Marietta
and Smyrna, College Park and Buford. However, the state is
scheduled to release new reports next week, and those rankings
could change.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will gasoline be available?
</P>
<P>
   A: It should be, assuming no disruptions in power to run pumps.
The American Petroleum Institute says the industry is prepared.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will telephones work?
</P>
<P>
   A: BellSouth and AT&AMP;T said in August they have tested their
public telephone networks for potential Y2K foul-ups and the tests
were 100 percent successful.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will the mail be delivered?
</P>
<P>
   A: The U.S. Postal Service says yes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will elevators work?
</P>
<P>
   A: Elevator operators, including Otis Elevators, one of the
largest manufacturers, predict no problems because elevators aren't
date-dependent. But elevators tied into larger building-control
systems could be affected if the larger systems have problems. If
you live in a high-rise building, check with your building manager.
</P>
<P>
   Money
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should I have extra cash on hand? Will sufficient cash be
available if many people want extra funds?
</P>
<P>
   A: You might want to have enough cash on hand to last a few
days, but don't empty your bank account. The Federal Reserve System
is preparing for the possibility that many Americans will withdraw
cash from banks: It has ordered $50 billion in new currency put
into circulation to cover demands on banks and automated teller
machines.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will ATM machines work? Should I worry about bank records or
the security of my accounts?
</P>
<P>
   A: Problems with ATMs are not expected. Federal agencies are
inspecting banks to make sure all functions, including ATMs, will
continue uninterrupted. However, some experts recommend keeping
records of financial transactions, especially those conducted near
the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should I worry about bills, mortgage payments or other
financial records?
</P>
<P>
   A: Experts recommend keeping copies of important documents, such
as payroll and credit union records, 1998 and 1999 tax information,
deeds, medical records, bank statements, investment reports, and
car and insurance payments. Especially, keep documentation on
expensive items or services purchased or business transacted from
December 1999 through January 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Food and drugs
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should I stockpile food and water or such supplies as diapers
and baby formula?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Food Distributors International Web site expects ``Jan.
1, 2000, will be just another shopping day.'' But the general
advice is to prepare as you would for a winter storm or other
natural disaster, including possible power outages. The Red Cross
recommends preparing for 10 days to two weeks of inconveniences.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Should I have extra supplies of prescription or
over-the-counter medicine?
</P>
<P>
   A: Federal agencies report they don't expect problems with drug
distribution but recommend consumers refill prescriptions when they
have a five-to-seven day supply of medicine remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Police, fire, traffic
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will police be reachable? Will 911 systems work?
</P>
<P>
   A: It is too soon to tell. In July, the state rated many metro
area 911 systems ``not yet ready/making progress.'' Among them were
Cherokee, Rockdale, DeKalb, Douglas, Clayton and Fayette counties
and the cities of Decatur and East Point. Rated ``not
ready/questionable'' were the city of Atlanta, Conyers and Gwinnett
County. 911 systems in Cobb and Fulton counties and in Smyrna
reported to the state they are prepared for the change. The status
reports from police and sheriff's departments were even less
encouraging. Ranked not ready were: Atlanta police, Cobb police and
sheriff, Clayton and Coweta sheriff's departments, Gwinnett police
and East Point police. The Decatur police and DeKalb police and
sheriff's office were ``making progress.'' The Cherokee sheriff's
office reported it is prepared. Fulton police did not report.
However, the state is due to release a new report next week, and
those rankings could change.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will traffic lights work?
</P>
<P>
   A: Metro area traffic engineers say yes, assuming electricity
continues to flow.
</P>
<P>
   Other worries
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will appliances such as televisions and microwave ovens work?
</P>
<P>
   A: Trade associations say that absent power interruptions, home
appliances aren't likely to be affected, because most _ coffee
makers, microwaves, clock radios, and heating and cooling equipment
_ use clock, rather than calendar, functions. Even products that
have calendars, such as VCRs and camcorders, are not likely to have
problems unless you bought them before 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Specific information on products and models is available on many
manufacturers' Web sites. The Consumer Electronics Manufacturers
Association's Web site (www.cemacity.org/govt/CEMA2000.htm) has
links to member companies' Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Will it be safe to fly?
</P>
<P>
   A: Airplane manufacturers say planes will be OK. The Federal
Aviation Administration's air traffic computer systems were
reported compliant by June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What can I do to make sure my PC works?
</P>
<P>
   A: Many PCs, especially those bought before mid-1997, may have
Y2K hardware problems. Major computer manufacturers offer
information about possible problems and fixes or ``patches'' that
can be downloaded. Check the Web site of your computer manufacturer
for information. Apple Macintosh reports that its computers should
not have any date-related hardware problems. Information is
available on Apple computer's home page
(ww.apple.com/about/year2000/). PC users also should check their
software for Y2K compliance. For information, check the software
manufacturer's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What else do I need to know to be prepared?
</P>
<P>
   A: There are Year 2000 scams are encouraging consumers to buy
unnecessary items and overpriced kits, or move money or investments
into so-called protected programs. Avoid them and use common sense.
Never give out your Social Security number or bank account numbers
over the telephone to callers you do not know. Include elderly
relatives or other vulnerable family members in your planning.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If there are Y2K problems, when will they start and how long
will they last?
</P>
<P>
   A: The experts say it's unlikely that all the lights will go out
or other systems will fail at midnight, Dec. 31. A more likely
scenario is that there will be small failures that may affect the
operation of large systems over the first several weeks or months
of 2000. The result may be service interruptions that are limited
in area and time.
</P>
<P>
   Sources: State of Georgia; U.S. government Web sites; Atlanta
Journal-Constitution archives.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
