<HEADER>
A0508 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-INJURIES-     09-21 0613
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-INJURIES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons try to rebound after losing first 2 games, AndersonBy
Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Jamal Anderson's season began in a limousine on his
way to contract negotiations in Greenville, S.C., to end his 14-day
holdout.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons running back's season ended Tuesday, probably, with
him wedged into an MRI tube to reveal that Anderson tore the
anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee in Monday night's 24-7
loss at Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   The injury happened when he tried to cut on the artificial
surface in Texas Stadium and heard a ``pop.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson will undergo surgery in a couple weeks. He was not
placed immediately on injured reserve, however, because of a slim
chance that he could return by the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Falcons will try to rebound from an 0-2
start without a back who last season rushed for franchise records
of 1,846 yards and 14 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm extremely upset and saddened by this turn of fate,'' said
a statement from Anderson, who last month got a five-year, $32
million contract. ``I will do everything in my power to return
better than I was before, as quickly as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons have two healthy running backs: Byron Hanspard, who
missed last season with a serious left knee injury, and Ken
Oxendine, who did not dress for the first two games.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta will add at least one other back, either today or
Thursday. A list of possibilities includes Raymont Harris, Rashaan
Salaam and former Falcon Harold Green.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons also were calling around the league on Tuesday to
inquire about trade possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Some adjustments will be made to accommodate the running style
of Hanspard, who gained 76 yards on 19 carries against the Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   The third-year pro, who is 5-feet-10 and 200 pounds, is quicker
and lighter than Anderson, and better suited to outside running
plays, draws and screens.
</P>
<P>
   As a rookie in 1997, he had what were then three of the 12
longest runs in franchise history. Hanspard carried the ball 53
times for 335 yards and a stellar 6.3-yard average.
</P>
<P>
   In the final preseason game of `98, he tore the anterior
cruciate ligament and patella tendon in his left knee.
</P>
<P>
   Hanspard was not available for comment Tuesday, which was the
players' day off.
</P>
<P>
   Oxendine, a seventh-round draft choice last year from Virginia
Tech, had 50 yards on 18 carries as a rookie. He is 6 feet and 230
pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's running last year was the main reason the Falcons led
the NFL in average time of possession. In addition, his run threat
set up the Falcons' play-action passing attack.
</P>
<P>
   His absence places more pressure on a passing game that sorely
needs quarterback Chris Chandler to return from the strained right
hamstring that kept him out of the Dallas game.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you'll do . . . is run plays that Byron likes, and they
are a little bit different than what Jamal likes,'' coach Dan
Reeves said. ``We will . . . try to work Ken Oxendine in there
some, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's injury does not affect his $7.5 million signing
bonus, which is guaranteed, and he is guaranteed his $1.9 million
salary for the season. His charge of $3.4 million against the
Falcons' salary cap remains in effect.
</P>
<P>
   NFL teams have insurance to cover medical emergencies but not
for wages for injured players.
</P>
<P>
   If Anderson is not placed on IR, and another back is signed, the
team would have to release another player to make room on the
roster.
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
