<HEADER>
A0513 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      09-21 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MONEY, SMALL IDEAS, MEDIOCRE PEOPLE MAKE FOR BORING POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ I hereby announce my withdrawal from the San
Francisco mayor's race and the 2000 presidential campaign. The
public has spoken, saying it doesn't give a damn about either.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, my wife has spoken. She said if I write about either
topic again she'll invoke the prenuptial clause about boredom.
</P>
<P>
   Politics bores the average American more than waiting in stuffy
airports for overcrowded planes, and nowadays fills many political
writers with the urge to be assigned to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   Big money, small ideas and mediocre people have made politics
less relevant to our lives than the new TV season.
</P>
<P>
   NBC has a show set in the White House called ``The West Wing.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics say it's good, but it remains to be seen whether the
public wants more inside looks at the Oval Office _ even with Rob
Lowe as a presidential aide.
</P>
<P>
   Casting celebrities is the only way to keep people interested in
politics. That's why Hillary Clinton, Jesse Ventura and Warren
Beatty have gotten so much coverage for doing almost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Mayor Willie Brown is a celebrity too, but four
years of hearing him celebrate himself has worn out his welcome.
He's likely to win re-election because his opponents, Clint Reilly
and Frank Jordan, are less appealing than he is.
</P>
<P>
   Da Mayor could become default mayor.
</P>
<P>
   It's a good thing the candidates decided to quit ``debating''
(berating is more like it). I refuse to attend any more of those
circuses, too, or be deafened by crowds of heckling political
lackeys.
</P>
<P>
   We just want this thing to be over. Brown's power and money kept
many would-be candidates out of the race. Instead they feebly hope
to fill Brown's large ermine mantle four years from now. The rest
of us just hope to catch a bus, or not have a highrise or loft
dropped on our heads.
</P>
<P>
   Brown couldn't have bought better opponents than Jordan and
Reilly. It feels as if we're at a Don King fight, with a
heavyweight blowhard vs. the best chumpdom can offer _ and it can't
end mercifully in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Already I've said too much about these guys. But from now on, I
swear I won't write about them _ unless they do something
surprising, like agreeing to bring in Indonesian troops to monitor
the election.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential sweepstakes, George W. Bush and Al Gore have
disappeared in a cloud of imaginary cocaine and wood chips.
</P>
<P>
   Things are so dull on the national political scene that Bill
Bradley is provoking interest.
</P>
<P>
   It's no surprise that the Reform Party is getting a lot of
press. It could be the spoiler in the election, but for now it's an
enhancer for political writers.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party will let anyone in. Its list of potential
candidates includes Jesse Ventura (who has said he doesn't want to
run, alas), Ross Perot, Lowell Weicker, Donald Trump and maybe even
Patrick Buchanan.
</P>
<P>
   The Reform Party is an unlocked ward for the self-deluded.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura, the head of the party, is the psychiatric attendant.
</P>
<P>
   That's how weird it is.
</P>
<P>
   Perot once talked about the federal budget as the ``crazy aunt
down in the basement.'' Now Trump and Buchanan are jockeying for
position, and the bedlam is on the first floor of the house Perot
built.
</P>
<P>
   To be nominated by the Reform Party, you don't have to pass a
litmus test on abortion, guns or gays. Instead your ego has to test
off the charts on the Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory.
</P>
<P>
   That's a psychological test invented at the University of
Minnesota, not the set of roles played by Governor Ventura of that
state. Lately he's been playing the sanest man in American
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Ventura wants to crush Buchanan's possible bid to become the
Reform Party nominee. He prefers former Connecticut Gov. Lowell
Weicker, who is crazy to want to be president because he's too
stable.
</P>
<P>
   Weicker favors the right to abortion, gun control and free trade
_ things that can only get him in trouble in the Reform Party or
with conservatives. Buchanan is against free trade and the right to
abortion, and the only guns he would ban are those used in World
War II to fight the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   This is a guy who said that Nazi Germany presented no threat to
the United States. This is a guy going nowhere but back to
loudmouth talk shows _ on the leading militia channels.
</P>
<P>
   But never fear. The enemies of Buchanan's brand of retro-
isolationism have a cosmopolitan new ally, The Donald.
</P>
<P>
   Donald Trump is trying to seduce the Reform Party by daringly
attacking Buchanan for being soft on the Third Reich.
</P>
<P>
   Reform Party intrigues are entertaining compared with the issue
of what went up George W. Bush's nose. But how can you enjoy
anything that makes you root for Donald Trump?
</P>
<P>
   Anything can happen in politics, but the smart money is on
nothing good happening.
</P>
<P>
   That includes the idea of columnists kicking politics. Still,
it's time to go cold turkey on turkeys who leave us cold.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1841EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
