u w BC-BUS-CRASHES-0922-COX     09-21 0903
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUS-CRASHES-0922-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SAFETY BOARD SNUBS SEAT BELTS IN SCHOOL BUSES
 &HT;    430&AMP;add
 &HT;    By ANDREW MOLLISON
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Seat belts might not help your children on school
buses, and might even hurt them if the belts are installed before
the seats are redesigned, the National Transportation Safety Board
decided Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The seats are not designed for seat belts. That's the bottom
line,'' said Jim Hall, chairman of the influential advisory board,
after the board was briefed by its staff on computer simulations of
school-bus crashes with and without seat belts.
</P>
<P>
   New York and New Jersey have required seat belts in new school
buses for eight years. Florida and Louisiana passed such laws this
year, and a similar bill in California is awaiting the governor's
decision on whether to sign it into law. The other states don't
have seat-belt rules for full-size school buses.
</P>
<P>
   With or without seat belts, today's school buses fail to offer
children enough protection when they are sideswiped or roll over,
the safety board concluded. The five-member board voted unanimously
to recommend that the National Highway Transportation Safety
Administration (NHTSA) develop better crash-safety standards for
school buses within the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will take the board's recommendations seriously, because
they've been working on them for a long time,'' said NHTSA
spokesman Tim Hurd. ``We are right in the middle of a two-year
study of school buses, including whether there is a better way to
protect the occupants.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hall noted that some of his board's recommendations for
safety improvements for the big tour buses known as motor coaches
have been pending at NHTSA since the early 1970's.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes it's frustrating,'' Hall said. He said he had one
consolation about how long it takes to change federal bus rules:
``The big yellow school bus remains by far the safest way for
children to go to and from school.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just blowing smoke,'' responded Alan J. Ross, president
of the National Coalition for School Bus Safety, which favors seat
belt requirements. ``They had 50,000 accidents last year in a fleet
of 500,000 buses. Most were minor, but ... if your kid rides a bus
twice a day for twelve years, your kid has a good chance of being
in an accident.''
</P>
<P>
   In an average year, 24 million children ride on school buses,
but only four die in accidents while riding in a bus. Injury rates,
though obviously higher, are unknown, because local, state and
federal data are fragmented and unreliable, the safety board said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As the board voted Tuesday for more study, rather than a quick
change in existing rules, lobbyists for the bus industry and state
school-bus bureaucracies congratulated one another, while
representatives of seat-belt makers looked glum.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I heard the board say is that there must be a way to make
a school bus a safer vehicle, although at this time we need more
research to make that happen,'' said Mike Martin of the National
Association for Pupil Transportation. ``Everybody should support
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gary Murphy, chief executive officer of Busbelts (cq)
Development Corp. of Norwood, Mass., which makes school-bus
restraints, said, ``We have some questions about the validity of
the research, and we're going to re-examine the data.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulations adopted two decades ago require that
school-bus seats consist of a flat pan with a cushion covered with
a slippery fireproof material, and attached to a high, flexible
back padded on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Rows of such seats, placed close together, protect seated
children if a bus is hit from the front or rear, according to the
board's safety engineers. But they told the board that if a truck
rams a bus from the side or sideswipes it, the children in the bus,
whether or not they are wearing seat belts, can slide sideways on
the flat seats and hit the inside of a bus or fly out a window or
door.
</P>
<P>
   The engineers said that vans, light trucks or cars are safer
with seat belts, because their curved, bucket-type seats _
especially in conjunction with light-thrust air bags _ help prevent
that. The staff also said that seat belts work better in short
vehicles than in long buses, in which someone seated at the rear
can suddenly accelerate by 25 miles per hour in less than a second
if the bus starts to spin.
</P>
<P>
   The bus safety coalition disputes that analysis. Ross said,
``Smaller school buses have the same kind of seats as the big ones,
and they have been using seat belts with good results for years.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal rules would have to be changed in order to legalize
major design changes in school buses, so competition between
manufacturers in the next few years is not expected to take the
form of a race to be the first in offering safer designs.
</P>
<P>
   In another decision Tuesday, the safety board recommended that
NHTSA combat the problem of passengers being thrown out the windows
during crashes of the large tour buses by speeding up its research
into new flexible, plasticized glass for windows. To minimize the
crushing of passengers during rollovers, the board said NHTSA
should adopt tougher roof standards for new school buses and tour
buses within two years.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
