<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0521 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-TIMOR-INDONESIA-NYT &LR;      09-21 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-INDONESIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN LEADER DEFENDS DECISION ON FOREIGN TROOPS 
</HEADLINE>
   (With TIMOR-RDP) 
 (nk) 
 By MARK LANDLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ Disliked at home, discredited abroad and
discounted by virtually everyone, President B.J. Habibie trudged
into parliament on Tuesday to explain his decision to allow foreign
troops in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I could do, and what I think is the best for
Indonesia,'' Habibie said in a 75-minute speech that represented
the first time that an Indonesian leader has had to go to
parliament to defend himself.
</P>
<P>
   Habibie urged the highest legislative body, the People's
Consultative Assembly, to ratify East Timor's resounding vote for
independence when it meets next month. Under the terms of an
agreement with the United Nations, the assembly has to vote on the
results of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to accept the results,'' Habibie said. ``It seems as
if the people of East Timor have rejected the offer of autonomy''
</P>
<P>
   Habibie said Indonesia, which annexed the former Portuguese
colony in 1976, would have never been accepted by the world if it
had not allowed the East Timorese to determine their future. He
said he had tried to stem the bloody aftermath of the balloting by
imposing martial law. When that failed, he added, the government
had little choice but to accept the troops.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope that the East Timor crisis would not go deeper,''
Habibie said as lawmakers watched with ill-concealed impatience.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia has been in a surly mood since soldiers from
Australia, Britain and other countries began fanning across East
Timor this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel particularly hurt, because we are in such a difficult
situation,'' a political and military analyst, Salim Said, said.
``Internationally as well as domestically, we have so many
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In the capital of North Sumatra, Medan, protesters swarmed over
the gates of the Australian Consulate, burned the flag and replaced
it with an Indonesian one, Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta, protests have flared in front of parliament and the
Australian Embassy. An Australian official said that gunfire hit
the embassy on Monday but that no one was injured.
</P>
<P>
   Although Habibie seems more politically fragile than ever, he
lashed out at Australia, the leader of the peacekeeping force and,
arguably, Indonesia's most important ally. Habibie said Australia
had overreacted and had breached the terms of a defense agreement
with Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that Australia has violated certain laws and
regulations in intervening in domestic problems of other
countries,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Indonesia suspended the pact with Australia last week, after
Australian officials had repeatedly condemned Jakarta for having
failed to halt the violence in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   But that scarcely stopped the Australians. On Monday, Foreign
Minister Alexander Downer declared that Australia would support a
U.N. tribunal to prosecute Indonesian officials for human rights
abuses in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
   People here complain that Australia is being highhanded. They
note that when Indonesia invaded East Timor and annexed it in 1976,
Australia was the sole country to recognize the move. But now
Australia has emerged as Indonesia's most strident critic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most Indonesians are offended by the attitude of
Australians,'' Said said. ``There is an element of the Australian
elite that has always considered Indonesia as its little brown
uncivilized neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts in Australia said pragmatism was driving the East Timor
policy. Australia tolerated the annexation, in part because
Indonesia was willing to draw boundaries in the Timor Sea, which
separates East Timor and Australia and which contains rich oil
deposits. East Timor's previous sovereign, Portugal, had dragged
its feet on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   After the fall of Indonesia's leader, Suharto, rekindled
independence passions, however, Australia determined that the East
Timorese should be given the right to vote on their future.
Australia also feared that unrest would encourage refugees to flee
to Australia, 370 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of the invasion, Australia did not have the
resources to do anything about it,'' said Harold Crouch, an
Indonesia expert at the Australian National University in Canberra.
``As circumstances change, policies change.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a measure of Habibie's low standing that many people were
disappointed when he announced at the end of the speech that he
would not withdraw his candidacy for president in elections in
November.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0273 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0522 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MICROSOFT22-COX     09-21 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FINAL FIREWORKS FLY IN LANDMARK MICROSOFT TRIAL
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Courtroom battles in the historic Microsoft
antitrust trial ended Tuesday as they began, with prosecutors
deriding the software giant as a high-tech outlaw and defense
lawyers asserting their hugely successful client has done no wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, counsels, the case is submitted,'' U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson said after sitting mute through five
hours of oral arguments over what actual facts were brought out in
testimony that ended in June.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is expected to issue his own voluminous findings of fact
before the end of the year. Based on the judge's ruling, the
contending parties may gain a fresh incentive to settle _ thereby
avoiding a final judgment from Jackson and, perhaps, years of
appeals and private litigation.
</P>
<P>
   In view of the high interest generated by the case, Jackson
agreed to shift Tuesday's oral arguments to a sixth-floor
ceremonial courtroom that is normally used to hear appeals. It was
the same setting where Microsoft won an important 2-1 verdict from
the U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in June 1998, overruling
Jackson's demand that Microsoft cleave its Internet Explorer Web
browser from the underlying Windows 95 operating system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The antitrust laws are not about the government picking
winners and losers,'' boomed John Warden, the company's lead
litigator. ``If consumers side with Microsoft, Microsoft will come
out on top, and this is as it should be,'' Warden concluded.
</P>
<P>
   The only area in which Warden and his opposite number, David
Boies, agreed was, as Boies put it: ``Central planning is bad.''
But in his final rebuttal of the day, Boies was quick to add: ``It
is bad whether it is done by the government or by a powerful
monopolist.''
</P>
<P>
   From the prosecutors' perspective, the guts of the case have
remained unchanged since the original complaint was filed 16 months
ago, despite vast changes in the marketplace, including the $10
billion takeover of Netscape Communications Corp., Microsoft's
archrival in the browser wars, by America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Boies contended that Microsoft's Windows software continues to
monopolize the operating system market for personal computers.
Moreover, he argued, Microsoft gained its dominant position by dint
of its ``anticompetitive conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no limits to what it will do to squelch emerging
competition,'' Boies asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Flashing internal e-mails and sworn testimony on three 10-foot
screens spread across the courtroom, Boies portrayed Microsoft as a
ruthless predator determined to enshrine its flagship product.
Windows runs on more than 90 percent of the world's personal
computers and is largely responsible for the vast wealth of the
world's richest man, company chairman Bill Gates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft is like the emperor without clothes,'' said Stephen
Houck, the lead lawyer for the states, who began the government's
arguments. ``Everyone knows, including Microsoft, that it's a
monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden responded, however, that ``the government has made no
valid claim that Microsoft achieved its market power _ whatever it
is _ by illegal means.'' To emphasize his point, Warden showed the
``evidence'' on the courtroom screens. They were completely white.
</P>
<P>
   Barring a settlement, Jackson will call on both sides to submit
yet another set of briefs on the ``conclusions of law'' to follow
those they have given him on their proposed ``findings of fact.''
</P>
<P>
   If so, given the wide gap between the warring parties, the judge
is most likely to frame his own conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   Should Jackson conclude that Microsoft has broken the nation's
antitrust laws, as the government and 19 state attorneys general
contend, the case would then enter a remedial phase, in which a
range of penalties could be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson could then call the lawyers back into his courtroom to
hear still further arguments on these issues, but he indicated no
intention to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0274 </DOCNO>
