<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 18:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0527 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-NOTES-660&AMP;ADD-NYT &LR;      09-21 1066
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOTES-660&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CBS SCORES, FOR OPENERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BILL CARTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The new television season started with a bit of a bang for CBS
and a distinctive whimper from the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   The first night of the official season, Monday, provided good
news for two new CBS shows, ``Ladies Man'' and ``Family Law,'' and
a surprisingly lackluster effort from Fox, which apparently missed
the memo that the new season was beginning: Fox didn't even put on
any original programming.
</P>
<P>
   ABC had the best night of any network, thanks largely to its old
reliable, ``Monday Night Football,'' which moved back to 9 p.m.
this season. But ``20/20'' at 8 had an especially big night for
ABC.
</P>
<P>
   NBC got some promising news from its new drama ``Law and Order:
Special Victims Unit'' and some ominous news from its gasping
comedies ``Suddenly Susan'' and ``Veronica's Closet,'' both of
which were thrashed by CBS' comedies, even in the young-adult
ratings that NBC always says are all that count, and that CBS
usually tries its best to ignore.
</P>
<P>
   CBS' ``King of Queens,'' newly moved to 8, had the best rating
of any show on television at that hour among viewers between the
ages of 18 and 49, a 4.9, easily defeating ``Suddenly Susan,''
which limped in with a 3.7 rating in NBC's preferred category. In
the overall ratings, ``The King of Queens'' far surpassed
``Susan'': a 9.1 rating to a 5.9. (Each rating point this season
represents 1,008,000 homes, or 1 percent of the country's estimated
100.8 million TV-watching households.)
</P>
<P>
   That set up the new CBS comedy ``Ladies Man'' at 8:30, when CBS
again buried NBC, going with the equally dismal ``Veronica's
Closet,'' in every ratings category.
</P>
<P>
   At both 8 and 8:30 Fox ran repeats of ``That '70s Show,''
finishing last in both cases and thus helping the new comedies on
the other networks.
</P>
<P>
   At 9 CBS' mightiest comedy, ``Everybody Loves Raymond,'' got off
to a stellar start with a 12.1 rating and a big 6.7 rating among
those younger adults, in both cases second only to football among
all shows for the night.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was helped by Fox, which relied on a repeat of ``Ally
McBeal.'' Because of its commitments to postseason baseball, Fox
won't begin new episodes of ``Ally McBeal'' until Oct. 25. In the
meantime the network is sticking with repeats rather than filling
in with specials.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Ally McBeal'' repeat probably also helped the new spinoff
of ``Law and Order'' get established. CBS executives said that show
had the best preseason awareness with viewers. That proved out as
``Special Victims Unit'' improved by more than three ratings points
over its ``Veronica'' lead-in.
</P>
<P>
   The show did so well that it may help the argument being made by
its executive producer, Dick Wolf, that it really ought to be on at
10 p.m. NBC's ``Dateline'' scored a rather disappointing 7.9 rating
at 10.
</P>
<P>
   That was far behind CBS' other new show for the night, ``Family
Law,'' which began with a strong 11.5 rating. It proved to be
especially appealing to the audience CBS believes is most available
on Mondays against football: women between the ages of 25 and 54.
</P>
<P>
   The results were even better news for CBS because they came one
night after another new show, ``Judging Amy,'' scored a big rating
in a one-time Sunday night tryout. The actual premiere for that
series was on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   And although Fox executives said Tuesday that they were less
concerned about doing well during the early days of a season than
in doing the best job to establish shows as hits, the network must
surely be concerned about some new shows that are not off to strong
starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get Real'' has not done well in a couple of tries against
repeats on the other networks in the first two weeks. And the
much-touted comedy ``Action'' was at best a modest success in its
premiere last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   To add to the stumbling start for Fox last week, with a number
of original shows it managed to fall behind even CBS into fourth
place for ratings among young adults, a rare event for both
networks.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vital to HBO's Plans
</P>
<P>
   One network that is very happy with its series lineup is HBO,
which announced Tuesday that it was renewing all its current series
for another season.
</P>
<P>
   That means only four shows, but series have never been stronger
for HBO. The network had already officially given ``The Sopranos''
another season, which starts in January, but Tuesday it gave
another year of episodes to the comedies ``Sex and the City'' and
``Arliss'' and the drama ``Oz.''
</P>
<P>
   Those three shows are all summer series. They begin in June and
run until the fall. Now all will be back next June.
</P>
<P>
   All three shows have seen their ratings rise this past summer,
with ``Sex and the City'' also rising like a rocket in terms of the
reaction in the press and around water coolers. It was easily the
most talked-about show anywhere this summer and even received
several Emmy nominations.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks at least partly to the success of ``Sex and the City,''
``Arliss,'' which follows it, had its best season ever. ``Arliss''
was on the verge of cancellation last season but was saved by a
campaign initiated by its creator and star, Robert Wuhl.
</P>
<P>
   This season it needs no campaign. ``Arliss'' was up 18 percent
in ratings.
</P>
<P>
   HBO will add 13 new episodes of ``Arliss'' next summer, 16 of
``Sex and the City'' and eight of ``Oz,'' the intense prison drama
that also just concluded its strongest season ever.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Albrecht, the president of original programming for HBO,
said series programming, which this pay-cable network once avoided,
is becoming vital to its plans. ``We've come to realize that series
are the staple of television,'' Albrecht said. ``You have to keep
people involved over a long period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   He said HBO was actively developing more series, although he
admitted that finding series that are distinctive enough to stand
out on HBO were hard to find.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd really like to be able to add two more comedies next
summer,'' he said. ``And by January of 2001 I want to be doing at
least one more drama to go along with `The Sopranos.'''
</P>
<P>
   Of the latter, he said, even though HBO is technically only
committed to 13 episodes more this winter, ``it and `Sex and the
City' probably have a free pass for more seasons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
