<HEADLINE>
JAPAN'S PRIME MINISTER WINS THE ENDORSEMENT OF HIS PARTY 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By STEPHANE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The governing Liberal Democratic Party re-elected Prime
Minister Keizo Obuchi as its president Tuesday, thus extending his
term as the head of Japan's government.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi, who has been prime minister for a year, has proven
unexpectedly popular, using his long-honed political skills to
cobble together a coalition government that insures him legislative
success and doling out generous dollops of taxpayer money to push
the lagging economy into action.
</P>
<P>
   Using his ability to cajole his political colleagues into
acceding to his wishes, Obuchi has pushed through credit guarantees
to bail out small- and mid-sized businesses, lowered taxes for the
rich, given the middle-class incentives to spend on housing and
handed out shopping vouchers that were financed by deficit bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Obuchi's popularity has waned lately. A survey of
4,544 voters this month by the Mainichi Shimbun, one of Japan's
leading daily newspapers, showed Obuchi's approval rating falling 8
percentage points to 32 percent, the second consecutive month in
which voters have cast a more critical eye on his achievements.
</P>
<P>
   Shigenori Okazaki, a political analyst with Warburg, Dillon,
Read, said the prime minister had been hurt by the recent alliance
he established between the Liberal Democrats and Komeito, a
political party backed by a wealthy lay Buddhist organization, Soka
Gakkai, that most Japanese regard with suspicion.
</P>
<P>
   A recent proposal to raise mandatory social security
contributions has also hurt him, Okazaki said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, few political commentators doubt that Obuchi will serve
as prime minister for the next two years, when he would once again
stand for election. He controls the largest faction in the party
and has used his skills as a conciliator to win the support of the
next two largest factions.
</P>
<P>
   His biggest immediate challenge is to sway conservatives within
the party who opposed the alliance with Komeito. There is likely to
be a struggle over the allocation of the political spoils
associated with the next supplementary budget, with Komeito hoping
to see a bigger portion for welfare spending and the conservatives
pushing for more conventional public works spending.
</P>
<P>
   The two groups are also likely to be at loggerheads in the
looming debate over amending the Constitution, with the
conservatives pushing for a more hawkish agenda and Komeito urging
amendments that impose a greater responsibility on the government.
</P>
<P>
   Although he was challenged by two colleagues for the party
leadership, Koichi Kato and Taku Yamasaki, Obuchi's triumph Tuesday
was widely expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kato and Yamasaki didn't expect to win from the beginning,''
said Masumi Ishikawa, a professor at the Niigata University of
International and Information Studies. ``They ran because they
wanted to establish themselves as future candidates for the job.''
Obuchi got 350 votes of the 514 cast; Kato had 113 and Yamasaki 51.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
