<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ETHNIC-ALBANIAN FORCE CLAIMS VICTORY IN TALKS WITH NATO 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ As NATO and U.N. officials in Kosovo
released details on Tuesday about the civilian force that will
replace the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army, the Kosovo Albanian
guerrillas were quietly congratulating themselves on winning the
deal they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what negotiations are for,'' said Hashim Thaci, the
political leader of the rebel group and the chief negotiator,
looking confident behind his desk in his downtown office. The
rebels held the international community to their promise, made as
the peacekeepers were preparing to move into Kosovo, and the
bargain was kept, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci nearly derailed the negotiations with tough last-minute
demands that brought the two sides to an impasse during all-night
negotiations on Sunday. His stubborn stance forced an extension of
the deadline and the personal intervention of NATO's supreme
commander, Gen. Wesley Clark.
</P>
<P>
   Thaci may not have endeared himself to the NATO and U.N.
negotiators for that, but he is being regarded by many Kosovo
Albanians _ as even some of the Western negotiators concede _ as a
leader who stood up for his commanders under enormous pressure from
the West and won them a good deal. As he prepares to start his own
political party and career, he also appears to have the trust of
his top military commanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the last three days we were all together, we worked
together and reached the decision together,'' he said. The
commanders were present during the last day of negotiations and met
with Clark when he flew in.
</P>
<P>
   That meeting was seen as important in swinging the commanders
behind the agreement. ``He is NATO's most senior military officer
and himself a soldier with fighting experience,'' a spokesman for
the peacekeeping force said. ``And don't forget, NATO was bombing
here while they were fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear if Clark gave any informal promises to the
Albanians, but Thaci credited him with a realistic and moderate
approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had experience of dealing with this kind of situation that
others did not,'' Thaci said. ``They knew they should reach an
agreement but did not know how.''
</P>
<P>
   The new Kosovo Protection Corps, which will have 3,000 active
and 2,000 reserve members, has been assiduously described as
civilian by United Nations and peacekeeping officials. But the
rebels succeeded in including the word ``protection'' in the name,
which in the Albanian translation gives the distinct flavor of a
defense force.
</P>
<P>
   The rebel leadership will also have a major role in recruiting
members for the organization, together with the peacekeepers, and
the senior rebel officers have already been appointed to the new
corps. Agim Ceku, the rebel chief of staff, has been approved by
the U.N. special representative, Bernard Kouchner, to lead the
corps.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels also appear to have won something of what they wanted
on the issue of weapons. The force will have 2,000 weapons,
although the majority will be held under lock and key on
peacekeepers' bases. Two hundred of the weapons, sidearms, will be
permanently in use by bodyguards and guards of bases and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the corps will also be allowed to carry personal
weapons for their own protection and can apply for permits from the
U.N. police. It is not clear how many will win permission. The
rebels had asked for several hundred permits and, one official
close to the negotiations said, may get as many as 200.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most telling indication that the rebels won what
they wanted was that they emerged looking better than the
negotiators for the United Nations and the peacekeepers, who looked
exhausted. Their relief that the deal was done was evident.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tense,'' said one U.N. official who had taken part
in the all-night negotiations. They had prepared contingency plans
in the event of the failure of a deal, but that could have meant a
stand-off around the rebel bases, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot go and arrest 10,000 men for wearing uniforms,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
