<HEADLINE>
NBC'S `THE WEST WING' LOOKS LIKE A WINNER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The West Wing'' doesn't crackle the way ``Sports Night'' did
last season. But creator Aaron Sorkin may end up with a bigger
winner because ``The West Wing'' is on NBC, which knows a thing or
two about marketing. (``Sports Night'' is on ABC, which couldn't
sell water to a thirsty man in the desert.)
</P>
<P>
   Generously populated like an episode of ``ER'' (minus the
scrubs), ``The West Wing'' is a busy, buzzy hive of
behind-the-scenes franticness. Instead of saving lives, the corps
d'elite is trying to champion the presidency of Josiah Bartlet
(Martin Sheen), favorite son of New Hampshire and maverick chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin, who wrote the film ``The American President,'' which
inspired the series, likes to keep his characters in hyperdrive.
This helps an hour pass quickly, but it requires viewers to pay
attention, lest they miss a subtle moment _ Sorkin's stock in
trade. For instance, when chief of staff Leo McGarry (John Spencer)
is complaining to The New York Times about the crossword puzzle,
it's an amusing moment _ ``They always hang up on me,'' he
complains _ but it's also metaphorical. Getting a staff to respect
the presidency is McGarry's task. Sometimes they foolishly speak
their minds in public, as deputy chief of staff Josh Lyman (Bradley
Whitford) does. Sometimes they sleep with high-priced call girls by
mistake, as deputy communications director Sam Seaborn (Rob Lowe)
does.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's premiere tries to be too cute, but Sorkin is
good at creating likable characters. Blessed with a great cast, he
may have given NBC a two-term lock.
</P>
<P>
   The West Wing. One-hour drama series about behind-the-scenes
activity at the White House. Starring Rob Lowe, Martin Sheen, Moira
Kelly, Bradley Whitford, John Spencer, Richard Schiff and Allison
Janney. Season premiere Wednesday night on NBC. Parental guideline
rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
