<SLUG> BC-POPULATION22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WORLD POPULATION TO HIT 6 BILLION ON OCT. 12, UN SAYS
 &HT;    With POPULATION-DATA.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON - The Earth's population will officially reach 6
billion on Oct. 12, the United Nations Population Fund announced
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The milestone is both hopeful and discouraging, demographers
say.
</P>
<P>
   ``People ask whether 6 billion is a lot,'' said Amy Coen,
president of Population Action International, a family planning
advocacy group. ``It's not so much the number itself as how quickly
we got here.''
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, the number represents longer life spans in
most countries, with a global life expectancy of 66, compared with
46 in 1950. More old people are adding their numbers to the overall
total.
</P>
<P>
   It means lower infant mortality, which has fallen by two-thirds
since 1950.
</P>
<P>
   It reflects improved health care, sanitation, clean water and
education in the developing countries of Asia, Africa and Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   Because of a sharp and unexpected decrease in human fertility,
the 6 billionth human being is arriving later than was predicted 30
years ago. Couples in developing countries have reduced the size of
families from almost six children in 1969 to under three.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, projections that the world's population would
eventually reach between 10 billion and 14 billion appear to have
been wrong. U.N. demographers now project that growth will start
leveling off near the middle of the next century at around 9
billion.
</P>
<P>
   The population number also has its dark aspects.
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reduce maternal deaths in many developing countries
have largely failed. While seven American women died for every
100,000 live births last year, the corresponding figure in Sierra
Leone was 1,800 deaths per 100,000 live births, and in Bolivia,
370.
</P>
<P>
   The AIDS epidemic is spreading faster than was anticipated only
five years ago. The World Health Organization estimates that
infections by HIV increased by 10 percent last year, to 33.4
million people worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In Botswana, which has the world's highest HIV prevalence rate,
one out of four adults is infected. Life expectancy has fallen from
61 in the late 1980s to 47 today, and is expected to plunge to 30
sometime after 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Another dark spot has been reduced interest among developed
countries in providing assistance for family planning activities in
poorer regions.
</P>
<P>
   Although still the world's leading donor for population
activities, the United States has recently reduced its level of
support because of funding restrictions passed by Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``Countries need to invest in population and reproductive health
programs,'' said Robert Engelman, Population Action International
vice president for research. ``Population could then stabilize by
the middle of the next century, a crucial step toward a more
equitable world for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the AIDS epidemic, the world's population growth rate
is being guided now by a ``demographic transition'' from high
fertility and high mortality to low fertility and low mortality,
the U.N. fund said in its report, ``6 Billion, a Time for
Choices.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In may respects, the less-developed regions are now about
halfway through this transition, approximately where the
more-developed regions were a half-century ago,'' the report
stated.
</P>
<P>
   While the 4, 5 and 6 billion marks in global population were
reached at accelerating rates _ 14, 13 and 12 years apart
respectively _ the rate of increase has already started to slow,
and the 7 billion mark won't be reached until 2013, or in 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
