<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VETERANS-HEALTH22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    HOUSE PASSES BILL EXPANDING VETERANS HEALTH CARE
 &HT;    By SUE SCHULTZ
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House approved a bill Tuesday ordering the
Department of Veterans Affairs to meet more of the long-term health
care needs of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to put a halt to the erosion of the Veterans
Administration's long-term health care,'' said Rep. Cliff Stearns,
R-Fla., chairman of the House subcommittee on veterans' health.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which Stearns sponsored, would require the VA to
provide more home and community-based health care options and
increase the amount it spends on long-term care. It was approved
Tuesday evening on a 369-46 vote.
</P>
<P>
   If approved by the Senate and signed by the president, the bill
would give veterans who have earned the Purple Heart in combat
higher priority access to health care, previously only offered to
former prisoners of war.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also authorize the VA to make grants to assist
homeless veterans and would re-evaluate the criteria for building
and remodeling state veterans' homes.
</P>
<P>
   Other improvements include a new pilot program providing primary
coverage for dependents of veterans, reimbursement of emergency
treatment at hospitals outside the agency's designated clinics for
veterans without health insurance, and a counseling program for
veterans who are victims of sexual trauma.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would also require the VA to develop an evaluation
program that would solicit input from veteran organizations and
employee unions on improvements to the access and quality of
service at VA hospitals throughout the nation.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also earmarks money for medical construction at
facilities in Orlando and Kansas City and for leasing new
facilities in Lubbock. Texas, and San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns said the VA has insufficient money to deal with the
nation's increasing number of older veterans. Earlier this month,
the House attempted to rectify the imbalance by giving the
department a $19.6 billion budget for 2000, the most it has ever
received in one year.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns said, ``The new millennium should not become a source of
fear or concern for our nation's veterans.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
