<SLUG> BC-AIR-CANADA-ONEX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR CANADA REJECTS HOSTILE BID FROM ONEX  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By TIMOTHY PRITCHARD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Air Canada rejected a hostile takeover proposal on
Tuesday from Onex Corp., a conglomerate that wants to merge Air
Canada with its weak rival, Canadian Airlines International.
</P>
<P>
   Delivering a formal response for the first time to the $1.8
billion (Canadian), or $1.2 billion (United States), offer Onex
made for both airlines last month, Air Canada's board called the
proposal harmful and urged shareholders not to sell their stock.
</P>
<P>
   Onex's offer is financially backed by the AMR Corp., the parent
of American Airlines, which owns a third of Canadian Airlines. The
takeover proposal would leave Canada with only one major airline.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference call with reporters, Air Canada's chairman,
Robert A. Milton, said that the Onex offer was ``structured to
rescue Canadian Airlines at Air Canada's expense, and to transfer
$1 billion (Canadian) of value from our shareholders to Onex, AMR
Corp. and Canadian's creditors and shareholders.''
</P>
<P>
   Milton would give no indication of Air Canada's preferred
strategy, but he said the airline might enlist the help of others
to thwart the takeover attempt. Analysts have speculated that the
airline may be talking with United Airlines and Deutsche Lufthansa
AG, which are its partners in the Star Alliance of international
airlines.
</P>
<P>
   Investors have been anticipating a sweetened price for Air
Canada shares since the initial takeover price of $8.25 (Canadian),
or $5.61 (United States), was announced on Aug. 24. The shares
closed on Tuesday at $9.90 (Canadian), or $6.73 (United States), on
the Toronto Stock Exchange, down 25 Canadian cents (17 cents).
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Airlines, based in Calgary, has been operating under
extreme financial difficulty for years and only the support of the
federal government and AMR has kept it flying. Air Canada, based in
Montreal, is far healthier financially but industry analysts say it
could be more profitable.
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada itself has seen the potential strategic value in a
combination with Canadian Airlines. In June, it sought to buy
Canadian Airlines' international routes for about $500 million
(Canadian), or $340 million (United States), and offered to
integrate their domestic flight schedules.
</P>
<P>
   Milton has said AMR blocked that proposal and pushed its own
plan to take over Air Canada through Onex. AMR remains an obstacle
to any revamping plan, Milton said on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When Onex bid for the shares of both Air Canada and Canadian
Airlines, coupled with a proposal to merge the two, its chances of
success looked reasonably good.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald W. Schwartz, the chairman of the Toronto-based Onex, has
good connections in Ottawa, having been a high-profile fund-raiser
for the governing Liberal party. And because Onex owns Sky Chefs,
an airline food service company, he knows something about the
business. When the government decided in July to temporarily lift
competition measures in the Transportation Act to let the two
airlines discuss ways to improve their fortunes, Schwartz saw an
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian Airlines quickly endorsed Onex's offer of $2
(Canadian), or $1.36 (United States), a share for its stock.
Schwartz has given no indication that Onex is willing to pay more
than $8.25 (Canadian) a share for Air Canada.
</P>
</TEXT>
