<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GUNS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO `ENFORCE OUR CURRENT GUN LAWS' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CLAY ROBISON 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Smoked out again on the gun issue, Gov. George
W. Bush on Tuesday turned over $1.6 million to the state attorney
general's office to help beef up prosecution of gun-law violations
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican presidential front-runner, whose opposition to
more gun-control laws drew renewed criticism after last week's
church shooting in Fort Worth, vowed to ``vigorously enforce our
current gun laws.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have some very tough laws against gun violence in Texas,
and federal law with its mandatory sentences is tough as well,''
Bush said. ``Only with tough enforcement can we win the war against
gun violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Some $1.28 million of the grant will allow Texas Attorney
General John Cornyn to hire eight assistants to help state and
federal prosecutors seek tougher sentences for criminals who use
guns.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder will fund a public awareness program, which will
include a toll-free hotline encouraging Texans to report people
illegally carrying firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The program, dubbed ``Texas Exile,'' is patterned after a
program in Richmond, Va., which, according to Bush and Cornyn, has
drastically reduced gun crime in that city.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he and Cornyn were working on the program before Larry
Gene Ashbrook walked into Fort Worth's Wedgwood Baptist Church last
week and shot 14 people, seven fatally, before killing himself.
</P>
<P>
   It was the latest in a series of recent mass shootings across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if the new effort could help prevent such tragedies,
Bush replied, ``We certainly hope so.''
</P>
<P>
   But he added: ``It's hard to convince a crazy man not to act. If
it wasn't a gun, it may have been a pipe bomb. The idea is to send
a clear message ... that there will be a consequence.''
</P>
<P>
   In Fort Worth last week to comfort the families of Ashbrook's
victims, Bush said, ``I don't know if government could have done
something to prevent this man from walking into a church.''
</P>
<P>
   During his first year in office, Bush signed the law that allows
Texans to carry concealed handguns with a license. Ashbrook,
however, did not have a license.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth shooting prompted Vice President Al Gore, a
candidate for the Democratic presidential nomination, to renew his
attacks on the Texas governor over the gun issue.
</P>
<P>
   And the latest issue of Time magazine called Bush a ``loser''
for the week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas massacre spotlights Guv's slavish devotion to N.R.A.
(National Rifle Association). Where's the `compassion,' Big Guy?''
the magazine wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Bush called the criticism ``politics.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing my job. The attorney general is doing his job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said law enforcement officers already were enforcing gun laws
but added that this program will escalate the effort into a ``war
on people who are illegally carrying weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in explaining his opposition to new gun-control laws as a
presidential candidate, has criticized the Clinton administration
for lax enforcement of existing gun laws.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the new assistants that he will hire will be
cross-designated as both federal and state prosecutors. Whenever
possible, they hope to take advantage of federal sentencing
guidelines that allow any convicted felon or drug trafficker caught
with a gun to be sentenced to five years in a federal prison.
</P>
<P>
   The sentences can be increased if the felon was involved in
criminal activity when arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Exile means ``exiled to prison,'' Cornyn said. The ``zero
tolerance'' program, he said, ``sends a clear message to convicted
felons and drug dealers. If you carry a weapon in Texas, you'll do
hard time in federal prison.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush criticized the Clinton administration for what he called a
40 percent decline in federal prosecutions of gun offenses during
the past six years. But federal prosecutors from Texas joined the
governor and Cornyn to support their announcement.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Attorney Paul Coggins of Dallas, a Clinton appointee, said
the new resources were ``tremendously needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides the hotline, the public awareness campaign will include
newspaper ads, bus posters and billboards carrying the message that
``Gun Crime Means Hard Time.'' That slogan was borrowed from the
city of Fort Worth, which even before last week's church shooting
had patterned a local program after the one in Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and Cornyn said that Richmond, Va., had the second highest
murder rate in the nation in 1997, the year it began ``Project
Exile,'' an intensive effort to keep guns out of the hands of
criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the Richmond program, which is supported
by the NRA, more than 300 criminals have been convicted. The city's
murder rate has dropped by 33 percent, and its rate of violent
crime has decreased by almost 50 percent, Bush and Cornyn said.
</P>
<P>
   As he has before, Bush told reporters Tuesday that he supported
criminal background checks for gun purchasers.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, in the wake of fatal shootings at a high school in
Littleton, Colo., Bush said he supported requiring background
checks of people purchasing guns from unlicensed sellers at gun
shows. But he did not lobby the Texas Legislature for a gun show
bill, which was killed by a House committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said the loophole should be closed in federal law.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
