<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-WOMEN-745&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LINGERIE AD ON BILLBOARD SPARKS MEXICAN DEBATE ON WOMEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By SAM DILLON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Anna Fusoni Ponthier, a television executive, was
driving home from work along one of Mexico City's major
thoroughfares in May when she saw a towering billboard photograph
of a blond model, clad only in bra and panties, promoting a line of
lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you move it like you shake it ...'' the advertisement said,
citing part of a vulgar adage popular in Mexican cantinas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `How horrible!''' recalled Ms. Fusoni, who worked
for a time as an editor at Vogue magazine after her graduation from
Vassar in 1966. ``That's not funny, that's just gratuitous
aggression against women.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of nursing her anger quietly, Ms. Fusoni fired the first
shots in what has grown into Mexico's latest battle over sexuality
and women's rights. In letters to trade associations and
advertising groups, she complained that the campaign by the Vicky
Form lingerie company was sexist and degrading.
</P>
<P>
   Her letter-writing campaign led to an appearance on a television
talk show in July, and her criticisms set off a clamorous cultural
debate. Feminist groups criticized the Vicky Form billboards,
saying they were incitements to rape. A Mexico City government
agency that works to provide legal and other aid for women
collected thousands of signatures on a protest petition.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the federal prosecutor for consumer affairs ordered the
company to clean up the advertisement and threatened to impose
heavy fines. The company agreed to paint a dramatic black X over
the slogan that Ms. Fusoni saw and on others on its billboards here
and in 10 other Mexican cities.
</P>
<P>
   Waldo Cervantes, the advertising executive responsible for the
campaign, said the blacked-out slogans would serve to protest what
he called an attack on free expression.
</P>
<P>
   The billboards all feature photographs of a model in underwear
and a popular aphorism suggesting some sexual interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the safe is left open, even an honest man will steal,''
reads one advertisement, showing Ignacia Esnal, an Argentine model,
seated in lingerie with her legs spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``A bird in the hand is worth ...'' reads another slogan,
alongside a photo of another Argentine model, Jackie Fedete,
beckoning consumers with a come-hither gaze.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after receiving a May 17 letter of complaint from Ms.
Fusoni, the Council for Self-Regulation and Ethics in Advertising,
a private sector group, wrote urging Vicky Form to tone down its
advertising, saying the language used ``denigrates and offends
women, as well as men and children.'' The company responded by
eliminating two billboards that had been criticized as especially
obnoxious.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a clear attack on free expression,'' Cervantes said in
an interview. The government's threat to impose fines, he said,
resulted from a campaign by a wealthy elite.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built this advertising campaign on folk expressions that
are an accumulation of popular wisdom,'' Cervantes said. ``Most of
our critics are cultural retrogrades who are out of step with the
tastes of the Mexican masses.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our campaign has worked well,'' he added, noting that the
billboards, along with a similar campaign last year, had helped to
quintuple Vicky Form's sales.
</P>
<P>
   Several diners, passing Cervantes' table and seeing several
poster-sized photographs of the Vicky Form billboards piled on a
chair, stopped to offer opinions.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're enchanting!'' gushed a paunchy man who identified
himself as a merchant but declined to offer his name.
</P>
<P>
   Cervantes, inspired by the show of support, called out,
``They're Argentine models!''
</P>
<P>
   Araceli Ibarra Granjales, a hospital administrator, gazed at the
posters for a time, a finger at the corner of her mouth, before
concluding, ``I think they're in good taste.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Mexico City government disagreed. The city, run by the
Party of the Democratic Revolution, a leftist coalition of former
socialists and Communists, waded into the controversy after it came
to the attention of officials at Promujer (For Women), a
300-employee municipal agency that works to promote self-esteem and
business opportunities and offers legal counseling to women.
</P>
<P>
   ``To sell its lingerie, Vicky Form offers us female models in
positions that together with slogans or sayings present them as
merchandise offered to men, which is offensive to us women,'' says
the petition that Promujer employees are encouraging city residents
to sign.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The petition drive has invited comparison to a 1996 campaign in
which billboards advertising Wonderbra brassieres came under attack
from the National Action Party, which has roots in the Roman
Catholic Church, as violations of public decency.
</P>
<P>
   The Wonderbra billboards displayed a woman with a sumptuous
bosom wearing a satin brassiere and saying, ``I'm sorry, I just
can't hide it.'' After municipal governments in several cities
governed by National Action put pressure on Wonderbra to remove the
billboards, several prominent leftists criticized the center-right
party as intolerant and prudishly moralistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please make clear that our criticisms of Vicky Form are not
based on moralism _ this is different,'' Gabriela Delgado
Ballesteros, a psychology professor and Party of the Democratic
Revolution activist who is Promujer's general coordinator, said in
an interview. ``In my opinion, the Wonderbra billboards were
excellent. They showed a woman who was proud of how she looked. But
the Vicky Form ads are just vulgar insults.''
</P>
<P>
   The city's petition drive aroused strong emotions in many women.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get angry every time I see one of these billboards,'' said
Katia Gonzalez Romero, the coordinator of a municipal office in the
working-class Iztacalco district, who collected 300 signatures.
``When you're a woman in Mexico, you have to protect your body
every minute you're in the street or you'll be touched. And this
campaign just invites more sexual aggression.''
</P>
<P>
   With public clamor growing, the federal government stepped in.
An Interior Ministry official, the general coordinator of the
national commission for women, began to exert pressure on the
company.
</P>
<P>
   The federal prosecutor for consumer affairs filed suit against
Vicky Form, arguing that the billboards were deceptive to
consumers. Vicky Form surrendered, agreeing to cover the slogans.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Fusoni said she had been hoping the industry would police
itself and was not entirely comfortable with the government's
decision to suppress the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing is certain,'' she said. ``This shows that women's
complaints are beginning to have real political weight.''
</P>
</TEXT>
