<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NAZI-PAST-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VISIT BY U.S. JEWS LEADS GERMAN TOWNSPEOPLE TO CONFRONT NAZI PAST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL LOPEZ  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Atonement, of a deep and fragile kind, stirred in
a rural Bavarian town of Unsleben this summer, where the fairy-tale
castle, red-tiled roofs and rolling farmland hide the sins of the
past.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the synagogue, abandoned when Unsleben's 150 Jews fled
Nazi genocide in the late 1930s, reportedly became a stable, then
grange, and now, the town hall. The granary where Ludwig Nauman
processed grain for the local farmers also has been absorbed by the
town government building. The Nauman homestead, where Ludwig and
Hilde Nauman's son, Fred, played so many decades ago with his
beloved dog Orpal, is remodeled, the family name erased from its
outer wall. Someone else lives there now.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Nauman of Ballston Lake, N.Y. and 40 members of his
extended family in early July traveled to Unsleben, in this
famously picturesque part of Germany, at the invitation of resident
Angela Bungert, who forced Unsleben to confront its past.
</P>
<P>
   The trip did not spur an overwrought epiphany in Nauman, now 69,
who has vague boyhood memories of a traumatic immigration to
America. Rather, he and other relatives describe the return to
Unsleben as a simple affirmation of humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we discovered is that people are not uniformly bad or
good,'' he said, ``that even though this society allowed these
horrors to happen, the descendants of those people are interested
in putting this shame behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Though it's not their personal shame, it's a national shame.
And they do want to reach out.''
</P>
<P>
   The key German host, Bungert, a journalist and public relations
specialist, in a message to Nauman, had spoken of the unease
stirred among some Unslebeners about the return of their former
Jewish neighbors: ``Some people here are afraid. This box they
don't want to open. But it will be very good to have you here in
Unsleben.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, days before Yom Kippur, the most solemn day of the
Jewish religious year, marking repentance and soul-seaching, Nauman
described the journey back to Unsleben.
</P>
<P>
   It all began last year, when Nauman, secretary treasurer of New
York State United Teachers, who is also an avid genealogist, was
seeking family records. He contacted Bungert through an unfinished
Web site on Unsleben. She soon raised the prospect of a visit, and
Nauman and his older sisters, Lottie Hess and Ruth Derison, rallied
relatives from as far away as Israel and France.
</P>
<P>
   Then this summer they returned to a place many had fled some 61
summers before, in 1938.
</P>
<P>
   By that year, Hitler's laws restricting the rights of Jews had
crippled the population. Because Jews were forbidden to trade with
Gentiles, Ludwig Nauman's grain business all but stopped. Sponsored
by family in the United States, he had immigrated to New York City
the previous year to get a job and later retrieve his family.
</P>
<P>
   Within 18 months, according to Nauman, nearly all of Unsleben's
150 Jews, a thriving community of bakers, teachers and factory
owners, were gone. On Nov. 9 and 10 of that year, Nazis initiated
what is considered the first act of widespread aggression of the
Holocaust. Now referred to as Kristallnacht, ``the night of
shattered glass,'' the pogrom was responsible for the murder of 91
Jews, the imprisonment of thousands and the destruction of
synagogues, cemeteries and businesses throughout Germany and
Austria.
</P>
<P>
   Bavaria was a stronghold of the Nazi party. In Munich, Hitler
established the party's administrative complex and his racial
Nuremberg Laws were born there on Sept. 15, 1935.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe what saved us was the fact that it got bad early enough
for us to get out,'' said Nauman. Today, he comments with some
irony about his strong attachment to Orpal, the shepherd dog he
left behind and whose absence left a more indelible mark than his
father's departure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would have had to get rid of him anyway if we didn't leave,
because Jews were not allowed to have thoroughbred animals.'' To
the 8-year-old, boarding the SS Manhattan bound for South Ferry in
New York, was a ``great adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred saw his first motion picture and had his first taste of
chewing gum, which he now believes was taffy. But his sister Ruth,
just a year older, in a recent family newsletter, wrote of
terrifying memories. ``People I remembered so were beaten up, or
worse, sent to concentration camps to die. I still see myself as a
little girl, drapes tightly drawn, hearing Nazis passing by ... ''
</P>
<P>
   That Fred Nauman has so few memories is now significant. His
parents had effectively smoothed what had to have been a worrisome
passage to America. ``Many years later, I finally realized how
brave it must have been for my father ... to just pick up and go
somewhere else, with the whole family,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, too, his parents spoke of the betrayal they felt, in an
atmosphere in which Gentile friends did little to help their
oppressed neighbors. A rural middle-class couple, the Naumans lost
everything. Ludwig Nauman, who did not speak English, had to begin
life in New York stocking shelves at S. Klein, the department store
at Union Square. Typical of many immigrants, he insisted that his
children speak English at home. The Naumans, too, would host other
arriving relatives in their Queens home.
</P>
<P>
   The Nauman relatives' return to Germany reads, in family
newsletters, much like a VIP tour: a concert in the family's honor,
a visit to the town castle.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there was trepidation, worry about being received with
hostility by some townspeople. It didn't happen. ``The atmosphere
surprised all of us, on just how positive it was. We were expecting
at least some significant resentment. I'm sure it was there
somehow, but it didn't manifest itself.''
</P>
<P>
   After the war, what was then West Germany began a program of
reparations. The government reinstituted his father's veterans
pension and his mother's social security and gave each of the
Nauman children about $2,000 because they'd been denied public
schooling. Now, the Nauman family is uninterested in pursuing
further reparations or claims to property, feeling that it would
raise the potential for some anti-Semitic sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   A German newspaper, Sueddeutsche Zeitungticle, also pointed out
a fervent desire by some townspeople to tell the truth about the
disppearance of Unsleben's Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The article described how one woman, in her 90s, doggedly made
sure she dictated the name of every Jewish resident she could
remember before she died. Most were able to escape to far-flung
destinations including Cuba and South America, but 16 people were
deported to concentration camps.
</P>
<P>
   The Naumans did not lose immediate relatives, but some of those
who were deported and died were distantly related, he said.Nauman
said his family was not looking for a direct apology from their
hosts, many of whom were not born until after the war.
``Philosophically I don't blame the children for the sins of the
parents,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1926EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
