<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0291 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0557 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-BOS &LR;      09-21 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON SAYS US CAN'T BE LONE WORLD POLICEMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Narrowing America's guideposts on when and
where it should intervene in the world's burgeoning humanitarian
crises, President Clinton told the UN General Assembly Tuesday that
stopping mass killing required a shared responsibility and that the
United States couldn't do it alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know some are troubled that the United States and others
cannot respond to every humanitarian catastrophe in the world,''
said a hoarse Clinton, struggling to speak. ``We cannot do
everything, everywhere. But just because we have different
interests in different parts of the world does not mean we can be
indifferent to the destruction of innocents in any part of the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's comments _ his seventh annual speech to the General
Assembly _ came against a backdrop of criticism of the United
States' varying responses to humanitarian tragedies around the
world and followed by a day a call by Secretary-General Kofi Annan
for the UN Security Council to take the lead role in humanitarian
interventions.
</P>
<P>
   Twice in the last 16 months Clinton had seemed to indicate that
the United States would take a more active role in stopping mass
killing. In Rwanda, on the fourth anniversary of the genocide that
killed a half-million people, he pledged the United States would
``never again'' stand aside and do nothing if it had evidence of
mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   And in Macedonia after the end of the Kosovo war, he told NATO
troops in Macedonia, ``If somebody comes after innocent civilians
and tries to kill them en masse because of their race, their ethnic
background or their religion, and it's within our power to stop it,
we will stop it.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton, who remains stung by the failed 1993 peacekeeping
mission in Somalia that ended in retreat, Tuesday tried to lower
expectations of future US role in stopping conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should work to end violence. (But) that does not mean our
response in every case can or should be the same. Sometimes,
collective military force is both appropriate and feasible.
Sometimes, concerted economic and political pressure combined with
diplomacy is a better answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also offered two other ``resolutions'' for the United
Nations in coming years: that it should battle global poverty more
effectively and work toward ending the threat posed by weapons of
mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   He made only passing reference to the US debt to the United
Nations, which some estimates say approaches $1.7 billion, pledging
he will try to get Congress to pass legislation authorizing the
payment.
</P>
<P>
   His most closely followed portion of the speech, though, was on
principles of intervention, an issue which has become the talk of
the United Nations in the first week of its 54th annual session.
Annan also said rogue states should not expect that their borders
will protect them if they commit atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton took issue with Annan's belief that the Security Council
act as the world's sole arbitrer of humanitarian tragedies. The
United States and its 18 NATO allies sidestepped the Security
Council before bombing Serbia because it didn't want to be
embarrassed by Russian and Chinese vetoes.
</P>
<P>
   On taking action in the Kosovo war, Clinton said, ``Had we
chosen to do nothing in the face of this brutality, I do not
believe we would have strengthened the UN. We would have risked
discrediting the UN. By acting as we did, we helped to vindicate
the principles and purposes of the UN Charter, and to give the
United Nations the opportunity it now has to play the central role
in shaping Kosovo's future.''
</P>
<P>
   A Western diplomat, speaking on condition of anonymity,
applauded Annan's efforts to raise the issue, but said Annan's
ideas contained ``a fatal flaw. The UN is not a self-selecting
institution. The major powers consist of Russia, France, China, the
US and the UK. If we are going to put his words into practice, the
United Nations has got to overcome the divisiveness of the major
powers in order to respond to big crises.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, said Clinton, the world's reaction to slaughters ``will
depend on the capacity of countries to act and on their national
interests. NATO acted in Kosovo, for example, top stop a vicious
campaign of ethnic cleansing in a place where we had important
interests at stake and the ability to act effectively.
</P>
<P>
   ``The same considerations brought Nigerian troops and their
partners to Sierra Leone and Australians and others to East
Timor,'' Clinton said. ``And that is proper _ so long as we work
together and support each other, so long as we don't collectively
abdicate responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who spent only eight hours in New York and met with at
least seven heads of state (Portugal, Argentina, Slovakia, South
Africa, Colombia, Tanzania and Venezuela) also raised multiple
questions in his speech on how the world would respond to the most
pressing problems in the next century.
</P>
<P>
   He rattled off an alarming set of statistics on the world's
widening gap between rich and poor: 1.3 billion people live on less
than a $1 a day; a person in South Asia is almost 700 times less
likely to use the Internet than a person in the United States; 40
million people die every year of hunger, a toll almost as high as
all those killed in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Said Clinton: ``We must refuse to accept a future in which one
part of humanity lives at the cutting edge of a new economy, while
another lives at the edge of survival.''
</P>
<P>
   His solutions: keep markets open; reduce debt of countries
struggling to rise; try to reverse global climate change because it
devastates agriculture and accelerates the spread of disease; and
provide better health care.
</P>
<P>
   And then he gave more depressing numbers: AIDS is expected to
kill more people and orphan more children in Africa over the next
10 years than all the wars of the 20th Century combined; and only 2
percent of all global biomedical research is devoted to the major
killers of the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged another $100 million to fight the AIDS epidemic
in Africa, and said he will convene a special White House meeting
to strengthen incentives for research and development toward
vaccines for malaria, tuberculosis, AIDS and other diseases. Among
those invited will be public health experts, pharmaceutical company
CEOs, foundation representatives and members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Correspondent Joe Lauria contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
