<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-MASTRANGELO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSEPH P. MASTRANGELO, 77; WAS WASHINGTON POST FEATURE WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Joseph P. Mastrangelo, a Boston native who began a newspaper
career inking drawings for Walt Kelly's comic strip ``Pogo'' and
who later became a feature writer for the Washington Post, died
Saturday (Sept. 18) of a heart ailment at his home in Washington,
D.C. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. Mastrangelo was the quintessential `newspaperman' of the
old school,'' the Washington Post noted in its obituary.
</P>
<P>
   In newspaper stories often praised for warmth and wit, Mr.
Mastrangelo sometimes recalled his youth as one of 12 children
growing up in three-deckers in and around Boston.
</P>
<P>
   If the written word became Mr. Mastrangelo's forte, art was his
first love. He married an artist, and his two children are artists,
Susan Mastrangelo of New York and Ann Mastrangelo of Brookline,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   As a child, Mr. Mastrangelo learned the fine points of curve and
color from an older brother who, under the name of Charles Martin,
gained fame for paintings that regularly graced the cover of The
New Yorker magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Mastrangelo's artistic ambitions were interrupted by
World War II. The day after Pearl Harbor, he enlisted in the
Merchant Marine, and promptly had a ship torpedoed out from under
him. Preferring to be on the shooting end of torpedoes, he arranged
a transfer to the Navy's submarine service.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Mr. Mastrangelo came to New York, where his skill
at drawing maps and inking comic strips landed him jobs at PM, the
New York Herald Tribune, and the New York Times.
</P>
<P>
   It was his skill as a cartographer that brought him to the
Washington Post, and he spent much of the 1960s and early '70s
drawing maps that accompanied Post reports on the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mr. Mastrangelo could tell funny stories, colleagues
urged him to moonlight as a writer, and soon the one-time mapmaker
was writing a humor column called ``Out &AMP; About.''
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include two daughters, two sisters, a brother, and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1929EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0568 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r e BC-TV-WESTWING-REVIEW-55     09-21 0873
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-WESTWING-REVIEW-550&AMP;ADD-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRISK `WEST WING' SHOWS A BUSY, DIGNIFIED PRESIDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A TV series about the White House isn't supposed to move. It's
supposed to sit down ponderously and tend to national business.
</P>
<P>
   It figures to be eye-glazingly dull, because when TV types get
close to important things, real things, it converts them into
oatmeal.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, NBC proves expectations wrong. It's all in the
execution. The White House of ``The West Wing'' is a jumping place.
</P>
<P>
   Come to think of it, it's a little like ``ER.'' You half expect
the Prez (Martin Sheen) to order up a couple cc's of FEMA funds in
a frantic ploy to save a stricken patient.
</P>
<P>
   ``ER'' producer John Wells, one of the three co-executive
producers of ``The West Wing,'' might account for the swirling
sense of busyness in the presidential business.
</P>
<P>
   Check those tracking shots as chief of staff Leo McGarry (John
Spencer) arrives at work early in the show. On the way to his
office, wearing his raincoat, he's seemingly accomplished more than
some executives do in a full day.
</P>
<P>
   After all, 1,200 Cubans are bobbing on rafts en route to Miami.
The president, Josiah Bartlet (this fictional president is supposed
to be descended from one of the signers of the Declaration of
Independence), has just injured himself riding a bicycle into a
tree.
</P>
<P>
   And more. A powerful senator is thinking about challenging for
the presidency. Deputy chief of staff Josh Lyman (Bradley Whitford)
has enraged the Christian right with his remarks on a TV chat show.
</P>
<P>
   Then too, McGarry is in a huff because he's sure the name
Khadafy has been misspelled in the New York Times crossword puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   If the show's hectic pacing is ``ER''-ish, there's an even
heavier infusion of another producer, Aaron Sorkin, in Wednesday
night's pilot.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin (``Sports Night,'' ``A Few Good Men'') displayed a knack
for capturing the modern presidential aura in the 1995 film ``The
American President,'' in which Michael Douglas played the president
and Sheen played the chief of staff. That film was a pre-Monica
romantic comedy in which Sorkin's script was moderately reverential
in conjuring a vaguely liberal, feel-good executive mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin wrote the script for Wednesday's ``West Wing,'' and he's
duplicated his feat. It's as if Monica Lewinsky never passed
through the Oval Office on her fateful path toward Bill Clinton's
zipper.
</P>
<P>
   Sorkin has made Josiah Bartlet a Democrat, and a former
governor, like Clinton. But at first blush, at least, Bartlet isn't
someone who'd take a sexual interest in a White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen makes his appearance late in the show, supported by
crutches from his bicycle mishap. He snuffs out some staff
nonsense, spouts a few homilies involving his granddaughter, waxes
idealistic about the Cuban boat people and reminds everyone that
playtime had ended.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen is a good choice, authoritative and yet still folksy and
approachable. He does seem a bit manic at first, though. There's
something weird about him; I think it's the dentures.
</P>
<P>
   (As for the show's first lady, she does exist, at least on
paper. Her name is Abby, but she doesn't turn up in the first
episode and apparently won't be seen for several weeks, at least.)
</P>
<P>
   This time, Sorkin's obvious respect for the dignity of the
office works intentionally as a kind of balm for viewers who'd
welcome a fresh gust of decency, even fictional decency, from 1600
Pennsylvania Ave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe there's a certain amount of wish fulfillment here,''
Sorkin said in a recent interview. ``Maybe we'll be excited to look
at the White House the way we wish it was a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Not that ``The West Wing'' is altogether Capra-esque. There's a
budding story line, for example, involving Rob Lowe as deputy
communications director Sam Seaborn. He's spent a night with a call
girl. He didn't know she was a call girl, but there's a scandal
brewing if Sorkin wants a cup of it.
</P>
<P>
   The ensemble cast also includes Allison Janney (``American
Beauty'') as press secretary C.J. Gregg, Richard Schiff as
communications director Toby Ziegler and Moira Kelly (``To Have and
to Hold'') as political consultant Madeline Hampton.
</P>
<P>
   It's an exceptional cast, in a brisk, smart, satisfyingly
dramatic take on life in America's most auspicious workplace. Score
one for NBC; ``The West Wing'' figures to be a hit.
</P>
<P>
   _ Which is more than can be said for another Wednesday show,
ABC's ``Oh Grow Up,'' a horrendous sitcom about three guys sharing
a house in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Make that three guys and a talking dog called Mom. It speaks in
subtitles. ``Arf, arf'' means ``Get a room.'' Laugh? Really, I
thought I'd die.
</P>
<P>
   The guys are Hunter (Stephen Dunham), a skirt chaser; Norris
(David Alan Basche), an aspiring artist; and Ford (John Ducey),
who's just declared that he's gay and left his wife (Rena Sofer).
</P>
<P>
   The unbelievable aspect of this forgettable comedy is that it's
created by Alan Ball, who wrote the much-praised script for
``American Beauty.'' It's a fact, and a head-scratcher.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (For use by New York Times News Service clients) &QL;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
