<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-CHINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RESPONSE TO QUAKE, BEIJING OFFERS AID AND SYMPATHY 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ Saying that the people of China and Taiwan are ``as
closely linked as flesh and blood,'' President Jiang Zemin of China
offered condolences and aid to Taiwan's earthquake victims on
Tuesday in a statement issued by the Foreign Ministry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The catastrophe and agony of our Taiwan compatriots affect the
hearts of all Chinese,'' Jiang was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
   China's press on Tuesday evening carried similar messages of
sorrow and concern from several of the agencies dedicated to
relations with Taiwan, which China considers a lost province that
must be reunited with the mainland.
</P>
<P>
   The statements on Tuesday made no direct reference to Chinese
anger over the Taiwanese president's recent rejection of the
longstanding ``one China'' formula. President Lee Teng-hui's
assertion this summer that Taiwan and China must negotiate as two
separate states, seen here as a step toward declaring independence,
was answered with a barrage of warlike statements from Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   But in response to questions on Tuesday, a Foreign Ministry
spokeswoman, Zhang Qiyue, repeated the customary reference to
Taiwan as a region of China, pressing the point by thanking foreign
countries that were sending aid to earthquake victims. She said
that the sovereignty dispute and the earthquake were ``two
different subjects'' and that China would not relent in its demand
for political unification.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang's statement said: ``We are willing to provide all possible
assistance to reduce losses from the earthquake disaster.'' So far,
the only announcement of concrete assistance has come from the
Chinese Red Cross, which pledged to send $100,000 in cash and
$60,400 in relief materials. As of Tuesday night there have been no
calls for public donations, such as followed disastrous floods on
the mainland last year.
</P>
<P>
   On the national television news on Tuesday evening, the disaster
in Taiwan played second, after reports on Jiang's visit to a museum
exhibit celebrating the 50-year history of the People's Republic.
The government is mounting a huge celebration of the Oct. 1
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   In the news report on the earthquake, China Central Television
featured the statements of deep sympathy by Jiang and other leaders
and an announcement of the Red Cross aid.
</P>
<P>
   The television report also said that the State Council's Taiwan
Affairs office had sent an ``urgent circular'' to the Taiwan
Affairs offices in each province, calling on them to show concern
and sympathy for ``Taiwanese compatriots'' living or touring in
their localities. The provincial offices were also instructed to
assist any resident Taiwanese who wanted to return quickly to
Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the political freeze, tens of thousands of Taiwanese
pursue business in China and it is also a popular tourist
destination for Taiwanese, many of whom have relatives on the
mainland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
