<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-DOGS-COX     09-21 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-DOGS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Some animals displaced by flood reunited with owners
 &HT;    By David Blount
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ As floodwaters left by Hurricane Floyd began
rising, Dr. Bobby Sherwood jumped in a canoe and paid an an unusual
visit to his office at Riverside Veterinary Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   With 4 feet of water sloshing inside the clinic, Sherwood sprung
open the cages of animals kenneled at the facility. Next, he called
other boaters to help him rescue the animals.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ben Turner said all but four animals were rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost one client's Chihuahua,'' he said. ``We also lost
three cats we had taken in after they were abandoned. We managed to
get all of the other animals out.''
</P>
<P>
   Next door to Riverside, rescue attempts for the animals at the
Rocky Mount Animal Shelter were not as successful. Several smaller
dogs, two adult cats and six kittens were killed by floodwaters
before city workers could reach the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We managed to save about 15 dogs and eight cats,'' said
Officer Don Cashwell, a shelter employee. ``We came in on boat on
Thursday and managed to get them out. The water was probably
waist-deep. We just didn't expect it to get so high.''
</P>
<P>
   Cashwell said most of the animals were frantic as workers began
hauling them out of the building. Many of the dogs were standing on
their hind legs to keep above the high water.
</P>
<P>
   Officer Jean Wood is sheltering the rescued animals at her home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are glad we got here, but we are sorry we couldn't save
them all,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Leonard, owner of Animal World, was less fortunate in her
rescue attempts. Leonard tried to find someone to take her to the
store last Wednesday and Thursday, but could not find an available
boat.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, however, she found someone with a personal watercraft
who was willing to brave the waters to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was 4 feet of water at that point outside the mall,''
Leonard said. ``Judging by the damage, I'd say the water got 6 or 7
feet deep in the store.''
</P>
<P>
   The water pressure was so great outside the door to the mall
that Leonard had to use a crow bar to pry open the entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was horrible,'' she said. ``Everything was floating. It was
like being aboard the Titanic. There were dumpsters floating
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Once inside Animal World, Leonard discovered most of her animals
had already drowned. The only survivors of the flood were a snake,
two cages of finches, a guinea pig, and one puppy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one dog was a pug,'' Leonard said. ``The others were baby
poodles and baby Yorkshires, and they couldn't make it. This one
was three weeks older than the rest and was just a little taller.
He was able to tread water just a little longer.''
</P>
<P>
   Leonard, fittingly, has named the pooch Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided if were going to keep it, we should name it after
the storm,'' she said. ``We are keeping the animals at my son's
house until we can find another location for the store.''
</P>
<P>
   While the mall remains closed, Leonard is looking for a new
location for her shop. Her customers have remained loyal as well,
offering to clean up and do whatever is necessary to reopen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cried from Thursday to Monday,'' Leonard said. ``I don't
know if I have any tears left. Those animals were pets that we
tried to find good homes for and we took care of. It is so hard to
see something that you've played with and handled and now it's
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Only three of the 15 animals at the Rocky Mount Children's
Museum managed to survive the flood.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, a 40-year-old alligator, Snarf, a 35-year-old python,
and Lizzy, a boa constrictor, are the only occupants left at the
mud-covered museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are excited that they made it,'' said Parks and Recreation
Director Pete Armstrong. ``Still, the workers at the museum were
devastated by the animals we did lose. We were scheduled to redo
the museum before the flood and now we just have a lot more to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong said he talked with FEMA officials and hoped funds
would be available for the damaged museum.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a branch that deals with art centers and museums,''
he said. ``They recognize the value these places add to the
community.''
</P>
<P>
   In another neighborhood, one pet owner was reunited with his
lost dog after the storm.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Harry G. Fish was evacuated from his home on Thursday
morning by boat, according to his daughter-in-law Ashley Fish,
leaving behind the family German shepherd, Duchess.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no way they could get her out the door,'' Ashley
Fish said. ``The current was too strong. ``You could hear her
barking and it was not a good sound. But the water was 4 or 5 feet
deep inside the house at that point. They (her in-laws) were taken
to my parents' house and were so sad about the dog.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday afternoon, Dr. Fish's son, Don, was determined to
find Duchess and reunite the dog with her owner.
</P>
<P>
   At 5 p.m. that night, Ashley Fish received an excited phone call
from Louis Pulley, a family friend who said he had discovered the
missing dog.
</P>
<P>
   ``They brought the dog over to Dr. Fish and everyone was so
elated,'' she said. ``It was very emotional for all of them. We
don't know how she got out. She would not put one toe in the water
before, but she learned how to swim quick and fast when she had to.
It was a bright spot in a dark day.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
