<HEADLINE>
WORKING WOMAN IN TROUBLE WITH IN-LAWS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``l'' lifestyle file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   Senior royals are peeved at the &UR; Countess of Wessex &LR; , says a
Sunday Times of London report cited by reader  &UR; Julie Pinchin &LR; ,
because the former  &UR; Sophie Rhys-Jones  &LR;  has a money-making career.
According to the Times,  &UR; Sir Robin Janvrin &LR; , private secretary to
the queen, has been dispatched to tell the newest royal that she
must make a choice between her career and her role as a royal.
</P>
<P>
   When the countess posed for publicity photos with new Rover cars
after her PR firm won the Rover account, the queen was
``surprised,'' said the newspaper. In addition, the countess's
planned promotional tour for Rover in the United States has
 &UR; Prince &LR;   &UR; Charles &LR;  and  &UR; Princess Ann &LR;  ``aghast,'' said the
newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   The  &UR; Earl of Wessex  &LR; (formerly  &UR; Prince Edward &LR; ) recently sold a
U.S. television network a series on the life of the  &UR; Queen &LR; 
 &UR; Mother &LR; , his grandmother. She is refusing to cooperate, says the
Times.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE BIG QUESTION &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Confusion is a necessary part of art, writes playwright  &UR; Tom &LR; 
 &UR; Stoppard &LR;  in the New York Review of Books.
</P>
<P>
   Citing great 20th century plays _ ``Waiting for Godot'' and
``The Birthday Party'' _ Stoppard says they each ``broke a
contract, which up to that era had been thought to exist between a
play and its audience.'' Before those plays, it seemed ``that if
you could be bothered to show up to watch something up there, then
the thing up there had certain obligations toward you, such as the
obligation to give you the minimum information you needed to make
sense of the whole.''
</P>
<P>
   The best plays can leave the audience somewhat frustrated,
writes Stoppard. ``Art which stays new, in  &UR; Ezra Pound &LR; 's phrase,
is art in which the question `what does it mean?' has no correct
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHALLENGE TO A BAY AREA DUEL? &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Howard Junker &LR; , editor of the Bay Area literary magazine
Zyzzyva, has drawn a playful (to give him the benefit of a doubt)
sword on  &UR; Wendy Lesser &LR; , editor of the Bay Area literary magazine
the Threepenny Review. They're ``hardly rivals,'' writes Junker in
his latest issue, because Lesser's model is the New York Review of
Books; his is the New Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   But several points must be made: In 1980, when he worked at the
University Art Museum, she declined his offer of using some of its
art in her magazine. Also, in 1991, she rejected a piece he had
submitted. Then, he recalls a softball game years ago between the
two journals, when poet  &UR; Robert Pinsky &LR; , playing for the Review,
crashed into him on purpose at second base. ``I was so shocked
...'' writes the editor, ``that I merely called him a jerk.''
</P>
<P>
   And 12 years ago, when the Los Angeles Times wrote a piece about
the two journals, Lesser's picture was on the front page of the
arts section and Junker's was inside. Furthermore, Junker was
unable to obtain a free copy of Lesser's recent book of
autobiographical essays, ``The Amateur.'' Sometimes life really
isn't fair.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ Rep.  &UR; Jesse Jackson Jr. &LR; , D-Ill., and his father, the  &UR; Rev. &LR; 
 &UR; Jesse Jackson &LR; , are co-authors of the forthcoming ``It's About the
Money! How You Can Get Out of Debt, Build Wealth and Achieve Your
Financial Dreams,'' says Roll Call. A press release about the book
says that the authors believe making money ``is the fourth step in
the movement to freedom,'' after emancipation from slavery, getting
the right to vote and the end of segregation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Last week's account of the theft of a Golden Nica award was
incorrect. Etoy's ``theft'' was a hoax, and the trophy was returned
immediately after the press conference. Also, it was not the award
