<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOMING-POPULATION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD POPULATION EXPECTED TO REACH 6B IN OCTOBER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DOLORES KONG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Marking the fastest population spurt in history, the world will
reach six billion people Oct. 12, a milestone that raises serious
questions about the limits of the planet's resources, UN officials
say.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Earth's population reached its first billion in 1804,
each subsequent billion has taken less time attain. In fewer than
40 years, the world's population has doubled from three billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The sixth billion is the fastest we'll be adding, taking only
12 years,'' said Carl Haub, a demographer with the Population
Reference Bureau, a nonprofit demographic and information
organization in Washington. ``When is billion No. 7 going to
come?''
</P>
<P>
   Unchecked, the growth could harm the environment, lead to
disease and famine, prompt wars over increasingly scarce resources
and limit the ability of nations to provide education, housing,
jobs and health care to its citizens, say UN officials and others
concerned about the potential for overpopulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The carrying capacity of the glob? No one has the answer,''
said Dr. Nafis Sadik, executive director of the United Nations
Population Fund, which Tuesday released a report, ``6 Billion: A
Time for Choices.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she added in a telephone interview Tuesday, ``whether the
world will stabilize at 7-1/2 billion, 8-1/2 billion, 9-1/2 billion
_ it's something we could influence by the actions of today.''
</P>
<P>
   While Sadik pointed to such successes over the last few decades
as the increase worldwide in use of contraception from 10 percent
to 60 percent and the halving of the average family size, she said
much more must be done.
</P>
<P>
   The potential for overpopulation has held humankind's attention
since at least the time of T.R. Malthus, a 19th century English
economist and clergyman who predicted population growth would
exceed the food supply unless war, famine and disease reduced the
numbers, or the growth was slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago in Cairo, at an international conference, 179
countries, including the United States, agreed that population is
linked to poverty, empowerment of women and environmental
protection. Both developed and developing nations agreed that $17
billion a year would be needed by the year 2000 for international
family planning and reproductive health services, but that figure
looks unlikely to be reached.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big part of that is the US failure to live up to its
agreement,'' said Brian Dixon, director of government relations for
Zero Population Growth, a grass-roots organization concerned with
the effects of rapid population growth, in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Officials concerned about overpopulation criticized some members
of Congress for holding up the millions of dollars promised for
international family planning services _ as well as the more than
$1 billion owed the United Nations in back dues _ because of US
abortion politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have held it up as hostage on their anti-choice agenda,''
said Representative Carolyn Maloney, a New York Democrat who has
co-sponsored legislation to reauthorize $25 million in funding for
international family planning services. She participated in a
telephone news conference announcing the release of the UN
Population Fund's report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame that it's gotten tied up in so many other
political battles,'' said Sally Ethelston, a spokeswoman for
Population Action International a private, nonprofit research and
advocacy organization in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Coalition for Life, however, has urged
its members to support attempts by Representative Chris Smith of
New Jersey to tie both payment of UN back dues and international
family planning funding to strict anti-abortion provisions. ``The
reform most needed at the UN is to get them out of the population
control business,'' the coalition stated in a recent Internet
posting.
</P>
<P>
   Another critic of the United Nations, Ben Wattenberg, a senior
research fellow at the conservative American Enterprise Institute,
called the UN's claims ``pretty silly.'' While he agreed that the
sixth billionth baby will be born any day now, he said UN world
population projections are inflated, and that the numbers will be
adjusted downward because of the decline in the fertility rate that
is already occurring, according to a syndicated column published
last week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1941EDT &QL; 
