<TEXT>
<P>
   ATTENTION ALL EDITORS:
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow, The New York Times will publish its most comprehensive
special news section ever _ on electronic commerce. Stories from
this section will be available for oneshot purchase from The New
York Times Syndicate starting Friday, Sept. 24.
</P>
<P>
   What follows are brief descriptions of some of the stories that
The Syndicate will be offering. More stories will be available for
purchase. All will be slugged BC-E-COMMERCE-keyword-NYTSF and will
be sent to category codes ``a'' general news and ``f'' business
news.
</P>
<P>
   For more information about the stories from this special
section, contact one of the following New York Times Syndicate
sales representatives:
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697.
</P>
<P>
   _ Europe and Asia: KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11; fax,
47-42-80-44 or 47-42-18-81; telex, 282-942.
</P>
<P>
   _ Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A FEEDING FRENZY MADE FOR CONSUMERS &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By SAUL HANSELL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Internet companies and their investors are desperate to get big
fast _ so much so that they are almost willing to bribe people to
shop with them. As a result, the savvy cyberconsumer can find sites
selling all sorts of items. You name it, someone has started a Web
site to sell it: Autoweb, Furniture.com, Pets.com, and the list
goes on. What's the allure? Which Internet retailers are making
money? And which aren't?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUY HERE, AND WE'LL TELL YOU WHAT YOU LIKE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By PHIL PATTON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There are Hollywood agents, literary agents, real-estate agents
and travel agents. Now meet Internet agents. ``Intelligent agent''
programs and their kin, ``shopping bots,'' are among the hottest
new areas of electronic commerce. They hold out the promise of
making shopping on the Internet better not just by finding lower
prices but matching products to the needs and tastes of individual
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAN EMERGES, STILL BREATHING, AFTER E-CAVE CONFINEMENT &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MATT RICHTEL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E-commerce has revolutionized the selling of books, compact
disks, travel and financial services and computer hardware and
software _ commodities shoppers don't need to squeeze and prod to
get a handle on. But will the on-line bazaar work for everyday
survival? In an attempt to find out, writer Matt Rich sealed
himself into an E-cave. For five days, he ordered all sustenance
and entertainment from the Net. He survived, but will he ever be
the same? Here, he offers his diary.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHAT SEX SITES CAN TEACH EVERYONE ELSE &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By COREY KILGANNON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Where can an E-business turn for a model of how to make money on
the Web? To the entrepreneurs who were the first to make E-commerce
pay and whose businesses are still the most profitable sector of
the Internet: the on-line pornographers. Pornography sites have
pioneered technical and marketing developments that are at the
heart of the business plans of many enterprises that would not be
caught dead on the same server. Writer Corey Kilgannon explains how
the porn industry is thriving. In a sidebar titled ``Keeping It Out
of Your House,'' Kilgannon lists the software filters for blocking
pornography from personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOW TO TALK DOT-COM LIKE A WEBMASTER &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By GILES FELTON &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Every leap of technology brings its own leap of jargon. After
all, it's an easy way for Early Adopters to distinguish themselves
from I-Just-Learned-How-to-Program-My-VCR-and-Now-You-Expect-Me
to-Do-WWW-What? In this feature, Giles Felton offers a guide to
some of the more useful new terms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NIGHT OF THE LIVING BID: TALES FROM AN HOUR OF EBAY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By LISA GUERNSEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since Ebay, the on-line auction house, opened its doors in 1995,
more than 3.8 million people have registered to participate, and
millions more have visited its site, www.ebay.com. Watch the items
for sale on this site and traces of the new E-Commerce community
emerge. Recent auctions included a Minnkota speedboat motor, a
computer with a 500-megahertz processor and 12 sets of Beanie
Babies. In this article, Lisa Guernsey offers a few of their
stories. In a related sidebar, Guernsey lists some hard-learned
lessons from EBay users.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; LATEST HIT ON CAMPUS: CRESCENDO IN E-MAJOR &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By MARY B.W. TABOR &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to offering degrees, the halls of academia are not
immune to trying what's hot every now and then. What's sizzling
right now, given the successes of the dot-com crowd, is the
E-commerce credential. Colleges and universities nationwide are
rushing to turn the study of business on the Internet into degrees,
majors, minors, concentrations, specialities, certificates,
fellowships and research centers. A report.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MAKE A QUICK PURCHASE. WAIT FOR THE DELIVERY MAN &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID KIRBY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting products out of the virtual shopping cart and into the
home is a barrier to E-commerce growth. But the cost of home
delivery and the hassle of waiting for it are enough to drive even
patient consumers to the mall. And who has ever returned a sweater
on-line? But things are beginning to change, writes David Kirby.
Home delivery, a hallmark of the 19th century, is making a big
comeback. And analysts say that means that whatever else happens in
E-commerce, the delivery industry will be a big winner. A report.
</P>
<P>
   Many Thanks!
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times Syndicate
</P>
