<HEADLINE>
`ONCE AND AGAIN' TO GET BOOTED TO A DIFFERENT TIME SLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0601 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u e BC-TV-REVIEW-ONCE-HNS &LR;      09-21 0706
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-REVIEW-ONCE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ONCE AND AGAIN' TO GET BOOTED TO DIFFERENT TIME SLOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK McGUIRE  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Of all the new shows, there is only one guarantee: ``Once and
Again'' will be knocked from its Tuesday night perch come November.
</P>
<P>
   Yep, it's a goner. It is also the best show ABC is introducing,
and one of the best dramas of the new season, an insightful adult
look at post-divorce dating and the complications posed for and by
the kids. And it will still get the boot.
</P>
<P>
   That's because ``Once and Again'' is just renting the 10 p.m.
Tuesday time slot on ABC until ``NYPD Blue'' returns Nov. 9.
</P>
<P>
   After that, it is slated to return in January, probably into the
``Monday Night Football'' slot after the season ends. Maybe sooner,
maybe not.
</P>
<P>
   That is better than a two-month hiatus _ two months for a show,
even as good as this one, to fade from memories and viewer
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   ABC is conceding it is a big risk. Renting a slot worked for
``The Practice,'' which slid into the Monday night slot from
Saturdays a few years back before finding a home on Sundays. And
maybe it can work again.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the network likes the show _ and with good reason _
judging from all the promotional effort behind it. And the
creators, Edward Zwick and Marshall Herskovitz, the makers of
``thirtysomething'' and ``My So-Called Life'' (now there is a
strong pedigree), are confident that ABC will keep the show strong,
even if it leaves the air for a period.
</P>
<P>
   And they are not so convinced that it will.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're a network executive. A show goes on the air and it does
extremely well. It seems to build momentum. Do you take it off the
air?'' Zwick rhetorically asked reporters in July. ``Or, if you
take it off the air, do you then pay no attention to it during that
time and make sure people forget about it and lose all the momentum
that you had?''
</P>
<P>
   The story follows two single parents, the recently separated
Lily Manning (Sela Ward) and Rick Sammler (Billy Campbell), as they
tentatively venture into seeking and accepting love after marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, each gives documentary-style analysis via
black-and-white interviews with an unseen, unheard third party.
They don't talk directly to the camera _ a fad this season _ but
the inserts in the drama provide insights that otherwise could
weigh down the narrative.
</P>
<P>
   The children, particularly Manning's lovelorn and confused
14-year-old daughter Grace (Julia Whelan), throw constant obstacles
into the burgeoning relationship.
</P>
<P>
   A show that focuses on the ``Can-I-get-a-sitter?'' instead of
``Can-I-get-Dad's-car?'' dilemmas of dating is refreshing.
</P>
<P>
   The moment this show was announced, it was immediately dubbed
``fortysomething,'' and that is not a slight. Ward, best known for
her Emmy-winning role on ``Sisters,'' is at 43 one of the sexiest
people on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think perhaps unwittingly they've written something that
celebrates age, that celebrates that at 40 there is life,'' Ward
said. What a refreshing, unique concept for a youth-obsessed
industry. What a refreshing show.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a thought raised by a colleague: How disconcerting is it
for those who remember the original recipe (and the late) Colonel
Sanders, the dignified, Southern gentleman in a white coat of KFC
fame, now portrayed as an animated dervish who resembles Foghorn
Leghorn on crack?
</P>
<P>
   And have you seen the ad for Levi's in which a bodaciously
beautiful woman and a guy strip naked out of their jeans _ and the
rest of their clothes _ with the catch being that their bodies are
invisible?
</P>
<P>
   It is among the most titillating spots to ever air on network
television (along with those Herbal Essence/women moaning shampoo
commercials), even though it shows, well, nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The commercial is great at getting attention for Levi's, a
hurting company. But even though I'm about as far from a prude as
you can get, this should not air in daytime or early evenings, as
it has (especially during football games). Even showing nothing,
the ad leaves little to the imagination.
</P>
<P>
   McGuire can be reached at 518-454-5467 or by e-mail at
mmcguiretimesunion.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0314 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0602 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS &LR;      09-21 1309
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JASPER-TRIAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARENTS OF WHITE SUPREMACIST PLEAD FOR SON'S LIFE, EMBRACE VICTIM'S
FAMILY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PATTY REINERT 
and RICHARD STEWART 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRYAN, Texas _ The parents of a white supremacist convicted in
last year's dragging death of a black man tearfully embraced the
victim's family Tuesday, moments after pleading with jurors to
spare their son's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like all of you people to know our hearts and our
prayers are with you,'' a sobbing Lawrence Russell Brewer Sr. said
as he shook hands with James Byrd Jr.'s parents, sisters and nephew
outside the courtroom. ``God bless you all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had met under different circumstances,'' he told
Byrd's father, James Byrd Sr. ``I'm awfully embarrassed by this.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that he hoped he and Byrd could go fishing together one
day. Byrd took Brewer's hand and nodded in acceptance.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just breaks my heart to know this family lost someone,''
Brewer said later. ``They're wonderful people.''
</P>
<P>
   Jurors convicted Lawrence Russell Brewer Jr. of capital murder
Monday in the June 7, 1998, death of James Byrd Jr., a 49-year-old
disabled man who was stripped and chained by his ankles to a pickup
and dragged more than three miles down backwoods roads east of
Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   The same jury will hear closing arguments in the trial's
punishment phase and decide whether Brewer, 32, should get a life
sentence or join fellow racist John William ``Bill'' King on death
row. A third defendant, 24-year-old Shawn Allen Berry, will be
tried next month in Jasper.
</P>
<P>
   The emotional scene came after Helen Brewer had testified about
her son's childhood and asked jurors to let him live. After the
lunch break, Brewer's father, a former Army sergeant, took the
stand, crying and begging jurors to spare his son.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the bottom of my heart, there are two things I would
really want,'' Brewer told the jury, his voice breaking. ``That's
to ask for forgiveness and to allow my son ... If you take his life
you're killing more than one.
</P>
<P>
   ``This family is torn apart, as I'm sure the Byrd family is,''
he said. ``To take his life is more than this family can bear.''
</P>
<P>
   Brewer told the jury that although he was stationed overseas for
much of his son's childhood, all five of his children were reared
in a strict, religious, military family. The younger Brewer was
taught to ``trust and love not only God but his fellow man,''
regardless of skin color, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He described his son as a polite youngster who as a teen-ager
fell in with the wrong crowd and began using drugs and skipping
school. Against his wife's wishes, Brewer said, he kicked his
14-year-old son out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to have Russell leave our home,'' he cried. ``I was
afraid he would influence our other children.''
</P>
<P>
   As he stepped down from the witness stand, Brewer, said, ``God
bless you, the Byrd family.'' He stopped at the defense table and
grabbed his son's hand on his way out, and both sobbed quietly.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, who has a history of heart problems, then took a
nitroglycerin tablet. Once outside the courtroom, he collapsed into
a chair. A paramedic who had been standing by gave him oxygen and
checked his pulse and blood pressure as a precaution.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer, a Vietnam veteran, said begging for his son's life was
worse than anything he had ever faced in the Army. ``This was by
far the most painful thing I've ever had to do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Helen Brewer and others testified that when her son
would occasionally sneak home after being kicked out, she would
allow him to stay briefly in a camper behind the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd tell him, 'Russell, you know your daddy won't let you come
home,''' she said. ``He would always say, 'Which way, Momma? Which
way do I go?'
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good person. He's a loving person,'' she said. ``Drugs
is what led him astray. He just got with the wrong people.''
</P>
<P>
   When she visited him in the Jasper County Jail shortly after his
arrest, Helen Brewer said her son ``cried and cried and cried.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And he said, 'I don't remember,''' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's aunt, cousin and a family friend also testified
Tuesday, tearfully telling jurors that Brewer had always been a
quiet, timid child who cowered and hung his head when people talked
to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no way he could ever be a leader,'' said Paula Cruz, a
friend from church.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer's defense attorney Doug Barlow showed the jury 11
poster-size color photos of Brewer growing up. They included
pictures of Brewer and his brother as boys, posing with their arms
around a black friend, and Brewer with his Hispanic ex-wife and
their son.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Roberts, a psychologist called by the defense, testified
that Brewer, though not mentally ill, has a severe anti-social
personality disorder, suffers from paranoia and has attempted
suicide more than once.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs reassurance. He wants to be included,'' Roberts
testified. ``But he also has a strong fear that people will reject
him or humiliate him so he hangs on the fringes of the group.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how that personality jibed with Brewer's status as the
leader, or ``Exalted Cyclops,'' of a racist prison gang, Roberts
pointed out that Brewer wasn't a very effective leader and that the
group fell apart under his leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Russell could lead a horse to water if it's thirsty,''
he said. ``He wanted to be the leader, but it was like Fred
Flintstone wanting to be the Grand Pooba of the Water Buffalo
Club.''
</P>
<P>
   And Roberts disagreed with a psychiatrist who had testified for
the prosecution that Brewer would be a continuing threat if he were
allowed to live.
</P>
<P>
   On cross-examination, Assistant U.S. Attorney Johnny Stevens,
who is assisting Jasper County prosecutors, asked Roberts: ``If I
had asked you on June 6, 1998, whether he would be a future danger,
what would you have said?''
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said he would have answered no.
</P>
<P>
   ``And you would have been wrong,'' Stevens said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's certainly possible that I'm wrong now,'' Roberts replied,
``but I think the odds are low.''
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, prosecutors had called witnesses who testified about
Brewer's previous prison record, which includes convictions for
burglary, cocaine possession and parole violations that have kept
the defendant in prison most of his adult life. They also showed
the jury several guns that Brewer had stolen after breaking into
the homes of two men.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatrist Edward Gripon testified Tuesday that after
interviewing Brewer for more than two hours, he concluded that the
killer's personality disorder causes him to blame others for his
own actions, to engage in self-pity and to show no remorse. Brewer
was bothered more by being caught than by what he did, Gripon said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Brewer would be a continuing threat, Gripon said,
``Unlike those of us who wonder what our potential for violence
might be, Mr. Brewer has answered that question.''
</P>
<P>
   As court recessed Tuesday, Byrd family members said they were
touched when the Brewers greeted them outside the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem like a very nice family,'' said Clara Taylor, Byrd's
sister. ``There's no need to blame them for what their son did.''
</P>
<P>
   But she said the elder Brewer's pain was caused by the actions
of his son. ``And our pain was caused by what his son did.''
</P>
<P>
   Another of Byrd's sisters, Stella Brumley, said that as a
parent, she could empathize with Brewer's parents and expected them
to ask for their son's life. ``I can understand that part of it,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said her brother's killer might have been a model child,
``but he didn't turn out to be a model person when he made a choice
June 7 to do something so hideous.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether Brewer deserves mercy, she said, ``He didn't give
any mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
