<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-JORDAN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JORDAN TEEING IT UP _ BUT ON NANTUCKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The Ryder Cup, also known as the Where's
Jordan Jubilee, moved into its second day Tuesday with former NBA
icon Michael Jordan not to be spotted among the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan was nearby, and he was on a golf course, but he wasn't on
the Massachusetts mainland. For the second straight day, he teed it
up with friends at the tony Nantucket Golf Club, the same course he
played Monday with ex-NHL great Mario Lemieux, former Pittsburgh
Penguin Dan Quinn, and Mike Eruzione, the former Boston University
Terrier who captained Team USA's hockey gold medal triumph at the
1980 Olympics in Lake Placid, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, along the fairways here at The Country Club, the most
often heard question among the spectators was, ``Have you seen
Michael?'' Tiger Woods is all the rage on the course, but that's
only inside the ropes. The biggest buzz of the tournament could
come when MJ hits the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is believed to have rented a home bordering the course
through the tournament's final matches Sunday. Just where that
house is, and just how much of a ransom Jordan shelled out to rent
it this week, remains speculation. The latest rumor had Jordan
occupying a beige, two-story colonial, with Victorian touches,
located just behind the course's International Pavilion adjacent to
the No. 2 tee box.
</P>
<P>
   However, a young man who answered the door at 195 Newton Street,
with its backyard abutting the International Pavilion, denied
Jordan would be staying there.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said, ``this is a private residence. He is on the
street, though, from what I hear. I wish he was staying here.''
</P>
<P>
   If Jordan golfed all the courses he was rumored to play, he
would be one tired hacker. Varying reports had His Airness teeing
it up at Wannamoisett in Rumford, R.I., Farm Neck on Martha's
Vineyard (a Bill Clinton favorite), and both Brae Burn and Charles
River in Newton. Spokesmen for all four noted courses said Jordan
had not golfed there Tuesday and there were no plans for him to
play there later this week.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan played in a traveling Nantucket foursome Monday,
accompained by Lemieux (new owner of the Pittsburgh Penguins),
Quinn, and Eruzione. They opened with nine holes at Sankaty Head,
which was being aerated, and then moved on to play a full loop at
nearby Nantucket Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some notification that (Jordan) was coming out,'' said
Mark Heartfield, the pro at Sankaty Head. ``I believe that Mario
Lemieux is a member at Oakmont in Pittsburgh and the pro there, Bob
Ford, called here and asked if they could play.''
</P>
<P>
   Word around Sankaty Head was that Jordan shot 37, 1 over par, on
the front nine before moving on to the next course.
</P>
<P>
   A source familiar with Jordan's plans for later this week said
the retired superstar will host a party at his rented home for
members of both Ryder Cup squads. Two other retired icons, former
NHL star Wayne Gretzky and ex-Denver Bronco John Elway, are
expected to attend. The crowds along the fairways could hold more
famous faces than the fairways themselves.
</P>
<P>
   In a news conference, US Ryder Cup star Tiger Woods said he
spoke with Jordan Monday night. Jordan played for the US Dream Team
that won the basketball gold medal at the 1984 and '92 Olympics _ a
tournament with an international profile akin to the Ryder Cup _
but Woods said he didn't trade tournament comparisons with Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just kind of talked about what he's doing and just kind of
shooting the breeze,'' said Woods. ``That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Practice resumes bright and early Wednesday and the real stuff
begins Friday. Until then, the Where's Jordan Jubilee continues.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
