<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-BIZPACT-COX     09-21 0530
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-BIZPACT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Business start picking up pieces in flood's wake
 &HT;    By Gene Metrick
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROCKY MOUNT, N.C. _ Twin County merchants began the grimy task
of cleaning up their flood-damaged businesses this week.
</P>
<P>
   At Tarrytown Mall, maintenance workers and office employees
joined shop owners in dredging out the mud and moisture left by the
55 inches of water that had filled the inside of the mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastation _ 100 percent of our stores received water
damage,'' said Leigh Haislip, general manager of the mall.
</P>
<P>
   The mall's benches, plants and garbage cans lay heaped together
in piles, strewn across different spots along the main walkways.
Shop owners, their friends and employees wandered in and out of the
stores, surveying the damages and looking to see what could be
recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what I'm going to do, I don't have any flood
insurance,'' said Chong Pak, owner of Tharrington's Cobbler Shop,
as he and his wife, Yisoon, carried their damaged tools and
supplies outside for cleaning. ``It's a big mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Haislip said the cleanup will be limited to daylight hours until
the power is restored.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no structural damage, so that's the good news,'' she
said. ``But where do you start?''
</P>
<P>
   Prem Gulabrai, owner of Le New York and PJ's Sportswear, said
aside from cleaning up and working toward eventually re-opening,
his main concern is his creditors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always had good credit, so I hope the suppliers can
understand,'' he said. ``For the moment, we're just trying to do
our best. Everything is destroyed.''
</P>
<P>
   Across U.S. 301, vehicles streaked with mud and debris filled
the Premier Ford-Lincoln Mercury car lot. In the front, a dumpster
was wedged against a light pole, straddling the hoods of two new
Ford Expeditions like an ornamental marker reminding passers-by of
the fury of the receded waters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The total inventory was under water except for maybe 20
cars,'' said David Hughes, general manager of the car dealership.
``They'll be total losses.''
</P>
<P>
   Hughes said the cleanup effort began Saturday, with small crews
of employees tackling the chore of removing the silt and stains
left by the 5 feet of water that at one time sloshed throughout the
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to try to operate by replacing the carpet and
patching things up,'' he said. ``But the building damages are
miniscule compared to the equipment damages.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with the damaged vehicles, the dealership also lost most
of its service tools and computer diagnostic equipment, Hughes
said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Allen said he'll soon be looking for a new location for his
Sunset Music store, which was buried under 7 feet of water after
Stony Creek overflowed and turned the intersection of Sunset Avenue
and Forrest Hill Road into a raging river engulfing everything in
its path.
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably 90 percent of the merchandise and equipment is lost _
there's water inside everything,'' he said. ``We'll be busy for a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Metrick writes for The Rocky Mount Telegram, Rocky Mount,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
