<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0615 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-NATO-MEETING-640&AMP;ADD-     09-21 1012
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-MEETING-640&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER KOSOVO, EUROPEAN ALLIES DISCUSS MODERNIZING FORCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (gm) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ NATO defense ministers, meeting for the first time
since the end of the Kosovo air war, agreed on Tuesday that the
European members of the alliance have to spend far more money on
modern arms and equipment to carry their share of the
responsibility in war.
</P>
<P>
   The Kosovo war, with its daily demonstrations of the huge
disparities between American and European forces, confirmed the
growing technology gap between the two forces and its effect on
even the most sophisticated armies to react quickly in war.
</P>
<P>
   In the closed session on Tuesday morning, Clinton administration
and NATO officials said, Lord Robertson, the British minister of
defense who will become secretary-general of NATO next month, said
that even though the European countries sent only 2 percent of
their combined armed forces for use in the Balkans, they did so
slowly and with great difficulty. If they could not use the 2
percent effectively, then what, Robertson asked his fellow defense
ministers, was the use of the remaining 98 percent of their armies.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of Defense William Cohen argued that the lesson of
Kosovo is that even though European governments are trimming their
budgets, they can spend their defense money more wisely _ on better
weaponry as well as on new communications equipment and transport.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO countries spend roughly 60 percent of what the United
States does and they get about 10 percent of the capability, ``
Cohen said on Tuesday. ``That has to change.''
</P>
<P>
   A lack of precision-guided munitions was chief among the
European shortcomings during the war. Even though European
warplanes sometimes flew half of the nightly bombing sorties, they
had to rely on the United States to supply them with the
laser-guided bombs they needed to hit their targets.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we learned is that in a conflict like this,
it is not politically sustainable in the long run for one ally to
have to bear as much of the burden of actually delivering the
ordinances,'' said a senior administration official.
</P>
<P>
   Transporting troops and equipment was another large problem for
the Europeans. On Tuesday, they agreed to a suggestion from Cohen
to take greater advantage of private commercial planes and
aircraft. For his part, Cohen said the United States learned of its
own shortfalls during the Kosovo campaign and as a result is buying
more C-17 transport planes, more ships to carry heavy equipment and
more precision-guided munitions.
</P>
<P>
   Other major headaches arose with European logistics and
engineering capabilities, their spotty communications networks and
their intelligence capabilities, administration and NATO officials
have said.
</P>
<P>
   Several countries did not have secure radio networks for their
pilots and were forced to speak to pilots of other NATO nations on
the open airwaves, which were monitored by the Serbs. That problem
should have been easy to solve, said a senior NATO defense
official.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does it take to have secure radios we all can use?'' the
official said. ``Not much. It takes the Europeans buying American
radios and they don't want to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   After undertaking a defense review of British forces, Robertson
said Tuesday that the Europeans can find the money to buy new
equipment by cutting unnecessary duplication of their efforts and
taking better advantage of their multinational forces.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO's 50th anniversary summit meeting in Washington last
spring, when the outcome of the Kosovo air campaign was uncertain,
all NATO members adopted a ``defense capability initiative''
requiring the European nations to close the gap between the United
States and Europe. Now, with the alliance proclaiming victory in
Kosovo, Cohen is trying to insure that the Europeans follow through
on their promises.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We're not saying they have to look like us but we are saying
we all have to be able to talk to each other, we have to be able to
share data and intelligence and work together as a team,''' said a
senior administration official here.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, there are few countries other than the United
States that produce all the equipment that will be on the
Europeans' shopping lists. Cohen said on Tuesday that the United
States is developing lower-cost precision guided munitions that
would be more affordable for the European allies and that the
United States manufactures the special aircraft for collecting
intelligence that the Europeans said they would acquire.
</P>
<P>
   To make those purchases the Europeans will have to overhaul
their budgets and make more drastic changes in their armed forces
that still look too much like Cold War standing armies, lacking the
mobility and the resources to be deployed quickly outside their
national borders.
</P>
<P>
   Without those changes, the Europeans will be unable to take the
next step in creating their own defense and security arm within
NATO, a goal they reconfirmed this year in the midst of the Kosovo
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some European nations were humiliated to discover that for all
the money they spent they could not fly with the big boys in
Kosovo,'' said a senior Administration official.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials would not provide estimates of the amounts that
nations would have to spend to upgrade, saying only that individual
countries would have to find the money. With financial difficulties
making it difficult for many European governments to maintain their
current level of defense spending, the defense ministers gathered
here avoided making any promises of actual increases in their
defense budgets.
</P>
<P>
   One solution may be trans-Atlantic mergers and joint ventures
between European and American defense industries, a policy the
Department of Defense began pursuing this summer. Such mergers
would help Europe catch up with American technology and help insure
the compatibility of the equipment used by the alliance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 1953EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
