<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0617 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      09-21 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FRIEDMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: GO AHEAD, BORE ME! 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By THOMAS L. FRIEDMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Go ahead. Get crazy for a minute. In the wake the latest
Israeli-Palestinian agreement there are several reasons to be just
a tad optimistic about the prospects for a final settlement. I
could go down the whole list, but the most exciting thing is the
silence _ the deafening silence with which the silent majorities in
both Israel and the Arab world have embraced this latest deal.
</P>
<P>
   The tough-minded accord that the Israeli prime minister, Ehud
Barak, recently negotiated to improve and implement the Wye
agreement was exactly what the Israeli everyman has been looking
for. The Israeli center concluded that it was not comfortable with
the idealist approach to peacemaking of Shimon Peres and, to some
extent, Yitzhak Rabin. They seemed to be going too fast. And then
the Israeli center decided it was not comfortable with the cynicism
and media manipulations of Bibi Netanyahu, who only seemed to want
to go nowhere fast.
</P>
<P>
   The Israeli center wanted something in between _ someone who was
more interested in making a difference than in making a point,
someone who wouldn't give away anything cheap, but someone who
would just do it, if and when the ``it'' on the table made sense.
That is what Barak represents. A few days after the Israeli Knesset
ratified the accord, I asked an Israeli friend, Victor Friedman, a
consultant who lives in the village of Zichron Yaakov, what was the
mood. He messaged back: ``I've been trying to take the pulse of the
country. The problem is, I'm having a hard time finding it. When I
ask people what's been going on, the universal answer is `nothing.'
So I continue to give Barak high marks for his amazing ability to
make progress without arousing strong emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Barak says that by Feb. 13 he wants to have worked out the
outline of a final deal with the Palestinians _ including
Jerusalem, water, settlements and refugees. That's very ambitious.
But the silence in Israel suggests that Barak is going to have a
relatively free hand. And even if the Big Deal can't be struck,
Barak will have the latitude to offer the Palestinians a mini-deal:
a Palestinian state in a large part of the West Bank, in return for
guarantees of demilitarization and a willingness to postpone the
unresolved existential issues, such as Jerusalem, for later. For an
ailing Arafat, who wants to see a Palestinian state before he dies,
that could be tempting.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for a little optimism is the partnership that's
been restored. Barak actually had Arafat to his house for talks.
During the past few years no problem was too small for the two
sides to find a way to argue forever about it. Today, the mood is
no problem is too large that they can't find a way to manage it.
That may not last, but, for now, it's a real asset. Said the U.S.
negotiator Aaron Miller: ``If there is one thing we have learned
it's that the odds of implementation, for any agreement between
Israelis and Palestinians, go way up if they are problem-solving
with one another directly, and making commitments to one another
directly.''
</P>
<P>
   Add it all up and you find that they're increasingly building a
critical mass of people in Israel and the Arab world, not who love
each other, but, much more important, who are willing and able to
ignore each other. We know now that love is not going to be part of
any Israeli-Arab deal. But we can hope for silent acquiescence. The
way to build silence is by building an expanding pool of people who
not only want to tend their own gardens, without reference to the
other side, but who are able to do so. That's why things like the
safe passage road between Gaza and the West Bank, or the new port
in Gaza, which were part of the latest accord, are important.
</P>
<P>
   The parties' ability to focus inward will never be 100 percent,
because they're too intertwined and there will always be people
without gardens, and therefore there will always be another bomb
that can crash the silence. But you can get a deal where a
significant portion of Palestinians and Israelis are simply no
longer interested in the conflict so that the worst explosions are
contained. The more people who yawn about the peace process _ and
get exercised instead about democracy, tariffs, schools and
religious issues _ the more you should take heart.
</P>
<P>
   The romance of the peace process is over. For now, love will not
be its product or byproduct. I'm rooting for indifference and
acquiescence. Blessed are the peacemakers, for they shall make us
bored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
