<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELAN PRESIDENT STRESSES HIS COMMITMENT TO DEMOCRACY 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: FILED in ``a'' and ``i'' categories.)  
 (For use by New York Times Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Venezuelan President Hugo Chavez, denying that he was
trying to impose a dictatorship, on Tuesday promised that he would
build a democracy in Venezuela that would help end poverty in his
oil-rich nation.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, making his first visit to the United States since being
sworn in as president last January, said the basis for his reform
program was the incongruity between Venezuela's rich natural
resources and the widespread poverty of its citizens.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can such a rich country with oil, gas, gold, iron and
fertile soil be inhabited by 85 percent poor people?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez answered his own question, attributing the country's
economic disparities to a national malaise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are leaving a terrible time that we all have lived
through,'' Chavez declared. ``For the last 20 years, we went into a
freefall, an economic and moral crisis. This crisis is the mother
of our movement. We are contributing to leading the people in a
democratic way and a peaceful way out of that time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Venezuela, we had corrupt people incapable of governing,''
he said. ``They took away democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, a follower of the great South American 19th century
liberator Simon Bolivar, sounded a populist note as he described
his program and cited American history to emphasize his commitment
to democracy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are creating a democracy that will recover its ethical
content, its social content and institutional content so that the
different branches of government will really work to serve the
people,'' Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As Abraham Lincoln said, `We will have a government of the
people, by the people and for the people,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Venezuelan president spoke to a gathering of business
executives and media leaders before he addressed the U.N. General
Assembly.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez told the audience that he knew that his government's
sweeping changes have caused a ``great deal of concern'' in the
United States and elsewhere, but he assured the crowd that his
country would remain free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has a dictatorship arrived? Has violence arrived? Has chaos
arrived? Has the end of democracy arrived?'' Chavez asked. ``I can
tell you that none of those things has happened,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point in his remarks, Chavez acknowledged that he was
``surprised at how fast change has come to Venezuela.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez spoke at a luncheon hosted by Randolph and Veronica
Hearst to an audience that included financier George Soros; retired
banker David Rockefeller; Mort Zuckerman, publisher of the New York
Daily News; Martin Singerman, publisher of the New York Post;
Gustavo A. Cisneros, prominent businessman in Venezuela and the
United States; Linda Wachner, chairman and CEO of Warnaco; members
of Chavez' Cabinet; and Carlos Biero, Venezuela's ambassador to the
United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the week, Chavez travels to Washington to meet with
President Clinton. He is expected to renew his assurances to the
American president that his government is committed to democracy
and the anti-drug campaign.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of Venezuela's two main parties, Democratic Action and
the Social Christian Party, which ruled Venezuela for 40 years,
have accused Chavez and his followers of a crude power grab. The
party leaders say the constitutional assembly, elected in July to
rewrite the country's constitution is a tool of Chavez designed to
do an end run around Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis reached a climax late last month when the assembly
voted essentially to shut down the Congress. Chavez's opponents
compared him with Cuba's communist dictator Fidel Castro.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, a major purchaser of Venezuelan oil, took a
dim view of the assembly's action. But early this month, the
assembly relented and agreed with the Congress on a power-sharing
scheme until Venezuela's new constitution is completed this month.
A referendum approving or disapproving is expected to be held in
November, according to Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Venezuelan leaders are now trying to soothe feelings in U.S.
financial and political circles.
</P>
<P>
   However, so far the administration has remained skeptical of
Chavez's promises. Last month, U.S. Undersecretary of State Thomas
Pickering said in Caracas, said the Clinton administration ``will
judge President Chavez's actions and steps to the degree to which
his is able and willing not only in his rhetoric but in his actions
to support the democratic future.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (STORY COULD END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though Chavez's actions have generated some criticism abroad
that democracy is being endangered in Venezuela, the country's 23
million people have largely hailed the moves.
</P>
<P>
   If anything, the popularity of Chavez, a 45-year-old former
paratroop colonel who led a failed coup attempt in 1992, has risen
as a result of his reform campaign. He was elected last December
with 57 percent of the vote, but a public opinion survey taken in
August by Datanalisis, a leading polling and market research
company in Venezuela, gave him a national approval rating of nearly
75 percent.
</P>
<P>
   According to Michael Shifter, a professor of Latin American
politics at Georgetown University, public sentiment against
