<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 19:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0619 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-ASPHALT-FEUD-HNS &LR;      09-21 1385
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASPHALT-FEUD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAVEL PIT OPERATOR'S PROPOSAL SPLITS LONGTIME RESIDENTS,
NEWCOMERS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JUNCTION, Texas _ A gravel pit operator's plan to make asphalt
on the banks of the scenic North Llano River has caused friction
between longtime residents and urban-refugee newcomers in this town
that calls itself the ``front porch of the West.''
</P>
<P>
   Some folks say the proposal by the well-established company
won't hurt anybody. Even a major flood over the riverside pit
wouldn't ruin the scenic waterway as it winds through town, they
contend.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side are residents who argue that Texas
environmental regulators and local governments have proven inept at
policing this and other gravel pits. In the midst of another
drought, the notion of using oily substances near clean water
worries these residents enough to produce a petition drive, heated
public meetings and a growing network of activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the last clean river in Texas,'' said Bill Neiman, a
resident for five years. ``This is not just a Junction problem.
This is for everyone in Texas to know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Neiman moved his family here from the Dallas area to escape
health problems that he said were caused by big-city smog.
   In the middle are those like Kimble County Judge Delbert
Roberts, who want more information before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last thing that any member of the Commissioner's Court of
this county wants is any kind of pollution,'' he said. He's waiting
for environmental experts to clarify the likely impact of the
asphalt plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will never say pollution is justifiable because we need
jobs, we need industry. No sir,'' Roberts said. ``That's just
common sense.''
</P>
<P>
   All the factions among the county's 4,500 residents are waiting
to find out if the Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission
grants an air emissions permit to Weirich Bros. Inc. of Johnson
City. A tentative decision could come this fall.
</P>
<P>
   For 12 years, the Weirich company has been mining gravel along
the North Llano where it joins the South Llano. Their confluence
gave the town its name and produced the Llano River, which cuts
eastward through the Hill Country and empties into Lake LBJ.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're proposing to do would not be harmful to people,
wildlife or the environment,'' insists co-owner Terry Weirich.
</P>
<P>
   Because of water contamination dangers, Weirich said he'd prefer
not to make the asphalt beside the river, but new regulations at
the state Department of Transportation favor bidders who provide
precoated crushed rock for state highway improvements. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``This is a process that has been shoved down our throats by
the Texas Department of Transportation,'' Weirich said. ``When they
told me I was going to have to do this, I pleaded with them not to.
I didn't think this was a proper thing to do on the river. I'm
having to do this to retain my share of business.''  &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; As it is, Weirich said he won't have the necessary permit in
time to bid for jobs next year. The coated gravel would be used in
the transportation agency's San Angelo region, which includes
Junction.
</P>
<P>
   The plant currently operates with the only state permit required
_ a river dredging permit from the Texas Department of Parks and
Wildlife. &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR; ``The state's authority is so splintered and in most cases so
thin that it really is a problem,'' said Parks and Wildlife
official Rollin MacRae, who oversees regulation of the five
riverbed gravel operations in Texas, including three on the Brazos
and one on the North Sulphur River.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have a bad operator, then they can go a long way''
without consequence, he said. But the Junction site is not known as
a trouble spot, he added.
</P>
<P>
   The facility also has water-related permits from two federal
agencies, but neither has intervened in the current dispute. Water
is used to cleanse gravel after it is mined with a dredging crane,
although the pit is inactive due to seasonal low river flow. When
the pit is operating, water used to clean gravel is supposed to
pass through a settling pond before reaching the river, a state
official said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only real requirement is that they reintroduce 90 percent
of the waters they extract from the Llano River back into the Llano
River,'' said TNRCC spokesman Ruben Ochoa.
</P>
<P>
   Downstream water clouding was attributed to the plant after a
storm earlier this year, but Ochoa said it was quickly corrected
with repairs to a storm-damaged berm. A fuel spill also was cited
and remedied, Ochoa said, noting that no formal complaints have
been lodged about dust or other air particulates drifting into the
atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Weirich Bros. has been responsive to the TNRCC and respectful
of the process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed air permit for Weirich's mobile precoating
equipment would allow emission of up to 7 pounds per hour of
volatile organic compounds and the plant would be authorized to
produce up to 50 tons of precoat gravel per hour. Both amounts were
described as harmless by Ochoa.
</P>
<P>
   ``The facility is relatively small compared to asphalt
facilities that are permitted by the TNRCC on a pretty regular
basis. The typical facility will produce 200 to 300 tons per
hour,'' he said, ``and the larger ones will produce 600 to 1,000
tons per hour.''
</P>
<P>
   The state engineers' recommendation will be sent to the
conservation commission's three members. More than 200 people have
signed petitions seeking a public hearing.
</P>
<P>
   If the permit is granted, opponents of the plan would have to
decide whether to pay for a legal challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman said a few hunters from Houston already have contributed
a small amount of money to an ad hoc group that is questioning the
air quality permit.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't come here only for the deer,'' Neiman said. ``It's
the last clean place in Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a false radio news report that the permit had already
been granted resulted in an incident that shows how emotional the
issue has become: A neighbor of the gravel plant whose toddler has
respiratory problems broke into tears when she heard that report.
</P>
<P>
   The frantic woman's first call was to Neiman, the man who gets
the blame by some people when they complain about meddling
newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, Neiman brings a unique viewpoint to the debate. As a
private pilot who routinely takes to the air to seek fields of
wildflowers for seed havesting, he often soars over the gravel pit,
which is mostly hidden from public view because it is tucked behind
tall tree lines and around river bends from public roads.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one on the ground can see what's been going on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman said he began photographing the site several months ago
to document what he said was clouded river water downstream from
the pit.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed it escalated significantly,'' he said. Neiman said
the photos, which were provided to regulatory agencies, suggest
that earthen barriers and retention ponds don't always work as
intended to filter impurities from the returning river water.
</P>
<P>
   The water is under the jurisdiction of the Lower Colorado River
Authority, whose officials said last week they will upgrade
water-quality monitoring on the Llano River next month by
installing a new pollution detection device downstream from the
pit. The agency said the nearest closest monitoring station is more
than 30 miles downriver.
</P>
<P>
   In all, at least seven governmental entities have some
regulatory authority over the pit's operations, which also fall
under the jurisdictions of the county and city.
</P>
<P>
   Weirich said the array of regulators, which also includes the
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, can be befuddling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every day, there seems to be something new and different,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   He expects a protracted struggle to secure the air permit. If
obtained, he next would seek a wastewater discharge permit, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not looking forward to it ... but I do believe the
public outcry is unfounded. We're probably 10 times smaller than
most plants,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what else to do but fight this and stick to my
guns. The demand for this material is not just going to die because
there are some environmentalists in Junction, Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
