<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF: INDIA; JAPAN; BRITAIN; NORTHERN IRELAND;
GERMANY; FRANCE; ITALY; MEXICO; ISRAEL; IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   INDIA: POLLS PUT HINDUS AHEAD
</P>
<P>
   An exit poll by the private Star TV said the Hindu
nationalist-led coalition is heading for a sweeping victory in
national elections that conclude Oct. 3. Another exit poll,
broadcast by the state television network, put the coalition firmly
in the lead, though not by such a large margin. A third, smaller
exit poll, by a regional newspaper in the state of Maharashtra,
showed the coalition narrowly ahead.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN: LIBERAL LEADER RE-ELECTED
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democratic Party re-elected Prime Minister Keizo
Obuchi as its president, thus extending his term as head of the
government. Obuchi, who has been in office a year, has proven
unexpectedly popular, using his political skills to cobble together
a coalition that insures him legislative success and doling out
money to push the economy.
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN: GOALS TO END POVERTY
</P>
<P>
   Elaborating on a recent pledge by Prime Minister Tony Blair to
eradicate child poverty in Britain in 20 years, the government set
a series of measurable goals to improve housing, health care and
education, increase jobs and incomes and counter bias. Social
Security Secretary Alistair Darling said, ``For the first time a
government is standing up to be counted setting specific standards
against which we will be judged tackling poverty and its causes.''
</P>
<P>
   NORTHERN IRELAND: CLASHES CONTINUE
</P>
<P>
   The rival Catholic and Protestant parties, Sinn Fein and the
Ulster Unionists, met together with Sen. George Mitchell in Belfast
but continued to clash over whether the Northern Ireland peace
agreement could go forward without any disarmament by IRA
guerrillas. Mitchell, chairman of the talks that led to the April
1998 accord, is in the third week of a mission to rescue the
stalemated accord, and a spokesman said, ``There is no formula on
the table at this stage.''
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: VATICAN CURBS ABORTION
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Karl Lehmann, the head of the German Bishops' Conference,
has received a letter from the Vatican telling German bishops that
the church can no longer hand out counseling certificates to women
to enable them to get abortions. Under German law, a woman wanting
to end her pregnancy must first receive a certificate saying she
has been counseled by an advisory service. One-sixth of the 1,500
such services in the country are run by the Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE: NEW CHIRAC RIVAL
</P>
<P>
   The already frazzled right-wing party of President Jacques
Chirac suffered a new split when a sixth candidate, Michele
Alliot-Marie, entered the race to head the Gaullist movement, the
Rally for the Republic. This will make it even harder for Chirac to
unite the party behind his effort to be re-elected in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   FRANCE, ITALY: ONE-DAY CAR BAN
</P>
<P>
   Paris and Rome, and more than 150 other European towns and
cities, will join to celebrate a pedestrians' day on Wednesday by
keeping cars out of urban centers. Many boulevards, avenues and
squares will be accessible only to strollers, rollerskaters,
joggers and pedicabs. Some will allow buses and electric vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   THE AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO: NEW EFFORT BY OPPOSITION
</P>
<P>
   Fourteen academics and intellectuals who are trying to help
eight opposition parties break the impasse in talks over forming a
coalition for the July 2000 general elections said they were
writing a new proposal for how the parties could pick a single
presidential candidate. But Vicente Fox and Cuauhtemoc Cardenas,
the two main opposition candidates, exchanged icy greetings in a
chance public encounter and both suggested they are writing the
coalition out of their plans.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: PROTEST ON U.N. ENVOY
</P>
<P>
   Israel protested the naming by Secretary-General Kofi Annan of a
special envoy to the Mideast, saying Annan had expanded the title
and functions beyond that of a coordinator of U.N. activities in
the region. Terje Roed-Larsen was named special coordinator for the
Middle East Peace Process and Annan's personal representative to
the Palestine Liberation Organization and the Palestinian
Authority. Israel's U.N. mission says the title implies a role for
the organization in peace talks and is ``unacceptable to the
government of Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ: JOURNALIST HURT IN ATTACK
</P>
<P>
   A Swedish journalist was slightly hurt in southern Iraq when a
missile apparently fired by a Western warplane landed within 50
yards of a car in which he was riding. Jan Arell, of The Goteborg
Post, said the attack had been preceded by nearby antiaircraft
fire. U.S. military spokesmen confirmed that American and British
planes had been in action at about the time Arell was hurt.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
