<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 20:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0624 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-OLY-HEARING-COX     09-21 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-HEARING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Republican delivers scathing assessment of Atlanta Olympics
bidding
 &HT;    (EDS: Moving to (w) Washington and (s) Sports categories.)
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A House Republican on Tuesday accused Atlanta
Olympics officials and the International Olympic Committee of
engaging in a ``pattern of corruption'' to win the 1996 Games.
</P>
<P>
   At a Capitol Hill news conference, Rep. Fred Upton (R-Mich.)
strongly disputed assertions by Atlanta organizers that the city's
bid process was ``open and fair.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very little you can think of that wasn't on the table
to try and get'' votes, said Upton, who plans to call Olympics
Chief Billy Payne and former Atlanta mayor Andrew Young to testify.
``And it shouldn't happen. It's wrong. There's a word called
'ethics.' Clearly votes were for sale and it's got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Upton delivered his assessment of the Atlanta bid process less
than a week after Atlanta organizers submitted a report to Congress
outlining what Atlanta officials did to influence the IOC, whose
members voted in 1990 to give Atlanta the Games.
</P>
<P>
   The report details how Payne and other top officials gave lavish
gifts and travel and offered scholarships and job assistance to IOC
members and their families. Many of the gifts and extra travel were
in direct violation of IOC rules. Several U.S. laws were also
broken, Upton said, but prosecutions are unlikely because the
statute of limitations has expired.
</P>
<P>
   At hearings scheduled for the week of Oct. 11, Upton will call
Payne, Young and IOC chief Juan Antonio Samaranch to explore
possible legislation to govern future Olympics. Samaranch refused
to testify at a Senate hearing earlier this year, and Upton said
House Commerce Committee Chairman Tom Bliley (R-Va.) was prepared
to subpoena Samaranch if he refused to testify again next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hoping that he'll be cooperative and that we can get to
the bottom of this,'' said Upton, who chairs the House Commerce
Committee subcommittee on oversight and investigations. ``We want
to ask him, 'Did the IOC not know about this?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Because Samaranch is not a U.S. citizen, he can be served with a
subpoena only if he enters the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Others invited to testify are former Maine Sen. George Mitchell,
who authored a report about excessive gift-giving in Salt Lake
City's bid for the 2002 winter Games, and Peter Ueberroth, who
organized the 1984 summer Olympics in Los Angeles, and who is a
member of a new IOC commission working on reforms of the bid
process.
</P>
<P>
   Former attorney general Griffin Bell, who authored the report to
Congress on the Atlanta Games, will also testify.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the right time to discuss the future of the Olympic
Games, and we are delighted to participate in that process,'' Bell
said Tuesday. ``Much recent discussion has focused on questionable
bidding practices and what has gone wrong. I hope that this hearing
will encourage new discussion about what is good about the Games
and how to keep it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Upton said his panel will consider ending the IOC's exemption
from the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act as a possible way to stop
the long-standing practice of gift-giving to IOC members to
influence the selection of host cities for the games.
</P>
<P>
   And he suggested the U.S. businesses that provide much of the
financial support for the Olympics through advertising might be
willing to pressure the IOC to clean up the bidding process.
</P>
<P>
   Next month's hearings will be the second this year into
allegations of excessive gift giving to IOC members on the part of
U.S. host cities. In April, Sen. John McCain (R-Ariz.) held
hearings into the allegations surrounding the Salt Lake City bid
process.
</P>
<P>
   Upton's hearings will likely be another forum for members of
Congress to express their unhappiness with the pace of internal
reforms at the IOC, and with the reluctance of Samaranch to fully
acknowledge the scope of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Upton declined to draw too many comparisons between Atlanta and
Salt Lake City, but said apparent misconduct in both arose from the
same ``culture of corruption'' that permitted bid cities to offer
any gift or inducement to win the support of IOC members.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hoping that what happened in Salt Lake City was an
aberration,'' Upton said. ``Clearly it wasn't. The sky was the
limit in terms of the gifts being offered and the number being
accepted. It's got to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   At his news conference, Upton released copies of memos and
letters found in the files of Atlanta organizers that pointed to
some of the most egregious violations.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the memos from Payne to staff identify the specific
gifts or inducements that would be welcome by a particular IOC
member. For a Russian IOC member, Payne said, ``decorations for
their new home would be appreciated.''
</P>
<P>
   For another, Payne offered to help have the member's book
translated into English. On another occasion, Payne wrote to
Robinson-Humphrey Co. in Atlanta to ask for help in getting a job
for the son of an IOC member from Venezuela.
</P>
<P>
   Payne also arranged for IOC members and their spouses to play
golf at the Augusta National Golf Club, a perk that had been
suggested to Payne by the IOC member from Switzerland, Marc Hodler,
who blew the whistle on influence-peddling in the IOC when the Salt
Lake scandal erupted last year.
</P>
<P>
   While Upton generally praised Atlanta officials for opening
their records to his committee and cooperating with its
investigation, the Michigan Republican said Atlanta officials
should have ``blown the whistle a lot earlier than they did.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't have to give some of these sweet gifts that in any
normal layman's definition one would feel was bad,'' Upton said.
``Would have they gotten the Games if they had not done so? I don't
know. Maybe that's something we'll ask Samaranch.''
</P>
<P>
   A bid committee spokesman would not respond to Upton's harsh
characterization of Atlanta's campaign tactics. ``We recognize that
the report has caught the interest of the Commerce committee,''
said Lee Echols, a spokesman for Payne, ``but if our report leads
to a progressive discussion and analysis of what can strengthen the
Olympic movement, then we believe our report will have served a
good purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Customs laws were broken and trade embargoes ignored, according
to disclosures in the Atlanta report, said Upton . But he added it
was unlikely the Justice Department, which is investigating the
Salt Lake City bid process, would be called into examine them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not what our focus is now,'' he said. ``Our focus is to
make sure that it doesn't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ken Foskett writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
