<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Wednesday, Sept. 22. The N.Y. Times News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   TAIWAN-QUAKE (Taipei, Taiwan) _ With the death toll from
Tuesday's devastating earthquake rising by the hour, rescuers work
to reach thousands of people still trapped in the rubble of felled
buildings and houses. By Calvin Sims. (We plan to move the story by
8:45 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.) 1,100 words.
</P>
<P>
   The story runs under a 3-column, 1-line hed. With photos and
map.
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   CLEMENCY-CONGRESS (Washington) _ A Senate counterterrorism
committee hears from Justice and FBI witnesses on Clinton's
clemency for FALN members. According to documents released by
Congress on Tuesday, Louis Freeh, the FBI director, had warned the
Justice Department that releasing any of the prisoners ``would
likely return committed, experienced, sophisticated and hardened
terrorists to the clandestine movement.'' By Katharine Q. Seelye.
(Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead:
</P>
<P>
   1-column photo reefer to U.N.-CLINTON; story inside.
</P>
<P>
   TRADE-REPORT (Washington) _ Another leap in the United States
trade deficit in July fuels fears that the continuing surge in
imports is threatening the health of the dollar. As the American
dollar dips yet again versus the Japanese yen, largely because of
disappointment over the widening trade gap at home and inaction by
monetary authorities in Tokyo, stocks and bonds react by falling
sharply in financial markets. By David E. Sanger. (Scheduled to
move by 9 p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   FOLD
</P>
<P>
   SCI-ISLAND-LAB (Plum Island, N.Y.) _ The Department of
Agriculture is seeking to convert a laboratory it operates here,
the Plum Island Animal Disease Center, into the sort of heavily
protected lab at which the most dangerous animal diseases are
studied. By Judith H. Miller. (Scheduled to move by 8:15 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.) 2,200 words.
</P>
<P>
   With map and photo.
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NY-DIVORCE (New York) _ The chief administrator of the Manhattan
Matrimonial Court has accepted tens of thousands of dollars in
bribes over the last seven years to expedite and get approvals on
hundreds of divorces, including some that involved fraud. Three
divorce lawyers involved in the schemes have been indicted, and as
many as 20 other divorce lawyers and court employees are under
investigation. By David Rohde. (Scheduled to move by 9 p.m. ET in
``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ASIANAMERICANS-POLITICS (Los Angeles) _ In the relatively brief
span of one presidential cycle the role of Asian Americans in
national politics appears to have changed in fundamental ways.
After years as one of the most financially generous but
underrepresented ethnic minorities in American politics, many Asian
Americans are nursing deep wounds from what they regard as a string
of insulting scandals. And this time, they say, things will be
different. By James Sterngold. (The story has moved in ``p'' news
file.) 2,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   BELL-ATLANTIC-VODAFONE (Undated) _ A new player is emerging as a
formidable opponent in the U.S. cellular phone wars. Bell Atlantic,
the nation's largest local phone company, and Britain's largest
wireless concern Vodafone Airtouch PLC, struck a deal to combine
their U.S. wireless operations and create the nation's largest
coast-to-coast network. By Laura M. Holson. (Scheduled to move by 9
p.m. ET in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TIMOR-RDP (Dare, East Timor) _ As the international team of
peacekeepers fans out from East Timor's capital, there are
emotional scenes in the hills as pro-independence refugees meet
U.N. officials and peacekeepers who have arrived to help them
secure independence. By Seth Mydans. (The story has moved in ``i''
news file.) 1,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY-ISRAEL (Berlin) _ Accompanied by survivors of a Nazi
concentration camp, Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel arrives in
Berlin on the first state visit to the German capital since the
government moved here last month. The visit is charged with
symbolism. By Roger Cohen. (The story has moved in ``i'' news
file.) 725 words.
</P>
<P>
   SCHIELE-PAINTING (New York) _ Almost two years after two
paintings by Egon Schiele, looted by the Nazis, arrived in the
United States from Austria for a three-month exhibition at the
Museum of Modern Art, New York's highest court rules that a grand
jury subpoena keeping the works here while their ownership is
investigated is invalid. By Judith H. Dobrzynski. (The story has
moved in ``e'' news file.) 800 words.
</P>
