<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following for
clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of Wednesday,
Sept. 22, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please call
Bob Schenet on the national-foreign desk at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   SPY-SMUGGLERS (Undated) _ Canada and the United States have
teamed up to employ a network of spy satellites, underwater
acoustic sensors and electronic interception techniques to track
smuggling ships from Chinese ports, across the north Pacific Ocean
and into Canadian waters where they have been intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   By Ed Offley and Joel Connelly. (Story will move in the ``i''
category.)
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-CORNELL (Undated) _ As the lead singer of Soundgarden,
Chris Cornell helped reinvent hard rock. Borrowing from heavy metal
and punk, the Seattle band joined Pearl Jam, Mudhoney, Nirvana and
other local groups in creating a sound that turned the city into an
alternative-rock mecca in the early 1990s. The 35-year-old Seattle
resident continues to explore that landscape on his first solo
album, ``Euphoria Morning,'' just out from A&AMP;M Records.
</P>
<P>
   By Gene Stout. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-WESTWING (Undated) _ Review of ``The West Wing,'' new series
premiering Wednesday on NBC.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-GROWUP (Undated) _ Review of ``Oh Grow Up,'' new series
premiering Wednesday on ABC.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story has moved in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FBC-THIEL-COLUMN (Boulder, Colo.) _ Roaming Rick Neuheisel's old
stamping grounds in search of what passion/venom exists for the
coach who bolted to Washington to become a millionaire.
</P>
<P>
   By Art Thiel. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   BBA-MARINERS (Seattle) _ Seattle Mariners host Kansas City
Royals.
</P>
<P>
   By Dan Raley. (Story will move in the ``s'' category.)
</P>
