<SLUG> BC-HERO-TEX </SLUG>
 
(For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By DEANNA BOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skye Noe was about 15 miles outside of Abilene, Texas, nearing
the end of an all-day drive from his Colorado hometown to Abilene
Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   Lonzo Wallace, a Fort Worth, Texas, Fire Department deputy
chief, and his wife, Nell, were on their way home to suburban
Burleson after visiting their sons in college, one at the Air Force
Academy in Colorado Springs and the other at Texas Tech University
in Lubbock.
</P>
<P>
   Some say it was a miracle that the 18-year-old student and
veteran firefighter chanced upon each other along that dark stretch
of Interstate 20 in the early morning hours of Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   It proved to be a heroic and life-saving meeting, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Noe, tired and lulled to sleep by the monotonous drive, veered
off the roadway, down a steep incline and crashed into a concrete
embankment.
</P>
<P>
   His Chrysler New Yorker burst into flames, trapping him inside.
</P>
<P>
   The Wallaces, traveling behind him, saw the car plunge off the
highway and stopped. Lonzo Wallace raced to pull Noe from the
flaming wreckage, then just hours later drove to Fort Worth for a
meeting; his wife used their cell phone to call 911, then stayed at
the hospital with Noe until his parents arrived from Aurora, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're just both angels,'' said the teen's mother,
Kathleen Noe. ``To find someone that would take time out of their
lives to help somebody else is very unusual.''
</P>
<P>
   Their heroics didn't go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Wallaces were honored in a ceremony during the
Fort Worth City Council meeting. On Monday, they were recognized at
a special ceremony and lunch at Abilene Christian University.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Barnard, the Dean of Campus Life at Abilene Christian,
said the Wallaces' action ``is a great message for our students
about the kind of people we're educating them to be, the kind of
people that will get involved in society and get involved in
life.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wallaces are reluctant heroes. News about their actions
would not surface from their lips, but from an Abilene paramedic
who alerted the Fort Worth Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``God just meant for us to be there and to do what we did,''
Lonzo Wallace said. ``It's kind of amazing when you really thing
about it.''
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Skye Noe had attended a church function in Denver that weekend
and was more than half way through the 12-hour drive to Abilene
when his car's starter went out in Dumas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was Labor Day (weekend), so it was a real hard job to try
to find a mechanic,'' Noe said.
</P>
<P>
   Four hours later, the car was repaired and he was back on the
road.
</P>
<P>
   Lonzo and Nell Wallace had attended parents weekend at the Air
Force Academy, where their oldest son is a student, and then
stopped at Texas Tech to visit their younger son.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace, 46, first spotted Noe on the highway leading out of
Lubbock, and the two drivers took turns following each other. They
temporarily separated when Noe stopped for gas, then met up again
on I-20, just outside of Merkle, after the Wallaces pulled over and
swapped seats for Nell Wallace to drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``When (Noe's) car came past, I said something to the effect to
my wife that, `That was the car I was following early and if you
get behind it, it's a good person to follow.''
</P>
<P>
   About 35 miles outside of Abilene, Noe said, the day's long
drive began to wear on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had all my windows down and the radio on full blast just
trying to stay awake,'' Noe said.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty minutes later, shortly before 1 a.m., he fell asleep at
the wheel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit a mile marker, woke up and slammed on my brakes,'' Noe
said. ``I remember going off the edge and going toward the concrete
embankment. I don't actually recall the collision.''
</P>
<P>
   Traveling behind the Chrysler, the Wallaces had watched it veer
to the left.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went off the road onto the median and then he just
disappeared in between the two bridges,'' Lonzo Wallace said.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace told his wife to stop and call 911 while he ran to the
top of the approximately 14-foot embankment. Down below, the
wrecked car lay on its side, bursting into flames.
</P>
<P>
   A truck driver who had also stopped ran for his fire
extinguisher as Wallace scooted down the steep embankment toward
the burning car.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hear him down there. He was moaning,'' Wallace
recalled. ``I hollered to him to crawl out of the car, but he
couldn't move.''
</P>
<P>
   Noe said he had been knocked unconscious and came to in a daze,
his body hanging halfway out the door. He was bleeding heavily from
a gash on the head and later would learn he also had a crushed
vertebrae.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember seeing some of my stuff on fire,'' Noe said. ``I
remember his voice yelling, but I couldn't really move. He ran up
and grabbed me under my arms and dragged me.''
</P>
<P>
   As they waited for help, Lonzo Wallace called Noe's parents in
Colorado to let them know about the wreck.
</P>
<P>
   ``I woke them up and told them what was going on,'' Wallace
said. ``I put the phone up to (Noe's) ear so his dad could hear his
voice.''
(Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
