<HEADLINE>
49ERS PONDER HOW TO DO A BETTER JOB OF PROTECTING YOUNG 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JEFFRI CHADIHA  
 c1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ One of the first things Steve Mariucci did
on Monday morning was pull right tackle Jeremy Newberry into his
office.
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers coach wasn't looking to extend blame. He only wanted
to see where Newberry's head was a day after the New Orleans Saints
rocked Steve Young's world. Apparently, Newberry was OK enough that
Mariucci didn't lose faith in him for Monday's game against
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just asked me what the deal was,'' said Newberry, a
second-year player who moved from center to tackle in the
offseason. ``I told him I wasn't playing like I normally do. I was
just trying to do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Newberry wasn't the sole reason Young endured one of his
worst beatings in Sunday's 28-21 victory, he is the least
experienced lineman and the one who protects Young's backside.
</P>
<P>
   Therefore, Newberry is the lineman the coaches have to be most
concerned about.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci acknowledged he has considered replacing Newbrry with
right guard Derrick Deese, who also has experience at tackle. But
for now, Mariucci doesn't seem willing to make a quick alteration
to his lineup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jeremy had a tough game,'' Mariucci said. ``He got frustrated
early in the game and never recovered mentally. He has to grow and
get better. He's been much better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   The personnel will remain the same for another week, Mariucci
said, but he realizes something has to change. The Saints sacked
Young five times and knocked him down 21 times overall. They
reached him by rushing four down linemen and by sending waves of
blitzers as well, leaving the 49ers to ponder how best to protect
him.
</P>
<P>
   Mariucci emphasized that normally sacks aren't totally the fault
of offensive linemen. Good coverage, a missed assignment by a
running back or a passer's refusal to unload the ball in a timely
fashion all can contribute to a quarterback's demise.
</P>
<P>
   However, offensive line coach Pat Morris felt otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offensive line will take the brunt of the criticism and
they should,'' Morris said. ``It's the nature of the position. You
have to protect the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   The 49ers' problems with the Saints' pressure can be traced to
two factors.
</P>
<P>
   The first is that the 49ers, as in a season-opening loss to
Jacksonville, were forced to use come-from-behind tactics. That led
them to abandon a running game that didn't intimidate anyone to
begin with, enabling the Saints defense to tee off on Young (who
said he felt fine Monday).
</P>
<P>
   The other factor was personnel. Starting left tackle Dave Fiore
underwent arthroscopic surgery on his right knee on Sept. 4 and
still isn't 100 percent. The 49ers also will be without their best
blocking back (Garrison Hearst) throughout the season and their
best blocking tight end (Greg Clark) is still recovering from five
broken ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never really appreciated having a good blocking tight end,''
Young said. ``I always liked having a tight end like Brent Jones, a
guy who could get open in space. As far as the running game and
having a sixth guy to protect in the passing game, and still be
able to get down the middle of the field, I really value that
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Until the 49ers are able to run effectively and return Clark to
the lineup, they will have to contemplate their offensive line
situation, one that is muddled by a lack of depth. If Deese has to
move to tackle, Mariucci would have to choose from a host of
unproven guard candidates (Newberry, rookie Tyrone Hopson and
second-year man Phil Ostrowski) or play reserve Ben Lynch at center
and move starting center Chris Dalman to guard.
</P>
<P>
   These appear to be options Mariucci will only seriously consider
if what happened on Sunday becomes a weekly occurrence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a blitz game,'' Mariucci said. ``Pressuring the
quarterback is a sign of the times. We have to handle it. We got
blitzed last year. This is nothing new. What's different is Steve
got hit 21 times. That's what we have to correct.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
