<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 20:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0638 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-AMNESTY-CLINTON-BOS &LR;      09-21 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMNESTY-CLINTON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI WARNS THAT FREED FALN MEMBERS POSE CRIMINAL THREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Puerto Rican nationalists released last week
under presidential decree are dangerous criminals who ``represent a
threat to the United States,'' a senior FBI official said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are terrorists. They are criminals,'' Neil Gallagher, the
FBI's assistant director for national security, told the House
Committee on Government Reform.
</P>
<P>
   And in an embarrassing split with the White House, FBI Director
Louis Freeh also warned in a letter released Tuesday by the
committee that freeing the members of the Armed Forces of National
Liberation, known by the Spanish acronym of FALN, could be
dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   Letting out the nationalists would ``psychologically and
operationally enhance the ongoing violent and criminal activities
of Puerto Rican terrorist groups,'' Freeh said in the draft letter
to House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry J. Hyde, Republican of
Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde had asked Freeh on Aug. 27 to reveal his position on the
clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   Those released ``would likely return committed, experienced,
sophisticated and hardened terrorists to the clandestine
movement,'' said the letter, which was never officially sent to
Hyde.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, in his most detailed public defense to date
of the politically explosive decision, said he had considered the
clemency offer to the 16 FALN members case by case, and they were
all serving ``extremely long sentences'' that were ``out of
proportion to their crimes.'' No politics was involved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a five-page letter to a political ally, Representative Henry
Waxman, Democrat of California, Clinton said the 16 FALN members _
14 of whom accepted his clemency offer _ were ``not convicted of
crimes involving bodily harm to anyone,''and the prisoners'
sentences were ``unduly severe.'' Waxman read the letter at the
start of Tuesday's hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Those conclusions were angrily disputed at Tuesday's hearing by
victims of the FALN and by Republican House members. The
administration's own Justice Department appointees were less
critical, but pointedly refused to defend the president for his
clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher and Michael B. Cooksey, assistant director for
correctional programs at the Bureau of Prisons, detailed the crimes
the 16 were believed to have been involved in _ despite the fact
that most of them were convicted of seditious conspiracy. One
inmate, Oscar Lopez, who refused the clemency offer, is so
dangerous he had to be moved to a maximum-security prison and is
considered an escape risk, Cooksey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter-in-law is Puerto Rican, and my two granddaughters
have Puerto Rican heritage,'' said a somber Richard Pastorella, a
retired New York City police detective who was blinded during an
FALN attack. ``When they show me crayon drawings they made, I have
to pretend I see them and appreciate their effort,'' said
Pastorelli, breaking down into quiet tears.
</P>
<P>
   Acting assistant attorney general Jon P. Jennings extended his
``deepest sympathies'' to the victims of the FALN's admitted
campaign of bombing, robbery and murder. Jennings' remarks were the
first, and as yet only, public expression of condolence to the
victims from the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's session carried more theatrical than practical punch,
since Congress cannot reverse a presidential clemency decision.
</P>
<P>
   But opponents of Clinton's offer are keeping up the heat. Both
the House and Senate have passed separate resolutions denouncing
his decision.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-controlled House is now set to vote again, on the
already-approved Senate resolution. The expected passage of the
resolution would put Clinton in the awkward position of having to
sign it _ thus denouncing himself _ or not sign it, drawing another
round of criticism.
</P>
<P>
   The amnesty offer to the FALN members has been a political
disaster for the White House and problematic for First Lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton, who is exploring a bid for the US Senate seat in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's ruling drew criticism from some in law enforcement
that he was ``soft on terrorism.'' And Mrs. Clinton's abrupt
remarks that the clemency offer should be revoked angered Puerto
Rican politicians, not in the least because she did not inform them
before making her comments.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have expressed anger over Clinton's refusal to hand
over documents that might explain how and why the clemency decision
was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't hide behind executive privilege,'' said House Government
Reform Committee Chairman Dan Burton, Republican of Indiana, adding
he would issue another document subpoena.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
