<HEADLINE>
RYLANDER INTRODUCES TASK FORCE TO EXAMINE TEST TAMPERING IN TEXAS
SCHOOLS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MELANIE MARKLEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Calling herself ``the education watchdog for the
people of Texas,'' Comptroller Carole Keeton Rylander introduced a
task force Tuesday that will examine test tampering and data
manipulation in schools.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander, speaking at Houston Independent School District
headquarters, said the task force will spend the next year looking
into statewide reports of cheating on tests, bogus dropout rates
and too little money being funneled into instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander's announcement comes after the Texas Education Agency
gave bad ratings to two districts _ Austin and Ysleta _ that
submitted erroneous dropout data. Fourteen other districts are
under investigation. Area districts that are affected include
Houston, Channelview, Clear Creek, North Forest, Pearland and
Sheldon.
</P>
<P>
   ``TEA has been catching these problems,'' Rylander said.
``However, the emphasis has been on intervention and enforcement.
We are concentrating on the preventative aspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Rylander, who also spoke in Dallas and Austin, commended Houston
Superintendent Rod Paige for aggressive action at a half dozen
schools last spring where there was evidence of tampering with
answer documents to the Texas Assessment of Academic Skills.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of an investigation into test tampering, which also
involved 10 other districts, Paige fired one substitute, dismissed
one principal, reprimanded a second principal and suspended three
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander also praised Paige for ordering schools to quit
exempting students from taking the TAAS even though including more
limited-English and special education students resulted in lower
test scores this year.
</P>
<P>
   After conducting surveys and interviews as part of the probe,
Rylander said the task force should know the extent of the cheating
and data-manipulation problems in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't tell you today how widespread it is,'' she said,
``but if it is happening at all, it needs to stop.''
</P>
<P>
   The task force will be chaired by Barry Thompson, former
chancellor of the Texas A&AMP;M University System.
</P>
<P>
   Also serving on the committee: Thaddeus Lott, director of four
HISD charter schools; Beatrice Lucio, a principal in Brownsville;
Wilhelmina Delco, a former state representative from Austin;
Michael R. Levy, founder and publisher of Texas Monthly; Roy
Barrera, San Antonio attorney; and Jeri Stone, executive director
and general counsel for the Texas Classroom Teachers Association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas leads the nation in developing a comprehensive
accountability system,'' Stone said. ``Unfortunately as a
corollary, we also may be a bit ahead of the game in terms of
people discovering where there are loopholes or where there are
opportunities to manipulate the system.''
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of instructional costs, Rylander said the task
force will study why only 52 cents out of every education tax
dollar in the state is spent on instruction. HISD officials,
however, said they spend 60.4 percent of their funds on
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Rylander said the group also will determine if school districts
are accurately reporting their administrative costs.
</P>
<P>
   Some districts may report that they are lowering the number of
administrators, she said, but their offices stay filled.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that we must keep a system of viable public
education,'' Delco said. ``In order to do that, we have to generate
the confidence of the people in this state and the investment they
make through their taxes for public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
