</HEADLINE>
  
 Tuesday, Sept. 21, 1999     
 Editors      The Hearst News Service has filed the following for
Wednesday. If you have questions, please call Susie McBee at
<TEXT>
<P>
   (The ``HNS'' tag appears in all sluglines.)  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (``w'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FALN-CLEMENCY (Washington) _ A Senate subcommittee holds a
hearing into President Clinton's anti-terrorism policy in wake of
his clemency for some Puerto Rican members of the FALN terrorist
group. At the same time, the House Government Reform Committee
meets to probe the FALN matter. Clinton sends a letter to the House
committee defending his clemency, but some lawmakers attack the
decision. By JOHN C. HENRY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL NEWS (``p'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-SENATE (Washington) _ In the latest version of reading
political tea leaves, Frank Luntz, a Republican adviser to New York
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, says the Thanksgiving plans of the First
Family will indicate whether Hillary Clinton will run for the
Senate from New York. If the Clintons go to their new home in
Chappaqua, N.Y., then she'll run, he says, but if they stay in
Washington, she won't. We get White House response. By STEWART M.
POWELL. Already filed in the POLITICAL NEWS (``p'') and WASHINGTON
NEWS (``w'') categories.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JASPER-TRIAL (Bryan, Texas) _ It's a dramatic scene outside the
courtroom here when convicted killer Russell Brewer's parents cry,
ask for forgiveness and embrace relatives of Brewer's victim, James
Byrd Jr. Brewer, a white supremacist, was convicted of dragging to
death the disabled black man in the East Texas town of Jasper. The
jury is expected to decide Wednesday if Brewer gets the death
penalty. By PATTY REINERT.
</P>
<P>
   HEROES-TEXAS (Austin, Texas) _ At the University of Texas, not
all of the heroes have always been cowboys. Many of them are
Confederate soldiers. That is about to change, when the
predominantly white university with a history of rocky race
relations unveils a statue next week of Martin Luther King Jr. By
POLLY ROSS HUGHES.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CHAVEZ (New York) _ Hugo Chavez, in his first visit to
the United States as president of Venezuela, promises that his
country will be a democracy, not a dictatorship. We cover his
remarks at a private luncheon in New York and later at the United
Nations General Assembly. By MARK HELM. Story will also be filed in
the INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'') category.
</P>
<P>
   ASPHALT-FEUD (Junction, Texas) _ The West Texas town that gets
its name from the union of the pristine North and South Llano
rivers is in the midst of an oldtimer-newcomer feud. Weirich
Brothers Co., which has mined sand and gravel from the riverbeds
for years, wants an air pollution permit to produce asphalt. The
newly arrived environmental refugees from cities like Houston and
Dallas are having apoplexy. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Pittsburgh) _ After losing four of their last five
games, the first-place Houston Astros will send Scott Elarton to
the mound Tuesday night to face the Pittsburgh Pirates in the
second game of a three-game series. By CARLTON THOMPSON.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN (Houston) _ The latest with the NFL
expansion race between Los Angeles and Houston. By MICKEY
HERSKOWITZ.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-CART (Houston) _ Rookie Juan Montoya has come out of nowhere
to dominate the CART racing circuit this season, and he has a
chance to clinch the season points title at this weekend's Houston
Grand Prix. By TERRY BLOUNT.
</P>
<P>
   GLF-RYDER (Brookline, Mass.) _ Long hitters may get all the
attention, but the short game could be the key to victory at the
Ryder Cup golf event this weekend. By EDDIE SEFKO.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ Referendum results suppressed by
Congress for a year and only now made public show that the District
of Columbia voted overwhelmingly last fall to legalize the medical
use of marijuana. Nonetheless, congressional Republicans are
determined to overrule the voters, and the lawmakers have the power
to do it. By MARIANNE MEANS.
</P>
