<HEADER>
A0649 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-NCMAIN-COX     09-21 1213
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-N </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 C MAIN-COX &HT;    City officials ask most businesses to close; water deliveries
arrive
 &HT;    By Dawn Bryant
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. _ The city of Greenville lost water service
Tuesday, prompting officials to bring in portable toilets and
trucks of water and ask most businesses to close because of fire
and public health concerns.
</P>
<P>
   Most Greenville Utilities water customers lost service or water
pressure Tuesday after floodwaters kept the submerged Old River
Road treatment station from meeting demand. Portable toilets popped
up around town as businesses struggled to cope.
</P>
<P>
   It could be at least two days before service is restored. But
GUC officials are working on ways to rig temporary equipment _
similar to efforts that restored electrical service over the
weekend _ to get the water flowing sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always try something else to make it work,'' said Malcolm
Green, GUC's general manager/CEO. ``There is a possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   In other developments:
</P>
<P>
   _ River levels seem to have leveled keeping officials from
having to shut off power to Greenville and three-fourths of Pitt
County.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Tar River appeared to hit a crest of 29.72 feet.
</P>
<P>
   _ County officials issued a mandatory evacuation order for the
Clark's Neck area.
</P>
<P>
   _ Preliminary countywide damage estimates, based on property tax
records, are at $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Portable toilets and jugs of water arrived Tuesday to help
residents survive for the next few days without water service,
which was lost earlier that day. Three water distribution points
were expected to open late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The city issued a voluntary closing order for all Greenville
businesses except pharmacies and grocery and convenience stores to
minimize the likelihood of losses if a fire should occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to get as much shut off as we can,'' said Ron Moore,
interim fire-rescue chief. ``Our only resources are the water we
carry around in our trucks.'' Those six vehicles hold about 500
gallons each.
</P>
<P>
   Five tankers of firefighting water, which isn't clean enough to
drink, was expected to arrive from Wake County late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Officials also asked neighboring fire stations for help and
identified area swimming pools that could be drained in an
emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Pitt County Memorial Hospital pumped water from its
rehabilitation pool for uses other than drinking, including
flushing toilets and cleaning floors. Officials were trying to line
up other water suppliers.
</P>
<P>
   They also were reviewing the possibility of moving patients to a
single unit to conserve. Signs on bathrooms warn patients and staff
not to use them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The water is the problem right now,'' said Jeannine Hutson,
hospital spokeswoman. ``This is a significant hurdle.''
</P>
<P>
   Customers of Eastern Pines and Bell Arthur water corporations
still have service, but a boil-order remains. As a safety
precaution, residents in those areas should boil cooking and
drinking water for three minutes to kill any bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   Conditions also worsened and then improved at the North Holly
Street electric substation, where a fragile setup that ended a
nearly 24-hour blackout Saturday continued to be threatened.
</P>
<P>
   Water heights _ just three inches shy of forcing a blackout _
seemed to have leveled, keeping officials from having to shut off
power.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my feeling we will have made the threshold,'' Green said.
``We should be in pretty good shape.''
</P>
<P>
   But an oil slick on the water spotted early Tuesday posed a
potential fire problem.
</P>
<P>
   With 230,000 volts running through the lines, boat crews
guarding the equipment from floating debris had to be pulled.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were trying to find the source of the oil and line up
means to keep it from the wires. If it gets too close, GUC would
have to shut off the power.
</P>
<P>
   A string web brought in Tuesday to collect the oil from the
water's surface should do the trick, Green said.
</P>
<P>
   The electrical setup _ one line bringing power in, another
distributing it _ still is a delicate one until the water recedes,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we will be past the power crisis,'' Green said.
``What we really have is an electrical system with just one switch.
This is a very patched-up substation.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tar River, which appeared to hit a crest of 29.72 feet
Tuesday, wasn't backing off its attack on the area with its
record-shattering levels.
</P>
<P>
   Evacuations continued Monday night, with county officials
issuing the mandatory order in the Clark's Neck area, which is on
the county's eastern border.
</P>
<P>
   Residents there were directed to shelters at Stokes Elementary
and Washington High schools.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 residents remained in the seven shelters, which
are now operated by the American Red Cross.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters north of the river aren't accessible by road, with
officials relying on helicopters and boats to transport food,
medication and other supplies.
</P>
<P>
   With Tuesday's rains preventing choppers from flying, the Pitt
County Sheriff's Department depended on boats only.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of water service forced officials to relocate about 500
residents in shelters at E.B. Aycock and Wintergreen to two schools
in Ayden, which still has utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Early Tuesday evening, shelter organizers were trying to find
utility-serviced buildings to relocate residents staying in the
North Pitt and Wellcome schools.
</P>
<P>
   Officials urge anyone who had open sores or cut themselves while
in the water to get a tetanus shot, especially if they haven't had
one in the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   The city continued to monitor the flooded Green Mill Run, which
snakes its way through the city and has forced some of its
neighbors to evacuate. Officials don't anticipate issuing a fourth
round of voluntary notices.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Tar River started flooding last week, the city has
transported 775 residents from homes threatened by floods. Hundreds
more fled in their own vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Floyd's 13 inches of rain Wednesday and Thursday fell
on already saturated ground from Tropical Storm Dennis' repeat
visits and other recent rains. The combination has produced the
worst flood in Greenville's history.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary countywide damage estimates, based on property tax
records, are at $1.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Some of GUC's 26,130 water customers started noticing a drop in
water pressure Tuesday after the plant couldn't produce enough
water to meet demands, with it tapping overground storage tanks.
Once those 8.5 million gallons are used, the faucets will run dry.
</P>
<P>
   PCMH, which is about 90 percent full, has forestry, National
Guard and private company tankers working with area fire
departments to bring in water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be able to do our thing using this system,'' hospital
vice president Stephen Lawler said. ``It's probably not the ideal
situation, but it's something we can do.''
</P>
<P>
   With the water crisis, portable toilet vendors were swamped with
calls.
</P>
<P>
   About midday Tuesday, East Coast Rent-A-John received about 30
calls and had 19 messages on the answering machine. The Farmville
business was distributing the dozen or so unrented toilets to
emergency officials and a few retailers offering disaster-relief
materials.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
