<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0650 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r a BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-BUSH-T     09-21 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-BUSH-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS GOVERNOR ANNOUNCES STRONGER ENFORCEMENT OF GUN LAWS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By JAY ROOT 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Less than a week after eight people died in a
hail of bullets at Wedgwood Baptist Church in Fort Worth, Texas
Gov. George W. Bush announced plans on Tuesday to crack down on gun
crimes across Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired in part by a Fort Worth program to be unveiled next
week, Bush said Texas Exile, a multi-agency initiative putting
eight new prosecutors on the trail of gun law violators, will make
Texas safer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to protect our citizens is to vigorously enforce
the tough laws we have on the books,'' said Bush, who opposes
restrictions such as gun registration and licensing. ``This is a
war on people illegally carrying weapons.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the leading Republican presidential candidate, has been
criticized by political rivals for not offering more concrete
solutions to the type of violence that occurred in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   But he said the new initiative was not aimed at those critics
nor crafted in response to the Wedgwood massacre. Bush said Texas
Exile has been in the works for several weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said he hopes the program will put a damper on gun
violence but acknowledged it might not have stopped the kind of
rampage Larry Gene Ashbrook unleashed at the church.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to convince a crazy man not to act,'' Bush said.
``If it wasn't a gun it might have been a pipe bomb. The idea is to
send a clear message and that maybe if somebody hears the clear
message that there will be a consequence, it will convince somebody
not to carry a gun in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush got testy when reporters asked if the drive to step up
prosecutions was an acknowledgement that past efforts have been
insufficient.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is now a concerted effort. We are enforcing laws on the
books in the state of Texas. People are being arrested for
illegally carrying guns,'' he said. ``This is just a more focused
effort.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas Exile will be administered by Attorney General John Cornyn
in coordination with the four United States attorneys assigned to
Texas. The program will initially be funded by a $1.6 million grant
from the governor's office.
</P>
<P>
   Cornyn said the prosecutors will be ``cross-designated'' so that
they can pursue violations of both state and federal weapon laws in
order to maximize jail time. Typically, federal gun violations
carry five-year minimum sentences.
</P>
<P>
   The program also will include a public awareness campaign and,
eventually, a toll-free hotline that will receive tips about
possible gun law violators.
</P>
<P>
   It was largely modeled after Project Exile in Richmond, Va., a
cooperative effort among federal, state and local officials aimed
at increasing jail time for gun law violators.
</P>
<P>
   Since implementing the program, Richmond, which had the nation's
second highest murder rate in 1997, has seen its murder rate drop
by more than 30 percent and its violent crime rate fall by nearly
half.
</P>
<P>
   But the Texas program also was inspired in part by the Safe City
USA program to be unveiled in Fort Worth next week, Cornyn said.
The initiative, pushed by Fort Worth businessmen Lee and Perry
Bass, will include a privately financed $745,000 publicity
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   One example of the inspiration Fort Worth gave the state is its
slogan: ``Gun Crime Means Hard Time.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our message today and for each day hereafter in the state of
Texas is that gun crime means hard time,'' said Cornyn. ``Texas
Exile is about incarcerating those who illegally carry, possess or
sell guns without infringing upon the rights of law-abiding
citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was well received by Bruce Elfant, a Travis
County constable and member of Texans Against Gun Violence. But
Elfant questioned the timing of Bush's announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish that the governor hadn't waited until he was running
for president to propose something like this,'' Elfant said. ``We
do need more prosecutions.''
</P>
<P>
   Elfant said Bush has ``done everything the NRA (National Rifle
Association) has wanted him to do,'' and faulted the governor for
not doing more to keep guns out of the hands of criminals, such as
requiring a three-day waiting period for weapon purchases at gun
shows.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be able to build enough jails or hire enough cops to
deal with every gun crime if we don't do these preventative
strategies to reduce the access to guns by children and
criminals,'' Elfant said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush attributed questions about the timing of his announcement
to politics. As to why he did not act sooner, the governor
suggested the reason was that he has a better working relationship
with Cornyn, a Republican, than with former Attorney General Dan
Morales, a Democrat who retired in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attorney general and I finally got together,'' Bush said.
``This is an attorney general that I feel comfortable working
with.'' He said it was possible he and Morales could have done
something similar, but ``we just never had a meeting of the
minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Morales could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
