<SLUG> BC-BLACKS-CREDIT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Minorities have tougher time with credit, loans than whites
 &HT;    By Shelia M. Poole
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Nicholas Harrell has always realized the importance of
having good credit.
</P>
<P>
   Harrell, a financial analyst at SunTrust Bank, doubled payments
to retire his school loans four years early and today, the
38-year-old Atlanta resident is debt free. ``When I walk into a
mortgage company, they should love me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While Harrell likely won't have any problem getting a mortgage
loan, many other African Americans do because of poor credit
histories. According to Freddie Mac, 72 percent of white households
own homes, compared to 46 percent of African American households
and 44 percent of Hispanic households.
</P>
<P>
   A new report says African American borrowers are more likely
than whites and Hispanics to experience credit problems.
Forty-eight percent of African American borrowers and 34 percent of
Hispanic borrowers have ``bad credit records, compared to just 27
percent of whites, according to the report released this week by
Freddie Mac and five historically black colleges and universities,
including Clark Atlanta University.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can tell you horror stories about friends who have bad
credit now because of the ways things were mismanaged when they
were in undergraduate school,'' said Harrell. ``Everyone had credit
cards and people were using them. By the time they left
undergraduate school they were $4,000 to $5,000 in debt with 21
percent interest. That's a tough way to start out.''
</P>
<P>
   To help minorities avoid credit problems Freddie Mac said
Tuesday it has teamed with the schools to boost home ownership
rates by helping minority consumers understand the benefits of
having good credit reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the industry to grow in the future have to look to raising
home ownership rates,'' said Freddie Mac spokesman Sharon McHale.
</P>
<P>
   Freddie Mac has been working with the schools _ Clark Atlanta,
Benedict College, Florida A &AMP; M, Howard University and St.
Augustine's College _ since January when it awarded the schools
$1.3 million for the effort. Since then more than 50 focus groups
have been conducted and an national survey of 12,000 consumers.
</P>
<P>
   The results will be used to develop an initiative to help
consumers obtain and maintain good credit. The National Urban
League and the National Association for the Advancement of Colored
People have also signed up to help implement the program, including
distributing an educational curriculum for teens and young adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know that good credit has a lot to do with the quality
of life that you have,'' said Marvin Patterson, associate dean of
the business school at CAU. ``We want to take this issue beyond the
college environment into the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Such programs help in the long run, said Carol Hetzler, manager
of the Atlanta branch of the Consumer Credit Counseling Service,
which sees about 400 clients a month. ``People don't realize until
its too late the damage they've done to their credit when they're
young,'' she said. Bad credit ``doesn't just go away. It takes
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheila Poole writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
