<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-BELVOIR22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Church serves as rescue base north of river
 &HT;    By Bobby Burns
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELVOIR, N.C. _ Gum Swamp Church is no longer just a place of
worship _ it's a makeshift relief post and command center.
</P>
<P>
   Church members, three deputy sheriffs, four forest rangers and a
handful of volunteer firefighters have staged search and rescue
operations from the Belvoir fellowship hall, served hundreds of
meals and even delivered some by truck and by boat.
</P>
<P>
   ``People that live all around the community are in here for
food, water, baby supplies, whatever we can get,'' said Eugene
James, a church member and chairman of the Pitt County Board of
Commissioners. ``We're encouraging them to stay at home, stay off
the roads. They can come in here once a day and pick up what they
need.''
</P>
<P>
   Five days after Hurricane Floyd, communities north of the Tar
River continued grassroots relief efforts to distribute vital
supplies to thousands of residents cut off by flood water from
Greenville. N.C. Forestry Service helicopters have flown Red Cross
meals to Belvoir volunteers since Sunday. When rain grounded the
planes Tuesday they used one ranger's boat to ferry supplies.
</P>
<P>
   The Belvoir community roughly follows N.C. 33 from Greenville
northwest to the Edgecombe County line. Flooding has devastated the
area, the group at Gum Swamp said. The water has swept up mobile
homes along Old River Road, rolling them along with the current.
</P>
<P>
   James and others estimated that 200 to 300 people remain in
flooded areas from Belvoir Crossroads to Penny Hill to the north.
More remain to the south near Belvoir Elementary School. Dozens of
them on Tuesday wandered the half-flooded streets of soggy trailer
parks and sat on the porches of scattered homes.
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Wilder, of 820 Barrus Construction Road made his way to
Gum Swamp Church Tuesday morning to pick up a cardboard box of food
for himself, his wife and three sons. Styrofoam takeout plates of
stew, bread and vegetables filled the box.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used up everything at the house and we've been to some of
the side stores and they're just about sold out,'' said Wilder, a
machinist at Vermont American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what makes it bad is not being able to get out
anywhere. Everybody on this side of the Tar River has to go to
Bethel or Williamston and they don't have anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Long lines and rationing persisted Tuesday at Pitt County's
single grocery store north of the river, Bethel IGA, although basic
necessities including milk and gasoline were available there and in
neighboring Martin County. A line also snaked outside the door at
Bethel Pharmacy.
</P>
<P>
   The area, like much of the county on Tuesday, also lost its
water supply. The prospect promised to pose challenges for
residents in shelters at Wellcome Middle School and North Pitt High
School.
</P>
<P>
   At Wellcome, residents and volunteers were collecting rain water
to flush toilets. At North Pitt, they were collecting water from a
nearby creek. Officials at both shelters before the Reflector's
early publishing deadline were hoping portable toilets would be
delivered.
</P>
<P>
   Numbers at both schools had declined by Tuesday as some
residents moved to a shelter set up at Stokes Elementary and others
found accommodations with family and friends. Wellcome was down to
246 from more than 400 and North Pitt was down to about 400 from
nearly 800 registered there Monday, workers said.
</P>
<P>
   Improvising make-do measures like catching rainwater has become
routine at the facilities. At North Pitt for instance, residents
are holding school for the children and at Wellcome volunteers
supplemented their cereal breakfast with sandwiches on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Food supplies at the facilities were more than adequate Tuesday.
At North Pitt, volunteers sorted through piles of donated clothing
spread out on the stage and first several rows of seats in the
school auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   Volunteers have been brought in by helicopter. Bad weather on
Tuesday kept ECU student Devan Raghavan longer than he expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a 6-month-old baby and with the prospect of no water
and no power I'm a little worried,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His mother speaks no English and his wife speaks no Malayalam,
his native tongue. He usually interprets for them. ``I'm wondering
what they are saying to each other. What are they going to do with
the baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in Belvoir, Derrick Moore was spending his third wedding
anniversary making sure residents were fed and safe.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service assistant ranger and the three other rangers
work out of Belvoir and decided to stick it out when the river
started rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stuck in Belvoir basically because there wasn't anybody
else up here. It's been isolated since the storm,'' said Moore.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the supplies are in Greenville, its just that nobody could
get it to us until we got the Forestry Service helicopter .... We
were in bad shape a couple of days ago but we're doing OK now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
