<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BANKRUPT-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BANKRUPTCY BILL IS BLOCKED IN FIGHT OVER MINIMUM PAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVID E. ROSENBAUM and STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to force a vote on a measure to increase the
minimum wage, Democratic Senators blocked Republican legislation to
revamp federal bankruptcy laws Tuesday, at least for the time
being.
</P>
<P>
   The bankruptcy bill, a version of which was approved by the
House of Representatives in May, is one of the few Republican
legislative initiatives still in play this year. Strongly supported
by the banking and credit card industries, it would make it harder
for consumers to avoid paying debts by declaring bankruptcy.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats, led by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts, want
to attach an amendment that would raise the federal minimum wage,
now $5.15 an hour, to $6.15 in two 50-cent installments over the
next two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raising the minimum wage is critical to preventing the
economic free fall that often leads to bankruptcy,'' Kennedy said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But most Republicans say that raising the minimum wage would be
devastating to some small businesses and would cost many working
people their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Voting along party lines Tuesday evening, the Senate rejected a
Republican move to invoke cloture and bring the bankruptcy bill to
a vote. The vote was 53-45, seven votes shy of the 60 needed to
halt debate. If cloture had been approved, the Democrats'
minimum-wage amendment would have been foreclosed.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes, however, party leaders were meeting to try to
negotiate a compromise. The prevailing view in both parties Tuesday
was that a deal could eventually be worked out that would lead to
passage of both the minimum-wage increase and the overall
bankruptcy legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The minimum wage issue has divided Republicans and Democrats for
generations, and arguments have hardly changed since the federal
minimum wage was introduced, at 25 cents an hour, in the 1930s.
</P>
<P>
   On one side are the Democrats and liberal economists who hold
that market forces have failed workers in low-paying jobs. A fair
minimum wage, they say, prevents sweatshops and rewards people who
leave welfare rolls and go to work. These advocates maintain that
the resulting job loss, if any, will be trivial.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, Republicans and conservative economists say
that much of the benefit will go to teen-agers who do not really
need the money. Some businesses, especially smaller ones, will go
bankrupt and others will raise prices, leading to inflation. Many
poor people, the opponents say, will lose jobs because businesses
will let them go rather than raise their pay.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the economic arguments, the political situation is
clear: This is a good issue for Democrats, and Republicans are
likely to switch rather than fight.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, Republican leaders have conceded that they do not
have the votes to defeat the Democratic bill. They are working on a
face-saving compromise that would tie the minimum-wage increase to
some modest tax breaks for small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the legislation said Tuesday that despite the
setback, they expected the bankruptcy measure to be introduced
again, particularly since a similar measure passed in the last
session by a vote of 97-1.
</P>
<P>
   But even if it is adopted, the Senate legislation can not become
law until it is reconciled with a more stringent version that was
adopted by the House last May. President Clinton's advisers have
recommended that he veto that measure, although it was adopted by a
veto-proof margin of 313-108. Senate negotiators have tried to
draft a more lenient bill in the hopes of gaining White House
support.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate legislation, largely written by Sens. Charles E.
Grassley, R-Iowa, and Robert G. Torricelli, D-N.J., is more
favorable to debtors.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights and consumers groups have been critical of the
House and Senate measures for largely favoring debtors over
creditors, and hitting women and the less affluent harder.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
