<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0656 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-GALLO-THEATER-DESIGNE     09-21 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GALLO-THEATER-DESIGNER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSTRUCTING LOONIER-THAN-LIFE WORLDS ON STAGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 Steven Drukman is writing a history of avant-garde theater in
America.  
 By STEVEN DRUKMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What makes a David Gallo design a David Gallo design?
Mr. Gallo will only say, ``I tend to do things
(italics)large.''(end italics) That's a rather broad esthetic
philosophy, but it sits well with the husky, garrulous man whose
latest larger-than-life set surrounds the action of ``Epic
Proportions,'' a new comedy opening Thursday at the Helen Hayes
Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Still, how does Gallo explain that in a world where producers
pray that people leave the theater humming, talk of his sets may be
the buzz going up the aisle? Or how does he explain critical
notices praising his painted backdrops before weighing in on the
playwright, director or leading lady? (In the opening paragraph of
a 1997 New York Times review of ``Bunny Bunny,'' Peter Marks called
Gallo's set ``ahhh-inspiring'' and wrote that ``Mr. Gallo is one up
on any dog or child on a New York stage: he has created
scene-stealing scenery.'')
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, when hired to create a world where a comatose
patient has an out-of-body experience (as in last season's ``New
Brain'' at Lincoln Center) or giant puppets blur the line between
actor and scenery (as in ``Jackie: An American Life''), how does
Gallo find so many ways to make set pieces into sight gags?
</P>
<P>
   ``Gosh, I don't know,'' he replies, politely pretending to
entertain these questions. ``Luck? Listening to good music? Somehow
the ability to tell a joke with an inanimate object just comes to
me. I'm not big on figuring out how.''
</P>
<P>
   It may be the only thing Gallo, 33, isn't big on. With eyebrows
swooping like a tsunami over sparkling blue eyes, he is a spiral of
energy and looks very much like the Tasmanian Devil from Warner
Brothers cartoons. In conversation, his hands help an avalanche of
words tumble out of his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   His frenetic style proves that suddenly being on the A-list of
designers makes downtime a scarce resource. Among his credits from
last year are three Broadway revivals _ ``Little Me,'' ``The Lion
in Winter'' (both at the Roundabout) and ``You're a Good Man,
Charlie Brown'' _ which overlapped with what Gallo estimates were
about 10 other shows off Broadway and around the country.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking amid the hubbub of his Times Square design studio,
Gallo admits that he consumes anything and everything in popular
culture _ vintage comic books, rock-and-roll, Cecil B. DeMille
movies _ for visual ideas. It's a pragmatic, if ad hoc, technique
and seems to work for someone with Gallo's schedule.
</P>
<P>
   Already this season, in addition to ``Epic Proportions''
(directed by Jerry Zaks and starring Kristin Chenoweth, both Tony
Award winners), Gallo's set for ``Voices in the Dark'' is on view
at the Longacre Theater, and Off Broadway audiences have already
seen his work in ``Jar the Floor'' at Second Stage.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo's forthcoming projects include the Broadway-bound
``Thunder Knocking on the Door,'' written and directed by Keith
Glover, and two world premieres off Broadway (``The Wild Party'' at
the Manhattan Theater Club and ``Bubbly Black Girl'' at Playwrights
Horizons). For the last decade, his design has supported the
azure-tinted antics of Blue Man Group's ``Tubes'' at the Astor
Place Theater.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo leads a busy and peripatetic life, in some ways a second
version of his childhood, when he traveled around Europe as the son
of an Air Force officer. He thinks he has designed 150 shows since
he dropped out of the State University of New York at Purchase 11
years ago to work in professional theater, but that's only a guess;
he hasn't had a moment to stop and count.
</P>
<P>
   In an age when so many set designers have advanced degrees from
Yale or New York University, Gallo seems to have an MFA of the
streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``While at school, I already had scripts on my desk to design
shows for (italics)real(end italics) theaters,'' he says. ``O.K.,
they were small and paid zip, but that was better than finishing my
requirements to do props for some sophomore's show.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of job offers increased steadily, and Gallo accepted
them all. ``I was broke but didn't care,'' he says. ``Still don't.
I just said, `Yeah, keep 'em comin'.' Then I'd find myself on a
train to Philly, sketching a show, and I'd spent all my money on
the ticket. So I'd hitchhike to some rinky-dink theater from the
station, having never been in Philly before.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo says he worked for eight years this way, never taking a
day off, making the past ``one big blur to where I am right now.''
But he recalls that his big break was in 1989, with Michael Greif's
production of ``Machinal'' at the Naked Angels. ``Definitely '89,''
he says. ``It had to be. Spike Lee's `Do the Right Thing' was out
that year, and that Public Enemy tune was really big on the
radio.'' In 1990, ``Machinal'' moved to the Joseph Papp Public
Theater, where Gallo worked as an assistant to the designer James
Youmans.
</P>
<P>
   ``But even then,'' he says, ``for what we used to call the Papp
test'' _ a meeting with Joseph Papp to approve a show's design _
``I had to jump the turnstile of the subway with a huge model of
the set in my hand, because I couldn't afford a token.''
</P>
<P>
   While at the Public, Gallo met a tyro director named Michael
Mayer (who was also working as an assistant, to the director David
Warren). This sparked a decadelong collaboration, beginning with
Mayer's first paid directing job, in the undergraduate department
of drama at Yale, and continuing with the well-received national
tour of ``Angels in America.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The two men have worked together on a total of 11 shows
(including, most recently, the Off Broadway ``Stupid Kids,'' and on
Broadway, last season's ``Lion in Winter,'' ``You're a Good Man,
Charlie Brown'' and the Tony-winning ``View From the Bridge'').
</P>
<P>
   Mayer explains Gallo's appeal: ``It was only a matter of time
before critics caught on to David. He works so hard and makes
(italics)huge(end italics) statements, but not at the expense of
the play. He does what a director does for a script _ lets it tell
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayer and Gallo will work together again on a stage adaptation
of the movie musical ``Thoroughly Modern Millie.'' Their version,
also starring Ms. Chenoweth, is slated for a Broadway run next
year. The lighting designer Donald Holder, winner of a Tony for
``The Lion King,'' collaborated with Gallo on many shows, including
``Hughie,'' starring Al Pacino, at Circle in the Square in 1996 and
August Wilson's ``Jitney,'' which has traveled the country and is
heading for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking by telephone from London, Holder said: ``David works
harder than most designers and probably wouldn't stop if he wasn't
told to. Working in the business has been Dave's graduate school.
He would have no personal life if he hadn't made a very good choice
in that his associate is also his girlfriend.''
</P>
<P>
   Holder is referring to Lauren Helpern, a set decorator, who
often takes care of what Gallo calls ``the detail work that I hate
to deal with.'' Ms. Helpern lives with Gallo on the Upper East Side
and received credit as co-designer on ``Voices in the Dark,''
Gallo's most recent collaboration with Holder.
</P>
<P>
   When stretched with overlapping projects, Gallo has hired up to
12 temporary assistants to draft and build models, and he maintains
two full-time associates. He recently hired a part-time office
assistant who urged him to wear both a cellular phone and a pager,
which he attaches and detaches from his baggy jeans with nervous
energy. He claims that he's usually too busy to answer them.
</P>
<P>
   Gallo is mildly chagrined about one aspect of his growing fame:
after Marks used the word ``cartoonish'' to describe the inventive
scenery in ``Bunny Bunny,'' it seemed to Gallo that the word was
everywhere. Ben Brantley pointed out in his Times review that
``Jackie: An American Life'' was presented as ``that `little
cartoon''' that the play's subject, Jacqueline Onassis, saw running
alongside her life. ( Gallo points out that his scenery, which had
the look of live animation, merely represented Mrs. Onassis's own
description of her sometimes-surreal existence.)
</P>
<P>
   After his crayon-colored set for ``You're a Good Man, Charlie
Brown'' gained so much attention, Gallo believes, people formed
final judgments about what makes a David Gallo design a David Gallo
design _ and it didn't matter that they were almost always
complimentary. (Writing in New York magazine, John Simon noted,
``Nobody does cartoonish scenery better than David Gallo.'')
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, that musical is based on a comic strip!'' Gallo says.
`So suddenly it was, like, `Hey, want your play to look like a
cartoon? Get David Gallo.' As if I didn't have hundreds of other
styles in my portfolio. Look, if the play calls for realistic
detail work, that's cool with me. I'll do it; I just find it
boring. It's like doing scales and arpeggios.''
</P>
<P>
   Gallo's design for ``Epic Proportions'' offers yet another
example of what is coming to be regarded as his signature style of
vibrant colors and cartoonish perspective. To suggest the location
of a 1930s biblical epic being filmed in the Arizona desert, Gallo
designed what he calls ``one big one-note joke.'' In the second
act, the goddess Isis (played by Ms. Chenoweth) is shackled to the
upstage wall in a pair of chains so enormous, they look straight
out of Looney Tunes.
</P>
<P>
   He explains: ``Because those movies were all about excess, man.
So, on stage I put the bottom 15 feet of a 1,000-foot Corinthian
column. You don't see the Sphinx, but the Sphinx's big toe.''
</P>
<P>
   True to his love for popular culture, Gallo dreams of designing
the definitive rock-and-roll musical on Broadway. He says, ``I
loved doing `Tommy,' but that wasn't it.'' ( Gallo worked as the
associate scenic designer for the international tour and Broadway
run of the 1993 production of the rock opera.) ```Rent' wasn't it.
But I bet Prince has a great musical locked inside that paisley
head of his. Or if Bruce Springsteen wrote a musical, man, I'd be
all over that!''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
