<HEADER>
A0658 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-A     09-21 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRIPPLED BY DIVIDED OPPOSITION, MILOSEVIC FOES STAGE MODEST
RALLIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
may make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(HLW) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ In a modest beginning to a campaign by a
divided opposition to oust the Yugoslav president, Slobodan
Milosevic, tens of thousands of people attended rallies in some 20
Serbian towns on Tuesday evening, hearing pleas to keep marching
until Milosevic goes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to come here every day and clean Serbia drop by
drop,'' said the Democratic Party leader, Zoran Djindjic, speaking
in a light rain to some 20,000 people in the central Square of the
Republic. ``And if on the 10th day, 2 million people are on the
streets of Serbia, it means that Serbia is healthy,'' and Milosevic
will have to resign.
</P>
<P>
   Far fewer than that turned out across Serbia on Tuesday night,
with some 7,000 people in Novi Sad, 20,000 in Nis, 10,000 in
Kragujevac (with support from the car workers at the Zastava plant)
and a good turnout of 10,000 in Smederevo, in eastern Serbia,
normally a regime stronghold, according to officials of the
Alliance for Change coalition and some local media estimates. In
general, the police did not interfere.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, the mood was hopeful but not confident, with many
interviewed in the crowd expressing doubts that rallies alone will
oust Milosevic. They also expressed unhappiness with the continuing
divisions in the opposition, symbolized by the rivalry between
Djindjic and his erstwhile partner, Vuk Draskovic of the larger
Serbian Renewal Movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here to start something that must go to the end,'' said
the popular mayor of Cacak, Velimir Ilic, in his speech. ``Whether
we succeed or not depends on us.'' But Ilic also sharply criticized
Draskovic, who chose not to take part in these rallies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ask other opposition parties to join us and not cooperate
with the regime,'' Ilic said. ``We are the opposition and they are
the servants of Slobodan Milosevic.''
</P>
<P>
   The designated ``prime minister'' of an opposition-nominated
``transitional government,'' Dragoslav Avramovic, a former banker,
also appealed to other opposition parties Tuesday night to support
him, saying the Alliance alone was not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Draskovic has called for early elections as the best way to oust
Milosevic and said he believed these rallies would fail. His stance
has created bitterness among Alliance followers and some of the
people who came here Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Draskovic is now part of the regime,'' said Jovan Bandin, a
businessman who said he intended to demonstrate as long as
necessary. ``He does everything he can to stop real change.''
</P>
<P>
   Ognjen Pribicevic, a close adviser to Draskovic, said he thought
these rallies ``will show clearly that the Alliance for Change does
not have the strength to produce change in Serbia.'' Draskovic's
push for early, free and fair elections is the only workable policy
to change the regime, Pribicevic said. ``And still the only guy
with real credibility is Vuk Draskovic,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But if Milosevic rejects early elections, Draskovic and his
party will go out into the streets, perhaps by the end of October,
Pribicevic said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then it will be different,'' he said. ``There will be a clear
issue, not just empty words.''
</P>
<P>
   While there was some scuffling with the police in Smederevo, the
only tension of the night was in Novi Sad, where Nenad Canak, an
Alliance leader and head of the League of Social Democrats of
Vojvodina, had threatened to ``take over'' the provincial assembly
and ``evict its illegal tenants.'' In the end, demonstrators chose
a symbolic path Tuesday night, marching to the doors of the
building, where only a few policemen were standing, and then
turning aside after yelling slogans and blowing whistles.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, there was some nostalgia for the three months of
daily rallies in the winter of 1996-97, when the opposition was
united in the Zajedno, or Together, coalition. Then, daily
demonstrators blowing whistles got local election results
reinstated, but Milosevic hung on.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic whistles were on sale Tuesday night from vendors for
about 50 cents, and after the rally speeches, demonstrators were
urged to walk through Belgrade as they did three years ago, blowing
their whistles in derision at City Hall, the state television
headquarters, the Serbian parliament and the offices of Politika,
the state-run newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Matic, the Yugoslav information minister, said in an
interview earlier in the day that the opposition simply wanted to
grab power on the streets because it was afraid of elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name for someone who wants power without elections is
Lenin,'' he said. ``Djindjic doesn't want elections _ he can't win
more than 2 percent of the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, when asked if the government would call early elections,
Matic shrugged and said: ``Why? We have real work to do, to rebuild
the country, fix housing, bridges and railroads.''
</P>
<P>
   Without the participation of Draskovic, Matic said with some
satisfaction, ``these demonstrations can't be very big.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
