<SLUG> BC-CHURCHSHOOTING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO PROZAC FOUND IN KILLER'S HOME, POLICE NOW SAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service Clients) 
By KATHY SANDERS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ |The head of the Wedgwood Baptist Church
shooting investigation said on Tuesday that, contrary to what he
told news media on Monday, no Prozac was found in the home of the
gunman.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Mark Krey said his earlier account was based on
misinformation that a search of Larry Gene Ashbrook's home had
yielded a vial for the anti-depressant Prozac had been prescribed
for him.
</P>
<P>
   After talking with his lead investigator yesterday, Krey said he
learned that all medications found in the home were the type
primarily prescribed for people suffering from congestive heart
failure and belonged to Ashbrook's father, Jack Ashbrook, who died
in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point during the course of the last several days and
the subsequent search on the home of Larry Ashbrook, there was a
general conversation in which someone mentioned Prozac had been
found,'' Krey said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't personally look at the specific inventory prior to
the interview. This morning it was pointed out to me that the
information was incorrect,'' Krey said.
</P>
<P>
   That does not detract from the police belief that the death of
Ashbrook's father probably pushed him over the edge of reason, Krey
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When his father died, he lost the major stabilizing factor in
his life,'' Krey said.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, detectives pulled the medicine vials from the police
property room and inventoried them to verify what medicines had
been confiscated from the house.
</P>
<P>
   A log used by Jack Ashbrook to document his medication usage is
believed to have been used later by Larry Ashbrook, who may have
begun taking his father's medicine, police said.
</P>
<P>
   It is one of several theories being investigated as police try
to determine why the 47-year-old Ashbrook, whose brother called him
a paranoid schizophrenic, embarked on the deadly rampage at
Wedgwood Baptist Church a week ago Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Seven people were shot to death and seven were wounded before
Ashbrook sat in a back pew and shot himself in the right temple.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives face a monumentous task as they start reviewing more
than 70 witness statements to document where everyone was sitting,
what they saw, what they heard and who they saw die, Krey said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also are awaiting toxicology reports from Ashbrook's
autopsy.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives interviewed four of the more seriously injured
victims on Tuesday after physicians said they were well enough to
be questioned, Krey said.
</P>
<P>
   Homicide Detective Curt Brannan, whose duty the night of the
shooting was to interview victims who could talk, said nearly
everyone believed the shooting spree to be part of a skit.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the exception of those who saw him walk in and pull
the pistol. ... The picture I immediately gained was all were in
total disbelief of the reality of this,'' Brannan said. ``There was
a lot of confusion, not all heard the explosion'' of the pipe bomb
Ashbrook threw down an aisle toward the front of the sanctuary, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who did see him come in described him raising the front
of his shirt, pulling out the handgun and start shooting at people
outside in the hallway sitting on the couch,'' Brannan said.
</P>
<P>
   None of the witnesses recognized Ashbrook or knew of any
connection between him and the church or any church member, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Receipts found in Ashbrook's belongings indicate that leading up
to the shooting, he had gone to a Home Depot store every day since
March, a federal official said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The official, who did not want to be identified, said Ashbrook
made a purchase during each visit to the hardware warehouse store
to get items as small as a few nuts and bolts to larger items such
as hand tools.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept this log'' meticulously recording each purchase, the
official said, adding, ``He apparently liked Home Depot.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the purchases was for the concrete mix Ashbrook poured
down his toilet, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   (Staff Writer Jack Douglas Jr. contributed to this report.)
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
