<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PRACTICE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RYDER STARS AWE THE CROWD _ AND IT'S ALL IN FUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ The spectators in the bleachers to the right
of the sixth tee prepared for fun. Back down the fairway, nearly
300 yards away, three launchers were tucked away in a tee box that
can comfortably fit four golfers, four golf bags, and four caddies
(though a shoe horn is recommended).
</P>
<P>
   It was a practice round and the crowd couldn't care less about
putting for dough. They wanted Phil Mickelson, David Duval, and
Tiger Woods to drive for show. All right, said the players, it's
show time. Titanium, please.
</P>
<P>
   But first, Mark O'Meara was allowed to hit and he calmly slapped
an iron into the middle of the fairway.
</P>
<P>
   Formalities aside and with serious competition still days away,
the players obliged. Though, quite honestly, they were using a
practice round for what it is intended _ seeing what they can do
and what they can't.
</P>
<P>
   Duval crushed first, his drive splitting the fairway and coming
to rest a mere 10-15 yards shy of the green. Ho-hum. A mere 285.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson slammed one that went right, into rough above a
bunker. Not bad, but not what the fans wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Next up, Woods. The hole measures 310 yards but in a flash
Woods's drive rocketed out of the chute. ``Left,'' he yelled, and
the crowd on the hill next to the green moved quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Mickelson wanted another go at it and he drilled one high into
the sky. It landed softly on the right side of the green and the
crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   Not to be outdone, Woods blasted another, but this time it drew
a straight line to the center of the green. It hit at the front of
the green and rolled back onto the fringe. Mission accomplished.
The crowd roared again, and as they left the tee, the young and
talented trio laughed heartily.
</P>
<P>
   It was a far cry from a month ago when these four players and
the Ryder Cup seemed as compatible as a Hollywood marriage. But the
compensation issue that scarred the PGA Championship _ during a
week in which US captain Ben Crenshaw said he was disappointed in
Woods, O'Meara, Duval, and Mickelson _ is ``ancient history,''
according to Jeff Maggert, and the matter at hand is golf.
</P>
<P>
   So golf it was under gray skies, with the 12 Europeans going off
in three foursomes, followed by three groups of Americans. It was
noteworthy that Colin Montgomerie and Paul Lawrie, both Scotsmen,
were with Darren Clarke and Lee Westwood, best friends who are
considered a lock as a pairing.
</P>
<P>
   Then came Jose Maria Olazabal and Miguel Angel Jimenez, another
team that seems certain. With Jesper Parnevik in a group with
Sergio Garcia, it appeared as if James had pretty much shown his
opening lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Or had he?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you think maybe I was pairing them together to mislead you?
Pull a complete pranker on the press? I'm dealing with some devious
people here.''
</P>
<P>
   Like virtually everyone else on campus Tuesday, James was having
fun. That goes for the players, because back at the sixth hole
Woods &AMP; Co. had arrived on the green. The gallery on the hill to
the left of the pin had made room for Woods, at least just enough
room for him to squeeze in with his lob wedge.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to play that one, Tiger,'' said a spectator.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' said Woods, grinning, ``we're playing a match,'' well
aware that O'Meara had drilled a wedge to within 2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   So Woods calmly stood over a shot that not a handful of people
in the world could have executed, a flop off hard pan to a green
sloping away from him. Somehow, Woods slid his club under the ball,
popped it in the air, and landed it just on the green. It came to
rest a few feet from the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the crowd roared.
</P>
<P>
   Duval had a flip wedge into the green and Mickelson gave a nod
of approval to his second drive, for which the crowd again offered
its appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   All of which led to speculation that perhaps Crenshaw was
tipping his hand, that perhaps Woods and Duval, or Woods and
Mickelson, or Mickelson and Duval _ you know, long guns together _
were being auditioned.
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw wouldn't budge. He saw eight of his team members play
here Aug. 30, ``and I saw the formation of a couple of thoughts for
certain teams. They may go out again tomorrow. We're going to talk
about it late this afternoon and maybe after the dinner tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   No rush. There are two more days of practice. Two more days to
grab those seats next to the sixth green. Though Scott Dickinson of
Newburyport was quite happy not to be sitting. He was one of those
who made room for Woods to hit his wedge shot, and as the world's
greatest golfer headed to the seventh tee, someone in the crowd
begged of Woods: ``Hey, Tiger, how about that ball we threw down
for you?''
</P>
<P>
   Woods chuckled, then tossed them the ball, which Dickinson
caught. Yes, it had ``Tiger Woods'' imprinted on it.
</P>
<P>
   Will he put it into play? ``No way,'' said Dickinson. ``It's
going right in the trophy case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
