<HEADLINE>
EUROPEANS GIVE THE COURSE THE TWICE OVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Slow play at a practice round? Well, with
Europeans involved, on a course they are barely familiar with, it
happened. The foursome of Sergio Garcia, Jesper Parnevik, Andrew
Coltart, and Jean Van de Velde took their time navigating The
Country Club layout, hitting second and third shots while
evaluating the course from every angle.
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to drive the US contingency of Tiger Woods, David
Duval, Phil Mickelson, and Mark O'Meara to skip some holes. Instead
of remaining behind the Europeans on the ninth hole, the foursome
skipped to No. 14 and finished their round before retiring to the
locker room. After lunch, Woods and Duval returned to the course to
play holes 9-13.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Best left unseen
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   European captain Mark James was asked why he stopped watching
the Lee Westwood-Darren Clarke pairing. Was it a good or bad sign?
``(Westwood) must have thought it was bad because Lee and Darren
birdied four of the last five.'' . . . Some of James's predecessors
have also made the trip to Brookline. Former captain Tony Jacklin
(four teams) is in the Boston area, and Bernard Gallacher (three)
was on site Tuesday, preparing for his NBC analyst job . . . Van de
Velde, the Frenchman who had the British Open won before collapsing
with a triple-bogey at the 18th hole, had no such closing woes
Tuesday. From a greenside bunker, Van de Velde holed out for a
birdie on 18 . . . After teeing off on the 15th, Colin Montgomerie
joined his father, James, off the fairway and went for a walk in
the woods . . . Butch Harmon, Woods's swing coach, also works with
Clarke and spent a lengthy time with Jose Maria Olazabal on the
driving range to work out some problems.
</P>
</TEXT>
