<SLUG> BC-CAHNERS-RESIGN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAHNERS INFORMATION UNIT CHIEF OUT AMID   DROPING PROFITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ Cahners Business Information chief executive
Bruce Barnet stepped down from the Newton trade publisher last
week, apparently under pressure from the company's British-Dutch
parent.
</P>
<P>
   Like other trade publishers, Cahners has faced big profit
declines recently due to growing competition from Internet-based
media. Last month Cahners said it would restructure and lay off 300
people, mostly at operations in Illinois and Pennsylvania.
</P>
<P>
   Now Barnet has joined the exodus, leaving ``to pursue other
investment and business opportunities,'' according to Tom Nutile, a
spokesman for Cahners, a unit of Reed Elsevier PLC, whose
headquarters are in London and Amsterdam.
</P>
<P>
   Sources familiar with the matter said Reed Elsevier's new chief
executive, Crispin Davis, sought the change because of concerns
about Cahners' profits, which fell 45 percent for the first six
months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, these sources said, Cahners had failed to
capitalize on its combination with trade magazines from the Chilton
publishing group, which Reed Elsevier purchased from Walt Disney
Co. for $447 million in 1997. Barnet was ``just not meeting his
numbers,'' said one Cahners employee familiar with the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Barnet, a Time Inc. veteran who joined Cahners three years ago,
didn't return telephone calls and messages seeking comment. But
others who worked with him said he wanted to devote more resources
to on-line publishing ventures than Davis would authorize.
</P>
<P>
   London-based executives at Reed Elsevier couldn't be reached for
comment Tuesday. ``We wish Bruce well in his future endeavors,''
Davis said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   Nutile said Barnet's job is being filled ``for the time being''
by Brian Nairn, Cahners chief operating officer, who had overseen
operations in its offices in Des Plaines, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Nutile declined to elaborate on whether the company would
consider other candidates for the top job. Davis has said he won't
outline the company's broader restructuring plans until next
spring. A sale of Cahners is also a possibility, as is a move of
the unit's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Nairn had previously overseen some of Cahners' largest
publishing groups, including those aimed at the electronics and
manufacturing industries.
</P>
<P>
   In August Cahners reported revenue of $442 million for the first
six months of the year, a 2 percent decline compared to the same
period in 1998. Operating profit fell 45 percent, Cahners said,
though it didn't break out the exact figures. It attributed the
drop to an unanticipated slowdown in sales growth.
</P>
<P>
   The results also reflected Cahners' heavy spending to market its
own content on the Web, said analyst Philip Olesen, executive
director at Warburg Dillon Reed in New York.
</P>
<P>
   While those expenses may have staved off gains by other
competitors, they haven't led to much new advertising revenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's where the Web has really hurt them already,'' Olesen
said. But the Web also represents an opportunity for the company,
he said, if Cahners can ``distinguish itself with proprietary,
must-have industry information'' on its network of Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Cahners didn't announce Barnet's departure, which was first
reported Friday by the New York Post. Other talent leaving Cahners
includes Brian Kardon, formerly senior marketing vice-president who
has joined the HomePortfolio.com consumer Web site, and Susan Rice,
Cahners senior vice-president for human resources, who has told
colleagues she will leave at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Cahners' best-known magazines include the Hollywood trade
journal Daily Variety, and Publishers Weekly in New York. The
company has about 550 employees in Newton, where it produces some
of its 128 trade journals such as Electronic Business, Design News
and Test &AMP; Measurement World.
</P>
<P>
   The Newton office was relatively unaffected by the latest round
of job cuts, losing just 27 positions; deeper cuts came at Cahners
units in Radnor, Pa. and in Illinois.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
