<HEADER>
A0683 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-PINETOPS-COX     09-21 1042
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-PINETOPS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. flooding 'like water from a bathtub'
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINETOPS, N.C. _ The swirling black water had receded enough
Tuesday for Albert Reid to go back home, back to the place where he
almost drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Five of his neighbors died Thursday in Hurricane Floyd's rising
flood waters. Another, a 5-year-old girl, is missing and presumed
dead in the snaky underbrush of Town Creek, still too deep for
rescuers.
</P>
<P>
   It was one of the worst tragedies spawned by Floyd last week as
it plowed up the East Coast. Some rivers are just now cresting in
North Carolina, proof that, in this storm, water was more deadly
than hurricane-force winds.
</P>
<P>
   East of Pinetops, a motor boat attempting to carry a dozen
people to safety overturned. In Thursday's early morning, the
torrent carried half of them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, I thought about a lot of things under that water,'' Reid,
64, said Tuesday as he walked past his flood-ravaged home, past a
dead horse, past the cedar tree where his wife, Mary, clung in the
branches until she was rescued after the boat capsized.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-rising waters covered all but the rooftops in the
neighborhood of Dodge City in Edgecombe County, so badly damaged it
warranted a visit Monday from President Clinton. Here in Pinetops,
where mobile homes and stately homes interrupt acre upon acre of
water-logged tobacco and cotton, residents have begun venturing out
from the elementary-school emergency shelter as far as the
retreating waters will allow.
</P>
<P>
   Along Town Creek, a Tar River tributary, the surge uprooted oaks
and sycamores and tossed around metallic propane gas tanks like
balloons. A jumble of logs and branches blocked Bynum Farm Road,
where rescuers spray-painted red Xs over front doors to signal that
they already had searched for survivors.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, water covered the heads of Jesus and his disciples,
portrayed in a tapestry tacked above the sanctuary door of St.
Stevenson Holy Church of Deliverance. Inside the dark hall, the
water overturned pews and the pulpit, swelled the red-carpeted
floor and perched a foot stool atop the door of the pastor's study.
</P>
<P>
   The receding waters left a smelly, chocolate-brown residue on
the tile floor of what once was a cheerfully painted daycare center
at the rear of the church. Diapers and toiler paper were among the
debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were floating in here like inside a big aquarium,''
said Glen Williams, 37, a church deacon.
</P>
<P>
   The stench of dead livestock hung in the air, seemingly pressed
down by the low gray clouds that dumped more rain Tuesday on top of
Floyd's torrential rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's downpour swelled rivers faster than people in
low-lying areas could escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden it came out like water pouring from a
bathtub,'' said Roosevelt Lewis, 70, throwing out corn Tuesday to
what remains of his chicken flock in Dodge City. He and his
brother, Milton, lost 55 goats and five horses_Diamond, Missy, Two
Step, Blackie and J.R. One was stuck in a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, police blocked the entrance to Dodge City except to
property owners and rescuers whose search for 5-year-old Teshika
Vines has turned from rescue to recovery.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Carlos Vines, won't stop looking in emergency
shelters until he knows for sure whether his daughter is dead.
Volunteer fireman Mike Stallings fears that she is. What's
uncertain is where she is.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities confirmed the deaths of five: Carlos Vines' wife,
Keisha; her parents, Ben and Vivian Mayo; and neighborhood children
Cabrina and Destiny Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for hope in the tragedy, the Rev. Carolyn Slade, St.
Stevenson's pastor, pointed to a teal-green cinderblock house. The
rising waters trapped 11 people in the attic, and all were rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that we pulled 200 to 300 people to safety,'' said
Stallings, a member of the South Edgecombe volunteer fire
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the Lord giveth and taketh away,'' Slade said. ``But
we were not prepared for this. It hurts, it really hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, when Floyd veered toward the North Carolina coast,
residents of Dodge City braced for winds, but not for rain.
</P>
<P>
   Before he went to bed last Wednesday, Albert Reid moved his two
Cadillacs and Mazda pickup truck out from under the pine trees in
his yard. He didn't want to risk falling branches denting them.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't sleep that night, anticipating howling winds that
never came. He was surprised at dusk by the water rising from Town
Creek behind his house. He cranked his pickup, but it stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Reid went back inside and told his wife they'd have to wait for
a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Ben Mayo was ferrying neighbors to safety in his
flat-bottomed aluminum boat. On a return trip to the flooding
subdivision, Mayo picked up Reid and his wife, bringing the number
of passengers to 12.
</P>
<P>
   As the boat rode against the swift current, Mayo gunned the
motor, and the bow popped up in the air. Water poured in the back,
and the boat turned over with its hull bobbing above water.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped underneath, Reid bobbed up and down, gasping for breath,
until he was able to get out from under the boat. In the half
light, he remembers two or three children clinging to the hull. He
had lost track of his wife and his step-daughter when another man
tossed him a rope attached to the boat and told him to wrap it
around a utility pole.
</P>
<P>
   The boat stopped, and Reid escaped into a nearby house with
several others. As the water rose, they climbed into the attic,
hoping for rescuers who arrived several hours later in a boat.
</P>
<P>
   They retrieved the people in the house and Reid's wife and her
daughter from a nearby cedar tree. Over the weekend, searchers
found the bodies of five victims. Officials returned Mayo's boat to
the carport of his dark empty house, at the edge of the dense woods
where they believed the current swept 5-year-old Teshika.
</P>
<P>
   Reid remembers seeing her drifting away, across Annie Mae Ellis'
front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get her,'' Reid said, ``but she was too far
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Chris Burritt writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
