<SLUG> BC-FALN-CLEMENCY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEFENDS CLEMENCY DECISION IN LETTER TO HOUSE PANEL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (Eds.: See optional trims) 
 
By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton tried Tuesday to blunt criticism
of his clemency offer to 16 radical Puerto Rican separatists,
saying he was motivated by the prisoners' lengthy sentences,
numerous pleas for leniency and not by politics.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to House members investigating the militants' early
release, Clinton defended his Aug. 11 decision, saying it was based
on the merits of each case and the timing was dictated by the
departure of former White House counsel Charles Ruff.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, the question ... was whether the prisoners' sentences
were unduly severe and whether their continuing incarceration
served any meaningful purpose,'' the president wrote, noting that
their prison-time ranged from 35 to 90 years.
</P>
<P>
   The president's five-page letter, read aloud during a House
Government Reform Committee hearing, was not his first explanation
of what factored into his clemency decision, but it is his most
detailed and fullest to date. It drew immediate criticism from
victims of bombing attacks attributed to the Puerto Rican
separatists, known by the acronym FALN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is going to commute my sentence?'' asked Richard
Pastorella, a former New York police officer who was blinded and
lost the fingers of his right hand and the feeling in his left when
a bomb exploded in 1982 outside police headquarters. The FALN
claimed responsibility for the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been bearing this cross for 17 years,'' Pastorella said.
``I'll never be free of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Connor, a banker whose father was killed in a FALN bombing
in 1975, called Clinton's explanation ``an affront.'' The
president's letter ``is not only weak, but (it) insults the
intelligence of the American people who obviously know that (the
clemency offer) was done for political purposes,'' Connor told the
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Acknowledging that clemency was opposed by federal prosecutors
and the FBI, Clinton's letter Tuesday said he followed Ruff's
guidance. ``His recommendation and my decision were based on our
view of the merits of the requests,'' the president said.
``Political considerations played no role in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   The president's letter was delivered less than a week after he
notified the committee that he was invoking executive privilege and
would not provide Congress access to documents and testimony from
high-level administration officials involved in the clemency.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to citing the president's limited right to
confidentiality of communications with aides, the White House
argued that Congress has no oversight over the president's
constitutional authority to grant clemency.
</P>
<P>
   The clemency information had been subpoenaed by the committee,
whose inquiry was triggered by criticism that the clemency offer
was made to help first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton's anticipated
bid for the Senate in New York. The state is home to about 1.3
million Puerto Rican expatriates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those offered clemency claimed membership in FALN _ the
Spanish abbreviation for the Armed Forces of National Liberation.
The group was blamed for 130 bombing of U.S. civilian and military
targets between 1974 and 1983. Six people were killed in the
attacks and dozens were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Of those offered clemency, 14 accepted and two declined. Eleven
were paroled two weeks ago, another has five more years to serve
before he is eligible for parole and two had their fines reduced.
</P>
<P>
   The FALN members _ who were tried almost a decade before
Congress enacted anti-terrorism laws in 1990 _ were convicted of
seditious conspiracy and possession of weapons and explosives. Most
had been behind bars for nearly 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Among the people urging their release were former President
Carter, South African Archbishop Desmond Tutu, several members of
Congress and Coretta Scott King, widow of slain civil rights leader
the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, which was addressed to Rep. Henry Waxman,
D-Calif., Clinton reminded committee members that he required the
prisoners to renounce violence as a condition of clemency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of those who supported unconditional clemency for the
prisoners argued that they were political prisoners who acted out
of sincere political beliefs. I rejected this argument,'' Clinton
wrote. ``No form of violence is ever justified as a means of
political expression in a democratic society based on the rule of
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our society believes, however, that a punishment should fit
the crime,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to counter Clinton's claim that none of the Puerto Rican
nationals had been involved in violent crimes, committee Chairman
Dan Burton, R-Ind., began Tuesday's hearing with a grainy videotape
from the FBI showing two of the militants making a letter bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Burton then cited court records indicating that four of the
militants had been arrested in connection with an armored car
holdup in Connecticut and were allied with a group that killed a
San Juan police officer, ambushed a Navy school bus killing two
sailors, and shot an Army officer at Fort Buchanan in Puerto Rico.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burton said one of the nationalists who turned down the clemency
offer had 15 years tacked onto his sentence after he was found
guilty of planning a violent prison break and ordering a slaying by
his confederates.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the president know about this man before he offered to let
him out of prison?'' Burton asked. ``The American people believe
the time has come to put these people away and not let them back on
the streets.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(END OPTIONAL TRIM) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Burton and other Republicans on the committee, along with
several witnesses, said Clinton's decision sends the wrong message
about U.S. policy toward terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pray to God this will not start a new reign of terror,''
said Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Gallagher, the FBI's assistant director for national
security, said the militants freed by Clinton ``are criminals, and
they are terrorists, and they represent a threat to the United
States.'' The administration had blocked Gallagher from testifying
at similar hearings last week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the panel released a letter from FBI Director Louis
Freeh saying that he had warned the Justice Department that
releasing any of the prisoners ``would likely return committed,
experienced, sophisticated and hardened terrorists to the
clandestine movement'' for Puerto Rican independence.
</P>
<P>
   In correspondence with House Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry
Hyde, R-Ill., Freeh said his agency has opposed release of the FALN
members and had restated that position as recently as June 28,
about six weeks before Clinton's clemency offer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
