<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-0922-COX     09-21 1118
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-0922-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RESCUERS HUNT FOR 3,000 BURIED TAIWANESE AFTER KILLER QUAKE
 &HT;    800&AMP;ADD
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAICHUNG, Taiwan _ Rescuers worked frantically into a second,
critical day Wednesday to uncover an estimated 3,000 people who may
still be buried alive in the ruins of a massive earthquake that
killed more than 1,770 people and smashed entire mountain towns in
central Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Concrete lay buckled and ripped as though a giant claw had
slashed it in the hardest hit neighborhood in Taichung, the
third-largest city on Taiwan. Apartment buildings were splintered
into giant crumbs of concrete and the earth had heaved into a new
hillock.
</P>
<P>
   Along one small street where scores perished, more than 200
survivors spent the night on blankets on an outdoor basketball
court of the Taiwan army's Dakuan Supply Base, a few hundreds yards
from the ruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're too afraid to sleep inside,'' said Capt. Lee Tai Shen,
showing an almost vacant, temporary dormitory the soldiers had
created by giving up their own bunks. With most survivors sleeping
on hard concrete outside, fewer than a dozen people, mostly women
and children, had bunched themselves fully clothed on bunkbeds in
one corner of the room. Ranks of other available beds stood crisply
made and empty.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tried to rescue the people around here last night,'' Lee
said, describing how his troops ran out to the devastation just
after the temblor jolted the northern half of Taiwan awake at 1:47
a.m. (local time) Tuesday. They managed to save 60-70 people, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   This was the island's second deadliest earthquake after a 1935
tremor at a magnitude of 7.4 killed 3,276 Taiwanese. Every year
Taiwan trembles under the influence of dozens of earthquakes
because it sits on the western edge of the Pacific ``Rim of Fire,''
where the Philippine tectonic plate smashes against the Eurasian
land mass that historically spawned steep mountains, volcanoes and
earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
   Just in this one neighborhood hundreds were injured, a part of
the more than 4,400 injuries reported island-wide by the Interior
Ministry's disaster management center.
</P>
<P>
   Another six shelters were set up in this area alone, and
hundreds of schools and other buildings were converted to makeshift
housing across the island for the 100,000 Taiwanese left homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of thousands refused the aid, however, preferring to
sleep outside or in small, open-front shops Tuesday night, from
which they could escape quickly if need be. In one such shop, a
family of three spread blankets on chairs clustered together like a
queen-sized bed to wait out the dark night.
</P>
<P>
   Electric power remained nonexistent Wednesday morning for about
4 million Taiwanese families, although more than a million
households had electricity restored, mostly in the area of the
capital city Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   With a population exceeding 100,000, Taichung city lies at the
periphery of the most extensive damage that radiates from the
quake's epicenter to the southeast. At a town called Puli near the
epicenter, 95 percent of the buildings were reported wrecked. That
area has been practically inaccessible except by helicopter, its
roads mostly heaved into impassable ruins.
</P>
<P>
   Near Puli, bodies were reported piling up in roadside tents,
after morgues and hospitals were filled. Radio reports said there
was urgent need for refrigeration in the late summer heat, to keep
bodies from decomposing.
</P>
<P>
   Appeals for blood, medical supplies, bottled water and
bulldozers came from the hardest hit communities there near the
center of the shockwave that registered 7.6 on the Richter scale,
according to the U.S. Geological Survey. Taiwan's Central Weather
Bureau put the quake at the 7.3 level.
</P>
<P>
   Seismologist Yi Men Wu warned that ``very strong'' aftershocks
could be in store, as high as 6.5 in the coming two weeks. He said
there already had been 1,280 aftershocks as of 9 p.m. (local time)
Tuesday, but only 28 were severe enough to be felt.
</P>
<P>
   A serious aftershock registering 6.8 rattled the island on
Wednesday morning and had its epicenter in this same central region
hit worst by Tuesday's quake.
</P>
<P>
   Already disaster teams started arriving Tuesday from Japan and
Singapore, and the United States dispatched two military aircraft
with about 70 rescue staff and sniffer dogs. Also en route was a
Turkish search and rescue team that had saved 200 people from the
earthquake that shattered Turkey last month.
</P>
<P>
   China's President Jiang Zemin put aside the searing dispute that
has rattled relations between the mainland and this island of 22
million the Chinese government calls a breakaway province.
</P>
<P>
   The disaster ``hurt the hearts of people on the mainland, as the
Chinese people on both sides of the Taiwan strait are as closely
linked as flesh and blood,'' he said. China's Red Cross promised to
send $100,000 worth of disaster aid and $60,000 worth of relief
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's leadership, which set off the latest round in the
50-year feud when it distanced itself from the notion of a single
China by declaring the two governments should have ``special
state-to-state relations,'' expressed cautious thanks.
</P>
<P>
   ``This would be a good beginning to improving ties,'' Su Chi,
chair of the Taiwan Mainland Affairs Council.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Taiwan's damage appeared less severe than the widespread
destruction in Turkey, where a 7.3 level earthquake killed more
than 15,000 people. Buildings here, especially around the island's
main north-south geological fault line, have been solidly built out
of concrete.
</P>
<P>
   Recent rapid development, however, has produced complaints of
builders ignoring construction codes and bribing building officials
to wink at inferior construction. That may have contributed to the
collapse of select buildings, especially in Taipei, while adjacent
structures stood fast.
</P>
<P>
   In Taipei, where major damage was limited to a scattering of
buildings and a bridge, life already was beginning to return to
normal. Many offices and schools, including the American School of
Taiwan, announced they were reopening their doors Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The American Institute in Taiwan, the U.S. government's
unofficial embassy on the island, had sent personnel to this
central Taiwan area to monitor needs and relay the requests for
help to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never had this big of an earthquake here,'' said Kevin
Huang, 25, as he stood in line to rent an electric generator in
suburban Taipei. ``We thought we were safe.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
