<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIMOR-VIOLENCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EAST TIMORESE OFFER CAUTIOUS WELCOME TO PEACEKEEPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DILI, Indonesia _ Monday this impoverished, seaside capital was
an eerie and unrelenting vision of ruin: row after row of buildings
and vehicles scorched beyond repair, streets empty of cars, people
nowhere to be found except huddled nervously in a giant makeshift
tarpaulin camp by the port.
</P>
<P>
   But Tuesday, the second day that United Nations-approved
peacekeepers poured into this island territory armed with a mandate
to use force if needed to halt the bloody backlash against the
winners of an Aug. 30 vote for independence, Dili began _ almost
magically _ to spring back to life.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since Sept. 4, when a landslide popular vote
to separate from Indonesia was announced, unleashing a savage
revenge campaign by militias backed by Indonesian security forces,
terrified men who were targeted for death emerged from their hiding
places in the hills. Women, children and the elderly, meanwhile,
spilled onto Dili's streets to celebrate a new beginning for their
would-be nation.
</P>
<P>
   Children clapped and cheered as scores of heavily armed
Australian commandos strode in formation down both sides of Dili's
main street Tuesday, their eyes darting back and forth for enemies,
but encountering only grateful smiles, friendly waves and eager
cries of ``Hello mister!'' One man threw himself to his knees and
raised cupped hands heavenward to a convoy of Australian armored
personnel carriers that cruised central Dili.
</P>
<P>
   The multinational force has had a surprisingly smooth entry
considering that militia leaders had warned that they were
``thirsty for the blood of white people'' and would target
Australians for meddling in Indonesia's affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the troops got an effusive emotional reception from
thousands of people here and in the mountain redoubt of Dare _ a
welcome perhaps most striking for what it revealed about the
undaunted spirit of East Timorese who favor independence.
</P>
<P>
   The ``nation'' is in tatters _ infrastructure gutted, homes,
farms and shops destroyed, and thousands of people feared dead. Yet
people said their commitment to freedom is even stronger now, and
the arrival of foreign troops and the departure of Indonesian ones
is the first step in securing that goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's only been two or three hours that I've seen young men on
the streets. They've all been hidden for two weeks at least,''
cried a delighted Maria de Fatima, 32, a social worker. She said
displaced people squatting at Dili's port shared their limited food
with the men who came down from the hills Tuesday, because many in
the mountains were in danger of starving.
</P>
<P>
   Some separatist rebels ventured down from the hills to see the
international force for themselves, and rejoiced by showing their
flag and singing songs before returning, said a young sympathizer
who was with them.
</P>
<P>
   As for the militias, most residents say the last ones left
Monday. ``But the main worry of the people here is not the
militias, but the military,'' said de Fatima. ``The militias are
just the curtains; the army is behind it all.''
</P>
<P>
   With the supposed withdrawal of 80 percent of the Indonesian
troops in the territory, the terror and suspicion created by the
soldiers seemed to be abating. The remaining Indonesian troops _
until now, cruel adversaries of independence supporters _ were
suddenly friendly Tuesday, smiling at local residents venturing out
for the first time in weeks and waving at foreign journalists
retunring to the decimated city.
</P>
<P>
   As the people around here cheerfully hailed a passing truckload
of crimson-bereted Indonesian naval officers, de Fatima became
incensed, spitting out bitterly, ``Those are the same troops who
broke into my clinic on the 10th of September and destroyed all my
medicines.''
</P>
<P>
   Others have not forgotten the recent horrors, of course, and
some of the mutual friendliness may be protective camouflage on
both sides. Indonesian soldiers don't want to be caught inciting
violence once peackeepers arrive, and ordinary people who survived
this month's bloodshed don't want to stand out in the crowd if
Indonesian troops turn nasty again.
</P>
<P>
   Already, though, some of that camouflage has faded away. A
father of two who used to don a militia t-shirt to avoid being
targeted as an independence supporter cheerfully pointed out that
he is now proudly wearing a t-shirt with the face of Xanana Gusmao,
the longtime Timorese resistance leader.
</P>
<P>
   For some here, though, the peacekeepers are a welcome sight, but
too belated. Antonia Carvalho, 40, is a mother of eight whose
husband was slain by militias on Sept. 4.
</P>
<P>
   Forced from her home, she now has no food, clean clothes or
medicine, and her 3-year-old daughter is dying in a squatters camp
at a burned-out hotel. ``I am glad for everyone else that the
troops are here,'' Carvalho said quietly, ``but my husband is
already dead, so they are too late for me.''
</P>
<P>
   A ride through Dili and its adjacent communities paints a
sobering portrait of how methodical the militia- and
military-sponsored destruction seems to have been, and just how
long it may take to rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   The home of Nobel Peace Lauriate Bishop Carlos Ximenes Belo was
blackened by fire, the roof missing and a gaping hole in the wall
exposing a Virgin Mary statue inside.
</P>
<P>
   Running water, telephones and electricity are almost impossible
to find now. The acrid, nose-burning stench of recent fires and
smoldering ashes hangs over several streets.
</P>
<P>
   Graffiti is everywhere, even on furniture abandoned on the road.
``Autonomy tragedy'' said one message, referring to the decisive
vote for autonomy under Indonesian rule or separation. ``Mission
impossible,'' declared another, an apparent reference to the tough
task for foreign peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Australian Army Corporal Peter Condie, 28, who was at the front
of a platoon that marched into the decimated downtown, was neither
surprised by the destruction, nor by the warm welcome he received
from locals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supporting the entire idea of their having
independence,'' Convie said, adding quickly, ``Well, I can only
speak for myself.''
</P>
<P>
   It is precisely that perceived bias among peacekeepers that
grates on the government and nationalists in Jakarta, where shots
were fired at the Australian Embassy. In Medan, Indonesia's third
largest city, student protesters stormed the Australian Consulate,
burned its flag along with an American one, and raised an
Indonesian flag.
</P>
<P>
   In Dili, troops met no resistance, disarming and detaining six
civilians for carrying weapons. Shots were fired near the heliport,
a command-post for the international force, but no assailant was
caught.
</P>
<P>
   In the nearby mountain area of Dare, where 50,000 people fled
the violence in Dili, 2,000 people, some with tears of relief,
greeted the returning UN mission chief and his UN military escort
as saviors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Long live East Timor,'' and ``Viva independencia!'' chanted
the refugees who had fled to the hills, most of them men in their
20s to 40s.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the UN people come, we are very, very happy,'' declared
Sernao Gomes, 28, a university student who has been hiding in the
jungle for 16 days, eating rice and wild plants. As for the
militias, he said confidently, ``I think they will be finished.
Militias are just tools of the military.''
</P>
<P>
   And yet, Gomes, admitted, ``every night we still hear the sound
of shooting, so we are still afraid.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
