u a BC-FLOODS-HARVEY-COX     09-21 0683
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-HARVEY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Harvey makes his mark on Florida
 &HT;    By Clay Lambert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Last week, Hurricane Floyd spared Palm
Beach County by taking a fortuitous turn to the north. Tuesday,
Tropical Storm Harvey drooped south of its projected course,
leaving Palm Beach County residents twice lucky and relatively dry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The primary reason is a fairly strong cold front rolling
through Alabama and Mississippi,'' said David Kosier, a National
Weather Service meteorologist in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   That cold front may have warmed the hearts of the water-logged
from Boca Raton north, but it didn't leave a dry eye anywhere from
Miami south to Key West. Particularly hard hit were people on the
west coast. Weather watchers in Naples reported over 10 inches of
rain Tuesday, according to the National Weather Service.
</P>
<P>
   The storm was expected to curve slightly northeast as it left an
exit wound somewhere in Broward or Miami-Dade. It will also pick up
speed, Kosier said. He predicted Harvey would roll ashore on Grand
Bahama Island this morning.
</P>
<P>
   What's next?
</P>
<P>
   Kosier said that we can all expect sunshine on the horizon.
Hurricane Gert is no threat to the eastern U.S. coast, and nothing
else is brewing in the tropics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like we'll get back to normal sunshine and afternoon
showers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a steady weakening as it passed over South Florida,
Harvey still managed to cause some trouble. As it moved inland,
passing over Everglades City by late afternoon, it left streets in
the small fishing village under two feet of water and spawned flood
warnings in Miami-Dade and Monroe counties.
</P>
<P>
   In Palm Beach County, there were a few minor showers and a
little wind, but nothing else.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had some strong winds _ about 15 to 20 mph,'' said Palm
Beach International Airport spokeswoman Lisa Waters. ``The tower
had some gusts.''
</P>
<P>
   But airport operations have not been affected due to Harvey, she
said. Two commuter flights to Tampa were cancelled Tuesday morning,
but other flights were running on schedule, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some flights from PBIA to the Bahamas were cancelled, but that
was a holdover from Hurricane Floyd _ not a result of Harvey, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   On the western side of the peninsula, where the storm made
landfall, things were wetter. More than 10 inches of rain fell in
parts of Collier County, according to the National Weather Service
in Miami. A number of secondary streets were closed due to high
water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had up to 30 homes and businesses suffer some
flooding,'' said Ken Pineau, director of the Collier County
Emergency Operations Center in Naples. Monday night, almost 50 cars
in the Naples area were disabled because of the water.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey dropped much lesser amounts of rain in other counties,
with about an inch falling in Miami-Dade and Broward by
mid-afternoon and more later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   Schools closed for the day in the Keys, St. Lucie, Collier and
Lee counties, mostly out of concern for localized street flooding.
</P>
<P>
   Tropical storm warnings were posted for Grand Bahama Island and
the Abacos in the northern Bahamas.
</P>
<P>
   Harvey, which formed late Sunday from a tropical depression in
the eastern Gulf of Mexico, had sustained winds at near 50 mph,
with higher gusts, when it made landfall, but weakened as it
crossed South Florida. Tropical storm force winds of at least 39
mph extended out 115 miles, mainly to the east of the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The center is not really well defined. It's just kind of a
raggedy system,'' said Stephen Baig, oceanographer at the National
Hurricane Center in Miami. ``Essentially, the southern peninsula of
Florida is going to get lots of rain and gusts.''
</P>
<P>
   Once over the Atlantic, Harvey should accelerate northeastward
during the next day or two and become absorbed by a cold front,
according to the hurricane center.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Lambert writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla. Lillian Weis contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
