<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-SCALPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALPERS FIND IT'S NOT SUCH A `HOT' TICKET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHIRA SPRINGER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ They are the unofficial greeters at the Ryder
Cup. No uniform comes with the job, but nervous twitches, constant
cell phone use and day-old stubble give the group away. Tuesday
just outside The Country Club, scalpers congregated along a metal
fence on Clyde Street. They welcomed visitors by asking, ``You
selling tickets?''
</P>
<P>
   The scalpers' pitch was met by both stares and questions. And
finally a few prospective customers. All sorts of deals were
proposed outside the main gate. The scalpers sought tickets for
Friday, Saturday, and Sunday _ the match play days. The spectators
wanted to swap practice days or sell tickets they couldn't use. But
by lunch time, business was so slow the scalpers used one of their
many village passes to get free meals.
</P>
<P>
   The Ryder Cup continues to be a lesson in supply and demand.
Tickets to the practice rounds: high supply, low demand,
unexpectedly low prices. Parking spaces: low supply, high demand,
exorbitantly high prices. Merchandise: high supply, high demand,
happy consumers.
</P>
<P>
   While fans walked away with bags full of golf sweaters, official
posters, and Ryder Cup Christmas ornaments _ and locals made a few
extra dollars _ the scalpers were left with pockets of unused
tickets. According to the would-be profiteers, two key factors
conspired to limit sales. First, many golf fans were not willing to
take public transportation to explore the market. They assumed a
scarcity of Ryder Cup tickets and didn't want to take the time.
Spectators who rely on scalpers always fear they won't get in.
Second, newspaper articles listed going rates for single-day
tickets ranging between $125-$650, which scared buyers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't give them away,'' said a scalper named John as he
tried unloading tickets to the practice rounds. ``Send me some
buyers. People can't get near the place to get tickets. They've got
to get on a bus. And they don't want to get on a bus to get
tickets. They always write it up like it's a big thing, but all
you've got to do is show up, just like any other event.''
</P>
<P>
   John, who asked that only his first name be used, offered
tickets to watch Tuesday's practice for $10 and $20. He refused to
take any tickets for today, believing rain would make them an even
harder sell. Tickets to the first public practice were in such
great supply that a spectator walked up to John and gave him three
grounds passes. The man thought he was giving the scalper a gift.
</P>
<P>
   The great fear among those outside the front gate was that
business would remain slow the rest of the week. From his first day
at the Ryder Cup, John sensed the only tickets worth anything
significant were those for the competition days. But even the
asking price for those tickets will be far less than anticipated.
They should not approach the $600 to $700 range. Based on Tuesday,
the scalpers felt $200 was a more accurate number.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who got them thought they were worth a fortune,'' said
John G. from LA. ``People held on to them. They wanted top dollar,
but demand has gone way down. We'll get $200 tops, but there's
always a pigeon paying more.''
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the professional scalpers had the best deals of
the day. Spectators who found themselves with an extra ticket at
the last minute tried to recoup their losses along Clyde and Newton
Streets. Inexperienced at the art of reselling tickets, they
flashed grounds passes in full view of Brookline Police officers.
Although scalping tickets is illegal in Massachusetts, the local
police in four instances focused on directing traffic rather than
stopping any exchange. In fact, a security guard assisting the
police, who declined to give his name, advised a woman in her 60s
on scalping tickets, telling her how it's done at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Rich Greene of Glastonbury, Conn., sat on a stone wall on Clyde
Street, hoping to sell extra passes to the practice rounds. He
bought a whole set a tickets through ebay.com. However, the deal
required that he purchase two tickets for each of the practice
dates. He sold a ticket for Thursday's session for $50, but by 11
a.m. his patience was waning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll take whatever I can get for them,'' said Greene, who
spent approximately $83 for each practice-day ticket. ``I'm not
trying to make a killing off them. I'm just trying to get some
money back and defray the cost. I probably overpaid for all of
them, but how many times can you go to the Ryder Cup?''
</P>
<P>
   Other spectators exhibited the same spare-no-expense attitude
with parking spaces. Despite tournament organizers' requests for
fans to take public transportation and keep traffic around The
Country Club to a minimum, some drove as close as they could. Then,
they searched for places to legally park. In one case, the price
for parking exceeded the price for tickets. The Exxon station at
the corner of Newton and Grove Streets charged $75 for the day. And
many motorists were happy to pay the fee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to pay,'' said John Mancini of East
Greenwich, R.I., as he sifted through a roll of $20 bills. ``We
don't ask questions. I figure whatever he (owner John Douros) says,
I'm going to pay.''
</P>
<P>
   By 10:30 a.m., the gas station lot was nearly full. Judging from
the number of parked cars and the inconvenience the Ryder Cup posed
for his business, Douros did not think he was overcharging.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm losing money because if it wasn't for the Ryder Cup, I'd
have 20 cars to repair today,'' he said. ``My customers are not
coming for gas because they are afraid of the traffic. I've got to
do what I've got to do to make up for some of the loses. At $75,
I'm losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   One mile up Newton Street, Marilyn and John Dalzell charged $30
per spot, the same price they posted during the 1988 US Open,
though the couple acknowledged they were considering a $10 price
raise. Even with the increase, its likely their driveway will
remain the best buy in Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Inside The Country Club, prices were high, but none of the fans
expected to find a bargain. They entered the Ryder Cup Golf Shop to
spend. And a line that stretched from the tent's entrance almost
back to the pro shop proved they would not be deterred.
</P>
<P>
   When the weekend golfers and Tiger Woods admirers entered the
20,000 square-foot shop, they were awed. Glassy-eyed fans toted
armloads of merchandise.
</P>
<P>
   At the Ryder Cup, value was in the eye of the beholder and not
in the hands of those left holding extra tickets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
