<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0375 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0697 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBN-FALCONS-DISCORD-C     09-21 1033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-DISCORD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons look to fly against winds of change
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Future NFL Hall of Fame running back Marcus Allen was
spotted at Hartsfield International Airport Tuesday morning, but he
wasn't on his way to try out for the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Calling up a retired legend like Allen isn't the way to replace
Jamal Anderson, whose season likely ended Monday night when he tore
the anterior cruciate ligament in his right knee.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Anderson's injury isn't the only reason the Falcons are
0-2. Quarterback Chris Chandler, for example, missed Monday's game
with a strained hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   After a run of negative events since the Falcons appeared in the
Super Bowl for the first time, just putting together back-to-back
winning seasons for the first times has become a very daunting
task.
</P>
<P>
   Many of these occurrences come as baggage for teams that
suddenly become winners. Coach Dan Reeves said Anderson's injury,
while a terrible blow, is part of pro football.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way life is,'' he said. ``You are going to have
adversity. The teams that handle it best are going to be the teams
that are in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson's absence isn't the only change.
</P>
<P>
   Last season was marked by a minimal number of serious injuries,
and the team's penchant for forcing and capitalizing on other
teams' mistakes while making few of its own.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the Falcons have a minus-five turnover ratio after
leading the NFL last year with a plus-20 mark.
</P>
<P>
   The first piece of bad news came the night before the Super
Bowl, when free safety Eugene Robinson was arrested for
solicitation.
</P>
<P>
   Within a month, Tony Martin, the team's leading receiver last
season, was released in connection with legal problems (he was
later cleared), and leading tackler Cornelius Bennett was released
in a cost-cutting move.
</P>
<P>
   Before the draft, the Falcons approached the Patriots about the
possibility of trading Anderson. Then, Atlanta traded next year's
first-round draft choice to Baltimore, and got the Ravens'
second-round choice, No. 42 overall.
</P>
<P>
   They selected Mississippi State tight end Reggie Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   As Anderson began training camp in a holdout, reserve running
back Gary Downs season ended on the second day with a serious right
knee injury.
</P>
<P>
   Then, the Falcons kept all four tight ends, one more than last
year, and just three running backs, one less than last year.
</P>
<P>
   After Anderson's injury, that became a problem.
</P>
<P>
   On the field, the Falcons can't hold onto the ball, turning it
over seven times already, setting up or accounting directly for 31
of the their opponents' 41 points.
</P>
<P>
   Off the field, the front office has taken steps to lock up some
potential free agents.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson got a five-year, $32 million contract, wide receiver
Terance Mathis a four-year, $12 million contract, and fullback Bob
Christian a five-year, $10 million deal.
</P>
<P>
   But the seven-year, $52.5 million contract signed by defensive
tackle Travis Hall is different.
</P>
<P>
   Hall had three years left on his current deal, and while he was
underpaid to begin with, Alan Herman, the agent for defensive end
Lester Archambeau said his client is underpaid, too.
</P>
<P>
   His $800,000 in salary is less than half the going rate for
starting defensive linemen.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, Herman said, Archambeau -- who led the team
last year with 10 sacks and seven forced fumbles along with 77
tackles -- is in the final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a disappointing negotiation as far as Lester is
concerned,'' Herman said. ``I'm not sure I'm clear on why you would
extend a player who has three years remaining when you have a
player like Lester who is up.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Age) has been an issue, but Terance Mathis is 32 as well.
Travis got a $5 million signing bonus, Terance a $3 million bonus.
Lester was not offered $3 million, and yet he's 32 years old, like
Terance. He's like the Rodney Dangerfield of the Falcons. He
doesn't get any respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year Atlanta had uncanny chemistry on the way to a 16-3
record. There by no means appears to be unrest in the locker room,
but nine starters who can become unrestricted or restricted free
agents are wondering if they will get new contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all know when each other's contracts are up,'' said
strong-side linebacker Henri Crockett, who can become a restricted
free agent after the season. ``But I don't think that's the
problem. Every player is different, though.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons thought they solved their long-standing problem at
backup quarterback when they signed former New York Giants starter
Danny Kanell to a two-year, $2.1 million contract.
</P>
<P>
   But he has been sloppy, and Tony Graziani has likewise been
erratic, although Reeves said the play of the offensive line has
had as much to do with the offensive meltdown as anything.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has been solid, though, and on the plus side,
Chandler may return for Sunday's game at St. Louis, and Atlanta is
19-5 when he starts and finishes a game.
</P>
<P>
   Also, parity is running rampant in a league where both Super
Bowl teams are 0-2, and the four teams that went to the conference
championship games last year are a combined 1-7.
</P>
<P>
   Three teams that began last season 0-2 -- the Jets, Bills and
Cardinals -- went on to earn playoff berths.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, the Falcons' division doesn't include any juggernauts.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the end is not here.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not so much a different vibe around here as we just got
to get on the same page,'' said right tackle Ephraim Salaam. ``I
only speak for the offensive side of the ball; the defense is
playing pretty good. We got to practice, practice, practice.''
</P>
<P>
   Or, as linebacker Keith Brooking said, ``We've got to keep our
heads up. We can accomplish the things we set out to do this year,
and that's to win the NFC West.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeves agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not going to get a lot of sympathy from anybody,'' he
said. ``People aren't really interested in anything other than
results.''
</P>
<P>
   Matt Winkeljohn writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
