<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO URGE WITHHOLDING INTERNATIONAL LOANS FROM RUSSIA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANDREW BROMAN 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A top Clinton administration official said Tuesday
that in light of recent accusations of Russian money laundering,
the United States will urge withholding international loans from
that country until its leaders implement more reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the pervasive problems in the rule of law in Russia, we
do not believe at this point that the provision of new funds would
be constructive,'' Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers told the
House Banking Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Summers also said the Clinton administration will introduce new
policies Thursday aimed at curbing banking abuses. He defended U.S.
policy toward Russia in the face of Republican criticism that the
administration has lacked oversight.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton proposal will focus on how U.S. banks handle foreign
money and will include requirements that storefront check cashers,
brokerage firms and casinos notify authorities of suspicious
activities the way banks do.
</P>
<P>
   Recent allegations that Russian mobsters funneled $10 billion
through the Bank of New York largely prompted House committee
members' concerns over U.S. policy toward Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury and Justice departments launched a probe into the bank
in April when they first heard of the diversions. No one has been
charged in the case, and U.S. investigators have not commented
publicly on it. But Summers did say that no information showed
money from the International Monetary Fund was diverted to the
nation's 15th largest bank.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF, which has 182 countries as members, was formed to help
maintain a stable system of buying and selling currencies so that
countries can make payments in foreign money without delay.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Foreign Minister Igor Ivanov said Tuesday that Russians
wanted the scandal investigated, even if it implicated officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have an interest that is no less than the American
interest,'' Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   Summers told lawmakers that while the administration will
monitor Russian finances closer, the U.S. and the IMF should not
abandon the troubled country.
</P>
<P>
   To ignore Russia would ``limit our ability to support Russian
economic and financial stability; it would inhibit our ability to
promote democratization, and it would raise the risk that the
United States and the West would be labeled as scapegoats for
Russia's failure to address its problems,'' Summers said.
</P>
<P>
   Committee Chairman Rep. James Leach, R-Iowa, said he will
introduce legislation that will restrict how U.S. banks work with
overseas institutions and prevent them from opening and maintaining
accounts with off-shore banks that are not under the same
supervision as those in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   He said the legislation is intended to ``pierce the veil of
secrecy that for too long has made it possible for offshore
financial institutions to skirt U.S. laws.''
</P>
<P>
   Up to $15 billion in Russian funds were sent to offshore
accounts over the last year, the administration acknowledged.
</P>
<P>
   As concerns mount over the former superpower's decline, some
Republicans are asking, ``who lost Russia?'' and some critics blame
the fiasco on Vice President Al Gore, a presidential candidate who
has played a major role in U.S.-Russian dealings.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrats said only Russia can blame itself for its
troubles. ``Nobody lost Russia,'' said Rep. Jay Inslee, D-Wash.
``Russia was not ours to lose. It will be a Russian ... not an
American failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Summers said continued IMF or World Bank involvement in Russia
will depend on:
</P>
<P>
   _ Completion of an investigative report, detailing offshore
operations of the Central Bank of Russia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stronger controls at the CBR to manage reserves, markets and
extension of credit to commercial banks.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``regime'' of regular external IMF-reviewed audits of the
CBR.
</P>
<P>
   _ New safeguards on the use of international aid for budget
support.
</P>
<P>
   But Summers said the IMF has followed Russian finances, and that
the agency has canceled parts of loans amounting to $228 million
because of the Russia's financial crisis. He said since 1993, the
policy toward Russia has focused on a balance between what was
necessary and what was politically feasible.
</P>
<P>
   At least, Summers said, the worst case Russian-scenario has not
come true.
</P>
<P>
   ``.... Many of the things that were feared not very long ago:
hyperinflation, collapse of the Russian state, a return to
communism, and so forth, a major nationalist revival in an
anti-American fashion _ many of the things that were most feared
have also not materialized.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, some members of the committee said the bottom line was
to keep Russia from reverting to Cold War ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my hope that this does not relegate into some kind of a
partisan issue, but that we keep our eye on the ball,'' said Rep.
Paul Ryan, R-Wis. ``And that is that we help the Russian people get
a healthy growing economy with a currency that has a solid store of
value.''
</P>
<P>
   In a related development Tuesday, Switzerland's government
announced that Swiss banks have frozen $16.8 million in accounts
suspected to be linked to the Russian laundering case.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
