<HEADER>
A0703 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-DIVORCE-730&AMP;ADD-NY     09-21 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-DIVORCE-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BRIBERY CASE TAINTS 2,000 DIVORCES IN MANHATTAN MATRIMONIAL
COURT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By DAVID ROHDE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The chief administrator of the Manhattan Matrimonial
Court has accepted tens of thousands of dollars in bribes over the
last seven years to expedite hundreds of divorces and get approvals
on others that were fraudulently prepared, prosecutors said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The administrator, Steven Singer, admitted on Friday that he
accepted bribes ranging from $10 to hundreds of dollars to take
divorce papers and _ without having verified the authenticity of
the papers as required _ quickly forward them to a judge for
signing as uncontested divorces.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said some of the documents involved a wide array of
fraud, including husbands forging their wives signatures on divorce
settlements that required the husbands to make only paltry child
support payments. In other cases, Singer said, he took the bribes
simply to expedite the cases for impatient couples, cutting the
waiting time to a couple of days from two to four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The cases that were expedited, court officials said, would
likely be allowed to stand. But divorces that involved fraud would
probably be thrown out. As a result, people who believed they had
been legally divorced and then remarried may be bigamists,
prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   The Manhattan district attorney, Robert Morgenthau, said Tuesday
that his office was reviewing about 2,000 divorces granted by the
Manhattan Matrimonial Court, but he cautioned that the
investigation was in its initial stages and that it was not yet
known how many of the divorces might have involved fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Two divorce lawyers have previously been indicted in the schemes
and two clerks were indicted Tuesday, prosecutors said, and as many
as 20 other divorce lawyers and court employees are under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said that all of the cases being investigated came
from low-cost legal offices, known in the field as ``divorce
mills,'' that cater to immigrants and the poor with relatively
low-cost services.
</P>
<P>
   Singer, who was arrested in June, pleaded guilty on Friday in
state Supreme Court in Manhattan to multiple counts of accepting
bribes. He is scheduled to be sentenced by Justice John Cataldo of
state Supreme Court on Jan. 10 and faces up to seven years in
prison and a $5,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   The charges stunned colleagues of Singer, a leading expert on
New York matrimonial law who frequently gave speeches to bar
associations on the topic. He had served as supervising clerk for
matrimonial cases in Manhattan since 1996 and been a court clerk
for 28 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a very, very bright fellow who was extremely intelligent
and worked all hours,'' said one court official. ``It's just
incomprehensible to so many of us, and deeply disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Singer oversaw a staff of 20 clerks whose duties included
verifying requests for uncontested divorces, which require both
husband and wife to sign affidavits stating they agree to the
terms. Court officials said more than 90 percent of divorces in New
York are uncontested.
</P>
<P>
   State law allows New York residents to apply for divorce in any
county they wish, and Manhattan's courts have a reputation for
quickly processing uncontested divorces, the officials said. The
Manhattan Matrimonial Court processes by far the most divorce cases
in the state, handling between 12,000 and 15,000 a year, or more
than half of the total number of uncontested divorces in the state.
Court officials attributed that case load to the concentration of
divorce mills in Manhattan and the reputation for quick processing.
</P>
<P>
   After Singer and his staff verified the validity of the divorce
papers, they forward them to a judge or court-appointed referees
for signing, court officials said. Court officials said the judges
check the papers again themselves, but divorce lawyers said they
believe court clerks are the ones who generally make sure ``all the
t's are crossed and i's dotted.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said Singer ignored clear signs of fraud in exchange
for the bribes and was caught in a series of sting operations
mounted by the district attorney's office between 1997 and this
spring.
</P>
<P>
   Five undercover investigators went to Singer with documents
containing forged signatures. They all received court-certified
divorces. Eight other undercover investigators filed divorce papers
using the names of Manhattan district attorneys who served in the
late 1800s. Again, all of the divorces were approved.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``It varied from case to case,'' one prosecutor said, referring
to the fraud. ``But for the most part it was to get the divorce
quickly and with no questions asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors said they feared that poor and immigrant women, in
particular, could have been victimized in some of the schemes.
Those women, divorce lawyers said, may be unaware of state laws
that guarantee them a percentage of their husband's income as child
support in most cases.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation was started in 1997 over a child support case.
A woman complained to court officials that she had received a copy
of an uncontested divorce settlement that she never agreed to. The
settlement included a far smaller amount of child support than she
wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Divorce lawyers and court officials said the cases confirm
long-running concerns about the activities of divorce mills. The
shops, which charge as little as $500 for a divorce, have emerged
as a cheap alternative to hiring private lawyers whose divorce fees
can easily rise into the thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Court officials said they have also long suspected the shops of
submitting false forms declaring their clients to be impoverished
and unable to pay the $275 in divorce paper filing fees, but then
charging the client $275 anyway and pocketing the money.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
