<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0704 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-SHORTGAME-H     09-21 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-SHORTGAME-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDDIE SEFKO  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ At a time when pro golfers are divided into
three subsets _ long, longer and Tiger Woods _ it's important to
note that this week's Ryder Cup will not be won with a smoking
driver.
</P>
<P>
   The more crucial elements to victory at The Country Club will be
a blazing putter, red-hot wedge shots and recovery shots that
extinguish a fire before it blazes out of control.
</P>
<P>
   These factors are worth so much more in Ryder competition than
the booming tee shot. You can't win a par-4 or par-5 from the tee
box (although it can be lost with one bad swing). But a par-saving
putt or a morale-stealing chip-in that deflates the opponent is far
more valuable in team competition than a 320-yard drive. Nobody
knows that better than U.S. captain Ben Crenshaw.
</P>
<P>
   ``The short game in match play is very, very important, because
it has to do with knitting your holes together,'' Crenshaw says.
``It's up to the players. They have to ask themselves: `How can I
get better? How can I improve my short game?'
</P>
<P>
   ``Quite frankly, I think we're due. The Europeans have held the
Cup the last couple of times because of a couple of things. It may
sound simplistic, but they've done a better job of holing out at
the right times. And they have gotten the ball up and down in tough
situations when they needed to.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are two areas where the Americans must improve. Crenshaw
knows it. And the players should know it, too, says Dave Pelz, the
short-game wizard who has taught Ryder Cuppers on both sides the
fine points of saving strokes around the green.
</P>
<P>
   Look no further than last year's Presidents Cup, when the
International team used a dagger-through-the-heart chip-in from
Australian Craig Parry and an unlikely long-range hole-out by New
Zealander Frank Nobilo to destroy the Americans' confidence early
in the match. They were never the same afterward and wound up
getting pummeled.
</P>
<P>
   Pelz knows intimately the strengths and weaknesses of Colin
Montgomerie, Payne Stewart and others, and he says the Americans
will have to concentrate on saving themselves with the short game
if they hope to win back the Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why match play is so much different than any other
format,'' Pelz says. ``Ben is on the right track. Focus on the
short game. With these guys at their level, you don't have to teach
mechanics. But you can always sharpen those mechanics. None of
those guys have bad mechanics. If they're sharp, they're very, very
good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have them hitting distance wedges to targets at least
30 or 45 minutes a day. Chipping, long lag putts, bump-and-run
shots _ players of this level should spend two to three hours a day
for two weeks working on those shots before a big event like
this.''
</P>
<P>
   There's a reason why competitions like the Ryder Cup come down
to chipping and putting. The alternate-shot format leads to more
missed greens, which then requires players to recover if they want
to save par.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is so much margin for error in the full golf swing in
terms of power,'' Pelz says. ``If you hit a drive 270 or 290 or
300, they're all great drives.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with a wedge, if you're a foot short, you might be in a
bunker. And if you're two feet long, you're over the green. Only if
the shot is perfect does it turn out the way you want it to. The
requirements are so much more demanding. And when things are tense,
you have to approach the short game with soft hands. If your
muscles are tight, you have no chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelz knows firsthand that at least one American has done his
short-game homework going into the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``Payne is probably the best, day in and day out, when it comes
to having a solid all-around short game,'' he says. ``If he hits
the ball half-decent off the tee, he's in contention every week. I
would take his wedge game against anybody's. And he's become so
much of a better putter. Earlier in his career, he had trouble
making putts. Now, he's probably making more than he deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know Payne spent a lot of time on his short game leading up
to the Ryder Cup. He worked on it every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Pelz, who says he will be rooting for the American team even
though he works extensively with Montgomerie and Jesper Parnevik,
believes the mental advantages of a good short game are every bit
as important as any physical edge.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy gets up and down two or three times, then maybe he
sinks a chip shot, he starts thinking that there's no way you can
beat him,'' Pelz says. ``That's why Freddie (Couples) has been so
good at match play for so many years. He gets his opponent so
demoralized, they start thinking they can't beat this guy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans know the feeling. They're hoping to reverse it
this time around.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0379 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0707 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLEMENCY-CONGRESS-ART     09-21 1262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-CONGRESS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI DIRECTOR OPPOSED CLEMENCY `UNEQUIVOCALLY,' LETTER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Ill., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI ``unequivocally opposed'' President
Clinton's offer of clemency to 16 Puerto Rican nationalists,
asserting that the release of most of the prisoners would
reinvigorate their terrorist movement, according to a letter
prepared by the law enforcement agency.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, prepared by FBI Director Louis J. Freeh said the
clemency ``would likely return committed, experienced,
sophisticated and hardened terrorists to the clandestine movement''
for Puerto Rican independence. The letter also said the clemency
would ``psychologically and operationally enhance'' allies in the
militant organization FALN who had killed five people and maimed 83
in terrorist activities in the 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh did not sign the letter, which was addressed but never
sent to Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee. But senior law enforcement officials said Tuesday night
that the letter accurately reflected Freeh's opposition to leniency
for the Puerto Rican militants.
</P>
<P>
   A draft of the letter was sent from the FBI to the Justice
Department for review prior to Freeh's signature. Ultimately, the
letter without his signature was sent to Democrats on Capitol Hill,
where it was released Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said the issue of clemency had been raised since 1994
and that Freeh had objected to it as recently as June 28; even so,
the letter said, Freeh was unaware that the president was actually
contemplating any commutation when the White House announced its
offer on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   While some officials have privately acknowledged disapproval of
the president's decision, Freeh's letter is the first official
indication from within the administration of the fierce
disagreement that raged within the law enforcement community over
Clinton's offer of clemency to the 16 terrorists, 14 of whom are
now out of prison. The letter did not say what evidence had led to
the opposition to clemency.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time Tuesday, Clinton provided his first full
explanation of his decision in a letter to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Casting himself in the tradition of previous presidents who have
granted clemency in cases that were unpopular, Clinton portrayed
his release of the prisoners as an act of courage. He cited
Theodore Roosevelt's grant of amnesty to Filipino nationals who
fought U.S. control of the Philippines and Jimmy Carter's
commutation of sentences of Puerto Rican nationalists who had
opened fire on the House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They exercised the power vested in them by the Constitution to
do what they believed was right, even in the face of great
controversy,'' Clinton wrote of his predecessors. ``I have done the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   The president did not deal with the question of whether the
release of the prisoners might reignite the dormant terrorist
movement. But Rep. Vito Fossella, R-N.Y., asserted that recent
statements by a known Puerto Rican militant and ally of the
prisoners indicated that the release was stirring old passions.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted Filiberto Ojeda Rios, the leader of Los Macheteros, a
terrorist organization allied with the ex-prisoners, as telling a
Puerto Rican radio station that if the United States committed
aggressive acts against Puerto Rico, his group would ``not remain
with their arms crossed, you can be sure of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's letter came to light at a congressional hearing designed
by Republicans to portray the president's act as reckless.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans coaxed out of other law enforcement officials a
concern that the ex-prisoners constitute a threat to American
security. While the officials were bound under the president's
claim of executive privilege not to disclose internal deliberations
over the matter, they catalogued the violent actions of the FALN,
the terrorist organization to which the prisoners belong.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Gallagher, assistant director of national security for the
FBI, told the panel, ``These are criminals and they are terrorists
and they represent a threat to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has acknowledged that it has no control over clemency
matters, which are the sole prerogative of the president. But
Clinton's explanation Tuesday appeared to make little difference to
those in the hearing room, who see the move as a political disaster
for the president and for his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is
likely to seek the Senate seat from New York. She has run into
political trouble for at first supporting, then denouncing, her
husband's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have wanted to draw out the drama. The panel,
chaired by Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the government
Reform Committee, called several victims of FALN attacks, bringing
them to testify for the third time in less than two weeks. They
included Richard Pastorella, a retired New York City detective, who
was severely injured in a 1982 attack. He lost his sight in both
eyes, and his face is held together by 20 titanium screws.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who thinks of us?'' Pastorella asked in a bitter voice.
``Certainly not Mr. Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims, and relatives of those who had been killed in
terrorist attacks, said that contrary to federal requirements, they
had not been notified of the prisoners' pending release.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Republicans took issue with Clinton's apparent belief that
just because the prisoners had not been convicted of doing bodily
harm, they deserved to go free. Republican after Republican
asserted that there was no distinction between people who were
accessories to violent crimes and those who actually pulled the
trigger. ``The only reason some of them didn't commit murders or
bombings is because they were arrested before they got a chance
to,'' said Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Two Democrats, both African-Americans, offered a minimal defense
of the clemency. Rep. Danny K. Davis, D-Ill., said, ``Democracy can
be fellowship as well as punishment.'' Rep. Edolphus Towns, D-N.Y.,
urged Congress to ``move on'' and examine issues that ``have a real
effect on the lives of average Americans.'' The committee's ranking
Democrat, Rep. Henry Waxman of California, said reluctantly that he
``probably'' would not have granted the clemency.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, the president disclosed some of the arguments
that former President Carter had used in persuading Clinton to
grant clemency in this case. He said that Carter wrote to him in
1997 that releasing the prisoners would be ``a significant
humanitarian gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter also said that any concern that clemency might be viewed
as leniency was mitigated by the length of time that they had
already served, Clinton wrote. Most of them had been in prison at
least 16 years, a period that Clinton said was not commensurate
with the crimes of which they were convicted, which included
sedition, conspiracy and armed robbery but not bodily harm to
anyone.
</P>
<P>
   And for the first time since he made the offer, Clinton said the
decision was difficult and that he had not minimized the concerns
of law enforcement personnel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did what I believe equity and fairness dictated,'' he wrote.
``I certainly understand, however, that other people could review
the same facts I did and arrive at a different decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
