<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOBACCO LAWSUITS TURN TOLERANCE ON ITS HEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Undated) Unless you read the business press regularly, you
probably aren't aware of the latest effort to use the U.S. legal
system to prey on the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Wall Street Journal and Investor's Business Daily lamented
in recent editorial page commentaries how foreign countries have
gotten on the tobacco-lawsuit crowd. The development underscores
how America's growing contempt for the spirit of tort law threatens
global destabilization of the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the $200 billion-plus payoff achieved by U.S.
state governments in their depredations against Big Tobacco, six
countries from south of the border have recently consolidated cases
against the industry in federal court in Washington, D.C.
Meanwhile, a dozen other countries are initiating or considering
similar suits.
</P>
<P>
   Their hope apparently is to follow the lead of U.S. officials by
pursuing compensatory relief for health-care costs their smokers
have allegedly imposed on the citizenry at large. The litigation
undertaken by Brazil, Bolivia, Venezuela, Guatemala, Panama and
Nicaragua, however, is even more contemptuous of legal rationality
than comparable U.S. efforts.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that these nations feign surprise at learning tobacco
is a health hazard is as amusing as it is outrageous, but it's not
as outrageous as their policy conflicts. Some not only profit
handsomely from tobacco monopolies but also ship especially
hazardous tobacco to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, for instance, is a leading tobacco exporter, but its
lawsuit ignores its tobacco industry. Moreover, its exporters,
according to George Washington University law professor Jonathan
Turley in a Journal column, were cited 11 times in the past year by
U.S. officials for exporting tobacco tainted with 20 pesticides
legally prohibited here as human health hazards.
</P>
<P>
   Turley also noted that even as Russia pursues a tobacco claim in
Washington, its legislature in Moscow is considering establishment
of a tobacco monopoly. This would allow Russia, he points out, ``to
claim both the profits and damages from this product.''
</P>
<P>
   Another irony, Turley says, is the fact that even as these
countries justify their legal actions based on public health
concerns, some have ``infamous records on human rights or the
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the U.S. government seems to have no choice but to
allow foreign brigands use of our courts to prey on legal American
enterprises selling legal products to consumers for their legal
consumption.
</P>
<P>
   Two corrosive developments in American society make this bizarre
scenario possible. One is increasing public tolerance of
indefensibly unfair treatment of those singled out for demonization
by self-appointed moral crusaders. Another is the manipulation of
this tolerance by political demagogues and legal beagles to create
public acceptance of egregious distortions of the spirit of the
law. This eases the national conscience to the extent of allowing
the legal theft of huge sums of money from the demonized parties.
</P>
<P>
   If this greed-inspired corruption of the legal system is allowed
to run its logical course, America in the mid-21st century may be
as anarchic as Russia today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0384 </DOCNO>
