<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMBO-HIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`MAMBO NO. 5' SINGER TURNS OUT MONDO PARTY SONG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED SHUSTER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ After a (START ITALS)vida loca(END ITAL) summer,
everyone's doing the mambo, actually ``Mambo No. 5 (A Little Bit
of...),'' stylish crooner Lou Bega's saucy international smash now
zooming up the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   The party song _ a zesty remake of a 1949 instrumental by Perez
``Prez'' Prado, the late Cuban king of mambo _ just hit No. 6 on
the singles chart after only five weeks. That's what happens when a
number crosses over onto several radio formats at once, including
Top 40, adult Top 40 and modern adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a song for the women of the world,'' purrs Bega, 24, from
his home in Munich, Germany. ``It's not an ordinary love song. It
makes you want to dance.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Ugandan father and Sicilian mom, Bega recalls
hearing Prado's original version around the house as a kid. Last
summer, the obscure producer and lyricist was sitting at an outdoor
cafe putting female names to the catchy mambo rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   In the remake, the unmarried Bega sings over bubbly percussion
and brass: ``To me, flirtin', it's just like a sport ... A little
bit of Rita is all I need, a little bit of Tina is what I see, a
little bit of Sandra in the sun, a little bit of Mary all night
long.''
</P>
<P>
   Bega, who sports white pin-stripe suits complete with spats and
Borsalino hats, says Prado would've understood.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hit me like a crack of lightning,'' the singer said. ``I
knew Prez would have wanted lyrics in his song and he would've
wanted it to be heard in the next millennium. The mambo was a
forgotten rhythm after the '50s. I want to take it into the new
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Bega's full-length debut, naturally titled ``A Little Bit Of
Mambo,'' recently reached No. 12 on the Billboard 200. The smash
title track, available only on the album in the U.S., was issued as
a single in Germany last April; by May, it was triple platinum.
``Mambo No. 5'' has since topped the charts in more than a dozen
countries.
</P>
<P>
   Bega doesn't lose his cool when the dreaded m-word (macarena) is
mentioned. In more than a few places, ``Mambo No. 5'' has been
likened to that once-ubiquitous novelty song and dance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The macarena wasn't an artist, it was a song,'' Bega insists.
``It was better for them to put out a single than an album. I'm
going to go on tour and put on a real show _ a show with a band,
dancers, horns and lots of percussion.''
</P>
<P>
   Just don't hold your breath waiting for ``Mambo No. 6.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2117EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0385 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0718 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MARILYN-PERFUME-$ADV2     09-21 1111
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARILYN-PERFUME-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARILYN MONROE: LASTING CHARISMA THAT STILL TURNS THE ORDINARY INTO
GOLD  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Deanne Stillman is the author of the award-winning one-act play
``Inside the White House,'' about John F. Kennedy and Marilyn
Monroe in the afterlife.  
 By DEANNE STILLMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Over the last couple of years, the estate of
Marilyn Monroe has not been kind to the goddess whose memory it
protects. In 1997, it sanctioned a line of Marilyn Monroe lingerie.
</P>
<P>
   The '50s-style underwear was hawked at department stores. Now
comes an estate-approved perfume called Marilyn, from International
Flavors and Fragrances, the company that has recreated the essence
of Elizabeth Taylor, Victoria Principal and Christie Brinkley. This
takes the concept of celebrity perfume to a new level: the notion
of smelling like a famous dead person _ even Marilyn Monroe _ is at
best an odd one. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eugene P. Grisanti, the chief executive president of
International Flavors and Fragrances, says the perfume will be
``sensual, sexy, with undertones of amber and resin, glamorous and
elegant with freesia, childish and light, like Marilyn.''
</P>
<P>
   To publicize the new perfume, International Flavors is
sponsoring an auction of Marilyn Monroe relics at Christie's in New
York on Oct. 27 and 28. The company's involvement in the auction is
not a secret, but it might as well be: the press coverage has
focused entirely on the celebrated ``Happy Birthday President''
dress _ the see-through sheath in which Monroe serenaded John F.
Kennedy at his birthday party.
</P>
<P>
   It has been unveiled publicly for the first time since Monroe
wore it in 1962 and is predicted to fetch bids into the low seven
figures. This and the other relics for sale are owned by Monroe's
estate. Without their illustrious provenance, many of them could
have belonged to almost any middle-class woman in the 1950s and
'60s.
</P>
<P>
   A preview of the lode here in August revealed cook books, hair
clips, stiletto heels, gowns, dresses and tops that might be found
at vintage-clothing shops. The ordinary quality of certain items
makes them all the more appealing, physical evidence of the ``every
gal'' side of Monroe's character.
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, the fact that it was Monroe who actually wore
the three pairs of proffered jeans in ``The River of No Return''
places their starting price at $20,000 to $30,000. The Mexican
sweater she wore when photographed by George Barris on the Santa
Monica beach in 1962 is estimated at $30,000 to $50,000. The
cowgirl boots that she wore in ``The Misfits'' may be worth $4,000
to $6,000.
</P>
<P>
   Some items simply amuse (photographs of Mafia, the Maltese dog
given to her by Frank Sinatra; a plaster floor lamp in the shape of
a palm tree). One souvenir that might interest those who desire a
celebrity menorah is Monroe's for $2,000 to $4,000; her certificate
of conversion to Judaism, earned while she was married to Arthur
Miller, is also on the block, for $8,000 to $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   (Coincidentally, right now at Sotheby's, and continuing on
Amazon.com, the Barry Halper collection of baseball memorabilia is
for sale. Halper, who owns a two-percent share of the Yankees, has
acquired dozens of noteworthy items, including a letter Joe
DiMaggio wrote to his ex-wife Monroe from Rome shortly before she
sang at the president's ball. ``Just came from a very interesting
visit to the Vatican,'' he wrote in part, ``Tomorrow we have an
audience with Holy Father ... Yesterday I paid a visit to the
little leagues. Luckily after my fourth swing I connected and hit
it out of the park. As ever, Love Joe.'' The letter, released after
DiMaggio's death, is priced at $8,000 to $12,000.)
</P>
<P>
   The most interesting material at auction includes 400 books from
Monroe's library. Perhaps more than anything, she longed to be
taken seriously (and the proceeds from this portion of the sale go
to Literacy Partners, a nice gesture but really a kind of beard for
the whole shebang).
</P>
<P>
   Her friends have said that she was a reader of great passion and
curiosity, as the books in her collection indicate. They include
works by John Steinbeck, Mark Twain, William Styron, Somerset
Maugham, William Faulkner, Willa Cather and Colette. While male
authors are identified by their names or under categories like
literature, poetry and plays.
</P>
<P>
   The two women are given back-of-the-bus treatment, available in
Lot 566, ``Women Authors.'' One suspects that Monroe _ by all
accounts an egalitarian _ might have found the category puzzling,
perhaps even insulting.
</P>
<P>
   By far the most telling book in her library is ``The Little
Engine That Could,'' by Piper Watty (Lot 522), although this is a
fact apparently lost on auctioneers. According to the catalog, it
has ``childish pencil scrawls at end, possibly Marilyn Monroe's.''
Missing from the history is that Monroe carried this book with her
to the Kennedy birthday ball, according to Gloria Steinem in her
essay ``Marilyn.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And now: about that dress. Studded with rhinestones on
flesh-colored silk gauze, it was stitched onto Monroe before she
made her entrance at Madison Square Garden to sing for the
president. The gown was not lined, and there was nothing underneath
but the goddess herself; the country still reverberates from the
glittering apparition she presented that night.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, she was introduced by the president's brother-in-law
Peter Lawford as ``the late Marilyn Monroe.'' She led the crowd in
a breathy chorus of ``Happy Birthday,'' apparently gripped by deep
fear, propped up, according to Ms. Steinem, by pills, champagne and
the children's book. ``I can now retire from politics,'' Kennedy
said, ``after having had, ah, `Happy Birthday' sung to me in such a
sweet, wholesome way.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The image of Monroe singing to Kennedy burns brightly over time,
like other images whose players have long been reduced to dust. On
that evening, in that scene of our national play, she became the
disciple ministering to the adored, the acolyte praising the
soon-to-be-martyred president, as Mary Magdalene comforted Jesus
Christ on his path.
</P>
<P>
   The gown she wore contains magic and mystery, sweat and tears;
in it she gave immeasurable mojo to Camelot. The relic ought to be
donated to the Smithsonian, not auctioned to the highest bidder; a
cloth so sacred to the national culture ought not have a price.
</P>
<P>
   Who will buy it? To what end? And would Monroe want to be a
perfume? When told by a drama coach that he felt ``sex vibrations''
as she read Checkhov, she replied, ``I want to be an artist, not
... a celluloid aphrodisiac.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
