<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0386 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT     09-21 0749
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SPEND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATE LEADER PRESSES NAVY ON A SHIP IT DOES NOT WANT 
</HEADLINE>
 (nk) 
 By TIM WEINER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Congress is about to break its self-imposed
spending limits again. To help understand why, consider the LHD-8.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott wanted half a billion dollars
to start building a $1.5 billion ship called the LHD-8 at the
Ingalls Shipyard in Mississippi, his home state.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, at his behest, approved the money this summer. But
the House did not. Last month, House aides asked the Navy how much
money really was needed to start the project. Last week, the Navy
drafted an answer: $295 million, a lot less than Lott wanted.
</P>
<P>
   One of Lott's senior aides, a retired Navy officer, obtained the
draft and faxed a handwritten memorandum on the senator's
stationery to an admiral at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The memorandum said $295 million was ``the wrong answer.'' The
right answer _ the answer that ``the Navy needs to support'' _ was
``at least $375 M to $500 M,'' it said. ``We have worked too hard
to give up on the $500 M now.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication, according to several people involved in the
process, was that the Navy should alter its testimony to support
Lott's position. It has not.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the Navy never asked for the money to buy a new LHD-8,
a miniature aircraft carrier for launching Marine assaults by
helicopter. It says it would prefer to spend the money elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The LHD-8 memorandum is only one example of the pressures in
Congress to spend more money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only unusual thing about this is that it was put in
writing,'' said Dale Bumpers, director of the Center for Defense
Information, who left the Senate in 1998 after 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a common practice,'' said Bumpers, who served on
Senate military spending panels. ``Everybody in the United States
Senate that I know anything about protects whatever defense
industry they have in their state.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott's tenure as majority leader has been a boon for the Ingalls
shipyard in Pascagoula, where his father once worked as a pipe
fitter. The shipyard, owned by Litton Industries, is the state's
largest employer. All told, Mississippi military contractors and
bases are in line to receive about $8 billion in the coming year.
The operating budget of the state of Mississippi is $9.9 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Lott's spokesman, John Czwartacki, called the LHD-8 memo ``an
inartful attempt to point out a way to save taxpayers $1 billion.''
</P>
<P>
   Expensive weapons systems like the LHD-8 often cost more if they
take longer to build, just as a 30-year mortgage costs more than a
15-year mortgage. The half-billion dollars requested by Lott would
save money in the long run by speeding up production of the ship,
Czwartacki said.
</P>
<P>
   A House-Senate conference on the military spending bill, set to
begin on Wednesday, will decide the fate of the LHD-8, the F-22
fighter jet and other high-priced weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Enormous pressure has been placed on the House by the Senate and
Speaker Dennis Hastert to restore $1.8 billion for the first six
F-22 jets. The House cut the money this summer, after Republican
opponents argued that the F-22 was too expensive and too untested.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force and the prime contractor, Lockheed-Martin, have
fought back with lobbying, arm-twisting, and paid announcements on
National Public Radio news shows. They are likely to win: Some of
the money for the F-22's will probably be put back. But that deal
is far from done, House aides said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   When that conference is over, Congress will likely have approved
$17 billion or more in new increases for the coming year, creating
a Pentagon budget of roughly $270 billion.
</P>
<P>
   That is more than half the money Congress allotted to run all
government agencies in the coming fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The other half of the money, $268 billion, is supposed to run
the rest of the government. Republican lawmakers are beginning to
acknowledge that that is not enough and that the spending caps
imposed in 1997 will be broken, just as they were last year.
Military spending will be the force that breaks them, said Sen. Ted
Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Congress should ``acknowledge what is obvious,'' said Lott's
spokesman, Czwartacki. ``We'll spend more than the caps permit.
Let's be honest with ourselves and the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   So far, the acknowledgment remains a bare whisper.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
