<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE
</HEADLINE>
  (pr) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROWTH IN TRADE DEFICIT PROMPTS CONCERN FOR DOLLAR
</P>
<P>
   Another leap in the U.S. trade deficit in July fueled fears that
a continuing surge in imports is threatening the health of the
dollar. The Commerce Department reported that the trade deficit for
the month hit $25.2 billion, higher than the June imbalance of
$24.6 billion, confounding expectations that the deficit would
start to shrink as economic growth picks up around the world.
Imports from China, Western Europe and Japan all hit new highs,
well above the projections of most economists who have followed the
trade flows with increasing concern.
</P>
<P>
   Stock prices were pulled down by a further slide in the value of
the dollar against the yen, warnings about third-quarter earnings,
worries about the earthquake in Taiwan and the trade deficit. The
Dow Jones industrial average plunged 225.43 points, to 10,598.47.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index fell 27.95 points, to
1,307.58. The Nasdaq composite index dropped 65.05 points, to
2,821.10.
</P>
<P>
   GOLDMAN POSTS STRONG RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   Goldman Sachs Group reported surprisingly strong earnings in its
first full quarter as a public company, a striking reversal from a
year ago when fallout from Russia's economic woes forced the
investment banking firm to postpone plans for its initial public
offering of stock. Goldman, which went public with an offering of
$3.7 billion on May 4, said it earned $638 million, or $1.32 per
diluted share, in its fiscal third quarter, exceeding the
expectations of Wall Street analysts.
</P>
<P>
   DISPARITY IN MINORITY CREDIT RATINGS
</P>
<P>
   Even in the current flush economic times, with home ownership
rates reaching record highs, a disproportionately large number of
minorities, chiefly African Americans, have poor credit ratings,
according to a new study.
</P>
<P>
   PENSION FIGHT MOVES TO CONGRESS
</P>
<P>
   The fight over cash-balance pensions has moved to Congress,
where lobbyists and congressional aides say the dispute over IBM's
pension switch will probably help spur legislation to rein in the
plans.
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN MONETARY POLICY UNCHANGED
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese central bank voted to leave monetary policy
unchanged, defying Government officials and economists who have
been demanding that the bank take aggressive steps to reverse the
yen's heady rise in value.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA PLANS TO MAKE PAYMENTS
</P>
<P>
   President Hugo Chavez of Venezuela, in an effort to reassure
foreign investors, said his Government would make all its debt
payments while at the same time work on a market-friendly proposal
that would allow it to pay off its current debt over a longer
period of time. His comments came as investors are keeping a close
watch on emerging markets in Latin America. Ecuador is struggling
to avoid a default on its foreign debt and Brazil is still working
to come back from the devaluation of its currency in January.
</P>
<P>
   HEWLETT AND ORACLE TO COLLABORATE
</P>
<P>
   Hewlett-Packard strengthened its Internet presence with the
announcement of a deal with Oracle to collaborate on developing and
selling Oracle's electronic commerce software on Hewlett-Packard
computers.
</P>
<P>
   AIR CANADA REJECTS HOSTILE BID
</P>
<P>
   Air Canada rejected a hostile takeover proposal from Onex, a
conglomerate that wants to merge Air Canada with its weak rival,
Canadian Airlines International.
</P>
<P>
   3COM EARNINGS BEAT EXPECTATIONS
</P>
<P>
   3Com attributed its strong first-quarter earnings, which
exceeded estimates, to strong growth in hand-held computing
products and improved operating efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   HARPERCOLLINS ANNOUNCES CUTS
</P>
<P>
   HarperCollins, which recently acquired William Morrow &AMP; Company
and Avon Books, announced a series of moves to consolidate its
imprints, which resulted in layoffs of 74 employees and the
departure of top executives from Morrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
