<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-NOTES22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Course set-up suits aggressive players
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ It is a U.S. Open golf course, having hosted
the 1988 championship won by Curtis Strange, but it is not a U.S.
Open set-up.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody's complaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rough's not going to be eight inches thick,'' Justin
Leonard said, ``and I think that's going to make for some
aggressive play.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Crenshaw, the United States captain, didn't want The Country
Club to be unplayable from the rough for the 33rd Ryder Cup this
week. Fans want to watch birdies beat pars, he surmised; they don't
want to see players hack out wedges from the rough and halve a hole
with bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just thought that maybe just a little lighter rough off the
fairways would be a little more conducive, a little more exciting
in match play, especially hitting into these little greens,''
Crenshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   A wonderful course reworked by Rees Jones, The Country Club has
two short par-4's on the front nine that will tempt U.S. players
such as Tiger Woods and Davis Love III to try drivers, depending on
their match status. The course also has European-style bunkers with
massive lips and surrounding high grass and the high fescue common
in England and Scotland. It is a shotmaker's golf course, not a
TPC-type layout that might favor the U.S. But as David Duval said,
anyone on either team ``can manage OK on just about any golf course
you put them.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We enjoy the course,'' Scotland's Colin Montgomerie said.
``It's got a European feel to it. It's not one of your Florida-type
courses or a modern American course. It's an Old World American
course, and we tend to enjoy them more.''
</P>
<P>
   Some home cooking
</P>
<P>
   Crowds of about 20,000 for a Tuesday practice round, roaring for
individual shots as though it were the weekend of a major, are a
big part of Ryder Cup week. It might be a distraction, but at least
Americans are unlikely to cheer a U.S. missed putt, as the European
fans did at Valderrama. ``I played with Scott Hoch last year in a
match at Valderrama,'' Jeff Maggert said. ``When we teed off, he
said, `Man, you guys aren't used to this, but I'm used to people
rooting against me every week on the PGA Tour.' ''. . . . After a
first-day outfit of pea-green and khaki, the U.S. came back strong
Tuesday with dark blue shirts and gray slacks. . . . The four
players of the Medinah money issue were contained in one foursome
Tuesday _ Woods paired with Duval and Mark O'Meara with Phil
Mickelson. . . . Two European players have American caddies _ Lance
Ten Broeck with Jesper Parnevik and Jerry Higginbotham with Sergio
Garcia. When Ten Broeck misclubbed Parnevik by 10 yards at Akron
last month, the Swede kidded him by saying, ``Was that to prepare
me for the Ryder Cup?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
