<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0734 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-1STLD-WR     09-21 0992
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAIWAN-QUAKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESCUERS WORKING ROUND THE CLOCK TO REACH SURVIVORS OF TAIWAN
QUAKE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REMOVES references to Richter Scale in 9th graf.) (ART ADV: A map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By CALVIN SIMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAIPEI, Taiwan _ With the death toll from Tuesday morning's
devastating earthquake rising by the hour, rescuers around the
island worked through the day and night to reach thousands of
people still trapped inside felled buildings and houses.
</P>
<P>
   In cities across the island, many high-rise buildings listed at
eerie angles or lay flattened. In the worst-hit counties near the
epicenter, Taichung and Nantou, highways and bridges were twisted,
buckled and impassable to traffic. Much of the island, including
sections of the capital, Taipei, lay in darkness through the night.
Water and telephone services were also disrupted in many regions.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday night, more than 1,700 people around the island were
reported dead, and at least 4,400 injured and hundreds of thousands
homeless. The Interior Ministry said at least 30,000 homes were
destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   Though Taipei was spared much of the devastation that ravaged
central Taiwan, the quake collapsed the lower stories of the
78-room Sung Shan Hotel, leaving it leaning precariously against a
neighboring building.
</P>
<P>
   About 100 people were rescued from the hotel building, which
also houses apartments and a bank, but another 80 remained trapped
inside.
</P>
<P>
   The building's 81-year-old superintendent, Hsu Ling-mei, who
lives nearby, raced to the site early Tuesday morning and stood
vigil into the night, anxiously noting on a sheet of paper the
names of residents carried out on stretchers to ambulances waiting
nearby.
</P>
<P>
   With tears coursing down his face, Hsu explained that he knew
everyone in the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't leave until I know they're OK,'' he said. ``If my
presence here alone is helping, I will stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Aftershocks continued to rattle the stricken island and to
terrorize its 22 million residents. More than 1,000 were recorded,
including one that registered a potent 6.8. The main quake, which
struck at 1:47 a.m. Tuesday, measured 7.7 and was centered 90 miles
south of Taipei.
</P>
<P>
   Nantou County Executive Peng Pai-hsien appealed for donations of
bulldozers, cars, quilts and food, saying 100,000 people were left
homeless in the county. He said morgues were ``full of bodies, and
the county needed body bags and freezers in the summer heat.''
</P>
<P>
   President Lee Teng-hui, who traveled by helicopter to central
Taiwan to inspect the damage, called the quake ``the island's worst
in a century.'' He called on local residents to join forces in the
rebuilding effort and pledged financial support from the
government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first priority is to save the people who are trapped,'' he
said. ``Then we restore water and power, and then to rebuild
houses, roads, and public facilities.''
</P>
<P>
   At toppled buildings across the country, hundreds of soldiers
assisted rescuers, often by digging through the rubble with their
bare hands in search of survivors.
</P>
<P>
   It was a day of profound grief for the many who lost loved ones
to the quake and joy for those who were reunited with family and
friends they had feared were dead.
</P>
<P>
   Television reports throughout the day showed soldiers pulling
bloodied bodies from buildings and relatives of the dead sitting in
front of buildings crying and weeping.
</P>
<P>
   One man who was rescued from a collapsed high-rise building in
Taichung said in a television interview that while he was trapped
in the ruins, he could hear the voices of his children also caught
in the wreckage nearby, calling to him. But after a while, he said,
their voices faded away and he did not know where they were.
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, where rescue efforts were scarce, people sifted
through the debris calling the names of relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, Japan, Russia and Singapore agreed to send
transport planes, helicopters, and rescue personnel to help out. A
United Nations disaster assessment team was also on the way.
</P>
<P>
   Despite recent tensions between Beijing and Taipei, President
Jiang Zemin of China offered aid to the quake victims and extended
condolences, though in words that underlined Beijing's insistence
on its sovereignty over what it considers a renegade province.
</P>
<P>
   The quake ``hurt the hearts of people on the mainland as the
Chinese people on both sides of the Taiwan Strait are as closely
linked as flesh and blood,'' the state-run New China News agency
said in a paraphrase of Jiang's remarks. China's Red Cross said it
would provide $100,000 in disaster aid and $60,000 in relief
supplies.
</P>
<P>
   Railway services were paralyzed throughout the island Tuesday
morning while schools and many company offices in northern Taiwan,
including Taipei, were closed for the day. The Taipei stock
exchange and foreign exchange market also were closed Tuesday and
Wednesday, but Taipei's international airport operated as normal.
</P>
<P>
   Some residents of Taichung, in central Taiwan, called on the
government to investigate whether some of the damaged buildings
violated the country's building codes.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday evening, television broadcasts showed city blocks in
Taichung where apartment towers had been felled like dominoes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was not so good support in those buildings to begin
with,'' a woman told a local television newscaster. ``You should
have seen it: it was one small bam and everything was gone.
</P>
<P>
   Many were high-rise apartment buildings that had sprouted up in
recent years in a period of rapid development. Chen Jianren, a
government spokesman, acknowledged that many of the newer buildings
may not have met strict specifications. ``There may be problems
with some developers,'' he said. ``The quality of buildings, that
must be investigated.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
