   (NYT25) PLUMB ISLAND, N.Y. -- Sept. 20, 1999 --
SCI-ISLAND-LAB-1, 09-20 - An aerial view of Plum Island, just
across the Peconic Bay from the Hamptons, where the Agriculture
Department already operates a laboratory where foreign animal
diseases such as the dreaded foot-and-mouth and African swine fever
are studied. The department is now seeking money to turn the Plum
Island Animal Disease Center into the sort of top security
laboratory at which the most dangerous animal diseases that can
affect humans can be examined. (The Plum Island Animal Disease
Center /New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) KINSTON, N.C. -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- HURRICANE-CAROLINA,
09-21 -- A National Guard truck drives past the Riverview Hotel in
Kinston where water from the Neuse River continued to rise on
Tuesday. More rain fell on North Carolina today, a dismal and
unwelcome sight to tens of thousands who have had homes damaged by
the floods caused by Hurricane Floyd or are in shelters because
they are unable to return home because of the rising water levels.
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) SPEEDWELL, N.J. -- Sept. 21, 1999 --
OCEAN-SPRAY-OUTLOOK, 09-21 -- Cranberry workers harvesting the crop
at the Lee Brothers in 1997. Ocean Spray, who sells about $1.4
billion worth of cranberry drinks and other products, is besieged
by crises ranging from an oversupply of cranberries to increased
competition. Ocean Spray has sharply cut the price it pays farmers
for the fruit. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) READING, Mass. -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- RAIDED-WORKERS-BOS,
09-21 --At Jupiter Electric, the Marshall Family, from left,
Maureen, Wayne and James, were victims of ``stripping.'' The
practice of ``stripping'' is when union organizers in the
construction trades raid small and midsized nonunion contractors of
skilled workers and offer them to contractors who have signed union
agreements. As a result, shops are losing employees in a tough
labor market where replacements are hard to find. (Janet
Knott/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 21, 1999 --
GLF-RYDER-MECCA-BOS, 09-21 -- As if the USA golf bag with orange
tiger heads covering the clubs wasn't enough, a sign tells
on-lookers that Tiger Woods is hitting practice balls. The Ryder
Cup is likely to draw a higher concentration of business executives
than other sports spectacles like the Super Bowl and college
basketball's Final Four. It has become the ultimate event for
business in the ultimate sport for business. (Jim Davis/Boston
Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 21, 1999 --
GLF-RYDER-PARNEVIK-BOS, 09-21 -- Jesper Parnevik ponders a putt
during practice for the Ryder Cup. Parnevik is one of the world's
finest golfers, a winner on both the European and US PGA tours,
twice the British Open runner-up, and a member of the team that
retained the Ryder Cup against the United States at Valderrama,
Spain, two years ago. He will be at The Country Club in Brookline
this weekend as Europe tries to make it three in a row. (Barry
Chin/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 21, 1999 - CLINTON-TRAVEL, 09-21 --
Sen. Larry Craig, R-Idaho, right, listens to a question from a
reporter while Sen. Jeff Sessions, right, R-Ala., holds a report
from the General Accounting Office detailing the cost of three
presidential trips during a news conference on Tuesday. The report
indicated that Clinton's travels to Africa, China, and Chile had
cost the government $72.1 million and the Senators characterized
the expense as excessive. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 21, 1999 - TRADE-REPORT, 09-21 --
Treasury Secretary Lawrence Summers during his appearance before
the House Banking Committee on Tuesday. Another leap in the United
States trade deficit in July raised new fears on Tuesday that a
surge in imports is threatening the health of the dollar, and
helped send the Dow Jones Industrial average down 200-plus points.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- Sept. 21, 1999 --
ASIANAMERICAN-POLITICS-2, 09-21 -- Thomas Chan, a founder of the
newly formed Asian Pacific American Bar Association from his
office. ``I think this has been a great experience,'' he says of
the scandal surrounding Asian-Americans charged of improper
political fund-raising. `` Finally, there's something galvanizing
the Asian-American community.'' (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) FRIENDLY HILLS, Calif. -- Sept. 21, 1999 --
ASIANAMERICAN-POLITICS-1, 09-21 -- Mary Miyashita, a highly
regarded Democratic fund-raiser for more than 40 years, holds a
donor list in the backyard of her home. Like many Asian-Americans,
Ms. Miyashita feels that Victor W. Hwang was unfairly vilified in
the fund-raising scandal, less because of any violations of the law
than because of his Asian ancestry. (Edward Carreon/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- CLEMENCY-CONGRESS, 09-21
-- Retired Detectives Richard Pastorella, is comforted by his
former Anthony Senft during their testimony before the House
Committee on Government Reform on Tuesday. Pastorella lost five
fingers and was left blind after he tried to disarm a bomb across
the street from police headquarters in New York in 1982. Sneft lost
an eye in the explosion. The Puerto Rican nationalist group known
by its initials FALN claimed responsibility for the 1982 bombing.
(Shana Raab/ New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. -- Sept. 21, 1999 - TALENT-AGENT,
09-21 --James Wiatt in the screening room of the William Morris
Agency. Wiatt's departure from International Creative Management to
join William Morris has roiled Hollywood's talent agency business.
(Marissa Roth/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) BELGRADE -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- YUGOSLAVIA-POLITICS, 09-21
-- Protesters, one seen through a portrait of President Slobodan
Milosevic, during a demonstration against the Yugoslav leader on
Tuesday. Tens of thousands of angry Serbs shouting ``Slobo Go
Away,'' demanded Milosevic step down. The demonstration marked the
start of a nationwide opposition campaign to force the hard-line
leader from office. (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- ROAST-CHICKEN-2, 09-21 --
At Daniel, roast chicken is served in easy-to-eat pieces. Chefs
have raised the bar, demanding better chickens to work with and
tossing aside classic roasting techniques to develop better ones.
(Boyd Hagen/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- ROAST-CHICKEN-1, 09-21 --
Roast chicken at Gramercy Tavern is teamed with morels, asparagus,
artichokes, fennel and roasted tomatoes. ``I have it because this
chicken is so good it's worth being on the menu,'' says Tom
Colicchio, the chef at Gramercy Tavern, who uses organic,
free-range chickens. (Michael Rogol/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) UNDATED -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- COOKING-RADISHES, 09-21 --
Radishes have been cultivated for so long that they actually
predate written history. Today, radishes turn up in Mexican,
Indian, Chinese, Japanese, Thai, North African, French, Italian and
Russian cookbooks, but they are barely on the culinary radar in
this country. (Tony Cenicola/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) UNDATED -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- PORK-EATING-WELL, 09-21 --
Paul Willis, a coordinator for Niman Ranch's pork program, with
pigs being raised the old-fashioned way. The pigs sold under the
brand Niman Ranch, are raised on small family farms, not indoors at
factory farms that are similar to modern-day chicken houses, with
thousands of animals kept close together. (New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) LODI, N.J. -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- HURRICANE-NY, 09-21 --
Rosalia Invorvaia walks outside her home where she has piled up
damaged belongings on Tuesday. Invorvaia's basement was flooded by
heavy rains from Hurricane. Days after the storm whipped through
the area, many people are still reeling from its aftereffects.
(Keith Meyers/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 21, 1999 - U.N.-CLINTON-3, 09-21
-- President Clinton joins U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
center; South African President Thabo Mbeki, right, and other
leaders in a toast at a luncheon honoring heads of state and
government taking part in this year's U.N. General Assembly session
on Tuesday. In his address before the world body, Clinton
challenged the U.N. and countries in Africa, Asia and elsewhere to
strengthen their ability to stop mass killings like those in Kosovo
and East Timor. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CARACAS, Venezuela -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN,
SEPT. 26 --VENEZUELA-ECONOMY-COX, 09-21 -- Soaring unemployment,
political unrest, restive labor unions, stifled consumer spending:
the portrait of Venezuela's economy is not one to invite a stampede
of foreign investment. Yet American companies are already here in a
big way, their names a part of Caracas' landscape like this
McDonald's restaurant looming over a park in the Venezuelan
capital. (Mike Williams/Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) UNDATED -- Sept. 21, 1999 - OBIT-MRAZ-B&AMP;W, 09-19 --
Charles Mraz, tends to his honey bees in this 1975 file photo.
Mraz, an inventive beekeeper who since the 1930's had been the
country's leading evangelist for the therapeutic use of bee stings,
a still unproven treatment, died on Monday at his home in
Middlebury, Vt. He was 94. Mraz was widely known among beekeepers
for developing a hardy strain of bees well suited to survive in the
chilly Champlain in Vermont and for figuring out how to get cranky
bees safely out of the way so honey could be harvested more easily.
(New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 21, 1999 - U.N.-CLINTON-2, 09-21
-- From left, U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Richard Holbrooke,
National Security Advisor Sandy Berger and Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright listen to President Clinton's address to the
United Nations General Assembly on Tuesday. Clinton told delegates
that the U.N. must play a very large role in preventing mass
slaughter and dislocation of innocent people in conflicts such as
Kosovo, East Timor and elsewhere around the world. (Paul
Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 21, 1999 --
GLF-RYDER-CUP-2-BOS, 09-21 - U.S. Ryder Cup team members Payne
Stewart, left, sits on Mark O'Meara, during a practice session at
The Country Club on Tuesday. The European team defends its
possession of the Ryder Cup against the U.S. in competition
beginning September 24. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BROOKLINE, Mass. -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- GLF-RYDER-CUP-BOS,
09-21 --Ben Crenshaw, left, captain of the U.S. Ryder Cup team,
holds the Ryder Cup while joking with fellow team member Tiger
Woods on Tuesday at The Country Club. The European team will defend
its possession of the Ryder cup against the U.S. in competition
beginning September 24. (Jim Davis/Boston Globe Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) UNITED NATIONS -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- U.N.-CLINTON, 09-21
-- President Clinton waits to be introduced to the United Nations
General Assembly before his address on Tuesday. Clinton told
delegates that the United Nations must play a very large role in
preventing mass slaughter and dislocation of innocent people in
conflicts such as Kosovo, East Timor and elsewhere around the
world. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
