<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Tuesday, 09/21/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) PHILADELPHIA -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- MEDICARE-HMOS, 09-21
-- Esther Welsh and her husband David go over their prescription
medication at a senior center in July. The Welshs spend about $150
in medications per month. The Clinton Administration said on
Tuesday that health maintenance organizations would no longer
provide free drug coverage to any Medicare recipients next year,
and White House officials expressed alarm about the trend toward
fewer benefits and higher prices. (Nicole Bengiveno/New York Times
Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- FILIBUSTER-CONGRESS,
09-21 -- Sen. Orin Hatch, R-Utah, chairman of the Senate Judiciary
Committee, speaks to reporters on Capitol Hill on Tuesday.
Underlying the current convoluted political maneuvering on the Hill
is a complaint shared by Senate Democrats and the White House that
most of President Clinton's judicial nominees have been languishing
in the Senate. At the same time, Senate Democrats and the White
House insist, the Republicans are pushing through with
extraordinary speed the nomination of Ted Stewart, a friend of Sen.
Hatch. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- BRADLEY-MOYNIHAN, 09-21
-- Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the four-term Democrat from New
York who will retire after this term, will endorse former Senator
Bill Bradley for president on Thursday in New York City. The
endorsement could potentially provide Bradley with a lift in the
state's crucial primary and among independent Democrats across the
country. Moynihan is seen in a 1997 file photo. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) BOUND BROOK, N.J. -- Sept. 21, 1999 - HURRICANE-NY-2,
09-21 -- Victoria Leon stands next to a table full of trinkets she
saved from her flooded home on Tuesday. As the nation's top
emergency management official visited New Jersey on Tuesday to try
to reassure residents of flood-damaged communities, more rain fell,
raising rivers and anxiety levels. (Norman Y Lono/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) NEW YORK -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- MRSBRADLEY-PROFILE, 09-21
-- Ernestine Schlant, professor of German and Comparative
Literature at Montclair State University and wife of presidential
candidate Bill Bradley, during an interview on Tuesday. At 64, she
has written five books, raised two daughters (one is from an
earlier marriage) and survived breast cancer and a mastectomy in
1992. She has the spirit of someone who is living on extra time.
``Whenever I speak with breast cancer survivors, we all agree that
life after cancer is better than it was before,'' she said.
(Librado Romero/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) PLUMB ISLAND, N.Y. -- Sept. 21, 1999 -- --
SCI-ISLAND-LAB-2, 09-21 -- From left, Drs. Tom Burrage, Steven
Kleibocker and Daniel Rock, at an electron microscope on Plumb
Island where the Agriculture Department operates a laboratory where
foreign animal diseases such as the dreaded foot-and-mouth and
African swine fever are studied. The department is now seeking
money to turn the island research center into the sort of top
security laboratory at which the most dangerous animal diseases
that can affect humans can be examined. (The Plum Island Animal
Disease Center /New York Times Photo)
</P>
