<SLUG> BC-NASDAQ-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: NASDAQ, ONCE HOT FOR A PUBLIC ISSUE, NOW HEADING
PRIVATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By DIANA B. HENRIQUES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Just a few months ago, the buzz among the NASDAQ
market's members and advisers was IPO _ an initial public offering
of NASDAQ shares that would transform the market where some of
America's hottest technology stocks are traded.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, the talk has shifted. Now, the emphasis is on a
private placement, an arrangement that would allow the National
Association of Securities Dealers, NASDAQ's owner, to sell a
minority part of its stake privately to outsiders, including Wall
Street firms and even technology giants like Microsoft and Intel.
</P>
<P>
   For NASD leadership at least, a private placement would be an
interim step toward the goal of a public offering of NASDAQ shares.
But the placement, expected to be on the agenda for discussion when
the NASDAQ board meets in two weeks, raises two serious questions
for the association and its chief executive, Frank Zarb.
</P>
<P>
   Can Zarb attract the strong investors he needs? And can he do so
without alienating the small brokerage firms, which may feel
threatened if their giant rivals become the dominant investors in
the new NASDAQ market?
</P>
<P>
   On the first issue, early signs are encouraging. A Wall Street
executive who has been briefed on the association's plans said that
major investment banks have already been approached about the
possibility of taking a minority stake in the NASDAQ market, and
have been ``impressed by how forward-looking this really is.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he confirmed that there were plans to offer some of
those shares to certain NASDAQ-listed companies like Microsoft and
Intel. ``By bringing in the leading listed companies, there is a
much higher likelihood that those and other companies like them
would remain listed on the NASDAQ system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That should not come as a surprise, several market executives
said privately. In the fine print of a news release that NASD
issued in July, one item on a list of next steps was ``move toward
a possible private placement to key participants,'' including
companies whose shares are listed on NASDAQ and technology
partners.
</P>
<P>
   But as for the second question, Zarb obviously still faces a
delicate balancing act. The association's leadership still hopes
that it can eventually spin off NASDAQ as a publicly traded
company, with a private placement as a sort of halfway house on the
road to public ownership sometime in the future, perhaps by the end
of next year.
</P>
<P>
   A private stock sale would generate cash to help finance the
association's regulatory arm, which would remain under the control
of the parent group. And, advocates say, a private sale might
inject healthy profit motives into an organization that has
sometimes been hamstrung by competing interests.
</P>
<P>
   Private placements have been done by several foreign stock
exchanges that subsequently became publicly traded companies,
according to Benn Steil, a senior fellow in foreign economic policy
at the Council on Foreign Relations in New York. ``But the key to
its effectiveness is to make sure that the shareholder base is as
diverse as possible,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If powerful NASDAQ companies like Microsoft and Intel are being
invited to participate in the private placement, along with giant
Wall Street firms and active NASDAQ market makers, that could be a
very healthy development, Steil added.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Microsoft only owns 1 percent of NASDAQ, then their
ambition will be to maximize the value of those shares, whereas if
all the shares are given to members, that would not be the case,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, he said, if NASD members are able to limit
the private placement to themselves _ or if no more than a minority
stake is ever sold to outsiders _ it would probably have little
effect on NASDAQ's ability to confront the competition it now faces
from the stock trading services called electronic communications
networks, or ECNs.
</P>
<P>
   In the last year, NASDAQ and the New York Stock Exchange have
explored the possibility of changing their ownership structure so
that they can better compete with these new rivals for America's
stock-trading business.
</P>
<P>
   Both markets are, in effect, owned by their members. But while
the Big Board's members own the exchange directly through their
ownership of seats, association members have only an indirect stake
in the NASDAQ market, John Coffee Jr., a securities law professor
at Columbia University, noted.
</P>
<P>
   The NASDAQ market, created in 1969, is already structured as a
for-profit company with shares of stock outstanding. But all of
those shares are owned by NASD, a nonprofit association with a
33-member board representing roughly 5,500 member firms.
</P>
<P>
   Because those members have competing and sometimes conflicting
interests, the association's leadership has not been able to
respond quickly enough to new competitors in new technologies,
Coffee said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What brought all this about was the inability of the NASD
leadership to get the small broker-dealers to buy into their
vision,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   If theory, the association's board could sell a minority stake
to outside investors without a full membership vote, since the
association would still retain control of NASDAQ.
</P>
<P>
   But Zarb and his staff are very sensitive to the views of the
organization's smaller members, according to the executive who has
been briefed on the association's plans. ``I don't think they are
going to go too far down the road without trying to make sure that
they have support from the membership,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The next test will come at the association's board meeting Oct.
7, when the organization continues its discussions about the future
of NASDAQ.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
