r f BC-UCLA-STUDY-LADN     09-21 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UCLA-STUDY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA PREDICTS GOLDEN ERA FOR STATE WILL END
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY   J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- California's economy will remain in a growth mode
over the next 20 years, but don't expect a sequel to the Golden
State's gilded past, concluded a long-range forecast released
Wednesday by UCLA's Anderson School.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, the state will close out the century on a strong
note, with nonfarm employment growing 3.4 percent this year, almost
matching the average annual increase from 1950 through 1990.
Coupled with 1998's rate of 3.7 percent, the last two years of this
tumultuous decade will be the best.
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA's economic forecast predicts job growth to fall sharply
next year before settling into a sustainable rate of 2.1 percent
over the long term. In the four decades between 1950 and 1990, the
state churned out jobs at a 3.5 percent annual growth rate, nearly
double that of the nation's.
</P>
<P>
   California will be able to maintain that kind of gap but not the
pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is unlikely, however, that the next 20 years in California
will see a repeat of the golden era of the 1950s, '60s, '70s and
'80s,'' said economist Tom K. Lieser, executive director of the
UCLA Business Forecasting Project.
</P>
<P>
   And while the state is entering the next decade from a position
of economic strength, the dynamics of today are vastly different
from those of the past. So too is the world stage, always a big
role player in the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the 1980s, the United States was fighting the
Cold War, much to the benefit of California's defense industry.
Home computers were an oddity, not a commodity.
</P>
<P>
   The reverse of that is true today, major factors that led to a
total restructuring of the state's economy.
</P>
<P>
   The maturing of this new economy should see the creation of 8.2
million jobs over the next two decades, bringing the state's total
to 21.85 million jobs, said Lieser's forecast. More than half of
the increase will come from firms that provide a variety of
business services.
</P>
<P>
   Here is a snapshot of UCLA's take on California:
</P>
<P>
   The expanding economy will be led by a robust service sector;
Lieser predicts that 20 years from now, residents will take care of
most of their finances online. The most dynamic element has been
and will continue to be high-tech services such as software
development and other data processing activities.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace has reached critical mass and further large cuts are
not likely, but growth of in-state production and employment will
be limited. California will still be a top-flight location for
research and development.
</P>
<P>
   Agriculture was the state's other major industry 10 years ago,
and the farm sector is still strong today. It will remain a growth
sector.
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment will remain above 5 percent during the next 20
years, above the national average, as the state continues to draw
new residents.
</P>
<P>
   Real personal income will grow by 3.3 percent annually through
2020.
</P>
<P>
   Permits for new residential construction will average about
220,000 annually between 2006 and 2020.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Gibson, chief economist for the California Department of
Finance, said the UCLA forecast is not overly optimistic. His
department only looks 10 years into the future, and the forecast is
for job growth of 2.2 percent annually for the last five years of
the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big news, of course, is that it's still twice the U.S.
(rate). The big difference now is demographics. Things are just not
as favorable for employment growth over the next 20 years as they
have been for the last 50 years,'' Gibson said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, UCLA's long-range forecast this year is not different
from the one issued at this time last year. The biggest difference,
Lieser noted, is pegging the state's population at 47.7 million by
2020, a reduction of 2 million from last year's forecast.
</P>
<P>
   And while the state will be more crowded in 20 years, it's a
condition that California residents have coped with in the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day-to-day life is similar. The sun shines, and we're still
clearly different from most other places in the nation,'' Lieser
said. ``It just takes a little more time out of your day to deal
with the congestion. And you may have to work a little harder or
longer to keep up with the house payments.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
