<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0743 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-GLF-RYDER-PRIDE-COX     09-21 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-PRIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. tries to quiet money flap
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ A month ago, they were branded as Malcontents
at Medinah. Some were campaigning for payment from the Ryder Cup,
charitable or otherwise, and getting ripped publicly by others.
Their captain boiled over at a PGA Championship news conference,
singling out players with misplaced priorities. A week later, one
of them called the captain ``out of line.''
</P>
<P>
   So much for ideal Ryder Cup preparation. U.S. captain Ben
Crenshaw surely must need an electron microscope to measure team
cohesion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the guys concentrate on winning and forget about
all the controversy,'' three-time Ryder Cup participant Paul
Azinger said. ``If there's animosity, I think that's the only way
we can lose.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is no evidence that the team has been fatally
fragmented. The Americans, who begin Ryder Cup play Friday against
the Europeans, might not have become ``The Waltons'' since Medinah,
but they appear to be focused. Satisfied that the PGA of America
will have some form of charitable donation plan in place later this
year, the players and Crenshaw insist that the issue is dead.
</P>
<P>
   They met Monday at a Boston restaurant for a causal lobster
dinner with wives or girlfriends, laughed a lot and continued the
bonding process. David Duval led the team in a song that neither he
nor a grinning Tiger Woods cared to detail for the media. They also
appointed Justin Leonard to give a statement in Tuesday morning's
opening news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know we're going to get asked about compensation, so I'd
like to put an end to that right now,'' Leonard said. ``We're here
to play the matches, and compensation is no longer a part of this
with the players. . . . If we could just keep the questions away
from that . . . we would all really appreciate it.''
</P>
<P>
   It is not a forgotten issue. The daily view of The Country
Club's sea of corporate tents will serve as a reminder of the
event's financial power _ revenue reportedly is $63 million _ but
the U.S. players seem genuinely united in their mission to reclaim
the Cup after two consecutive losses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't noticed a lot of nonunity from the beginning,'' Jeff
Maggert said. ``I don't think anyone was really mad at other
players. . . . I really think (for) all the players, that's ancient
history, what happened a month ago at Medinah. We're ready to play
some golf.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're very unified,'' Mark O'Meara said. ``Ben is a
great guy. I think no one denies that. He's got a lot of emotion, a
lot of fire; he showed that (at Medinah). And he has a lot of
compassion for the game and for the Ryder Cup. I know that Ben
probably feels badly about what happened. I feel badly that that
happened. . . . But I think we're all on the same page. I don't
think the players at any time were ever thinking about boycotting
the Ryder Cup. They know it's an honor.''
</P>
<P>
   The Europeans have seemed somewhat aghast that a financial issue
could dominate a competition built on emotion and pride. England's
Lee Westwood has been among the most critical of the American
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we play for money 51 weeks of the year,'' Westwood
said, ``so one week playing for pride and honor is not too much to
ask. . . . I grew up watching Nick Faldo, Seve Ballesteros, Ian
Woosnam and people like that, and the last thing on their mind
looked to be money. You knew they were there for the honor of
representing their country and their continent. That's the way I
was brought up. I just don't think money should come into it at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   This time, Europe has managed to lead up to the matches without
controversy. Two years ago, some wondered about their cohesion
after the flap that pushed injured Miguel Angel Martin off the
squad. They won anyway. This year, despite seven rookies and some
controversy about European captain Mark James' selection of young
Andrew Coltart instead of veteran Bernhard Langer, Europe's image
sparkles. Its players seem looser, perhaps a result of the U.S.
team facing more pressure, particularly on home soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our focus is solely on winning the Cup back,'' said
Tom Lehman, who with Payne Stewart, is expected to emerge as a team
leader. ``We haven't won for a few years, and I know, personally,
I'm sick and tired of being on a losing team.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Sheeley writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
