<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0745 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-MONROE-PIANO-SALE-$AD     09-21 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONROE-PIANO-SALE-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ALCHEMY OF AN ICON: MARILYN MONROE AT AUCTION  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT., 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 Mitchell Owens is a contributing writer for Architectural Digest.  
 By MITCHELL OWENS 
  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ As grand pianos go, the one going on the block at
Christie's next month is nothing special. Paderewski did not play
it. Neither did Liberace, though he would have swooned over its
fondant-white finish and maybe added some stylistic flourishes of
his own.
</P>
<P>
   And as far as Christie's knows, no one but Marilyn Monroe, its
last owner, ever tickled its ivories, though it is possible that
Frank Sinatra, a Monroe beau, might have plunked out a tune or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing we do know for certain is that it needs
tuning,'' said Vredy Lytsman, a spokeswoman for Christie's.
</P>
<P>
   Out of tune and bearing a few bumps and scratches, the baby
grand piano is a highlight of the sale of Marilyn Monroe's personal
effects at Christie's new salerooms at Rockefeller Center on Oct.
27 and 28. Like most of the celebrity-driven sales of late, this
one offers lots (more than 1,000) that range widely in quality,
from the brash (the transparent Jean-Louis sequinned gown she wore
to serenade John F. Kennedy at his Madison Square Garden birthday
extravaganza in 1962) to the banal (the kind of battered
mass-produced 1950s furniture found in any thrift shops).
</P>
<P>
   Stored since the actress' death in 1963, at 35, the belongings
are being sold by the heirs of Lee Strasberg, the acting coach, to
whom Monroe's will left ``all of my personal effects and
clothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Charles Foster Kane's sled, Rosebud, the piano is a
touchstone in Monroe's history, the sole surviving relic of a
childhood that, while sad, was not as Dickensian as Monroe's
overzealous press agents _ and the actress herself _ often claimed.
</P>
<P>
   Background information provided by Christie's states that the
piano was sold, along with the rest of the family's belongings,
after her mother, Gladys Baker, a film lab technician at Columbia
Pictures, was hospitalized with paranoid schizophrenia and her
younger daughter, Norma Jeane, was placed in an orphanage. It is
expected to bring $10,000 to $15,000, but, given its celebrity
ownership, it will doubtless bring much more.
</P>
<P>
   As the official Monroe narrative goes, she stumbled across it at
another auction, and the struggling actress and model shuttled it
from one Southern California storage unit to another until she was
able to move it into her own home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even when I didn't have enough money to eat, I borrowed money
to keep that piano in storage,'' the actress said an early
interview, her comments shaped and dramatized at the encouragement
of her press agent and her guardian-business manager, Grace
Goddard. Whether Goddard and the agent came up with the piano's
provenance, too, is unknown _ it reportedly was once owned by the
movie star Frederic March _ but Monroe's feelings for the piano
seemed genuine. ``My happiest hours as a little girl were around
that piano,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   What's missing from the tale _ and the Christie's entry _ are
the details. ``My Sister, Marilyn'' (Algonquin Books, 1994), an
affecting memoir written by the actress' half-sister, Berniece
Baker Miracle, and her niece, Mona Rae Miracle, relates that the
piano was a seventh-birthday present from Monroe's mother.
</P>
<P>
   Gladys Baker bought it on credit, as she did all the furniture
in her little two-story house near the Hollywood Bowl, where Monroe
sat and practiced with a local teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Miracle (pronounced MIRE-cuhl) wrote that after her
mother's breakdown, the piano was saved by an elderly family
friend, who took over the payments and placed it in her living
room. The friend later brought Norma Jeane home, too, after it
became apparent that her mother would be unable to care for her
again. The piano lessons began anew, and Monroe passed on a bit of
that knowledge to her niece, who recalled her aunt teaching her how
to play ``Chopsticks.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, the piano accompanied Monroe from house to
house, marriage to marriage. Eventually, around 1957, it ended up
in the Manhattan apartment that she and her second husband, the
playwright Arthur Miller, bought. That is also when the
instrument's complexion went from its original classic black to
musical-comedy white.
</P>
<P>
   The three-bedroom, two-bath, 13th-floor apartment at 444 East
57th Street was decorated in a movie-star chic style befitting
America's reigning silver-screen beauty. Apartment 138 was,
Beatrice Miracle recalled, ``a world of white'' reflected in a
multiplicity of mirrors: white walls, white furniture, white
louvered doors, white carved fireplace and, in a surprising touch
of sophisticated whimsy, a 1930s white plaster floor lamp by the
French designer Serge Roche, shaped liked a palm tree (a presale
estimate of $2,000 to $3,000).
</P>
<P>
   ``Decorating takes my worries away,'' said the actress, who even
had a white poodle, a gift from Sinatra.
</P>
<P>
   To fit in with the blanched scheme, the piano was custom-coated
with shining white lacquer, thick enough to obscure the
manufacturer's name on the keyboard cover. ``Unknown American
manufacturer'' is Christie's best guess. The actress' sister wrote
that it was made by Franklin, a company that a sales manager at
Steinway identified as the Franklin Piano Co. of New York City,
which manufactured inexpensive but well-constructed instruments
from 1900 until 1933.
</P>
<P>
   Though the piano was always front and center in Monroe's
surroundings, it seems that the platinum-blond bombshell was, at
the end of the day, a typical music-loving homeowner with memories
of afterschool arpeggios.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't play,'' she told her sister. Which explains,
perhaps, why it was more often used as a display stand for a vase
of her favorite flowers, red anthuriums.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
