<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-A&AMP;M-OFFENSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS A&AMP;M'S OFFENSE FACING FIRST TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MIKE JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLLEGE STATION, Texas _ Texas A&AMP;M running back Dante Hall was
surprised yesterday to learn that the fifth-ranked Aggies are
second nationally in total offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are?'' Hall said. ``Hey, that feels good. I feel proud.
Times change, don't they?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. The Aggies' offense was 91st in Division I-A last
season. One of coach R.C. Slocum's off-season goals was to
dramatically improve that standing. Early returns indicate
resounding success. After two games, A&AMP;M is averaging 538.5 yards a
game, 0.17 of a yard behind national leader Louisville.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies also rank second nationally with a 49.5-point scoring
average, behind Louisville's 50 points a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that says that finally things are coming together a
little bit,'' quarterback Randy McCown said. ``We've always had a
great defense. Now, we've got a pretty good offense as well.''
</P>
<P>
   How good remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's game at Kyle Field against Southern Mississippi (2-1)
might shed more light. The Golden Eagles' defense (No. 19
nationally) held Nebraska to 185 yards total offense and gave up
only one offensive touchdown in last week's 20-13 loss on the
Cornhuskers' turf. Nebraska had not been handcuffed offensively
like that since gaining only 179 yards against Oklahoma in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt Southern Miss has an excellent defense,'' A&AMP;M
offensive coordinator Steve Kragthorpe said. ``We respected them
before. The country respects them now because of what they did last
week.''
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles held A&AMP;M to 171 yards offense last season, though A&AMP;M
won 24-6 as the Aggies' defense forced five turnovers that resulted
in 13 points. Hall, playing with a sore hamstring, led the limited
offense with touchdown runs of 44 and 16 yards, gaining 76 yards on
eight carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will be the most confusing defense we play all year,''
Hall said. ``They move around a lot and don't give you time to
read. It will definitely be a test.''
</P>
<P>
   Slocum is looking for a better yardstick to judge his offense
after victories over Louisiana Tech and Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to proclaim that we are a great offensive team
at this time because I don't think we are,'' Slocum said. ``I don't
think we've been tested under fire yet. We haven't had to line up
and really grind it out yet. I expect we \Rmight have to\S this
week, and that will be good for us.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
