<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0749 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BIBLE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV     09-21 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIBLE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING NEW PICTURES TO FAMILIAR OLD WORDS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Mass.)  (af) 
 Miles Unger's most recent article for Arts &AMP; Leisure was about the
Boston Cyberarts Festival.  
 By MILES UNGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HATFIELD, Mass. _ In the beginning was the word. The pictures,
as every illustrator knows, can only follow, flowing from those
words but also subtly shaping their course, directing our gaze here
or there and fixing vividly in our minds the more abstract and
open-ended text.
</P>
<P>
   Who today can read Scripture immune to the blandishments of
Raphael's pretty, blond Madonnas or picture David without the
perfect physique Michelangelo gave him?
</P>
<P>
   Putting pictures to words is Barry Moser's profession, but never
has the challenge been greater than in his latest project: a
monumental, fully illustrated version of the King James Bible. Not
only is this the most central, most revered and surely most
contested text in our culture, but it is one already firmly fixed
in our collective minds by religious inclination and by the
countless artists who have already left their mark.
</P>
<P>
   Moser, while keenly aware of those precedents and
preconceptions, has approached this daunting project by returning
to the words themselves to confront familiar stories as if for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the millenniums-old project of depicting religious
stories in books, paintings and sculpture, when Moser's Pennyroyal
Caxton Bible comes out on Friday it will be the first time a major
artist has illustrated the complete texts of both the Old and New
Testaments since the French artist Gustave Dore's Bible of 1865.
</P>
<P>
   The rarity of modern illustrated Bibles is not difficult to
explain. Philip Cronenwett, the special collections librarian at
Dartmouth College, points out that the popularity of illustrated
Bibles declined in the 15th century with the invention of printing,
which increased literacy and decreased the need for didactic visual
accompaniment.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps an even more critical reason for artistic caution is the
realization that any image is an act of interpretation that cannot
possibly please each of the many groups that regard the text as
divine revelation. ``It's scary for an artist to approach something
like this,'' says Cronenwett. ``You're taking theology into your
hands.''
</P>
<P>
   Moser, a burly, white-bearded man with an irreverent sense of
humor and an oratorical flourish that betrays his Tennessee
origins, does not seem intimidated, apparently relishing the
thought that his choices will ruffle a few feathers. Armed with
decades of experience as one of America's foremost illustrators and
book designers and a youthful interlude as a Methodist preacher _ a
vocation prompted by a near miss by a hunter's bullet _ Moser seems
more than ready to take on the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   For the opening image of this Bible, ``Adam and Eve in the
Garden of Eden,'' he had originally toyed with the idea of giving
the first couple African features: ``I decided that since all the
evidence points to the human race originating in Africa, I was
going to make (italics)my(end italics) Adam and Eve black,'' Moser
recalls, grinning slyly.
</P>
<P>
   While he eventually rejected the idea, he struggled to find an
appropriate form in which to represent the father and mother of all
humanity. ``Much as I would like to fly in the face of the white
establishment, especially the ultra-right-wing Christian groups,
and show a black Adam and Eve, I ultimately didn't, because the
question is: Whose literature is it? And the answer is: It's Jewish
literature. And who did the Jewish writers have in mind? Jews _ not
Africans, not Scandinavians.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Moser showed Adam and Eve at a distance, their faces
deep in shadow, a solution that allowed him to remain true to the
text while giving them an iconic universality. ``I wrestled with
the problem, and that wrestling is what ultimately gave rise to
that particular image.''
</P>
<P>
   This wrestling is typical of Moser, who relies on the text to
jolt the reader from the comfortable expectations that can be a
barrier to understanding.
</P>
<P>
   For his ``Tower of Babel,'' Moser has avoided the usual
cloud-scraping turret, directing our gaze instead to a stretch of
barren land on which we see only the base of an apparently massive
edifice. It is an image that emphasizes desolation. ``What struck
me on the umpteenth reading,'' he explains, ``was that what
happened was, the inability to communicate caused everyone to
leave. They abandoned the place.''
</P>
<P>
   Through his choice of image, Moser has shifted the emphasis from
the line ``Let us build us a city and a tower, whose top may reach
unto heaven,'' to ``So the Lord scattered them abroad from thence
upon the face of all the earth,'' in keeping with his often dark
vision of Scripture.
</P>
<P>
   Moser, despite his brief association with organized religion and
an abiding interest in what he calls ``the idea of God,''
subscribes to no particular creed, and this has freed him to tell
the story in his idiosyncratic way. His hope is to ``make the book
more accessible in the intimacy of the imagery.''
</P>
<P>
   One characteristic of Moser's interpretation is its
human-centered drama, particularly when compared with Dore's
cast-of-thousands pageantry, which could well have served as the
model for many a Hollywood epic.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pervasive sense of solitude that reveals much about
Moser's approach to religious experience. ``If we think about God
at all, we think about it in our own heads, and in our quiet
moments, when we're alone,'' he says. ``One's relationship with God
is necessarily a private and solitary thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of the images, from ``Joseph in Prison'' to the
``Annunciation'' to the deeply moving image of Christ raising his
cup to proclaim ``This is my blood of the new testament, which is
shed for many,'' emphasize the frailty of the solitary man or woman
who must bear the weight of the world. It is a world in which the
actions and convictions of fallible humans count for more than the
supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   ``The entire Bible is moved along by people, it's about
people,'' Moser insists. A haunting image of Abraham and Isaac
reveals no interceding angel to stop the hand of the grieving
father, and the ``Annunciation'' shows Mary alone with her
thoughts. Even Satan, though certainly a sinister-looking
character, makes a solo entrance without his usual pyrotechnics.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   While Moser has very much taken his own tack, he has enlisted a
team of advisers to steer him clear of potential missteps. In
addition to hewing closely to the text, he looked for guidance to
the Midrash, the medieval Jewish commentary on Scripture. According
to Professor Shalom Goldman of Emory University, who served on his
advisory panel, ``Not only did he not want to offend anyone, but I
think he wanted to actively respect the Jewish tradition. His
approach was to be inclusive.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, however, the Pennyroyal Caxton edition, named for
Moser's press and his sponsor's company, is not a work of theology
but of art. At $10,000 a copy _ a trade edition will be available
from Viking Studio for $65 _ this two volume, 1,100-page work is of
superb craftsmanship meant for the rarefied fine-book market, where
bibliophiles are willing to pay for hand binding, archival paper
and old-fashioned letterpress printing.
</P>
<P>
   Claudia Cohen and Sarah Creighton, bookbinders in whose
Easthampton, Mass., studios the Bibles are being assembled, explain
the cost as a factor not only of the materials _ including the
imported vellum used for the covers and custom-manufactured paper
imported from Germany _ but also of the hours of skilled labor
demanded by a technology that has remained essentially unchanged
for centuries.
</P>
<P>
   Moser, while uncomfortable with the elitism implied in the
five-figure price tag and the limited edition of 400, is a
perfectionist unwilling to cut corners and sparing neither himself
nor his potential buyers. Not only has he engraved each of the
roughly 230 images himself _ Dore, in contrast, shipped out his
drawings to professional engravers _ but he labored on almost every
aspect of the book's design.
</P>
<P>
   Countless hours were spent finding exactly the right typeface to
stand up to the density of the engraved images _ he finally hit on
a 13-point Galliard and commissioned a new set of Hebrew letters
from Matthew Carter, its designer _ and he recalls the agonizing
process of tinkering with the exact dimensions of the gutter
between the two columns of type that form each page, a crucial
element in what he describes as ``the vertical monumentality of the
book.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he aims to create a masterpiece in this most traditional
of art forms, Moser is happy to employ new technologies when they
will serve to deliver the product more efficiently. (For example,
the engraving blocks he used for the images are made from a
synthetic polymer, replacing the traditional but increasingly rare
boxwood.)
</P>
<P>
   Still, the engraving technique itself _ in which the block is
carved by hand, leaving those raised areas left untouched to carry
the ink that will form the image _ is an old and notoriously
difficult medium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bear of a technique,'' Moser admits, ``mostly because
it doesn't forgive mistakes.'' Demonstrating that technique in his
light-filled, hilltop studio, he uses the time-tested tools of the
trade _ burins, spitz stickers and gravers _ to conjure deftly a
face half lost in shadow, a process he once compared to a biblical
separating of light from dark.
</P>
<P>
   Concessions to modern technology are not simply a matter of
convenience. Near the solid wooden desk with its leather engraver's
bag and hand tools sits another desk with a large computer monitor
on which many of the images for the Bible were composed through a
seamless blending of drawing and scanned, collaged photographs,
which were then transferred to the block for engraving.
</P>
<P>
   The photographic origin of many images shines through the
linear, abstract quality of the engraving medium, often giving a
startling immediacy to the scenes.
</P>
<P>
   For the image to accompany the line from Mark ``Suffer the
little children to come unto me,'' Moser has portrayed a Jesus
whose frank smile and unidealized face seem to capture a candid
moment on the wing. ``There are no made-up faces here,'' he says,
noting that he used a local chef to model for Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Reimagining this sacred cast of characters as living, breathing
men and women lies at the heart of Moser's project. For all its
traditional splendor, the Pennyroyal Caxton Bible is not a
comfortable book; it has the power to startle as readers begin to
recognize themselves in those iconic, larger-than-life characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these people are flawed,'' Moser says, ``just like the
people who will be picking up the book and reading it.'' In
bringing a sacred text down to earth, Moser may just have created
the Bible for our time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
