<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWCOMERS-FOREIGN-FIRMS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BAY AREA A BIG LURE FOR FOREIGN FIRMS TO RELOCATE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO -- Everyone talks about the problems of doing
business in the Bay Area, including highway gridlock, a serious
housing shortage, &UR;  &LR; astronomical living costs and so-so public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the region's high-tech companies are being
aggressively recruited by other states and countries.
</P>
<P>
   But not everyone is ditching the Bay Area. In fact, local
startups are getting venture capital financing in record amounts
and going public in record numbers this year.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign companies are even relocating to the area because it
remains the epicenter of the information technology revolution and
the explosive growth of the Internet and e-commerce.
</P>
<P>
   Data on the number of foreign firms moving to the bay is hard to
find but there is strong anecdotal evidence. Consider these
examples:
</P>
<P>
   -- Former Israeli paratrooper Eli &LR;   &LR; Barkat moved BackWeb
Technologies from a Tel Aviv suburb to San Jose, Calif., two years
ago because the Internet communication software market is here. The
company went public in June and is now worth more than $650
million.
</P>
<P>
   -- Germany's Marco Boerries got hooked on computers when he was
an exchange student at High School in Palo Alto, Calif., 15 years
ago. After returning to Hamburg, he dropped out of school to start
an office productivity software company called Star Division. Last
year, he moved its headquarters to Fremont, Calif., and three weeks
ago, he sold the company to Sun Microsystems in a
multimillion-dollar deal.
</P>
<P>
   -- Canadian Bill Lipsin, CEO of Ironside Technologies, relocated
the e-commerce order management software company from Toronto to
Pleasanton, Calif., a year ago at the suggestion of U.S. investors.
He figures the move has raised Ironside's credibility and should
position it for a successful public offering sometime next year.
</P>
<P>
   BackWeb's Bold Move
</P>
<P>
   Eli Barkat started BackWeb Technologies in 1995 while he was a
partner at BRM, an Israeli venture capital company. Within a year,
the company had landed a few customers for its product, which
provides Internet access to critical, time-sensitive company
information. BackWeb also was looking for more financing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to immediately establish headquarters in Silicon
Valley,'' said Barkat, 36. ``The CEO has to be where the market is.
And with the Internet, that's North America. This is the center of
gravity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm also a great believer in the influence of culture on a
company. In Silicon Valley, people live, breathe and dream the
Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   For online businesses, getting a product to market quickly to
beat competitors and build customer acceptance is crucial. ``It's
hard enough to learn about the business and build the product,''
said Barkat. ``You don't want to have to learn about the culture,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkat also moved BackWeb because he was tired of spending 90
percent of his time in the air or on the road. BackWeb opened its
headquarters in San Jose with a handful of Israeli managers and
hired local talent from companies such as Netscape, Oracle,
PeopleSoft and Silicon Graphics.
</P>
<P>
   By moving to the Bay Area, Barkat figures he had much better
success attracting key employees. ``Top executives in the valley
don't want to work for a company a 10-hour time zone away and have
to wake up in the middle of the night to convince someone about
something,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like several other foreign companies that have relocated to the
Bay Area, BackWeb kept its research and development staff back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works like a charm.'' said Barkat. BackWeb has about 200
employees, including 70 in Silicon Valley, 60 in Ramat Gan near Tel
Aviv and the rest at offices in Canada, Europe and Japan.
</P>
<P>
   In its drive to become what Barkat calls ``The FedEx of the
Internet'' in delivering time-sensitive information, BackWeb has
signed some major customers. Compaq uses it to deliver software
updates to customers of its Presario computers. Cisco Systems uses
BackWeb to deliver video alerts to thousands of salespeople, and
Hewlett-Packard uses it to update manuals of its field service
staff.
</P>
<P>
   Fulfilling the dream of most high-tech startups, BackWeb went
public in June and is now worth more than $650 million.
</P>
<P>
   Other Israeli Internet companies also are taking flight to
Silicon Valley. GuruNet, which started in Jerusalem in December to
make Web information access easier, has just set up temporary
headquarters in Palo Alto and is looking for a permanent Bay Area
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic jams or not, you have to be close to your customers
and market,'' said Chairman Robert Rosenschein, who grew up in
Pennsylvania but spent the past 16 years in Israel. The company
will keep its research staff in Israel but expects to have up to 50
local employees by the end of next year.
</P>
<P>
   GuruNet's mission is to deliver free instant information in a
simple one-click, pop-up window within any Windows application. It
delivers real-time information such as news and stock quotes as
well as dictionary and other reference information when users
simply point to words in a document.
</P>
<P>
   Another Israeli Internet software company planning to move to
Silicon Valley is Personetics. Founder and CEO Moshe Raccah, 33,
said the move ``is only a matter of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel has some of the best software engineers, and Intel, IBM
and Microsoft all have development centers in Israel. But Raccah
said, ``Most Israeli managers don't have the necessary experience
in marketing and selling to U.S. customers.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, very few Israeli venture capital firms have
participated in building top Internet companies. But Raccah noted
that perhaps the most important reason to move to Silicon Valley is
the sheer number of Internet companies. ``Being close to your
customers, your partners and your competitors, means that you will
have the opportunity to build stronger partnerships and have better
access to the information, the so-called buzz.''
</P>
<P>
   Star's Flight
</P>
<P>
   When Marco Boerries moved Star Division from Germany to Fremont
in 1998, it was almost like coming home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was infected with the Silicon Valley virus in 1884 when I
was 16 and a foreign exchange student at Palo Alto High School,''
said Boerries. ``From that point, I didn't want to go back to
Germany,''
</P>
<P>
   On his first journey to the Bay Area, Boerries stayed with an
American family who had an Apple IIe. Soon he was hooked not just
on games but on VisiCalc, the first electronic spreadsheet.
</P>
<P>
   Boerries' parents wanted him to return to Germany and he did.
But nine months after leaving Palo Alto, he dropped out of high
school and used $2,000 in savings to create what he feels is ``the
best office productivity software in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Star Division started small and remained that way for some time.
By 1996, however, it was expanding beyond Germany into the rest of
Europe before it entered the U.S. market in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That's when Boerries moved the company to Fremont and himself,
his wife and two kids to a tony Peninsula suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to explain why,'' said Boerries in perfect English.
``Silicon Valley is where dot-com strategies get born, get made,
get successful. If you are not here, you don't have the opportunity
to grow as fast and find the right partners.``
</P>
<P>
   Boerries also got tired of making eight trips a year to North
America. With 200 employees, Star Division kept its research team
in Germany and had 30 employees at Fremont headquarters, including
Boerries and three other Germans. Then three weeks ago, Boerries
sold the company in which he owns an 80 percent stake to Sun
Microsystems for undisclosed millions.
</P>
<P>
   Boerries is now Sun's vice president and general manager of
Webtop and Application Software.
</P>
<P>
   Ironside Goes for Gold
</P>
<P>
   Ironside Technologies moved from Toronto to Pleasanton a year
ago ``to gain extra credibility and access to a much larger source
of financing,'' said CEO Bill Lipsin.
</P>
<P>
   The company was started in 1995 to make e-commerce software that
would allow companies to take customer orders and fill them over
toll-free phone lines without the need for costly call center
employees. It was initially financed by Canadian companies. Later,
General Electric and Euclid Partners of New York agreed to invest,
but they suggested that the company move to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The Bay Area was the obvious choice. ``Investors pay premiums
for companies headquartered here because within 30 miles you have
unparallelled technical engineering skills, the venture capital
community and business decision-makers,'' said Lipsin.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the panache that the Bay Area adds to a name and
investment, it's the place to develop business relationships and
find partners. Such links are crucial to the success of many
e-commerce businesses, and Ironside has made several of them. For
example, it has partnered with Ariba Inc., another e-commerce
company that recently went public and has a market value topping $6
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Ironside chose Pleasanton as its new home because it noticed a
lot of East Bay residents who commuted across the bay preferred not
to. In addition, housing prices are generally less than around
Santa Clara.
</P>
<P>
   Ironside has 105 employees, including 35, mostly local hires, in
Pleasanton and 70 in Toronto, where R&AMP;D is still based.
</P>
<P>
   It's an advantage ``paying 65-cent dollars for world-class
skills in Toronto,'' said Lipsin.
</P>
<P>
   He figures it's also worth the additional costs to relocate to
Silicon Valley and capture the attention of business partners,
customers, financiers and ultimately U.S. stock market investors.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing a phrase from California's Gold Rush 150 years ago,
Lipsin said, ``We don't want to be a flash-in-the-pan IPO.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
