r f BC-SOCIAL-SOCIAL-SECURIT     09-21 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOCIAL-SOCIAL-SECURITY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 HOPE FADES FOR SOCIAL SECURITY REFORM
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DAVID LAZARUS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
Despite President Clinton's declared ambition to ``save Social
Security first,'' the ``odds have dimmed'' for reform of the system
this year, Social Security Commissioner Kenneth Apfel said in an
interview Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   And even if the system can be overhauled before retiring Baby
Boomers drive it into projected bankruptcy by 2032, Apfel conceded
that younger workers _ those now in their 30s and 40s _ will have
to finance most if not all of their retirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of Americans are going to need more than
Social Security,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Apfel was making the rounds of local media outlets to publicize
what is being billed as the ``largest customized mailing'' ever
undertaken by a federal agency. Beginning October 1, the Social
Security Administration will send out annual benefits statements to
125 million workers.
</P>
<P>
   The statements, at a cost to the government of about $70 million
a year, are intended to help people with their retirement planning.
They will include estimates of monthly payments if one retires at
62, 67 or 70, based on present earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will help people understand what Social Security is, and
what it isn't,'' Apfel said.
</P>
<P>
   What it isn't is solvent in about three decades, unless
officials in Washington decide to stop playing Frisbee with the
program and hunker down to make some serious, and politically
painful, changes.
</P>
<P>
   No one disputes that as the Boomers start heading out to
pasture, payments to Social Security beneficiaries will outstrip
taxes by as much as $10 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   The only question is what to do about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is raise the retirement age,'' said David
Levine, an associate professor of economics at the University of
California at Berkeley's Haas School of Business. ``But that would
cut back on benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Such a prospect clearly holds little favor with those of more
advanced years, who have toiled for decades with an understanding
that the ``normal retirement age,'' when full Social Security
payments kick in, will come between 65 and 67, depending on date of
birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trimming benefits is obviously the least popular alternative
as far as public opinion goes,'' said John Rother, director of
legislation and public policy for the influential American
Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had hoped that we would have gotten Social Security reform
done this year,'' he said. ``That we didn't is a disaster. The
uncertainty about the future will continue.''
</P>
<P>
   To illustrate its new benefits statement, the Social Security
Administration created a fictional 39-year-old worker earning
$68,400 a year. (Of course, the scenario assumes that the Social
Security system will remain fully functional in years ahead.)
</P>
<P>
   If this worker retired at 62, she would receive $1,105 a month
in Social Security payments (unadjusted for inflation). By retiring
at 67, she would get $1,580, and retirement at 70 would gain her a
monthly check of about $1,905.
</P>
<P>
   Those earning less than $68,400, would reap considerably less.
In any case, few such individuals would be able to get by on $1,000
to $2,000 a month.
</P>
<P>
   In his most recent State of the Union address, Clinton proposed
dedicating a projected $2.7 trillion in budget surpluses over the
next 15 years to salvaging Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   But Republican lawmakers are pushing instead for those surpluses
to be applied to a 10-year, $792 billion tax cut, which Clinton has
vowed to veto. There is no certainty that future budget windfalls
will go to Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   No less a prognosticator than Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan has called the current Social Security system
``unsustainable,'' and told Congress in January that either payroll
taxes will have to be raised or benefits cut if the program is to
survive.
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan was critical of proposals that some or all of Social
Security funds be invested in the stock market to boost their rate
of return.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Apfel isn't ruling out making such investments.
``I think it would be good to see a more diversified portfolio,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Laurence Seidman, a professor of economics at the University of
Delaware and author of the recently published book ``Funding Social
Security,'' believes the government should hire a handful of
established brokerages to manage a more aggressive mix of stock and
bonds on behalf of Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   He also sees no way around trimming benefits and boosting taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't get something for nothing,'' Seidman said. ``We have
to be willing to make sacrifices now to make the system stronger in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Apfel conceded that ``a full package'' of reforms is likely in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We may see a lower benefit structure,'' he said. ``We may also
look at raising the wage cap for payroll taxes,'' which now stands
at $72,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Social Security is not an obsolete institution,'' Apfel
stressed. ``It's been a part of the country's fabric for 65 years,
and it will be for the next 65 years.''
</P>
<P>
   One way or another.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
