<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0760 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-GROWBUSINESS-COLUMN-S     09-21 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWBUSINESS-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 SILENCE ISN'T GOLDEN IN VENTURE CAPITALISM
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By PETER SINTON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the signs that your pitch for money is going
nowhere? Venture capital firms don't always come right out and say
``no.'' And in many cases, they don't say anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   A: At last week's ``Boot Camp for Startups'' sponsored by
Garage.Com, veteran entrepreneur Kamran Elahian had several
suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   If venture capital firms do not return calls or e-mail, that's
an ominous signal, said Elahian, who has founded about 10
companies, including NeoMagic and Centillium.
</P>
<P>
   If you are lucky enough to win a face-to-face meeting and at its
conclusion the investors ``are not chomping at the bit to plan the
next meeting,'' he added, ``that's a good indication the answer is
`no.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If you are meeting with assistants instead of partners, that's
also a sign ``you still have a long way to go.''
</P>
<P>
   VCs talk about the importance of compelling business models,
competitive advantage and market potential of the companies they
invest in. But Elahian said that ultimately ``a good VC only
invests in people, good people. The rest is mumbo jumbo.``
</P>
<P>
   UCLA electrical engineering professor John Villasenor listed a
number of no-no's that will kill a VC deal: 1. refusing to divulge
key technology details; 2. bluffing about expertise or anything
else; and 3. having technical personnel who don't understand how
their work relates to the product and business strategy.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; COL. 1 of GROW22 (9381 ) &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &LR; Sites for Soar Eyes
</P>
<P>
   Q: Last week, you mentioned a number of helpful business Web
sites but you left out an awful lot of them.
</P>
<P>
   A: You're right. The problem is that there suddenly are so many
online sites specializing in helping small businesses manage their
operations, sell their products, and buy goods and services over
the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been inundated by Web-hosted services and portals
targeting small and medium-size businesses,'' said Jack Wilson,
editorial director of ComputerLetter, which is published by
Technologic Partners and this week covers the wave of venture
capital-backed startups. ``As many as 15 or 20 venture deals are
announced every day and many deal with small business.''
</P>
<P>
   The market is huge. It is estimated that more than half of the
4.3 million U.S. businesses with up to 10 employees already use the
Internet and are ripe for e-mail, online calendar, ``virtual disk''
data storage and other Web-based services.
</P>
<P>
   On the plus side, Wilson said many online sites offer small
businesses a way to get sophisticated solutions cheaply for
everything from strategic planning to managing financial and human
resources, with no need to install software or hire technical
specialists. But there are negatives, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trusting sensitive information, the life blood of your
company, to a brand new, untested and unknown quantity and hoping
the centralized system doesn't go down like eBay is a lot to ask,''
he noted. New Web companies often offer their services, or trial
memberships, for free. But be aware that once they build traffic,
they might want to sign you up for pay-only services. Free sites
also often make money if you buy from listed partners or
advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the sites I mentioned last week,
Freemerchant.com, Bigstep.com and eCongo.com are local companies
that put small businesses online with custom Web sites at no
initial cost. Another company, Hotbiz.com, offers four e-commerce
subscription services ranging from free to $30 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The flood of new sites (for sore eyes) continues: On Monday, San
Francisco's Desktop.com unveiled a free Internet service that
allows users to integrate the favorite sites, services and files.
The same day, IBM announced Small Business Web Connections. But Big
Blue is not giving its comprehensive Internet solutions away; it
will charge users at least $99 a month.  &LR; Wednesday &LR; , Microsoft is
expected to announce its own set of new small-business offerings.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
