<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0765 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-OVERLAY-AREA-CODES-SF     09-21 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OVERLAY-AREA-CODES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 11-DIGIT DIALING FOR 408 AREA CODE ON HOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By DEBORAH SOLOMON &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Copyright 1999 San Francisco Chronicle &QL;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &QL;  &LR; 
SAN FRANCISCO -- California regulators late Tuesday put on hold a
plan that would have required everyone in the 408 area code to dial
11 digits when making a phone call, saying they want more time to
determine whether the region is actually in need of a new area
code.
</P>
<P>
   The order by the state Public Utilities Commission puts off
until Jan. 8, 2000, a decision on whether to permanently stop a
planned ``overlay.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an 11th-hour reprieve for San Jose, Calif., area residents,
who were supposed to start dialing 11 digits on October 2. The
suspension is also an indication that overlays planned for the Bay
Area in the 415, 510 and 650 &UR;  &LR; area codes soon may meet a similar
fate, industry watchers said.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC's executive order was issued after Pacific Bell sent a
letter asking state regulators to suspend the 408 overlay until
January 8.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's decision adds to growing momentum to end overlays in
California.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the PUC scrapped California's first overlay in the
310 area code in the wake of a federal decision that should free up
phone numbers across the state.
</P>
<P>
   After halting the overlay, PUC Commissioner Joel Hyatt said he
wants to avoid implementing 11-digit dialing in any region and will
try to end the seven overlays planned for California.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a consumer group asked the PUC to do just that,
filing a motion to temporarily halt 11-digit dialing across
California
</P>
<P>
   The Office of Ratepayer Advocates, an independent arm of the
California Public Utilities Commission, asked the PUC to stop
California's seven planned overlays until it determines whether
11-digit dialing is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to overlays comes in the wake of several decisions
by the Federal Communications Commission, which give California
more flexibility in how it assigns phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the FCC gave California the right to hand out new
numbers to phone companies in blocks of 1,000 instead of 10,000.
The FCC also told the state it could require phone companies to
return any unused phone numbers so they could be reassigned to
other phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both decisions should free up more phone numbers for California
and could avoid the need for overlays.
</P>
<P>
   Overlays have been implemented to deal with the growing shortage
of phone numbers across the state. Instead of dividing a ``maxed
out'' region geographically and giving customers in one half a new
area code, an overlay lets existing customers keep their area code
and assigns a new area code to new phone lines. However, everyone
in the overlay area must dial 11 digits _ 1 plus the area code and
seven-digit phone number _ on every call, even when making calls
within their own area code.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in 415, 510 and 650 are supposed to get overlays in
the next two years.
</P>
<P>
   The 310 overlay in West Los Angeles was plagued with problems.
Customers, who were confused and frustrated at having to dial 11
digits, flooded the PUC with complaints. The overlay, which began
in April, did not work with some security systems, and customers
had trouble getting through to some phone numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The PUC voted to pull it last week, saying the FCC's decision
could free up phone numbers and end the need for 11-digit dialing
in 310 and other regions across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Natalie Billingsley, a telecommunications expert with ORA, said
the FCC's decision merits a suspension of the planned overlays
until the state is certain they are necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much easier to suspend them'' than to implement and then
stop them as is happening in the 310 area, Billingsley said. It
will take about two months to undo the 310 overlay and reprogram
the switches in that region.
</P>
<P>
   Billingsley said ORA wants to avoid seeing something similar
happen in other regions and wants the PUC to approve the suspension
so customers aren't inconvenienced.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Getzug, a Pac Bell spokesman, said the phone company also
wants to avoid putting an overlay in place if the PUC may
eventually decide it's not necessary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to eliminate any customer confusion that would
arise,'' Getzug said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Berkeley's mayor also asked the PUC to halt the
overlay planned for 510.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
