s e BC-TORONTO-FILM-FEST-$AD     09-21 0862
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TORONTO-FILM-FEST-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CANADIAN GOURMET SHOP FOR CINEMA CONNOISSEURS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Please note subslug for FIENNES-FILMS) 
(af) 
 By RICK LYMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Ralph Fiennes sat alone at one of the big round tables
that sprouted like mushrooms around the half-darkened hotel meeting
room overlooking Bloor Street. He doodled idly on a small pad of
lined yellow paper, geometric shapes wrapped around letters and
half-finished faces. Empty water glasses and scraps of paper
littered the tables.
</P>
<P>
   The 10-day Toronto International Film Festival ended its 24th
incarnation last Saturday after playing host to more than 300
films, dozens of major stars and filmmakers and hundreds of
journalists and industry types from all over the world.
</P>
<P>
   Private parties at fancy restaurants, art galleries and even S&AMP;M
clubs had lit up the Canadian night. Limousines choked every major
hotel entryway.
</P>
<P>
   Fiennes had done his bit and was contemplating escape. ``I find
it can be very difficult to just move around in public during the
festival,'' he said. ``It's as though everyone has their antennas
out, they're on alert, on the lookout for celebrities.''
</P>
<P>
   Slightly bleary from a day's worth of questions about
``Sunshine'' _ a Hungarian generational epic by the director Istvan
Szabo in which he plays three roles _ Fiennes was collecting his
thoughts after the last of the journalists had left and was
preparing to make a 36-hour getaway before he had to return for yet
another push, this time for ``Onegin,'' an adaptation of Pushkin's
narrative poem directed by Martha Fiennes, his sister.
</P>
<P>
   The Toronto festival has always been a gourmet shop for film
lovers _ all the best produce, artfully arrayed, glistening with
the mist of celebrity. But it is also part publicity frenzy, in
which actors and directors try to generate buzz for movies about to
open, and part film marketplace, in which finished films that do
not yet have distributors try to attract a company willing to buy
the rights to exhibit them. The highbrow shares a berth with the
mainstream, the obscure with the familiar, the serious with the
daffy.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrities seem to overrun Toronto, where the local newspapers
offer a daily roster of who's in town and where they might be
spotted (hint: the lobby of the Four Seasons Hotel is
(italics)the(end italics) place for star sightings) _ Bruce Willis,
Meryl Streep, Ed Harris, Denzel Washington, Claudia Schiffer, Kim
Basinger, Sigourney Weaver, Kevin Spacey, Ethan Hawke, Maggie
Smith, Catherine Deneuve, Robin Williams and on and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the most basic level, it's a lot of free publicity,'' said
the director Steven Soderbergh, who brought his new film, ``The
Limey,'' to the festival. ``You can jump-start a buzz and hope it
reaches a tipping point where it becomes a movie people want to
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes a single film will burst from the pack and emerge as a
festival favorite, as Robert Duvall's ``Apostle'' did in 1997.
While no one film stood out this year, there were several that
attracted coteries of admirers: ``Boys Don't Cry,'' based on the
true story of a girl named Teena Brandon who passed herself off as
a boy; ``A Map of the World,'' with Sigourney Weaver starring in an
adaptation of Jane Hamilton's bleak, bleak novel, and ``Happy,
Texas,'' a slightly trimmed-down version of the wacky Sundance hit
about escaped convicts posing as beauty pageant organizers.
</P>
<P>
   The Hollywood studios brought some of their prestige fall and
holiday releases, among them Lasse Hallstrom's adaptation of ``The
Cider House Rules,'' based on the John Irving novel; Scott Hicks'
adaptation of ``Snow Falling on Cedars,'' the enormously popular
novel about prejudice and obsession in the Pacific Northwest, and
Norman Jewison's version of the Rubin Carter saga, ``The
Hurricane,'' which was shown as a work in progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``American Beauty,'' a Dreamworks debut by the British stage
director Sam Mendes about suburbia gone rancid, won the People's
Choice Award. But to give some idea of the breadth of the festival,
and the eclecticism and sophistication of the Toronto audience, the
runners-up for that award were ``The Cup,'' a delightful film from
Bhutan about Buddhist monks who are obsessed with playing soccer,
and ``Yesterday's Children,'' a drama from the Philippines about
outcasts in a drought-stricken village.
</P>
<P>
   Although everyone was on the lookout for the hot, undiscovered
film that would engender a bidding war, it never appeared. Several
movies were picked up, and talks were begun for several more that
are expected to be finalized soon, but there were no reports of
gigantic checks written or feverish midnight negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the best independent films were bought up in the weeks
leading up to the festival,'' said a top executive with one
distribution company who was still scouting for films late in the
festival. ``I think we'll find when we look back that this festival
did a little bit of good for a large number of films, but was
make-or-break for none of them. Mostly, I think people will
remember the parties.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2150EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
