<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0420 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-CLINTON-ART-600&AMP;     09-21 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-CLINTON-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON URGES U.N. TO INTERVENE MORE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ President Clinton urged other members of the
United Nations on Tuesday to strengthen their collective capacity
for intervening to prevent the kinds of mass killings and ethnic
repression that ravaged Kosovo and East Timor, saying that there
are limits to what individual nations can accomplish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Promising too much can be as cruel as caring too little,''
Clinton said in a speech to the General Assembly. ``But
difficulties, dangers and costs are not an argument for doing
nothing.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we are faced with deliberate, organized campaigns to
murder whole peoples, or expel them from their land,'' he
continued, ``the care of victims is important, but not enough. We
should work to end the violence.''
</P>
<P>
   But the president offered no specific proposals for helping the
United Nations take responsibility for peacekeeping, even though
its efforts in that regard have been hobbled by the failure of the
United States to pay what it owes the world organization.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Clinton waited till the end of his speech before turning
to the subject uppermost on the minds of most of his audience: the
$1.6 billion in arrears that the United Nations says Washington
owes in back dues, interest and other assessments.
</P>
<P>
   The president described the United Nations as ``indispensable''
and said that ``the United States also has the responsibility to
equip the U.N. with the resources that it needs to be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I think most of you know, I have strongly supported the
United States meeting all its financial obligations to the United
Nations, and I will continue to do so,'' he continued. ``We will do
our very best to succeed this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But the delegates, who greeted him with a standing ovation last
year, partly to show sympathy for his problems over the Monica
Lewinsky affair, failed to applaud his intentions Tuesday. He
received polite but unenthusiastic applause.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's spokesman, Joe Lockhart, said there has been ``obvious
and articulated concern from many quarters'' about the United
States' unpaid debt to the United Nations. But he described the
response to Clinton's speech in the General Assembly as positive
and appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like a basketball arena where people are standing,
loudly cheering,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton started his day at the United Nations by discussing the
American arrears with Secretary-General Kofi Annan, who has been
critical of the debt.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said, ``The president again
indicated that this was a high priority for him and that he was
very much going to work hard to try to see if we could resolve this
problem this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the U.N. Charter, the United States could be stripped of
its vote in the General Assembly at the end of 1999 unless it pays
sufficiently on its arrears. In a report released in July, the U.S.
General Accounting Office estimated that the United States would
need to pay about $153 million in addition to the $508 million the
State Department expects to pay before the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved a bill on June 22 that authorized a payment
of more than $800 million to the United Nations, but it attached
conditions unilaterally cutting the American share of the budget
from 25 percent to 20 percent and its share of peacekeeping
expenses from 31 percent to 25 percent. The House has yet to vote
on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Several diplomats and representatives of nongovernmental
organizations said Clinton had lost credibility in terms of his
ability to get the American dues paid.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In his remarks about stopping mass killings and ethnic
cleansing, Clinton acknowledged the United States' reluctance to
get drawn into other deadly internal conflicts like those in
Africa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that some are troubled that the United States and
others cannot respond to every humanitarian catastrophe in the
world,'' Clinton said. ``We cannot do everything everywhere. But
simply because we have different interests in different parts of
the world does not mean we can be indifferent to the destruction of
innocents in any part of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton defended NATO's decision to begin an air war against
Serbia, saying that it followed a consensus in the Security Council
that Serbian atrocities against Kosovo's ethnic Albanians were
unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Had we chosen to do nothing in the face of this brutality, I
do not believe we would have strengthened the United Nations,''
Clinton said. ``Instead, we would have risked discrediting
everything it stood for.''
</P>
<P>
   His assertion was implicitly contradicted by the Russian foreign
minister, Igor S. Ivanov, who said that the United Nations'
authority had been ``seriously and painfully tested'' by the crises
over ethnic cleansing in Kosovo and weapons inspections in Iraq.
Russia objected to military action in both.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have managed through joint efforts to bring the settlement
of the Kosovo problem back within the legal and political framework
of the United Nations,'' Ivanov said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton proposed two other long-term goals for the United
Nations: eradicating poverty and disease, and helping poorer
countries join the global economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We must refuse to accept a future in which one part of
humanity lives on the cutting edge of a new economy, while the
other lives at knife edge of survival,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The second goal was stopping the spread of nuclear, biological
and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said cooperation was especially needed to keep weapons
of mass destruction out of the hands of terrorist groups. ``They
may have weaker capabilities than states, but they have fewer
compunctions about using such weapons,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   After his speech, Clinton held meetings with several other
leaders, including President Andres Pastrana of Colombia, whose
country has been destabilized by guerrilla warfare and drug
trafficking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2152EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0421 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0768 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ELIMINATE-ABERNATHY-T     09-21 0033
</HEADER>
<BODY>
