<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-ENDOWMENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD ENDOWMENT SEES DECLINE IN INVESTMENT RETURN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Harvard can't shake its thirst for diamond-in-the-rough
start-up companies. And the result is parched investment returns.
</P>
<P>
   The university's mega-endowment, the largest of its kind in the
world, has fallen far short of its investment goals, mostly because
it cannot place as much money as it would like into high-flying
venture capital funds.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard Management Co., the university's investment arm, said
Tuesday that the endowment returned 12.2 percent over the last
fiscal year, and now stood at $14.4 billion.
</P>
<P>
   While that increase is nothing to sneeze at, and is a big
rebound from losses in the summer of 1998, it comes up well short
of Harvard's lofty goal of gaining 18.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For the fiscal year ended June 30, the university's portfolio,
which started the 12-month period at $13.2 billion, earned about
$900 million. It also received donations and pledges totaling about
$400 million.
</P>
<P>
   By ordinary standards, Harvard's investments did quite well. But
the university measures its performance against its own internal
benchmarks, which required it to do much better.
</P>
<P>
   More shortfalls may be in the works. In its annual letter to
investors, Harvard Management warned that the good times of
previous years may dry up in coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Venture capital funds, the object of Harvard's lust, provide
seed money to small, young companies that then grow and issue
publicly traded stock, handing windfall returns to their initial
investors. Many Internet companies began life as venture
capital-funded startups before going on to become lucrative
household names.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that Harvard's behemoth portfolio _ it is about
twice the size of Princeton's or Stanford's _ sought to invest 15
percent of its holdings in the world's top 10 venture capital
funds. (Harvard wants to buy only the leading funds). But with so
much competition among investors for a piece of that action, the
funds limit how much individual institutions can invest. The result
was that Harvard found itself with nearly a billion dollars it had
to place in non-venture capital investments just as its venture
capital benchmark took off, mostly on a rash of Internet initial
public offerings in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the endowment's private-equity section, which
includes venture capital, gained 29.2 percent last fiscal year,
about half its target of 56.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 27.7 percent.
Harvard does not compare itself against the common market measure,
which it says does not reflect the endowment's particular mix of
stocks, bonds, and other investments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We simply have been unable to place as much money as we would
like with the top venture capital funds,'' said Harvard
Management's president, Jack R. Meyer. If the venture capital
benchmark ``continues to produce triple rates of return, things
will be difficult.'' Harvard Management has since scaled back
private-equity assets to 12 percent of its portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the lofty but unreached goals, the Cambridge institution
is still doing slightly better than the average university
endowment. The median performance of 100 large institutional funds,
including large-university endowments, was 11.2 percent for 12
months through June, according to the Trust Universe Comparison
Service.
</P>
<P>
   Unusual among universities, Harvard manages just over two-thirds
of its portfolio internally, and farms out the rest to money
managers. Meyer said that nearly all the internal managers
outperformed their benchmarks, and that some ``external'' managers
at unnamed money management companies did not measure up.
</P>
<P>
   Mirroring broad downturns, the Cambridge institution's holdings
in emerging market stocks, commodities, and real estate also failed
to do as well as expected. Harvard's emerging markets assets, which
constitute 9 percent of the endowment's portfolio, gained only 3.8
percent last fiscal year, far below the 21 percent benchmark.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's money managers appear best at picking foreign stocks.
These shares, representing 15 percent of the university's
portfolio, rose 11.5 percent, nearly twice their target level.
Harvard has nearly one-quarter of its assets in US stocks, which
outperformed their benchmark of 21.3 percent by more than 4
percentage points. The gains were calculated after fees were paid
to Harvard's investment managers.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's endowment has done well in recent years. With a
five-year annualized return of 20.1 percent, in line with the
university's expectations, the portfolio is in the top 5 percent of
all institutional funds. For the previous fiscal period ended June
1998, Harvard's endowment rose 20.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Meyer ended his letter on a cautionary note, saying that
``the past five years have provided extraordinary returns _ returns
that we do not expect to persist.'' He said the portfolio could
have a negative return this year for the first time in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard's endowment, which has had to worry about portfolio
manager defections in recent years, lost high-yield manager Tim
Peterson this month. Meyer said Harvard had placed $220 million in
Peterson's new Boston firm, Regiment Capital.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
