<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0772 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-Y2K-HOSPITALS-BOS &LR;      09-21 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-Y2K-HOSPITALS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAY STATE HOSPITALS STRIVING TO BECOME Y2K PROOF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Despite setbacks, Y2K prognosis is good, state's
hospitals say
</P>
<P>
   A survey released Tuesday has found that most Massachusetts
hospitals have yet to complete work that will ensure their
computers and automated medical equipment will perform normally
after the millennial date change.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, mailed July 27 to all Massachusetts hospitals, found
that only 49 percent of hospitals had finished upgrading biomedical
devices, 52 percent had contingency plans ready in the event power
and lights go out, and 68 percent had confidence in their phone and
voice-mail systems.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Jacobsen, deputy commissioner at the Department of Public
Health, said the survey showed improvement from one carried out
last January. ``But I would say they have a long way to go,''
Jacobsen said. ``Hospitals have good reason to maintain quality of
care after January 1, and they're not there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Tuesday, officials at many hospitals said they had
finished their Y2K projects since the survey was done, or that they
were on schedule for completion in the next month or two.
</P>
<P>
   Some others said they were waiting for software upgrades from
manufacturers or had one or two devices left to upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   For example, technicians at Massachusetts General Hospital are
expecting corrective software to fix a General Electric
electrocardiogram system, said James Noga, chief information
officer, ``and we will be installing it this week.''
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, he said, all other vulnerable computers, elevators,
phone, heating and cooling, and other systems are ready for the
date change. ``That really leaves us focusing on contingency
planning,'' much of which is already in place because it's similar
to planning for large winter storms, said Noga.
</P>
<P>
   Like other industries, hospitals are heavily dependent on
computerized equipment and systems. Many older systems contained a
programming shortcut, leaving them potentially vulnerable to errors
or failure when the date changes from 1999 to 2000. Previously,
many programmers provided only for two-digit years, so that next
New Year's Day a computer might read 00 as 1900, and some
computer-containing devices could fail.
</P>
<P>
   The DPH can't directly regulate computer equipment at the
hospitals, but does, through its licensing function, have
responsibility for ensuring that the facilities maintain their
quality of care.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant DPH Commissioner Nancy Ridley said, ``We're very
pleased with the cooperation we've received from the hospitals''
and are confident that those not yet in compliance are working
diligently to be ready. Jacobsen said that DPH will ``hold their
feet to the fire'' with follow-up checks of hospitals that are
lagging.
</P>
<P>
   At Melrose-Wakefield Health Care, information services head
Scott Blanchett said that all life-critical medical equipment has
been checked and updated. ``I think we are going to be prepared for
whatever happens,'' he said. Several contingency plans have been
drawn up, he said, adding that ``our intent is to roll them out
during November and December _ we want them to be fresh in the
employees' minds.''
</P>
<P>
   Emerson Hospital in Concord tested its contingency plan during
Hurricane Floyd's visit last week, said Charleen Sotolongo,
director of safety and security. As at other facilities, she said
that only a few medical devices remain to be upgraded as soon as
the software arrives.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, a number of hospital officials told the Globe they
were worried mostly about utilities, phone service, and other
external factors. That concern still exists, Y2K planners said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Testing of information systems is still in progress at Care
Group's hospitals, which include Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center and New England Baptist Hospital, said Dr. Alan Robbins,
head of Care Group's Y2K preparations. But none of those systems
has a role in health care or is critical to the hospitals'
functioning, he said.
</P>
<P>
   As confident as they are that equipment will work normally when
the date changes, officials at Care Group are taking no chances,
said Robbins. ``We're going to have someone, literally, standing
next to every patient at 12:01'' on New Year's Day, he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe correspondent Jennifer Zeis contributed to this article.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
