<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0773 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-GEN-FUTURE-LADN-(SLAN     09-21 2636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-FUTURE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNOLOGY WILL CHANGE THE PLAYING FIELD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ OK, sports fans, try this one on: A few years from
now you're watching a ballgame on your 10-foot High Definition
Television with 16-speaker Super Surround Sound but growing weary
of that constant center-field camera angle.
</P>
<P>
   So you push a button and now you're watching from the Catcher
Cam. Flick again and you're watching the manager's neck veins bulge
as his pitcher goes 3-0 to a .220 hitter.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe you're watching the Masters, and instead of the network
feed, you'd rather take in Tiger Woods II's entire round. Or it's a
NASCAR race and you just as soon go in circles exclusively with the
in-car camera of Jeff Gordon, who now looks almost 30.
</P>
<P>
   Zoom ahead another 50 years and imagine donning some Michael
Crichton-inspired helmet and watching an NFL playoff game (sorry,
still no L.A. team) through a virtual-reality experience that keeps
making you want to duck.
</P>
<P>
   It could all happen. A new order awaits the world of sports and
not just in how we view it. The new millennium brings an eclectic
sports offering, and if much of it is uncertain, what it does
promise is there will be more of it.
</P>
<P>
   More teams, more specialty sports, more technology, more
commercialization, more TV influence, more global, and naturally,
more expensive.
</P>
<P>
   It's going to be everywhere anytime you want it and almost any
way you'd like it. There will be a sport for everyone. Some might
come with flashy whiz-bang gizmos, some won't change a lick, some
might be pushed aside by the latest and greatest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to keep getting overspecialized and be more like
`Rollerball' _ a more violent and unpredictable society, and more
schizophrenic society,'' said former major-league pitcher Bill
``Spaceman'' Lee. ``Not really your agrarian vegetarian.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that meat eaters don't need sports, too. As it is, baseball,
basketball and football might remain the three most popular sports
in the U.S., but they have been getting squeezed for the past 20
years, bombarded by sports no longer satisfied with some one-line
mention in the roundup sections of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   In the next century, new sports will continue to multiply and
flourish. Fashions change, at least on the periphery. The continued
specialization of cable channels only opens additional entrees for
every sport this side of the ``Geraldo Lawn Bowling Channel.''
</P>
<P>
   Neal Pilson, whose Pilson Communications in New York is a TV
sports consultant company that includes such clients as NASCAR, the
Arena Football League and the LPGA, is the former president of CBS
sports. And he's bullish on the continued growth of sports in the
new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could make an argument that in the next century we will be
in a 1,500-channel universe,'' Pilson said. ``I could make an
argument that the major sports properties in the 1,500-channel
universe will remain unchanged because of the unique nature of the
event. There is only one World Series. There is only one Super
Bowl. There is only one NFL, one NBA.
</P>
<P>
   ``And if you have it, your 1,499 competitors won't. There are
really no other distinguishing programming properties similar to
sports. Everyone has movies. Everyone has news. Everyone has sports
news. Everyone can create entertainment series and specials. But
the unique nature of a sports event distinguishes your distribution
service from everyone else's, makes it special. Sports will
continue to give you that unique opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   It's clear. Sports are not going away, they just figure to
mushroom out all over the place. Not that there won't be plenty of
changes. &QL; 
TECHNO FREAKS UNITE &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Technology and the Internet will continue their growing
influence on the way we view sports, if not play them. Pilson can
see the remote that customizes your TV viewing in the
not-so-distant future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have more and more opportunities to select our
viewing platform, to watch from unique perspectives, whether it's
camera locations or special advantages not available to the
spectator,'' Pilson said. ``We're going to see more participants
being miked. You'll get more audio out of sports events _ find out
what the pitcher said to the catcher, what the quarterback said in
the huddle, what the manager or coach are saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're going to find you will be even closer to the event
itself, and given the opportunities that will be available with
digital television and the compression of signals, you'll be able
to select how you watch sports events, rather than in the past
being dictated to by the director who sits in the truck.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, you might learn a new appreciation for the guy in
the truck.
</P>
<P>
   Virtual reality and entertainment _ which just underwent an odd
research marriage with the Pentagon at USC _ already has sports
imaginations flying.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Prazmark is the senior vice president for new business
development at International Management Group, the largest sports
and event marketing group in the world, and is already toying with
the idea of virtual-reality sports viewing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's very interesting,'' Prazmark said. ``I want to do a
sales presentation where, let's say, I'm selling the Olympic Games.
I want to bring them in a presentation theater and have them do
virtual-reality experience as if they're going down the luge or
walking through the sponsor village. And we're pretty close to
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee thinks that would offer a definite upside.
</P>
<P>
   ``For fans who (complain) and moan about guys swinging at a bad
pitch, have him stay in there and look slider low and away from
Clemens, and then have him throw one right at his ear,'' Lee said.
``He'd get the feeling. It's called the Tony Conigliaro effect.''
</P>
<P>
   David Carter, who teaches the business of sports at USC and owns
a sports-marketing company in Los Angeles, said the most immediate
technological impact on sports might be the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-tech component, the Internet in particular, is going
to be critical because it is largely untapped in terms of selling
broadcast rights over your computer, to getting a better handle on
how to maximize the amount of merchandise you can sell over these
different sites,'' Carter said. ``Players themselves may
increasingly not want to be part of their own league deals, if they
can create their own Web sites and sell merchandise directly.''
</P>
<P>
   HDTV is already on its way, offering a particular advantage to
viewing sports. Jeff Shell, president of Fox Sports Networks, saw a
recent HDTV demonstration in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expected to be just wowed by the crystal-clear image, which
was very impressive and made you feel like you were almost there,''
Shell said. ``But what was really interesting about the HDTV stuff
was that because the picture is much wider and longer, when you're
watching a basketball game, you don't have to keep moving the
camera around. You can see the whole half court. You can see the
plays developing, players cutting, and not just focusing on the
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Shell, though, sees the future offering options, not necessarily
a life-style change for the viewer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is, it's not going to completely effect the way
people watch sports if they're not at the game,'' he said. ``I
think people still want to sit down on their couch, grab a beer and
watch the game if they can't get out to the park.'' &QL; 
YEAH, IT'S A SMALL WORLD &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   And shrinking by your DSL micro-second. Sports increasingly
reach out across the globe. In a digitalized, Internet, satellite
world, all things seem possible. And sooner rather than later.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think five years from now, if you're a cricket fanatic and
you're sitting here in the United States and there's a live match
in India, you could turn on your computer and find that cricket
match on your TV in real time and in imagery that we're used to,''
Prazmark said. ``You're going to be able to span the globe for the
sport you want.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. professional leagues, too, have been flirting with reaching
out beyond the northern border. The NFL has a league in Europe. The
NBA plays a game in Japan. The San Diego Padres have played in
Mexico. The Chicago Cubs and New York Mets are set to play in Japan
next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we've done about as much as we can with the
local markets,'' said Dodgers first baseman Eric Karros, who has
his own Web site. ``In the last 10 years the local markets have
been exploited a lot more than in the past. How much more can you
do? I think the next logical step is global.''
</P>
<P>
   Travel time, however, is still extensive across the Pacific and
Atlantic, and it's difficult to imagine the Lakers making regular
trips to Europe. The future calls, but that Star Trek ``energize''
thing is not in the offering.
</P>
<P>
   But that doesn't mean there isn't some kind of international pro
competition looming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we may find is that the teams are not involved in
league play, but down the road an NBA division or an NHL division
may be located in Europe,'' Pilson said. ``And while they might not
play the U.S. and Canadian teams on a regular basis, they might be
one of six divisions that participate in the Stanley Cup or the NBA
championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee, of course, has his own unique slant on the future of global
sports. Sort of John Lennon meets Babe Ruth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see a complete world market, with no flags, no borders, no
bounderies, no federal governments _ just local governments, kind
of a Machiavellian city-state _ where the marketplace dictates
everything without military involvement,'' Lee said. ``I see more
of a utopian game, with nice parks and natural grass and no foul
territory, no designated hitter, wood bats in Little League. It all
hinges on getting rid of all your flags.'' &QL; 
THE LATEST AND GREATEST &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   So what will we all be watching in this shrunken world? Lee's
``Rollerball,'' the James Caan movie of a corporate-run sports
world where international cities compete in a violent game that
denounces individuality? Will soccer finally have its day in the
U.S.? Will a minor sport now become big, or a new sport emerge that
captures the national imagination? What's next?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's called the WWF,'' Lee said. ``More people watch junk.
`Never underestimate the ignorance of the American public' _ P.T.
Barnum. You know? Hell, everything's gotten that way. It's sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Most agree with Pilson, that it will be difficult for any new
sport to challenge the existing sports dominating the national
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see it, but who's to say everybody won't be playing
soccer 25 years from now,'' said Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn.
``Who's to say that football will still be looked upon as it is
now? Who knows, pool might become the sport of 2025. Ping-Pong,
tennis maybe. X-Games _ now that I can't watch.''
</P>
<P>
   USC's Carter said if there's a perceived market for those who
follow any new sport, however unique, it has a chance to grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cable channels essentially have cable channels of their own
now,'' he said. ``As that happens, the audiences reached by those
channels _ like the Golf Channel, Classic Sports _ might become
smaller, but they also might become demographically more desirable.
They might be delivering to advertisers and sponsors a tighter
group of desired viewers.''
</P>
<P>
   Hey, there's room for everybody. Each in his own little sporting
compartment.
</P>
<P>
   David Simon, president of the Los Angeles Sports Council, said
growing immigration means an increased diversity of U.S. sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this community, immigration has had a tremendous impact on
sports,'' Simon said. ``Soccer is the most noticeable example, but
it's not the only one. Another that doesn't get talked about very
much is badminton. Southern California is a hotbed of badminton
because it is especially popular in a handful of Asian countries,
and we have a lot of people here who come from those counries. It
is the national sport in Indonesia.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the sport rising in popularity today can quickly become
passe tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at beach volleyball,'' Karros said. ``Four or five years
ago, that was a hot thing. Guys were making a hundred grand, you
had rival leagues. I mean, it was big. You had coverage on NBC. Now
it kind of ran its course.'' &QL; 
WHEN IS ENOUGH ENOUGH? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   At some point, can it become sports overload? Is there a
saturation level waiting on the sporting horizon? How fragmented
can sports continue to become?
</P>
<P>
   Carter said a saturation level will only be reached in sports
when advertisers feel they're no longer getting enough bang for
their buck. Pilson said don't count on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing we've seen so far would appear to indicate a
saturation level,'' Pilson said. ``America's love affair with
sports and sports properties doesn't show any signs of abatement.
Teams come and go. Some teams do better than others. It's a cylical
situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I don't see the NBA or the NHL or NFL or major-league
baseball going out of business because people decide they want to
go jogging or ride a bicycle.''
</P>
<P>
   How specific can we continue to develop? Can the NASCAR Channel
be far off? Is there room for the badminton hour, the cricket
marathon, the women's-sports channel, the world Poke'mon playoffs?
</P>
<P>
   Listen up: Money rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it's women's sports, amateur sports or other types of
professional men's leagues just emerging _ like Arena football _
unless the networks and the corporations believe they have a
coveted demographic audience, whether it's on TV or the Internet or
reading in the papers, then it's not going to be worth their
time,'' Carter said. &QL; 
BROTHER, CAN YOU SPARE A SLEEVE? &UR;
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   For now, advertisers continue to flow into sports, into those
unique marketing opportunities, like some never-ending money
fountain. Every event now seems sponsored. Arenas, stadiums and
ballparks without a corporate name are becoming the exception.
Luxury boxes are reinventing the looks and priorities of our
stadiums. Advertising signage is squeezed into more spots at
venues, into more corners of the TV screen. Baseball is talking
about letting some advertising slip onto uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is going to look like a NASCAR driver and that ain't
too good,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   But Prazmark said companies could grow weary of shelling out
millions to advertise events, when they might be able to just own
the entire show.
</P>
<P>
   And then reap some of the profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the business of sport will change,'' he said. ``I
believe corporations will want to truly become partners with these
events and not renters of signage and buying some tickets. The big
corporations will want to begin to create and fund their own events
and also use their marketing expertise to build a business out of
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the growing commericalization of sports, a visit to the
ballpark continues to take a growing hunk out of the wallet. And
it's not just the common fan who notices rising prices at sporting
events.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you're kind of forced into the new sports, just
because how pricey the existing sports are,'' Gwynn said. ``When I
came to Dodger Stadium with my dad and brother, it was 50 cents for
us under-12 guys to sit in the bleachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I buy season tickets in San Diego behind home plate, and
they're $125 a game. I shell out some hefty coin to get my season
tickets, so I can only imagine the average fan coming to the
ballpark and paying $6 for parking, tickets for a family of four,
hot dogs, popcorn, peanuts, soda _ man, that's a C-note to come to
the game. And the way the game is going, 25 years from now that
could be two, three hundred dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   Sports in the future figure to come with a price.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
