u a BC-MILLENNIUM-JUMP-BOS &LR;      09-21 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-JUMP-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON'S MILLENNIUM TO PLAY OUT IN GREENWICH TIME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDITH GAINES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Fireworks will explode, bands will play, couples will
kiss, and champagne corks will fly.
</P>
<P>
   But in Boston this New Year's Eve, the city will greet the year
2000 not at midnight, but five hours earlier, at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In an announcement timed to mark the countdown to the new
century, which is 100 days from today (Sept. 22), city officials
say they have decided to start ringing in the New Year when it
arrives in Greenwich, England.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be marking the millennium when it's midnight in
Greenwich, according to Greenwich Mean Time, which is the
universally accepted standard of time for the world,'' Mayor Thomas
M. Menino said.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement may sound quirky and could be controversial.
</P>
<P>
   But it means Boston will be the first city in the nation to
celebrate the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
   It means that children, who will be leaders in the new
millennium, can join in the festivities and get home before
bedtime, Menino said.
</P>
<P>
   Planners do not appear concerned that the early party could
reinforce a perception that the city shuts down unfashionably
early.
</P>
<P>
   They expect about 2 million to attend First Night, about 500,000
more than in previous years. The city will continue entertainment
between the first countdown and the more traditional one.
</P>
<P>
   And, with the celebration starting early, citizens panicky about
possible Y2K computer system crashes, electric grid failures, or
runs on banks and food supplies can ``return to the comfort and
safety of their own homes before midnight,'' said David Mugar,
chairman and executive producer of millennial events for Boston
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Mugar stressed that city officials think there's no need for
alarm. ``We don't believe there will be more than a few minor
computer glitches,'' he said. ``But if people are apprehensive,
this gives them a choice.''
</P>
<P>
   Plans call for First Night's 5:30 p.m. Grand Parade down
Boylston and Charles streets to culminate at Boston Common. Just
before 6:59 p.m., the mayor and some children from Boston's
neighborhoods will light a sterling silver replica of Paul Revere's
lantern, ``symbolizing Boston's leadership role as a beacon of
freedom in the new millennium,'' Menino said.
</P>
<P>
   A 60-second countdown will commence at 6:59 and at 7 p.m.,
midnight in England, a huge Jumbotron television screen on the
Common will broadcast the scene live from Greenwich, England, and
other countries in the first time zone, as they welcome the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   Simultaneously, there will be 15 minutes of fireworks from the
Common, the site of the first fireworks shows when First Night
began 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Night owls should not despair. An additional fireworks display
will occur as usual over Boston Harbor at midnight Boston time,
preceded by a two-hour Boston Pops concert.
</P>
<P>
   Planners acknowledge that many revelers may ignore the official
early start and toot their party horns at midnight Boston time.
</P>
<P>
   But the 7 p.m. event gives families an opportunity to celebrate
``at the exact time considered the offical international turning
point of the millennium,'' said Michael Taylor, president of Boston
2000.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a century, Greenwich Mean Time has been the
world's official clock.
</P>
<P>
   Historically, most towns around the world kept their own local
time using sundials. Noon was the time when the sun passed directly
overhead. This worked pretty well until the development of railways
in the mid-19th century. With most towns having their own time,
arranging timetables became a scheduler's nightmare.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1884, representatives of 25 countries gathered in
Washington to create a standardized system. They decided to fix one
line, which would be 0 degrees longitude, running from the North
Pole to the South Pole. Every country could then establish its
position relative to that meridian.
</P>
<P>
   After considerable debate, the delegates chose the meridian that
passed through the main telescope at the Royal Observatory in
Greenwich, England. They opted for Greenwich because the
observatory's astronomers, by tracking the movements of heavenly
bodies, had played a key role in early navigation and timekeeping
at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Time zones were created at uniform distances from this line,
with the first time zone using what became known as Greenwich Mean
Time.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Observatory was moved from Greenwich to Herstmonceux
in 1948 and in 1990 it moved again to Cambridge, England, where it
is now. But the prime meridian, as it is known, still passes
through Greenwich.
</P>
<P>
   Thus far, Boston is the only city in the United States to
announce that it will celebrate the new millennium when it arrives
in Greenwich. But its festivities will be coordinated with
ceremonies in the United Kingdom, Iceland, the Ivory Coast,
Portugal, Ghana, Mali, Morocco, and other countries in the world's
first time zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making this an international celebration, which is
appropriate since we're a city of immigrants,'' Taylor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
