<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0428 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0778 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BROOKLYN-PHILHARMONIC     09-21 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROOKLYN-PHILHARMONIC-ART-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY OF WAR, POP AND FAITH  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, SEPT. 26) 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(af) 
 By PAUL GRIFFITHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For their season that opens on Friday at the Brooklyn
Academy of Music, Robert Spano and the Brooklyn Philharmonic have
put together a set of programs to survey the 20th century from the
vantage point of its end.
</P>
<P>
   This is a 20th-century season in two ways: not only does all the
music come from the last hundred years, but the planning has a very
20th-century feel. Spano and his orchestra are concerned less with
great composers than with great themes _ war, politics, pop
culture, the environment, faith _ and there is no attempt to see
that all the outstanding creative personalities are represented.
Even Stravinsky, the century's musical giant, is ignored.
</P>
<P>
   An approach based on ideas and influences, rather than artists,
works well for 20th-century music, because so few composers have
been able, or wanted, to avoid winds of thought and feeling blowing
in from right outside their art. If one wanted to assemble thematic
programs of 19th-century music, it might be hard to find evidence
of, say, industrialization, widening democracy and the growth of
science, though it would be interesting to try.
</P>
<P>
   But thanks above all, perhaps, to increased communications,
composers in the 20th century have generally lived less separate
lives.
</P>
<P>
   War, in particular, has struck many, and the first Brooklyn
program focuses, almost inevitably, on World War II, which _ not to
underestimate its other effects _ disrupted the careers of most
leading European composers and left the United States a major
musical power, strengthened by the presence of so many
distinguished immigrants and a new self-confidence among native
musicians.
</P>
<P>
   Bartok wrote his Divertimento for a performance in Switzerland
in 1939, when there was no chance of his getting a new work played
in the musical heartland of Germany and Austria. Richard Strauss'
``Metamorphosen'' was a response to the bombed German cities of
1945. That both scores are for strings is partly an accident: they
were both written for a string orchestra directed by the patron
Paul Sacher.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the string-ensemble medium allowed
these composers to reflect on war in ways that were, whether ironic
or tragic, distanced from noisy militarism.
</P>
<P>
   The third work in this war concert _ Shostakovich's Chamber
Symphony, an adaptation of the composer's Eighth String Quartet by
the conductor Rudolf Barshai _ comes from 1960, a time when the war
was cold. (If Stravinsky had been admitted, a pairing of his almost
contemporary ``Movements'' with the Shostakovich might have said a
lot about artistic contradictions across the Iron Curtain.)
</P>
<P>
   Shostakovich offers a prime example, too, of a composer affected
by politics, though the Brooklyn choice for that theme _ John
Adams' opera ``Nixon in China,'' to be performed in concert in
early December _ is equally interesting. Alice Goodman's libretto
gives voice to the world leaders of 1972 _ Nixon and Henry
Kissinger; Mao and his wife; Chou En-lai _ but what they engage in
is all small talk and personal reminiscence, bobbing along on the
grand sweep of time that is conveyed by the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon sings of making history, but really, history is making
him. We are a long way here from the heroic deeds and majestic
self-assertion of kings and princes in operas by Handel or Verdi.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Shostakovich's music looks forward from the first
concert to the subject of the second, so Adams' opera anticipates
the Brooklyn Philharmonic's next theme: popular culture. Adams,
like many composers in the classical tradition who have grown up
since World War II, found something he wanted in rock and pop, but
the third Brooklyn concert, in February, will skip back to
musicians influenced by jazz (Kurt Weill and Conlon Nancarrow),
tango (Astor Piazzolla) or the movies (Toru Takemitsu).
</P>
<P>
   This looks like the most heterogeneous mixture. The dissonant
feelings for jazz shown in Weill's ``New Orpheus'' _ optimistic and
anxious, embracing and eschewing _ are perhaps characteristic of a
European reaction in the 1920s and '30s, whereas Nancarrow's
joyful, zestful exploration of jazz motifs and rhythmic
complexities is more typical of an American and of a later time:
the orchestra will perform some of his player-piano studies of the
'50s, in realizations by Yvar Mikhashoff.
</P>
<P>
   Alongside all this come Piazzolla's Concerto for Guitar and
Accordion and three film scenes scored by Takemitsu. But maybe the
jostle is pop culture's, too.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in April, comes a look at how a composer's music might be
shaped by the environment: specifically, the Finnish environment of
lakes and forests, of wide horizontals, of white, gray and green,
of long winters and sudden springs. &QL; 
Sibelius' Fifth Symphony is the big work, preceded by pieces from
living Finnish composers: Magnus Lindberg, Aulis Sallinen and
Einojuhani Rautavaara.
</P>
<P>
   It is a pity that Kaija Saariaho was not included (there are,
indeed, no women composers in the series), but the concert offers a
rare chance to hear Rautavaara's classic ``Cantus Arcticus,'' a
concerto for recorded bird songs and live orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   More birds will be heard in May, but now from the orchestra,
when David Wilson-Johnson and Heidi Grant Murphy sing three scenes
from Messiaen's opera ``St. Francois d'Assise,'' ending the series
on notes of conviction, openness and hope. And perhaps, after all,
the season will show that what will be remembered from the 20th
century, as from the 19th, will not be the themes but the
individual voices: Bartok's furious and vigorous, Nancarrow's
crazily mechanized, Messiaen's resplendent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2202EDT &QL; 
