u s BC-GLF-RYDER-USNOTES-BOS     09-21 0517
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-RYDER-USNOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US PLAYERS IN TALKATIVE MOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE CONCANNON AND JIM MCCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLINE, Mass. _ With the start of the 33d Ryder Cup closing
in, the Americans were in a talkative mood Tuesday. Almost all of
it was business-related.
</P>
<P>
   You had David Duval talking about playing on a team ``with 11
personalties.'' Tiger Woods needed a history lesson when he said
Jack Nicklaus had a losing record in the Ryder Cup (actually
17-8-3), and Jim Furyk stating that ``if I knew for sure we weren't
going to win, I wouldn't play at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the normally taciturn Jeff Maggert offering this
food for thought on the possible matchups. ``Let's face it. We've
got the 12 best players in the world and if they just go out and
play golf and hit golf shots, it's hard to mess up putting two guys
together.''
</P>
<P>
   When Duval was asked about team chemistry, he responded, ``I
think that's where we've got a big advantage. We only have 11
people with personalities on our team. So you only have to get 11
people to get along together.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, this is a chance for redemption after his 1-3-1
record two years ago at Valderrama. ``I really didn't know all the
guys on the team that well,'' he said. `I didn't know their wives,
didn't know their girlfriends, their kids. This year it's
different. I know everybody on the team. It's a big difference. It
makes you feel a little more comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Love looks sound
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If there was any question about the health of Davis Love III, it
seemed to be answered during Tuesday's practice round. Paired with
Tom Lehman, Steve Pate, and Justin Leonard, Love appeared to be
swinging free and easy. He took good rips at several drives and
when faced with a testy, long bunker shot at the underrated eighth
hole, Love executed it perfectly. His sore neck and back appear
fine after taking a lengthy break prior to arriving in Brookline.
That's bad news for Bob Estes, who finished 11th in the Ryder Cup
point standings and would have been Love's replacement.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Sutton back after 12 years &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Hal Sutton, who once said he might forgo another Ryder Cup
opportunity because of abuse from the gallery that drove his former
wife to tears, is back after 12 years. ``It's changed a lot in
those 12 years,'' he said. ``When you drive into the gate, you see
all the tents. I heard there's 4,000 volunteers here this week. It
would take me awhile to tell you about all the things I've noticed
just in the first 45 minutes here. It's pretty interesting to see
where the Ryder Cup has come from and where it is today.'' . . .
Leonard, winner of the 1997 British Open, noted The Country Club is
similar to a US Open course. ``It's a little different from the way
the USGA would set it up,'' he said. ``We want to go out there and
make birdies to win holes. That's what people enjoy watching. In
general, the rough's not going to be eight inches deep. Guys are
able to take chances. It should provide for some pretty aggressive
play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
