<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S THEME PARK JUST PART OF JONES' DREAM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys owner Jerry Jones has dedicated this
season to remembering the past.
</P>
<P>
   And rightfully so. Few organizations have had a greater first 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   But don't mistake Jones' nostalgia for contentment.
</P>
<P>
   While looking back, Jones is also considering major changes in
the future with a franchise icon: Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Cowboys' lease at Texas Stadium doesn't expire until
2008, Jones said it's not too early to start thinking about a new
home because it takes five or six years to build a stadium. That
could be a new stadium in a new location like Arlington or that
could be a renovated Texas Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   What's certain is that the current building has gone from state
of the art to obsolete.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this juncture we've got 17 new or renovated stadiums in the
NFL with several more on the drawing board,'' Jones said. ``The
facts are that Texas Stadium will be one of five or six stadiums
that haven't had major renovations.''
</P>
<P>
   Already mindful of state legislation that paved the way for two
new stadiums in Houston, Jones is also paying attention to Dallas'
Olympic bid. A Cowboys representative attends every meeting of the
Dallas 2012 committee, for, as Jones concedes, ``the Olympic thing
is something that has be considered for a venue like this, and we
need to see where it fits in the Olympic plan.''
</P>
<P>
   You see, Jones is not looking for a simple Texas Stadium
face-lift. He's talking about a tummy tuck, liposuction and colored
contacts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have the very best stadium in sports, and that's what I
want,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   What Jones wants is Jerry's World: a 100,000-seat stadium with a
retractable dome, and a theme park. The extra seats and the dome
would guarantee a Super Bowl would be played there. The theme park
is Jones' answer to Six Flags Over Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can have a 350-day-a-year destination point, not a place
that plays 10 or 11 games a year and makes do on the other days,''
Jones said. ``We can be the focal point of Texas and the focal
point of sports. It's the idea of having a place themed toward
sports and the activities of sports. We want to have different
activities that people can come on Tuesday in June and enjoy as
much as they can on Sunday in November. That's my goal.'' Honoring
the past and dreaming for the future, Jones is still Jones. Put Tex
in This message is for Jerry Jones. It's time to bring former
Cowboys general manager Tex Schramm back into the fold. What better
way to commemorate the franchise's 40-year anniversary than by
putting the man who helped start] it all into the Ring of Honor.
More than one former player noted that it was nice to see Schramm
at the team's official anniversary reception Sunday _ though they
also acknowledged that Schramm didn't look good, health-wise. Jones
should do the right thing and honor Schramm for what he's meant to
the franchise while Schramm can still appreciate it. Red Rock's
future Get one thing straight about last week's signing of fullback
Tim Lester to replace injured starter Daryl Johnston.
</P>
<P>
   Lester is the Cowboys' fullback for now. Robert Thomas, who was
moved from linebacker to fullback in training camp, is the Cowboys'
fullback of the future.
</P>
<P>
   At least, that's the word from Cowboys coach Chan Gailey, who
says he's excited about the 6-foot-1, 260-pound Thomas' potential
as a fullback. The former Henderson State star certainly has the
size, decent speed and bulldog-like tenacity.
</P>
<P>
   Most important, Thomas is passionate about the game and
succeeding in it. Thomas started out as the longest of long shots.
He was undrafted out of college and he has endured stints in the
Canadian Football League and NFL Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is here because he refused to give up on his dream to
play in the NFL. The Cowboys know if he takes that same
perseverance while learning his new position, they have a fullback
of the future.
</P>
<P>
   Talking Moose
</P>
<P>
   Less than a week after being sidelined for the season and
possibly his career with another neck injury, Johnston was on the
sideline with his teammates Monday. He said he plans to stay around
to lend moral support and guidance to his fellow fullbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised, however, if Johnston leaves the sidelines
for a radio booth in the near future. KVIL play-by-play man Brad
Sham has approached Johnston about joining him and Babe Laufenberg
on the Cowboys' broadcasts. Prime Time ballet Ever wonder why
cornerback Deion Sanders went to Dr. Bill Hamilton for his toe
surgery?
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton is considered the leading authority on sports-related
toe injuries, and he is the doctor of choice for the nation's top
ballet dancers.
</P>
<P>
   No Deion-hits-like-a-ballerina jokes, please.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
