<HEADLINE>
U.S. HELPING CANADA TRACK MIGRANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY AND JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Canada and the United States are using a network of spy
satellites, underwater acoustic sensors and electronic interception
techniques to track smuggling ships from Chinese ports, across the
north Pacific Ocean and into Canadian waters where they have been
intercepted.
</P>
<P>
   Since July 20, Canada has seized four ships carrying more than
600 Chinese. They are believed to have paid smugglers about $38,000
apiece to be slipped into Canada after a long sea trip under
primitive conditions.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth ship is believed to have unloaded its human cargo before
it was spotted sinking south of the Queen Charlotte Islands early
in July.
</P>
<P>
   Canadian officials have been reluctant to explain how their
CP-140 Aurora patrol aircraft have known where to spot boatloads of
illegal Chinese along Canada's vast coastline.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would give an advantage to people we are trying to
intercept,'' said Lt. David McKinnon, a Canadian Navy spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   But in fact, Canada and the United States are cooperating
closely in tracking the smuggling ships. It is a matter of great
interest to both nations _ Canada doesn't want a flood of illegal
immigrants, while the United States is concerned that many of them
will end up in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is an ongoing agreement between the U.S. Navy and the
Canadian Navy to foster cooperation in intelligence in that part of
the world,'' one U.S. Navy intelligence official said.
</P>
<P>
   Another U.S. Navy official confirmed that the service _ along
with other U.S. intelligence and law enforcement agencies _ has
been sharing information with the Canadians, although he declined
to specify the source of the data or how it was shared, saying such
information is classified.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadians also decline to be specific.
</P>
<P>
   ``In conjunction with our allies, we can be wherever we need to
be. We are working with the U.S. Navy and U.S. Department of
Defense all the time,'' McKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   Such information-sharing is conducted in part through the
Northwest Regional Naval Intelligence Center at Whidbey Island
Naval Air Station.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, the center has operated at a heavily guarded
facility staffed by several hundred military intelligence
specialists, including Canadian military personnel.
</P>
<P>
   Non-military experts point to several types of
intelligence-gathering methods available.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Richelson, a senior fellow at the nonprofit National
Security Archive in Washington, D.C., said, ``There are
(intelligence-gathering) assets under the sea, on land, in the air
and in space that can be used to monitor'' smuggler ships.
Richelson specializes in U.S. and foreign intelligence agencies,
and has studied the 40-year intelligence-sharing partnership
between the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Richelson and retired Adm. David Jeremiah, former commander of
the U.S. Pacific Fleet, said in separate interviews that the
U.S.-Canadian military partnership is structured to handle ``new''
security problems such as drug trafficking or illegal migrant
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would not surprise me to find there is collaboration,''
Jeremiah said of the illegal immigrant situation, particularly
since immigration officials suspect Chinese aliens who make it
ashore in Canada are headed to find work in urban centers like New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   While Canada has naval ships and patrol aircraft, it is the U.S.
Navy and U.S. intelligence agencies that are able to shadow the
smuggler ships from the moment they leave China, Richelson said.
</P>
<P>
   McKinnon acknowledged that ``you (the United States) have assets
as far as Guam, on the other side of the Pacific. We certainly work
with that.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Cold War, the United States developed overlapping
surveillance systems to track the Soviet Navy and its nuclear
submarine fleet in the Pacific, and many of those systems are still
active.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, Richelson said, they have been modified to
conduct surveillance on other activities, including drug smuggling,
illegal driftnet fishing and now, the smuggling of illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
   The at-sea surveillance is far more effective than trying to
track down illegal immigrants once they have entered Canada and can
cross virtually at will into the United States. Many New York-bound
illegals choose a notorious smuggling area near Cornwall, Ontario,
where Mohawk Indian reserves straddle the U.S.-Canada boundary
along the St. Lawrence River.
</P>
<P>
   Last December, U.S. and Canadian officials used a sting
operation to crack an illegal human smuggling ring operating there.
U.S. Attorney General Janet Reno called it ``the largest global
alien smuggling ring'' operating in the two countries and estimated
that it had carried as many as 3,800 illegal aliens into the United
States over a two-year period. Many were from China's Fujian
Province, where most of those aboard the ships seized this summer
were from.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of the methods available for tracking smuggling
ships:
</P>
<P>
   Satellites: Since the early 1970s, the United States has
operated a family of powerful spy satellites that can locate and
track ships by photographing them or triangulating their radio
broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Underwater sensors: The multi-billion-dollar Sosus (for sound
surveillance) System originally designed to locate and track Soviet
submarines has been altered since the decline of the Soviet/Russian
Navy to monitor surface ships as well. Navy officials say Sosus has
been effective in detecting illegal driftnet fishing vessels as
well as smuggling ships.
</P>
<P>
   Patrol aircraft: Both the U.S. and Canadian military in the
Pacific Northwest operate land-based aircraft that can locate
suspicious ships and submarines. The P-3C Orion and CP-140 Aurora
aircraft usually patrol areas the surveillance networks say harbor
suspicious vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Civilians: Tips from members of the public can be part of the
arsenal combating smuggling ships. ``We use sonar sets, ships at
sea, everything up to Joe and Jane Canada sitting on their deck and
spotting something suspicious on the water below their home,''
McKinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   SUGGESTED BOX:
</P>
<P>
   The surveillance of the smuggling ships intercepted off Canada
this summer is the latest example of the U.S. military tracking
civilian targets. Here are some other incidents:
</P>
<P>
   In April 1988, U.S. Navy officials revealed that four Iranian
grain ships heading for Vancouver, B.C., through the Strait of Juan
de Fuca had been tracked all the way from the Persian Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   Concern over possible terrorism was high because U.S. Navy
aircraft had sunk two Iranian warships in the Gulf the same week as
the Iranian grain ships entered the strait.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, the U.S. Coast Guard intercepted the vessel
Encounter Bay with 72 tons of high-grade Laotian marijuana 600
miles off the Washington coast.
</P>
<P>
   Officials disclosed in a federal court hearing the Encounter Bay
had been under U.S. surveillance since it was loaded with the drug
cargo in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, officials disclosed that a special U.S. Navy
intelligence unit based on Vancouver Island was involved in
surveillance of a Russian commercial shipping company operating in
western Canadian ports and in Puget Sound.
</P>
<P>
   The company's vessels were suspected of carrying out Russian
military intelligence missions, including snooping on Trident
submarines based at Bangor Submarine Base on Hood Canal.
</P>
<P>
   A U.S. Navy intelligence officer assigned to the unit suffered
eye burns from a laser while photographing a Russian freighter from
a helicopter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
