<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-FLOODS-PINETOPS-1STUP     09-21 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOODS-PINETOPS-1STUPDATE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    N.C. rain just won't go away
 &HT;    (EDS: UPDATES death of missing girl.)
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PINETOPS, N.C. _ The swirling black water had receded enough
Tuesday for Albert Reid to go back home, back to the place where he
almost drowned.
</P>
<P>
   Five of his neighbors died Thursday in Hurricane Floyd's rising
floodwaters. Another, a 5-year-old girl, disappeared into the snaky
underbrush of Town Creek. Her body was found Tuesday. The flooding
was one of the worst tragedies spawned by Floyd as it plowed up the
East Coast last week. Some rivers are just now cresting in North
Carolina, proof that, in this storm, water was more deadly than
hurricane-force winds.
</P>
<P>
   East of Pinetops, a motor boat attempting to carry a dozen
people to safety overturned. In Thursday's early morning, the
torrent carried half of them away.
</P>
<P>
   ``God, I thought about a lot of things under that water,'' Reid,
64, said Tuesday as he walked down Dodge Street, past his
flood-ravaged home, past a dead horse, past the cedar tree where
his wife, Mary, clung in the branches until she was rescued after
the boat capsized.
</P>
<P>
   The fast-rising waters covered all but the rooftops in the Dodge
City neighborhood, so badly damaged it warranted a visit Monday
from President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Pinetops, where mobile homes and stately homes interrupt
acre upon acre of water-sogged tobacco and cotton, Edgecombe County
residents have begun venturing out from the elementary school
emergency shelter as far as the retreating waters will allow.
</P>
<P>
   Along Town Creek, a Tar River tributary, surging water uprooted
oaks and sycamores and tossed around metallic propane gas tanks
like balloons. A jumble of logs and branches blocked Bynum Farm
Road, where rescuers spray-painted red X's over front doors to
signal they had searched for survivors.
</P>
<P>
   At its peak, water covered the heads of Jesus and his disciples,
portrayed in a tapestry tacked above the sanctuary door of St.
Stevenson Holy Church of Deliverance. Inside the dark hall, the
water overturned pews and the pulpit, swelled the red-carpeted
floor and perched a foot stool atop the door of the pastor's study.
</P>
<P>
   The receding waters left a smelly chocolate-brown residue on the
tile floor of what once was a cheerfully painted day care center at
the rear of the church. Diapers and toiler paper were among the
debris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things were floating in here like inside a big aquarium,''
said Glen Williams, 37, a church deacon.
</P>
<P>
   The stench of dead livestock hung in the air, seemingly pressed
down by the low gray clouds that dumped more rain Tuesday on top of
Floyd's torrential rainfall.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's downpour swelled rivers faster than people in
low-lying areas could escape.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden it came out like water pouring from a
bathtub,'' said Roosevelt Lewis, 70, throwing out corn Tuesday to
what remains of his chicken flock in Dodge City. He and his
brother, Milton, lost 55 goats and five horses _ Diamond, Missy,
Two Step, Blackie and J.R. One was stuck in a tree.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, police blocked the entrance to Dodge City except to
property owners and rescue workers whose search for 5-year-old
Teshika Vines came to a tragic end.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, Carlos Vines, had refused to stop looking in
emergency shelters until he knew for sure whether his daughter was
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities confirmed five other deaths: Carlos Vines' wife,
Keisha; her parents, Ben and Vivian Mayo; and neighborhood children
Cabrina and Destiny Flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Looking for hope in the tragedy, the Rev. Carolyn Slade, St.
Stevenson's pastor, pointed to a teal-green cinder block house. The
rising waters trapped 11 people in the attic, and all were rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ``We estimate that we pulled 200 to 300 people to safety,'' said
firefighter Mike Stallings, a member of the South Edgecombe
Volunteer Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know the Lord giveth and taketh away,'' Slade said. ``But
we were not prepared for this. It hurts, it really hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   A week ago, when Floyd veered toward the North Carolina coast,
residents of Dodge City braced for winds, but not for rain.
</P>
<P>
   Before he went to bed last Wednesday, Albert Reid moved his two
Cadillacs and Mazda pickup out from under the pine trees in his
yard. He didn't want to risk falling branches denting them.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't sleep that night, anticipating howling winds that
never came. He was surprised at dusk by the water rising from Town
Creek behind his house. He cranked his pickup, but it stalled.
</P>
<P>
   Reid went back inside and told his wife they'd have to wait for
a boat.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbor Ben Mayo was ferrying neighbors to safety in his
flat-bottomed aluminum boat. On a return trip to the flooding
subdivision, Mayo picked up Reid and his wife, bringing the number
of passengers to 12.
</P>
<P>
   As the boat rode against the swift current toward Bynum Farm
Road, Mayo gunned the motor and the bow popped up in the air. Water
poured in the back, and the boat turned over with its hull bobbing
above water.
</P>
<P>
   Trapped underneath, Reid bobbed up and down, gasping for breath,
until he was able to get out from under the boat.
</P>
<P>
   In the half light, he remembers two or three children clinging
to the hull. He had lost track of his wife and his stepdaughter
when another man tossed him a rope attached to the boat and told
him to wrap it around a utility pole.
</P>
<P>
   The boat stopped, and Reid escaped into a nearby house with
several others. As the water rose, they climbed into the attic,
hoping for rescuers who arrived several hours later in a boat.
</P>
<P>
   They retrieved the people in the house and Reid's wife and her
daughter from a nearby cedar tree.
</P>
<P>
   Overthe weekend, searchers found the bodies of the five
victims. Officials returned Mayo's boat to the carport of his dark
empty house, at the edge of the dense woods where the current swept
away 5-year-old Teshika.
</P>
<P>
   Reid remembers seeing her drifting away, across Annie Mae Ellis'
front yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get her,'' Reid said, ``but she was too far
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
