<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0808 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-TEX-SECURITIES-FRAUD-     09-21 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEX-SECURITIES-FRAUD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FBI arrests Texas man on securities fraud charges
 &HT;    By Laylan Copelin
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Brian Russell Stearns came to Austin last year
spreading money around. He bought a $2 million-plus mansion
overlooking Lake Austin. He donated to charities, invested in a
fleet of million-dollar aircraft and rubbed shoulders with
politicians.
</P>
<P>
   He attended President Clinton's fundraiser in Austin last May
and sat at the head table with Hillary Clinton when she visited
here in August to raise money for a possible U.S. Senate campaign
in New York. He paid off Garry Mauro's $100,000 campaign debt from
his unsuccessful run for governor.
</P>
<P>
   What no one knew at the time was that the FBI was investigating
Stearns, 29, for securities fraud. On Monday, the FBI arrested
Stearns at his Lake Austin home, charged him with securities fraud,
then seized the house, two jets worth more than $10 million, a $2
million helicopter and $800,000 in vehicles, plus undisclosed
amounts of money in bank accounts. Stearns was in custody Tuesday
awaiting a bail hearing in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   In a complaint, the FBI accused Stearns, who is married with a
small child, of selling $3.3 million in bogus securities to a
Georgia man. Stearns, according to the FBI, also is on five-year
probation for a 1994 conviction for grand theft in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Copeland, head of the FBI's white-collar crime unit in
Austin, said the six-month investigation is continuing.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are other victims out there,'' said Copeland, declining
to speculate on how many.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Butler, a partner with Realtor Tosca Gruber, said
Stearns came to them in the spring of 1998, looking at homes up to
$4 million and using an alias.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all sorts of people in this price range,'' she said.
``He told us he did international money handling _ in large sums.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler said Stearns bought the 8,000-square foot house. She said
he later deposited $900,000 as earnest money to buy 137 acres of
Lake Austin waterfront for $6 million, but he forfeited the money
when he did not come up with the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said he also hired off-duty police officers to guard his
house and planes. Law enforcement officers, who requested
anonymity, said Stearns liked to hang around police.
</P>
<P>
   No Austin Police Department officers are believed to have worked
for Stearns, but the Police Department is conducting an
``administrative inquiry'' into what role, if any, the city's park
police or marshals may have played, according to police.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be unusual for park police or city marshals to be
doing off-duty security,'' said Joe Canales, chief of staff for the
city manager. ``The police are just checking to make sure
everything is correct and appropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Byland, an Austin businessman, said Stearns had been a
partner of his in the aviation business.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know him long,'' said Byland, who added that he knew
nothing of Stearns' dealings in securities.
</P>
<P>
   He declined further comment.
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Garrett with Capitol Wings said Stearns chartered planes
from the company for about a year.
</P>
<P>
   Then Stearns invested in a Gulfstream III, a jet about the size
of a DC-9, that is capable of making trans-Atlantic flights. The
jet's plush interior seats 12 to 14 people and is worth $10 million
to $20 million. According to the FBI, authorities also seized a
Learjet 35A and an Italian helicopter, a $2 million craft with jet
turbines.
</P>
<P>
   Among the vehicles seized: two 1999 BMWs, a 1998 Mercedes LS
600, a 1998 Toyota Land Cruiser and a 1999 Four Winds power boat.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns' wealth quickly put him inside Austin's social circles.
</P>
<P>
   Butler said he was introduced at various charity events and gave
great parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``He liked to spend money,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   His spending included giving $1,000 to attend Clinton's
fundraiser at the house of advertising executive Roy Spence, a
longtime friend of Clinton's. Stearns paid another $1,000 to attend
Hillary Clinton's event in August.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, another longtime friend of the Clintons, said he
metStearns through a friend.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro said Stearns promised to raise $80,000 for Hillary Clinton
by selling tickets to the event. However, Mauro said Stearns failed
to do so. Mauro said he had Stearns checked out by the White House
and the Democratic Party but he was unaware of Stearns' problems
with law enforcement, even his conviction in Maryland for grand
theft.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, who lost to Gov. George W. Bush in 1998, said he met
Stearns for breakfast to discuss a contribution.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked for $5,000,'' said Mauro, trying to erase his 1998
campaign debt. ``He asked, 'How much do you owe?' I told him
$100,000 and he said, 'Why don't I just write you a check?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The check cleared.
</P>
<P>
   According to the FBI, Stearns got his money by lying to
investors. In an affidavit, FBI agent Evan Rae said Stearns
convinced Brent R. Butts of Ellijay, Ga., to invest $3.3 million in
bogus securities with a promise of a 40 percent return every 35
days without putting the money at risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``These schemes purport to invest in very high yield, European
bank debentures in a secret world market open only to select
individuals,'' Rae wrote. According to the Federal Reserve, Rae
wrote, ``These instruments do not exist.''
</P>
<P>
   The money, according to the FBI, went into Stearns' personal
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   Butts could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Laylan Copelin writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
