<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0814 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-MICH-HENSON-NYT &LR;      09-21 0777
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-MICH-HENSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORK IN THE ROAD LOOMS FOR HENSON 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a two-sport athlete, with one of the sports outside his
university, Michigan's Drew Henson has more leverage than most
sophomore quarterbacks. But he does not plan to use it to force his
coach, Lloyd Carr, to choose him as first-string quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've told everyone that I'm not going to leave early,'' Henson
said. ``I'm here for the long run. I can't guarantee anything. A
person my age, how much better situation would you want to be in as
a quarterback with the Michigan Wolverines, with the season we have
a chance of having? I wouldn't trade it for any other situation.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees are hoping that Henson will eventually trade it
for another situation _ major league baseball. Henson is also a top
prospect in the Yankee farm system, a third baseman who played for
the Yankees' Class A team in Tampa, Fla., this summer. In 69 games,
he batted .280, with 71 hits in 254 at-bats, including 13 homers
and 12 doubles. He had 37 runs batted in, walked 26 times and
struck out 71 times.
</P>
<P>
   Henson said he follows the Yankees, the defending World Series
champions, in newspapers, on television and on the Internet. ``I'm
a huge sports fan,'' he said after leading his team to an 18-13
victory over Syracuse last Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Many people around Ann Arbor, Mich., are becoming Henson fans,
as the Wolverines have streaked to a 3-0 start and the No. 4
ranking in the nation. Although he entered the game in relief of
Tom Brady for the third consecutive week, Henson played all of the
final three quarters, his most time so far. He seemed more nimble
and poised than Brady, a fifth-year senior, who completed 5 of 10
passes for 26 yards. Carr said Brady would start next week at
Wisconsin when the Wolverines open their Big Ten schedule. Henson
said that decision was all right with him. For now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to play, everyone's got a certain role, and
mine's changing as the course of the season goes,'' Henson said.
``Whatever they tell me to do, I'm going to do it. No one likes to
sit, but it's something that I've got used to. And I've learned
from. Right now I'm playing well, so I'm happy about my role as it
is on the team at this time.''
</P>
<P>
   That includes the Yankees, even if they wanted to move him to
the major league roster next season. ``They wouldn't,'' Henson
said, ``and I'm not ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not yet, but the Yankees appear to have no doubt he will
be sometime soon. According to Mark Newman, who will soon be named
director of baseball operations for the Yankees, Henson improved
steadily over the summer, mixed well with his teammates and made
several acrobatic plays at third base. ``It was more than we could
hope for,'' Newman said. ``Actually, it was kind of stunning.'' At
19, he was one of the youngest players in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said Henson hit a ball over the scoreboard beyond the
left-center fence at Legends Field, the Yankees' minor league park
in Tampa, and hit a home run in Jupiter, Fla., that was ``Ruthian,
McGwiresque.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He shows tremendous raw power, agility and athleticism, and
all the kinds of mental skills you could want,'' Newman said.
``He's a special, special guy. He's in the Jeter category, that
kind of person, that kind of talent.''
</P>
<P>
   It's possible that Henson could become the successor to Scott
Brosius at third, and he might be tantalized by the prospect of
playing alongside Derek Jeter, who grew up in Kalamazoo and became
a high-school star in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Henson may be ready for a larger football role. Against
Syracuse, his touchdown pass to the fullback Aaron Shea came with 3
minutes 4 seconds remaining in the first half and gave Michigan a
13-7 lead. On second down and 10 from the Syracuse 22, Henson took
the snap, backpedaled and drew the Syracuse rushers toward him
before tossing softly and accurately to Shea, who caught the pass
on a screen pattern and rumbled into the end zone.
</P>
<P>
   Henson finished with 16 completions in 28 pass attempts for 151
yards.
</P>
<P>
   Newman said the Yankees had not talked to Henson about football.
``That's going to play out over time,'' Newman said. ``We don't
pressure him, we don't bug him about this. We knew this going in,
and we definitely understand. It's just a wait-and-see issue. He's
a guaranteed major league player, and a good one. This guy is going
to be a great one.''
</P>
<P>
   Newman was asked about the possibility that Henson might want to
play both sports professionally, like Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll cross that bridge when we get to it,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
