<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0816 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT     09-21 0782
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: CALL TO ARMS FOR THE BATTLE OF ATLANTA 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For the first two months of this season, Dave Wallace
was cruising along, minding his business, as the Mets' senior
executive of player personnel and adviser to general manager Steve
Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Then suddenly in early June, when the Mets dismissed their
pitching coach, Bob Apocada, and two other coaches, Wallace found
himself plucked from the front office and sent in to coach the
team's wobbly pitching staff.
</P>
<P>
   Three months later, Wallace and the Mets find themselves here at
Turner Field with three opportunities to run down and catch a team
and a franchise that has tormented them for much of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have reminded the Mets of everything they lacked:
consistency, depth and an awesome arsenal of pitching. The Mets and
the Braves are still a study in contrast, the differences framed by
their respective pitching staffs, specifically the three who
started this crucial series: John Smoltz, Tom Glavine and Greg
Maddux for Atlanta; Rick Reed, Orel Hershiser and Al Leiter for the
Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's rotation is part of baseball lore, like Tinkers to
Evers to Chance. Reed, Hershiser (in recent years) and Leiter are
part of the less glorious journeyman tradition, one in which
careers rise and fall, are discarded and salvaged. Then one season,
they fall into the right space, the stars are aligned correctly,
and they find themselves staring a pennant in the face.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace's role in crunch time is to allow the staff to feel the
adrenaline but keep it in check. Smoltz, Glavine and Maddux put
their own pressure on a staff like the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   ``You try to encourage guys to do what they do best and do what
they've done all year,'' he said, ``Stay within themselves, execute
the pitches they know how to execute and not get carried away with
all the hype and the moment and the `Oh my gosh, I'm facing Greg
Maddux, I've got to be perfect because he's going to be perfect.'
We just have to go after their hitters the best way we know how
within the realm of our strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a burden of proof always, especially at this time of
year. When you combine September, being in a pennant race and the
fact that you're facing those guys over there _ the Smoltzes and
the Glavines and the Madduxes _ they enjoy those confrontations,
those challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have the best record in baseball since June 6, which
corresponds with Wallace's arrival and Apodaca's departure. There
have been no sudden innovations, no pitching epiphany. Mostly
Wallace has been a mound psychologist.
</P>
<P>
   While Smoltz, Glavine and Maddux have been the Braves'
foundation for a decade, Reed, Hershiser and Leiter have had
multiple careers in alternating cites with varying results. Reed,
Tuesday night's starter, was a replacement player in 1995 for the
Reds. After a frosty beginning Reed became a force for the Mets,
finishing 13-9 in 1997 and 16-11 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser, the star of the Dodgers' 1988 championship team and
the unanimous choice that year for the Cy Young Award in the
National League, is the oldest on the staff and the most
analytical.
</P>
<P>
   ``He breaks the game down as well as anyone I know,'' Wallace
said. ``He'll know what he has to do. He'll know who he's pitching
against, what the situation is, who's on base, who the next hitter
is who he doesn't want to beat him.''
</P>
<P>
   Leiter, who was at the core of the turmoil that brought Wallace
from the front office to begin with, is the wildest card of a
pitching staff full of wild cards. He has had two careers within a
career. He broke in in 1984 but never won more than four games
until 1993, when he was 9-6 with Toronto. After two dismal seasons
with Toronto, the last an 11-11 effort, Leiter went to the Marlins,
where he experienced a two-season resurrection. Last season Leiter
was 17-6, but this season Leiter is 11-11 (coincidentally, the same
as Glavine).
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real emotional, but that has to be controlled'' Wallace
said of Leiter. ``If he controls himself emotionally, he'll be
fine. That's my job to keep these guys in tune and not get caught
up in the hoopla.''
</P>
<P>
   The hoopla is growing. With 11 games to go, the Mets, who spent
so many years wishfully looking at Atlanta from a distance, find
themselves in touching distance. Will Wallace's inherited staff
finally pull the Mets ahead?
</P>
<P>
   ``You know that those guys are going to keep their team in the
ball game,'' Wallace said, nodding toward the Braves' clubhouse.
``That's all you can ask _ for your guys to keep you in the game
for most of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
