A0818 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS22-COX     09-21 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS22-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jones secures win for Braves with dual homers
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Chipper Jones was sick of all the talk, and sick of
all the waiting.
</P>
<P>
   It showed on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   He started Game 1 of The series against the Mets with a home run
from the left side of the plate, and finished it with a home run
from the right to power the Braves to a 2-1 win and a 1-0 lead in a
game he's promised would be key.
</P>
<P>
   The National League MVP candidate hit the magical 100 RBI
plateau at the perfect time _ the bottom of the eighth inning with
left-hander Dennis Cook on to turn him around at the plate. Jones
burned Bobby Valentine for the second time this season as the 1999
power-hitting right-handed version of Jones homered from both sides
of the plate for the third time this season, second against the
Mets. Of his 43 homers, 14 have come from the right side.
</P>
<P>
   On his bat and John Smoltz's arm, the Braves got a two-game lead
with two games to go in Part 1 of this series, that continues next
week in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The series to all but decide the NL East pennant began Tuesday
night with traffic backed up down Capital Ave, the press box
packed, an undeniable October chill in the air, and the major
league scoreboard in left center field finally rendered
meaningless.
</P>
<P>
   Matching that backdrop, the Braves sent the all-time winningest
postseason pitcher Smoltz to the mound, sleeved, bearded and jacked
up, judging by the 95's popping up on the speed of pitch sign.
Smoltz had had only one win in his previous 14 starts. His Mets
counterpart, Rick Reed, meanwhile, had brought the Mets 11 wins in
his last 14 starts.
</P>
<P>
   But in a series like this - that feels like the postseason - and
the season on the line, the past is moot. And so together they
pitched the way postseason games are supposed to be pitched, with
runs at an absolute premium. They fought to a 1-1 draw, leaving the
bullpens to decide the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves drew first blood on a Chipper Jones home run in the
first inning, a rip to right center for his 42nd home run and 99th
RBI of the season.
</P>
<P>
   But the peskiest bunch of hitters in the National League (tops
as a team with a .366 on-base percentage) weren't going to stand
for that long. Rey Ordonez singled to lead off the third inning and
after a blown Rick Reed bunt attempt, scored on consecutive singles
from Rickey Henderson and Edgardo Alfonzo. Alfonzo's liner glanced
off Jose Hernandez's glove and into center field for the game-tying
blow, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz saved his best pitching for the No. 3 and 4 hitters in
the inning as he retired John Olerud and Mike Piazza on a pair of
groundouts to the middle infield to hold it right there.
</P>
<P>
   These two teams haven't budged all year and weren't about to
start on Tuesday night. Through six innings they matched each other
with a run on five hits for the Mets and six for the Braves.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz's night ended with a big seventh inning when he stranded
runners at second and third, striking out Rickey Henderson on his
eight pitch of the at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Braves closer John Rocker sealed the win with 3 strikeouts in
the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll Rogers writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
