<HEADER>
A0827 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-CLEMENCY-CONGRESS-1ST     09-21 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLEMENCY-CONGRESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FBI DIRECTOR OPPOSED CLEMENCY `UNEQUIVOCALLY,' LETTER SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: SUBS grafs 2-6 to clarify, letter was prepared FOR Freeh,
sted BY him; ADDS that letter was included in subpoenaed documents
sent by White House to Congress, sted sent to Democrats; ADDS Freeh
objected when clemency first raised in '94; Raises prior 12th graf,
Freeh's letter ..., to new 3rd graf.) 
(ATTN: Ind., Ill., Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The FBI ``unequivocally opposed'' President
Clinton's offer of clemency to 16 Puerto Rican nationalists,
asserting that the release of most of the prisoners would
reinvigorate their terrorist movement, according to a letter
prepared by the law enforcement agency.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, prepared for FBI Director Louis J. Freeh, said the
clemency ``would likely return committed, experienced,
sophisticated and hardened terrorists to the clandestine movement''
for Puerto Rican independence. The letter also said the clemency
would ``psychologically and operationally enhance'' allies in the
militant organization FALN who killed five people and maimed 83 in
terrorist activities in the 1970s and '80s.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh's letter came to light at a congressional hearing intended
by Republicans to portray the president's act as reckless. Also
Tuesday, Clinton provided his first full explanation of his
decision in a letter to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Freeh did not sign the FBI letter, which was addressed but never
sent to Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee. But senior law enforcement officials said Tuesday night
that the letter accurately reflected Freeh's position.
</P>
<P>
   A draft of the letter was sent from the FBI to the Justice
Department for review prior to Freeh's signature, law enforcement
officials said. The letter was among the thousands of documents
sent by the White House to Congress in response to subpoenas for
information about the president's clemency decision.
</P>
<P>
   The letter said that Freeh had objected to clemency when it was
first raised in 1994, and again as recently as June 28; even so,
the letter said, Freeh was unaware that the president was actually
contemplating any commutation when the White House announced its
offer on Aug. 11.
</P>
<P>
   While some officials have privately acknowledged disapproval of
the president's decision, Freeh's letter is the first official
indication of the fierce opposition among law enforcement officials
to the clemency offer to the 16 terrorists, most of whom have
accepted it.
</P>
<P>
   Casting himself in the tradition of previous presidents who have
granted clemency in cases that were unpopular, Clinton portrayed
his release of the prisoners as an act of courage. He cited
Theodore Roosevelt's grant of amnesty to Filipino nationals who
fought U.S. control and Jimmy Carter's commutation of sentences of
Puerto Rican nationalists who had opened fire on the House of
Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   ``They exercised the power vested in them by the Constitution to
do what they believed was right, even in the face of great
controversy,'' Clinton wrote. ``I have done the same.''
</P>
<P>
   The president did not deal with the question of whether the
release of the prisoners might reignite the dormant terrorist
movement. But Rep. Vito Fossella, R-N.Y., asserted that recent
statements by a known Puerto Rican militant and ally of the
prisoners indicated that the release was stirring old passions.
</P>
<P>
   He quoted Filiberto Ojeda Rios, the leader of Los Macheteros, a
terrorist organization allied with the FALN, as telling a Puerto
Rican radio station that if the United States committed aggressive
acts against Puerto Rico, his group would ``not remain with their
arms crossed, you can be sure of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans coaxed out of other law enforcement officials a
concern that the ex-prisoners constituted a threat to American
security. While the officials were bound under the president's
claim of executive privilege not to disclose internal deliberations
over the matter, they catalogued the violent actions of the FALN,
the terrorist organization to which the prisoners belong.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Gallagher, assistant director of national security for the
FBI, told the panel, ``These are criminals and they are terrorists
and they represent a threat to the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress has acknowledged that it has no control over clemency
matters, which are the sole prerogative of the president. But
Clinton's explanation Tuesday appeared to make little difference to
those in the hearing room, who see the move as a political disaster
for the president and for his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton, who is
likely to seek the Senate seat from New York. She has run into
political trouble for at first supporting, then denouncing, her
husband's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have wanted to draw out the drama. The panel, led by
Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the government Reform
Committee, called several victims of FALN attacks, bringing them to
testify for the third time in less than two weeks. They included
Richard Pastorella, a retired New York City detective, who was
severely injured in a 1982 attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who thinks of us?'' Pastorella asked in a bitter voice.
``Certainly not Mr. Clinton,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The victims, and relatives of those who had been killed in
terrorist attacks, said that contrary to federal requirements, they
had not been notified of the prisoners' pending release.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And Republicans took issue with Clinton's apparent belief that
just because the prisoners had not been convicted of doing bodily
harm, they deserved to go free. ``The only reason some of them
didn't commit murders or bombings is because they were arrested
before they got a chance to,'' said Burton.
</P>
<P>
   Two Democrats, both African-Americans, offered a minimal defense
of the clemency. Rep. Danny K. Davis, D-Ill., said, ``Democracy can
be fellowship as well as punishment.'' Rep. Edolphus Towns, D-N.Y.,
urged Congress to ``move on'' and examine issues that ``have a real
effect on the lives of average Americans.'' The committee's ranking
Democrat, Rep. Henry Waxman of California, said reluctantly that he
``probably'' would not have granted the clemency.
</P>
<P>
   In his letter, the president disclosed some of the arguments
that former President Carter had used in persuading Clinton to
grant clemency in this case. He said that Carter wrote to him in
1997 that releasing the prisoners would be ``a significant
humanitarian gesture.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter also said that any concern that clemency might be viewed
as leniency was mitigated by the length of time that they had
already served, Clinton wrote. Most of them had been in prison at
least 16 years, a period that Clinton said was not commensurate
with the crimes of which they were convicted, which included
sedition, conspiracy and armed robbery but not bodily harm to
anyone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
