<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORD-CANADA-DEAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORD IN PACT WITH CANADA'S AUTO WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ The Ford Motor Co. reached a tentative, three-year
contract Tuesday evening with the union representing its Canadian
workers, three hours before a threatened strike at midnight.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was similar to the generous deal that
DaimlerChrysler AG negotiated with the United Automobile Workers
union last Thursday, although that contract is for four years.
</P>
<P>
   Both deals call for workers to receive annual wage increases of
3 percent plus annual cost of living adjustments nearly equal to
the inflation rate. With Canadian inflation running at close to 2
percent, the union said that this would mean total annual wage
increases would be roughly 4.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Both deals also provide large increases in pension benefits, to
encourage older workers to retire, partly to make way for younger
workers and partly to allow auto workers to reduce their work
forces slowly so as to become more competitive. The Canadian
retirees will receive an immediate, 13.5 percent increase in
monthly pension payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an excellent agreement,'' said Basil Hargrove, the
president of the Canadian Auto Workers union, which represents
13,300 Ford workers in Canada. The union's members will vote on the
agreement on Sunday; similar ratification votes in the past have
been easily approved.
</P>
<P>
   The final issue in the negotiations involved the union's
contention that Ford planned to move the production of minivan
seats in 2002 from a unionized supplier, the Lear Corp., to Magna
International Inc., which is not unionized. Hargrove said that this
issue had not been resolved, and would be the subject of further
talks with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian union plans to ask the General Motors Corp. and
DaimlerChrysler to accept similar deals. Hargrove said that the
union had not chosen which company would come next in the
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's peaceful settlement is a coup for Ford. Canadian
auto workers have a militant tradition of going on strike against
at least one auto maker each time a labor contract expires; the
contract in force for the last three years expired at midnight. The
union has checked its records back to 1970 and found a strike every
time that a contract expired except in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Armstrong, a union spokeswoman, said that she believed that
there had also been strikes after every contract expiration before
1970, going back to the first contracts in the late 1930s, although
the union has not checked its records back that far. The Canadian
Auto Workers union split off from the less militant UAW union and
became independent in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   The Canadian workers have almost always struck the first company
with which their leaders have sought a deal. An exception to that
rule came on the last contract, in 1996, when the Canadian workers
staged a three-week walkout against GM after reaching a
pattern-setting contract with what was then the Chrysler Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the frequency of strikes, auto makers have been willing
to expand their operations in Canada. While auto workers used to
earn the same on both sides of the border, the weakness of the
Canadian dollar in recent years has made auto workers' wages and
other costs there a third lower than in the United States.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2243EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0450 </DOCNO>
