<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; tta-z
u f BC-TRADE-REPORT-1STLD-WR     09-21 1179
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRADE-REPORT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREASE IN TRADE DEFICIT FUELS WORRIES ABOUT HEALTH OF DOLLAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to change 12 percent to 14 percent in 8th graf. Gives more
precise dollar-yen figures in 9th graf, followed by insertion re
early trading in Tokyo.)  (See also MARKET, JAPAN-ECON) 
(ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Another leap in the U.S. trade deficit in July
fueled fears Tuesday that the continuing surge in imports is
threatening the health of the dollar.
</P>
<P>
   As the American currency dipped yet again vs. the Japanese yen,
largely because of disappointment over the widening trade gap at
home and inaction by monetary authorities in Tokyo, stocks and
bonds reacted by falling sharply in financial markets. On Wall
Street, the Dow Jones industrial average dropped more than 225
points, or slightly more than 2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department reported that the trade deficit for July
hit $25.2 billion, higher than the June imbalance of $24.6 billion,
confounding expectations that the deficit would start to shrink as
economic growth picks up around the world. Imports from China,
Western Europe and Japan all hit new highs, well above the
projections of most economists who have followed the trade flows
with increasing concern. And exports advanced only slightly.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials sought to put the numbers in
perspective. ``The figures are still not as bad as they were in
1987,'' William Daley, the Commerce secretary, said Tuesday, noting
that in 1987 _ the last time it set a record _ the trade deficit
was 3.3 percent of the country's gross domestic product. Currently
it is closer to 2.8 percent, but it is rising fast. ``But the
numbers are high enough that they are a political problem, and they
could become an economic problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But many analysts fear that the steady increase of the trade
imbalance _ expected to hit $250 billion this year _ is
undercutting the value of the dollar as money flows out of the
United States to pay for an apparently insatiable American demand
for imported cars, electronics and luxury goods. A weak dollar,
which makes imports more expensive for consumers, could in turn
contribute to inflation and prompt the Federal Reserve to engineer
another increase in interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   ``With each new record trade deficit, the dollar grows more
vulnerable,'' said Michael Fenollosa, an international economist
with John Hancock Mutual Life Insurance Co.
</P>
<P>
   Until this summer, rising imports were generally regarded as
relatively good news in the financial markets. The dollar was
strong, and the influx of relatively inexpensive electronics, auto
parts and other goods served to revive shattered Asian economies
and helped to contain inflation. That contributed to keeping
interest rates low.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past two months, the calculus has started to
change. While the American economy remains strong, the dollar has
fallen more than 14 percent against the yen since July, far more
than expected. Some analysts have begun to worry that there is no
bottom in sight for the American currency.
</P>
<P>
   And what the markets received Tuesday was a double dose of news
that the challenges may only grow worse: Just before the trade
numbers came out, Japan's central bank declined to take aggressive
steps to reverse the yen's heady rise in value. Those steps might
have only been a stopgap measure. Nonetheless, a message was sent
to investors that the yen would continue to rise, and that message
soon became self-fulfilling. In New York Tuesday, the dollar
settled at 104.87 yen, vs. 106.38 yen on Monday, a significant
shift by the standards of the currency markets.
</P>
<P>
   (In early trading in Tokyo on Wednesday, the dollar strengthened
a bit against the yen.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fair to say that there's considerable tension with the
Japanese right now,'' one senior administration official said.
``These are the kinds of shifts that can portend trouble if you
leave them untreated.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Japan's finance minister and former prime minister, Kiichi
Miyazawa, is expected here this weekend for the annual meetings of
the World Bank and the International Monetary Fund, and Japan's
strategy for capping the rise of its currency is expected to be the
lead item on his agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bank of Japan is independent of the government just as
the Federal Reserve is _ and in recent years, as the power of
Miyazawa's finance ministry has waned, the central bank has become
considerably more willing to exercise that independence.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's figures complicate the politics of trade for the
administration on several fronts. The surging imports from China _
the deficit was $6.31 billion in July and is $35.65 billion so far
this year _ greatly complicate the administration's efforts to win
congressional approval of a deal to get China into the World Trade
Organization this year, if negotiations on that deal are wrapped up
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Even apart from that, the Republican majority leader in the
House, Dick Armey of Texas, said Tuesday that he doubted that any
deal struck with Beijing would make it through the House. Lawmakers
who ``have a long-term commitment to freedom of trade, they're
saying: `I don't want to go home and face the anger of my
constituents if I vote for this.'''
</P>
<P>
   Daley acknowledged Tuesday that the most disturbing aspect of
the figures was that exports to China are still falling.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decline in our exports to China is difficult to square
with the continued strong growth in their domestic economy,'' he
said. ``China is part of the global marketplace. If China truly
wants to join the World Trade Organization, the Chinese government
must open her markets to foreign goods and services.''
</P>
<P>
   The figures also give fuel to the critics of Vice President Al
Gore. So far the rising trade deficit is the biggest chink in the
administration's economic armor, and Republicans are doing what
they can to exploit the argument that Gore has contributed to a
strategy of running up the deficit.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton suggests that such a strategy was in place: He
said in New Zealand last week that the United States deliberately
allowed its trade deficit to rise in an effort to aid the countries
of Asia after the economic crisis that struck in July 1997. But he
did not discuss how to reverse that trend now that their economies
are recovering.
</P>
<P>
   Imports in July surged by 1 percent to a record $104.2 billion,
exceeding the modest rise in exports to $79 billion from $78.6 the
previous month.
</P>
<P>
   The deficit with Japan slightly exceeded the deficit with China,
at $6.78 billion in July, and $40.37 for the year so far. But the
problem is not only with Asian nations _ trade with Canada and
Mexico, America's partners in the North American Free Trade
Agreement, totaled about a third of the deficit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0451 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0835 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS &LR;      09-21 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXASA&AMP;M-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NEIL HOHLFELD  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
COLLEGE STATION _ The tradition of causing turnovers is alive and
well at Texas A&AMP;M, where the 1999 version of the Wrecking Crew
defense has come up with six interceptions and three fumble
recoveries that have led to 41 points in two games.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Aggies are averaging 538.5 yards and 49.5 points per game
after easy wins over Louisiana Tech and Tulsa, ranking second in
the NCAA in both categories. The new-look offense is on a roll, but
the defense is at the root of the big numbers.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Gamble, a redshirt freshman who has worked his way into
the linebacker position vacated by Dat Nguyen, says the turnovers
aren't by coincidence. It's what the defense tries to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mindset for us, the Wrecking Crew mindset,'' said
Gamble, who recovered a fumble in his first game with the Aggies
against Louisiana Tech. ``When you fly around the ball like we do,
good things are going to happen. Turnovers have a chance to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you do that, you're helping your offense, putting them in
position to have a short drive. That's definitely part of the
Wrecking Crew defense. We practice every day to cause turnovers.
Whether it's stripping the ball or putting ourselves in position to
get an interception, we're trying to cause them. Turnovers are
game-breakers.''
</P>
<P>
   The fifth-ranked Aggies will get their toughest test to date
this season Saturday afternoon when they host Southern Mississippi
at Kyle Field. The Golden Eagles lost 20-13 at Nebraska last week,
with the Cornhuskers needing two touchdowns by their defense to
avoid a major upset.
</P>
<P>
   That's what the Aggies will look for this week, a continuation
of the pressure defense that causes turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tradition here. It's encouraged,'' said senior
cornerback Jason Webster, who has two interceptions this season and
five in his career. ``The Wrecking Crew had a tradition of
turnovers, and we're here to carry on that tradition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pride ourselves on three-and-out _ or less if we can get a
fumble or interception _ and getting the offense back out on the
field. We just don't think about stopping teams. We want to help
our offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Some things haven't changed at Texas A&AMP;M, but there is one big
difference this year in the defense. Gamble, a former two-way star
at Alto High School, has been so active and effective he is now
listed as the starter at strong-side linebacker.
</P>
<P>
   That means Gamble gets the defensive signals from the sideline
and relays them in the huddle. The position of leadership doesn't
faze Gamble in the least. He comes from football stock _ his
father, Lucky, played at Baylor and is the coach at Alto.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable getting in the huddle and talking in the
huddle and being a leader,'' Gamble said. ``I was a quarterback for
three of my four years in high school. I called the defense in high
school, too. I'm used to being vocal. To tell you the truth, I
wouldn't like to be in a position where it wasn't like that.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Aggies did not shift their linebacking corps just
because they like Gamble's leadership. They like his ability to
make tackles _ he's tied with Webster for the team lead with 16 _
and his intensity in pursuing the ball.
</P>
<P>
   In the first two games of his collegiate career, Gamble says it
almost seems like something is missing. After playing quarterback
and linebacker in high school, he's not used to resting half the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny, because I'm so used to playing both ways that it's
like I've got all this energy left late in the game,'' Gamble said.
``I'm flying around every play. You can bust it every time and
don't have to worry about getting tired in the fourth quarter.
After you play defense, you get to go over to the sideline and
chill out. That's been the easiest thing for me to adjust to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble, 6-2 and 227 pounds, seems a natural for the Wrecking
Crew. During his redshirt season, he impressed the coaching staff
by playing with abandon on the scout team. Wherever the ball was,
Gamble was right there.
</P>
<P>
   The Aggies intended to replace Nguyen with Cornelius Anthony,
last year's starter at weak-side linebacker. After Gamble's
excellent showing in the season opener at Louisiana Tech, Anthony
was shifted back to the weak side to give Gamble more playing time.
This week, Gamble is listed as the starter at strong-side
linebacker for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew he was going to be a good player, so it was really a
matter of finding more playing time for him,'' said Aggies coach
R.C. Slocum. ``If he was playing behind Cornelius, he wasn't going
to be on the field as much as we'd like.''
</P>
<P>
   Gamble was the Class 2A defensive player of the year in 1997
after making 212 tackles, including 66 stops behind the line. On
offense, he passed for 1,501 yards and rushed for 1,025, but he
knew defense was his future at Texas A&AMP;M.
</P>
<P>
   Slocum always has liked players who force the action, and
Gamble's aggressiveness fits into the Aggies' scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of our philosophy is having pressure defense, being able
to make something happen on defense,'' Slocum said. ``We kind of
expect that. Part of playing good defense is expecting to knock
balls loose and intercept balls and pick up fumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had a pretty good history of doing that. I think our
guys go into games expecting to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
