</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRADLEY-MOYNIHAN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOYNIHAN TO ENDORSE BRADLEY IN PRESIDENTIAL RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JAMES DAO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, the four-term Democrat
from New York, will endorse former Sen. Bill Bradley for president
Thursday in New York City, potentially providing Bradley a lift in
the state's crucial primary and among Democrats across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement was expected, since Moynihan and Bradley have
been close friends and comrades on a variety of issues, including
tax and welfare policy, since Bradley joined the Senate in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   But in scheduling the announcement just before a meeting of the
Democratic National Committee in Washington this weekend, Bradley
seemed intent on sending a message to Democratic leaders from
around the country that his campaign is gaining strength against
the party's presumed front-runner, Vice President Al Gore. Both
candidates are to address the committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bradley is on a bit of a roll right now and this just adds to
the momentum,'' said Steve Murphy, a Democratic consultant who is
not allied with either campaign. ``Nationally, it adds a little bit
more political credibility to the candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The announcement also comes amid a spate of endorsements
released by Gore's campaign in recent days, including support from
California officials, Hispanic leaders and 10 members of Congress
from New York, including the dean of the delegation, Rep. Charles
B. Rangel of Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan is the third, and most prominent, senator to endorse
Bradley, who represented New Jersey in the Senate for three terms
before retiring in 1996. The others are Sen. Bob Kerrey of Nebraska
and Sen. Paul Wellstone of Minnesota. He has also been endorsed by
one member of the House, Rep. William O. Lipinsky, D-Ill.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has been endorsed by more than 100 members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   It is always difficult to measure the importance of political
endorsements, and with Moynihan, the task is even more complicated.
</P>
<P>
   He has not been an influential force within the New York state
Democratic Party for years, and thus his endorsement is not likely
to pull a significant number of Democratic officials into the
Bradley camp.
</P>
<P>
   But polls indicate that Moynihan, who is retiring at the end of
next year, remains popular with voters across New York, including
in the more conservative northern and western reaches of the state.
So his support could give Bradley a lift in the New York primary on
March 7, when 292 delegates will be at stake. Many Democrats say
Bradley must win the primary to keep his insurgent campaign alive.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan _ who has been an adviser to four presidents, the
ambassador to India, a Harvard professor and the author of numerous
books _ is also widely regarded as the Senate's reigning
intellectual, and his endorsement could help burnish Bradley's
image with well-educated voters.
</P>
<P>
   More difficult to measure is whether Moynihan will help Bradley
among Democrats who are unhappy with the Clinton administration,
either for policy reasons or because of the president's affair with
Monica S. Lewinsky. Moynihan has often clashed with the Clinton
White House. He disagreed with its health care plan when he was the
chairman of the powerful Senate Finance Committee. He voted against
the 1996 welfare bill that Clinton points to as a signature
achievement, and after it passed, Moynihan strongly denounced it.
</P>
<P>
   He also applauded Sen. Joseph I. Lieberman's denunciation of
Clinton's affair with Ms. Lewinsky as ``disgraceful'' and
``immoral.'' But Moynihan later voted against convicting Clinton on
impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Bradley and Gore campaigns, as well as Moynihan's
office, declined to comment on the endorsement. But an official
close to Moynihan said that it more reflected his friendship with
Bradley than discontent with Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The two became friends in 1978 when Moynihan endorsed Bradley in
his first campaign for Senate. In the Senate, Moynihan supported
Bradley's efforts to revamp the tax code, which led to the sweeping
Tax Reform Act of 1986, which reduced rates and closed loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   They also cut similar figures in the Senate as somewhat aloof,
thoughtful and academic outsiders who seemed less than comfortable
with the roiling floor battles and partisan politics of legislative
life.
</P>
<P>
   When he endorsed Bradley, a former professional basketball star,
in 1978, Moynihan quoted Woodrow Wilson, saying, ``Men of ordinary
physique and discretion cannot be presidents and live, if the
strain be not somehow relieved. We shall be obligated always to be
picking our chief magistrates from among wise and prudent athletes
_ a small class.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
