<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 22:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-CLINTON-TRAVEL-ART-NY     09-21 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-TRAVEL-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP SAYS $72 MILLION FOR CLINTON TRIPS GOES TOO FAR 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Releasing a report showing that President Clinton's
travels to Africa, China and Chile had cost the government $72.1
million, the Senate's third-ranking Republican accused the
president Tuesday of traveling overseas to an extent that was
``almost abusive of the right and the privilege and the
responsibility'' of his office.
</P>
<P>
   The draft study by the General Accounting Office of three of
Clinton's overseas trips was made public by Sen. Larry E. Craig of
Idaho, along with Sens. Jeff Sessions of Alabama and Craig Thomas
of Wyoming, who are also Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Craig, who is chairman of the Senate Republican Policy
Committee, pointed in particular to the president's six-nation tour
of Africa last year because it cost $42.8 million and involved more
than 1,300 government officials who accompanied the president and
his delegation or went ahead as advance teams. The total does not
include Secret Service security expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that's an awful high price tag to pay for an
apology,'' Craig said, apparently referring to Clinton's speech in
Uganda in which he expressed regret for the role of the United
States in African slavery. Clinton also spoke of a list of errors
in American policy toward Africa, like embracing dictators as
allies during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Asked by reporters to further explain his remark, Craig said:
``I'm not saying we shouldn't express that point of view. I'm
saying it's a very costly way to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   But members of the Congressional Black Caucus, many of whom
accompanied Clinton on the Africa trip, took issue with Craig's
remark about a costly apology and asked why the senators had not
looked at the costs of the president's trips to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``You cannot measure in dollars and cents the value that this
historic trip by a president of the United States had to Africans
throughout the continent,'' said Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., ``and
how proud it made African-Americans.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Conyers Jr., D-Mich., said Craig's remark ``reflects a
profound lack of sensitivity to the history of our two continents,
which speaks volumes about the Republican Party as we head into the
next election season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican news conference was the latest salvo from a
Republican Congress now investigating the 1993 siege at Waco, the
president's granting of clemency to Puerto Rican nationalists and
Clinton's Russia policy.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said that the General Accounting Office report had been
commissioned long ago and that the timing of its release had been
coincidental. But he added, ``If the house of cards is crumbling, I
would suggest that while it may be a brick at a time, it will bring
a whole wall down.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, as the senators noted, has traveled to 59 countries as
president. The three men said they had asked the accounting office
to focus on the three trips in particular because of news accounts
that they were expensive.
</P>
<P>
   The study of the costs of presidential travel was released as
Republican leaders in Congress were struggling to find a way to cut
spending bills to the levels required by the 1997 balanced budget
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The senators Tuesday blamed Clinton for some of their problems,
noting that much of the financing for his trips came from military
readiness accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember in the closing days of our military engagement over
Kosovo, we ran out of smart bombs?'' Craig said. ``The amount of
money on these three trips would have acquired 3,000 smart bombs.''
</P>
<P>
   Sessions said the $60 million the trips had cost the Pentagon
could have been used for things like military recruitment, or
veterans affairs or to give men and women in uniform extra money so
that they would no longer need to rely on food stamps.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Department of Defense paid 88 percent of the estimated
costs of the Africa trip, 83 percent of the Chilean trip and 74
percent of the trip to China right out of our defense budget,''
Sessions said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Lockhart, the White House press secretary, Tuesday staunchly
defended the president's overseas travel, saying the trips ``more
than pay for themselves.'' He said, ``One-third of the 20 million
new jobs created in this country under this administration comes
from increased exports. The president has been very aggressive
about opening markets so that jobs can be created here at home.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Lockhart said that much of the costs incurred by the Pentagon
were for secure communication and physical security. He said that
in Africa in particular the Pentagon had had to create a system for
security and secure communications.
</P>
<P>
   The accounting office found that the Pentagon had spent about
$37.7 million on the Africa trip, with the bulk of the costs going
for ``passenger and strategic lift'' and refueling. The airlift and
refueling missions were made to transport 13 Army and Marine Corps
helicopters. The Pentagon also deployed troops to provide medical
services and aircraft maintenance and to erect temporary aviation
sites and accommodations for travel in Africa.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2255EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
