<SLUG> BC-CAMEL-AD-COLUMN-875&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: CAMEL'S KINDLER, GENTLER CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the most unusual recent campaigns for a mainstream
consumer product is being replaced with a series of softer, less
confrontational advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Since May 1998, a brash, unconventional campaign carrying the
deliberately hyperbolic theme ``Mighty tasty!'' has peddled the
Camel line of cigarettes sold by R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. The
oddball, almost surreal ads, created by Mezzina/Brown in New York,
have mocked the anti-tobacco movement and celebrated those who
continue to smoke.
</P>
<P>
   The replacement ads by the same agency, which are scheduled to
begin appearing this week as October issues of magazines reach
newsstands, take a different tack. Rather than lampooning critics
of smoking, they seek attention with a playful commemoration of the
Camel brand's history, which dates to 1913, as well as a new theme,
``Pleasure to burn.''
</P>
<P>
   The shift is indicative of the increasingly frequent changes in
campaigns for products marketed in the mass media. The goal for
such ads is to remain fresh and appealing to avoid a fate that may
be worse than alienating consumers: boring them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We found the `Mighty tasty!' campaign highly successful with
adult smokers, who appreciated it as a spoof of many of the social
conventions of our time,'' said Fran Creighton, marketing vice
president for Camel at R.J. Reynolds in Winston-Salem, N.C., a unit
of RJR Holdings Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The new campaign ``is a `re-expression' of what Camel is
about,'' she added, ``an authentic, original brand with an
irreverent personality.''
</P>
<P>
   Another reason for the change, Ms. Creighton said, was ``our
ability to meet the challenge of getting our message across in all
the media available to us'' now that limits on cigarette
advertising, which started in November, rule out billboards and
other outdoor posters.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Pleasure to burn'' ads are simpler, less graphically busy
and thus more likely to ``telegraph their message'' than the
``Mighty tasty!'' campaign, she added, making them more appropriate
for the remaining venues for cigarette advertising: print, direct
mail and signs in stores, bars and clubs.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Mighty tasty!'' campaign, shot by David LaChapelle, the
fashion photographer, in bright, saturated colors, featured some of
the most offbeat images and characters ever created by Madison
Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   There was a ``politically incorrect parade'' with floats
promoting meat, beer and Camels; a tribe of cannibal women cooking
``man stew''; a prisoner who escapes from his cell by fashioning a
dummy from scores of Camel packs; a man and woman held captive by a
lizardlike alien that keeps them happy by providing them with
Camels; a maid who brazenly flicks her cigarette ash into the meal
she is cooking for her stuffy rich employers, and a family racing
to a bomb shelter as a giant meteor hurtles earthward, their arms
overflowing with cartons of Camels.
</P>
<P>
   With so many of the ads being centered on flattering smokers by
portraying them as defiant rebels, laughing at trouble, danger and
even death, the subtext seemed to paraphrase the last line of a
Dorothy Parker poem, ``You might as well smoke.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the prisoner ad was a sly reminder that prison is one
of the few indoor public facilities that still permit smoking, Ms.
Creighton replied, laughing: ``I don't know. I haven't been
there.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign even offered outlandish versions of the warning
labels affixed to films and television shows admonishing ``viewer
discretion advised.'' For instance, ``package tampering'' and
``self-parole'' were among the fake advisories for the prison ad,
while the maid was flagged for ``premeditated ashing.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics complained that the make-believe advisories subtly
mocked the surgeon general's warnings against smoking required on
all cigarette packs and ads.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's clearly trying to undercut the authority of the surgeon
general,'' said Bob Garfield, the ad critic for the trade
publication Advertising Age, ``and clearly aimed at people below
age who are encouraged to flout authority.'' In a review in July
1998, Garfield castigated the campaign as ``Mighty nasty.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, the ``Pleasure to burn'' ads are mild as May, to
quote an old slogan for a Camel competitor, Marlboro. The idea is
to ``mix the contemporary and classic with a little bit of fun,''
Ms. Creighton said, ``looking for characters who represent all the
decades of Camel's popularity'' who are ``celebrating the heritage
of the brand yet relevant to today.''
</P>
<P>
   The device used in the new ads, which are hand-painted and
airbrushed for a vintage effect, is a graphic game that could be
called ``find the anachronism.'' The first two ads show images
seemingly from the 1930s or 1940s, a leggy pinup girl talking on
the phone and a man in a trenchcoat and battered fedora. But on
closer inspection, the reader notices that the phone she is using
is cellular and he is wearing a small gold earring.
</P>
<P>
   After the new ads were described to Garfield, he said: ``I'd
find it difficult to quibble with that, short of someone finding
some similarity to `what's wrong with this picture?' in Highlights
for Children. To a degree that looking for the little anachronisms
gets people involved, it can only improve the advertising.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ms. Creighton said that criticism of the ``Mighty tasty!''
campaign had nothing to do with its discontinuation because ``we
got very positive feedback from our smokers as well as smokers of
competitive brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Camel line has risen to No. 4 among all American
brands in shipments for the first eight months of 1999, compared
with seventh for the full year 1998 and sixth for the full year
1997.
</P>
<P>
   While the market share for Camel products like Camel Lights and
Camel Menthol has remained flat, shipments for brands that had
ranked ahead of Camel like GPC and Basic have slipped. Camel is now
the second-largest R.J. Reynolds brand, behind Doral but ahead of
Winston.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Creighton declined to discuss spending for the ``Pleasure to
burn'' campaign. Ad spending rose substantially in 1998, to $77.9
million, from $61.4 million a year earlier, according to
Competitive Media Reporting, which tracks advertising expenditures.
For the first six months of 1999, ad spending declined to $24
million from $34.8 million in the corresponding period of 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
