<HEADLINE>
TWO HOME RUNS BY JONES POWER BRAVES TO 2-1 VICTORY OVER METS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Atlanta Braves entered this series one game ahead
of the Mets, but well behind the image of invincibility they had
constructed during this decade. As their disabled list began to
look like an overstuffed social registry for baseball players, the
Braves had struggled to hold off the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   When Chipper Jones stepped to the plate in the bottom of the
eighth inning, his first-inning home run having produced Atlanta's
early lead before the Mets tied the score in the third inning,
first place in the National League East rested on his bat. There
really was no other appropriate way for the first game of this
series to be decided: the Mets' bullpen, one of the best in the
league, against one of the league's best players.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had replaced Turk Wendell with Dennis Cook to face
Jones, trading a pitcher who had given up four hits to Jones this
season for a pitcher who had yielded just one. But on a 1-1 pitch,
Jones smacked his second home run of the night _ they came from
different sides of the plate _ to give the Braves a 2-1 lead and a
victory that boosts them to two games ahead of the Mets in the
division.
</P>
<P>
   As are so many games involving the Braves, this one was
determined by pitching, but not the kind normally expected of the
Braves. If the names sounded familiar, then the results did not.
This was a matchup of two pitchers struggling to reestablish
themselves at the tail end of what had been unexpectedly
disappointing seasons. The aces will come later in the series with
a glamour matchup in the third game; this was one for the gritty
working stiffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed's season had been marred by injuries to his calf and
finger, interrupting what had been an uneven season, at best. On
July 25, he held the Braves to one run in 6 and one-third innings,
but opposing batters are hitting almost .300 against him this
season and he has walked more batters than he had in his previous
two season. The finger injury that put him on the 15-day disabled
list for most of August had sent him on an even more tortuous quest
for consistency.
</P>
<P>
   In his two starts, both no decisions, since his return, he had a
6.30 earned run average and Bobby Valentine was convinced that Reed
was leaving his pitches up. Reed disagreed and Valentine dropped
Octavio Dotel from his six-man rotation rather than Reed, but it
was no surprise when Jones, the Braves' most valuable player
candidate, and the third batter Reed faced, hit his 42d home run of
the season on a 2-1 pitch that Reed left up in the strike zone to
give the Braves a quick 1-0 lead. It looked like an inevitably long
night for Reed and the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   But John Smoltz is not the same pitcher who once won the Cy
Young. For one thing, he doesn't even look the same, having
completely remade himself into a side-armer to alleviate the
chronic pain in his right elbow when he pitches. His results have
not been the same, either and that has been astonishing.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz was 9-8 with a 3.51 ERA entering the game, but since
changing his motion Aug. 9, he is 1-3 with four no decisions and a
3.38 ERA. Valentine said none of Smoltz's pitches even looked
similar to what he used to throw _he called Smoltz's remolding
``remarkable'' _ and that he hoped the Mets would approach Smoltz
as an entirely new pitcher, one they had never seen before. Smoltz
walked two batters in the first two innings, but did not allow a
run.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets finally got to him in the third, when Rey Ordonez
singled to center field. Reed struck out, but Rickey Henderson hit
a line drive single to center and Edgardo Alfonzo hit a shot that
tipped off shortstop Jose Hernandez's glove and rolled into center
as Ordonez came around to tie the score 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, Reed had settled down, and, although still
inconsistent, he showed his best stuff since his return. With
pitches routinely clocked in the low to mid-90s and his pitches
staying down, in the second inning, he allowed two singles, but
also struck out three. In the third, he struck out Bret Boone, the
number two hitter, and caught line drives from leadoff hitter
Gerald Williams and Jones. Reed had not made it past the sixth
inning in his two starts since coming off the disabled list, but,
after the second, he got ahead of almost every hitter he faced.
</P>
<P>
   He did not allow a runner into scoring position until the sixth,
when Ryan Klesko slapped a one-out double down the left-field line
and moved to third on a wild pitch. But Reed got Andruw Jones to
fly out to right field _ it was the seventh out recorded by the
outfield on a gusty night _ to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets fared no better against Smoltz. After the run scored in
the third inning, the Mets had only two baserunners through the
sixth, and Mike Piazza's baserunning snafu after he hit a one-out
single _ he stepped off first when Robin Ventura lined out to
second baseman Bret Boone, who then threw to first for the double
play _ ended that threat abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   But with the game deadlocked _ and Reed having thrown 106
pitches in six innings _ Valentine pinch hit for Reed in the
seventh. Reed had done all the Mets could have hoped. In six
innings, he had shown the control that had eluded him recently,
giving up just one run and striking out six with no walks. With two
out and Roger Cedeno having walked to first, Bonilla _ who was
batting .280 against Smoltz with four doubles _ smacked a double to
the right field wall. But the hard-hit shot got to the wall quickly
and right fielder Gerald Williams got there just as fast. Cedeno
had to hold up at third.
</P>
<P>
   That brought Henderson, who had singled and doubled already, to
the plate. He took Smoltz to a full count. But Smoltz threw
Henderson high heat and Henderson swung and missed to end the
inning. He pitched seven innings, allowing just the one run on six
hits, with three walks and six strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
