<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE SHARP AS YANKEES DROP WHITE SOX, 3-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The infamous right-center-field bleachers were almost
empty Tuesday night as fewer than 100 people paid $7 to sit in
soggy seats and watch the best team in the American League play. It
was a blustery night, and the rain that had fallen throughout the
day put the game between the Yankees and the White Sox in peril. At
least that was what the normal bleacher denizens must have thought.
</P>
<P>
   But the rain stopped, a blue tarp was removed from the field and
the Yankees began their final home stand of the regular season with
a game that was more important than some fans realized. The Yankees
are virtually guaranteed to reach the postseason, but they are
still trying to clinch a division title and still trying to
maintain the finest record in the league, serious goals for a team
that has not won anything yet.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the precise way Andy Pettitte pitched and the
intelligent way the Yankees played in the 3-1 victory, the Yankees
displayed how crucial this game was to their future. If the Yankees
want to subdue the Red Sox in the AL East and remain ahead of the
Indians and the Rangers for home-field advantage during the
playoffs, they must treat every night the way they treated Tuesday
night. As if it is already October.
</P>
<P>
   That was how Pettitte pitched. Other than Carlos Lee's homer in
the second, Pettitte allowed no runs on five hits to the White Sox
over seven and one third innings. When Pettitte's cut fastball is
really operating, he treats runners on base like dust beneath his
cleats. That was what happened Tuesday night as Pettitte held the
White Sox to no hits in eight at-bats with runners on base,
destroying rally attempts and winning for the seventh time in his
last 10 decisions.
</P>
<P>
   With Paul O'Neill delivering two runs, the Yankees won for the
sixth time in their last seven games and stayed three games ahead
of the Red Sox, who also won. The Yankees (91-59) kept a one-half
game edge over the Indians (91-60) for the top record in the league
as Cleveland also won. Even with bleachers barren, these games are
still important.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you play for the Yankees, if you don't win, it's
disappointing,'' said David Cone, who was talking about winning the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   After James Baldwin had tamed the Yankees on three hits in the
first four innings, Ricky Ledee and the rookie D'Angelo Jimenez,
who started at third base for Scott Brosius, stroked back-to-back
singles to start the fifth. With runners on first and third, Joe
Girardi pushed a beautiful bunt along the first-base line. Ledee
did not leave third until the ball was bunted successfully and he
easily scored to even the score, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Girardi, who peeked toward third as soon as the bunt was down,
was greeted in the dugout like a player who had just ripped a
two-run homer after his team-best sixth sacrifice hit of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch lined a sharp single to left field, but Jimenez
was nailed at the plate by about eight feet when Darrin Jackson
made a powerful throw home.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees continued attacking Baldwin and Derek Jeter
reached first on a single into the shortstop hole to put runners on
first and third. O'Neill, who had slammed his bat and his helmet
after third baseman Craig Wilson made a leaping catch on his liner
in the third, rocketed a ball to where it could not be caught. It
was close. O'Neill's shot to right-center was almost grabbed by
Magglio Ordonez, but he was tentative in the wet grass and the ball
nicked off his glove for a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   With the two runs batted in, O'Neill has 100 and has knocked in
at least 100 for three straight years. O'Neill, who revealed last
week that he wanted to play one more year with the Yankees before
retiring after the 2000 season, has been hitting like someone who
has a lot of productive years left.
</P>
<P>
   In O'Neill's last nine games, he has 6 homers and 19 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson replaced Pettitte with a runner on first and one out
in the eighth and retired two straight batters, pumping his arms
like a chain saw as he returned to the dugout. Mariano Rivera, the
invincible closer, handled the ninth for his 42d save and the
Yankees moved closer to attaining some serious goals.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
