<HEADLINE>
HEWLETT-PACKARD IN DEAL WITH ORACLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Hewlett-Packard Co., long a laggard behind Sun
Microsystems and IBM in computer systems for electronic commerce,
took a step toward strengthening its Internet presence with the
announcement Tuesday of a deal with Oracle Corp. to collaborate on
developing and selling Oracle's electronic commerce software on
Hewlett-Packard computers.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle said it would make HP-UX, Hewlett-Packard's version of
the Unix operating system, a ``strategic development platform'' for
all of Oracle's e-business software applications. In practical
terms, this should ensure that each new version of Oracle's
software runs as well on Hewlett-Packard's computers as it does on
machines made by Sun, Hewlett-Packard's archrival in the network
and Internet server market.
</P>
<P>
   The endorsement of Oracle, the clear leader in software for
electronic commerce, is key to Hewlett-Packard's Internet products,
which it calls ``e-services.''
</P>
<P>
   The benefit to Oracle is less clear, but it could give a boost
to the company's new customer relationship management applications,
or CRM, which manage tasks like sales contacts and service calls.
Hewlett-Packard has agreed to use and co-sell the Oracle Sales
component of Oracle's CRM suite of software programs. Oracle has
said it views CRM as a major growth driver for the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   On a day of broad market downturns, Hewlett-Packard shares
closed at $99.375, down $4.6875, on the New York Stock Exchange,
while Oracle shares closed at $44.50, down 62.5 cents, in NASDAQ
trading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are together addressing the CRM market first because it is
the fastest-growing market today,'' Carly Fiorina,
Hewlett-Packard's president and chief executive officer, said at a
press conference at the company's Palo Alto headquarters Tuesday
morning. ``This is a major shift from the way Hewlett-Packard has
done business in the past when we were more of a Switzerland,
partnering with everybody. Today we are making a clear choice.''
</P>
<P>
   This was the first major announcement from Hewlett-Packard since
Ms. Fiorina took the company's reins in July. It is part of a
strategy articulated by Ann Livermore, president of the enterprise
computing division, to announce a new strategic partnership every
week, emphasizing deals designed to irritate Sun and IBM and
counter the perception of Hewlett-Packard as the also-ran of the
Web.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Earle, Hewlett-Packard's senior vice president and chief
marketing officer for the enterprise computing division, noted that
the company's stock price had doubled since the e-services strategy
was announced. ``The Internet aura has been successfully applied to
HP,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the deal helped Hewlett-Packard at the expense of
Sun, which every year sells billions of dollars worth of servers
running Oracle's database software. But Gary Bloom, Oracle's
executive vice president, insisted the company would not emphasize
one hardware platform over another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the close relationship with Sun has changed at
all,'' Bloom said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   He said the major benefit to Oracle would be adding
Hewlett-Packard's sales force to the marketing of its customer
relationship management software. ``I get a virtual extension of
the Oracle sales organization,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
