<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILIBUSTER-CONGRESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SENATE PARADOX, DEMOCRATS STALL CLINTON NOMINEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Tuesday added a new chapter to the
strange and complex history of judicial politics as Republicans
tried and failed to end a Democratic effort to block votes on three
of President Clinton's nominees to the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Not only were Democrats blocking the nominees of a Democratic
president, but White House officials were sympathetic to their
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Underlying the convoluted political maneuvering is a complaint
shared by the Senate Democrats and the White House that most of
President Clinton's nominees have been languishing in the Senate.
At the same time, Senate Democrats and the White House insist, the
Republicans are pushing through with extraordinary speed the
nomination of Ted Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, who is one of the three nominees being held up, is a
Utah Republican and friend of Sen. Orrin Hatch, also a Utah
Republican and chairman of the Judiciary Committee. Clinton
nominated Stewart last July as a courtesy to Hatch, hoping that the
gesture would encourage the Republicans to move swiftly on some of
Clinton's other nominees, the ones he really wants to put on the
bench.
</P>
<P>
   It was meant to be a a classic political bargain to get things
going, but both sides seem to have taken away a different
understanding of the terms of the deal. A result of Tuesday's
stalemate, several senators agreed, is the potential to end
consideration of all judicial nominations until after the
presidential election of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch has been adamant that Stewart must be confirmed to a
federal district court seat in Utah before others are considered. A
Clinton administration official said this week that it was
fundamentally unfair that Stewart, nominated barely two months ago,
gets a vote in the Senate while other nominees have waited for
years.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict intensified Tuesday as the Republicans tried to
invoke cloture, a procedure to force a vote on the Stewart
nomination and end the threat of a filibuster, an extended debate.
The vote, along party lines, was 55 to 44, leaving the Republicans
five votes short of the 60 votes needed to invoke cloture.
</P>
<P>
   The threat of a filibuster and a cloture vote have rarely
occurred in judicial nomination fights. Even during the hotly
contested Supreme Court nominations of Robert H. Bork in 1987 and
Clarence Thomas in 1991, no filibuster was even contemplated.
</P>
<P>
   Richard A. Baker, the Senate historian, said the procedure seems
to have been used on only a handful of occasions in the Senate's
history. Although there was no filibuster threat in the cases of
Bork or Thomas, cloture was invoked, for example, in 1971 to force
a vote on President Nixon's nomination of William H. Rehnquist, now
the chief justice, to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   After the Republicans failed in their cloture attempt, the
Democrats tried and failed to force votes on two Clinton nominees
they say should be considered before Stewart. Republicans used
their majority to block votes on Marsha L. Berzon and Richard A.
Paez to fill seats on the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals, based
in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Paez, a district court judge, has waited more than four years
for a floor vote, setting a record. Democrats have argued that the
Republicans are opposed to him, and would rather kill the
nomination by simply never bringing up his nomination rather than
allowing a vote that would leave them in the politically difficult
position of opposing a Hispanic jurist.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Berzon has waited about three years to be considered by the
full Senate.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
