u a BC-SCHOOL-BUS-SAFETY-NYT     09-21 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-BUS-SAFETY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO GAIN SEEN IN SEAT BELTS ON SCHOOL BUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., La., Calif.)  (jt) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Adding seat belts to school buses will cause
additional head injuries and probably additional deaths in some
crashes, the National Transportation Safety Board said Tuesday, and
instead it recommended better padding to protect the students.
</P>
<P>
   While the safety board's findings are influential, they have no
regulatory authority and the announcement will have no legal power
over New York and New Jersey, the only two states that currently
require seat belts on school buses.
</P>
<P>
   School buses built since 1977 rely for safety not on seat belts,
but on closely spaced seats with high, padded seat backs.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there has been growing agitation for belts: For the last
seven years, New Jersey has required that the belts be installed on
new buses and, where installed, that students use them; New York
has required their installation on new buses for 12 years. Florida
and Louisiana will require their installation on new buses in a few
years. California's Legislature just passed a school bus seat belt
law, although Gov. Gray Davis has not said if he would sign it.
</P>
<P>
   But engineers determined in a study that was unanimously
endorsed by the five board members Tuesday that the belts, by
holding a child's pelvis firmly in place, allowed the torso to
crack like a whip, with a child's head striking a seat back or a
hard object with greater force than if the child's whole body had
been thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have been unable to determine if there is going to be a
safety benefit derived from those seat belts,'' said Joseph
Osterman, director of highway safety at the board, who noted that
the severity of head impact is a major predictor of the likelihood
of death.
</P>
<P>
   Lap belts alone are clearly a problem, investigators said. And
lap-shoulder combinations are not much better, because the forces
pushing sideways in bus crashes are often much stronger than in
passenger cars and can shake a body loose from the shoulder belt.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the board, James E. Hall, said that the close
spacing of seats with padded seat backs, called
compartmentalization, ``appears to work very well in the frontal
crash,'' but is not adequate for side-impact and roll-over crashes.
He added that ``the only way to reach additional safety benefits is
with the redesign of the seats.''
</P>
<P>
   That could include arm rests, ceiling pads, making the seat
backs even higher, or molding the seats and seat backs, now flat
slabs, to the human form, and covering them with something less
slippery, board engineers said. One problem, they said, is that
molding the seats might reduce their capacity to two children a
seat, from three.
</P>
<P>
   While the board found the evidence ambiguous enough to avoid
recommending the belts, it also was not persuaded to endorse taking
them out.
</P>
<P>
   Both board officials said that school buses are a safe form of
transportation, with an average of nine deaths a year, and that
even with better protection against side impacts and roll overs,
there would still be five or so deaths annually.
</P>
<P>
   One side effect of the low death rate, officials said, is a
sketchy database. Investigators said they could not find accidents
involving belt-equipped buses to analyze, so instead they had
resorted to models of accidents in which students had been killed
or badly hurt, and used a computer to determine what would have
happened if they had been wearing belts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
