<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 23:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0956 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-GLF-GARCIA-RYDER-TEX     09-21 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GARCIA-RYDER-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXUBERANT SERGIO GARCIA COULD BREAK HEARTS OF HIS AMERICAN FANS AT
RYDER CUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kids, especially ``ni$os'', say the darndest things. Art
Linkletter drove home that point on network television in the 1950s
and 1960s. He even wrote a book about it.
</P>
<P>
   But no one, least of all U.S. Ryder Cup captain Ben Crenshaw,
saw this request coming. It happened in May at the Memorial
Tournament, when Sergio Garcia offered an introduction and a
suggestion.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, 19, is known simply as ``El Ni$o'' (The Kid) to fans in
his native Spain. Throughout Europe, the youngest player in Ryder
Cup history is acclaimed as the visiting team's shining hope to
keep the trophy on the other side of the Atlantic Ocean when the
33rd Ryder Cup matches conclude Sunday at The Country Club in
Brookline, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Back in May, however, Garcia was merely three tournaments into
his professional career. He was playing week-to-week on sponsor's
exemptions and working every angle to gain access into high-profile
events. That's why he tracked down Crenshaw at Muirfield Village
Golf Club in Dublin, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He came over and looked at me with that baby face and said,
`Mr. Crenshaw, this is the first time I meet you,' '' Crenshaw
recalled. `` `I have played well enough to be on the U.S. PGA Tour.
Would you pick me on your Ryder Cup team?' That says everything
about Sergio. He is so endearing. How could you not love this
kid?''
</P>
<P>
   For a fleeting moment, Crenshaw found himself hating those pesky
Ryder Cup rules mandating that members of his U.S. squad must be
born in America or be the child of U.S. citizens. Imagine, as
Crenshaw did, heading to the first tee for Friday's opening match,
with Garcia and Tiger Woods paired together in an alternate-shot
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, professional golf's most engaging, emotional players
are destined to be adversaries during Ryder Cup week. This could
create a quandary for galleries at The Country Club. American fans
have become so smitten with the smiling, bubbly Garcia that most
gallery members cheered against Woods _ the PGA Tour's top gate
attraction _ and for Garcia during the final round of the PGA
Championship on Aug. 15 in Medinah, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked like I was an American, or more than that,'' said
Garcia, who finished second to Woods by one stroke. ``The crowds
were amazing. Inside of me, I felt like I won.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia hoisted no hardware that day. But he captured the
imagination of the golf world with his blend of youthful
exuberance, guts, guile, creativity and ability. In many ways, said
Tom Lehman, Garcia reminds veteran players of his mentor, Seve
Ballesteros. But with a refreshing twist.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sergio is Seve with a smile,'' Lehman said. ``That's really
what he is. He's a very creative and swashbuckling kind of a
charismatic guy. You can't help but just love him.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's road to becoming the youngest competitor in Ryder Cup
history reads like a Hollywood script that would be rejected for
being sappier than ``Rocky'', and less realistic. The son of a club
golf professional in Borriol, Spain, Garcia began playing at 3, won
his club championship at 12 and was European amateur champ at 15.
</P>
<P>
   This season, he earned low-amateur honors at the Masters
Tournament before turning professional April 22 at the Spanish Open
in Barcelona. In his first PGA Tour event as a pro, the GTE Byron
Nelson Classic, Garcia tied for third and won $144,000. He claimed
his first professional victory July 4, at the European Tour's Irish
Open, and posted his best career finish in a major championship by
finishing as the runner-up to Woods at the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia's $378,000 payday from the PGA provided the boost he
needed to clinch a spot on the European Ryder Cup team despite
spotting fellow competitors an eight-month head start in
accumulating points toward an automatic berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, to be honest, has probably been a little over my
expectations,'' Garcia said. ``But I really love it.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia began eliciting that emotion at the PGA, where his
miraculous par save at the 16th hole in the final round. With his
ball nestled next to a tree root in the right rough, Garcia ignored
the advice of caddie Jerry Higginbotham to chip safely to the
fairway and play for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he shaped a slicing shot around the tree with a 6-iron.
Because he feared a ricochet, Garcia turned his head and closed his
eyes as he swung. The ball zipped through a narrow opening, covered
the 189 yards to the green and stopped 40 feet from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia began sprinting up the fairway as he followed its path,
jumping for joy as it stopped on the putting surface. He doffed his
cap to cheering fans, then smiled and covered his heart in mock
cardiac arrest, like Redd Foxx on ``Sanford &AMP; Son''.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the running and jumping, Garcia said: ``I'll
probably do it till I can't. I was so excited, that was the first
thing that came from me. When I won't be able to do that, I'll
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Barring a career-threatening injury, that leaves Garcia three
decades worth of similar spontaneous outbursts before reaching the
more sedate surroundings of the Senior Tour. Considering their
respective ages, Garcia joins the 23-year-old Woods on the short
list of players most likely to challenge Nick Faldo's career
records for Ryder Cup matches played (46), victories (23) and
points scored (25).
</P>
<P>
   He'll get his first opportunity at The Country Club, where
Garcia said he is not nervous and would like to butt heads with the
world's top-ranked player in singles, if possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play Tiger,'' Garcia said. ``When I turned pro, I
wanted to be the No. 1 golfer in the world. So I knew that meant I
was going to be a rival for Tiger. We might as well get started.''
</P>
<P>
   Observers anticipate a long series of head-to-head encounters
because the two share more than youth, long drives and a
willingness to display emotion between the gallery ropes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most impressive thing about Sergio is that when you look
at his irons and there's hardly a quarter-inch of clubface worn
away at the center. He hits the ball that squarely,'' said David
Feherty, a CBS golf analyst and member of Europe's 1991 Ryder Cup
team. ``Sergio and Tiger do that better than anyone in the game
today. It's like Tiger raised the bar and Sergio is going to jump
over it.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, of course, there are the intangibles. Crenshaw, normally
an eloquent speaker, gets tongue-tied on the subject of Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anyone can come up with enough adjectives for
this kid,'' Crenshaw said. ``He's something that we've never seen.
You watch him and think, `What do you have to do to beat this guy?'
He's incredible. This is magic, here.''
</P>
<P>
   Crenshaw's only regret is that Ryder Cup rules dictate that ``El
Ni$o'' must wave his magic wand against the U.S. team, rather than
for it.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
