<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS TRADE AGING HARPER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Derek Harper might have retired last
offseason had the Lakers not offered the lure of an NBA
championship. But the Lakers' title run ended prematurely and now
Harper's career might be over as well.
</P>
<P>
   In a salary-dumping move, Harper, a 16-year veteran, was traded
to the Detroit Pistons on Tuesday for a rookie who probably won't
ever draw a Lakers paycheck. But Harper, who turns 38 next month,
will retire rather than play for a noncontender. The move could
void the trade.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit General Manager Rick Sund, who drafted Harper in Dallas
in 1983, is trying to talk Harper into playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there's probably not enough icing in the world to put on
the cake,'' Harper said. ``I don't want to go to Detroit. I don't
want to play there. It has nothing to do with anybody there. . . .
But I don't like the chances of winning a championship there.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he'd prefer to spend time with his wife and four
children in Dallas and possibly take a long-standing offer of a
front-office job with the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   Harper started 29 of 50 games at point guard last season but
appeared to run out of gas late in the season and gave way to Derek
Fisher. New coach Phil Jackson apparently decided Harper had little
left to offer and he's lobbying management to sign former Chicago
Bulls guard Ron Harper, who turns 36 in January. That is likely to
happen.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers also are considering guard Brian Shaw and center
Benoit Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for Harper, the Lakers obtained Melvin Levett, a
6-foot-3 guard out of Cincinnati who was the 54th overall pick in
the June draft. The Pistons never tendered Levett a contract and
the Lakers probably won't either.
</P>
<P>
   If Harper retires, and if that voids the trade, the Lakers will
probably waive him, leaving them responsible for paying his $1.2
million salary for 1999-2000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0469 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-21 23:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-L.A.-POLICE-NYT &LR;      09-21 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-L.A.-POLICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CORRUPTION INQUIRY IN LOS ANGELES  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Wednesday, Sept. 22:
</P>
<P>
   An expanding corruption scandal in the Los Angeles Police
Department bodes ill for a city where residents in poor minority
communities have long complained of police arrogance and brutality.
A dozen officers have been suspended in an investigation that has
produced allegations of breathtaking misconduct. The scandal
widened into public view when one former officer, Rafael Perez,
agreed to cooperate with authorities in exchange for a lighter
sentence on his conviction for stealing cocaine from a police
evidence locker.
</P>
<P>
   Perez told investigators that in 1996 he and a former partner
intentionally shot a young unarmed Hispanic gang member, planted a
weapon beside the man and framed him for assaulting them. The
victim, who was left paralyzed, was convicted and sentenced to 23
years in prison as a result of the officers' false testimony. Last
week, prosecutors asked a judge to release the convicted man
immediately. Investigators are looking into another 1996 shooting
involving officers from the same division.
</P>
<P>
   The city's political leaders are pushing for a thorough criminal
investigation. A scandal in which an officer admits that an
innocent man was framed can have a devastating effect on the
credibility of other officers. Merely bringing the accused officers
to justice will not fully mend the broken public trust. Unless
there are intense efforts to expose misconduct and to impose
effective citizen oversight, the public is liable to believe that
other bad officers have simply not been caught. In Los Angeles, as
in episodes of police misconduct in New York, the difficult work of
building trust has been dealt a setback.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
