u f BC-CASH-BALANCE-PENSIONS     09-21 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CASH-BALANCE-PENSIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROSPECTS RISE FOR CURBS ON CASH-BALANCE PENSION PLANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By RICHARD A. OPPEL Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The fight over cash-balance pensions has moved to Congress,
where lobbyists and congressional aides say the dispute over IBM's
pension switch will probably help spur legislation to rein in the
plans.
</P>
<P>
   Any legislative action may not occur until next year, they said,
but even business lobbying groups and other opponents of new
cash-balance regulations say the controversy has heightened
lawmakers' awareness of the issue and appears to have improved
chances for legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Under cash-balance plans, which have been adopted by hundreds of
large companies in recent years, employees earn retirement benefits
evenly throughout their careers. With traditional plans, benefits
are figured using an employee's length of service and final pay, so
most benefits are earned late in the person's career.
</P>
<P>
   What has caught the attention of the Internal Revenue Service
and the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission _ both are
reviewing the new plans to see if they violate age-discrimination
laws _ are conversions that in some cases have reduced benefits for
middle-aged employees by one-fifth to one-half.
</P>
<P>
   After protests by thousands of its workers, IBM on Friday backed
down from a full-scale switch to a cash-balance plan, allowing any
employee at least 40 years old and with a decade of service to keep
their old pension benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the move, many IBM workers are still upset, and a Senate
committee Tuesday held a four-hour hearing to examine whether
pension switches there and at other companies have harmed workers.
</P>
<P>
   Stuart Brown, chief counsel of the Internal Revenue Service,
testified that the agency had never said that the plans result in
violations, per se, of age-discrimination laws. But he said
existing regulations, which generally state that pensions do not
run afoul of age-discrimination rules solely because of lower
future benefit accruals for older workers, are being re-examined.
</P>
<P>
   ``These regulations were proposed before significant numbers of
cash-balance plan conversions had occurred, and the special issues
posed by cash-balance plans were not considered or addressed at the
time they were developed,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Employers making cash-balance plan conversions must promise
each employee the greater of the protected benefits under the
original defined-benefit formula or the benefits calculated under
the new cash-balance formula,'' he said. ``In practice, some may
not.''
</P>
<P>
   And for companies that have already received notification of
tax-favored status for their new cash-balance plans, the IRS ``will
generally not seek retroactive disqualification of a plan.'' But he
added that IRS approval does not mean that employees whose rights
are violated by the new plan cannot sue to recover benefits.
</P>
<P>
   The legislative proposals now circulating in Congress include
forcing companies that convert to a cash-balance plan to give all
employees a choice of sticking with the old plan; prohibiting
``wear-away,'' or conversions that leave some employees working
years before they start accruing benefits again, and forcing
companies to explain clearly to employees how much a switch will
reduce future benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Cash-balance opponents note that two months ago, well before the
IBM reversal and federal investigations, a proposal by Sen. Tom
Harkin, D-Iowa, to eliminate ``wear-away'' failed by only a 48-52
vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most members of Congress have sympathy with this,'' said Karen
Friedman, director of the Pension Fairness Project at the Pension
Rights Center in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Employer groups also concede the uproar has increased chances
for legislation. There is ``a greater possibility that something
beyond'' a law simply tightening disclosure of benefit changes will
pass, said James Delaplane, vice president for retirement policy at
the Association of Private Pension and Welfare Plans.
</P>
<P>
   But he cautioned that too many new regulations could end up
hurting workers. He noted, as did Brown of the IRS, that nothing
prohibits companies from terminating pension plans, as long as they
pay all benefits already earned.
</P>
<P>
   Companies might otherwise scrap their plans if they have to lock
in a certain amount of future benefit accruals, regardless of ``how
tough the competition is or no matter if your company is in
trouble,'' Delaplane said. ``It's better to have these plans in
place for folks than to terminate them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
