<SLUG> BC-GOLDMAN-EARNINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOLDMAN EARNINGS STRONG FOR ITS FIRST PUBLIC QUARTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y.)   (af)  
 By PATRICK McGEEHAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Goldman Sachs Group Inc. reported surprisingly strong
earnings Tuesday in its first full quarter as a public company, a
striking reversal from a year ago when fallout from Russia's
economic woes forced the investment banking firm to postpone plans
for its initial public offering of stock.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman, which went public with an offering of $3.7 billion on
May 4, said it earned $638 million, or $1.32 a diluted share, in
its fiscal third quarter, which ended Aug. 27. The results were
essentially even with those Goldman reported for its fiscal second
quarter and nearly double the $329 million, or 69 cents a share,
that Goldman said it would have reported for the period a year ago
if it had been public then.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's results exceeded the expectations of Wall Street
analysts, whose average forecast was $1.09 a share, according to
First Call/Thomson Financial. Still, Goldman's stock fell along
with those of other financial-services companies, dropping $1.625,
to $59.125, on the New York Stock Exchange. That left the shares
above their offering price of $53 a share but well below their high
of $77.25.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very strong quarter across the board in investment
banking,'' said David Viniar, Goldman's chief financial officer.
Viniar added that he was ``cautiously optimistic'' about whether
the markets would stay strong enough to accept all of the stock and
bond offerings companies hope to complete in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
   The fees Goldman earned for advising companies on mergers and
for underwriting stock and bond offerings surged enough to offset a
late-summer decline in Goldman's revenue from trading stocks, bonds
and commodities. But what surprised analysts was a jump in the
value of investments Goldman has made in other companies.
</P>
<P>
   Those merchant-banking gains amounted to $328 million in the
quarter, compared with $189 million in the second quarter and just
$30 million in the period a year earlier. Some of those gains
occurred only on paper as Goldman marked up stakes it has in
companies that have gone public, such as Wit Capital, an online
investment bank that first sold stock in June.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something that reflects solid company
fundamentals,'' said Guy Moszkowski, an analyst at Citigroup's
Salomon Smith Barney unit. ``So it's not something that the market
is going to stand up and applaud.''
</P>
<P>
   Those markups increased Goldman's net revenue _ revenue after
interest expense _ for the quarter to $3.41 billion, down from
$3.47 billion in the second quarter but up from $2.14 billion in
the third quarter of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Fees for advising on mergers and acquisitions rose 10 percent,
to $616 million from $561 million in the quarter a year ago.
Underwriting revenue increased 34 percent, to $534 million from
$399 million the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman's total revenue for the quarter was $6.44 billion, up
from $6.36 billion in the previous quarter and $5.74 billion a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   To some degree, Goldman's results portend strong performances
from two other big securities firms slated to report earnings this
week, analysts said. The fiscal third quarters for Morgan Stanley
Dean Witter &AMP; Co. and Lehman Brothers Holdings Inc. ran through
August, while the reporting periods for some other big Wall Street
firms, including Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., end Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``The companies that are reporting now have a leg up because
June was clearly a stronger month than September will be,'' said
Joan Solotar, an analyst at Donaldson, Lufkin &AMP; Jenrette Inc. But,
she warned investors against extrapolating from Goldman's results
because Goldman has been gaining market share in its most
profitable business ``both domestically and, more importantly, in
overseas markets, which are growing.''
</P>
<P>
   A major facilitator of the merger mania that is sweeping through
Europe, Goldman now derives about 35 percent to 40 percent of its
revenue from outside the United States.
</P>
<P>
   All securities firms should report significantly higher earnings
for this period than they did a year ago, Ms. Solotar said, because
``last year was just a total washout for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   When financial turmoil spread across Asia to Russia and Latin
America, the firms' trading desks suffered huge losses on bonds
they were holding. Sales of stocks and bonds slammed to a halt as
investors scrambled for the relative safety of United States
Treasury bonds.
</P>
<P>
   By early this year, the U.S. financial markets had recovered and
the boom in merger activity and first-time stock sales by
technology companies had resumed. In recent weeks, though, concerns
about a third interest-rate hike by the Federal Reserve Board have
dragged on the markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is certainly softer'' so far in September, Viniar
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
