<HEADLINE>
CLIPS WON'T PAY, BUT FOR NOW TAYLOR STAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 c.1999 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Maurice Taylor, another one who figures to get
away, might have to spend a third season as the killer whale in the
Los Angeles Clippers' catch-and-release program.
</P>
<P>
   Now he must prove he's the reel deal.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, David Falk, has asked for the NBA maximum extension,
$70.9 million over six seasons. Clippers owner Donald Sterling, it
is believed, won't pay it, leaving Falk to peddle Taylor elsewhere
when his contract expires next year _ or conjure up a trade in the
meantime.
</P>
<P>
   But the team hasn't seen an acceptable trade offer and Taylor
will probably be a Clipper when the team opens training camp at
Southwest College on Oct. 5.
</P>
<P>
   __ Little man, big man: Candidates to fill the conspicuous
vacancies of point guard (an expected co-op arrangement with
semi-incumbent Troy Hudson) and backup center are Eric Murdock and
Zan Tabak.
</P>
<P>
   __ Also:The Clippers' new trainer is Jason Powell, who is
leaving his assistant trainer's gig with the San Francisco 49ers to
replace Ray Melchiorre, whose contract was not renewed. Powell
previously worked for the Clips as an assistant to former trainer
Keith Jones. . . . Rex Kalamian will be promoted from video
coordinator and part-time assistant coach to full-time assistant
coach, replacing Jim Brewer, whose contract also was not renewed.
</P>
</TEXT>
