A0988 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-USC-LADN     09-21 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROJANS CLEAR THE AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ On the heels of a precarious victory over San
Diego State, some USC players held an impromptu meeting to address
complaints that arose following the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talked about people's attitudes toward coaches, about
whether they were getting the ball, or not playing enough,''
linebacker Markus Steele said. ``You don't want that leading into
the next game. Because player attitudes can cost you. Certain
players just called out other players.''
</P>
<P>
   One topic that has become more important to the team and a
source of discussion is penalties. USC has 26 in two games and is
on pace to surpass last year's total of 119.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was talk about penalties and focusing on long-term
goals,'' strong safety David Gibson said. ``There was arguing on
the field (against San Diego State).''
</P>
<P>
   Steele said the meeting was meant to calm players down and avoid
any lingering dissension.
</P>
<P>
   ``When your opportunity comes, it comes, you can't dwell on
it,'' Steele said. ``We talked about what's wrong and said not to
worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Welch out: Offensive tackle Matt Welch missed Tuesday's
practice with abdominal pains and possible gallstones. Welch's
status for the game is questionable, but he was scheduled to play
tight end in goal-line situations this week. The Trojans faltered
in their goal-line offense against San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   __ Garner is back: Wide receiver Troy Garner, a Notre Dame High
alumnus, who was suspended for two weeks after arguing with
strength coach Matt Schiotz, has been reinstated to the team.
</P>
<P>
   __ Case over: USC settled the sexual-harassment lawsuit filed by
former administrative assistant Norma Navarro against the
university and ex-coach John Robinson, according to general counsel
Todd Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   The case was filed in December, 1997, and also included claims
of discrimination, unequal pay, failure to pay wages and wrongful
termination.
</P>
<P>
   Navarro, who eventually filed for bankruptcy, did not personally
receive any of the financial settlement.
</P>
<P>
   __ Soward shines: Wide receiver R. Jay Soward might have been
upset over not getting the ball enough against San Diego State, but
he had one of his best practices of the season Tuesday, making
several one-handed catches.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was sensational,'' USC coach Paul Hackett said. ``He
practiced just like he did all last week when he was on a whole
other level of practice for him. He was really focused and I think
it will show on Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Who's healthy?: Tailbacks Frank Strong (bruised knee) and
Malaefou MacKenzie (hamstring) practiced, but Hackett said both
were ``ginger and tentative.''
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver Matt Nickels has pneumonia and might miss the
Oregon game. Nickels' role would probably increase if he were
healthy and starter Windrell Hayes (sprained ankle) was unable to
play.
</P>
<P>
   As for Hayes, he walked on his injured ankle and believes he has
a chance to play. ``Stranger things have happened,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Without Hayes or Nickels, the Trojans have three healthy
receivers, plus a returning Steve Stevenson (sprained arch) and
Stanley Guyness, who is returning from knee surgery but saw the
first action of his career against San Diego State.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-09-21-99 2354EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990921.0475 </DOCNO>
