u w BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT &LR;      09-21 0968
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOBACCO-SUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. TO SUE TOBACCO FIRMS IN BID TO RECOVER HEALTH COSTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Minn.)   (Eds., this story is an added starter on NYT P.1)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID STOUT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Justice Department is about to file a civil
suit against the tobacco industry, seeking to recover billions of
dollars in health-related expenses that cigarette smoking has cost
over the decades, a government official said Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department believes smoking-related illnesses have
cost the American taxpayers billions of dollars, and it is seeking
ways to get the taxpayers' money back,'' said the government
official, who is familiar with the unfolding case and spoke Tuesday
night on condition he not be quoted by name.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawsuit had been expected since President Clinton
first proposed it in his State of the Union address last January,
it is still a blow to the industry, which had thought it had put
most of its legal problems behind it by settling hundreds of
millions of dollars in lawsuits by the states and beating back
congressional efforts to strongly regulate nicotine.
</P>
<P>
   A lawyer for the tobacco industry reached Tuesday night said he
was unaware of an imminent legal action by the government. But in
recent months officials from tobacco companies and a public
relations firm hired by the industry have conducted an aggressive
campaign depicting any federal lawsuit as ungrounded and legally
unviable. An effort was made in Congress this year to curtail
financing the Justice Department would need to pay for the
litigation against the industry.
</P>
<P>
   Following the State of the Union, the cigarette industry said
the president's remarks were ``blatantly political'' and meant to
demonize the tobacco companies. People who had long followed
tobacco litigation said the cigarette makers were rattled by the
prospect of facing an adversary _ the federal government _ with
pockets as deep as their own.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, which has been planned for nearly a year, may allege
that cigarette smoking has cost as much as $25 billion a year from
the effects of lung cancer and other diseases linked to the smoking
habit. The $25 billion is calculated from the numbers of health
claims paid to veterans and the elderly through Medicare, according
to The Washington Post, which reported on the impending suit in its
Wednesday editions.
</P>
<P>
   The official would not discuss the exact timing of the suit _
The Post said it may be filed as soon as Wednesday _ but he made it
clear that it is about to be lodged.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 46 states settled with tobacco companies for a total
of $206 billion for health costs the states had been saddled with
over the years because of smoking. Four other states had settled
similar claims earlier in a separate action.
</P>
<P>
   So at the start of 1999, the tobacco industry thought it had
insured its survival and perhaps even its prosperity, albeit at a
huge cost. The $206 billion is to be paid over 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's announcement that his administration would seek
recompense separate from the money to be paid to the states
surprised many Justice Department lawyers, as well as attorneys for
tobacco interests.
</P>
<P>
   In a clear signal of its seriousness, the Justice Department in
April hired a Minnesota law firm that had represented that state in
its action against the tobacco industry.
</P>
<P>
   The Post reported that as part of its suit, to be filed in U.S.
District Court, the Justice Department will contend that the
tobacco companies engaged in civil racketeering. The suit will
allege industrywide collusion in consumer fraud to conceal the
risks of smoking, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
   Because the state lawsuits were intended to recover health care
costs spent through the Medicaid program on low-income patients,
the federal government is seeking to recover similar expenses spent
treating the elderly through the Medicare program. The action is
also seeking reimbursement of costs spent treating smoking-related
ills among both active and retired military personnel and
government employees.
</P>
<P>
   The hiring of the Minnesota firm, Robins, Kaplan, Miller &AMP;
Ciresi of Minneapolis, brought a scathing response from the tobacco
industry. ``The administration has handed the keys to the Justice
Department over to the trial lawyers,'' an industry spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Justice Department said there was no arrangement for the
firm to get contingency fees if the government prevailed in a
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The outlines of the soon-to-be filed federal suit are unclear,
but lawyers involved in it have long said it would aim to win
concessions not included in the settlements between the big tobacco
companies and the states. These might include federal power to
regulate nicotine under the Food and Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
   It also became widely known soon after the president's
announcement that some lawyers in the Justice Department were
unhappy that Clinton had, in effect, tipped off the tobacco
companies well in advance.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the tobacco industry enjoyed near-invincibility in
the courtroom. Able to spend as much as necessary on legal counsel,
it was able to defeat virtually every lawsuit filed against
cigarette makers by longtime smokers who had become ill.
</P>
<P>
   But in the past several years, the tide has turned. The sight of
several tobacco executives swearing under oath in a congressional
hearing room that they did not believe nicotine was addictive was
offensive even to those who had not seriously pondered the danger
of cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco companies have been more vulnerable in courthouses
recently, and more vulnerable too in the court of public opinion,
as the dangers of smoking and the hazards of ``second-hand smoke''
have been widely publicized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
